				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 32: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra is King of all that moves and moves not, of creatures tame and
							horned, the Thunder-wielder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 32: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Over all living men he rules as Sovran, containing all as spokes within
							the felly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 33
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come, fain for booty let us seek to Indra: yet more shall he increase
							his care that guides us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Will not the Indestructible endow us with perfect knowledge of this
							wealth, of cattle?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I fly to him invisible Wealth-giver as flies the falcon to his
							cherished eyrie,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With fairest hymns of praise adoring Indra, whom those who laud him
							must invoke in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mid all his host, he bindeth on the quiver: he driveth cattle from what
							foe he pleaseth:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gathering up great store of riches, Indra. be thou no trafficker with
							us, most mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou slewest with thy bolt the wealthy Dasyu, alone, yet going with thy
							helpers, Indra!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far from the floor of heaven in all directions, the ancient riteless
							ones fled to destruction.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fighting with pious worshippers, the riteless turned and fled, Indra!
							with averted faces.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou, fierce Lord of the Bay Steeds, the Stayer, blewest from
							earth and heaven and sky the godless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							They met in fight the army of the blameless: then the Navagvas put
							forth all their power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							They, like emasculates with men contending, fled, conscious, by steep
							paths from Indra, scattered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whether they weep or laugh, thou hast o'erthrown them, O Indra, on the
							sky's extremest limit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Dasyu thou hast burned from heaven, and welcomed the prayer of him
							who pours the juice and lauds thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adorned with their array of gold and jewels, they o'er the earth a
							covering veil extended.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Although they hastened, they o'ercame not Indra: their spies he
							compassed with the Sun of morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							As thou enjoyest heaven and earth, O Indra, on every side surrounded
							with thy greatness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							So thou with priests bast blown away the Dasyu, and those who worship
							not with those who worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who pervaded earth's extremest limit subdued not with their charms
							the Wealth-bestower:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, the Bull, made his ally the thunder, and with its light milked
							cows from out the darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The waters flowed according to their nature; he raid the navigable
							streams waxed mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then Indra, with his spirit concentrated, smote him for ever with his
							strongest weapon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra broke through Ilibisa's strong castles, and Susna with his horn
							he cut to pieces:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Maghavan, for all his might and swiftness, slewest thy fighting
							foeman with thy thunder
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fierce on his enemies fell Indra's weapon: with. his sharp bull he rent
							their forts in pieces.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							He with his thunderbolt dealt blows on Vrtra; and conquered, executing
							all his purpose.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, thou helpest Kutsa whom thou lovedst, and guardedst brave
							Dagadyu when he battled,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							The dust of trampling horses rose to heaven, and Svitra's son stood up
							again for conquest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Svitra's mild steer, O Maghavan thou helpest in combat for the land,
							mid Tugra's houses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 33: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Long stood they there before the task was ended: thou wast the master
							of the foemen's treasure.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 34
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye who observe this day be with us even thrice: far-stretching is you
							bounty, Asvins and your course.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To you, as to a cloak in winter, we cleave close: you are to be drawn
							nigh unto us by the wise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three are the fellies in your honey-bearing car, that travels after
							Soma's loved one, as all know.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Three are the pillars set upon it for support: thrice journey ye by
							night, O Asvins, thrice by day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrice in the self-same day, ye Gods who banish want, sprinkle ye
							thrice to-day our sacrifice with meath;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And thrice vouchsafe us store of food with plenteous strength, at
							evening, O ye Asvins, and at break of day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrice come ye to our home, thrice to the righteous folk, thrice triply
							aid the man who well deserves your help.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thrice, O ye Asvins, bring us what shall make us glad; thrice send us
							store of food as nevermore to fail.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrice, O ye Asvins, bring to us abundant wealth: thrice in the Gods'
							assembly, thrice assist our thoughts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thrice, grant ye us prosperity, thrice grant us fame; for the Sun's
							daughter hath mounted your three-wheeled car.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrice, Asvins, grant to us the heavenly medicines, thrice those of
							earth and thrice those that the waters hold,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Favour and health and strength bestow upon my son; triple protection,
							Lords of Splendour, grant to him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrice are ye to be worshipped day by day by us: thrice, O ye Asvins,
							ye travel around the earth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Car-borne from far away, O ye Nasatyas, come, like vital air to bodies,
							come ye to the three.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrice, O ye Asvins, with the Seven Mother Streams; three are the jars,
							the triple offering is prepared.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Three are the worlds, and moving on above the sky ye guard the firm-set
							vault of heaven through days and nights.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where are the three wheels of your triple chariot, where are the three
							seats thereto firmly fastened?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When will ye yoke the mighty ass that draws it, to bring you to our
							sacrifice. Nasatyas?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Nasatyas, come: the sacred gift is offered up; drink the sweet juice
							with lips that know the sweetness well.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savitar sends, before the dawn of day, your car, fraught with oil,
							various-coloured, to our sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come, O Nasatyas, with the thrice-eleven Gods; come, O ye Asvins, to
							the drinking of the meath.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make long our days of life, and wipe out all our sins: ward off our
							enemies; be with us evermore.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Borne in your triple car, O Asvins, bring us present prosperity with
							noble offspring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 34: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							I cry to you who hear me for protection be ye our helpers where men win
							the booty.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 35
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI I first invoke for our prosperity; I call on Mitra, Varuna, to aid
							us here.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I call on Night who gives rest to all moving life; I call on Savitar
							the God to lend us help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Throughout the dusky firmament advancing, laying to rest the immortal
							and the mortal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Borne in his golden chariot he cometh, Savitar, God who looks on every
							creature.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The God moves by the upward path, the downward; with two bright Bays,
							adorable, he journeys.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savitar comes, the God from the far distance, and chases from us all
							distress and sorrow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							His chariot decked with pearl, of various colours, lofty, with golden
							pole, the God hath mounted,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The many-rayed One, Savitar the holy, bound, bearing power and might,
							for darksome regions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drawing the gold-yoked car his Bays, white-footed, have manifested
							light to all the peoples.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Held in the lap of Savitar, divine One, all men, all beings have their
							place for ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three heavens there are; two Savitar's, adjacent: in Yama's world is
							one, the home of heroes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As on a linch-pin, firm, rest things immortal: he who hath known it let
							him here declare it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, strong of wing, hath lightened up the regions, deep-quivering
							Asura, the gentle Leader.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where now is Surya, where is one to tell us to what celestial sphere
							his ray hath wandered?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The earth's eight points his brightness hath illumined, three desert
							regions and the Seven Rivers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							God Savitar the gold-eyed hath come hither, giving choice treasures
							unto him who worships.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The golden-handed Savitar, far-seeing, goes on his way between the
							earth and heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drives away sickness, bids the Sun approach us, and spreads the bright
							sky through the darksome region.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he, gold-handed Asura, kind Leader, come hither to us with his help
							and favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Driving off Raksasas and Yatudhanas, the God is present, praised in
							hymns at evening.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Savitar, thine ancient dustless pathways are well established in the
							air's mid-region:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 35: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							O God, come by those paths so fair to travel, preserve thou us from
							harm this day, and bless us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 36
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH words sent forth in holy hymns, Agni we supplicate, the Lord
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of many families who duly serve the Gods, yea, him whom others also
							praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men have won Agni, him who makes their strength abound: we, with
							oblations, worship thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our gracious-minded Helper in our deeds of might, be thou, O Excellent,
							this day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee for our messenger we choose, thee, the Omniscient, for our Priest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The flames of thee the mighty are spread wide around: thy splendour
							reaches to the sky.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Gods enkindle thee their ancient messenger,--Varuna, Mitra,
							Aryaman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That mortal man, O Agni, gains through thee all wealth, who hath poured
							offerings unto thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Agni, art a cheering Priest, Lord of the House, men's messenger:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							All constant high decrees established by the Gods, gathered together,
							meet in thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							In thee, the auspicious One, O Agni, youthfullest, each sacred gift is
							offered up:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							This day, and after, gracious, worship thou our Gods, that we may have
							heroic sons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him in his own splendour bright draw near in worship the devout.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men kindle Agni with their sacrificial gifts, victorious o'er the
							enemies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vrtra they smote and slew, and made the earth and heaven and firmament
							a wide abode.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The glorious Bull, invoked, hath stood at Kanva's side: loud neighed
							the Steed in frays for kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Seat thee, for thou art mighty; shine, best entertainer of the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 36: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
