				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							His herald rays are seen afar refulgent o'er the world of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like flames of fire that burn and blaze.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Swift and all beautiful art thou, O Surya, maker of the light,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Illuming all the radiant realm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou goest to the hosts of Gods, thou comest hither to mankind,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hither all light to be beheld.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							With that same eye of thine wherewith thou lookest brilliant Varuna,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Upon the busy race of men,
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Traversing sky and wide mid-air, thou metest with thy beams our days,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sun, seeing all things that have birth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Seven Bay Steeds harnessed to thy car bear thee, O thou farseeing One,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							God, Surya, with the radiant hair.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surya hath yoked the pure bright Seven, the daughters of the car; with
							these,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							His own dear team, he goeth forth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Looking upon the loftier light above the darkness we have come
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Surya, God among the Gods, the light that is most excellent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rising this day, O rich in friends, ascending to the loftier heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Surya remove my heart's disease, take from me this my yellow hue.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							To parrots and to starlings let us give away my yellowness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or this my yellowness let us transfer to Haritala trees.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							With all his conquering vigour this Aditya hath gone up on high,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 50: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giving my foe into mine hand: let me not be my foeman's prey.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 51
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAKE glad with songs that Ram whom many men invoke, worthy of songs of
							praise, Indra, the sea of wealth;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose gracious deeds for men spread like the heavens abroad: sing
							praise to him the Sage, most liberal for our good.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As aids the skilful Rbhus yearned to Indra strong to save, who fills
							mid-air, encompassed round with might,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rushing in rapture; and o'er Satakratu came the gladdening shout that
							urged him on to victory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast disclosed the kine's stall for the Angirases, and made a way
							for Atri by a hundred doors.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							On Vimada thou hast bestowed both food and wealth, making thy bolt
							dance in the sacrificer's fight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast unclosed the prisons of the waters; thou hast in the mountain
							seized the treasure rich in gifts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou hadst slain with might the dragon Vrtra, thou, Indra, didst
							raise the Sun in heaven for all to see.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With wondrous might thou blewest enchanter fiends away, with powers
							celestial those who called on thee in jest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, hero-hearted, hast broken down Pipru's forts, and helped Rjisvan
							when the Dasyus were struck dead.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou savedst Kutsa when Susna was smitten down; to Atithigva gavest
							Sambara for a prey.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							E'en mighty Arbuda thou troddest under foot: thou from of old wast born
							to strike the Dasyus dead.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							All power and might is closely gathered up in thee; thy bounteous
							spirit joys in drinking Soma juice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Known is the thunderbolt that lies within thine arms: rend off
							therewith all manly prowess of our foe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Discern thou well Aryas and Dasyus; punishing the lawless give them up
							to him whose grass is strewn.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be thou the sacrificer's strong encourager all these thy deeds are my
							delight at festivals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra gives up the lawless to the pious man, destroying by the Strong
							Ones those who have no strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vamra when glorified destroyed the gathered piles of the still waxing
							great one who would reach the heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							The might which Usana hath formed for thee with might rends in its
							greatness and with strength both worlds apart.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Hero-souled, the steeds of Vata, yoked by thought, have carried thee
							to fame while thou art filled with power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Indra hath rejoiced with Kavya Usana, he mounts his steeds who
							swerve wider and wider yet.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Strong hath loosed his bolt with the swift rush of rain, and he
							hath rent in pieces Susna's firm-built forts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou mountest on thy car amid strong Soma draughts: Saryata brought
							thee those in which thou hast delight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, when thou art pleased with men whose Soma flows thou risest to
							unchallenged glory in the sky.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							To old Kaksivan, Soma-presser, skilled in song, O Indra, thou didst
							give the youthful Vrcaya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, very wise, wast Mena, Vrsanaiva's child: those deeds of thine
							must all be told at Soma feasts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The good man's refuge in his need is Indra, firm as a doorpost, praised
							among the Pajras.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra alone is Lord of wealth, the Giver, lover of riches, chariots,
							kine, and horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the Mighty One, the self-resplendent, verily strong and great,
							this praise is uttered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 51: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we and all the heroes, with the princes, be, in this fray, O Indra,
							in thy keeping.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 52
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I GLORIFY that Ram who finds the light of heaven, whose hundred
							nobly-natured ones go forth with him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With hymns may I turn hither Indra to mine aid,--the Car which like a
							strong steed hasteth to the call.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as a mountain on firm basis, unremoved, he, thousandfold
							protector, waxed in mighty strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Indra, joying in the draughts of Soma juice, forced the clouds,
							slaying Vrtra stayer of their flow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For he stays e'en the stayers, spread o'er laden cloud, rooted in
							light, strengthened in rapture by the wise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra with thought, with skilled activity, I call, most liberal giver,
							for he sates him with the juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whom those that flow in heaven on sacred grass, his own assistants,
							nobly-natured, fill full like the sea,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beside that Indra when he smote down Vrtra stood his helpers, straight
							in form, mighty, invincible.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him, as in wild joy he fought with him who stayed the rain, his
							helpers sped like swift streams down a slope,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Indra, thunder-armed, made bold by Soma draughts, as Trta cleaveth
							Vala's fences, cleft him through.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Splendour encompassed thee, forth shone thy warrior might: the
							rain-obstructer lay in mid-air's lowest deep,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time, O Indra, thou didst cast thy thunder down upon the jaws of
							Vritra hard to be restrained.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The hymns which magnify thee, Indra, reach to thee even as water-brooks
							flow down and fill the lake.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Tvastar gave yet more force to thine appropriate strength, and forged
							thy thunderbolt of overpowering might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, Indra, thou whose power is linked with thy Bay Steeds hadst
							smitten Vrtra, causing floods to flow for man,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou heldst in thine arms the metal thunderbolt, and settest in the
							heaven the Sun for all to see.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							In fear they raised the lofty self-resplendent hymn, praise giving and
							effectual, leading up to heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Indra's helpers fighting for the good of men, the Maruts, faithful
							to mankind, joyed in the light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then Heaven himself, the mighty, at that Dragon's roar reeled back in
							terror when, Indra, thy thunderbolt
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							In the wild joy of Soma had struck off with might the head of Vrtra,
							tyrant of the earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, were this earth extended forth tenfold, and men who dwell
							therein multiplied day by day,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Still here thy conquering might, Maghavan, would be famed: it hath
							waxed vast as heaven in majesty and power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, bold of heart, in thine own native might, for help, upon the
							limit of this mid-air and of heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hast made the earth to be the pattern of thy strength: embracing flood
							and light thou reachest to the sky.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art the counterpart of earth, the Master of lofty heaven with all
							its mighty Heroes:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast filled all the region with thy greatness: yea, of a truth
							there is none other like thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whose amplitude the heaven and earth have not attained, whose bounds
							the waters of mid-air have never reached,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not, when in joy he fights the stayer of the rain: thou, and none else,
							hast made all things in order due.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Maruts sang thy praise in this encounter, and in thee all the
							Deities delighted,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 52: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time thou, Indra, with thy spiky weapon, thy deadly bolt, smotest
							the face of Vrtra.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 53
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WE will present fair praise unto the Mighty One, our hymns to Indra in
							Vivasvan's dwelling-place;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For he hath ne'er found wealth in those who seem to sleep: those who
							give wealth to men accept no paltry praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Giver of horses, Indra, giver, thou, of kine, giver of barley, thou art
							Lord and guard of wealth:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Man's helper from of old, not disappointing hope, Friend of our
							friends, to thee as such we sing this praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, most splendid, powerful, rich in mighty deeds, this treasure
							spread around is known to be thine own.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gather therefrom, O Conqueror, and bring to us: fail not the hope of
							him who loves and sings to thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well pleased with these bright flames and with these Soma drops, take
							thou away our poverty with seeds and kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Indra scattering the Dasyu through these drops, freed from their
							hate may we obtain abundant food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us obtain, O Indra, plenteous wealth and food, with strength
							exceeding glorious, shining to the sky:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we obtain the Goddess Providence, the strength of heroes, special
							source of cattle, rich in steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							These our libations strength-inspiring, Soma draughts, gladdened thee
							in the fight with Vrtra, Hero Lord,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time thou slewest for the singer with trimmed grass ten thousand
							Vrtras, thou resistless in thy might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou goest on from fight to fight intrepidly, destroying castle after
							castle here with strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, with thy friend who makes the foe bow down, slewest from
							far away the guileful Namuci.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast struck down in death Karañja, Parnaya, in Atithigva's very
							glorious going forth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unyielding, when Rjisvan compassed them with siege, thou hast destroyed
							the hundred forts of Vangrida.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							With all-outstripping chariot-wheel, O Indra, thou far-famed, hast
							overthrown the twice ten Kings of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							With sixty thousand nine-and-ninety followers, who came in arms to
							fight with friendless Susravas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast protected Susravas with succour, and Turvayana with thine
							aid, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou madest Kutsa, Atithigva, Ayu, subject unto this King, the young,
							the mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we protected by the Gods hereafter remain thy very prosperous
							friends, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 53: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee we extol, enjoying through thy favour life long and joyful and
							with store of heroes.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 54
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							URGE us not, Maghavan, to this distressful fight, for none may
							comprehend the limit of thy strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou with fierce shout hast made the woods and rivers roar: did not men
							run in crowds together in their fear?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sing hymns of praise to Sakra, Lord of power and might; laud thou and
							magnify Indra who heareth thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who with his daring might, a Bull exceeding strong in strength, maketh
							him master of the heaven and earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sing forth to lofty Dyaus a strength-bestowing song, the Bold, whose
							resolute mind hath independent sway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							High glory hath the Asura, compact of strength, drawn on by two Bay
							Steeds: a Bull, a Car is he.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The ridges of the lofty heaven thou madest shake; thou, daring, of
							thyself smotest through Sambara,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When bold with gladdening juice, thou warredst with thy bolt, sharp and
							two-edged, against the banded sorcerers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When with a roar that fills the woods, thou forcest down on wind's head
							the stores which Susna kept confined,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who shall have power to stay thee firm and eager-souled from doing
							still this day what thou of old hast done?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou helpest Narya, Turvasa, and Yadu, and Vayya's son Turviti,
							Satakratu!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou helpest horse and car in final battle thou breakest down the
							nine-and-ninety castles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							A hero-lord is he, King of a mighty folk, who offers free oblations and
							promotes the Law,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who with a bounteous guerdon welcomes hymns of praise: for him flows
							down the abundant stream below the sky.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							His power is matchless, matchless is his wisdom; chief, through their
							work, be some who drink the Soma,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Those, Indra, who increase the lordly power, the firm heroic strength
							of thee the Giver.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Therefore for thee are these abundant beakers Indra's drink,
							stone-pressed juices held in ladles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Quaff them and satisfy therewith thy longing; then fix thy mind upon
							bestowing treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							There darkness stood, the vault that stayed the waters' flow: in
							Vrtra's hollow side the rain-cloud lay concealed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							But Indra smote the rivers which the obstructer stayed, flood following
							after flood, down steep declivities.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							So give us, Indra, bliss-increasing glory give us great sway and
							strength that conquers people.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 54: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Preserve our wealthy patrons, save our princes; vouchsafe us wealth and
							food with noble offspring.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 55
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOUGH e'en this heaven's wide space and earth have spread them out,
							nor heaven nor earth may be in greatness Indra's match.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Awful and very mighty, causing woe to men, he whets his thunderbolt for
							sharpness, as a bull.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as the watery ocean, so doth he receive the rivers spread on all
							sides in their ample width.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He bears him like a bull to drink of Soma juice, and will, as Warrior
							from of old, be praised for might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou swayest, Indra, all kinds of great manly power, so as to bend,
							as't were, even that famed mountain down.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Foremost among the Gods is he through hero might, set in the van, the
							Strong One, for each arduous deed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He only in the wood is praised by worshippers, when he shows forth to
							men his own fair Indra-power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							A friendly Bull is he, a Bull to be desired when Maghavan auspiciously
							sends forth his voice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yet verily the Warrior in his vigorous strength stirreth up with his
							might great battles for mankind;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And men have faith in Indra, the resplendent One, what time he hurleth
							down his bolt, his dart of death.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Though, fain for glory, and with strength increased on earth, he with
							great might destroys the dwellings made with art,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He makes the lights of heaven shine forth secure, he bids, exceeding
							wise, the floods flow for his worshipper.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drinker of Soma, let thy heart incline to give; bring thy Bays
							hitherward, O thou who hearest praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Those charioteers of' thine, best skilled to draw the rein, the rapid
							sunbeams, Indra, lead thee not astray.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou bearest in both hands treasure that never fails; the famed One in
							his body holds unvanquished might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra, in thy members many powers abide, like wells surrounded by the
							ministering priests.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 56
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FOR this man's full libations held in ladles, he hath roused him,
							eager, as a horse to meet the mare.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He stays his golden car, yoked with Bay Horses, swift, and drinks the
							Soma juice which strengthens for great deeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the guidance-following songs of praise flow full, as those who
							seek gain go in company to the flood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him the Lord of power, the holy synod's might, as to a hill, with
							speed, ascend the loving ones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Victorious, great is he; in manly battle shines, unstained with dust,
							his might, as shines a mountain peak;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith the iron one, fierce e'en against the strong, in rapture,
							fettered wily Sushna fast in bonds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Strength the Goddess, made more strong for help by thee, waits
							upon Indra as the Sun attends the Dawn,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then. he who with his might unflinching kills the gloom stirs up the
							dust aloft, with joy and triumphing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou with might, upon the framework of the heaven, didst fix,
							across, air's region firmly, unremoved,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							In the light-winning war, Indra, in rapturous joy, thou smotest Vrtra
							dead and broughtest floods of rain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou with thy might didst grasp, the holder-up of heaven, thou who art
							mighty also in the seats of earth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 56: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, gladdened by the juice, hast set the waters free, and broken
							Vrtra's stony fences through and through.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 57
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him most liberal, lofty Lord of lofty wealth, verily powerful and
							strong, I bring my hymn,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose checkless bounty, as of waters down a slope, is spread abroad for
							all that live, to give them strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now all this world, for worship, shall come after thee--the offerer's
							libations like floods to the depth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the well-loved one seems to rest upon the hill, the thunderbolt of
							Indra, shatterer wrought of gold.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the terrible, most meet for lofty praise, like bright Dawn, now
							bring gifts with reverence in this rite,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose being, for renown, yea, Indra-power and light, have been created,
							like bay steeds, to move with speed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine, Indra, praised by many, excellently rich! are we who trusting in
							thy help draw near to thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lover of praise, none else but thou receives our laud: as earth loves
							all her creatures, love thou this our hymn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Great is thy power, O Indra, we are thine. Fulfil, O Maghavan, the wish
							of this thy worshipper.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							After thee lofty heaven hath measured out its strength: to thee and to
							thy power this earth hath bowed itself.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, who hast thunder for thy weapon, with thy bolt hast shattered
							into pieces this broad massive cloud.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast sent down the obstructed floods that they may flow: thou
							hast, thine own for ever, all victorious might.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 58
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							NE'ER waxeth faint the Immortal, Son of Strength, since he, the Herald,
							hath become Vivasvan's messenger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							On paths most excellent he measured out mid-air: he with oblation calls
							to service of the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Never decaying, seizing his appropriate food, rapidly, eagerly through
							the dry wood he spreads.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							His back, as he is sprinkled, glistens like a horse: loud hath he
							roared and shouted like the heights of heaven?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Set high in place o'er all that Vasus, Rudras do, immortal, Lord of
							riches, seated as High Priest;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hastening like a car to men, to those who live, the God without delay
							gives boons to be desired.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Urged by the wind be spreads through dry wood as he lists, armed with
							his tongues for sickles, with a mighty roar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Black is thy path, Agni, changeless, with glittering waves! when like a
							bull thou rushest eager to the trees.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With teeth of flame, wind-driven, through the wood he speeds,
							triumphant like a bull among the herd of cows,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With bright strength roaming to the everlasting air: things fixed,
							things moving quake before him as he flies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Bhrgus established thee among mankind for men, like as a treasure,
							beauteous, easy to invoke;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee, Agni, as a herald and choice-worthy guest, as an auspicious
							Friend to the Celestial Race.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, the seven tongues' deftest Sacrificer, him whom the priests elect
							at solemn worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Herald, messenger of all the Vasus, I serve with dainty food, I ask
							for riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grant, Son of Strength, thou rich in friends, a refuge without a flaw
							this day to us thy praisers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Agni, Son of Strength, with forts of iron preserve thou from distress
							the man who lauds thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be thou a refuge, Bright One, to the singer, a shelter, Bounteous Lord,
							to those who worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 58: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Preserve the singer from distress, O Agni. May he, enriched with
							prayer, come soon and early.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 59
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE other fires are, verily, thy branches; the Immortals all rejoice in
							thee, O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Centre art thou, Vaisvanara, of the people, sustaining men like a
							deep-founded pillar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The forehead of the sky, earth's centre, Agni became the messenger of
							earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara, the Deities produced thee, a God, to be a light unto the
							Arya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							As in the Sun firm rays are set for ever, treasures are in Vaisvanara,
							in Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of all the riches in the hills, the waters, the herbs, among mankind,
							thou art the Sovran.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the great World-halves, so are their Son's praises; skilled, as a
							man, to act, is he the Herald.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara, celestial, truly mighty, most manly One, hath many a
							youthful consort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even the lofty heaven, O Jatavedas Vaisvanara, hath not attained thy
							greatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art the King of lands where men are settled, thou hast brought
							comfort to the Gods in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now will I tell the greatness of the Hero whom Puru's sons follow as
							Vrtra's slayer:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni Vaisvanara struck down the Dasyu, cleave Sambara through and
							shattered down his fences.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara, dwelling by his might with all men, far-shining, holy mid
							the Bharadvajas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 59: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is lauded, excellent, with hundred praises by Purunitha, son of
							Satavani.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 60
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As 'twere Some goodly treasure Matarisvan brought, as a gift, the
							glorious Priest to Bhrgu,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Banner of sacrifice, the good Protector, child of two births, the
							swiftly moving envoy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Both Gods and men obey this Ruler's order, Gods who are worshipped, men
							who yearn and worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As Priest he takes his seat ere break of morning, House-Lord, adorable
							with men, Ordainer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May our fair praise, heart-born, most recent, reach him whose tongue,
							e'en at his birth, is sweet as honey;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom mortal priests, men, with their strong endeavour, supplied with
							dainty viands, have created.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Good to mankind, the yearning Purifier hath among men been placed as
							Priest choice-worthy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni be our Friend, Lord of the Household, protector of the riches
							in the dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As such we Gotamas with hymns extol thee, O Agni, as the guardian Lord
							of riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 60: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Decking thee like a horse, the swift prizewinner. May he, enriched with
							prayer, come soon and early.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 61
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							EVEN to him, swift, strong and high. exalted, I bring my song of praise
							as dainty viands,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							My thought to him resistless, praise-deserving, prayers offered most
							especially to Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praise, like oblation, I present, and utter aloud my song, my fair hymn
							to the Victor.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							For Indra, who is Lord of old, the singers have decked their lauds with
							heart and mind and spirit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him then with my lips mine adoration, winning heaven's light, most
							excellent, I offer,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To magnify with songs of invocation and with fair hymns the Lord, most
							bounteous Giver.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even for him I frame a laud, as fashions the wright a chariot for the
							man who needs it,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Praises to him who gladly hears our praises, a hymn well-formed,
							all-moving, to wise Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							So with my tongue I deck, to please that Indra, my hymn, as 'twere a
							horse, through love of glory,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To reverence the Hero, bounteous Giver, famed far and wide, destroyer
							of the castles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even for him hath Tvastar forged the thunder, most deftly wrought,
							celestial, for the battle,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith he reached the vital parts of Vrtra, striking-the vast, the
							mighty with the striker.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							As soon as, at libations of his mother, great Visnu had drunk up the
							draught, he plundered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The dainty cates, the cooked mess; but One stronger transfixed the wild
							boar, shooting through the mountain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him, to Indra, when he slew the Dragon, the Dames, too, Consorts of
							the Gods, wove praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The mighty heaven and earth hath he encompassed: thy greatness heaven
							and earth, combined, exceed not.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, of a truth, his magnitude surpasseth the magnitude of earth,
							mid-air, and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, approved by all men, self-resplendent, waxed in his home,
							loud-voiced and strong for battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through his own strength Indra with bolt of thunder cut piece-meal
							Vrtra, drier up of waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He let the floods go free, like cows imprisoned, for glory, with a
							heart inclined to bounty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The rivers played, through his impetuous splendour, since with his bolt
							he compassed them on all sides.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Using his might and favouring him who worshipped, he made a ford,
							victorious, for Turviti.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vast, with thine ample power, with eager movement, against this Vrtra
							cast thy bolt of thunder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rend thou his joints, as of an ox, dissevered, with bolt oblique, that
							floods of rain may follow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sing with new lauds his exploits wrought aforetime, the deeds of him,
							yea, him who moveth swiftly,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, hurling forth his weapons in the battle, he with impetuous wrath
							lays low the foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							When he, yea, he, comes forth the firm. Set mountains and the whole
							heaven and earth, tremble for terror.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Nodhas, ever praising the protection of that dear Friend, gain
							quickly strength heroic.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now unto him of these things hath been given what he who rules alone
							o'er much, electeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra hath helped Etasa, Soma-presser, contending in the race of steeds
							with Surya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus to thee, Indra, yoker of Bay Coursers, the Gotamas have brought
							their prayers to please thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 61: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bestow upon them thought, decked with all beauty. May he, enriched with
							prayer, come soon and early.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 62
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LIKE Angiras a gladdening laud we ponder to him who loveth song,
							exceeding mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us sing glory to the far-famed Hero who must be praised with fair
							hymns by the singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unto the great bring ye great adoration, a chant with praise to him
							exceeding mighty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through whom our sires, Angirases, singing praises and knowing well the
							places, found the cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Indra and the Angirases desired it, Sarama found provision for her
							offspring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati cleft the mountain, found the cattle: the heroes shouted with
							the kine in triumph.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mid shout, loud shout, and roar, with the Navagvas, seven singers, hast
							thou, heavenly, rent the mountain;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast, with speeders, with Dasagvas, Indra, Sakra, with thunder
							rent obstructive Vala.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praised by Angirases, thou, foe-destroyer, hast, with the Dawn, Sun,
							rays, dispelled the darkness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou Indra, hast spread out the earth's high ridges, and firmly fixed
							the region under heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the deed most worthy of all honour, the fairest marvel of the
							Wonder-Worker,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							That, nigh where heaven bends down, he made four rivers flow full with
							waves that carry down sweet water.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unwearied, won with lauding hymns, he parted of old the ancient Pair,
							united ever.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							In highest sky like Bhaga, he the doer of marvels set both Dames and
							earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Still born afresh, young Dames, each in her manner, unlike in hue, the
							Pair in alternation
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Round heaven and earth from ancient time have travelled, Night with her
							dark limbs, Dawn with limbs of splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rich in good actions, skilled in operation, the Son with might
							maintains his perfect friendship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou in the raw cows, black of hue or ruddy, storest the ripe milk
							glossy white in colour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Their paths, of old connected, rest uninjured; they with great might
							preserve the immortal statutes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							For many thousand holy works the Sisters wait on the haughty Lord like
							wives and matrons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thoughts ancient, seeking wealth, with adoration, with newest lauds
							have sped to thee, O Mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							As yearning wives cleave to their yearning husband, so cleave our hymns
							to thee, O Lord most potent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong God, the riches which thy hands have holden from days of old
							have perished not nor wasted.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Splendid art thou, O Indra, wise, unbending: strengthen us with might,
							O Lord of Power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							O mighty Indra, Gotama's son Nodhas hath fashioned this new prayer to
							thee Eternal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 62: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sure leader, yoker of the Tawny Coursers. May he, enriched with prayer,
							come soon and early.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 63
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU art the Mighty One; when born, O Indra, with power thou
							terrifiedst earth and heaven;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, in their fear of thee, all firm-set mountains and monstrous
							creatures shook like dust before thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thy two wandering Bays thou drawest hither, thy praiser laid
							within thine arms the thunder,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith, O Much-invoked, in will resistless, thou smitest foemen down
							and many a castle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Faithful art thou, these thou defiest, Indra; thou art the Rbhus' Lord,
							heroic, victor.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, by his side, for young and glorious Kutsa, with steed and car in
							battle slewest Susna,
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							That, as a friend, thou furtheredst, O Indra, when, Thunderer, strong
							in act, thou crushedst Vrtra;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, Hero, thou, great-souled, with easy conquest didst rend the
							Dasyus in their
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							distant dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							This doest thou, and art not harmed, O Indra, e'en in the anger of the
							strongest mortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lay thou the race-course open for our horses: as with a club, slay,
							Thunder-armed! our foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hence men invoke thee, Indra, in the tumult of battle, in the
							light-bestowing conflict.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							This aid of thine, O Godlike One, was ever to be implored in deeds of
							might in combat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Warring for Purukutsa thou, O Indra, Thunder-armed! breakest down the
							seven castles;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Easily, for Sudas, like grass didst rend them, and out of need, King,
							broughtest gain to Puru.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, God who movest round about us, feed us with varied food
							plenteous as water-
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Food wherewithal, O Hero, thou bestowest vigour itself to flow to us
							for ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prayers have been made by Gotamas, O Indra, addressed to thee, with
							laud for thy Bay Horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 63: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring us in noble shape abundant riches. May he, enriched with prayer,
							come soon and early.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 64
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BRING for the manly host, wise and majestical, O Nodhas, for the Maruts
							bring thou a pure gift.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I deck my songs as one deft-handed, wise in mind prepares the water
							that hath power in solemn rites.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They spring to birth, the lofty Ones, the Bulls of Heaven, divine, the
							youths of Rudra, free from spot and stain;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The purifiers, shining brightly even as suns, awful of form like
							giants, scattering rain-drops down.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Young Rudras, demon-slayers, never growing old, they have waxed, even
							as mountains, irresistible.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							They make all beings tremble with their mighty strength, even the very
							strongest, both of earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With glittering ornaments they deck them forth for show; for beauty on
							their breasts they bind their chains of gold.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The lances on their shoulders pound to pieces; they were born together,
							of themselves, the Men of Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loud roarers, giving strength, devourers of the foe, they make the
							winds, they make the lightnings with their powers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The restless shakers drain the udders of the sky, and ever wandering
							round fill the earth full with milk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The bounteous Maruts with the fatness dropping milk fill full the
							waters which avail in solemn rites.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							They lead, as 'twere, the Strong Horse forth, that it may rain: they
							milk the thundering, the never-failing spring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mighty, with wondrous power and marvellously bright, selfstrong like
							mountains, ye glide swiftly on your way.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like the wild elephants ye eat the forests up when ye assume your
							strength among the bright red flames.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Exceeding wise they roar like lions mightily, they, all-possessing, are
							beauteous as antelopes;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Stirring the darkness with lances and spotted deer, combined as
							priests, with serpents' fury through their might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Heroes who march in companies, befriending man, with serpents' ire
							through strength, ye greet the earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Upon the seats, O Maruts, of your chariots, upon the cars stands
							lightning visible as light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lords of all riches, dwelling in the home of wealth, endowed with
							mighty vigour, singers loud of voice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Heroes, of powers infinite, armed with strong men's rings, the archers,
							they have laid the arrow on their arms.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who with golden fellies make the rain increase drive forward the
							big clouds like wanderers on the way.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Self-moving, brisk, unwearied, they o'erthrow the firm; the Maruts with
							bright lances make all things to reel.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							The progeny of Rudra we invoke with prayer, the brisk, the bright, the
							worshipful, the active Ones
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							To the strong band of Maruts cleave for happiness, the chasers of the
							sky, impetuous, vigorous.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Maruts, the man whom ye have guarded with your help, he verily in
							strength surpasseth all mankind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Spoil with his steeds he gaineth, treasure with his men; he winneth
							honourable strength and prospereth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Maruts, to the worshippers give glorious strength invincible in
							battle, brilliant, bringing wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Praiseworthy, known to all men. May we foster well, during a hundred
							winters, son and progeny.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Will ye then, O ye Maruts, grant us riches, durable, rich in men,
							defying onslaught.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 64: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							A hundred, thousandfold, ever increasing? May he, enriched with prayer,
							come soon and early.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 65
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ONE-MINDED, wise, they tracked thee like a thief lurking in dark cave
							with a stolen cow:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee claiming worship, bearing it to Gods: there nigh to thee sate all
							the Holy Ones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Gods approached the ways of holy Law; there was a gathering vast as
							heaven itself.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The waters feed with praise the growing Babe, born nobly in the womb,
							the seat of Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like grateful food, like some wide dwelling place, like a fruit-bearing
							hill, a wholesome stream.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a steed urged to run in swift career, rushing like Sindhu, who may
							check his course?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Kin as a brother to his sister floods, he eats the woods as a King eats
							the rich.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When through the forest, urged by wind, he spreads, verily Agni shears
							the hair of earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a swan sitting in the floods he pants wisest in mind mid men he
							wakes at morn.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 65: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							A Sage like Soma, sprung from Law, he grew like some young creature,
							mighty, shining far.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 66
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LIKE the Sun's glance, like wealth of varied sort, like breath which is
							the life, like one's own son,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a swift bird, a cow who yields her milk, pure and refulgent to the
							wood he speeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He offers safety like a pleasant home, like ripened corn, the Conqueror
							of men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a Seer lauding, famed among the folk; like a steed friendly he
							vouchsafes us power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With flame insatiate, like eternal might; caring for each one like a
							dame at home;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bright when he shines forth, whitish mid the folk, like a car,
							gold-decked, thundering to the fight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He strikes with terror like a dart shot forth, e'en like an archer's
							arrow tipped with flame;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Master of present and of future life, the maidens' lover and the
							matrons' Lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him lead all your ways: may we attain the kindled God as cows their
							home at eve.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 66: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He drives the flames below as floods their swell: the rays rise up to
							the fair place of heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 67
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							VICTORIOUS in the wood, Friend among men, ever he claims obedience as a
							King.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gracious like peace, blessing like mental power, Priest was he,
							offering-bearer, full of thought.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, bearing in his hand all manly might, crouched in the cavern, struck
							the Gods with fear.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men filled with understanding find him there, when they have sting
							prayers formed within their heart.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, like the Unborn, holds the broad earth up; and with effective
							utterance fixed the sky.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Agni, guard the spots which cattle love: thou, life of all, hast gone
							from lair to lair.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso hath known him dwelling in his lair, and hath approached the
							stream of holy Law,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They who release him, paying sacred rites,--truly to such doth he
							announce great wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who grows mightily in herbs, within each fruitful mother and each
							babe she bears,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 67: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wise, life of all men, in the waters' home,--for him have sages built
							as 'twere a seat.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 68
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COMMINGLING, restless, he ascends the sky, unveiling nights and all
							that stands or moves,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As he the sole God is preeminent in greatness among all these other
							Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							All men are joyful in thy power, O God, that living from the dry wood
							thou art born.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							All truly share thy Godhead while they keep, in their accustomed ways,
							eternal Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong is the thought of Law, the Law's behest; all works have they
							performed; he quickens all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whoso will bring oblation, gifts to thee, to him, bethinking thee,
							vouchsafe thou wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Seated as Priest with Manu's progeny, of all these treasures he alone
							is Lord.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men yearn for children to prolong their line, and are not disappointed
							in their hope.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eagerly they who hear his word fulfil his wish as sons obey their
							sire's behest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 68: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, rich in food, unbars his wealth like doors: he, the House-Friend,
							hath decked heaven's vault with stars.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 69
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BRIGHT, splendid, like Dawn's lover, he hath filled the two joined
							worlds as with the light of heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When born, with might thou hast encompassed them: Father of Gods, and
							yet their Son wast thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, the Sage, the humble, who discerns like the cow's udder, the
							sweet taste of food,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a bliss-giver to be drawn to men, sits gracious in the middle of
							the house.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born in the dwelling like a lovely son, pleased, like a strong steed,
							he bears on the folk.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time the men and I, with heroes, call, may Agni then gain all
							through Godlike power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							None breaks these holy laws of thine when thou hast granted audience to
							these chieftains here.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							This is thy boast, thou smotest with thy peers, and joined with heroes
							dravest off disgrace.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like the Dawn's lover, spreading light, well-known as hued like morn,
							may he remember me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 69: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							They, bearing of themselves, unbar the doors: they all ascend to the
							fair place of heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 70
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY we, the pious, win much food by prayer, may Agni with fair light
							pervade each act,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He the observer of the heavenly laws of Gods, and of the race of mortal
							man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who is germ of waters, germ of woods, germ of all things that move
							not and that move,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him even in the rock and in the house: Immortal One, he cares for
							all mankind.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni is Lord of riches for the man who serves him readily with sacred
							songs.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Protect these beings thou with careful thought, knowing the races both
							of Gods and men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whom many dawns and nights, unlike, make strong, whom, born in Law, all
							things that move and stand,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath been won, Herald who sits in light, making effectual all our
							holy works.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou settest value on our cows and woods: all shall bring tribute to us
							to the light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men have served thee in many and sundry spots, parting, as 'twere, an
							aged father's wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 70: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Like a brave archer, like one skilled and bold, a fierce avenger, so he
						shines in fight.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 71
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 71: Verse 1
				-
					-
