							Bring him with reverence hither, most propitious in sacrifices, true to
							Law, the herald;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							For Agni, when he seeks the Gods for mortals, knows them full well and
							worships them in spirit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For he is mental power, a man, and perfect; he is the bringer,
							friend-like, of the wondrous.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The pious Aryan tribes at sacrifices address them first to him who
							doeth marvels.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Agni, foe-destroyer, manliest Hero, accept with love our hymns and
							our devotion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may the liberal lords whose strength is strongest, urged by their
							riches, stir our thoughts with vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus Agni Jatavedas, true to Order, hath by the priestly Gotamas been
							lauded.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he augment in them splendour and vigour: observant, as he lists, he
							gathers increase.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 78
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 1
				-
					-
						O JATAVEDAS, keen and swift, we Gotamas with sacred song exalt thee for thy
						glories' sake.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee, as thou art, desiring wealth Gotama worships with his song:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							We laud thee for thy glories' sake.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							As such, like Angiras we call on thee best winner of the spoil:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							We laud thee for thy glories' sake.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee, best of Vrtra-slayers, thee who shakest off our Dasyu foes:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							We laud thee for thy glories' sake.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							A pleasant song to Agni we, sons of Rahugana, have sung:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							We laud thee for thy glories' sake.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 79
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HE in mid-air's expanse hath golden tresses; a raging serpent, like the
							rushing tempest:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Purely refulgent, knowing well the morning; like honourable dames,
							true, active workers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy well-winged flashes strengthen in their manner, when the black Bull
							hath bellowed round about us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With drops that bless and seem to smile he cometh: the waters fall, the
							clouds utter their thunder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When he comes streaming with the milk of worship, conducting by
							directest paths of Order
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aryaman, Mitra, Varuna, Parijman fill the hide full where lies the
							nether press-stone.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, thou who art the lord of wealth in kine, thou Son of Strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe to us, O Jatavedas, high renown.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, Agni, kindled, good and wise, must be exalted in our song:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shine, thou of many forms, shine radiantly on us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, shining of thyself by night and when the morning breaks,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Burn, thou whose teeth are sharp, against the Raksasas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adorable in all our rites, favour us, Agni, with thine aid,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the great hymn is chanted forth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring to us ever-conquering wealth, wealth, Agni, worthy of our choice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							In all our frays invincible.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us, O Agni, through thy grace wealth that supporteth all our life,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy favour so that we may live.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Gotama, desiring bliss present thy songs composed with care
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Agni of the pointed flames.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the man fall, O Agni, who near or afar assaileth us:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Do thou increase and prosper us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Keen and swift Agni, thousand-eyed, chaseth the Raksasas afar:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 79: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							He singeth, herald meet for lauds.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 80
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THUS in the Soma, in wild joy the Brahman hath exalted thee:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, mightiest thunder-armed, hast driven by force the Dragon from the
							earth, lauding thine own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mighty flowing Soma-draught, brought by the Hawk, hath gladdened
							thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That in thy strength, O Thunderer, thou hast struck down Vrtra from the
							floods, lauding thine own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Go forward, meet the foe, be bold; thy bolt of thunder is not checked.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Manliness, Indra, is thy might: stay Vrtra, make the waters thine,
							lauding thine own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou smotest Vrtra from the earth, smotest him, Indra, from the sky.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let these life-fostering waters flow attended by the Marut host,
							lauding thine own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The wrathful Indra with his bolt of thunder rushing on the foe,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Smote fierce on trembling Vrtra's back, and loosed the waters free to
							run, lauding his own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							With hundred-jointed thunderbolt Indra hath struck him on the back,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, while rejoicing in the juice, seeketh prosperity for friends,
							lauding his own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, unconquered might is thine, Thunderer, Caster of the Stone;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thou with thy surpassing power smotest to death the guileful beast,
							lauding thine own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far over ninety spacious floods thy thunderbolts were cast abroad:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Great, Indra, is thy hero might, and strength is seated in thine arms,
							lauding thine own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Laud him a thousand all at once, shout twenty forth the hymn of praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hundreds have sung aloud to him, to Indra hath the prayer been raised,
							lauding his own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra hath smitten down the power of Vrtra,--might with stronger might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							This was his manly exploit, he slew Vrtra and let loose the floods,
							lauding his own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, even this great Pair of Worlds trembled in terror at thy wrath,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, Indra, Thunderer, Marut-girt, thou slewest Vrtra in thy strength,
							lauding thine own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							But Vrtra scared not Indra with his shaking or his thunder roar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							On him that iron thunderbolt fell fiercely with its thousand points,
							lauding his own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							When with the thunder thou didst make thy dart and Vrtra meet in war,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy might, O Indra, fain to slay the Dragon, was set firm in heaven,
							lauding thine own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							When at thy shout, O Thunder-armed, each thing both fixed and moving
							shook,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							E'en Tvastar trembled at thy wrath and quaked with fear because of
							thee, lauding thine own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							There is not, in our knowledge, one who passeth Indra in his strength:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							In him the Deities have stored manliness, insight, power and might,
							lauding his own imperial sway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Still as of old, whatever rite Atharvan, Manus sire of all,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 80: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dadhyach performed, their prayer and praise united in that Indra meet,
							lauding his own imperial sway.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 81
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE men have lifted Indra up, the Vrtra slayer, to joy and strength:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him, verily, we invocate in battles whether great or small: be he our
							aid in deeds of might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Hero, art a warrior, thou art giver of abundant spoil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strengthening e'en the feeble, thou aidest the sacrificer, thou givest
							the offerer ample wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When war and battles are on foot, booty is laid before the bold.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yoke thou thy wildly-rushing Bays. Whom wilt thou slay and whom enrich?
							Do thou, O Indra, make us rich.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mighty through wisdom, as he lists, terrible, he hath waxed in
							strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of Bay Steeds, strong-jawed, sublime, he in joined hands for
							glory's sake hath grasped his iron thunderbolt.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He filled the earthly atmosphere and pressed against the lights in
							heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							None like thee ever hath been born, none, Indra, will be born like
							thee. Thou hast waxed mighty over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he who to the offerer gives the foeman's man-sustaining food,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Indra lend his aid to us. Deal forth--abundant is thy wealth--that
							in thy bounty I may share.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, righteous-hearted, at each time of rapture gives us herds of kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gather in both thy hands for us treasures of many hundred sorts.
							Sharpen thou us, and bring us wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Refresh thee, Hero, with the juice outpoured for bounty and for
							strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							We know thee Lord of ample store, to thee have sent our hearts'
							desires: be therefore our Protector thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							These people, Indra, keep for thee all that is worthy of thy choice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 81: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Discover thou, as Lord, the wealth of men who offer up no gifts: bring
							thou to us this wealth of theirs.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 82
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GRACIOUSLY listen to our songs, Maghavan, be not negligent.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As thou hast made us full of joy and lettest us solicit thee, now,
							Indra, yoke thy two Bay Steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well have they eaten and rejoiced; the friends have risen and passed
							away.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The sages luminous in themselves have. praised thee with their latest
							hymn. Now, Indra, yoke thy two Bay Steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Maghavan, we will reverence thee who art so fair to look upon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thus praised, according to our wish come now with richly laden car.
							Now, Indra, yoke thy two Bay Steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He will in very truth ascend the powerful car that finds the kine,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who thinks upon the well-filled bowl, the Tawny Coursers' harnesser.
							Now, Indra, yoke thy two Bay Steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let, Lord of Hundred Powers, thy Steeds be harnessed on the right and
							left.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therewith in rapture of the juice, draw near to thy beloved Spouse.
							Now, Indra, yoke thy two Bay Steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 82: Verse 6
