					Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, Maruts, on the steeps ye pile the moving cloud, ye are like birds
							on whatsoever path it be.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Clouds everywhere shed forth the rain upon your cars. Drop fatness,
							honey-hued, for him who sings your praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Earth at their racings trembles as if weak and worn, when on their ways
							they yoke their cars for victory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							They, sportive, loudly roaring, armed with glittering spears, shakers
							of all, themselves admire their mightiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Self-moving is that youthful band, with spotted steeds; thus it hath
							lordly sway, endued with power and might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Truthful art thou, and blameless, searcher out of sin: so thou, Strong
							Host, wilt be protector of this prayer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							We speak by our descent from our primeval Sire; our tongue, when we
							behold the Soma, stirs itself.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, shouting, they had joined Indra in toil of fight, then only they
							obtained their sacrificial names.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Splendours they gained for glory, they who wear bright rings; rays they
							obtained, and men to celebrate their praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 87: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Armed with their swords, impetuous and fearing naught, they have
							possessed the Maruts' own beloved home.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 88
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COME hither, Maruts, on your lightning laden cars, sounding with sweet
							songs, armed with lances, winged with steeds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fly unto us with noblest food, like birds, O ye of mighty power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With their red-hued or, haply, tawny coursers which speed their
							chariots on, they come for glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brilliant like gold is he who holds the thunder. Earth have they
							smitten with the chariot's felly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For beauty ye have swords upon your bodies. As they stir woods so may
							they stir our spirits.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							For your sake, O ye Maruts very mighty and well-born, have they set the
							stone, in motion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The days went round you and came back O yearners, back, to this prayer
							and to this solemn worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Gotamas making their prayer with singing have pushed the well's lid
							up to drink the water.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							No hymn way ever known like this aforetime which Gotama sang forth for
							you, O Maruts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time upon your golden wheels he saw you, wild boars rushing about
							with tusks of iron.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you this freshening draught of Soma rusheth, O Maruts, like the
							voice of one who prayeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 88: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							It rusheth freely from our hands as these libations wont to flow.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 89
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY powers auspicious come to us from every side, never deceived,
							unhindered, and victorious,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That the Gods ever may be with us for our gain, our guardians day by
							day unceasing in their care.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the auspicious favour of the Gods be ours, on us descend the bounty
							of the righteous Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The friendship of the Gods have we devoutly sought: so may the Gods
							extend our life that we may live.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							We call them hither with a hymn of olden time, Bhaga, the friendly
							Daksa, Mitra, Aditi,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aryaman, Varuna, Soma, the Asvins. May Sarasvati, auspicious, grant
							felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Wind waft to us that pleasant medicine, may Earth our Mother
							give it, and our Father Heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And the joy-giving stones that press the Soma's juice. Asvins, may ye,
							for whom our spirits long, hear this.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him we invoke for aid who reigns supreme, the Lord of all that stands
							or moves, inspirer of the soul,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							That Pusan may promote the increase of our wealth, our keeper and our
							guard infallible for our good.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Illustrious far and wide, may Indra prosper us: may Pusan prosper us,
							the Master of all wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Tarksya with uninjured fellies prosper us: Brhaspati vouchsafe to
							us prosperity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Maruts, Sons of Prsni, borne by spotted steeds, moving in glory,
							oft visiting holy rites,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sages whose tongue is Agni, brilliant as the Sun,--hither let all the
							Gods for our protection come.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods, may we with our ears listen to what is good, and with our eyes
							see what is good, ye Holy Ones.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With limbs and bodies firm may we extolling you attain the term of life
							appointed by the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							A hundred autumns stand before us, O ye Gods, within whose space ye
							bring our bodies to decay;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Within whose space our sons become fathers in turn. Break ye not in the
							midst our course of fleeting life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aditi is the heaven, Aditi is mid-air, Aditi is the Mother and the Sire
							and Son.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 89: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aditi is all Gods, Aditi five-classed men, Aditi all that hath been
							born and shall be born.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 90
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY Varuna with guidance straight, and Mitra lead us, he who knows,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Aryaman in accord with Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For they are dealers forth of wealth, and, not deluded, with their
							might
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard evermore the holy laws.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shelter may they vouchsafe to us, Immortal Gods to mortal men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Chasing our enemies away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May they mark out our paths to bliss, Indra, the Maruts, Pusan,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							and Bhaga, the Gods to be adored.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, Pusan, Visnu, ye who run your course, enrich our hymns with kine;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bless us with all prosperity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The winds waft sweets, the rivers pour sweets for the man who keeps the
							Law
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may the plants be sweet for us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sweet be the night and sweet the dawns, sweet the terrestrial
							atmosphere;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sweet be our Father Heaven to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the tall tree be full of sweets for us, and full of sweets the Sun:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May our milch-kine be sweet for us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be Mitra gracious unto us, and Varuna and Aryaman:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 90: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, Brhaspati be kind, and Visnu of the mighty stride.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 91
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Soma, art preeminent for wisdom; along the straightest path thou
							art our leader.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our wise forefathers by thy guidance, Indu, dealt out among the Gods
							their share of treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou by thine insight art most wise, O Soma, strong by thine energies
							and all possessing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mighty art thou by all thy powers and greatness, by glories art thou
							glorious, guide of mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine are King Varuna's eternal statutes, lofty and deep, O Soma, is
							thy glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							All-pure art thou like Mitra the beloved, adorable, like Aryaman, O
							Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With all thy glories on the earth, in heaven, on mountains, in the
							plants, and in the waters,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With all of these, well-pleased and not in anger, accept, O royal Soma,
							our oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Soma, art the Lord of heroes, King, yea, Vrtra-slayer thou:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art auspicious energy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							And, Soma, let it be thy wish that we may live and may not die:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Praise-loving Lord of plants art thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him who keeps the law, both old and young, thou givest happiness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And energy that he may live.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guard us, King Soma, on all sides from him who threatens us: never let
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The friend of one like thee be harmed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							With those delightful aids which thou hast, Soma, for the worshipper,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even with those protect thou us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Accepting this our sacrifice and this our praise, O Soma, come,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							And be thou nigh to prosper us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well-skilled in speech we magnify thee, Soma, with our sacred songs:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come thou to us, most gracious One.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Enricher, healer of disease, wealth-finder, prospering our store,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be, Soma, a good Friend to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma, be happy in our heart, as milch-kine in the grassy meads,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							As a young man in his own house.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Soma, God, the mortal man who in thy friendship hath delight,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him doth the mighty Sage befriend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Save us from slanderous reproach, keep us., O Soma, from distress:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be unto us a gracious Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma, wax great. From every side may vigorous powers unite in thee:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be in the gathering-place of strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wax, O most gladdening Soma, great through all thy rays of light, and
							be
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							A Friend of most illustrious fame to prosper us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							In thee be juicy nutriments united, and powers and mighty foe-subduing
							vigour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Waxing to immortality, O Soma: win highest glories for thyself in
							heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Such of thy glories as with poured oblations men honour, may they all
							invest our worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth-giver, furtherer with troops of heroes, sparing the brave, come,
							Soma, to our houses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him who worships Soma gives the milch-cow, a fleet steed and a man
							of active knowledge,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Skilled in home duties, meet for holy synod, for council meet, a glory
							to his father.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Invincible in fight, saver in battles, guard of our camp, winner of
							light and water,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Born amid hymns, well-housed, exceeding famous, victor, in thee will we
							rejoice, O Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							These herbs, these milch-kine, and these running waters, all these, O
							Soma, thou hast generated.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							The spacious firmament bast thou expanded, and with the light thou hast
							dispelled the darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do thou, God Soma, with thy Godlike spirit, victorious, win for us a
							share of riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 91: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let none prevent thee: thou art Lord of valour. Provide for both sides
							in the fray for booty.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 92
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE Dawns have raised their banner; in the eastern half of the
							mid-air they spread abroad their shining light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like heroes who prepare their weapons for the war, onward they come
							bright red in hue, the Mother Cows.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Readily have the purple beams of light shot up; the Red Cows have they
							harnessed, easy to be yoked.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Dawns have brought distinct perception as before: red-hued, they
							have attained their fulgent brilliancy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							They sing their song like women active in their tasks, along their
							common path hither from far away,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bringing refreshment to the liberal devotee, yea, all things to the
							worshipper who pours the juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							She, like a dancer, puts her broidered garments on: as a cow yields her
							udder so she bares her breast.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Creating light for all the world of life, the Dawn hath laid the
							darkness open as the cows their stall.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							We have beheld the brightness of her shining; it spreads and drives
							away the darksome monster.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like tints that deck the Post at sacrifices, Heaven's Daughter hath
							attained her wondrous splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							We have o'erpast the limit of this darkness; Dawn breaking forth again
							brings clear perception.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							She like a flatterer smiles in light for glory, and fair of face hath
							wakened to rejoice us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Gotamas have praised Heaven's radiant Daughter, the leader of the
							charm of pleasant voices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dawn, thou conferrest on us strength with offspring and men,
							conspicuous with kine and horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O thou who shinest forth in wondrous glory, urged onward by thy
							strength, auspicious Lady,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dawn, may I gain that wealth, renowned and ample, in brave sons, troops
							of slaves, far-famed for horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bending her looks on all the world, the Goddess shines, widely
							spreading with her bright eye westward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Waking to motion every living creature, she understands the voice of
							each adorer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ancient of days, again again born newly, decking her beauty with the
							self-same raiment.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Goddess wastes away the life of mortals, like a skilled hunter
							cutting birds in pieces.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							She hath appeared discovering heaven's borders: to the far distance she
							drives off her Sister.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Diminishing the days of human creatures, the Lady shines with all her
							lover's splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							The bright, the blessed One shines forth extending her rays like kine,
							as a flood rolls his waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Never transgressing the divine commandments, she is beheld visible with
							the sunbeams.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Dawn enriched with ample wealth, bestow on us the wondrous gift
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith we may support children and children's sons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou radiant mover of sweet sounds, with wealth of horses and of kine
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shine thou on us this day, O Dawn auspiciously.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Dawn enriched with holy rites, yoke to thy car thy purple steeds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							And then bring thou unto us all felicities.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Asvins wonderful in act, do ye unanimous direct
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your chariot to our home wealthy in kine and gold.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye who brought down the hymn from heaven, a light that giveth light to
							man,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Do ye, O Asvins, bring strength hither unto us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither may they who wake at dawn bring, to drink Soma both the Gods
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 92: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Health-givers Wonder-Workers, borne on paths of gold.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 93
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI and Soma, mighty Pair, graciously hearken to my call,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accept in friendly wise my hymn, and prosper him who offers gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The man who honours you to-day, Agni and Soma, with this hymn,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bestow on him heroic strength, increase of kine, and noble steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The man who offers holy oil and burnt oblations unto you,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni and Soma, shall enjoy great strength, with offspring, all his
							life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni and Soma, famed is that your. prowess wherewith ye stole the kine,
							his food, from Pani.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye caused the brood of Brsaya to perish; ye found the light, the single
							light for many.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni and Soma, joined in operation ye have set up the shining lights in
							heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							From curse and from reproach, Agni and Soma, ye freed the rivers that
							were bound in fetters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							One of you Matarisvan brought from heaven, the Falcon rent the other
							from the mountain.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strengthened by holy prayer Agni and Soma have made us ample room for
							sacrificing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Taste, Agni, Soma, this prepared oblation; accept it, Mighty Ones, and
							let it please you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us good protection and kind favour: grant to the sacrificer
							health and riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso with oil and poured oblation honours, with God-devoted heart,
							Agni and Soma,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Protect his sacrifice, preserve him from distress, grant to the
							sacrificer great felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Invoked together, mates in wealth, Agni-Soma, accept our hymns:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Together be among the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni and Soma, unto him who worships you with holy oil
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shine forth an ample recompense.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni and Sonia, be ye pleased with these oblations brought to you,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							And come, together, nigh to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni and Soma, cherish well our horses, and let our cows be fat who
							yield oblations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 93: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant power to us and to our wealthy patrons, and cause our holy rites
							to be successful.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 94
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FOR Jatavedas worthy of our praise will we frame with our mind this
							eulogy as 'twere a car.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For good, in his assembly, is this care of ours. Let us not, in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The man for whom thou sacrificest prospereth, dwelleth without a foe,
							gaineth heroic might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He waxeth strong, distress never approacheth him. Let us not, in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we have power to kindle thee. Fulfil our thoughts. In thee the Gods
							eat the presented offering,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring hither the Adityas, for we long for them. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							We will bring fuel and prepare burnt offerings, reminding thee at each
							successive festival.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fulfil our thought that so we may prolong our lives. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							His ministers move forth, the guardians of the folk, protecting
							quadruped and biped with their rays.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mighty art thou, the wondrous herald of the Dawn. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art Presenter and the chief Invoker, thou Director, Purifier,
							great High Priest by birth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Knowing all priestly work thou perfectest it, Sage. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lovely of form art thou, alike on every side; though far, thou shinest
							brightly as if close at hand.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							O God, thou seest through even the dark of night. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods, foremost be his car who pours libations out, and let our hymn
							prevail o'er evil-hearted men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Attend to this our speech and make it prosper well. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Smite with thy weapons those of evil speech and thought, devouring
							demons, whether near or tar away.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then to the singer give free way for sacrifice. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							When to thy chariot thou hadst yoked two red steeds and two ruddy
							steeds, wind-sped, thy roar was like a bull's.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou with smoke-bannered flame attackest forest trees. Let us not in
							thy friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then at thy roar the very birds are terrified, when, eating-up the
							grass, thy sparks fly forth abroad.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then is it easy for thee and thy car to pass. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							He hath the Power to soothe Mitra and Varuna: wonderful is the Maruts'
							wrath when they descend.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be gracious; let their hearts he turned to us again. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art a God, thou art the wondrous Friend of Gods, the Vasu of the
							Vasus, fair in sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Under, thine own most wide protection may we dwell. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is thy grace that, kindled in thine own abode, invoked with Soma
							thou soundest forth most benign,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou givest wealth and treasure to the worshipper. Let us not in thy
							friendship, Agni, suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							To whom thou, Lord of goodly riches, grantest freedom from every sin
							with perfect wholeness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom with good strength thou quikenest, with children and wealth--may
							we be they, Eternal Being.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Such, Agni, thou who knowest all good fortune, God, lengthen here the
							days of our existence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 94: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 95
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To fair goals travel Two unlike in semblance: each in succession
							nourishes an infant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							One bears a Godlike Babe of golden colour; bright and fair-shining, is
							he with the other.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tvastar's ten daughters, vigilant and youthful, produced this Infant
							borne to sundry quarters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							They bear around him whose long flames are pointed, fulgent among
							mankind with native splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three several places of his birth they honour, in mid-air, in the
							heaven, and in the waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Governing in the east of earthly regions, the seasons hath he
							stablished in their order.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who of you knows this secret One? The Infant by his own nature hath
							brought forth his Mothers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The germ of many, from the waters' bosom he goes forth, wise and great,
							of Godlike nature.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Visible, fair, he grows in native brightness uplifted in the lap of
							waving waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When he was born both Tvastar's worlds were frightened: they turn to
							him and reverence the Lion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Two auspicious Ones, like women, tend him: like lowing cows they
							seek him in their manner.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He is the Lord of Might among the mighty; him, on the right, they balm
							with their oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like Savitar his arms with might he stretches; awful, he strives
							grasping the world's two borders.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He forces out from all a brilliant vesture, yea, from his Mothers draws
							he forth new raiment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							He makes him a most noble form of splendour, decking him in his home
							with milk and waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Sage adorns the depths of air with wisdom: this is the meeting
							where the Gods are worshipped.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wide through the firmament spreads forth triumphant the far-resplendent
							strength of thee the Mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Kindled by us do thou preserve us, Agni, with all thy self-bright
							undiminished succours.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							In dry spots he makes stream, and course, and torrent, and inundates
							the earth with floods that glisten.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							All ancient things within his maw he gathers, and moves among the new
							fresh-sprouting grasses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fed with our fuel, purifying Agni, so blaze to us auspiciously for
							glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 95: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 96
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HE in the ancient way by strength engendered, lo! straight hath taken
							to himself all wisdom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The waters and the bowl have made him friendly. The Gods possessed the
							wealth bestowing Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							At Ayu's ancient call he by his wisdom gave all this progeny of men
							their being,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, by refulgent light, heaven and the waters. The Gods possessed the
							wealth. bestowing Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praise him, ye Aryan folk, as chief performer of sacrifice adored and
							ever toiling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well-tended, Son of Strength, the Constant Giver. The Gods possessed
							the wealth bestowing Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Matarisvan rich in wealth and treasure, light-winner, finds a
							pathway for his offspring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard of our folk, Father of earth and heaven. The Gods possessed the
							wealth bestowing Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Night and Dawn, changing each the other's colour, meeting together
							suckle one same Infant:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Golden between the heaven and earth he shineth. The Gods possessed the
							wealth bestowing Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Root of wealth, gathering-place of treasures, banner of sacrifice, who
							grants the suppliant's wishes:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Preserving him as their own life immortal, the Gods possessed the
							wealth-bestowing Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now and of old the home of wealth, the mansion of what is born and what
							was born aforetime,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard of what is and what will be hereafter,--the Gods possessed the
							wealth bestowing Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Wealth-Giver grant us conquering riches; may the Wealth-Giver
							grant us wealth with heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the Wealth-Giver grant us food with offspring, and length of days
							may the Wealth-Giver send us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fed with our fuel, purifying Agni, so blaze to us auspiciously for
							glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 96: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 97
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							CHASING with light our sin away, O Agni, shine thou wealth on us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May his light chase our sin away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For goodly fields, for pleasant homes, for wealth we sacrifice to thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May his light chase our sin away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Best praiser of all these be he; foremost, our chiefs who sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May his light chase our sin away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							So that thy worshippers and we, thine, Agni, in our sons may live.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May his light chase our sin away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As ever-conquering Agni's beams of splendour go to every side,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							May his light chase our sin away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To every side thy face is turned, thou art triumphant everywhere.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May his light chase our sin away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O thou whose face looks every way, bear us past foes as in a ship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May his light chase our sin away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							As in a ship, convey thou us for our advantage o'er the flood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 97: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May his light chase our sin away.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 98
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 98: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 98: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							STILL in Vaisvanara's grace may we continue: yea, he is King supreme
							o'er all things living.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 98: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sprung hence to life upon this All he looketh. Vaisvanara hath rivalry
							with Surya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 98: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 98: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Present in heaven, in earth, all-present Agni,--all plants that grow on
							ground hath he pervaded.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 98: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni, may Vaisvanara with vigour, present, preserve us day and
							night from foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 98: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 98: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be this thy truth, Vaisvanara, to us-ward: let wealth in rich abundance
							gather round us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 98: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 99
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 99: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 99: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FOR Jatavedas let us press the Soma: may he consume the wealth of the
							malignant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 99: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni carry us through all our troubles, through grief as in a boat
							across the river.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 100
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY he who hath his home with strength, the Mighty, the King supreme of
							earth and spacious heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of true power, to he invoked in battles,--may Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whose way is unattainable like Surya's: he in each fight is the strong
							Vrtra-slayer,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mightiest with his Friends in his own courses. May Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whose paths go forth in their great might resistless, forthmilking, as
							it were, heaven's genial moisture.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With manly strength triumphant, foe-subduer,--may Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Among Angirases he was the chiefest, a Friend with friends, mighty amid
							the mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Praiser mid praisers, honoured most of singers. May Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong with the Rudras as with his own children, in manly battle
							conquering his foemen '
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With his close comrades doing deeds of glory,--may Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Humbler of pride, exciter of the conflict, the Lord of heroes, God
							invoked of many,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he this day gain with our men the sunlight. May Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							His help hath made him cheerer in the battle, the folk have made him
							guardian of their comfort.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sole Lord is he of every holy service. May Indra, girt by Maruts, be
							our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the Hero, on high days of prowess, heroes for help and booty
							shall betake them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath found light even in the blinding darkness. May Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							He with his left hand checketh even the mighty, and with his right hand
							gathereth up the booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even with the humble he acquireth riches. May Indra, girt by Maruts, be
							our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							With hosts on foot and cars he winneth treasures: well is he known this
							day by all the people.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							With manly might he conquereth those who hate him. May Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							When in his ways with kinsmen or with strangers he speedeth to the
							fight, invoked of many,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							For gain of waters, and of sons and grandsons, may Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Awful and fierce, fiend-slayer, thunder-wielder, with boundless
							knowledge, hymned by hundreds, mighty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							In strength like Soma, guard of the Five Peoples, may Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Winning the light, hitherward roars his thunder like the terrific
							mighty voice of Heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rich gifts and treasures evermore attend him. May Indra, girt by
							Maruts, be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whose home eternal through his strength surrounds him on every side,
							his laud, the earth and heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, delighted with our service, save us. May Indra, girt by Maruts,
							be our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							The limit of whose power not Gods by Godhead, nor mortal men have
							reached, nor yet the Waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Both Earth and Heaven in vigour he surpasseth. May Indra, girt by
							Maruts, he our succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							The red and tawny mare, blaze-marked, high standing, celestial who, to
							bring Rjrasva riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drew at the pole the chariot yoked with stallions, joyous, among the
							hosts of men was noted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Varsagiras unto thee, O Indra, the Mighty One, sing forth this laud
							to please thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rjrasva with his fellows, Ambarisa, Suradhas, Sahadeva, Bhayamana.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, much invoked, hath slain Dasyus and Simyus, after his wont, and
							laid them low with arrows.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							The mighty Thunderer with his fair-complexioned friends won the land,
							the sunlight, and the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra evermore be our protector, and unimperilled may we win the
							booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 100: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 101
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING, with oblation, praise to him who maketh glad, who with Rjisvan
							drove the dusky brood away.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fain for help, him the strong whose right hand wields the bolt, him
							girt by Maruts we invoke to be our Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, who with triumphant wrath smote Vyamsa down, and Sambara, and
							Pipru the unrighteous one;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who extirpated Susna the insatiate,--him girt by Maruts we invoke to be
							our Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He whose great work of manly might is heaven and earth, and Varuna and
							Surya keep his holy law;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, whose law the rivers follow as they flow,--him girt by Maruts we
							invoke to be our Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who is Lord and Master of the steeds and kine, honoured--the firm
							and sure--at every holy act;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Stayer even of the strong who pours no offering out,--him girt by
							Maruts we invoke to be our Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who is Lord of all the world that moves and breathes, who for the
							Brahman first before all found the Cows;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra who cast the Dasyus down beneath his feet,--him girt by Maruts we
							invoke to be our Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whom cowards must invoke and valiant men of war, invoked by those who
							conquer and by those who flee;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, to whom all beings turn their constant thought,--him girt by
							Maruts we invoke to be our Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Refulgent in the Rudras' region he proceeds, and with the Rudras
							through the wide space speeds the Dame.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The hymn of praise extols Indra the far-renowned: him girt by Maruts we
							invoke to be our Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O girt by Maruts, whether thou delight thee in loftiest gathering-place
							or lowly dwelling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come thence unto our rite, true boon-best-ower: through love of thee
							have we prepared oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							We, fain for thee, strong Indra, have pressed Soma, and, O thou sought
							with prayer, have made oblations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now at this sacrifice, with all thy Maruts, on sacred grass, O
							team-borne God, rejoice thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rejoice thee with thine own Bay Steeds, O Indra, unclose thy jaws and
							let thy lips be open.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou with the fair cheek, let thy Bay Steeds bring thee: gracious to
							us, he pleased with our oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guards of the camp whose praisers are the Maruts, may we through Indra,
							get ourselves the booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 101: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 102
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee the Mighty One I bring this mighty hymn, for thy desire hath
							been gratified by my laud.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							In Indra, yea in him victorious through his strength, the Gods have
							joyed at feast and when the Soma flowed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Seven Rivers bear his glory far and wide, and heaven and sky and
							earth display his comely form.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Sun and Moon in change alternate run their course, that we, O
							Indra, may behold and may have faith.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Maghavan, grant us that same car to bring us spoil, thy conquering car
							in which we joy in shock of fight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, whom our hearts praise highly in the war, grant shelter,
							Maghavan, to us who love thee well.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Encourage thou our side in every fight: may we, with thee for our ally,
							conquer the foeman's host.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, bestow on us joy and felicity break down, O Maghavan, the vigour
							of our foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							For here in divers ways these men invoking thee, holder of treasures,
							sing hymns to win thine aid.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ascend the car that thou mayest bring spoil to us, for, Indra, thy fixt
							winneth the victory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							His arms win kine, his power is boundless in each act best, with a
							hundred helps waker of battle's din
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is Indra: none may rival him in mighty strength. Hence, eager for the
							spoil the people call on him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy glory, Maghavan, exceeds a hundred yea, more than a hundred, than a
							thousand mid the folk,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The great bowl hath inspirited thee boundlessly: so mayst thou slay the
							Vrtras breaker-down of forts!
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of thy great might there is a three counterpart, the three earths, Lord
							men and the three realms of light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Above this whole world, Indra, thou hast waxen great: without a foe art
							thou, nature, from of old.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							We invocate thee first among the Deities: thou hast become a mighty
							Conquer in fight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Indra fill with spirit this our singer's heart, and make our car
							impetuous, foremost in attack.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast prevailed, and hast not kept the booty back, in trifling
							battles in those of great account.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							We make thee keen, the Mighty One, succour us: inspire us, Maghavan,
							when we defy the foe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra evermore be our Protector, and unimperilled may we win the
							booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 102: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 103
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THAT highest Indra-power of thine is distant: that which is here sages
							possessed aforetime.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							This one is on the earth, in heaven the other, and both unite as flag
							with flag in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He spread the wide earth out and firmly fixed it, smote with his
							thunderbolt and loosed the waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Maghavan with his puissance struck down Ahi, rent Rauhina to death and
							slaughtered Vyamsa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Armed with his bolt and trusting in his prowess he wandered shattering
							the forts of Dasas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cast thy dart, knowing, Thunderer, at the Dasyu; increase the Arya's
							might and glory, Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For him who thus hath taught these human races, Maghavan, bearing a
							fame-worthy title,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thunderer, drawing nigh to slay the Dasyus, hath given himself the name
							of Son for glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							See this abundant wealth that he possesses, and put your trust in
							Indra's hero vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He found the cattle, and he found the horses, he found the plants, the
							forests and the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the truly strong, whose deeds are many, to him the strong Bull
							let us pour the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Hero, watching like a thief in ambush, goes parting the possessions
							of the godless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well didst thou do that hero deed, O Indra, in waking with thy bolt the
							slumbering Ahi.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							in thee, delighted, Dames divine rejoiced them, the flying Maruts and
							all Gods were joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							As thou hast smitten Susna, Pipru, Vrtra and Kuyava, and Sambara's
							forts O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 103: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 104
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE altar hath been made for thee to rest on: come like a panting
							courser and be seated.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Loosen thy flying Steeds, set free thy Horses who bear thee swiftly
							nigh at eve and morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							These men have come to Indra for assistance: shall he not quickly come
							upon these pathways?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the Gods quell the fury of the Dasa, and may they lead our folk to
							happy fortune.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who hath only wish as his possession casts on himself, casts foam
							amid the waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Both wives of Kuyava in milk have bathed them: may they be drowned
							within the depth of Sipha.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This hath his kinship checked who lives beside us: with ancient streams
							forth speeds and rules the Hero,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Añjasi, Kulisi, and Virapatni, delighting him, bear milk upon their
							waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soon as this Dasyu's traces were discovered, as she who knows her home,
							he sought the dwelling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now think thou of us, Maghavan, nor cast us away as doth a profligate
							his treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, as such, give us a share of sunlight, of waters, sinlessness,
							and reputation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Do thou no harm to our yet unborn offspring: our trust is in thy mighty
							Indra-power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now we, I think, in thee as such have trusted: lead us on, Mighty One,
							to ample riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							In no unready house give us, O Indra invoked of many, food and drink
							when hungry.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Slay us not, Indra; do not thou forsake us: steal not away the joys
							which we delight in.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rend not our unborn brood, strong Lord of Bounty! our vessels with the
							life that is within them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to us; they have called thee Soma-lover: here is the pressed
							juice. Drink thereof for rapture.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 104: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Widely-capacious, pour it down within thee, and, invocated, hear us
							like a Father.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 105
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITHIN the waters runs the Moon, he with the beauteous wings in heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye lightnings with your golden wheels, men find not your abiding-place.
							Mark this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surely men crave and gain their wish. Close to her husband clings the
							wife.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, in embraces intertwined, both give and take the bliss of love.
							Mark this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O never may that light, ye Gods, fall from its station in the sky.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ne'er fail us one like Soma sweet, the spring of our felicity. Mark
							this my woe ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I ask the last of sacrifice. As envoy he shall tell it forth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where is the ancient law divine? Who is its new diffuser now? Mark this
							my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Gods who yonder have your home in the three lucid realms of heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							What count ye truth and what untruth? Where is mine ancient call on
							you? Mark this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							What is your firm support of Law? What Varuna's observant eye?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							How may we pass the wicked on the path of mighty Aryaman? Mark this my
							woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							I am the man who sang of old full many a laud when Soma flowed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yet torturing cares consume me as the wolf assails the thirsty deer.
							Mark this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like rival wives on every side enclosing ribs oppress me sore.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Satakratu, biting cares devour me, singer of thy praise, as rats
							devour the weaver's threads. Mark this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where those seven rays are shining, thence my home and family extend.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							This Trta Aptya knoweth well, and speaketh out for brotherhood. Mark
							this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May those five Bulls which stand on high full in the midst of mighty
							heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Having together swiftly borne my praises to the Gods, return. Mark this
							my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							High in the mid ascent of heaven those Birds of beauteous pinion sit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Back from his path they drive the wolf as he would cross the restless
							floods. Mark this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Firm is this new-wrought hymn of praise, and meet to be told forth, O
							Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							The flowing of the floods is Law, Truth is the Sun's extended light.
							Mark this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worthy of laud, O Agni, is that kinship which thou hast with Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here seat thee like a man: most wise, bring thou the Gods for
							sacrifice. Mark this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here seated, man-like as a priest shall wisest Agni to the Gods
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Speed onward our oblations, God among the Gods, intelligent. Mark this
							my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Varuna makes the holy prayer. To him who finds the path we pray.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							He in the heart reveals his thought. Let sacred worship rise anew. Mark
							this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							That pathway of the Sun in heaven, made to be highly glorified,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is not to be transgressed, O Gods. O mortals, ye behold it not. Mark
							this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Trta, when buried in the well, calls on the Gods to succour him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							That call of his Brhaspati heard and released him from distress. Mark
							this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							A ruddy wolf beheld me once, as I was faring on my path.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, like a carpenter whose back is aching crouched and slunk away. Mark
							this my woe, ye Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through this our song may we, allied with Indra, with all our heroes
							conquer in the battle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 105: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 106
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							CALL we for aid on Indra, Mitra, Varuna and Agni and the Marut host and
							Aditi.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as a chariot from a difficult ravine, bountiful Vasus, rescue us
							from all distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come ye Adityas for our full prosperity, in conquests of the foe, ye
							Gods, bring joy to us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as a chariot from a difficult ravine, bountiful Vasus, rescue us
							from all distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the most glorious Fathers aid us, and the two Goddesses, Mothers of
							the Gods, who strengthen Law.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as a chariot from a difficult ravine, bountiful Vasus, rescue us
							from all distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To mighty Narasamsa, strengthening his might, to Pusan, ruler over men,
							we pray with hymns.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as a chariot from a difficult ravine, bountiful Vasus, rescue us
							from all distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, make us evermore an easy path: we crave what boon thou hast
							for men in rest and stir.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like as a chariot from a difficult ravine, bountiful Vasus, rescue us
							from all distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sunk in the pit the Rsi Kutsa called, to aid, Indra the Vrtra-slayer,
							Lord of power and might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as a chariot from a difficult ravine, bountiful Vasus, rescue us
							from all distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Aditi the Goddess guard us with the Gods: may the protecting God
							keep us with ceaseless care.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 106: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 107
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 107: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 107: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE sacrifice obtains the Gods' acceptance: be graciously inclined to
							us, Adityas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 107: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hitherward let your favour be directed, and be our best deliverer from
							trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 107: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 107: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							By praise-songs of Angirases exalted, may the Gods come to us with
							their protection.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 107: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Indra with his powers, Maruts with Maruts, Aditi with Adityas grant
							us shelter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 107: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 107: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							This laud of ours may Varuna and Indra, Aryaman Agni, Savitar find
							pleasant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 107: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer' of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 108
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ON that most wondrous car of yours, O Indra and Agni, which looks round
							on all things living,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Take ye your stand and come to us together, and drink libations of the
							flowing Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As vast as all this world is in its compass, deep as it is, with its
							far-stretching surface,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So let this Soma be, Indra and Agni, made for your drinking till your
							soul be sated.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For ye have won a blessed name together: yea, with one aim ye strove, O
							Vrtra-slayers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So Indra-Agni, seated here together, pour in, ye Mighty Ones, the
							mighty Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Both stand adorned, when fires are duly kindled, spreading the sacred
							grass, with lifted ladles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drawn by strong Soma juice poured forth around us, come, Indra-Agni,
							and display your favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The brave deeds ye have done, Indra and Agni, the forms ye have
							displayed and mighty exploits,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The ancient and auspicious bonds of friendship,--for sake of these
							drink of the flowing Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							As first I said when choosing you, in battle we must contend with
							Asuras for this Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							So came ye unto this my true conviction, and drank libations of the
							flowing Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							If in your dwelling, or with prince or Brahman, ye, Indra-Agni, Holy
							Ones, rejoice you,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even from thence, ye mighty Lords, come hither, and drink libation of
							the flowing Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							If with, the Yadus, Turvasas, ye sojourn, with Druhyus, Anus, Purus,
							Indra-Agni!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even from thence, ye mighty Lords, come hither, and drink libations of
							the flowing Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whether, O Indra-Agni, ye be dwelling in lowest earth, in central, or
							in highest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even from thence, ye mighty Lords, come hither, and drink libations of
							the flowing Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whether, O Indra-Agni, ye be dwelling in highest earth, in central, or
							in lowest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even from thence, ye mighty Lords, come hither, and drink libations of
							the flowing Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whether ye be in heaven, O Indra-Agni, on earth, on mountains, in the
							herbs, or waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even from thence, ye mighty Lords, come hither, and drink libations of
							the flowing Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							If, when the Sun to the mid-heaven hath mounted, ye take delight in
							food, O Indra-Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even from thence, ye mighty Lords, come hither, and drink libations of
							the flowing Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus having drunk your fill of our libation, win us all kinds of
							wealth, Indra and Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 108: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 109
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LONGING for weal I looked around, in spirit, for kinsmen, Indra-Agni,
							or for brothers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							No providence but yours alone is with me so have I wrought for you this
							hymn for succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For I have heard that ye give wealth more freely than worthless
							son-in-law or spouse's brother.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So offering to you this draught of Soma, I make you this new hymn,
							Indra and Agni,
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us not break the cords: with this petition we strive to gain the
							powers of our forefathers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							For Indra-Agni the strong drops are joyful, for here in the bowl's lap
							are both the press-stones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For you the bowl divine, Indra and Agni, presses the Soma gladly to
							delight you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With hands auspicious and fair arms, ye Asvins, haste, sprinkle it with
							sweetness in the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							You, I have heard, were mightiest, Indra-Agni, when Vrtra fell and when
							the spoil was parted.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sit at this sacrifice, ye ever active, on the strewn grass, and with
							the juice delight you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surpassing all men where they shout for battle, ye Twain exceed the
							earth and heaven in greatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Greater are ye than rivers and than mountains, O Indra-Agni, and all
							things beside them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring wealth and give it, ye whose arms wield thunder: Indra and Agni,
							with your powers protect us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now of a truth these be the very sunbeams wherewith our fathers were of
							old united.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give, ye who shatter forts, whose hands wield thunder: Indra and Agni,
							save us in our battles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 109: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 110
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE holy work I wrought before is wrought again: my sweetest hymn is
							sung to celebrate your praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here, O ye Rbhus, is this sea for all the Gods: sate you with Soma
							offered with the hallowing word.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, seeking your enjoyment onward from afar, ye, certain of my
							kinsmen, wandered on your way,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sons of Sudhanvan, after your long journeying, ye came unto the home of
							liberal Savitar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Savitar therefore gave you immortality, because ye came proclaiming him
							whom naught can hide;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And this the drinking-chalice of the Asura, which till that time was
							one, ye made to be fourfold.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 110: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							When they had served with zeal at sacrifice as priests, they, mortal as
							they were, gained immortality.
						-
