					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Foe-chaser, born of Law, the Law's protectress, joy-giver, waker of all
							pleasant voices,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Auspicious, bringing food for Gods' enjoyment, shine on us here, most
							bright, O Dawn, this morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							From days eternal hath Dawn shone, the Goddess, and shows this light
							to-day, endowed with riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							So will she shine on days to come immortal she moves on in her own
							strength, undecaying.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							In the sky's borders hath she shone in splendour: the Goddess hath
							thrown off the veil of darkness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Awakening the world with purple horses, on her well-harnessed chariot
							Dawn approaches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bringing all life-sustaining blessings with her, showing herself she
							sends forth brilliant lustre.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Last of the countless mornings that have vanished, first of bright
							morns to come hath Dawn arisen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Arise! the breath, the life, again hath reached us: darkness hath
							passed away and light approacheth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							She for the Sun hath left a path to travel we have arrived where men
							prolong existence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Singing the praises of refulgent Mornings with his hymn's web the
							priest, the poet rises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shine then to-day, rich Maid, on him who lauds thee, shine down on us
							the gift of life and offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dawns giving sons all heroes, kine and horses, shining upon the man who
							brings oblations,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							These let the Soma-presser gain when ending his glad songs louder than
							the voice of Vayu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mother of Gods, Aditi's form of glory, ensign of sacrifice, shine forth
							exalted.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rise up, bestowing praise on our devotion all-bounteous, make us chief
							among the people.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whatever splendid wealth the Dawns bring with them to bless the man who
							offers praise and worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 113: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even that may Mitra, Varuna vouchsafe us, and Aditi and Sindhu, Earth
							and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 114
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To the strong Rudra bring we these our songs of praise, to him the Lord
							of Heroes with the braided hair,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That it be well with all our cattle and our men, that in this village
							all be healthy and well-fed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be gracious unto us, O Rudra, bring us joy: thee, Lord of Heroes, thee
							with reverence will we serve.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whatever health and strength our father Manu won by sacrifice may we,
							under thy guidance, gain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							By worship of the Gods may we, O Bounteous One, O Rudra, gain thy
							grace, Ruler of valiant men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come to our families, bringing them bliss: may we, whose heroes are
							uninjured, bring thee sacred gifts,
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither we call for aid the wise, the wanderer, impetuous Rudra,
							perfecter of sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he repel from us the anger of the Gods: verily we desire his
							favourable grace.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him with the braided hair we call with reverence down, the wild-boar of
							the sky, the red, the dazzling shape.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, his hand filled full of sovran medicines, grant us protection,
							shelter, and a home secure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the Maruts' Father is this hymn addressed, to strengthen Rudra's
							might, a song more sweet than sweet.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant us, Immortal One, the food which mortals eat: be gracious unto
							me, my seed, my progeny.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Rudra, harm not either great or small of us, harm not the growing
							boy, harm not the full-grown man.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slay not a sire among us, slay no mother here, and to our own dear
							bodies, Rudra, do not harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Harm us not, Rudra, in our seed and progeny, harm us not in the living,
							nor in cows or steeds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slay not our heroes in the fury of thy wrath. Bringing oblations
							evermore we call to thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as a herdsman I have brought thee hymns of praise: O Father of the
							Maruts, give us happiness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blessed is thy most favouring benevolence, so, verily, do we desire thy
							saving help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far be thy dart that killeth men or cattle: thy bliss be with us, O
							thou Lord of Heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be gracious unto us, O God, and bless us, and then vouchsafe us
							doubly-strong protection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							We, seeking help, have spoken and adored him: may Rudra, girt by
							Maruts, hear our calling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 114: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 115
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE brilliant presence of the Gods hath risen, the eye of Mitra, Varuna
							and Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The soul of all that moveth not or moveth, the Sun hath filled the air
							and earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as a young man followeth a maiden, so doth the Sun the Dawn,
							refulgent Goddess:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where pious men extend their generations, before the Auspicious One for
							happy fortune.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Auspicious are the Sun's Bay-coloured Horses, bright, changing hues,
							meet for our shouts of triumph.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bearing our prayers, the sky's ridge have they mounted, and in a moment
							speed round earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the Godhead, this might of Surya: he hath withdrawn what spread
							o'er work unfinished.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When he hath loosed his Horses from their station, straight over all
							Night spreadeth out her garment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							In the sky's lap the Sun this form assumeth that Varuna and Mitra may
							behold it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							His Bay Steeds well maintain his power eternal, at one time bright and
							darksome at another.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							This day, O Gods, while Surya is ascending, deliver us from trouble and
							dishonour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 115: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							This prayer of ours may Varuna grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu,
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 116
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I TRIM like grass my song for the Nasatyas and send their lauds forth
							as the wind drives rain-clouds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, in a chariot rapid as an arrow, brought to the youthful Vimada a
							consort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Borne on by rapid steeds of mighty pinion, or proudly trusting in the
							Gods' incitements.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That stallion ass of yours won, O Nasatyas, that thousand in the race,
							in Yama's contest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, Asvins, as a dead man leaves his riches, Tugra left Bhujyu in the
							cloud of waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye brought him back in animated vessels, traversing air, unwetted by
							the billows.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bhujyu ye bore with winged things, Nasatyas, which for three nights,
							three days full swiftly travelled,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							To the sea's farther shore, the strand of ocean, in three cars,
							hundred-footed, with six horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye wrought that hero exploit in the ocean which giveth no support, or
							hold or station,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time ye carried Bhujyu to his dwelling, borne in a ship with
							hundred oars, O Asvins.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The white horse which of old ye gave Aghasva, Asvins, a gift to be his
							wealth for ever,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Still to be praised is that your glorious present, still to be famed is
							the brave horse of Pedu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Heroes, ye gave wisdom to Kaksivan who sprang from Pajra's line, who
							sang your praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye poured forth from the hoof of your strong charger a hundred jars of
							wine as from a strainer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye warded off with cold the fire's fierce burning; food very rich in
							nourishment ye furnished.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Atri, cast downward in the cavern, Asvins ye brought, with all his
							people, forth to comfort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye lifted up the well, O ye Nasatyas, and set the base on high to open
							downward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Streams flowed for folk of Gotama who thirsted, like rain to bring
							forth thousandfold abundance.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye from the old Cyavana, O Nasatyas, stripped, as 'twere mail, the skin
							upon
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							his body,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 10: Line 3
					-
						-
							Lengthened his life when all had left him helpless, Dasras! and made
							him lord of youthful maidens.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worthy of praise and worth the winning, Heroes, is that your favouring
							succour O Nasatyas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time ye, knowing well his case, delivered Vandana from the pit
							like hidden treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							That mighty deed of yours, for gain, O Heroes, as thunder heraldeth the
							rain, I publish,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, by the horse's head, Atharvan's offspring Dadhyac made known to
							you the Soma's sweetness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							In the great rite the wise dame called, Nasatyas, you, Lords of many
							treasures, to assist her.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye heard the weakling's wife, as 'twere an order, and gave to her a son
							Hiranyahasta.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye from the wolf's jaws, as ye stood together, set free the quail, O
							Heroes, O Nasatyas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, Lords of many treasures, gave the poet his perfect vision as he
							mourned his trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							When in the time of night, in Khela's battle, a leg was severed like a
							wild bird's pinion,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Straight ye gave Vispala a leg of iron that she might move what time
							the conflict opened.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							His father robbed Rjrasva of his eyesight who for the she-wolf slew a
							hundred wethers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye gave him eyes, Nasatyas, Wonder-Workers, Physicians, that he saw
							with sight uninjured.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Daughter of the Sun your car ascended, first reaching as it were
							the goal with coursers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							All Deities within their hearts assented, and ye, Nasatyas, are close
							linked with glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							When to his house ye came, to Divodasa, hasting to Bharadvaja, O ye
							Asvins,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							The car that came with you brought splendid riches: a porpoise and a
							bull were yoked together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, bringing wealth with rule, and life with offspring, life rich in
							noble heroes; O Nasatyas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accordant came with strength to Jahnu's children who offered you thrice
							every day your portion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye bore away at night by easy pathways Jahusa compassed round on every
							quarter,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, with your car that cleaves the toe asunder, Nasatyas never
							decaying! rent the mountains.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							One morn ye strengthened Vasa for the battle, to gather spoils that
							might be told in thousands.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Indra joined ye drove away misfortunes, yea foes of Prthusravas, O
							ye mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 116: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
