						-
							From earth ye brought the sage to life in wondrous mode; be your great
							deeds done here for him who honours you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 119: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 119: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye went to him who mourned in a far distant place, him who was left
							forlorn by treachery of his sire.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 119: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rich with the light of heaven was then the help ye gave, and marvellous
							your succour when ye stood by him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 119: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 119: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you in praise of sweetness sang the honey-bee: Ausija calleth you in
							Soma's rapturous joy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 119: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye drew unto yourselves the spirit of Dadhyac, and then the horse's
							head uttered his words to you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 119: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 119: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							A horse did ye provide for Pedu, excellent, white, O ye Asvins,
							conqueror of combatants,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 119: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Invincible in war by arrows, seeking heaven worthy of fame, like Indra,
							vanquisher of men.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 120
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ASVINS, what praise may win your grace? Who may be pleasing to you
							both?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							How shall the ignorant worship you?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here let the ignorant ask the means of you who know--for none beside
							you knoweth aught--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not of a spiritless mortal man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Such as ye: are, all-wise, we call you. Ye wise, declare to us this day
							accepted prayer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Loving you well your servant lauds you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Simply, ye Mighty Ones, I ask the Gods of that wondrous oblation
							hallowed by the mystic word.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Save us from what is stronger, fiercer than ourselves.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forth go the hymn that shone in Ghosa Bhrgu's like, the song wherewith
							the son of Pajra worships you,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like some wise minister.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear ye the song of him who hastens speedily. O Asvins, I am he who
							sang your praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hither, ye Lords of Splendour, hither turn your eyes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							For ye were ever nigh to deal forth ample wealth, to give the wealth
							that ye had gathered up.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							As such, ye Vasus, guard us well, and keep us safely from the wicked
							wolf.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us not up to any man who hateth us, nor let our milch-cows stray,
							whose udders give us food,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far from our homes without their calves.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May they who love you gain you for their Friends. Prepare ye us for
							opulence with strengthening food,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Prepare us for the food that floweth from our cows
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							I have obtained the horseless car of Asvins rich in sacrifice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							And I am well content therewith.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May it convey me evermore: may the light chariot pass from men
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							To men unto the Soma draught.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							It holdeth slumber in contempt. and the rich who enjoyeth not:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 120: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Both vanish quickly and are lost.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 121
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHEN Will men's guardians hasting hear with favour the song of
							Angiras's pious children
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When to the people of the home he cometh he strideth to the sacrifice,
							the Holy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He stablished heaven; he poured forth, skilful worker, the wealth of
							kine, for strength, that nurtures heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mighty One his self-born host regarded, the horse's mate, the
							mother of the heifer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of red dawns, he came victorious, daily to the Angirases' former
							invocation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							His bolt and team hath he prepared, and stablished the heaven for
							quadrupeds and men two-footed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							In joy of this thou didst restore, for worship, the lowing company of
							hidden cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the three-pointed one descends with onslaught he opens wide the
							doors that cause man trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine is that milk which thy swift-moving Parents brought down, a
							strengthening genial gift for conquest;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the pure treasure unto thee they offered, the milk shed from the
							cow who streameth nectar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							There is he born. May the Swift give us rapture, and like the Sun shine
							forth from yonder dawning,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indu, even us who drank, whose toils are offerings, poured from the
							spoon, with praise, upon the altar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							When the wood-pile, made of good logs, is ready, at the Sun's worship
							to bind fast the Bullock,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then when thou shinest forth through days of action for the Car-borne,
							the Swift, the Cattle-seeker.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eight steeds thou broughtest down from mighty heaven, when fighting for
							the well that giveth splendour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							That men might press with stones the gladdening yellow, strengthened
							with milk, fermenting, to exalt thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hurledst forth from heaven the iron missile, brought by the
							Skilful, from the sling of leather,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou, O Much-invoked, assisting Kutsa with endless deadly darts
							didst compass Susna.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bolt-armed, ere darkness overtook the sunlight, thou castest at the
							veiling cloud thy weapon,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou rentest, out of heaven, though firmly knotted, the might of Susna
							that was thrown around him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mighty Heaven and Earth, those bright expanses that have no wheels,
							joyed, Indra, at thine exploit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vrtra, the boar who lay amid the waters, to sleep thou sentest with thy
							mighty thunder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mount Indra, lover of the men thou guardest, the well-yoked horses of
							the wind, best bearers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							The bolt which Kavya Usana erst gave thee, strong, gladdening,
							Vrtra-slaying, hath he fashioned.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The strong Bay Horses of the Sun thou stayedst: this Etasa drew not the
							wheel, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Casting them forth beyond the ninety rivers thou dravest down into the
							pit the godless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, preserve thou us from this affliction Thunder-armed, save us
							from the misery near us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us affluence in chariots, founded on horses, for our food and
							fame and gladness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Never may this thy loving-kindness fail us; mighty in strength, may
							plenteous food surround us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 121: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Maghavan, make us share the foeman's cattle: may we be thy most liberal
							feast companions.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 122
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SAY, bringing sacrifice to bounteous Rudra, This juice for drink to you
							whose wrath is fleeting!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Dyaus the Asura's Heroes I have lauded the Maruts as with prayer
							to Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong to exalt the early invocation are Night and Dawn who show with
							varied aspect.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Barren clothes her in wide-woven raiment, and fair Morn shines with
							Surya's golden splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Cheer us the Roamer round, who strikes at morning, the Wind delight us,
							pourer forth of waters!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sharpen our wits, O Parvata and Indra. May all the Gods vouchsafe to us
							this favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							And Ausija shall call for me that famous Pair who enjoy and drink, who
							come to brighten.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Set ye the Offspring of the Floods before you; both Mothers of the
							Living One who beameth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							For you shall Ausija call him who thunders, as, to win Arjuna's assent,
							cried Ghosa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							I will invoke, that Pusan may be bounteous to you, the rich munificence
							of Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear, Mitra-Varuna, these mine invocations, hear them from all men in
							the hall of worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giver of famous gifts, kind hearer, Sindhu who gives fair fields,
							listen with all his waters!
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praised, Mitra, Varuna! is your gift, a hundred cows to the Prksayamas
							and the Pajra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Presented by car-famous Priyaratha, supplying nourishment, they came
							directly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praised is the gift of him the very wealthy: may we enjoy it, men with
							hero children:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							His who hath many gifts to give the Pajras, a chief who makes me rich
							in cars and horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The folk, O Mitra-Varuna, who hate you, who sinfully hating pour you no
							libations,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lay in their hearts, themselves, a wasting sickness, whereas the
							righteous gaineth all by worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							That man, most puissant, wondrously urged onward, famed among heroes,
							liberal in giving,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Moveth a warrior, evermore undaunted in all encounters even with the
							mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to the man's, the sacrificer's calling: hear, Kings of
							Immortality, joy-givers!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							While ye who speed through clouds decree your bounty largely, for fame,
							to him the chariot rider.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vigour will we bestow on that adorer whose tenfold draught we come to
							taste, so spake they.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							May all in whom rest splendour and great riches obtain refreshment in
							these sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							We will rejoice to drink the tenfold present when the twicefive come
							bearing sacred viands.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							What can he do whose steeds and reins are choicest? These, the
							all-potent, urge brave men to conquest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The sea and all the Deities shall give us him with the golden ear and
							neck bejewelled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dawns, hasting to the praises of the pious, be pleased with us, both
							offerers and singers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Four youthful sons of Masarsara vex me, three, of the king, the
							conquering Ayavasa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 122: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now like the Sun, O Varuna and Mitra, your car hath shone, long-shaped
							and reined with splendour.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 123
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Daksina's broad chariot hath been harnessed: this car the Gods
							Immortal have ascended.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fain to bring light to homes of men the noble and active Goddess hath
							emerged from darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							She before all the living world hath wakened, the Lofty One who wins
							and gathers treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Revived and ever young on high she glances. Dawn hath come first unto
							our morning worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							If, Dawn, thou Goddess nobly born, thou dealest fortune this day to all
							the race of mortals,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Savitar the God, Friend of the homestead, declare before the Sun
							that we are sinless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Showing her wonted form each day that passeth, spreading the light she
							visiteth each dwelling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eager for conquest, with bright sheen she cometh. Her portion is the
							best of goodly treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sister of Varuna, sister of Bhaga, first among all sing forth, O joyous
							Morning.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Weak be the strength of him who worketh evil: may we subdue him with
							our car the guerdon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let our glad hymns and holy thoughts rise upward, for the flames
							brightly burning have ascended.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The far-refulgent Mornings make apparent the lovely treasures which the
							darkness covered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The one departeth and the other cometh: unlike in hue day's, halves
							march on successive.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							One hides the gloom of the surrounding Parents. Dawn on her shining
							chariot is resplendent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The same in form to-day, the same tomorrow, they still keep Varuna's
							eternal statute.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blameless, in turn they traverse thirty regions, and dart across the
							spirit in a moment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							She who hath knowledge Of the first day's nature is born refulgent
							white from out the darkness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Maiden breaketh not the law of Order, day by day coming to the
							place appointed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							In pride of beauty like a maid thou goest, O Goddess, to the God who
							longs to win thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							And smiling youthful, as thou shinest brightly, before him thou
							discoverest thy bosom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fair as a bride embellished by her mother thou showest forth thy form
							that all may see it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blessed art thou O Dawn. Shine yet more widely. No other Dawns have
							reached what thou attainest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rich in kine, horses, and all goodly treasures, in constant operation
							with the sunbeams,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Dawns depart and come again assuming their wonted forms that
							promise happy fortune.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Obedient to the rein of Law Eternal give us each thought that more and
							more shall bless us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 123: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shine thou on us to-day, Dawn, swift to listen. With us be riches and
							with chiefs who worship.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 124
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Dawn refulgent when the fire is kindled, and the Sun rising, far
							diffuse their brightness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savitar, God, hath sent us forth to labour, each quadruped, each biped,
							to be active.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not interrupting heavenly ordinances, although she minisheth human
							generations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The last of endless morns that have departed, the first of those that
							come, Dawn brightly shineth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							There in the eastern region she, Heaven's Daughter, arrayed in garments
							all of light, appeareth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Truly she followeth the path of Order, nor faileth, knowing well, the
							heavenly quarters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Near is she seen, as 'twere the Bright One's bosom: she showeth sweet
							things like a new song-singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							She cometh like a fly awaking sleepers, of all returning dames most
							true and constant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							There in the east half of the watery region the Mother of the Cows hath
							shown her ensign.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wider and wider still she spreadeth onward, and filleth full the laps
							of both heir Parents.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							She, verily, exceeding vast to look on debarreth from her light nor kin
							nor stranger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Proud of her spotless form she, brightly shining, turneth not from the
							high nor from the humble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							She seeketh men, as she who hath no brother, mounting her car, as
							'twere to gather riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dawn, like a loving matron for her husband, smiling and well attired,
							unmasks her beauty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sister quitteth, for the elder Sister, her place, and having looked
							on her departeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							She decks her beauty, shining forth with sunbeams, like women trooping
							to the festal meeting.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							To all these Sisters who ere now have vanished a later one each day in
							course succeedeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, like the past, with days of happy fortune, may the new Dawns shine
							forth on us with riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rouse up, O Wealthy One, the liberal givers; let niggard traffickers
							sleep on unwakened:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shine richly, Wealthy One, on those who worship, richly, glad.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 10: Line 3
					-
						-
							Dawn while wasting, on the singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							This young Maid from the east hath shone upon us; she harnesseth her
							team of bright red oxen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							She will beam forth, the light will hasten hither, and Agni will be
							present in each dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the birds fly forth from their resting places, so men with store of
							food rise at thy dawning.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, to the liberal mortal who remaineth at home, O Goddess Dawn, much
							good thou bringest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praised through my prayer be ye who should be lauded. Ye have increased
							our wealth, ye Dawns who love us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 124: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Goddesses, may we win by your good favour wealth to be told by hundreds
							and by thousands.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 125
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COMING at early morn he gives his treasure; the prudent one receives
							and entertains him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thereby increasing still his life and offspring, he comes with brave
							sons to abundant riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rich shall he be in gold and kine and horses. Indra bestows on him
							great vital power,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who stays thee, as thou comest, with his treasure, like game caught in
							the net, O early comer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Longing, I came this morning to the pious, the son of sacrifice, with
							car wealth-laden.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give him to drink juice of the stalk that gladdens; prosper with
							pleasant hymns the Lord of Heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Health-bringing streams, as milch-cows, flow to profit him who hath
							worshipped, him who now will worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him who freely gives and fills on all sides full streams of fatness
							flow and make him famous.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							On the high ridge of heaven he stands exalted, yea, to the Gods he
							goes, the liberal giver.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The streams, the waters flow for him with fatness: to him this guerdon
							ever yields abundance.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							For those who give rich meeds are all these splendours, for those who
							give rich meeds suns shine in heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The givers of rich meeds are made immortal; the givers of rich fees
							prolong their lifetime.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let not the liberal sink to sin and sorrow, never decay the pious
							chiefs who worship!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 125: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let every man besides be their protection, and let affliction fall upon
							the niggard.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 126
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH wisdom I present these lively praises of Bhavya dweller on the
							bank of Sindhu;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For he, unconquered King, desiring glory, hath furnished me a thousand
							sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							A hundred necklets from the King, beseeching, a hundred gift-steeds I
							at once accepted;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of the lord's cows a thousand, I Kaksivan. His deathless glory hath he
							spread to heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Horses of dusky colour stood beside me, ten chariots, Svanaya's gift,
							with mares to draw them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Kine numbering sixty thousand followed after. Kaksivan gained them when
							the days were closing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forty bay horses of the ten cars' master before a thousand lead the
							long procession.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Reeling in joy Kaksivan's sons and Pajra's have grounded the coursers
							decked with pearly trappings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							An earlier gift for you have I accepted eight cows, good milkers, and
							three harnessed horses,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pajras, who with your wains with your great kinsman, like troops of
							subjects, have been fain for glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 6
				-
					-
						[Ille loquitur]. Adhaerens, arcte adhaerens, illa quae mustelae similis se
						abdidit, multum humorem effundens, dat mihi complexuum centum gaudia.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 126: Verse 7
				-
					-
						[Ille loquitur]. Prope, prope accede; molliter me tange. Ne putes pilos
						corporis mei-paucos esse: tota sum villosa sicut Gandharium ovis.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 127
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI I hold as herald, the munificent, the gracious, Son of Strength,
							who knoweth all that live, as holy Singer, knowing all,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of fair rites, a God with form erected turning to the Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							He, when the flame hath sprung forth from the holy oil, the offered
							fatness, longeth for it with his glow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							We, sacrificing, call on thee best worshipper, the eldest of Angirases,
							Singer, with hymns, thee, brilliant One! with singers' hymns;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee, wandering round as 't were the sky, who art the invoking Priest
							of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							Whom, Bull with hair of flame the people must observe, the people that
							he speed them on.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He with his shining glory blazing far and wide, he verily it is who
							slayeth demon foes, slayeth the demons like an axe:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							At whose close touch things solid shake, and what is stable yields like
							trees.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							Subduing all, he keeps his ground and flinches not, from the skilled
							archer flinches not.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him, as one who knows, even things solid yield: unrough fire-sticks
							heated hot he gives his gifts to aid. Men offer Agni gifts for aid.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He deeply piercing many a thing hews it like wood with fervent glow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							Even hard and solid food he crunches with his might, yea, hard and
							solid food with might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here near we place the sacrificial food for him who shines forth fairer
							in the night than in the day, with life then stronger than by day.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							His life gives sure and firm defence as that one giveth to a son.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							The during fires enjoy things given and things not given, the during
							fires enjoy as food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, roaring very loudly like the Maruts' host, in fertile cultivated
							fields adorable, in desert spots adorable,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accepts and eats our offered gifts, ensign of sacrifice by desert;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							So let all, joying, love his path when he is glad, as men pursue a path
							for bliss.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as they who sang forth hymns, addressed to heaven, the Bhrgus with
							their prayer and praise invited him, the Bhrgus rubbing, offering
							gifts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							For radiant Agni, Lord of all these treasures, is exceeding strong.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 7: Line 3
					-
						-
							May he, the wise, accept the grateful coverings, the wise accept the
							coverings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee we invoke, the Lord of all our settled homes, common to all, the
							household's guardian, to enjoy, bearer of true hymns, to enjoy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee we invoke, the guest of men, by whose mouth, even as a sire's,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 8: Line 3
					-
						-
							All these Immortals come to gain their food of life, oblations come to
							Gods as food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Agni, most victorious with thy conquering strength, most Mighty
							One, art born for service of the Gods, like wealth for service of the
							Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most mighty is thine ecstasy, most splendid is thy mental power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 9: Line 3
					-
						-
							Therefore men wait upon thee, undecaying One, like vassals, undecaying
							One.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the mighty, conquering with victorious strength, to Agni walking
							with the dawn, who sendeth kine, be sung your laud, to Agni sung;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							As he who with oblation comes calls him aloud in every place.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 10: Line 3
					-
						-
							Before the brands of fire he shouteth singerlike, the herald, kindler
							of the brands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, beheld by us in nearest neighbourhood, accordant with the Gods,
							bring us, with gracious love, great riches with thy gracious love.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us O Mightiest, what is great, to see and to enjoy the earth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 127: Verse 11: Line 3
					-
						-
							As one of awful power, stir up heroic might for those who praise thee,
							Bounteous Lord!
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 128
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							By Manu's law was born this Agni, Priest most skilled, born for the
							holy work of those who yearn therefore, yea, born for his own holy
							work.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							All ear to him who seeks his love and wealth to him who strives for
							fame,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							Priest ne'er deceived, he sits in Ila's holy place, girt round in Ila's
							holy place.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							We call that perfecter of worship by the path or sacrifice; with
							reverence rich in offerings, with worship rich in offerings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through presentation of our food he grows not old in this his from;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							The God whom Matarisvan brought from far away, for Manu brought from
							far away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							In ordered course forthwith he traverses the earth, swift-swallowing,
							bellowing Steer, bearing the genial seed, bearing the seed and
							bellowing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Observant with a hundred eyes the God is conqueror in the wood:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							Agni, who hath his seat in broad plains here below, and in the high
							lands far away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Agni, wise High-Priest, in every house takes thought for sacrifice
							and holy service, yea, takes thought, with mental power, for sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Disposer, he with mental power shows all things unto him who strives;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							Whence he was born a guest enriched with holy oil, born as Ordainer and
							as Priest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When through his power and in his strong prevailing flames the Maruts'
							gladdening boons mingle with Agni's roar, boons gladdening for the
							active One,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then he accelerates the gift, and by the greatness of his wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							Shall rescue us from overwhelming misery, from curse and overwhelming
							woe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vast, universal, good he was made messenger; the speeder with his right
							hand hath not loosed his hold, through love of fame not loosed his
							hold.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He bears oblations to the Gods for whosoever supplicates.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							Agni bestows a blessing on each pious man, and opens wide the doors for
							him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Agni hath been set most kind in camp of men, in sacrifice like a
							Lord victorious, like a dear Lord in sacred rites.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							His are the oblations of mankind when offered up at Ila's place.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 7: Line 3
					-
						-
							He shall preserve us from Varuna's chastisement, yea, from the great
							God's chastisement.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni the Priest they supplicate to grant them wealth: him, dear, most
							thoughtful, have they made their messenger, him, offering-bearer have
							they made,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beloved of all, who knoweth all, the Priest, the Holy one, the Sage--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 128: Verse 8: Line 3
					-
						-
							Him, Friend, for help, the Gods when they are fain for wealth, him,
							Friend, with hymns, when fain for wealth.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 129
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE car which Indra, thou, for service of the Gods though it be far
							away, O swift One, bringest near, which, Blameless One, thou bringest
							near,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Place swiftly nigh us for our help: be it thy will that it be strong.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							Blameless and active, hear this speech of orderers, this speech of us
							like orderers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear, Indra, thou whom men in every fight must call to show thy
							strength, for cry of battle with the men, with men of war for victory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who with heroes wins the light, who with the singers gains the
							prize,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							Him the rich seek to gain even as a swift strong steed, even as a
							courser fleet and strong.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Mighty, pourest forth the hide that holds the rain, thou keepest
							far away, Hero, the wicked man, thou shuttest out the wicked man.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, to thee I sing, to Dyaus, to Rudra glorious in himself,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							To Mitra, Varuna I sing a far-famed hymn to the kind God a far-famed
							hymn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							We wish our Indra here that he may further you, the Friend, beloved of
							all, the very strong ally, in wars the very strong ally
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							In all encounters strengthen thou our prayer to be a help to us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							No enemy--whom thou smitest down--subdueth thee, no enemy, whom thou
							smitest down.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bow down the overweening pride of every foe with succour like to
							kindling-wood in fiercest flame, with mighty succour, Mighty One.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guide us, thou Hero, as of old, so art thou counted blameless still.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							Thou drivest, as a Priest, all sins of man away, as Priest, in person,
							seeking us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							This may I utter to the present Soma-drop, which, meet to be invoked,
							with power, awakes the prayer, awakes the demon-slaying prayer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he himself with darts of death drive far from us the scorner's
							hate.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							Far let him flee away who speaketh wickedness and vanish like a mote of
							dust.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							By thoughtful invocation this may we obtain, obtain great wealth, O
							Wealthy One, with Hero sons, wealth that is sweet with hero sons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who is wroth we pacify with sacred food and eulogies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 7: Line 3
					-
						-
							Indra the Holy with our calls inspired and true, the Holy One with
							calls inspired.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							On, for your good and ours, come Indra with the aid of his own
							lordliness to drive the wicked hence, to rend the evil-hearted ones!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The weapon which devouring fiends cast at us shall destroy themselves.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 8: Line 3
					-
						-
							Struck down, it shall not reach the mark; hurled forth, the fire-brand
							shall not strike.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							With riches in abundance, Indra, come to us, come by an unobstructed
							path, come by a path from demons free.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be with us when we stray afar, be with us when our home is nigh.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 9: Line 3
					-
						-
							Protect us with thy help both near and far away: protect us ever with
							thy help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art our own, O Indra, with victorious wealth: let might accompany
							thee, the Strong, to give us aid, like Mitra, to give mighty aid.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							O strongest saviour, helper thou, Immortal! of each warrior's car.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 10: Line 3
					-
						-
							Hurt thou another and not us, O Thunder-armed, one who would hurt, O
							Thunder-armed!
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Save us from injury, thou who art well extolled: ever the warder-off
							art thou of wicked ones, even as a God, of wicked ones;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou slayer of the evil fiend, saviour of singer such as I.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 129: Verse 11: Line 3
					-
						-
							Good Lord, the Father made thee slayer of the fiends, made thee, good
							Lord, to slay the fiends.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 130
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to us, Indra, from afar, conducting us even as a lord of heroes to
							the gatherings, home, like a King, his heroes' lord.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							We come with gifts of pleasant food, with juice poured forth, invoking
							thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							As sons invite a sire, that thou mayst get thee strength thee,
							bounteousest, to get thee strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, drink the Soma juice pressed out with stones. poured from the
							reservoir, as an ox drinks the spring, a very thirsty bull the spring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							For the sweet draught that gladdens thee, for mightiest freshening of
							thy strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							Let thy Bay Horses bring thee hither as the Sun, as every day they
							bring the Sun.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He found the treasure brought from heaven that lay concealed,
							close-hidden, like the nestling of a bird, in rock, enclosed in
							never-ending rock.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best Angiras, bolt-armed, he strove to win, as 'twere, the stall of
							kine;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							So Indra hath disclosed the food concealed, disclosed the doors, the
							food that lay concealed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grasping his thunderbolt with both hands, Indra made its edge most
							keen, for hurling, like a carving-knife for Ahi's slaughter made it
							keen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Endued with majesty and strength, O Indra, and with lordly might,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							Thou crashest down the trees, as when a craftsman fells, crashest them
							down as with an axe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, without effort hast let loose the floods to run their free
							course down,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							like chariots, to the sea, like chariots showing forth their strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							They, reaching hence away, have joined their strength for one eternal
							end,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 5: Line 4
					-
						-
							Even as the cows who poured forth every thing for man, Yea, poured
							forth all things for mankind.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eager for riches, men have formed for thee this song, like as a skilful
							craftsman fashioneth a car, so have they wrought thee to their bliss;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Adorning thee, O Singer, like a generous steed for deeds of might,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							Yea, like a steed to show his strength and win the prize, that he may
							bear each prize away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Puru thou hast shattered, Indra ninety forts, for Divodasa thy boon
							servant with thy bolt, O Dancer, for thy worshipper.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							For Atithigva he, the Strong, brought Sambara. from the mountain down,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 7: Line 3
					-
						-
							Distributing the mighty treasures with his strength, parting all
							treasures with his strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra in battles help his Aryan worshipper, he who hath hundred helps
							at hand in every fray, in frays that win the light of heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Plaguing the lawless he gave up to Manu's seed the dusky skin;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 8: Line 3
					-
						-
							Blazing, 'twere, he burns each covetous man away, he burns, the
							tyrannous away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Waxed strong in might at dawn he tore the Sun's wheel off. Bright red,
							he steals away their speech, the Lord of Power, their speech he steals
							away from them,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							As thou with eager speed, O Sage, hast come from far away to help,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 9: Line 3
					-
						-
							As winning for thine own all happiness of men, winning all happiness
							each day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lauded with our new hymns, O vigorous in deed, save us with
							strengthening help, thou Shatterer of the Forts!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 130: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, praised by Divodasa's clansmen, as heaven grows great with
							days, shalt wax in glory.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 131
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Indra Dyaus the Asura hath bowed him down, to Indra mighty Earth
							with wide-extending tracts, to win the light, with wide-spread tracts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							All Gods of one accord have set Indra in front preeminent.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							For Indra all libations must be set apart, all man's libations set
							apart.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							In all libations men with hero spirit urge the Universal One, each
							seeking several light, each fain to win the light apart.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee, furthering like a ship, will we set to the chariot-pole of
							strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							As men who win with sacrifices Indra's thought, men who win Indra with
							their lauds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Couples desirous of thine aid are storming thee, pouring their presents
							forth to win a stall of kine, pouring gifts, Indra, seeking thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When two men seeking spoil or heaven thou bringest face to face in war,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							Thou showest, Indra, then the bolt thy constant friend, the Bull that
							ever waits on thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This thine heroic power men of old time have known, wherewith thou
							breakest down, Indra, autumnal forts, breakest them down with
							conquering might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast chastised, O Indra, Lord of Strength, the man who worships
							not,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							And made thine own this great earth and these water-floods; with joyous
							heart these water-floods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							And they have bruited far this hero-might when thou, O Strong One, in
							thy joy helpest thy suppliants, who sought to win thee for their
							Friend.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Their battle-cry thou madest sound victorious in the shocks of war.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							One stream after another have they gained from thee, eager for glory
							have they gained.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Also this morn may he be well inclined to us, mark at our call our
							offerings and our song of praise, our call that we may win the light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As thou, O Indra Thunder-armed, wilt, as the Strong One, slay the foe,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							Listen thou to the prayer of me a later sage, hear thou a later sage's
							prayer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, waxen strong and well-inclined to us, thou very mighty, slay
							the man that is our foe, slay the man, Hero! with thy bolt.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slay thou the man who injures us: hear thou, as readiest, to hear.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 131: Verse 7: Line 3
					-
						-
							Far be malignity, like mischief on the march, afar be all malignity.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 132
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HELPED, Indra Maghavan, by thee in war of old, may we subdue in fight
							the men who strive with us, conquer the men who war with us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							This day that now is close at hand bless him who pours the Soma juice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							In this our sacrifice may we divide the spoil, showing our strength,
							the spoil of war.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							In war which wins the light, at the free-giver's call, at due oblation
							of the early-rising one, oblation of the active one,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra slew, even as we know--whom each bowed head must reverence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							May all thy bounteous gifts be gathered up for us, yea, the good gifts
							of thee the Good.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							This food glows for thee as of old at sacrifice, wherein they made thee
							chooser of the place, for thou choosest the place of sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Speak thou and make it known to us: they see within with beams of
							light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							Indra, indeed, is found a seeker after spoil, spoil-seeker for his own
							allies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							So now must thy great deed be lauded as of old, when for the Angirases
							thou openedst the stall, openedst, giving aid, the stall.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							In the same manner for us here fight thou and be victorious:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							To him who pours the juice give up the lawless man, the lawless who is
							wroth with us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When with wise plan the Hero leads the people forth, they conquer in
							the ordered battle, seeking fame, press, eager, onward seeking fame.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him in time of need they sing for life with offspring and with
							strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							Their hymns with Indra find a welcome place of rest: the hymns go
							forward to the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Parvata, our champions in the fight, drive ye away each man
							who fain would war with us, drive him far from us with the bolt.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Welcome to him concealed afar shall he the lair that he hath found.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 132: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							So may the Render rend our foes on every side, rend them, O Hero,
							everywhere.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 133
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH sacrifice I purge both earth and heaven: I burn up great
							she-fiends who serve not Indra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where throttled by thy hand the foes were slaughtered, and in the pit
							of death lay pierced and mangled.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O thou who castest forth the stones crushing the sorceresses' heads,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Break them with thy wide-spreading foot, with thy wide-spreading mighty
							foot.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do thou, O Maghavan, beat off these sorceresses' daring strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cast them within the narrow pit. within the deep and narrow pit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of whom thou hast ere now destroyed thrice-fifty with thy fierce
							attacks.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That deed they count a glorious deed, though small to thee, a glorious
							deed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, crush and bray to bits the fearful fiery-weaponed fiend:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strike every demon to the ground.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tear down the mighty ones. O Indra, hear thou us. For heaven hath
							glowed like earth in fear, O Thunder-armed, as dreading fierce heat,
							Thunder-armed!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most Mighty mid the Mighty Ones thou speedest with strong bolts of
							death,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							Not slaying men, unconquered Hero with the brave, O Hero, with the
							thrice-seven brave.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The pourer of libations gains the home of wealth, pouring his gift
							conciliates hostilities, yea, the hostilities of Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pouring, he strives, unchecked and strong, to win him riches
							thousandfold.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 133: Verse 7: Line 3
					-
						-
							Indra gives lasting wealth to him who pours forth gifts, yea, wealth he
							gives that long shall last.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 134
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vayu, let fleet-foot coursers bring thee speedily to this our feast, to
							drink first of the juice we pour, to the first draught of Soma juice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May our glad hymn, discerning well, uplifted, gratify thy mind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							Come with thy team-drawn car, O Vayu, to the gift, come to the
							sacrificer's gift.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the joy-giving drops, O Vayu gladden thee, effectual, well
							prepared, directed to the heavens, strong, blent with milk and seeking
							heaven;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That aids, effectual to fulfil, may wait upon our skilful power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							Associate teams come hitherward to grant our prayers: they shall
							address the hymns we sing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Two red steeds Vayu yokes, Vayu two purple steeds, swift-footed, to the
							chariot, to the pole to draw, most able, at the pole, to draw.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wake up intelligence, as when a lover wakes his sleeping love.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							Illumine heaven and earth, make thou the Dawns to shine, for glory make
							the Dawns to shine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For thee the radiant Dawns in the far-distant sky broaden their lovely
							garments forth in wondrous beams, bright-coloured in their new-born
							beams.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thee the nectar-yielding Cow pours all rich treasures forth as
							milk.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							The Marut host hast thou engendered from the womb, the Maruts from the
							womb of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							For thee the pure bright quickly-flowing Soma-drops, strong in their
							heightening power, hasten to mix themselves, hasten to the water to be
							mixed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To thee the weary coward prays for luck that he may speed away.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							Thou by thy law protectest us from every world, yea, from the world of
							highest Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Vayu, who hast none before thee, first of all hast right to drink
							these offerings of Soma juice, hast right to drink the juice
							out-poured,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, poured by all invoking tribes who free themselves from taint of
							sin,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 134: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							For thee all cows are milked to yield the Soma-milk, to yield the
							butter and the milk.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 135
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							STREWN is the sacred grass; come Vayu, to our feast, with team of
							thousands, come, Lord of the harnessed team, with hundreds, Lord of
							harnessed steeds!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The drops divine are lifted up for thee, the God, to drink them first.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							The juices rich in sweets have raised them for thy joy, have raised
							themselves to give thee strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Purified by the stones the Soma flows for thee, clothed with its lovely
							splendours, to the reservoir, flows clad in its refulgent light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thee the Soma is poured forth, thy portioned share mid Gods and
							men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							Drive thou thy horses, Vayu, come to us with love, come well-inclined
							and loving us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come thou with hundreds, come with thousands in thy team to this our
							solemn rite, to taste the sacred food, Vayu, to taste the offerings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							This is thy seasonable share, that comes co-radiant with the Sun.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							Brought by attendant priests pure juice is offered up, Vayu, pure juice
							is offered up.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The chariot with its team of horses bring you both, to guard us and to
							taste the well-appointed food, Vayu, to taste the offerings!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink of the pleasant-flavoured juice: the first draught is assigned to
							you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							O Vayu, with your splendid bounty come ye both, Indra, with bounty come
							ye both.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May our songs bring you hither to our solemn rites: these drops of
							mighty vigour have they beautified, like a swift steed of mighty
							strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink of them well-inclined to us, come hitherward to be our help.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							Drink, Indra-Vayu, of these Juices pressed with stones,
							Strength-givers! till they gladden you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Soma juices pressed for you in waters here, borne by attendant
							priests, are offered up to you: bright, Vayu, are they offered up.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Swift through the strainer have they flowed, and here are shed for both
							of you,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							Soma-drops, fain for you, over the wether's fleece, Somas over the
							wether's fleece.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Vayu, pass thou over all the slumberers, and where the press-stone
							rings enter ye both that house, yea, Indra, go ye both within.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The joyous Maiden is beheld, the butter flows. With richly laden team
							come to our solemn rite, yea, Indra, come ye to the rite.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ride hither to the offering of the pleasant juice, the holy Fig-tree
							which victorious priests surround: victorious be they still for us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							At once the cows yield milk, the barley-meal is dressed. For thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 8: Line 3
					-
						-
							O Vayu, never shall the cows grow thin, never for thee shall they be
							dry.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Bulls of thine, O Vayu with the arm of strength, who swiftly fly
							within the current of thy stream, the Bulls increasing in their might,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Horseless, yet even through the waste swift-moving, whom no shout can
							stay,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 135: Verse 9: Line 3
					-
						-
							Hard to be checked are they, like sunbeams, in their course. hard to be
							checked by both the hands.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 136
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BRING adoration ample and most excellent, hymn, offerings, to the
							watchful Twain, the bountiful, your sweetest to the bounteous Ones.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sovrans adored with streams of oil and praised at every sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							Their high imperial might may nowhere be assailed, ne'er may their
							Godhead be assailed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For the broad Sun was seen a path more widely laid, the path of holy
							law hath been maintained with rays, the eye with Bhaga's rays of light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Firm-set in heaven is Mitra's home, and Aryaman's and Varuna's.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							Thence they give forth great vital strength which merits praise, high
							power of life that men shall praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Aditi the luminous, the celestial, upholder of the people, come ye
							day by day, ye who watch sleepless, day by day.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Resplendent might have ye obtained, Adityas, Lords of liberal gifts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							Movers of men, mild both, are Mitra, Varuna, mover of men is Aryaman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Soma be most sweet to Mitra, Varuna: he in the drinking-feasts,
							shall have a share thereof, sharing, a God, among the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May all the Gods of one accord accept it joyfully to-day.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							Therefore do ye, O Kings, accomplish what we ask, ye Righteous Ones,
							whate'er we ask.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso, with worship serves Mitra and Varuna, him guard ye carefully,
							uninjured, from distress, guard from distress the liberal man.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aryaman guards him well who acts uprightly following his law,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							Who beautifies their service with his lauds, who makes it beautiful
							with songs of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worship will I profess to lofty Dyaus, to Heaven and Earth, to Mitra
							and to bounteous Varuna, the Bounteous, the Compassionate.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Praise Indra, praise thou Agni, praise Bhaga and heavenly Aryaman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							Long may we live and have attendant progeny, have progeny with Soma's
							help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							With the Gods' help, with Indra still beside us, may we be held
							self-splendid with the Maruts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 136: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni, Mitra, Varuna give us shelter this may we gain, we and our
							wealthy princes.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 137
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH stones have we pressed out: O come; these gladdening drops are
							blent with milk, these Soma-drops which gladden you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come to us, Kings who reach to heaven, approach us, coming hitherward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							These milky drops are yours, Mitra and Varuna, bright Soma juices blent
							with milk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here are the droppings; come ye nigh the Soma-droppings blent with
							curd, juices expressed and blent with curd.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now for the wakening of your Dawn together with the Sun-God's rays,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							juice waits for Mitra and for Varuna to drink, fair juice for drink,
							for sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							As 'twere a radiant-coloured cow, they milk with stones the stalk for
							you, with stones they milk the Soma-plant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May ye come nigh us, may ye turn hither to drink the Soma juice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 137: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							The men pressed out this juice, Mitra and Varuna, pressed out this Soma
							for your drink.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 138
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							STRONG Pusan's majesty is lauded evermore, the glory of his lordly
							might is never faint, his song of praise is never faint.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seeking felicity I laud him nigh to help, the source, of bliss,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							Who, Vigorous one, hath drawn to him the hearts of all, drawn them, the
							Vigorous One, the God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee, then, O Pusan, like a swift one on his way, I urge with lauds
							that thou mayst make the foemen flee, drive, camel-like, our foes afar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As I, a man, call thee, a God, giver of bliss, to be my Friend,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							So make our loudly-chanted praises glorious, in battles make them
							glorious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Pusan, in whose friendship they who sing forth praise enjoy
							advantage, even in wisdom, through thy grace, in wisdom even they are
							advanced.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, after this most recent course, we come to thee with prayers for
							wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							Not stirred to anger, O Wide-Ruler, come to us, come thou to us in
							every fight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not stirred to anger, come, Free-giver, nigh to us, to take this gift
							of ours, thou who hast goats for steeds, Goat-borne! their gift who
							long for fame.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, Wonder-Worker! may we turn thee hither with effectual lauds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 138: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							I slight thee not, O Pusan, thou Resplendent One: thy friendship may
							not be despised.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 139
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HEARD be our prayer! In thought I honour Agni first: now straightway we
							elect this heavenly company, Indra and Vayu we elect.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For when our latest thought is raised and on Vivasvan centred well,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							Then may our holy songs go forward on their way, our songs as 'twere
							unto the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As there ye, Mitra, Varuna, above the true have taken to yourselves the
							untrue with your mind, with wisdom's mental energy,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So in the seats wherein ye dwell have we beheld the Golden One,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							Not with our thoughts or spirit, but with these our eyes, yea, with the
							eyes that Soma gives.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Asvins, the pious call you with their hymns of praise, sounding their
							loud song forth to you, these living men, to their oblations, living
							men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							All glories and all nourishment, Lords of all wealth! depend on you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							The fellies of your golden chariot scatter drops, Mighty Ones! of your
							golden car.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well is it known, O Mighty Ones: ye open heaven; for you the
							chariot-steeds are yoked for morning rites, unswerving steeds for
							morning rites,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							We set you on the chariot-seat, ye Mighty, on the golden car.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							Ye seek mid-air as by a path that leads aright, as by a path that leads
							direct.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Rich in Strength, through your great power vouchsafe us blessings day
							and night.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The offerings which we bring to you shall never fail, gifts brought by
							us shall never fail.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Soma-drops, strong Indra! drink for heroes, poured, pressed out
							by pressing-stones, are welling forth for thee, for thee the drops are
							welling forth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							They shall make glad thy heart to give, to give wealth great and
							wonderful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							Thou who acceptest praise come glorified by hymns, come thou to us
							benevolent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Quickly, O Agni, hear us: magnified by us thou shalt speck for us to
							the Gods adorable yea, to the Kings adorable:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, O ye Deities, ye gave that Milch-cow to the Angirases,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 7: Line 3
					-
						-
							They milked her: Aryaman, joined with them, did the work: he knoweth
							her as well as I.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ne'er may these manly deeds of yours for us grow old, never may your
							bright glories fall into decay, never before our time decay.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							What deed of yours, new every age, wondrous, surpassing man, rings
							forth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 8: Line 3
					-
						-
							Whatever, Maruts! may be difficult to gain, grant us, whate'er is hard
							to gain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dadhyac of old, Angiras, Priyamedha these, and Kanva, Atri, Manu knew
							my birth, yea, those of ancient days and Manu knew.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Their long line stretcheth to the Gods, our birth-connexions are with
							them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 9: Line 3
					-
						-
							To these, for their high station, I bow down with song, to Indra, Agni,
							bow with song.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the Invoker bless: let offerers bring choice gifts; Brhaspati the
							Friend doth sacrifice with Steers, Steers that have many an excellence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now with our ears we catch the sound of the press-stone that rings
							afar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 10: Line 3
					-
						-
							The very Strong hath gained the waters by himself, the strong gained
							many a resting-place.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							O ye Eleven Gods whose home is heaven, O ye Eleven who make earth your
							dwelling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 139: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye who with might, Eleven, live in waters, accept this sacrifice, O
							Gods, with pleasure.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 140
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To splendid Agni seated by the altar, loving well his home, I bring the
							food as 'twere his place of birth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I clothe the bright One with my hymn as with a robe, him with the car
							of light, bright-hued, dispelling gloom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Child of a double birth he grasps at triple food; in the year's course
							what he hath swallowed grows anew.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, by another's mouth and tongue a noble Bull, with other, as an
							elephant, consumes the trees.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The pair who dwell together, moving in the dark bestir themselves: both
							parents hasten to the babe,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Impetuous-tongued, destroying, springing swiftly forth, one to be
							watched and cherished, strengthener of his sire.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For man, thou Friend of men, these steeds of thine are yoked,
							impatient, lightly running, ploughing blackened lines,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Discordant-minded, fleet, gliding with easy speed, urged onward by the
							wind and rapid in their course.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dispelling on their way the horror of black gloom, making a glorious
							show these flames of his fly forth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When o'er the spacious tract he spreads himself abroad, and rushes
							panting on with thunder and with roar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Amid brown plants he stoops as if adorning them, and rushes bellowing
							like a bull upon his wives.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Proving his might, he decks the glory of his form, and shakes his horns
							like one terrific, hard to stay.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now covered, now displayed he grasps as one who knows his resting-place
							in those who know him well.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							A second time they wax and gather Godlike power, and blending both
							together change their Parents' form.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The maidens with long, tresses hold him in embrace; dead, they rise up
							again to meet the Living One.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Releasing them from age with a loud roar he comes, filling them with
							new spirit, living, unsubdued.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Licking the mantle of the Mother, far and wide he wanders over fields
							with beasts that flee apace.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strengthening all that walk, licking up all around, a blackened path,
							forsooth, he leaves where'er he goes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, shine resplendent with our wealthy chiefs, like a loud-snorting
							bull, accustomed to the house.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou casting off thine infant wrappings blazest forth as though thou
							hadst put on a coat of mail for war.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this our perfect prayer be dearer unto thee than an imperfect
							prayer although it please thee well.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							With the pure brilliancy that radiates from thy form, mayest thou grant
							to us abundant store of wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grant to our chariot, to our house, O Agni, a boat with moving feet and
							constant oarage,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							One that may further well our wealthy princes and all the folk, and be
							our certain refuge.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Welcome our laud with thine approval, Agni. May earth and heaven and
							freely flowing rivers
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 140: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yield us long life and food and corn and cattle, and may the red Dawns
							choose for us their choicest.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 141
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YEA, verily, the fair effulgence of the God for glory was established,
							since he sprang from strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When he inclines thereto successful is the hymn: the songs of sacrifice
							have brought him as they flow
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wonderful, rich in nourishment, he dwells in food; next, in the seven
							auspicious Mothers is his home.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thirdly, that they might drain the treasures of the Bull, the maidens
							brought forth him for whom the ten provide.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time from out the deep, from the Steer's wondrous form, the Chiefs
							who had the power produced him with their strength;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Matarisvan rubbed forth him who lay concealed, for mixture of the
							sweet drink, in the days of old.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							When from the Highest Father he is brought to us, amid the plants he
							rises hungry, wondrously.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As both together join to expedite his birth, most youthful he is born
							resplendent in his light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then also entered he the Mothers, and in them pure and uninjured he
							increased in magnitude.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							As to the first he rose, the vigorous from of old, so now he runs among
							the younger lowest ones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Therefore they choose him Herald at the morning rites, pressing to him
							as unto Bhaga, pouring gifts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, much-praised, by the power and will of Gods, he goes at all times
							to his mortal worshipper to drink.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the Holy One, wind-urged, hath risen up, serpent-like winding
							through the dry grass unrestrained,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dust lies upon the way of him who burneth all, black-winged and pure of
							birth who follows sundry paths.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a swift chariot made by men who know their art, he with his red
							limbs lifts himself aloft to heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy worshippers become by burning black of hue: their strength flies as
							before a hero's violence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							By thee, O Agni, Varuna who guards the Law, Mitra and Aryaman, the
							Bounteous, are made strong;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							For, as the felly holds the spokes, thou with thy might pervading hast
							been born encompassing them round.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, to him who toils and pours libations, thou, Most Youthful!
							sendest wealth and all the host of Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee, therefore, even as Bhaga, will we set anew, young Child of
							Strength, most wealthy! in our battle-song.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us riches turned to worthy ends, good luck abiding in the
							house, and strong capacity,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth that directs both worlds as they were guiding-reins, and, very
							Wise, the Gods' assent in sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he, the Priest resplendent, joyful, hear us, he with the radiant
							car and rapid horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni, ever wise, with best directions to bliss and highest
							happiness conduct us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							With hymns of might hath Agni now been lauded, advanced to height of
							universal kingship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 141: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now may these wealthy chiefs and we together spread forth as spreads
							the Sun above the rain-clouds.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 142
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							KINDLED, bring, Agni, Gods to-day for him who lifts the ladle up.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Spin out the ancient thread for him who sheds, with gifts, the Soma
							juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou dealest forth, Tanunapat, sweet sacrifice enriched with oil,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brought by a singer such as I who offers gifts and toils for thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He wondrous, sanctifying, bright, sprinkles the sacrifice with mead,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thrice, Narasamsa from the heavens, a God mid Gods adorable.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, besought, bring hitherward Indra the Friend, the Wonderful,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For this my hymn of praise, O sweet of tongue, is chanted forth to
							thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The ladle-holders strew trimmed grass at this well-ordered sacrifice;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							A home for Indra is adorned, wide, fittest to receive the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrown open be the Doors Divine, unfailing, that assist the rite,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							High, purifying, much-desired, so that the Gods may enter in.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Night and Morning, hymned with lauds, united, fair to look upon,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strong Mothers of the sacrifice, seat them together on the grass.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the two Priests Divine, the sage, the sweet-voiced lovers of the
							hymn,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Complete this sacrifice of ours, effectual, reaching heaven to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Let Hotra pure, set among Gods, amid the Maruts Bharati, Ila, Sarasvati,
						Mahi, rest on the grass, adorable.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Tvastar send us genial dew abundant, wondrous, rich in gifts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							For increase and for growth of wealth, Tvastar our kinsman and our
							Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vanaspati, give forth, thyself, and call the Gods to sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni, God intelligent, speed our oblation to the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Vayu joined with Pusan, with the Maruts, and the host of Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Indra who inspires the hymn cry Glory! and present the gift.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come hither to enjoy the gifts prepared with cry of Glory! Come,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 142: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra, hear their calling; they invite thee to the sacrifice.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 143
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Agni I present a newer mightier hymn, I bring my words and song unto
							the Son of Strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, Offspring of the Waters, bearing precious things sits on the
							earth, in season, dear Invoking Priest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soon as he sprang to birth that Agni was shown forth to Matarisvan in
							the highest firmament.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When he was kindled, through his power and majesty his fiery splendour
							made the heavens and earth to shine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							His flames that wax not old, beams fair to look upon of him whose face
							is lovely, shine with beauteous sheen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The rays of Agni, him whose active force is light, through the nights
							glimmer sleepless, ageless, like the floods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send thou with hymns that Agni to his own abode, who rules, one Sovran
							Lord of wealth, like Varuna,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him, All-possessor, whom the Bhrgus with their might brought to earth's
							central point, the centre of the world.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He whom no force can stay, even as the Maruts' roar, like to a dart
							sent forth, even as the bolt from heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni with sharpened jaws chews up and eats the trees, and conquers them
							as when the warrior smites his foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							And will not Agni find enjoyment in our praise, will not the Vasu grant
							our wish with gifts of wealth?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Will not the Inspirer speed our prayers to gain their end? Him with the
							radiant glance I laud with this my song.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The kindler of the flame wins Agni as a Friend, promoter of the Law,
							whose face is bright with oil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Inflamed and keen, refulgent in our gatherings, he lifts our hymn on
							high clad in his radiant hues.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Keep us incessantly with guards that cease not, Agni, with guards
							auspicious, very mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 143: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With guards that never slumber, never heedless, never beguiled. O
							Helper, keep our children.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 144
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Priest goes forth to sacrifice, with wondrous power sending aloft
							the hymn of glorious brilliancy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He moves to meet the ladles turning to the right, which are the first
							to kiss the place where he abides.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him sang forth the flowing streams of Holy Law, encompassed in the
							home and birth-place of the God.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, when he dwelt extended in the waters' lap, absorbed those Godlike
							powers for which he is adored.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Seeking in course altern to reach the selfsame end the two copartners
							strive to win this beauteous form.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like Bhaga must he be duly invoked by us, as he who drives the car
							holds fast the horse's reins.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He whom the two copartners with observance tend, the pair who dwell
							together in the same abode,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							By night as in the day the grey one was born young, passing untouched
							by eld through many an age of man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him the ten fingers, the devotions, animate: we mortals call on him a
							God to give us help.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He speeds over the sloping surface of the land: new deeds hath he
							performed with those who gird him round.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							For, Agni, like a herdsman, thou by thine own might rulest o'er all
							that is in heaven and on the earth;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							And these two Mighty Ones, bright, golden closely joined, rolling them
							round are come unto thy sacred grass.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, accept with joy, be glad in this our prayer, joy-giver,
							self-sustained, strong, born of Holy Law!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 144: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							For fair to see art thou turning to every side, pleasant to look on as
							a dwelling filled with food.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 145
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ask ye of him for he is come, he knoweth it; he, full of wisdom, is
							implored, is now implored.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With him are admonitions and with him commands: he is the Lord of
							Strength, the Lord of Power and Might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They ask of him: not all learn by their questioning what he, the Sage,
							hath grasped, as 'twere, with his own mind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Forgetting not the former nor the later word, he goeth on, not
							careless, in his mental power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him these ladles go, to him these racing mares: he only will give
							ear to all the words I speak.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							All-speeding, victor, perfecter of sacrifice, the Babe with flawless
							help hath mustered vigorous might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whate'er he meets he grasps and then runs farther on, and straightway,
							newly born, creeps forward with his kin.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He stirs the wearied man to pleasure and great joy what time the
							longing gifts approach him as he comes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He is a wild thing of the flood and forest: he hath been laid upon the
							highest surface.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 145: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath declared the lore of works to mortals, Agni the Wise, for he
							knows Law, the Truthful.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 146
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I LAUD the seven-rayed, the triple-headed, Agni all-perfect in his
							Parents' bosom,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sunk in the lap of all that moves and moves not, him who hath filled
							all luminous realms of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As a great Steer he grew to these his Parents; sublime he stands,
							untouched by eld, far-reaching.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He plants his footsteps on the lofty ridges of the broad earth: his red
							flames lick the udder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Coming together to their common youngling both Cows, fairshaped, spread
							forth in all directions,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Measuring out the paths that must be travelled, entrusting all desires
							to him the Mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The prudent sages lead him to his dwelling, guarding with varied skill
							the Ever-Youthful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Longing, they turned their eyes unto the River: to these the Sun of men
							was manifested.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born noble in the regions, aim of all mens' eyes to be implored for
							life by great and small alike,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 146: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far as the Wealthy One hath spread himself abroad, he is the Sire
							all-visible of this progeny.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 147
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							How, Agni, have the radiant ones, aspiring, endued thee with the vigour
							of the living,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							So that on both sides fostering seed and offspring, the Gods may joy in
							Holy Law's fulfilment?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mark this my speech, Divine One, thou, Most Youthful! offered to thee
							by him who gives most freely.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							One hates thee, and another sings thy praises: I thine adorer laud thy
							form, O Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy guardian rays, O Agni, when they saw him, preserved blind Mamateya
							from affliction.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of all riches, he preserved the pious the foes who fain would harm
							them did no mischief.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The sinful man who worships not, O Agni, who, offering not, harms us
							with double-dealing,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be this in turn to him a heavy sentence may he distress himself by his
							revilings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, when a mortal knowingly, O Victor, injures with double tongue a
							fellow-mortal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 147: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							From him, praised Agni! save thou him that lauds thee: bring us not
							into trouble and affliction.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 148
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHAT Matarisvan, piercing, formed by friction, Herald of all the Gods.
							in varied figure,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is he whom they have set mid human houses, gay-hued as light and
							shining forth for beauty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They shall not harm the man who brings thee praises: such as I am, Agni
							my help approves me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							All acts of mine shall they accept with pleasure, laudation from the
							singer who presents it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him in his constant seat men skilled in worship have taken and with
							praises have established.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As, harnessed to a chariot fleet-foot horses, at his command let
							bearers lead him forward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wondrous, full many a thing he chews and crunches: he shines amid the
							wood with spreading brightness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Upon his glowing flames the wind blows daily, driving them like the
							keen shaft of an archer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, whom while yet in embryo the hostile, both skilled and fain to
							harm, may never injure,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 148: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men blind and sightless through his splendour hurt not: his
							never-failing lovers have preserved him.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 149
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HITHER he hastens to give, Lord of great riches, King of the mighty, to
							the place of treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The pressing-stones shall serve him speeding near us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As Steer of men so Steer of earth and heaven by glory, he whose streams
							all life hath drunken,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who hasting forward rests upon the altar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who hath lighted up the joyous castle, wise Courser like the Steed
							of cloudy heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bright like the Sun, with hundredfold existence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, doubly born, hath spread in his effulgence through the three
							luminous realms, through all the regions,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best sacrificing Priest where waters gather.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Priest doubly born, he through his love of glory hath in his keeping
							all things worth the choosing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 149: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The man who brings him gifts hath noble offspring.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 150
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 150: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 150: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI, thy faithful servant I call upon thee with many a gift,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 150: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As in the keeping of the great inciting God;
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 150: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 150: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou who ne'er movest thee to aid the indolent, the godless man,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 150: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who though wealthy never brings an offering.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 150: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 150: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Splendid, O Singer, is that man, mightiest of the great in heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 150: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, may we be foremost, we thy worshippers.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 151
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HEAVEN and earth trembled at the might and voice of him, whom, loved
							and Holy One, helper of all mankind,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The wise who longed for spoil in fight for kine brought forth with
							power, a Friend, mid waters, at the sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As these, like friends, have done this work for you, these prompt
							servants of Purumilha Soma-offerer,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give mental power to him who sings the sacred song, and hearken, Strong
							Ones, to the master of the house.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The folk have glorified your birth from Earth and Heaven, to be
							extolled, ye Strong Ones, for your mighty power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, when ye bring to singer and the rite, enjoy the sacrifice performed
							with holy praise and strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The people prospers, Asuras! whom ye dearly love: ye, Righteous Ones,
							proclaim aloud the Holy Law.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That efficacious power that comes from lofty heaven, ye bind unto the
							work, as to the pole an ox.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							On this great earth ye send your treasure down with might: unstained by
							dust, the crowding kine are in the stalls.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here in the neighbourhood they cry unto the Sun at morning and at
							evening, like swift birds of prey.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The flames with curling tresses serve your sacrifice, whereto ye sing
							the song, Mitra and Varuna.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Send down of your free will, prosper our holy songs: ye are sole
							Masters of the singer's hymn of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso with sacrifices toiling brings you gifts, and worships, sage and
							priest, fulfilling your desire,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him do ye draw nigh and taste his sacrifice. Come well-inclined to
							us unto our songs and prayer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							With sacrifices and with milk they deck you first, ye Righteous Ones,
							as if through stirrings of the mind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							To you they bring their hymns with their collected thought, while ye
							with earnest soul come to us gloriously.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rich strength of life is yours: ye, Heroes, have obtained through your
							surpassing powers rich far-extending might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 151: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not the past days conjoined with nights, not rivers, not the Panis have
							attained your Godhead and your wealth.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 152
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE robes which ye put on abound with fatness: uninterrupted courses
							are your counsels.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							All falsehood, Mitra-Varuna! ye conquer, and closely cleave unto the
							Law Eternal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							This might of theirs hath no one comprehended. True is the crushing
							word the sage hath uttered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The fearful four-edged bolt smites down the three-edged, and those who
							hate the Gods first fall and perish.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Footless Maid precedeth footed creatures. Who marketh,
							Mitra-Varuna, this your doing?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Babe Unborn supporteth this world's burthen, fulfilleth Law and
							overcometh falsehood.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							We look on him the darling of the Maidens, always advancing, never
							falling downward,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wearing inseparable, wide-spread raiment, Mitra's and Varuna's
							delightful glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unbridled Courser, born but not of horses, neighing he flieth on with
							back uplifted.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The youthful love mystery thought-surpassing, praising in Mitra-Varuna,
							its glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the milch-kine who favour Mamateya prosper in this world him who
							loves devotion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, well skilled in rites, be food, and calling Aditi with his lips
							give us assistance.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods, Mitra-Varuna, with love and worship, let me make you delight in
							this oblation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 152: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May our prayer be victorious in battles, may we have rain from heaven
							to make us prosper.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 153
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WE worship with our reverence and oblations you, Mitra Varuna,
							accordant, mighty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							So that with us, ye Twain whose backs are sprinkled with oil, the
							priests with oil and hymns support you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your praise is like a mighty power, an impulse: to you, Twain Gods, a
							well-formed hymn is offered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As the priest decks yon, Strong Ones, in assemblies, and the prince
							fain to worship you for blessings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Mitra-Varuna, Aditi the Milch-cow streams for the rite, for folk who
							bring oblation,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When in the assembly he who worships moves you, like to a human priest,
							with gifts presented.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may the kine and heavenly Waters pour you sweet drink in families
							that make you joyful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 153: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of this may he, the ancient House-Lord, give us. Enjoy, drink of the
							milk the cow provideth.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 154
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I WILL declare the mighty deeds of Visnu, of him who measured out the
							earthly regions,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who propped the highest place of congregation, thrice setting down his
							footstep, widely striding.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For this his mighty deed is Visnu lauded, like some wild beast, dread,
							prowling, mountain-roaming;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He within whose three wide-extended paces all living creatures have
							their habitation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the hymn lift itself as strength to Visnu, the Bull far-striding,
							dwelling on the mountains,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who alone with triple step hath measured this common
							dwelling-place, long, far extended.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him whose three places that are filled with sweetness, imperishable,
							joy as it may list them,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who verily alone upholds the threefold, the earth, the heaven, and all
							living creatures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May I attain to that his well-loved mansion where men devoted to the
							Gods are happy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							For there springs, close akin to the Wide-Strider, the well of meath in
							Visnu's highest footstep.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fain would we go unto your dwelling-places where there are many-horned
							and nimble oxen,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 154: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For mightily, there, shineth down upon us the widely-striding Bull's
							sublimest mansion.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 155
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To the great Hero, him who sets his mind thereon, and Visnu, praise
							aloud in song your draught of juice,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gods ne'er beguiled, who borne as 'twere by noble steed, have stood
							upon the lofty ridges of the hills.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your Soma-drinker keeps afar your furious rush, Indra and Visnu, when
							ye come with all your might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That which hath been directed well at mortal man, bow-armed Krsanu's
							arrow, ye turn far aside.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							These offerings increase his mighty manly strength: he brings both
							Parents down to share the genial flow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He lowers, though a son, the Father's highest name; the third is that
							which is high in the light of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							We laud this manly power of him the Mighty One, preserver, inoffensive,
							bounteous and benign;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							His who strode, widely pacing, with three steppings forth over the
							realms of earth for freedom and for life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							A mortal man, when he beholds two steps of him who looks upon the
							light, is restless with amaze.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							But his third step doth no one venture to approach, no, nor the
							feathered birds of air who fly with wings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, like a rounded wheel, hath in swift motion set his ninety racing
							steeds together with the four.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 155: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Developed, vast in form, with those who sing forth praise, a youth, no
							more a child, he cometh to our call.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 156
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FAR-SHINING, widely famed, going thy wonted way, fed with the oil, be
							helpful. Mitra-like, to us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, Visnu, e'en the wise must swell thy song of praise, and he who hath
							oblations pay thee solemn rites.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who brings gifts to him the Ancient and the Last, to Visnu who
							ordains, together with his Spouse,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who tells the lofty birth of him the Lofty One, shall verily surpass in
							glory e'en his peer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him have ye satisfied, singers, as well as ye know, primeval gem of
							Order even from his birth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, knowing e'en his name, have told it forth: may we, Visnu, enjoy the
							grace of thee the Mighty One.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sovran Varuna and both the Asvins wait on this the will of him who
							guides the Marut host.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Visnu hath power supreme and might that finds the day, and with his
							Friend unbars the stable of the kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even he the Heavenly One who came for fellowship, Visnu to Indra, godly
							to the godlier,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 156: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who Maker, throned in three worlds, helps the Aryan man, and gives the
							worshipper his share of Holy Law.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 157
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI is wakened: Surya riseth from the earth. Mighty, refulgent Dawn
							hath shone with all her light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Asvins have equipped their chariot for the course. God Savitar hath
							moved the folk in sundry ways.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, Asvins, ye equip your very mighty car, bedew, ye Twain, our power
							with honey and with oil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							To our devotion give victorious strength in war: may we win riches in
							the heroes' strife for spoil.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Nigh to us come the Asvins' lauded three-wheeled car, the car laden
							with meath and drawn by fleet-foot steeds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Three-seated, opulent, bestowing all delight. may it bring weal to us,
							to cattle and to men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring hither nourishment for us, ye Asvins Twain; sprinkle us with your
							whip that drops with honey-dew.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Prolong our days of life, wipe out our trespasses; destroy our foes, be
							our companions and our Friends.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye store the germ of life in female creatures, ye lay it up within all
							living beings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye have sent forth, O Asvins passing mighty, the fire, the sovrans of
							the wood, the waters,
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Leeches are ye with medicines to heal us, and charioteers are ye with
							skill in driving.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 157: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Strong, give sway to him who brings oblation and with his heart
							pours out his gift before you.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 158
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YE Vasus Twain, ye Rudras full of counsel, grant us, Strong
							Strengtheners, when ye stand beside us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							What wealth Aucathya craves of you, great Helpers when ye come forward
							with no niggard succour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who may give you aught, Vasus, for your favour, for what, at the Cow's
							place, ye grant through worship?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wake for us understanding full of riches, come with a heart that will
							fulfil our longing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							As erst for Tugra's son your car, sea-crossing, strong, was equipped
							and set amid the waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may I gain your shelter and protection as with winged course a hero
							seeks his army.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this my praise preserve Ucathya's offspring: let not these Twain
							who fly with wings exhaust me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not the wood ten times up-piled consume me, when fixed for you it
							bites the ground it stands on.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The most maternal streams, wherein the Dasas cast me securely bound,
							have not devoured me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Traitana would cleave my head asunder, the Dasa wounded his own
							breast and shoulders.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dirghatamas the son of Mamata hath come to length of days in the tenth
							age of human kind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 158: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He is the Brahman of the waters as they strive to reach their end and
							aim: their charioteer is he.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 159
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I PRAISE with sacrifices mighty Heaven and Earth at festivals, the
							wise, the Strengtheners of Law.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, having Gods for progeny, conjoined with Gods, through
							wonder-working wisdom bring forth choicest boons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With invocations, on the gracious Father's mind, and on the Mother's
							great inherent power I muse.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Prolific Parents, they have made the world of life, and for their brood
							all round wide immortality.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Sons of yours well skilled in work, of wondrous power, brought
							forth to life the two great Mothers first of all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To keep the truth of all that stands and all that moves, ye guard the
							station of your Son who knows no guile.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They with surpassing skill, most wise, have measured out the Twins
							united in their birth and in their home.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They, the refulgent Sages, weave within the sky, yea, in the depths of
							sea, a web for ever new.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is to-day the goodliest gift of Savitar: this thought we have when
							now the God is furthering us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 159: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							On us with loving-kindness Heaven and Earth bestow riches and various
							wealth and treasure hundredfold!
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 160
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE, Heaven and Earth, bestow prosperity on all, sustainers of the
							region, Holy Ones and wise,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Two Bowls of noble kind: between these Goddesses the God, the fulgent
							Sun, travels by fixed decree.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Widely-capacious Pair, mighty, that never fail, the Father and the
							Mother keep all creatures safe:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The two world-halves, the spirited, the beautiful, because the Father
							hath clothed them in goodly forms.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Son of these Parents, he the Priest with power to cleanse, Sage,
							sanctifies the worlds with his surpassing power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thereto for his bright milk he milked through all the days the
							party-coloured Cow and the prolific Bull.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Among the skilful Gods most skilled is he, who made the two
							world-halves which bring prosperity to all;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who with great wisdom measured both the regions out, and stablished
							them with pillars that shall ne'er decay.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Extolled in song, O Heaven and Earth, bestow on us, ye mighty Pair,
							great glory and high lordly sway,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 160: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whereby we may extend ourselves ever over the folk; and send us
							strength that shall deserve the praise of men.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 161
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHY hath the Best, why hath the Youngest come to us? Upon what embassy
							comes he? What have we said?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							We have not blamed the chalice of illustrious birth. We, Brother Agni,
							praised the goodness of the wood.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The chalice that is single make ye into four: thus have the Gods
							commanded; therefore am I come.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							If, O Sudhanvan's Children, ye will do this thing ye shall participate
							in sacrifice with Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What to the envoy Agni in reply ye spake, A courser must be made, a
							chariot fashioned here,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							A cow must be created, and the Twain made young. When we have done
							these things, Brother, we turn to you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thus, O Rbhus, ye had done ye questioned thus, Whither went he who
							came to us a messenger?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then Tvastar, when he viewed the four wrought chalices, concealed
							himself among the Consorts of the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As Tvastar thus had spoken, Let us slay these men who have reviled the
							chalice, drinking-cup of Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							They gave themselves new names when Soma juice was shed, and under
							these new names the Maiden welcomed them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra hath yoked his Bays, the Asvins' car is horsed, Brhaspati hath
							brought the Cow of every hue.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye went as Rbhus, Vibhvan, Vaja to the Gods, and skilled in war,
							obtained your share in sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye by your wisdom brought a cow from out a hide; unto that ancient Pair
							ye gave again their youth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Out of a horse, Sudhanvan's Sons, ye formed a horse: a chariot ye
							equipped, and went unto the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drink ye this water, were the words ye spake to them; or drink ye this,
							the rinsing of the Muñja-grass.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							If ye approve not even this, Sudhanvan's Sons, then at the third
							libation gladden ye yourselves.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Most excellent are waters, thus said one of you; most excellent is
							Agni, thus another said.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Another praised to many a one the lightning cloud. Then did ye shape
							the cups, speaking the words of truth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							One downward to the water drives the crippled cow, another trims the
							flesh brought on the carving-board.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							One carries off the refuse at the set of sun. How did the Parents aid
							their children in their task!
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							On the high places ye have made the grass for man, and water in the
							valleys, by your skill, O Men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rbhus, ye iterate not to-day that act of yours, your sleeping in the
							house of him whom naught can hide.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							As, compassing them round, ye glided through the worlds, where had the
							venerable Parents their abode?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye laid a curse on him who raised his arm at you: to him who spake
							aloud to you ye spake again.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							When ye had slept your fill, ye Rbhus, thus ye asked, O thou whom
							naught may hide, who now hath wakened us?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							The goat declared the hound to be your wakener. That day, in a full
							year, ye first unclosed our eyes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Maruts move in heaven, on earth this Agni; through the
							mid-firmament the Wind approaches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 161: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Varuna comes in the sea's gathered waters, O Sons of Strength, desirous
							of your presence.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 162
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 162: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 162: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SLIGHT us not Varuna, Aryaman, or Mitra, Rbhuksan, Indra, Ayu, or the
							Maruts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 162: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When we declare amid the congregation the virtues of the strong Steed,
							God-descended.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 162: Verse 2
				-
					-
