						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							For I am known as terrible, O Maruts I, Indra, am the Lord of what I
							ruined.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, O ye Maruts, hath your praise rejoiced me, the glorious hymn which
							ye have made me, Heroes!
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							For me, for Indra, champion strong in battle, for me, yourselves, as
							lovers for a lover.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here, truly, they send forth their sheen to meet me, wearing their
							blameless glory and their vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							When I have seen you, Maruts, in gay splendour, ye have delighted me,
							so now delight me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who here hath magnified you, O ye Maruts? speed forward, O ye lovers,
							to your lovers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Radiant Ones, assisting their devotions, of these my holy rites he
							ye regardful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							To this hath Manya's wisdom brought us, so as to aid, as aids the poet
							him who worships.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring hither quick! On to the sage, ye Maruts! These prayers for you
							the singer hath recited.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this your praise, may this your song, O Maruts, sung by the poet,
							Mana's son, Mandarya,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 165: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring offspring for ourselves with food to feed us. May we find
							strengthening food in full abundance!
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 166
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now let us publish, for the vigorous company the herald of the Strong
							One, their primeval might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With fire upon your way, O Maruts loud of voice, with battle, Mighty
							Ones, achieve your deeds of strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bringing the pleasant meath as 'twere their own dear son, they sport in
							sportive wise gay at their gatherings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Rudras come with succour to the worshipper; self-strong they fail
							not him who offers sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							To whomsoever, bringer of oblations, they immortal guardians, have
							given plenteous wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							For him, like loving friends, the Maruts bringing bliss bedew the
							regions round with milk abundantly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye who with mighty powers have stirred the regions up, your coursers
							have sped forth directed by themselves.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							All creatures of the earth, all dwellings are afraid, for brilliant is
							your coming with your spears advanced.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When they in dazzling rush have made the mountains roar, and shaken
							heaven's high back in their heroic strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Each sovran of the forest fears as ye drive near, aid the shrubs fly
							before you swift as whirling wheels.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Terrible Maruts, ye with ne'er-diminished host, with great benevolence
							fulfil our heart's desire.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where'er your lightning bites armed with its gory teeth it crunches up
							the cattle like a well-aimed dart.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Givers of during gifts whose bounties never fail, free from ill-will,
							at sacrifices glorified,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They sing their song aloud that they may drink sweet juice: well do
							they know the Hero's first heroic deeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							With castles hundredfold, O Maruts, guard ye well the man whom ye have
							loved from ruin and from sin,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The man whom ye the fierce, the Mighty ones who roar, preserve from
							calumny by cherishing his seed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Maruts, in your cars are all things that are good: great powers are
							set as 'twere in rivalry therein.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rings are upon your shoulders when ye journey forth: your axle turns
							together both the chariot wheels.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Held in your manly arms are many goodly things, gold chains are on your
							chests, and glistering ornaments,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Deer-skins are on their shoulders, on their fellies knives: they spread
							their glory out as birds spread out their wings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mighty in mightiness, pervading, passing strong, visible from afar as
							'twere with stars of heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lovely with pleasant tongues, sweet singers with their mouths, the
							Maruts, joined with Indra, shout forth all around.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is your majesty, ye Maruts nobly born, far as the sway of Aditi
							your bounty spreads.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even Indra by desertion never disannuls the boon bestowed by you upon
							the pious man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is your kinship, Maruts, that, Immortals, ye were oft in olden
							time regardful of our call,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Having vouchsafed to man a hearing through this prayer, by wondrous
							deeds the Heroes have displayed their might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							That, O ye Maruts, we may long time flourish through your abundant
							riches, O swift movers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							And that our men may spread in the encampment, let me complete the rite
							with these oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this your laud, may this your song, O Maruts, sung by the poet,
							Mana's son, Mandarya,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 166: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring offspring for ourselves with food to feed us. May we find
							strengthening food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 167
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							A THOUSAND are thy helps for us, O Indra: a thousand, Lord of Bays, thy
							choice refreshments.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth of a thousand sorts hast thou to cheer us: may precious goods
							come nigh to us in thousands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the most sapient Maruts, with protection, with best boons brought
							from lofty heaven, approach us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now when their team of the most noble horses speeds even on the sea's
							extremest limit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Close to them clings one moving in seclusion, like a man's wife, like a
							spear carried rearward,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well grasped, bright, decked with gold there is Vak also, like to a
							courtly, eloquent dame, among them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far off the brilliant, never-weary Maruts cling to the young Maid as a
							joint possession.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The fierce Gods drave not Rodasi before them, but wished for her to
							grow their friend and fellow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When chose immortal Rodasi to follow--she with loose tresses and heroic
							spirit--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							She climbed her servant's chariot, she like Surya with cloud-like
							motion and refulgent aspect.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Upon their car the young men set the Maiden wedded to glory, mighty in
							assemblies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When your song, Maruts, rose, and, with oblation, the Soma-pourer sang
							his hymn in worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will declare the greatness of these Maruts, their real greatness,
							worthy to be lauded,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							How, with them, she though firm, strong-minded, haughty, travels to
							women happy in their fortune.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mitra and Varuna they guard from censure: Aryaman too, discovers worthless
						sinners Firm things are overthrown that ne'er were shaken: he prospers,
						Maruts, who gives choice oblations.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							None of us, Maruts, near or at a distance, hath ever reached the limit
							of your vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							They in courageous might still waxing boldly have compassed round their
							foemen like an ocean.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we this day be dearest friends of Indra, and let us call on him in
							fight to-morrow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							So were we erst. New might attend us daily! So be with us! Rbhuksan of
							the Heroes!
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this your laud, may this your song, O Maruts, sung by the poet,
							Mana's
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							son, Mandarya,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 167: Verse 11: Line 3
					-
						-
							Bring offspring for ourselves with. food to feed us. May we find
							strengthening food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 168
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SWIFT gain is his who hath you near at every rite: ye welcome every
							song of him who serves the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may I turn you hither with fair hymns of praise to give great
							succour for the weal of both the worlds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surrounding, as it were, self-born, self-powerful, they spring to life
							the shakers-down of food and light;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like as the countess undulations of the floods, worthy of praise when
							near, like bullocks and like kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who, like Somas with their well-grown stalks pressed out, imbibed
							within the heart, dwell there in friendly wise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Upon their shoulders rests as 'twere a warrior's spear and in their
							hand they hold a dagger and a ring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Self-yoked they have descended lightly from the sky. With your own
							lash, Immortals, urge yourselves to speed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unstained by dust the Maruts, mighty in their strength, have cast down
							e'en firm things, armed with their shining spears.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who among you, O Maruts armed with lightning-spears, moveth you by
							himself, as with the tongue his jaws?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye rush from heaven's floor as though ye sought for food, on many
							errands like the Sun's diurnal Steed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Say where, then, is this mighty region's farthest bound, where, Maruts,
							is the lowest depth that ye have reached,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When ye cast down like chaff the firmly stablished pile, and from the
							mountain send the glittering water-flood?
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your winning is with strength, dazzling, with heavenly light, with
							fruit mature, O Maruts, fall of plenteousness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Auspicious is your gift like a free giver's meed, victorious, spreading
							far, as of immortal Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The rivers roar before your chariot fellies when they are uttering the
							voice of rain-clouds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The lightnings laugh upon the earth beneath them, what time the Maruts
							scatter forth their fatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prsni brought forth, to fight the mighty battle, the glittering army of
							the restless Maruts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nurtured together they begat the monster, and then looked round them
							for the food that strengthens.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this your laud, may this your song O Maruts, sung by the poet
							Mana's son,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mandarya,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 168: Verse 10: Line 3
					-
						-
							Bring offspring for ourselves with food to feed us. May we find
							strengthening food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 169
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As, Indra, from great treason thou protectest, yea, from great
							treachery these who approach us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, marking well, Controller of the Maruts grant us their blessings,
							for they are thy dearest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The various doings of all mortal people by thee are ordered, in thy
							wisdom, Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The host of Maruts goeth forth exulting to win the light-bestowing
							spoil of battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							That spear of thine sat firm for us, O Indra: the Maruts set their
							whole dread power in motion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							E'en Agni shines resplendent in the brush-wood: the viands hold him as
							floods hold an island.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us now that opulence, O Indra, as guerdon won by mightiest
							donation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May hymns that please thee cause the breast of Vayu to swell as with
							the mead's refreshing sweetness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With thee, O Indra, are most bounteous riches that further every one
							who lives uprightly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now may these Maruts show us loving-kindness, Gods who of old were ever
							prompt to help us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 169: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring forth the Men who rain down boons, O Indra: exert thee in the
