				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 176: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 176: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Slay everyone who pours no gift, who, hard to reach, delights thee not.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 176: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bestow on us what wealth he hath: this even the worshipper awaits.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 176: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 176: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou helpest him the doubly strong whose hymns were sung unceasingly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 176: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Indra fought, O Soma, thou helpest the mighty in the fray.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 176: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 176: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							As thou, O Indra, to the ancient singers wast ever joy, like water to
							the thirsty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 176: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							So unto thee I sing this invocation. May we find strengthening food in
							full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 177
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Bull of men, who cherishes all people, King of the Races, Indra,
							called of many,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fame-loving, praised, hither to me with succour turn having yoked both
							vigorous Bay Horses!
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy mighty Stallions, yoked by prayer, O Indra, thy. Coursers to thy
							mighty chariot harnessed,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ascend thou these, and borne by them come hither: with Soma juice out.
							poured, Indra, we call thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ascend thy mighty car: the mighty Soma is poured for thee and sweets
							are sprinkled round us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come down to us-ward, Bull of human races, come, having harnessed them,
							with strong Bay Horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here is God-reaching sacrifice, here the victim; here, Indra, are the
							prayers, here is the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strewn is the sacred grass: come hither, Sakra; seat thee and drink:
							unyoke thy two Bay Coursers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to us, Indra, come thou highly lauded to the devotions of the
							singer Mana.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 177: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Singing, may we find early through thy succour, may we find
							strengthening food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 178
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							IF, Indra, thou hast given that gracious hearing where with thou
							helpest those who sang thy praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blast not the wish that would exalt us may I gain all from thee, and
							pay all man's devotions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let not the Sovran Indra disappoint us in what shall bring both Sisters
							to our dwelling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him have run the quickly flowing waters. May Indra come to us with
							life and friendship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Victorious with the men, Hero in battles, Indra, who hears the singer's
							supplication,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Will bring his car nigh to the man who offers, if he himself upholds
							the songs that praise him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, Indra, with the men, through love of glory consumes the sacred
							food which friends have offered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The ever-strengthening song of him who worships is sung in fight amid
							the clash of voices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aided by thee, O Maghavan, O Indra, may we subdue our foes who count
							them mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 178: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be our protector, strengthen and increase us. May we find strengthening
							food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 179
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 179: Verse 1
				-
					-
						following Hymn was originally only found in the Appendix, with certain
						lines translated in Latin.--JBH.)
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 180
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LIGHTLY your coursers travel through the regions when round the sea of
							air your car is flying.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your golden fellies scatter drops of moisture: drinking the sweetness
							ye attend the Mornings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye as ye travel overtake the Courser who flies apart, the Friend of
							man, most holy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The prayer is that the Sister may convey you, all praised,
							meath-drinkers! to support and strengthen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye have deposited, matured within her, in the raw cow the first milk of
							the milch-cow,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Which the bright offerer, shining like a serpent mid trees, presents to
							you whose form is perfect.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye made the fierce heat to be full of sweetness for Atri at his wish,
							like streaming water.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fire-offering thence is yours, O Asvins, Heroes: your car-wheels speed
							to us like springs of honey.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like Tugra's ancient son may I, ye Mighty, bring you to give your gifts
							with milk-oblations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your greatness compasseth Earth, Heaven, and Waters: decayed for you is
							sorrow's net, ye Holy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, Bounteous Ones, ye drive your yoked team downward, ye send, by
							your own natures, understanding.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Swift as the wind let the prince please and feast you: he, like a pious
							man, gains strength for increase.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							For verily we truthful singers praise you the niggard trafficker is
							here excluded.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now, even now do ye O blameless Asvins, ye Mighty, guard the man whose
							God is near him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							You of a truth day after day, O Asvins, that he might win the very
							plenteous torrent,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agastya, famous among mortal heroes, roused with a thousand lauds like
							sounds of music.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							When with the glory of your car ye travel, when we go speeding like the
							priest of mortals,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							And give good horses to sacrificers, may we, Nasatyas! gain our share
							of riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							With songs of praise we call to-day, O Asvins, that your new chariot,
							for our own well-being,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 180: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							That circles heaven with never-injured fellies. May we find
							strengthening food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 181
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHAT, dearest Pair, is this in strength and riches that ye as Priests
							are bring from the waters?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							This sacrifice is your glorification, ye who protect mankind and give
							them treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May your pure steeds, rain-drinkers, bring you hither, swift as the
							tempest, your celestial coursers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rapid as thought, with fair backs, full of vigour, resplendent in their
							native light, O Asvins.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your car is like a torrent rushing downward: may it come nigh,
							broad-seated, for our welfare,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Car holy, strong, that ever would be foremost, thought-swift, which ye,
							for whom we long, have mounted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here sprung to life, they both have sung together, with bodies free
							from stain, with signs that mark them;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							One of you Prince of Sacrifice, the Victor, the other counts as
							Heaven's auspicious offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May your car-seat, down-gliding, golden-coloured, according to your
							wish approach our dwellings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men shall feed full the bay steeds of the other, and, Asvins they with
							roars shall stir the regions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forth comes your strong Bull like a cloud of autumn, sending abundant
							food of liquid sweetness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let them feed with the other's ways and vigour: the upper streams have
							come and do us service.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your constant song hath been sent forth, Disposers! that flows
							threefold in mighty strength, O Asvins.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thus lauded, give the suppliant protection moving or resting hear mine
							invocation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							This song of bright contents for you is swelling in the men's hall
							where three-fold grass is ready.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your strong rain-cloud, ye Mighty Ones, hath swollen, honouring men as
							'twere with milk's outpouring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The prudent worshipper, like Pusan, Asvins! praises you as he praises
							Dawn and Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 181: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, singing with devotion, he invokes you. May we find strengthening
							food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 182
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS was the task. Appear promptly, ye prudent Ones. Here is the
							chariot drawn by strong steeds: be ye glad.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Heart-stirring, longed for, succourers of Vispala, here are Heaven's
							Sons whose sway blesses the pious man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Longed for, most Indra-like, mighty, most Marut-like, most wonderful in
							deed, car-borne, best charioteers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring your full chariot hither heaped with liquid sweet: thereon, ye
							Asvins, come to him who offers gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What make ye there, ye Mighty? Wherefore linger ye with folk who,
							offering not, are held in high esteem?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pass over them; make ye the niggard's life decay: give light unto the
							singer eloquent in praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Crunch up on. every side the dogs who bark at us: slay ye our foes, O
							Asvins this ye understand.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make wealthy every word of him who praises you: accept with favour,
							both Nasatyas, this my laud.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye made for Tugra's son amid the water-floods that animated ship with
							wings to fly withal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whereon with God-devoted mind ye brought him forth, and fled with easy
							flight from out the mighty surge.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Four ships most welcome in the midst of ocean, urged by the Asvins,
							save the son of Tugra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who was cast down headlong in the waters, plunged in the thick
							inevitable darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							What tree was that which stood fixed in surrounding sea to which the
							son of Tugra supplicating clung?
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like twigs, of which some winged creature may take hold, ye, Asvins,
							bore him off safely to your renown.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Welcome to you be this the hymn of praises uttered by Manas, O
							Nasatyas, Heroes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 182: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							From this our gathering where we offer Soma. May we find strengthening
							food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 183
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAKE ready that which passes thought in swiftness, that hath three
							wheels and triple seat, ye Mighty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whereon ye seek the dwelling of the pious, whereon, threefold, ye fly
							like birds with pinions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Light rolls your easy chariot faring earthward, what time, for food,
							ye, full of wisdom, mount it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May this song, wondrous fair, attend your glory: ye, as ye travel, wait
							on Dawn Heaven's Daughter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ascend your lightly rolling car, approaching the worshipper who turns
							him to his duties,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whereon ye come unto the house to quicken man and his offspring, O
							Nasatyas, Heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let not the wolf, let not the she-wolf harm you. Forsake me not, nor
							pass me by or others.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here stands your share, here is your hymn, ye Mighty: yours are these
							vessels, full of pleasant juices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gotama, Purumilha, Atri bringing oblations all invoke you for
							protection.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like one who goes straight to the point directed, ye Nasatyas, to mine
							invocation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							We have passed o'er the limit of this darkness: our praise hath been
							bestowed on you, O Asvins.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 183: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come hitherward by paths which Gods have travelled. May we find
							strengthening food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 184
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 184: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 184: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
