					-
						-
							Far from us, Agni, put thou all diseases let them strike lauds that
							have no saving Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							God, make our home again to be a blessing, with all the Immortal
							Deities, O Holy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Preserve us, Agni, with perpetual succour, refulgent in the dwelling
							which thou lovest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Conqueror, most youthful, let no danger touch him who praises thee
							to-day or after.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give not us up a prey to sin, O Agni, the greedy enemy that brings us
							trouble;
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not to the fanged that bites, not to the toothless: give not us up,
							thou Conqueror, to the spoiler.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Such as thou art, born after Law, O Agni when lauded give protection to
							our bodies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							From whosoever would reproach or injure: for thou, God, rescuest from
							all oppression.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, well discerning both these classes, comest to men at early morn,
							O holy Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be thou obedient unto man at evening, to be adorned, as keen, by eager
							suitors.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him have we addressed our pious speeches, I, Mana's son, to him
							victorious Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 189: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we gain countless riches with the sages. May we find strengthening
							food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 190
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GLORIFY thou Brhaspati, the scatheless, who must be praised with hymns,
							sweet-tongued and mighty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To whom as leader of the song, resplendent, worthy of lauds, both Gods
							and mortals listen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							On him wait songs according to the season even as a stream of pious men
							set moving.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati--for he laid out the expanses--was, at the sacrifice, vast
							Matarisvan.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The praise, the verse that offers adoration, may he bring forth, as the
							Sun sends his arms out,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who gives daily light through this God's wisdom, strong as a dread
							wild beast, and inoffensive.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							His song of praise pervades the earth and heaven: let the wise
							worshipper draw it, like a courser.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							These of Brhaspati, like hunters' arrows, go to the skies that change
							their hue like serpents.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those, God, who count thee as a worthless bullock, and, wealthy
							sinners, live on thee the Bounteous,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							On fools like these no blessing thou bestowest: Brhaspati, thou
							punishest the spiteful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a fair path is he, where grass is pleasant, though hard to win, a
							Friend beloved most early.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Those who unharmed by enemies behold us, while they would make them
							bare, stood closely compassed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He to whom songs of praise go forth like torrents, as rivers eddying
							under banks flow sea-ward--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati the wise, the eager, closely looks upon both, the waters and
							the vessel.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							So hath Brhaspati, great, strong and mighty, the God exceeding
							powerful, been brought hither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 190: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he thus lauded give us kine and horses. May we find strengthening
							food in full abundance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 191
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							VENOMOUS, slightly venomous, or venomous aquatic worm,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Both creatures, stinging, unobserved, with poison have infected me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Coming, it kills the unobserved; it kills them as it goes away,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							It kills them as it drives them off, and bruising bruises them to
							death.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sara grass, Darbha, Kusara, and Sairya, Muñja, Virana,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where all these creatures dwell unseen, with poison have infected me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The cows had settled in their stalls, the beasts of prey had sought
							their lairs,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Extinguished were the lights of men, when things unseen infected me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Or these, these reptiles, are observed, like lurking thieves at evening
							time.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seers of all, themselves unseen: be therefore very vigilant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Heaven is your Sire, your Mother Earth, Soma your Brother, Aditi
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your Sister: seeing all, unseen, keep still and dwell ye happily.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Biters of shoulder or of limb, with needle-stings, most venomous,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unseen, whatever ye may be, vanish together and be gone.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Slayer of things unseen, the Sun, beheld of all, mounts, eastward, up,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Consuming all that are not seen, and evil spirits of the night.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							There hath the Sun-God mounted up, who scorches much and everything.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even the Aditya from the hills, all-seen, destroying things unseen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							I hang the poison in the Sun, a wine-skin in a vintner's house,
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He will not die, nor shall we die: his path is far: he whom Bay Horses
							bear hath turned thee to sweet meath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							This little bird, so very small, hath swallowed all thy poison up.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							She will not die, nor shall we die: his path is far: he whom Bay Horses
							bear hath turned thee to sweet meath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							The three-times-seven bright sparks of fire have swallowed up the
							poison's strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							They will not die, nor shall we die: his path is far: he whom Bay
							Horses bear hath turned thee to sweet meath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of ninety rivers and of nine with power to stay the venom's course,--
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							The names of all I have secured: his path is far: he whom Bay Horses
							bear hath turned thee to sweet meath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							So have the peahens three-times-seven, so have the maiden Sisters Seven
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Carried thy venom far away, as girls bear water in their jars.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							The poison-insect is so small; I crush the creature with a stone.
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							I turn the poison hence away, departed unto distant lands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forth issuing from the mountain's side the poison-insect spake and
							said:
						-
					-
						Mandala 1: Hymn 191: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Scorpion, they venom is but weak.
						-
		-
			Mandala 2
		-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 1
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU, Agni, shining in thy glory through the days, art brought to life
							from out the waters, from the stone:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							From out the forest trees and herbs that grow on ground, thou, Sovran
							Lord of men art generatad [sic] pure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine is the Herald's task and Cleanser's duly timed; Leader art thou,
							and Kindler for the pious man.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art Director, thou the ministering Priest: thou art the Brahman,
							Lord and Master in our home.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hero of Heroes, Agni! Thou art Indra, thou art Visnu of the Mighty
							Stride, adorable:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Brahmanaspati, the Brahman finding wealth: thou, O Sustainer,
							with thy wisdom tendest us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, thou art King Varuna whose laws stand fast; as Mitra,
							Wonder-Worker, thou must be implored.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aryaman, heroes' Lord, art thou, enrich ing all, and liberal Amsa in
							the synod, O thou God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou givest strength, as Tvastar, to the worshipper: thou wielding
							Mitra's power hast kinship with the Dames.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, urging thy fleet coursers, givest noble steeds: a host of heroes
							art thou with great store of wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rudra art thou, the Asura of mighty heaven: thou art the Maruts' host,
							thou art the Lord of food,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou goest with red winds: bliss hast thou in thine home. As Pusan thou
							thyself protectest worshippers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Giver of wealth art thou to him who honours thee; thou art God Savitar,
							granter of precious things.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							As Bhaga, Lord of men! thou rulest over wealth, and guardest in his
							house him who hath served thee well.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee, the people's Lord within the house, the folk press forward to
							their King most graciously inclined.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of the lovely look, all things belong to thee: ten, hundred, yea,
							a thousand are outweighed by thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, men seek thee as a Father with their prayers, win thee,
							bright-formed, to brotherhood with holy act.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art a Son to him who duly worships thee, and as a trusty Friend
							thou guardest from attack.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							A Rbhu art thou, Agni, near to be adored thou art the Sovran Lord of
							foodful spoil and wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou shinest brightly forth, thou burnest to bestow: pervading
							sacrifice, thou lendest us thine help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, God, art Aditi to him who offers gifts: thou, Hotri, Bharati, art
							strengthened by the song.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art the hundred-wintered Ila to give strength, Lord of Wealth!
							Vrtra-slayer and Sarasvati.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Agni, cherished well, art highest vital power; in thy delightful
							hue are glories visible.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art the lofty might that furthers each design: thou art wealth
							manifold, diffused on every side.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee, Agni, have the Adityas taken as their mouth; the Bright Ones have
							made thee, O Sage, to be their tongue.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							They who love offerings cling to thee at solemn rites: by thee the Gods
							devour the duly offered food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							By thee, O Agni, all the Immortal guileless Gods cat with thy mouth the
							oblation that is offered them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							By thee do mortal men give sweetness to their drink. Bright art thou
							born, the embryo of the plants of earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							With these thou art united, Agni; yea thou, God of noble birth,
							surpassest them in majesty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Which, through the power of good, here spreads abroad from thee,
							diffused through both the worlds, throughout the earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							The princely worshippers who send to those who sing thy praise, O Agni,
							guerdon graced with kine and steeds,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 1: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lead thou both these and us forward to higher bliss. With brave men in
							the assembly may we speak aloud.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 2
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH sacrifice exalt Agni who knows all life; worship him 'with
							oblation and the song of praise,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well kindled, nobly fed; heaven's Lord, Celestial Priest, who labours
							at the pole where deeds of might are done.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							At night and morning, Agni, have they called to thee, like milch-kine
							in their stalls lowing to meet their young.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As messenger of heaven thou lightest all night long the families of
							men. Thou Lord of precious boons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him have the Gods established at the region's base, doer of wondrous
							deeds, Herald of heaven and earth;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a most famous car, Agni the purely bright, like Mitra. to be
							glorified among the folk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him have they set in his own dwelling, in the vault, like the Moon
							waxing, fulgent, in the realm of air.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bird of the firmament, observant with his eyes, guard of the place as
							'twere, looking to Gods and men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he as Priest encompass all the sacrifice. men throng to him with
							offerings and with hymns of praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Raging with jaws of gold among the growing plants, like heaven with all
							the stars, he quickens earth and sky.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Such as thou art, brilliantly kindled for our weal, a liberal giver,
							send us riches in thy shine,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For our advantage, Agni, God, bring Heaven and Earth hither that they
							may taste oblation brought by man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, give us great wealth, give riches thousandfold. unclose to us,
							like doors, strength that shall bring renown.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make Heaven and Earth propitious through the power of prayer, and like
							the sky's bright sheen let mornings beam on us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Enkindled night by night at every morning's dawn, may he shine forth
							with red flame like the realm of light,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni adored in beauteous rites with lauds of men, fair guest of living
							man and King of all our folk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Song chanted by us men, O Agni, Ancient One, has swelled unto the
							deathless Gods in lofty heaven-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							A milch-cow yielding to the singer in the rites wealth manifold, in
							hundreds, even as he wills.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, may we show forth our valour with the steed or with the power of
							prayer beyond all other men;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							And over the Five Races let our glory shine high like the realm of
							light and unsurpassable.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Such, Conqueror! be to us, be worthy of our praise, thou for whom
							princes nobly born exert themselves;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose sacrifice the strong seek, Agni, when it shines for never-failing
							offspring in thine own abode.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Knower of all that lives, O Agni may we both, singers of praise and
							chiefs, be in thy keeping still.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Help us to wealth exceeding good and glorious, abundant, rich in
							children and their progeny.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The princely worshippers who send to those who sing thy praise, O Agni,
							guerdon, graced with kine and steeds,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 2: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lead thou both these and us forward to higher bliss. With brave men in
							the assembly may we speak aloud.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 3
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI is set upon the earth well kindled; he standeth in the presence of
							all beings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wise, ancient, God, the Priest and Purifier, let Agni serve the Gods
							for he is worthy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Narasamsa lighting up the chambers, bright in his majesty through
							threefold heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Steeping the gift with oil diffusing purpose, bedew the Gods at
							chiefest time of worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adored in heart, as is thy right, O Agni, serve the Gods first to-day
							before the mortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring thou the Marut host. Ye men do worship to Indra seated on the
							grass, eternal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Grass divine, increasing, rich in heroes, strewn for wealth' sake,
							well laid upon this altar,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							On this bedewed with oil sit ye, O Vasus, sit all ye Gods, ye Holy, ye
							Adityas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wide be the Doors, the Goddesses, thrown open, easy to pass, invoked,
							through adorations,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let them unfold, expansive, everlasting, that sanctify the class famed,
							rich in heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Good work for us, the glorious Night and Morning, like female weavers,
							waxen from aforetime,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yielders of rich milk, interweave in concert the long-extended thread,
							the web of worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the two heavenly Heralds, first, most wise, most fair, present
							oblation duly with the sacred verse,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Worshipping God at ordered seasons decking them at three high places at
							the centre of the earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sarasvati who perfects our devotion, Ila divine, Bharati all
							surpassing,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Three Goddesses, with power inherent, seated, protect this holy Grass,
							our flawless refuge!
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born is the pious hero swift of hearing, like gold in hue, well formed,
							and full of vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Tvastar lengthen our line and kindred, and may they reach the place
							which Gods inhabit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vanaspati shall stand anear and start us, and Agni with his arts
							prepare oblation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let the skilled heavenly Immolator forward unto the Gods the offering
							thrice anointed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Oil has been mixt: oil is his habitation. In oil he rests: oil is his
							proper province.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 3: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come as thy wont is: O thou Steer, rejoice thee; bear off the oblation
							duly consecrated.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 4
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FOR you I call theglorious refulgent Agni, the guest of men, rich in
							oblations
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom all must strive to win even as a lover, God among godly people,
							Jatavedas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bhrgus who served him in the home of waters set him of old in houses of
							the living.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Over all worlds let Agni be the Sovran, the messenger of Gods with
							rapid coursers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Among the tribes of men the Gods placed Agni as a dear Friend when they
							would dwell among them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Against the longing nights may he shine brightly, and show the offerer
							in the house his vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sweet is his growth as of one's own possessions; his look when rushing
							fain to burn is lovely.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He darts his tongue forth, like a harnessed courser who shakes his
							flowing tail, among the bushes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Since they who honour me have praised my greatness,-he gave, as 'twere,
							his hue to those who love him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Known is he by his bright delightful splendour, and waxing old renews
							his youth for ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like one athirst, he lighteth up the forests; like water down the
							chariot ways he roareth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							On his black path he shines in burning beauty, marked as it were the
							heaven that smiles through vapour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Around, consuming the broad earth, he wanders, free roaming like an ox
							without a herdsman,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni refulgent, burning up the bushes, with blackened lines, as though
							the earth he seasoned.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							I, in remembrance of thine ancient favour have sung my hymn in this our
							third assembly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Agni, give us wealth with store of heroes and mighty strength in food
							and noble offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Grtsamadas, serving in secret, through thee, O Agni, overcome
							their neighbours,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 4: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rich in good heroes and subduing foemen. That vital power give thou to
							chiefs and singers.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 5
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HERALD and teacher was he born, a guardian for our patrons' help,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Earner by rites of noble wealth. That Strong One may we grasp and
							guide;
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							In whom, Leader of sacrifice, the seven reins, far extended, meet;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who furthers, man-like, eighth in place, as Cleanser, all the work
							divine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When swift he follows this behest, bird-like he chants the holy
							prayers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He holds all knowledge in his grasp even as the felly rounds the wheel.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Together with pure mental power, pure, as Director, was he born.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Skilled in his own unchanging laws he waxes like the growing boughs.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Clothing thern in his hues, the kine of him the Leader wait on him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is he not better than the Three, the Sisters who have come to us?
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, laden with the holy oil, the Sitster [sic] by the Mother stands,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Priest delights in their approach, as corn at coming of the rain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							For his support let him perform as ministrant his priestly task;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, song of praise and sacrifice: we have bestowed, let us obtain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							That so this man well skilled, may pay worship to all the Holy Ones.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 5: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, Agni, this our sacrifice which wehave here prepared, to thee.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 6
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI, accept this flaming brand, this waiting with my prayer on thee:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hear graciously these songs of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With this hymn let us honour thee, seeker of horses, Son of Strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With this fair hymn, thou nobly born.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							As such, lover of song, with songs, wealth-lover, giver of our wealth!
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With reverence let us worship thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be thou for us a liberal Prince, giver and Lord of precious things.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drive those who hate us far away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Such as thou art, give rain from heaven, give strength which no man may
							resist:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give food exceeding plentiful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him who lauds thee, craving help, most youthful envoy! through our
							song,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most holy Herald! come thou nigh.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Between both races, Agni, Sage, well skilled thou passest to and fro,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							As envoy friendly to mankind.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Befriend us thou as knowing all. Sage, duly worship thou the Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 6: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							And seat thee on this sacred grass.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 7
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							VASU, thou most youthful God, Bharata, Agni, bring us wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Excellent, splendid, much-desired.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let no malignity prevail against us, either God's or man's.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Save us from this and enmity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							So through thy favour may we force through all our enemies a way,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As 'twere through streaming water-floods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Purifier Agni, high shinest forth, bright, adorable,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When worshipped with the sacred oil.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ours art thou, Agni, Bharata, honoured by us with barren cows,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With bullocks and with kine in calf
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wood-fed, bedewed with sacred oil, ancient, Invoker, excellent,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 7: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Son of Strength, the Wonderful.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 8
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now praise, as one who strives for strength, the harnessing of Agni's
							car,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The liberal, the most splendid One;
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who, guiding worshippers aright, withers, untouched by age, the foe:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When worshipped fair to look upon;
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who for his glory is extolled at eve and morning in our homes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose statute is inviolate;
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who shines refulgent like the Sun, with brilliance and with fiery
							flame,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Decked with imperishable sheen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him Atri, Agni, have our songs Strengthened according to his sway:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							All glories hath he made his own.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we with Agni's, Indra's help, with Soma's, yea, of all the Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 8: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Uninjured dwell together still, and conquer those who fight with us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 9
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ACCUSTOMED to the Herald's place, the Herald hath seated him, bright,
							splendid, passing mighty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose foresight keeps the Law from violation, excellent, pure-tongued,
							bringing thousands, Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Envoy art thou, protector from the foeman, strong God, thou leadest us
							to higher blessings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Refulgent, be an ever-heedful keeper, Agni, for us and for our seed
							offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we adore thee in thy loftiest birthplace, and, with our praises, in
							thy lower station.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The place whence thou issued forth I worship: to thee well kindled have
							they paid oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, best Priest, pay worship with oblation; quickly commend the gift
							to be presented;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thou art Lord of gathered wealth and treasure. of the bright song
							of praise thou art inventor.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The twofold opulence, O Wonder-Worker, of thee new-born each day never
							decreases.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enrich with food the man who lauds thee, Agni: make him the lord of
							wealth with noble offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he, benevolent with this fair aspect, best sacrificer, bring the
							Gods to bless us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 9: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sure guardian, our protector from the foemen, shine, Agni, with thine
							affluence and splendour.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 10
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							first, loudly calling, like a Father, kindled by man upon the seat of
							worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Clothed in his glory, deathless, keen of insight, must be adorned by
							all, the Strong, the Famous.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Agni the resplendent hear my calling through all my songs,
							Immortal, keen of insight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dark steeds or ruddy draw his car, or carried in sundry ways he makes
							them red of colour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							On wood supine they got the well-formed Infant: a germ in
							various-fashioned plants was Agni;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And in the night, not compassed round by darkness, he dwells exceeding
							wise, with rays of splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With oil and sacred gifts I sprinkle Agni who makes his home in front
							of all things living,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Broad, vast, through vital power o'er all expanded, conspicuous, strong
							with all the food that feeds him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I pour to him who looks in all directions: may he accept it with a
							friendly spirit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni with bridegroom's grace and lovely colour may not be touched when
							all his form is fury.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							By choice victorious, recognize thy portion: with thee for envoy may we
							speak like Manu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 10: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Obtaining wealth, I call on perfect Agni who with an eloquent tongue
							dispenses sweetness.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 11
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HEAR thou my call, O Indra; be not heedless: thine may we be for thee
							to give us treasures;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For these presented viands, seeking riches, increase thy strength like
							streams of water flowing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Floods great and many, compassed by the Dragon, thou badest swell and
							settest free, O Hero.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strengthened by songs of praise thou rentest piecemeal the Dasa, him
							who deemed himself immortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For, Hero, in the lauds wherein thou joyedst, in hymns of praise, O
							Indra, songs of Rudras,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							These streams in which is thy delight approach thee, even as the
							brilliant ones draw near to Vayu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							We who add strength to thine own splendid vigour, laying within thine
							arms the splendid thunder-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With us mayst thou, O Indra, waxen splendid, with Surya overcome the
							Dasa races.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hero, thou slewest in thy valour Ahi concealed in depths, mysterious,
							great enchanter,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dwelling enveloped deep within the waters, him who checked heaven and
							stayed the floods from flowing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, we laud thy great deeds wrought aforetime, we laud thine
							exploits later of achievement;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							We laud the bolt that in thine arms lies eager; we laud thy two Bay
							Steeds, heralds of Surya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, thy Bay Steeds showing forth their vigour have sent a loud cry
							out that droppeth fatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The earth hath spread herself in all her fulness: the cloud that was
							about to move hath rested.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Down, never ceasing, hath the rain-cloud settled: bellowing, it hath
							wandered with the Mothers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Swelling the roar in the far distant limits, they have spread wide the
							blast sent forth by Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra hath hurled down the magician Vrtra who lay beleaguering the
							mighty river.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then both the heaven and earth trembled in terror at the strong Hero's
							thunder when he bellowed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loud roared the mighty Hero's bolt of thunder, when he, the Friend of
							man, burnt up the monster,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, having drunk his fill of flowing Soma, baffled the guileful
							Danava's devices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drink thou, O Hero Indra, drink the Soma; let the joy-giving juices
							make thee joyful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							They, filling both thy flanks, shall swell thy vigour. The juice that
							satisfies hath helped Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Singers have we become with thee, O Indra: may we serve duly and
							prepare devotion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seeking thy help we meditate thy praises: may we at once enjoy thy gift
							of riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we be thine, such by thy help, O Indra, as swell thy vigour while
							they seek thy favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us, thou God, the riches that we long for, most powerful, with
							stare of noble children.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us a friend, give us an habitation; Indra, give us the company of
							Maruts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							And those whose minds accord with theirs, the Vayus, who drink the
							first libation of the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let those enjoy in whom thou art delighted. Indra, drink Soma for thy
							strength and gladness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast exalted us to heaven, Preserver, in battles, through the
							lofty hymns that praise thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Great, verily, are they, O thou Protector, who by their songs of praise
							have won the blessing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							They who strew sacred grass to be thy dwelling, helped by thee have got
							them strength, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Upon the great Trikadruka days, Hero, rejoicing thee, O Indra, drink
							the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come with Bay Steeds to drink of libation, shaking the drops from out
							thy beard, contented.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hero, assume the might wherewith thou clavest Vrtra piecemeal, the
							Danava Aurnavabha.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast disclosed the light to light the Arya: on thy left hand, O
							Indra, sank the Dasyu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we gain wealth, subduing with thy succour and with the Arya, all
							our foes, the Dasyus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our gain was that to Trta of our party thou gavest up Tvastar's son
							Visvarupa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							He cast down Arbuda what time his vigour was strengthened by libations
							poured by Trta.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra sent forth his whirling wheel like Surya, and aided by the
							Angirases rent Vala.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now let that wealthy Cow of thine, O Indra, yield in return a boon to
							him who lauds thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 11: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give to thy praisers: let not fortune fail us. Loud may we speak, with
							brave men, in the assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 12
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HE who, just born, chief God of lofty spirit by power and might became
							the Gods' protector,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Before whose breath through greatness of his valour the two worlds
							trembled, He, O men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who fixed fast and firm the earth that staggered, and set at rest
							the agitated mountains,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who measured out the air's wide middle region and gave the heaven
							support, He, men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who slew the Dragon, freed the Seven Rivers, and drove the kine forth
							from the cave of Vala,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Begat the fire between two stones, the spoiler in warriors' battle, He,
							O men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							By whom this universe was made to tremble, who chased away the humbled
							brood of demons,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, like a gambler gathering his winnings seized the foe's riches, He,
							O men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of whom, the Terrible, they ask, Where is He? or verily they say of
							him, He is not.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He sweeps away, like birds, the foe's possessions. Have faith in him,
							for He, O men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stirrer to action of the poor and lowly, of priest, of suppliant who
							sings his praises;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, fair-faced, favours him who presses Soma with stones made ready,
							He, O men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He under whose supreme control are horses, all chariots, and the
							villages, and cattle;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who gave being to the Sun and Morning, who leads the waters, He, O
							men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							To whom two armies cry in close encounter, both enemies, the stronger
							and the weaker;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom two invoke upon one chariot mounted, each for himself, He, O ye
							men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Without whose help our people never conquer; whom, battling, they
							invoke to give them succour;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He of whom all this world is but the copy, who shakes things moveless,
							He, O men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who hath smitten, ere they knew their danger, with his hurled weapon
							many grievous sinners;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who pardons not his boldness who provokes him, who slays the Dasyti,
							He, O men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who discovered in the fortieth autumn Sambara as he dwelt among the
							mountains;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who slew the Dragon putting forth his vigour, the demon lying there,
							He, men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who with seven guiding reins, the Bull, the Mighty, set free the Seven
							great Floods to flow at pleasure;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, thunder-armed, rent Rauhina in pieces when scaling heaven, He, O
							ye men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even the Heaven and Earth bow down before him, before his very breath
							the mountains tremble.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Known as the Soma-drinker, armed with thunder, who wields the bolt, He,
							O ye men, is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who aids with favour him who pours the Soma and him who brews it,
							sacrificer, singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom prayer exalts, and pouring forth of Soma, and this our gift, He, O
							ye men, Is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou verily art fierce and true who sendest strength to the man who
							brews and pours libation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 12: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may we evermore, thy friends, O Indra, speak loudly to the synod
							with our heroes.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 13
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Season was the parent, and when born therefrom it entered rapidly
							the floods wherein it grows.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thence was it full of sap, streaming with milky juice: the milk of the
							plant's stalk is chief and meet for lauds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They come trooping together bearing milk to him, and bring him
							sustenance who gives support to all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The way is common for the downward streams to flow. Thou who didst
							these things first art worthy of our lauds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							One priest announces what the institutor gives: one, altering the
							forms, zealously plies his task,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The third corrects the imperfections left by each. Thou who didst these
							things first art worthy of our lauds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dealing out food unto their people there they sit, like wealth to him
							who comes, more than the back can bear.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Greedily with his teeth he eats the master's food. Thou who didst these
							things first art worthy of our lauds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast created earth to look upon the sky: thou, slaying Ahi,
							settest free the river's paths.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee, such, a God, the Gods have quickened with their lauds, even as a
							steed with waters: meet for praise art thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou givest increase, thou dealest to us our food: thou milkest from
							the moist the dry, the rich in sweets.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou by the worshipper layest thy precious store: thou art sole Lord of
							all. Meet for our praise art thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou who hast spread abroad the streams by stablished law, and in the
							field the plants that blossom and bear seed;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou who hast made the matchless lightnings of the sky,-vast,
							compassing vast realms, meet for our praise art thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who broughtest Narmara with all his wealth, for sake of food, to slay
							him that the fiends might be destroyed,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Broughtest the face unclouded of the strengthening one, performing much
							even now, worthy art thou of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou boundest up the Dasa's hundred friends and ten, when, at one's
							hearing, thou belpest thy worshipper.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou for Dabhiti boundest Dasyus not with cords; Thou wast a mighty
							help. Worthy of lauds art thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							All banks of rivers yielded to his manly might; to him they gave, to
							him, the Strong, gave up their wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The six directions hast thou fixed, a five-fold view: thy victories
							reached afar. Worthy of lauds art thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Meet for high praise, O Hero, is thy power, that with thy single wisdom
							thou obtainest wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The life-support of conquering Jatusthira. Indra, for all thy deeds,
							worthy of lauds art thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou for Turviti heldest still the flowing floods, the river-stream for
							Vayya easily to pass
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Didst raise the outcast from the depths, and gavest fame unto the halt
							and blind. Worthy of lauds art thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prepare thyself to grant us that great bounty, O Vasu, for abundant is
							thy treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 13: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Snatch up the wonderful, O Indra, daily. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 14
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MINISTERS, bring the Soma juice for Indra, pour forth the gladdening
							liquor with the beakers.logeth ever
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To drink of this the Hero offer it to the Bull, for this he willeth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye ministers, to him who with the lightning smote, like a tree, the
							rain-withholding Vrtra-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring it to him, him who is fain to taste it, a draught of this which
							Indra here deserveth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye ministers, to him who smote Drhhikas who drove the kine forth, and
							discovered Vala,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Offer this draught, like Vita in the region: clothe him with Soma even
							as steeds with trappings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him who did Urana to death, Adhvaryus! though showing arms
							ninety-and-nine in number;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who cast down headlong Arbuda and slew him,-speed ye that Indra to our
							offered Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye ministers, to him who struck down Svasna, and did to death Vyamsa
							and greedy Susna,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Rudhikras and Namuci and Pipru,- to him, to Indra, pour ye forth
							libation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye ministers, to him who as with thunder demolished Sambara's hundred
							ancient castles;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who cast down Varcin's sons, a hundred thousand,-to him, to Indra,
							offer ye the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye ministers, to him who slew a hundred thousand, and cast them down
							upon earth's bosom;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who quelled the valiant men of Atithigva, Kutsa, and Ayu,-bring to him
							the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ministers, men, whatever thing ye long for obtain ye quickly bringing
							gifts to Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring to the Glorious One what bands have cleansed; to Indra bring, ye
							pious ones, the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do ye, O ministers, obey his order: that purified in wood, in wood
							uplift ye.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well pleased he longs for what your hands have tended: offer the
							gladdening Soma juice to Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the cow's udder teems with milk, Adhvaryus, so fill with Soma Indra,
							liberal giver.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							I know him: I am sure of this, the Holy knows that I fain would give to
							him more largely.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, ministers, the Lord of heavenly treasure and all terrestrial
							wealth that earth possesses,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him, Indra, fill with Soma as a garner is filled with barley full: be
							this your labour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prepare thyself to grant us that great booty, O Vasu, for abundant is
							thy treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 14: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gather up wondrous wealth, O Indra, daily. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 15
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, verily, will I declare the exploits, mighty and true, of him the
							True and Mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							In the Trikadrukas he drank the Soma then in its rapture Indra slew the
							Dragon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							High heaven unsupported in space he stablished: he filled the two
							worlds and the air's mid-region.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Earth he upheld, and gave it wide expansion. These things did Indra in
							the Soma's rapture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							From front, as 'twere a house, he ruled and measured; pierced with his
							bolt the fountains of the rivers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And made them flow at ease by paths far-reaching, These things did
							Indra in the Soma's rapture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Compassing those who bore away Dabhiti, in kindled fire he burnt up all
							their weapons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And made him rich with kine and cars and horses. These things did Indra
							in the Soma's rapture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mighty roaring flood he stayed from flowing, and carried those who
							swam not safely over.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							They having crossed the stream attained to riches. These things did
							Indra in the Soma's rapture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							With mighty power he made the stream flow upward, crushed with his
							thunderbolt the car of Usas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rending her slow steeds with his rapid coursers. These things did Indra
							in the Soma's rapture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Knowing the place wherein the maids were hiding, the outcast showed
							himself and stood before them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The cripple stood erect, the blind beheld them. These things did Indra
							in the Soma's rapture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praised by the Angirases he slaughtered Vala, and burst apart the
							bulwarks of the mountain.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He tore away their deftly-built defences. These things did Indra in the
							Soma's rapture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, with sleep whelming Cumuri and Dhuni, slewest the Dasyu, keptest
							safe Dabhiti.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							There the staff-bearer found the golden treasure. These things did
							Indra in the Soma's rapture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now let that wealthy Cow of thine, O Indra , yield in return a boon to
							him who lauds thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 15: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give to thy praisers: let not fortune fail us. Loud may we speak, with
							brave men, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 16
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him, your own, the best among the good, I bring eulogy, like
							oblation in the kindled fire.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							We invocate for help Indra untouched by eld, who maketh all decay,
							strengthened, for ever young.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Without whom naught exists, Indra the Lofty One; in whom alone all
							powers heroic are combined.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Soma is within him, in his frame vast strength, the thunder in his
							hand and wisdom in his head.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not by both worlds is thine own power to be surpassed, nor may thy car
							be stayed by mountains or by seas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							None cometh near, O Indra, to thy thunderbolt, when with swift steeds
							thou fliest over many a league.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For all men bring their will to him the Resolute, to him the Holy One,
							to him the Strong they cleave.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pay worship with oblation, strong and passing wise. Drink thou the
							Soma, Indra, through the mighty blaze.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The vessel of the strong flows forth, the flood of meath, unto the
							Strong who feeds upon the strong, for drink,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strong are the two Adhvaryus, strong are both the stones. They press
							the Soma that is strong for him the Strong.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong is thy thunderbolt, yea, and thy car is strong; strong are thy
							Bay Steeds and thy weapons powerful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, Bull, art Lord of the strong gladdening drink. with the
							strong Soma, Indra, satisfy thyself.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							I, bold by prayer, come near thee in thy sacred rites, thee like a
							saving ship, thee shouting in the war.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Verily he will hear and mark this word of ours: we will pour Indra
							forth as 'twere a spring of wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Turn thee unto us ere calamity come nigh, as a cow full of pasture
							turns her to her calf.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of a Hundred Powers, may we once firmly cling to thy fair favours
							even as husbands to their wives.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now let that wealthy Cow of thine, O Indra, yield in return a boon to
							him who lauds thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 16: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give to thy praisers: let not fortune fail us. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 17
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LIKE the Angirases, sing this new song forth to him, for, as in ancient
							days, his mighty powers are shown,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When in the rapture of the Soma he unclosed with strength the solid
							firm-shut stables of the kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let him be even that God who, for the earliest draught measuring out
							his power, increased his majesty;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hero who fortified his body in the wars, and through his greatness set
							the heaven upon his head.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou didst perform thy first great deed of hero might what time thou
							showedst power, through prayer, before this folk.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hurled down by thee the car-borne Lord of Tawny Steeds, the congregated
							swift ones fled in sundry ways.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He made himself by might Lord of all living things, and strong in vital
							power waxed great above them all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, borne on high, o'erspread with light the heaven and earth, and,
							sewing up the turbid darkness, closed it in.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He with his might made firm the forward-bending hills, the downward
							rushing of the waters he ordained.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fast he upheld the earth that nourisheth all life, and stayed the
							heaven from falling by his wondrous skill.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fit for the grasping of his arms is what the Sire hath fabricated from
							all kind of precious wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The thunderbolt, wherewith, loud-roaring, he smote down, and striking
							him to death laid Krivi on the earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							As she who in her parents' house is growing old, I pray to thee as
							Bhaga from the seat of all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant knowledge, mete it out and bring it to us here: give us the share
							wherewith thou makest people glad.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we invoke thee as a liberal giver thou givest us, O Indra, strength
							and labours.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Help us with manifold assistance, Indra: Migthy One, Indra, make us yet
							more wealthy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now may that weaithy Cow of thine, O Indra, give in return a boon to
							him who lauds thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 17: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give to thy praisers: let not fortune fail us. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 18
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE rich new car hath been equipped at morning; four yokes it hath,
							three whips, seven reins to guide it:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ten-sided, friendly to mankind, light-winner, that must be urged to
							speed with prayers and wishes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is prepared for him the first, the second, and the third time: he
							is man's Priest and Herald.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Others get offspring of another parent he goeth, as a noble Bull, with
							others.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Indra's car the Bay Steeds have I harnessed, that new well-spoken
							words may bring him hither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here let not other worshippers detain thee, for among us are many holy
							singers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, come hitherward with two Bay Coursers, come thou with four, with
							six when invocated.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come thou with eight, with ten, to drink the Soma. Here is the juice,
							brave Warrior: do not scorn it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, come thou hither having harnessed thy car with twenty, thirty,
							forty horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come thou with fifty well trained coursers, Indra, sixty or seventy, to
							drink the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to us hitherward, O Indra, carried by eighty, ninety, or an
							hundred horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							This Soma juice among the Sunahotras hath been poured out, in love, to
							glad thee, Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							To this my prayer, O Indra, come thou hither: bind to thy car's pole
							all thy two Bay Coursers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art to be invoked in many places Hero, rejoice thyself in this
							libation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ne'er be my love from Indra disunited still may his liberal Milch-cow
							yield us treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may we under his supreme protection, safe in his arms, succeed in
							each forth-going.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now may that wealthy Cow Of thine, O Indra, give in return a boon to
							him who lauds thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give to thy praisers: let not fortune fail us. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 19
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							DRAUGHTS of this sweet juice have been drunk for rapture, of the wise
							Soma-presser's offered dainty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherein, grown mighty in the days aforetime, Indra hath found delight,
							and men who worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Cheered by this meath Indra, whose hand wields thunder, rent piecemeal
							Ahi who barred up the waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So that the quickening currents of the rivers flowed forth like birds
							unto their resting-places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, this Mighty One, the Dragon's slayer, sent forth the flood of
							waters to the ocean.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He gave the Sun his life, he found the cattle, and with the night the
							works of days completed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him who worshippeth hath Indra given many and matchless gifts. He
							slayeth Vrtra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Straight was he to be sought with supplications by men who struggled to
							obtain the sunlight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him who poured him gifts he gave up Surya,-Indra, the God, the
							Mighty, to the mortal;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							For Etasa with worship brought him riches that keep distress afar, as
							'twere his portion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Once to the driver of his chariot, Kutsa, he gave up greedy Surya,
							plague of harvest;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Indra, for the sake of Divodasa demolished Sambara's
							nine-and-ninety castles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							So have we brought our hymn to thee, O Indra, strengthening thee and
							fain ourselves for glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we with best endeavours gain this friendship, and mayst thou bend
							the godless scorner's weapons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus the Grtsamadas for thee, O Hero, have wrought their hymn and task
							as seeking favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they who worship thee afresh, O Indra, gain food and strength,
							bliss, and a happy dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now may that wealthy Cow of thine, O Indra, give in return a boon to
							him who lauds thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give to thy praisers: let not fortune fail us. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 20
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As one brings forth his car when fain for combat, so bring we power to
							thee- regard us, Indra-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well skilled in song, thoughtful in spirit, seeking great bliss from
							one like thee amid the Heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, thou art our own with thy protection, a guardian near to men who
							love thee truly,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Active art thou, the liberal man's defender, his who draws near to thee
							with right devotion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra, called with solemn invocations. the young, the Friend, be
							men's auspicious keeper,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							One who will further with his aid the singer, the toiler, praiser,
							dresser of oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With laud and song let me extol that Indra in whom of old men prospered
							and were mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, implored, fulfil the prayer for plenty of him who worships, of
							the living mortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, Indra whom the Angirases' praise delighted, strengthened their
							prayer and made their goings prosper.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Stealing away the mornings with the sunlight, he, lauded, crushed even
							Asna's ancient powers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							He verily, the God, the glorious Indra, hath raised him up for man,
							best Wonder-Worker.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, self-reliant, mighty and triumphant, brought low the dear head of
							the wicked Dasa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra theVrtra-slayer, Fort-destroyer, scattered the Dasa hosts who
							dwelt in darkness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							For men hath he created earth and waters, and ever helped the prayer of
							him who worships.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him in might the Gods have ever yielded, to Indra in the tumult of
							thebattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							When in his arms they laid the bolt, he slaughtered the Dasyus and cast
							down their forts of iron.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now may that wealthy Cow of thine, O Indra, give in return a boon to
							him who lauds thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 20: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give to thy praisers: let not fortune fail us. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 21
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the Lord of all, the Lord of wealth, of light; him who is Lord
							for ever, Lord of men and tilth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who is Lord of horses, Lord of kine,of floods, to Indra, to the
							Holy bring sweet Soma juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the potent One, who conquers and breaks down, the Victor never
							vanquished who disposes all,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The migbty-voiced, the rider, unassailable, to Indra everconquering
							speak your reverent prayer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Still Victor, loved by mortals, ruler over men, o'erthrower, warrior,
							he hath waxen as he would;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Host-gatherer, triumphant, honoured mid the folk. Indra's heroic deeds
							will I tell forth to all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The strong who never yields, who slew the furious fiend, the deep, the
							vast, of wisdom unattainable;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who speeds the good, the breaker-down, the firm, the vast,-Indra whose
							rites bring joy hath made the light of Dawn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							By sacrifice the yearning sages sending forth their songs found
							furtherance from him who speeds the flood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							In Indra seeking help with worship and with hymn, they drew him to
							themselves and won them kine and wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, bestow on us the best of treasures, the spirit of ability and
							fortune;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 21: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Increase of riches, safety of our bodies, charm of sweet speech, and
							days of pleasant weather.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 22
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							At the Trikadrukas the Great and Strong hath drunk drink blent with
							meal. With Visnu hath he quaffed the poured out Soma juice, all that he
							would.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That hath so heightened him the Great, the Wide, to do his mighty work.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							So may the God attain the God, true Indu Indra who is true.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							So he resplendent in the battle overcame Krivi by might. He with his
							majesty hath filled the earth and heaven, and waxen strong.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							One share of the libation hath he swallowed down: one share he left.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							So may the God attend the God, true Indu Indra who is true.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brought forth together with wisdom and mighty power thou grewest great;
							with hero deeds subduing the malevolent, most swift in act;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giving prosperity, and lovely wealth to him who praiseth thee. So may
							the God attend the God, true Indu Indra who is true.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This, Indra, was thy hero deed, Dancer, thy first and ancient work,
							worthy to be told forth in heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time thou sentest down life with a God's own power, freeing the
							floods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							All that is godless may he conquer with his might, and, Lord of Hundred
							Powers, find for us strength and food.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 23
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WE call thee, Lord and Leader of the heavenly hosts, the wise among the
							wise, the famousest of all,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The King supreme of prayers, O Brahmanaspati: hear us with help; sit
							down in place of sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, God immortal! verily the Gods have gained from thee, the
							wise, a share in holy rites.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As with great light the Sun brings forth the rays of morn, so thou
							alone art Father of all sacred prayer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou hast chased away revilers and the gloom, thou mountest the
							refulgent car of sacrifice;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The awful car, Brhaspati, that quells the foe, slays demons, cleaves
							the stall of kine, and finds the light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou leadest with good guidance and preservest men; distress o'ertakes
							not him who offers gifts to thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who hates prayer thou punishest, Brhaspati, quelling his wrath:
							herein is thy great mightiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							No sorrow, no distress from any side, no foes, no creatures
							double-tongued have overcome the man,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou drivest all seductive fiends away from him whom, careful guard,
							thou keepest Brahmanaspati.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art our keeper, wise, preparer of our paths: we, for thy service,
							sing to thee with hymns of praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, whoever lays a snare for us, him may his evil fate,
							precipitate, destroy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, too, who threatens us without offence of ours, the evilminded,
							arrogant, rapacious man,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him turn thou from our path away, Brhaspati: give us fair access to
							this banquet of the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee as protector of our bodies we invoke, thee, saviour, as the
							comforter who loveth us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strike, O Brhaspati, the Gods' revilers down, and let not the
							unrighteous come to highest bliss.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through thee, kind -prosperer, O Brahmanaspati, may we obtain the
							wealth of Men which all desire:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							And all our enemies, who near or far away prevail against us, crush,
							and leave them destitute.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							With thee as our own rich and liberal ally may we, Brhaspati, gain
							highest power of life.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not the guileful wicked man be lord of us:-still may we prosper,
							singing goodly hymns of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong, never yielding, hastening to the battle-cry, consumer of the
							foe, victorious in the strife,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art sin's true avenger, Brahmanaspati, who tamest e'en the fierce,
							the wildly passionate.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso with mind ungodly seeks to do us harm, who, deeming him a man of
							might mid lords, would slay,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not his deadly blow reach us, Brhaspati; may we humiliate the
							strong ill-doer's wrath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mover mid the spoil, the winner of all wealth, to be invoked in
							fight and reverently adored,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati hath overthrown like cars of war all wicked enemies who fain
							would injure us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Burn up the demons with thy fiercest flaming brand, those who have
							scorned thee in thy manifested might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Show forth that power that shall deserve the hymn of praise: destroy
							the evil speakers, O Brhaspati.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, that which the foe deserves not which shines among the folk
							effectual, splendid,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							That, Son of Law I which is with might refulgent-that treasure
							wonderful bestow thou on us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us not up to those who, foes in ambuscade, are greedy for the
							wealth of him who sits at ease,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who cherish in their heart abandonment of Gods. Brhaspati, no further
							rest shall they obtain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Tvastar, he who knows each sacred song, brought thee to life,
							preeminent o'er all the things that be.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guilt-scourger, guilt-avenger is Brhaspati, who slays the spoiler and
							upholds the mighty Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mountain, for thy glory, cleft itself apart when, Angiras! thou
							openedst the stall of kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thoul O Brhaspati, with Indra for ally didst hurl down water-floods
							which gloom had compa-sed round.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Brahmanaspati, be thou controller of this our hymn and prosper thou
							our children.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 23: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							All that the Gods regard with love is blessed. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 24
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BE pleased with this our offering, thou who art the Lord; we will adore
							thee with this new and mighty song.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As this thy friend, our liberal patron, praises thee, do thou,
							Brhaspati, fulfil our hearts' desire.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who with might bowed down the things that should be bowed, and in
							his fury rent the holds of Sambara:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who overthrew what shook not, Brahmapaspati,-he made his way within the
							mountain stored with wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							That was a great deed for the Godliest of the Gods: strong things were
							loosened and the firmly fixed gave way.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He drave the kine forth and cleft Vala through by prayer, dispelled the
							darkness and displayed the light of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The well with mouth of stone that poured a flood of meath, which
							Brahmapaspati hath opened with his might-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							All they who see the light have drunk their fill thereat: together they
							have made the watery fount flow forth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ancient will be those creatures, whatsoe'er they be; with moons, with
							autumns, doors unclose themselves to you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Effortless they pass on to perfect this and that, appointed works which
							Brahmanaspati ordained.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who with much endeavour searching round obtained the Panis'
							noblest treasure hidden in the cave,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Those sages, having marked the falsehoods, turned them back whence they
							had come, and sought again to enter in.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The pious ones when they had seen the falsehoods turned them back, the
							sages stood again upon the lofty ways.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cast down with both their arms upon the rock they left the kindled
							fire, and said, No enemy is he.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							With his swift bow, strung truly, Brahmanaspati reaches the mark
							whate'er it be that he desires.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Excellent are the arrows wherewithal he shoots, keen-eyed to look on
							men and springing from his ear.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							He brings together and he parts, the great High Priest; extolled is he,
							in battle Brahmapaspati.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, gracious, for the hymn he brings forth food and wealth, the
							glowing Sun untroubled sends forth fervent heat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							First and preeminent, excelling all besides are the kind gifts of
							liberal Brhaspati.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							These are the boons of him the Strong who should be loved, whereby both
							classes and the people have delight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou who in every way supreme in earthly power, rejoicing, by thy
							mighty strength hast waxen great,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							He is the God spread forth in breadth against the Gods: he,
							Brahmanaspati, encompasseth this All.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							From you, twain Maghavans, all truth proceedeth: even the waters break
							not your commandment.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come to us, Brahmanaspati and Indra, to our oblation Iiie yoked steeds
							to fodder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The sacrificial flames most swiftly hear the call: the priest of the
							assembly gaineth wealth for hymns.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hating the stern, remitting at his will the debt, strong in the shock
							of fight is Brahmanaspati.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The wrath of Brahmanaspati according to his will had full effect when
							he would do a mighty deed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							The kine he drave forth and distributed to heaven, even as a copious
							flood with strength flows sundry ways.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Brahmanaspati, may we be evermore masters of wealth well-guided, full
							of vital strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Heroes on heroes send abundantly to us, when thou omnipotent through
							prayer seekest my call.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Brahmanaspati, be thou controller of this our hymn, and prosper thou
							our children.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 24: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							All that the Gods regard with love is blessed. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 25
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HE lighting up the flame shall conquer enemies: strong shall he be who
							offers prayer and brings his gift.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He with his seed spreads forth beyond another's seed, whomever
							Brahmanaspati takes for his friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With heroes he shall overcome his hero foes, and spread his wealth by
							kine wise by himself is be.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							His children and his children's children
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							grow in strength, whomever Brahmanaspati takes for his friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, mighty like a raving river's billowy flood, as a bull conquers
							oxen, overcomes with strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like Agni's blazing rush he may not be restrained, whomever
							Brahmanaspati takes for his friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For him the floods of heaven flow never failing down: first with the
							heroes he goes forth to war for kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He slays in unabated vigour with great might, whomever Brahmanaspati
							takes for his friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							All roaring rivers pour their waters down for him, and many a flawless
							shelter hath been granted him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 25: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blest with the happiness of Gods he prospers well, whomever
							Brahmanaspati takes for his friend.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 26
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE righteous singer shall o'ercome his enemies, and he who serves the
							Gods subdue the godless man.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The zealous man shall vanquish the invincible, the worshipper share the
							food of him who worships not.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worship, thou hero, chase the arrogant afar: put on auspicious courage
							for the fight with foes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Prepare oblation so that thou mayst have success. we crave the
							favouring help of Brahmanaspati.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He with his folk, his house, his family, his sons, gains booty for
							himself, and, with the heroes, wealth,believing
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who with oblation and a true heart serves Brahmanaspati the Father of
							the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso hath honoured him with offerings rich in oil, him Brahmanaspati
							leads forward on his way,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 26: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Saves him from sorrow, frees him from his enemy, and is his wonderful
							deliverer from woe.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 27
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE hymns that drop down fatness, with the ladle I ever offer to the
							Kings Adityas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Mitra, Aryanian, and Bhaga hear us, the mighty Varuna Daksa, and
							Amsa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With one accord may Aryaman and Mitra and Varuna this day accept this
							praise-song-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Adityas bright and pure as streams of water, free from all guile and
							falsehood, blameless, perfect.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Gods, Adityas, vast, profound, and faithful, with many eyes, fain
							to deceive the wicked,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Looking within behold the good and evil near to the Kings is even the
							thing most distant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Upholding that which moves and that which moves not, Adityas, Gods,
							protectors of all being,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Provident, guarding well the world of spirits, true to eternal Law, the
							debt-exactors.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May I, Adityas, share m this your favour which, Aryaman, brings profit
							e'en in danger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Under your guidance, Varuna and Mitra, round troubles may I pass, like
							rugged places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Smooth is your path, O Aryaman and Mitra; excellent is it, Varuna, and
							thornless.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thereon, Adityas, send us down your blessing: grant us a shelter hard
							to be demolished.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mother of Kings, may Aditi transport us, by fair paths Aryaman, beyond
							all hatred.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we uninjured, girt by many heroes, win Varuna's and Mitra's high
							protection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							With their support they stay three earths, three heavens; three are
							their functions in the Gods' assembly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mighty through Law, Adityas, is your greatness; fair is it, Aryaman,
							Varuna, and Mitra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Golden and splendid, pure like streams of water, they hold aloft the
							three bright heavenly regions.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ne'er do they slumber, never close their eyelids, faithful, far-ruling
							for the righteous mortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou over all, O Varuna, art Sovran, be they Gods, Asura! or be they
							mortals.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant unto us to see a hundred autumns ours be the blest long lives of
							our forefathers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Neither the right nor left do I distinguish, neither the cast nor yet
							the west, Adityas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Simple and guided by your wisdom, Vasus!
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 11: Line 3
					-
						-
							may I attain the light that brings no danger.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who bears gifts unto the Kings, true Leaders, he whom their
							everlasting blessings prosper,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Moves with his chariot first in rank and wealthy, munificent and lauded
							in assemblies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pure, faithful, very strong, with heroes round him, he dwells beside
							the waters rich with pasture.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							None slays, from near at hand or from a distance, him who is under the
							Adityas' guidance.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aditi, Mitra, Varuna, forgive us however we have erred and sinned
							against you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							May I obtain the broad light free from peril: O Indra, let not during
							darkness seize us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							For him the Twain united pour their fulness, the rain from heaven: he
							thrives most highly favoured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							He goes to war mastering both the mansions: to him both portions of the
							world are gracious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your guiles, ye Holy Ones, to quell oppressors, your snares spread out
							against the foe, Adityas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							May I car-borne pass like a skilful horseman: uninjured may we dwell in
							spacious shelter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							May1 not live, O Varuna, to witness my wealthy, liberal, dear friend's
							destitution.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 27: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							King, may1 never lack well-ordered riches. Lond may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 28
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THIS laud of the self-radiant wise Aditya shall be supreme o'er all that is
						in greatness.
					-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 2
				-
					-
						beg renown of Varuna the Mighty, the God exceeding kind to him who
						worships.
					-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Having extolled thee. Varuna, with thoughtful care may we have high
							fortune in thy service,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sinffing thy praises like the fires at coming, day after day, of
							mornings rich in cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we be in thy keeping, O thou Leader wide-ruling Varuna, Lord of
							many heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							O sons of Aditi, for ever faithful, pardon us, Gods, admit us to your
							friendship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He made them flow, the Aditya, the Sustainer: the rivers run by
							Varuna's commandment.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These feel no weariness, nor cease from flowing: swift have they flown
							like birds in air around us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loose me from sin as from a bond that binds me: may we swell, Varuna,
							thy spring of Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not my thread, while I weave song, be severed, nor my work's sum,
							before the time, be shattered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far from me, Varuna, remove all danger accept me graciously, thou Holy
							Sovran.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cast off, like cords that hold a calf, my troubles: I am not even mine
							eyelid's lord without thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strike us not, Varuna, with those dread weapons which, Asura, at thy
							bidding wound the sinner.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us not pass away from light to exile. Scatter, that we may live,
							the men who hate us
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							O mighty Varuna, now and hereafter, even as of old, will we speak forth
							our worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							For in thyself, invincible God, thy statutes ne'er to be moved are
							fixed as on a mountain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Move far from me what sins I have committed: let me not suffer, King,
							for guilt of others.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Full many a morn remains to dawn upon us: in these, O Varuna, while we
							live direct us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							O King, whoever, be he friend or kinsman, hath threatened me affrighted
							in my slumber-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							If any wolf or robber fain would harm us, therefrom, O Varuna, give
							thou us protection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							I not live O Varuna, to witness my wealthy, liberal dear friend's
							destitution.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 28: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							King, may I never lack well-ordered riches. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 29
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							UPHOLDERS of the Law, ye strong Adityas, remove my sin like her who
							bears in secret.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							You, Varuna, Mitra and all Gods who listen, I call to help me, I who
							know your goodness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, Gods, are providence and ye are power: remove ye utterly all those
							who hate us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As givers of good things deal with us kindly: this day be gracious to
							us and hereafter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What service may we do you with our future, what service, Vasus, with
							our ancient friendship?
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Aditi, and VaruVa and Mitra, Indra and Maruts, make us well and
							happy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, O ye Gods, are verily our kinsmen as such be kind to me who now
							implore you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not your car come slowly to our worship: of kinsmen such as you
							ne'er let us weary.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I singly have sinned many a sin against you, and ye chastised me as a
							sire the gambler.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far be your nets, far, Gods, be mine offences: seize me not like a bird
							upon her offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Turn yourselves hitherward this day, ye Holy, that fearing in my heart
							I may approach you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Protect us, God; let not the wolf destroy us. Save us, ye Holy, from
							the pit and falling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May I not live, O Varuna, to witness my wealthy, liberal, dear friend's
							destitution.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 29: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							King, may I never lack well-ordered riches. Loud may we speak, with
							heroes, in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 30
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE streams unceasing flow to Indra, slayer of Ahi, Savitar, God, Law's
							fulfiller,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Day after day goes on the sheen of waters. What time hath past since
							they were first set flowing?
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							His Mother-for she knew-spake and proclaimed him who was about to cast
							his bolt at Vrtra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cutting their paths according to his pleasure day after day flow to
							their goal the rivers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aloft he stood above the airy region, and against Vrtra shot his deadly
							missile.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enveloped in a cloud he rushed upon him. Indra subdued the foe with
							sharpened weapons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							As with a bolt, Brhaspati, fiercely flaming, pierce thou Vrkadvaras',
							the Asura's, heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as in time of old with might thou slewest, so slay even now our
							enemy, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Cast down from heaven on high thy bolt of thunder wherewith in joy thou
							smitest dead the foeman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							For gain of children make us thine, O Indra, of many children's
							children and of cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whomso ye love, his power ye aid and strengthen; ye Twain are the rich
							worshipper's advancers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Graciously favour us, Indra and Soma; give us firm standing in this
							time of danger.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let it not vex me, tire me, make me slothful, and never let us say,
							Press not the Soma;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							For him who cares for me, gives gifts, supports me, who comes with kine
							to me who pour libations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sarasvati, protect us: with the Maruts allied thou boldly conquerest
							our foemen,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							While Indra does to death the daring chieftain of Sandikas exulting in
							his prowess.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him who waylays, yea, him who would destroy us,-aim at him, pierce him
							with thy sharpened weapon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, with arms thou slayest foemen O King, give up the spoiler to
							destruction.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Perform, O Hero, with our valiant heroes the deeds heroic which thou
							hast to finish.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Long have they been inflated with presumption: slay them, and bring us
							hither their possessions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							I craving joy address with hymn and homage your heavenly host, the
							company of Maruts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 30: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							That we may gain wealth with full store of heroes, each day more
							famous, and with troops of children.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 31
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HELP, Varuna and Mitra, O ye Twain allied with Vasus, Rudras, and
							Adityas, help our car,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That, as the wild birds of the forest from their home, our horses may
							fly forth, glad, eager for renown.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, now ye Gods of one accord speed on our car what time among the
							folk it seeks an act of might;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, hasting through the region with the stamp of hoofs, our swift
							steeds trample on the ridges of the earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Or may our Indra here, the Friend of all mankind, coming from heaven,
							most.wise, girt by the Marut host,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accompany, with aid untroubled by a foe, our car to mighty gain, to win
							the meed of strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Or may this Tvastar, God who rules the world with power, one-minded
							with the Goddesses speed forth our car;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ila and Bhaga the celestial, Earth and Heaven, Pusan, Purandhi, and the
							Asvins, ruling Lords.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Or, seen alternate, those two blessed Goddesses, Morning and Night who
							stir all living things to act:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							While with my newest song I praise you both, O Earth, that from what
							moves not ye may spread forth threefold food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your blessing as a boon for suppliants we desire: the Dragon of the
							Deep, and Aja-Ekapad,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Trita, Rbhuksan, Savitar shall joy in us, and ihe Floods' swift Child
							in our worship and our prayer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							These earnest prayers I pray to you, ye Holy: to pay you honour, living
							men have formed them,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 31: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men fain to win the prize and glory. May they win, as a car-horse might
							the goal, your notice.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 32
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GRACIOUSLY further, O ye Heaven and Earth, this speech striving to win
							reward, of me your worshipper.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							First rank I give to you, Immortal, high extolled! I, fain to win me
							wealth, to you the migbty Pair.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let not man's guile annoy us, secret or by day: give not us up a prey
							to these calamities.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sever not thou our friendship: think thereon for us. This, with a heart
							that longs for bliss, we seek from thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring hither with benignant mind the willing Cow teeming with plenteous
							milk, full, inexhaustible.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							O thou invoked by many, day by day I urge thee with my word, a charger
							rapid in his tread.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With eulogy I call on Raka swift to hear may she, auspicious, hear us,
							and herself observe.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With never-breaking needle may she sew her work, and give a hero son
							most wealthy, meet for praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							All thy kind thoughts, O Raka, lovely in their form, wherewith thou
							grantest wealth to him who offers gifts-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With these come thou to us this day benevolent, O Blessed One,
							bestowing food of thousand sorts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							O broad-tressed Sinivali, thou who art the Sister of the Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accept the offered sacrifice, and, Goddess, grant us progeny.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							With lovely fingers, lovely arms, prolific Mother of many sons-
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Present the sacred gifts to her, to Sinlivali Queen of men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 32: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Her, Sinivali, her, Gungu, her, Raka, her, Sarasvati, Indrani to mine aid I
						call, and Vartunani for my weal.
					-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 33
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FATHER of Maruts, let thy bliss approach us: exclude us not from
							looking on the sunlight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gracious to our fleet courser be the Hero may we transplant us, Rudra,
							in our children.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With the most saving medicines which thou givest, Rudra, may I attain a
							hundred winters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far from us banish enmity and hatred, and to all quarters maladies and
							trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Chief of all born art thou in glory, Rudra, armed with the thunder,
							mightiest of the mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Transport us over trouble to well-being repel thou from us all assaults
							of mis. chief.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us not anger thee with worship, Rudra, ill praise, Strong God! or
							mingled invocation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Do thou with strengthening balms incite our heroes: I hear thee famed
							as best of all physicians.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May I with praise-songs win that Rudra's favour who is adored with
							gifts and invocations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ne'er may the tawny God, fair-checked, and gracious, swifthearing,
							yield us to this evil purpose.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Strong, begirt by Maruts, hath refreshed me, with most invigorating
							food, imploring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As he who finds a shade in fervent sunlight may I, uninjured, win the
							bliss of Rudra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where is that gracious hand of thine, O Rudra, the hand that giveth
							health and bringeth comfort,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Remover of the woe that Gods have sent us? O Strong One, look thou on
							me with compassion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the strong, great, tawny, fair-complexioned, I utter forth a
							mighty hymn of praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							We serve the brilliant God with adorations, we glorify, the splendid
							name of Rudra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							With firm limbs, multiform, the strong, the tawny adorns himself with
							bright gold decorations:
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The strength of Godhead ne'er departs from Rudra, him who is Sovran of
							this world, the mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worthy, thou carriest thy bow and arrows, worthy, thy manyhued and
							honoured necklace.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Worthy, thou cuttest here each fiend to pieces: a mightier than thou
							there is not, Rudra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praise him the chariot-borne, the young, the famous, fierce, slaying
							like a dread beast of the forest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Rudra, praised, be gracious to the singer. let thy hosts spare us and
							smite down another.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							I bend to thee as thou approachest, Rudra, even as a boy before the
							sire who greets him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							I praise thee Bounteous Giver, Lord of heroes: give medicines to us as
							thou art lauded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of your pure medicines, O potent Martits, those that are wholesomest
							and healthbestowing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Those which our father Manu hath selected, I crave from. Rudra for our
							gain and welfare.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Rudra's missile turn aside and spare us, the great wrath of the
							impetuous One avoid us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Turn, Bounteous God, thy strong bow from our princes, and be thou
							gracious to our seed and offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							O tawny Bull, thus showing forth thy nature, as neither to be wroth, O
							God, nor slay us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 33: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here, Rudra, listen to our invocation. Loud may we speak, with heroes,
							in assembly.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 34
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Maruts of resistless might who love the rain, resplendent, terrible
							like wild beasts in their strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Glowing like flames of fire, impetuous in career, blowing the wandering
							raincloud, have disclosed the kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They gleam with armlets as the heavens are decked with stars, like
							cloud-born lightnings shine the torrents of their rain.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Since the strong Rudra, O Maruts with brilliant chests, sprang into
							life for you in Prsni's radiant lap.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							They drip like horses in the racings of swift steeds; with the stream's
							rapid cars they hasten on their way.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Maruts with helms of gold, ye who make all things shake, con e with
							your spotted deer, one-minded, to our food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They have bestowed of Mitra all that live, to feed, they who for
							evermore cause their swift drops to flow;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose steeds are spotted deer, whose riches never fail, like horses in
							full speed, bound to the pole in work.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With brightly-flarning kine whose udders swell with milk, idth
							glittering lances on your unobstructed paths,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Maruts, of one mind, like swans who seek their nests, come to the
							rapturous enjoyment of the meath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To these our prayers, O Maruts, come unanimous, come ye to our
							libations like the praise of men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make it swell like a mare, in udder like a cow, and for the singer
							grace the song with plenteous strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us a steed, O Maruts migbty in the car; prevailing prayer that
							brings remembrance day by day;
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Food to your praisers, to your bard in deeds of might give winning
							wisdom, power uninjured, unsurpassed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When the bright-chested Maruts, lavish of their gifts, bind at the time
							bliss their horses to the cars,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then, as the milch-cow feeds her calf within the stalls, they pour
							forth food for all oblation-bringing men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Save us, O Maruts, Vasus, from the injurer, the mortal foe who makes us
							looked upon as wolves.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							With chariot all aflame compass him round about: O Rudras, cast away
							the foeman's deadly bolt.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well-known, ye Maruts, is that wondrous course of yours, when they
							milked Prsni's udder, close akin to her.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or when to shame the bard who lauded, Rudra's Sons, ye O infallible
							brought Trita to decay.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							We call youi such, great Maruts, following wonted ways, to the oblation
							paid to Visnu Speeder-on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							With ladles lifted up, with prayer, we seek of them preeminent,
							golden-hued, the wealth which all extol.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							They, the Dasagvas, first of all brought sacrifice: they at the break
							of mornings shall inspirit us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dawn with her purple beams uncovereth the nights, with great light
							glowing like a billowy sea of milk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Rudras have rejoiced thern in the gathered bands at seats of
							worship as in purple ornaments.
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							They with impetuous vigour sending down the rain have taken to
							themselves a bright and lovely hue.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soliciting their high protection for our help, with this our adoration
							we sing praise to them,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom, for assistance, like the five terrestrial priests. Trita hath
							brought to aid us hither on his car.
						-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may your favouring help be turned to us-ward, your kindness like a
							Iowing cow approach us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 34: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith ye bear your servant over trouble, and free your worshipper
							from scoff and scorning.
						-
			-
				Mandala 2: Hymn 35
			-
				-
					Mandala 2: Hymn 35: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 2: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 1
