						Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							These great libations to the Strong are offiered: in every birth is
							Jatavedas stablished.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stablished in every birth is Jatavedas, kindled perpetual by the
							Visvamitras.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we rest ever in the loving-kindness, in the auspicious grace of him
							the Holy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							This sacrifice of ours do thou, O Mighty, O truly Wise, bear to the
							Gods rejoicing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant us abundant food, thou priestly Herald, vouchsafe to give us
							ample wealth, O Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							As holy food, Agni, to thine'invoker give wealth in cattle, lasting,
							rich in marvels.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 1: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							To us he born a son, and spreading offspring. Agni, be this thy
							gracious will to us-ward.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 2
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him, Vaisvanara, who strengthens Holy Law, to Agni we present our
							praise like oil made pure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thoughtful insight human priests bring him anear, our Herald from
							of old, as an axe forms a car.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He made the heaven and earth resplendent by his birth: Child of two
							Mothers he was meet to be implored,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, oblation-bearer, gracious, ever-young, infallible, rich in
							radiant light, the guest of men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Within the range of their surpassinq power, by might, the Gods created
							Agni with inventive thought.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							I, eager to win strength, address him, like a steed, resplendent with
							his brilliance, with his ample light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eager to gain, we crave from him the friendly God strength confident,
							choiceworthy meet to be extolled:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Bhrgus' bounty, willing, strong with sages' lore, even Agni shining
							forth with light that comes from heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							For happiness, men, having trimmed the sacred grass, set Agni glorious
							for his strength before them here;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, with raised ladles, him bright, dear to all the Gods, perfecting
							aims of works, Rudra of solemn rites.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Around thy dwelling-place, O brightly-shining Priest, are men at
							sacrifice, whose sacred grass is trimmed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wishing to do thee service, Agni, they are there, desirous of thy
							friendship grant them store of wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He hath filled heaven and earth and the great realm of light, when at
							his birth the skilful held him in their hold.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He like a horse is led forth to the sacrifice Sage, graciously
							inclined, that he may win us strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Honour the oblation-bearer, him who knows fair rites, serve ye the
							Household Friend who knows all things that be.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He drives the chariot of the lofty ordinance: Agni most active, is the
							great High Priest of Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who are free from death, fain for him, purified three splendours
							of the mighty Agni, circling all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							To man, for his enjoyment, one of these they gave: the other two have
							passed into the sister sphere.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Man's sacrificial food hath sharpened like an axe, for brightness, him
							the Sage of men, the people's Lord,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Busied with sacred rites he mounts and he descends. He hath laid down
							his vital germ within these worlds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							He stirs with life in wombs dissimilar in kind, born as a Lion or a
							loudly-bellowing Bull:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara immortal with wide-reaching might, bestowing goods and
							wealth on him who offiers gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara, as of old, mounted the cope of heaven, heaven's ridge, well
							greeted, by those skilled in noble songs.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, as of old, producing riches for the folk, still watchful,
							traversesthe common way again.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							For new prosperity we seek to Agni, him whose course is splendid,
							gold-haired, excellently bright,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom Matarisvan stablished, dweller in the heaven, meet for high praise
							and holy, sage and true to Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							As pure and swift of course, beholder of the light, who stands in
							heaven's bright sphere a sign, who wakes at dawn,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, the head of heaven, whom none may turn aside-to him the Powerful
							with mighty prayer we seek.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							The cheerful Priest, the pure, in whom no guile is found, Friend of the
							House, praise-worthy, dear to all mankind,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 2: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fair to behold for beauty like a splendid car,- Agni the Friend of men
							we ever seek for wealth.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 3
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him who shines afar, Vaisvanara, shall bards give precious things
							that he may go on certain paths:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For Agni the Immortal serves the Deities, and therefore never breaks
							their everlasting laws.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, wondrous envoy, goes between the earth and heaven, firm seated as
							the Herald, great High Priest of men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He compassethwith rays the lofty dwelling-place, Agni, sent forward by
							the Gods, enriched with piayer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sages shall glorify Agni with earnest thoughts, ensign of sacrifice,
							who fills the synod full:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In whom the singers have stored up their holy acts to him the
							worshipper looks for joy and happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sire of sacrifice, great God of holy bards, Agni, the measure and
							the symbol of the priests,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hath entered heaven and earth that show in varied form: the Sage whom
							many love rejoiceth in his might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bright Agni with the bright car, Lord of green domains, Vaisvanara
							dweller in the floods, who finds the light,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pervading, swift and wild, encompassed round with powers, him very
							glorious have the Gods established here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, together with the Gods and Manu's folk by thought extending
							sacrifice in varied form,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Goes, car-borne, to and fro with those who crown each rite, the fleet,
							the Household Friend, who turns the curse aside.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sing, Agni, for long life to us and noble sons: teem thou with plenty,
							shine upon us store of food.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Increase the great man's strength, thou ever-vigilant: thou, longing
							for the Gods, knowest their hymns full well.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Mighty One, Lord of the people and their guest, the leader of their
							thoughts, devoted Friend of priests,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our solemn rites' announcer, Jatavedas, men with worship ever praise,
							with urgings for their weal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni the God resplendent, giver of great joy, hath on his lovely car
							compassed the lands with, might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us with pure laudations in his house approach the high laws of the
							nourisher of multitudes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							I celebrate thy glories, O Vaisvanara, wherewith thou, O farsighted
							God, has found the light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou filledst at thy birth both worlds, the earth and heaven: all this,
							O Agni, hast thou compassed of thyself.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							By his great skill the Sage alone hath brought to pass a great deed,
							mightier than Vaisvanara's wondrous acts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 3: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni sprang into being, magnifying both his Parents, Heaven and Earth,
							rich in prolific seed.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 4
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BE friendly with each kindled log of fuel, with every flash bestow the
							boon of riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring thou the Gods, O God, unto our worship: serve, well-inclined, as
							Friend thy friends, O Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni whom daily Varuna and Mitra the Gods bring thrice a day to this
							our worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Tanunapat, enrich with meath our service that dwells with holy oil,
							that offers honour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The thought that bringeth every boon proceedeth to worship first the
							Priest of the libation,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							That we may greet the Strong One with our homage. Urged, may he bring
							the Gods, best Sacrificer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							On high your way to sacrifice was made ready; the radiant flames went
							upward to the regions.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Full in the midst of heaven the Priest is seated: sirew we the sacred
							grass where Gods may rest them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Claiming in mind the seven priests' burntoblations, inciting all, they
							came in settled order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To this our sacrifice approach the many who show in hero beauty at
							assemblies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Night and Dawn, lauded, hither come together, both smiling, different
							are their forms in colour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							That Varuna and Mitra may accept us, and Indra, girt by Maruts, with
							his glories.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							I crave the grace of heaven's two chief Invokers: the seven swift
							steeds joy in their wonted manner.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							These speak of truth, praising the truth eternal, thinking on Order as
							the guards of Order.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Bharati with all her Sisters, Ila accordant with the Gods, with
							mortalls Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sarasvati with all her kindred Rivers, come to this grass, Three
							Goddesses, and seat them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well pleased with us do thou O God, O Tvastar, give ready issue to our
							procreant vigour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whence springs the hero, powerful, skilled in action, lover of Gods,
							adjuster of the press-stones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send to the Gods the oblation, Lord of Forests; and let the Immolator,
							Agni, dress it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He as the truer Priest shall offer worship, for the Gods' generations
							well he knoweth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come thou to us, O Agni, duly kindled, together with the potent Gods
							and Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 4: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							On this our grass sit Aditi, happy Mother, and let our Hail delight the
							Gods Immortal.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 5
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI who shines against the Dawns is wakened. The holy Singer who
							precedes the sages.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With far-spread lustre, kindled by the pious, the Priest hath thrown
							both gates of darkness open.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni hath waxen mighty by laudations, to be adored with hymns of those
							who praise him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Loving the varied shows of holy Order at the first flush of dawn he
							shines as envoy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Amid men's homes hath Agni been established, fulfilling with the Law,
							Friend, germ of waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Loved and adored, the height he hath ascended, the Singer, object of
							our invocations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni is Mitra when enkindled duly, Mitra as Priest, Varuna, Jatavedas;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mitra as active minister, and House-Friend, Mitra of flowing rivers and
							of mountains.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Earth's, the Bird's dear lofty place he guardeth, he guardeth in
							his might the course of Surya,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guardeth the Seven-headed in the centre, guardeth sublime the Deities
							enjoyment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The skilful God who knows all forms of knowledge made for himself a
							fair form, meet for worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							This Agni guards with care that never ceases the Sonia's skin, the
							Bird's place rich in fatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 5: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni hath entered longingly the longing shrine rich with fatness,
							giving easy access.
						-
					-
