					-
						-
							He, Agni! wins heroic might, he prospers well.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ensign of sacrifices, he, Agni, with Gods is come to us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Decked by the seven priests, to him who bringeth gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							ToAgni, the Invoking Priest, offer your best, your lofty speech,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him Ordainer-like who brings the light of songs.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let these our hymns make Agni grow, whence, meet for laud, he springs
							to life,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							To mighty strength and great possession, fair to see.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Best Sacrificer, bring the Gods, O Agni, to the pious man:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							A joyful Priest, thy splendour drive our foes afar
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							As such, O Purifier, shine on us heroic glorious might:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be nearest Friend to those who laud thee, for their weal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, wakeful, versed in sacred hymns, the holy singers kindly thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 10: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Oblation-bearer, deathless, cherisher of strength.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 11
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI is Priest, the great High Priest of sacrifice, most swift in act:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He knows the rite in constant course.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Oblation-bearer, deathless, well inclined, an eager messenger,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni comes nigh us with the thought.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ensign of sacrifice from of old, Agni well knoweth with his thought
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To prosper this man's aim and hope.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, illustrious from old time, the Son of Strength who knows all
							life,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Gods have made to their Priest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Infallible is Agni, he who goes before the tribes of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							A chariot swift and ever new.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strength of the Gods which none may harm, subduing all his enemies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni is mightiest in fame.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							By offering sacred food to him the mortal worshipper obtains.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							A home from him whose light makes pure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							From Agni, by our hymns, may we gain all things that bring happiness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Singers of him who knows all life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, in our deeds of might may we obtain all precious things:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 11: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Tle Gods are centred all in thee.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 12
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MOVED, Indra-Agni, by our hymn, come to the juice, the precious dew:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dr.ink ye thereof, impelled by song.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra-Agni, with the man who lauds you comes the wakening rite:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So drink ye both this juice assured.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through force of sacrifice I choose Indra-Agni who love the wise:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Sorna let these sate them here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni I invoke, joint-victors, bounteous, unsubdued,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Foe-slayers, best to win the spoil.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, singers skilled in melody hymn you, bringing lauds:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							I choose you for the sacred food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, ye cast down the ninety forts which DAsas held,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Together, with one mighty deed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Indra-Agni eeverent thoughts go forward from the holy task
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Along the path of sacred Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra-Agni, powers are yours, and dwellings and delightful food
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Good is your readiness to act.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, in your deeds of might ye deck heaven's lucid realms:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 12: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Famed is that hero strength of yours.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 13
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Agni, to this God of yours I sing aloud with utmost power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he come to us with the Gods, and sit, best Offerer, on the grass.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Holy, whose are earth and heaven, and succour waits upon his
							strength;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him men who bring oblations laud, and they who wish to gain, for grace.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He is the Sage who guides these men, Leader of sacred rites is he.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him your own Agni, serve ye well, who winneth and bestoweth wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may the gracious Agni grant most goodly shelter for our use;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whence in the heavens or in the floods he shall pour wealth upon our
							lands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The singers kindle him, the Priest, Agni the Lord of tribes of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Resplendent and without a peer through his own excellent designs.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Help us, thou Brahman, best of all invokers of the Gods in song.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beam, Friend of Maruts, bliss on us, O Agni, a most liberal God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, grant us treasure thousandfold with children and with nourishment,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 13: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, Agni, splendid hero strength, exalted, wasting not away.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 14
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE pleasant Priest is come into the synod, true, skilled in sacrifice,
							most wise, Ordainer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, the Son of Strength, whose car is lightning, whose hair is flame,
							hath shown on earth his lustre.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee I offer reverent speech: accept it: to thee who markest it,
							victorious, faithful!
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring, thou who knowest, those who know, and seat thee amid the sacred
							grass, for help, O Holy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Two who show their vigour, Night and Morning, by the wind's paths
							shall haste to thee O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When men adorn the Ancient with oblations, these seek, as on two
							chariot-seats, the dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee, strong Agni! Varuna and Mitra and all the Maruts sang a song
							of triumph,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time unto the people's lands thou camest, spreading them as the
							Sun of men, with lustre.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Approaching with raised hands and adoration, we have this day fulfilled
							for thee thy longing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Worship the Gods with most devoted spirit, a Priest with no unfriendly
							thought, O Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							For, Son of Strength, from thee come many succours, and powers abundant
							that a God possesses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, to us with speech that hath no falsehood grant riches, real, to
							be told in thousands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whatever, God, in sacrifice we mortals have wrought is all for thee,
							strong, wise of purpose!
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 14: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be thou the Friend of each good chariot's master. All this enjoy thou
							here, immortal Agni.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 15
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							RESPLENDENT with thy wide-extending lustre, dispel the terrors of the
							fiends who hate us
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May lofty Agni be my guide and shelter, the easily-invoked, the good
							Protector.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be thou To us, while now the morn is breaking, be thou a guardian when
							the Sun hath mounted..
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accept, as men accept a true-born infant, my laud, O Agni nobly born in
							body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bull, who beholdest men, through many mornings, among the dark ones
							shine forth red, O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lead us, good Lord, and bear us over trouble: Help us who long, Most
							Youthful God, to riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shine forth, a Bull invincible, O Agni, winning by conquest all the
							forts and treasures,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou Jatavedas who art skilled in guiding, the chief high saving
							sacrifice's Leader.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lighting Gods hither, Agni, wisest Singer, bring thou to us many and
							flawless shelters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring vigour, like a car that gathers booty: bring us, O Agni,
							beauteous.Rarth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Swell, O thou Bull and give those powers an impulse, e'en Earth and
							Heaven who yield their milk in plenty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shining, O God, with Gods in clear effulgence. Let not a mortal's evil
							will obstruct us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, as holy food to thine invoker, give wealth in cattle, lasting,
							rich in marvels.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 15: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							To us be born a son and spreading ofrspring. Agni, be this thy gracious
							will to us-ward.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 16
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS Agni is the Lord of great felicity and hero Strength;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of wealth in herds of kine; Lord of the battles with the foe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wait, Maruts, Heroes, upon him the Prosperer in whom is
							bliss-increasing wealth;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who in fights ever conquer evil-hearted men, who overcome the enemy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							As such, O Agni, deal us wealth and hero might, O Bounteous One!
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most lofty, very glorious, rich in progeny, free from disease and full
							of power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who made all that lives, who passes all in might, who orders service
							to the Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He works among the Gods, he works in hero strength, yea, also in the
							praise of men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us not up to indigence, Agni, nor want of hero sons,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nor, Son of Strength, to lack of cattle, nor to blame. Drive. thou our
							enemies away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Help us to strength, blest Agni! rich in progeny, abundant, in our
							sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 16: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Flood us with riches yet more plenteous, bringing weal, with high
							renown, most Glorious One!
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 17
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							DULY enkindled after ancient customs, bringing all treasures, he is
							balmed with unguents,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Flame-haired, oil-clad, the purifying Agni, skilled in fair rites, to
							bring the Gods for worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As thou, O Agni, skilful Jatavedas, hast sacrificed as Priest of Earth,
							of Heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So with this offering bring the Gods, and prosper this sacrifice today
							as erst for Manu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three are thy times of life, O Jatavedas, and the three mornings are
							thy births, O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With these, well-knowing, grant the Gods' kind favour, and help in stir
							aiid stress the man who worships.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni most bright and fair with song we honour, yea, the adorable, O
							Jatavedas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee, envoy, messenger, oblation-bearer, the Gods have made centre of
							life eternal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Priest before thee, yet more skilled in worship, stablished of
							old, healthgiver by his nature,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							After his custom offer, thou who knowest, and lay our sacrifice where
							Gods may taste it.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 18
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI, be kind to us when we approach thee good as a friend to friend,
							as sire and mother.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The races of mankind are great oppressors burn up malignity that
							strives against us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, burn up the unfriendly who are near us, burn thou the foeman's
							curse who pays no worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Burn, Vasu, thou who markest well, the foolish: let thine eternal
							nimble beams surround thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With fuel, Agni, and with oil, desirous, mine offering I present for
							strength and conquest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With prayer, so far as I have power, adoring-this hymn divine to gain a
							hundred treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give with thy glow, thou Son of Strength, when lauded, great vital
							power to those who toil to serve thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give richly, Agni, to the Visvamitras in rest and stir. Oft have we
							decked thy body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us, O liberal Lord, great gtore of riches, for, Agni, such art
							thou when duly kindled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou in the happy singer's home bestowest, amply with arms extended,
							things of beauty.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 19
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aow, quick, sage, infallible, all-knowing, I choose to be our Priest at
							this oblation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							In our Gods' service he, best skilled, shall worship: may he obtain us
							boons for strength and riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, to thee I lift the oil-fed ladle, bright, with an offering,
							bearing our oblation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							From the right hand, choosing the Gods' attendance, he with rich
							presents hath arranged the worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of keenest spirit is the man thou aidest give us good offspring, thou
							who givest freely.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In power of wealth most rich in men. O Agni, of thee, the Good, may we
							sing forth fair praises.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men as they worship thee the God, O Agni, have set on thee full many a
							brilliant, aspect.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							So bring Most Youthful One, the Gods' asserrigly, the Heavenly Host
							which thou to-day shalt honour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Gods anoint thee Priest at their oblation, and seat thee for thy
							task as Sacrificer,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Agni, be thou here our kind defender, and to ourselves vouchsafe the
							gift of glory.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 20
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH lauds at break of morn the priest invoketh Agni, Dawn, Dadhikras,
							and both the Asvins.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With one consent the Gods whose light is splendid, longing to taste our
							sacrifice, shall hear us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three are thy powers, O Agni, three thy stations, three are thy
							tongues, yea, many, Child of Order!
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Three bodies hast thou which the Gods delight in: with these protect
							our hymns with care unceasing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, many are the names thou bearest, immortal, God, Divine, and
							Jatavedas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And many charms of charmers, All-Inspirer! have they laid in thee, Lord
							of true attendants!
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, like Bhaga, leads the godly people, he who is true to Law and
							guards the seasons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ancient, all-knowing, he the Vrtra-slayer shall bear the singer safe
							through every trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I call on Savitar the God, on Morning, Brhaspati, and Dadhikras, and
							Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							On Varuna and Mitra, on the Asvins, Bhaga, the Vasus, Rudras and
							Adityas.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 21
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SET this our sacrifice among the Immortals: be pleased with these our
							presents, Jatavedas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Priest, O Agni, sit thee down before us, and first enjoy the drops of
							oil and fatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For thee, O Purifier, flow the drops of fatness rich in oil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							After thy wont vouchsafe to us the choicest boon that Gods may feast.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, Most Excellent! for thee the Sage are drops that drip with oil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art enkindled as the best of Seers. Help thou the sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee, O Agni, mighty and resistless, to thee stream forth the drops
							of oil and fatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With great light art thou come, O praised by poets! Accept our
							offering, O thou Sage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fatness exceeding rich, extracted from the midst,-this as our gift we
							offer thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Excellent God, the drops run down upon thy skin. Deal them to each
							among the Gods.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 22
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS is that Agni whence the longing Indra took the pressed Soma deep
							within his body.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Winner of spoils in thousands, like a courser, with praise art thou
							exalted, Jatavedas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							That light of thine in heaven and earth, O Agni, in plants, O Holy One,
							and in the waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith thou hast spread wide the air's mid-region-bright is that
							splendour, wavy, man-beholding.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, to the sea of heaven thou goest: thou hast called hither Gods
							beheld in spirit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The waters, too, come hither, those up yonder in the Sun's realm of
							light, and those beneath it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let fires that dwell in mist, combined with those that have their home
							in floods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guileless accept our sacrifice, great viands free from all disease.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, as holy food to thine invoker give wealth in cattle, lasting,
							rich in marvels.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 22: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To us be born a son and spreading offspring. Agni, be this thy gracious
							will to us-ward.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 23
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							RUBBED into life, well stablished in the dwelling, Leader of sacrifice,
							the Sage, the youthful,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here in the wasting fuel Jatavedas, eternal, hath assumed immortal
							being.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Both Bharatas, Devasravas, Devavata, have strongly rubbed to life
							effectual Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Agni, look thou forth with ample riches: be, every day, bearer of
							food to feed us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him nobly born of old the fingers ten produced, him whom his Mothers
							counted dear.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Praise Devavata's Agni, thou Devasravas, him who shall be the people's
							Lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He set thee in the earth's most lovely station, in Ila's place, in days
							of fair bright weather.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							On man, on Apaya, Agni! on the rivers Drsadvati, Sarasvati, shine
							richly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, as holy food to thine invoker give wealth in cattle, lasting,
							rich in marvels.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 23: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To us be born a son and spreading offspring Agni, be this thy gracious
							will to us-ward
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 24
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI, subdue opposing bands, and drive our enemies away.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Invincible, slay godless foes: give splendour to the worshipper.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lit with libation, Agni, thou, deathless, who callest Gods to feast,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accept our sacrifice with joy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With splendour, Agni, Son of Strength, thou who art worshipped, wakeful
							One.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seat thee on this my sacred grass.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With all thy fires, with all the Gods, Agni, exalt the songs we sing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And living men in holy rites.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grant, Agni, to the worshipper wealth rich in heroes, plenteous store,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 24: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make thou us rich with many sons.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 25
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU art the sapient Son of Dyaus, O Agni, yes and the Child of Earth,
							who knowest all things.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring the Gods specially, thou Sage, for worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni the wise bestows the might of heroes grants strengthening food,
							preparing it for nectar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou who art rich in food bring the Gods hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, infallible, lights Earth and Heaven, immortal Goddesses gracious
							to all men,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord through his strength, splendid through adorations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to the sacrifice, Agni and Indra come to the offerer's house who
							hath the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come, friendly-minded, Gods, to drink the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							In the floods' home art thou enkindled, Agni, O Jatavedas, Son of
							Strength, eternal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 25: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Exalting with thine help the gatheringplaces.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 26
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							REVERING in our heart Agni Vaisvanara, the finder of the light, whose
							promises are true,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The liberal, gladsome, car-borne God we Kusikas invoke him with
							oblation, seeking wealth with songs.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Agni, bright, Vaisvanara, we invoke for help, and Matarisvan
							worthy of the song of praise;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati for man's observance of the Gods, the Singer prompt to hear,
							the swiftly-moving guest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Age after age Vaisvanara, neighing like a horse, is kindled with the
							women by the Kusikas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni, he who wakes among Immortal Gods, grant us heroic strength
							and wealth in noble steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let them go forth, the strong, as flames of fire with might. Gathered
							for victory they have yoked their spotted deer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 26: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
