						-
							Thou hast established in her seat, O Indra, the level earth, vast,
							vigorous, unbounded.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Bull hath propped the heaven and air's mid-region. By thee sent
							onward let the floods flow hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who withheld the kine, in silence I yielded in fear before thy blow,
							O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He made paths easy to drive forth the cattle. Loud-breathing praises
							helped the Much-invoked One.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra alone filled full the earth and heaven, the Pair who meet
							together, rich in treasures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, bring thou near us from the air's mid-region strength, on thy car,
							and wholesome food, O Hero.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surya transgresses not the ordered limits set daily by the Lord of
							Tawny Coursers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							When to the goal he comes, his journey ended, his Steeds he looses:
							this is Indra's doing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men gladly in the course of night would look on the broad bright front
							of the refulgent Morning;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							And all acknowledge, when she comes in glory, the manifold and goodly
							works of Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							A mighty splendour rests upon her bosom: bearing ripe milk the Cow,
							unripe, advances.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							All sweetness is collected in the Heifer, sweetness which Indra made
							for our enjoyment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Barring the way they come. Be firm, O Indra; aid friends to sacrifice
							and him who singeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							These must be slain by thee, malignant mortals, armed with ill arts,
							our quiverbearing foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							A cry is beard from enemies most near us: against them send thy
							fiercest-flaming weapon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rend them from under, crush them and subdue them. Slay, Maghavan, and
							make the fiends our booty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Root up the race of Raksasas, O Indra rend it in front and crush it in
							the middle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							How long hast thou bebaved as one who wavers? Cast thy hot dart at him
							who hates devotion:
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							When borne by strong Steeds for our weal, O Leader, thou seatest thee
							at many noble viands.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we be winners of abundant riches. May Indra be our wealth with
							store of children.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bestow on us resplendent wealth. O Indra let us enjoy thine overflow of
							bounty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wide as a sea our longing hath expanded, fulfil it, O thou
							Treasure-Lord of treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							With kine and horses satisfy this longing with very splendid bounty
							skill extend it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seeking the light, with hymns to thee, O Indra, Kusikas have brought
							their gift, the singers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of the kine, burst the kine's stable open: cows shall be ours, and
							strength that wins the booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hero, whose might is true, thy home is heaven: to us, O Maghavan, grant
							gifts of cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call we on Maghavan, auspicious Indra, best Hero in this fight where
							spoil is gathered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 30: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Strong who listens, who gives aid in battles, who slays the Vrtras,
							wins and gathers riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 31
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WISE, teaching, following the thought of Order, the sonless gained a
							grandson from his daughter.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fain, as a sire, to see his child prolific, he sped to meet her with an
							eager spirit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Son left not his portion to the brother, he made a home to hold him
							who should gain, it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time his Parents gave the Priest his being, of the good pair one
							acted, one promoted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni was born trembling with tongue that flickered, so that the Red's
							great children should be honoured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Great is their germ, that born of them is mighty, great the Bays'
							Lord's approach through sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Conquering bands upon the Warrior waited: they recognized great light
							from out the darkness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The conscious Dawns went forth to meet his coming, and the sole Master
							of the kine was Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The sages freed them from their firmbuilt prison: the seven priests
							drove them forward with their spirit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							All holy Order's pathway they discovered he, full of knowledge, shared
							these deeds through worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Sarama had found the mountain's fissure, that vast and ancient
							place she plundered thoroughly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							In the floods' van she led them forth, light-footed: she who well knew
							came first unto their lowing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Longing for friendship came the noblest singer: the hill poured forth
							its treasure for the pious.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Hero with young followers fought and conquered, and straightway
							Angiras was singing praises,
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Peer of each noble thing, yea, all excelling, all creatures doth he
							know, he slayeth Susna.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our leader, fain for war, singing from heaven, as Friend he saved his
							lovers from dishonour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							They sate them down with spirit fain for booty, making with hymns a way
							to life eternal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							And this is still their place of frequent session, whereby they sought
							to gain the months through Order.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drawing the milk of ancient seed prolific, they joyed as they beheld
							their own possession.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Their shout of triumph heated earth and heaven. When the kine showed,
							they bade the heroes rouse them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra drove forth the kine, that Vrtra-slayer, while hymns of praise
							rose up and gifts were offered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							For him the Cow, noble and far-extending, poured pleasant juices,
							bringing oil and sweetness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							They made a mansion for their Father, deftly provided him a great and
							glorious dwelling;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							With firm support parted and stayed the Parents, and, sitting, fixed
							him there erected, mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the ample chalice had impelled him, swift waxing, vast, to
							pierce the earth and heaven,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him in whom blameless songs are all united: all powers invincible
							belong to Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							I crave thy powers, I crave thy mighty friendship: full many a team
							goes to the Vrtra-slayer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Great is the laud, we seek the Princes' favour. Be thou, O Maghavan,
							our guard and keeper.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, having found great, splendid, rich dominion, sent life and motion
							to his friends and lovers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra who shone together with the Heroes begot the song, the fire, and
							Sun and Morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vast, the House-Friend, he set the waters flowing, all-lucid, widely
							spread, that move together.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							By the wise cleansings of the meath made holy, through days, and nights
							they speed the swift streams onward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee proceed the dark, the treasure-holders, both of them sanctified
							by Surya's bounty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							The while thy ovely storming Friends, O Indra, fail to attain the
							measure of thy greatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be Lord of joyous songs, O Vrtra-slayer, Bull dear to all, who gives
							the power of living.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come unto us with thine auspicious friendship, hastening, Mighty One,
							with mighty succours.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like Angiras I honour him with worship, and renovate old song for him
							the Ancient.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Chase thou the many godless evil creatures, and give us, Maghavan,
							heaven's light to help m.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far forth are spread the purifying waters convey thou us across them
							unto safety.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Save us, our Charioteer, from harm, O Indra, soon, very soon, make us
							win spoil of cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							His kine their Lord hath shown, e'en Vrtra's slayer, through the black
							hosts he passed with red attendants.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Teaching us pleasant things by holy Order, to, us hath he thrown open
							all his portals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call we on Maghavan, auspicious Indra, best Hero in this fight where
							spoil is gathered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 31: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Strong who listens, who gives aid in battles, who slays the Vrtras,
							wins and gathers riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 32
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							DRINK thou this Soma, Indra, Lord of Soma; drink thou the draught of
							noonday which thou Iovest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Puffing thy cheeks, impetuous, liberal Giver, here loose thy two Bay
							Horses and rejoice thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Quaff it pure, meal-blent, mixt with milk, O Indra; we have poured
							forth the Soma for thy rapture.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Knit with the prayer-fulfilling band of Maruts, yea, with the Rudras,
							drink till thou art sated;
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those who gave increase to thy strength and vigour; the Maruts singing
							forth thy might, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink thou, O fair of cheek, whose hand wields thunder, with Rudras
							banded, at our noon libation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They, even the Maruts who were there, excited with song the
							meath-created strength of Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							By them impelled to act he reached the vitals Of Vrtra, though he
							deemed that none might wound him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pleased, like a man, with our libation, Indra, drink, for enduring hero
							might, the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of Bays, moved by sacrifice come hither: thou with the Swift Ones
							stirrest floods and waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou didst loose the streams to run like racers in the swift
							contest, having smitten Vrtra
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							With flying weapon where he lay, O Indra, and, godless, kept the
							Goddesses encompassed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							With reverence let us worship mighty Indra, great and sublime, eternal,
							everyouthful,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose greatness the dear world-halves have not measured, no, nor
							conceived the might of him the Holy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Many are Indra's nobly wrought achievements, and none of all the Gods
							transgress his statutes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He beareth up this earth and heaven, and, doer of marvels, he begot the
							Sun and Morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Herein, O Guileless One, is thy true greatness, that soon as born thou
							drankest up the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Days may not check the power of thee the Mighty, nor the nights, Indra,
							nor the months, nor autumns.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							As soon as thou wast born in highest heaven thou drankest Soma to
							delight thee, Indra;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							And when thou hadst pervaded earth and heaven thou wast the first
							supporter of the singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, puissant God, more mighty, slewest. Ahi showing his strength when
							couched around the waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The heaven itself attained not to thy greatness when with one hip of
							thine the earth was shadowed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sacrifice, Indra, made thee wax so mighty, the dear oblation with the
							flowing Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Worshipful, with worship help our worship, for worship helped thy
							bolt when slaying Ahi.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							With sacrifice and wish have I brought Indra; still for new blessings
							may I turn him hither,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him magnified by ancient songs and praises, by lauds of later time and
							days yet recent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							I have brought forth a song when longing seized me: ere the decisive
							day will I laud Indra;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then may lie safely bear us over trouble, as in a ship, when both sides
							invocate him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Full is his chalice: Glory! Like a pourer I have filled up the vessel
							for his drinking.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Presented on the right, dear Soma juices have brought us Indra, to
							rejoice him, hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not the deep-flowing flood, O Much-invoked One! not hills that compass
							thee about restrain thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Since here incited, for thy friends, O Indra, thou breakest e'en the
							firm built stall of cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call we on Maghavan, auspicious Indra, best Hero in this fight where
							spoil is gathered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 32: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Strong who listens, who gives aid in battles, who slays the Vrtras,
							wins and gathers riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 33
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FORTH from the bosom of the mountains, eager as two swift mares with
							loosened rein contending,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like two bright mother cows who lick their youngling, Vipas and Sutudri
							speed down their waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Impelled by Indra whom ye pray to urge you, ye move as 'twere on
							chariots to the ocean.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Flowing together, swelling with your billows, O lucid Streams, each of
							you seeks the other.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							I have attained the most maternal River, we have approached Vipas, the
							broad, the blessed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Licking as 'twere their calf the pair of Mothers flow onward to their
							common home together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							We two who rise and swell with billowy waters move forward to the home
							which Gods have made us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our flood may not be stayed when urged to motion. What would the
							singer, calling to the Rivers?
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Linger a little at my friendly bidding rest, Holy Ones, a moment in
							your journey.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With hymn sublime soliciting your favour Kusika's son hath called unto
							the River.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra who wields the thunder dug our channels: he smote down Vrtra, him
							who stayed our currents.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savitar, God, the lovely-handed, led us, and at his sending forth we
							flow expanded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							That hero deed of Indra must be lauded for ever that he rent Ahi in
							pieces.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He smote away the obstructors with his thunder, and eager for their
							course forth flowed the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Never forget this word of thine, O singer, which future generations
							shall reecho.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							In hymns, O bard, show us thy loving kindness. Humble us not mid men.
							To thee be honour!
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							List quickly, Sisters, to the bard who cometh to you from far away with
							car and wagon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bow lowly down; be easy to be traversed stay, Rivers, with your floods
							below our axles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, we will listen to thy words, O singer. With wain and car from far
							away thou comest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Low, like a nursing mother, will I bend me, and yield me as a maiden to
							her lover.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soon as the Bharatas have fared across thee, the warrior band, urged on
							and sped by Indra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then let your streams flow on in rapid motion. I crave your favour who
							deserve our worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							The warrior host, the Bharatas, fared over the singer won the favour of
							the Rivers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Swell with your billows, hasting, pouring riches. Fill full your
							channels, and roll swiftly onward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							So let your wave bear up the pins, and ye, O Waters, spare the thongs;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 33: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							And never may the pair of Bulls, harmless and sinless, waste away.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 34
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FORT-RENDER, Lord of Wealth, dispelling foemen, Indra with lightnings
							hath o'ercome the Dasa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Impelled by prayer and waxen great in body, he hath filled earth and
							heaven, the Bounteous Giver.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I stimulate thy zeal, the Strong, the Hero decking my song of praise
							forth; Immortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra, thou art equally the Leader of heavenly hosts and human
							generations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Leading, his band Indra encompassed Vrtra; weak grew the wily leader of
							enchanters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who burns fierce in forests slaughtered Vyamsa, and made the
							Milch-kine of the nights apparent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, light-winner, days' Creator, conquered, victorious, hostile
							bands with those who loved him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For man the days' bright ensign he illumined, and found the light for
							his joy and gladness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forward to fiercely falling blows pressed Indra, herolike doing many
							hero exploits.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These holy songs he taught the bard who gaised him, and widely spread
							these Dawns' resplendent colour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							They laud the mighty acts of him the Mighty, the many glorious deeds
							performed by Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He in his strength, with all-surpassing prowess, through wondrous arts
							crushed the malignant Dasyus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of the brave, Indra who rules the people gave freedom to the Gods
							by might and battle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wise singers glorify with chanted praises these his achievements in
							Vivasvan's dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Excellent, Conqueror, the victory-giver, the winner of the light and
							Godlike Waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who hath won this broad earth and this heaven, -in Indra they
							rejoice who love devotions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							He gained possession of the Sun and Horses, Indra obtained the Cow who
							feedeth many.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Treasure of gold he won; he smote the Dasyus, and gave protection to
							the Aryan colour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							He took the plants and days for his possession; he gained the forest
							trees and air's mid-region.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vala he cleft, and chased away opponents: thus was he tamer of the
							overweening.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call we on Maghavan, auspicious Indra, best Hero in the fight where
							spoil is gathered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 34: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Strong, who listens, who gives aid in battles, who slays the
							Vrtras, wins and gathers treasures.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 35
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MOUNT the Bay Horses to thy chariot harnessed, and come to us like Vayu
							with his coursers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, hastening to us, shalt drink the Soma. Hail, Indra. We have
							poured it for thy rapture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For him, the God who is invoked by many, the two swift Bay Steeds to
							the pole I harness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That they in fleet course may bring Indra hither, e'en to this
							sacrifice arranged completely.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring the strong Steeds who drink the warm libation, and, Bull of
							Godlike nature, be thou gracious.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let thy Steeds eat; set free thy Tawny Horses, and roasted grain like
							this consume thou daily.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those who are yoked by prayer I harness, fleet friendly Bays who take
							their joy together.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mounting thy firm and easy car, O Indra, wise and all-knowing come thou
							to the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							No other worshippers must stay beside them thy Bays, thy vigorous and
							smooth-backed Coursers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pass by them all and hasten onward hither: with Soma pressed we will
							prepare to feast thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine is this Sorna: hasten to approach it. Drink thou thereof,
							benevolent, and cease not.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sit on the sacred grass at this our worship, and take these drops into
							thy belly, Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The grass is strewn for thee, pressed is the Soma; the grain is ready
							for thy Bays to feed on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							To thee who lovest them, the very mighty, strong, girt by Maruts, are
							these gifts presented.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							This the sweet draught, with cows, the men, the mountains, the waters,
							Indra, have for thee made ready.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come, drink thereof, Sublime One, friendly-minded, foreseeing, knowing
							well the ways thou goest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Maruts, they with whom thou sharedst Soma, Indra, who made thee
							strong and were thine army,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							With these accordant, eagerly desirous drink thou this Soma with the
							tongue of Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drink, Indra, of the juice by thine own nature, or by the tongue of
							Agni, O thou Holy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accept the sacrificial gift, O Sakra, from the Adhvaryu's hand or from
							the Hotar's.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call we on Maghavan, auspicious Indra, best Hero in the fight where
							spoil is gathered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 35: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Strong, who listens, who.gives aid in battles, who slays the
							Vrtras, wins and gathers riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 36
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH constant succours, fain thyself to share it, make this oblation
							which we bring effective.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grown great through strengthening gifts at each libation, he hath
							become renowned by mighty exploits.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Indra were the Somas erst- discovered, whereby he grew
							strong-jointed, vast, and skilful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra , take quickly these presented juices: drink of the strong, that
							which the strong have shaken.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drink and wax great. Thine are the juices, Indra, both Somas of old
							time and these we bring thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as thou drankest, Indra, earlier Somas, so drink to-day, a new
							guest, meet for praises.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Great and impetuous, mighty-voiced in battle, surpassing power is his,
							and strength resistless.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him the broad earth hath never comprehended when Somas cheered the Lord
							of Tawny Coursers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mighty and strong he waxed for hero exploit: the Bull was furnished a
							Sage's wisdom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra is our kind Lord; his steers have vigour; his cows are many with
							abundant offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							As floods according to their stream flow onward, so to the sea, as
							borne on cars, the waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vaster is Indra even than his dwelling, what time the stalk milked out,
							the Soma, fills him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eager to mingle with the sea, the rivers carry the well-pressed Soma
							juice to Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They drain the stalk out with their arms, quick-banded, and cleanse it
							with a stream of mead and filters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like lakes appear his flanks filled full with Soma: yea, he contains
							libations in abundance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
