					-
						-
							Here, fair of cheek! let thy Bay Coursers place thee: drink of this
							lovely welleffused libation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 50: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With milk they made Indra their good Preserver, lauding for help and
							rule the bounteous rainer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Impetuous God, when thou hast drunk the Soma, enraptured send us cattle
							in abundance.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 50: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With kine and horses satisfy this longing with very splendid bounty
							still extend it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seeking the light, with hymns to thee, O Indra, the Kusikas have
							brought their gift, the singers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 50: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call we on Maghavan, auspicious Indra, best Hero in the fight where
							spoil is gathered;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Strong, who listens, who gives aid in battles, who slays the
							Vrtras, wins and gathers riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 51
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HIGH hymns have sounded forth the praise of Maghavan, supporter of
							mankind, of Indra meet for lauds;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who hath waxen great, invoked with beauteous songs, Immortal One,
							whose praise each day is sung aloud.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Indra from all sides go forth my songs of praise, the Lord of
							Hundred Powers, strong, Hero, like the sea,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Swift, winner of the booty, breaker-down of forts, faithful and
							ever-glorious, finder of the light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where battle's spoil is piled the singer winneth praise, for Indra
							taketh care of matchless worshippers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He in Vivasvan's dwelling findeth his delight: praise thou the
							ever-conquering slayer of the foe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee, valorous, most heroic of the heroes, shall the priests glorify
							with songg and praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Full of all wondrous power he goes to conquest: worship is his, sole
							Lord from days aforetime.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Abundant are the gifts he gives to mortals: for him the earth bears a
							rich store of treasures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The heavens, the growing plants, the living waters, the forest trees
							preserve their wealth for Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee, O Indra, Lord of Bays, for ever are offered prayers and songs:
							accept them gladly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As Kinsman think thou of some fresh assistance; good Friend, give
							strength and life to those who praise thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here, Indra, drink thou Soma with the Maruts, as thou didst drink the
							juice beside Saryata.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Under thy guidance, in thy keeping, Hero, the singers serve, skilled in
							fair sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							So eagerly desirous drink the Soma, our juice, O Indra, with thy
							friends the Maruts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Since at thy birth all Deities adorned thee for the great fight, O thou
							invoked of many.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							He was your comrade in your zeal, O Maruts: they, rich in noble gifts,
							rejoiced in Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							With them together let the Vrtra-slayer drink in his home the
							worshipper's libation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, Lord of affluent gifts, this juice hath been pressed for thee with
							strength
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink of it, thou who lovest song.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Incline thy body to this juice which suits thy Godlike nature well:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							May it cheer thee who lovest it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brave Indra, let it work through both thy flanks, and through thy head
							by prayer,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 51: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							And through thine arms, to prosper us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 52
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							INDRA, accept at break of day our Soma mixt with roasted corn,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With groats with cake, with eulogies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Accept, O Indra, and enjoy the well-dressed sacrificial cake: Oblations are
						poured forth to thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Consume our sacrificial cake, accept the songs of praise we sing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As he who woes accepts his bride.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Famed from of old, accept the cake at our libation poured at dawn,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Forgreat, O Indra, is thy power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let roasted corn of our midday libation, and sacrificial cake here
							please thee, Indra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time the lauding singer, keen of purpose and eager as a bull, with
							hymns implores thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							At the third sacrifice, O thou whom many praise, give glory to the
							roasted corn and holy cake.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							With offered viands and with songs may we assist thee, Sage, whom Vaja
							and the Rbhus wait upon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The groats have we prepared for thee with Pusan, corn for thee, Lord of
							Bay Steeds, with thy horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eat thou the meal-cake, banded with the Maruts, wise Hero,
							Vrtra-slayer, drink the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring forth the roasted corn to meet him quickly, cake for the bravest
							Hero mid the heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 52: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, may hymns accordant with thee daily strengthen thee, Bold One,
							for the draught of Soma.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 53
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ON a high car, O Parvata and Indra, bring pleasant viands, with brave
							heroes, hither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enjoy the gifts, Gods, at our sacrifices wax strong by hymns, rejoice
							in our oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stay still, O Maghavan, advance no farther. a draught of well-pressed
							Soma will I give thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With sweetest song I grasp, O Mighty Indra, thy garment's hem as a
							child grasps his father's.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adhvaryu, sing we both; sing thou in answer: make we a laud acceptable
							to Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Upon this sacrificer's grass he seated: to Indra shall our eulogy be
							uttered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							A wife, O Maghavan is home and dwelling: so let thy Bay Steeds yoked
							convey thee hither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whenever we press out for thee the Soma, let Agni as our Herald speed
							to call thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Depart, O Maghavan;again come hither: both there and here thy goat is
							Indra, Brother,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where thy tall chariot hath a place to rest in, and where thqu loosest
							thy loud-neighing Courser.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast drunk Soma, Indra, turn thee homeward; thy joy is in thy
							home, thy racious Consort;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where thy tall chariot hath a place to rest in, and thy strong Courser
							is set free with guerdon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bounteous are these, Angirases, Virupas: the Asura's Heroes and the
							Sons of Heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They, giving store of wealth to Visvamitra, prolong his life through
							countless Soma-pressings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Maghavan weareth every shape at pleasure, effecting magic changes in
							his body,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Holy One, drinker out of season, coming thrice, in a moment, through
							fit prayers, from heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mighty sage, God-born and God-incited, who looks on men, restrained
							the billowy river.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Visvamitra was Sudas's escort, then Indra through the Kusikas grew
							friendly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like swans, prepare a song of praise with pressing-stones, glad in your
							hymns with juice poured forth in sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye singers, with the Gods, sages who look on men, ye Kutikas drink up
							the Soma's savoury meath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come forward, Kusikas, and be attentive; let loose Sudas's horse to win
							him riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							East, west, and north, let the King slay the foeman, then at earth's
							choicest place perform his worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Praises to Indra have I sung, sustainer of this earth and heaven. This
						prayer of Visvamitra keeps secure the race of Bharatas.
					-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Visvamitras have sung forth this prayer to Indra Thunder-aimed:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							So let him make us prosperous.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Among the Kikatas what do thy cattle? They pour no milky draught, they
							heat no caldron.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring thou to us the wealth of Pramaganda;give up to us, O Maghavan,
							the low-born.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sasarpari, the gift of Jamadagnis, hath lowed with mighty voice
							dispelling famine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Daughter of the Sun hath spread our glory among the Gods,
							imperishable, deathless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sasarpari brought glory speedily to these, over the generations of the
							Fivefold Race;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Daughter of Paksa, she bestows new vital power, she whom the ancient
							Jamadagnis gave to me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong be the pair of oxen, firm the axles, let not the pole slip nor
							the yoke be broken.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Indra, keep the yoke-pins from decaying: attend us, thou whose
							fellies are uninjured.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, give our bodies strength, strength to the bulls who draw the
							wains,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strength to our seed and progeny that they may live, for thou art he
							who giveth strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Enclose thee in the heart of Khayar timber, in the car wrought of
							Sinsapa put firmness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Show thyself strong, O Axle, fixed and strengthened: throw us not from
							the car whereon we travel.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let not this sovran of the wood leave us forlorn or injure us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Safe may we be until we reach our homes and rest us and unyoke.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							With various aids this day come to us, Indra, with best aids speed us,
							Maghavan, thou Hero.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him who hatcth us fall headlong downward: him whom we hate let
							vital breath abandon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							He heats his very axe, and then cuts a mere Semal blossom off.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra, like a caldron cracked and seething, so he pours out foam.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men notice not the arrow, O ye people; they bring the red beast deeming
							it a bullock.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							A sluggish steed men run not with the courser, nor ever lead an ass
							before a charger.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							These men, the sons of Bharata, O Indra, regard not severance or close
							connexion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 53: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							They urge their own steed as it were another's, and take him, swift as
							the bow's string, to battle.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 54
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him adorable, mighty, meet for synods, this strengthening hymn,
							unceasing, have they offered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni hear us with his homely splendours, hear us, Eternal One, with
							heavenly lustre.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To mighty Heaven and Earth I sing forth loudly: my wish goes out
							desirous and well knowing
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Both, at whose laud in synods, showing favour, the Gods rejoice them
							with the living mortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Heaven and Earth, may your great law he faithful: he ye our leaders
							for our high advantage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Heaven and Earth I offer this my homage, with food, O Agni, as I
							pray for riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, holy Heaven and Earth, the ancient sages whose word was ever true
							had power to find you;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And brave men in the fightwhere heroes conquer, O Earth, have known you
							well and paid you honour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							What pathway leadeth to the Gods? Who knoweth this of a truth, and who
							will now declare it?
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seen are their lowest dwelling-places only, but they are in remote and
							secret regions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sage who looketh on mankind hath viewed them bedewed, rejoicing in
							the seat of Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							They make a home as for a bird, though parted, with one same will
							finding themselves together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Partners though parted, with far-distant limits, on one firm place both
							stand for ever watchful,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, being young for evermore, as sisters, speak to each other names
							that are united.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							All living things they part and keep asunder; though bearing up the
							mighty Gods they reel not.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							One All is Lord of what is fixed and moving, that walks, that flies,
							this multiform creation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Afar the Ancient from of old I ponder, our kinship with our mighty Sire
							and Father,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Singing the praise whereof the Gods by custom stand on the spacious
							far-extended pathway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							This laud, O Heaven and Earth, to you I utter: let the kind-hearted
							hear, whose tongue is Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Young, Sovran Rulers, Varuna and Mitra, the wise and very glorious
							Adityas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The fair-tongued Savitar, the golden-handed, comes thrice from heaven
							as Lord in our assembly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bear to the Gods this song of praise, and send us, then, Savitar,
							complete and perfect safety.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Deft worker, skiful-handed, helpful, holy, may Tvastar, God, give us
							these things to aid us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Take your delight, Ye Rbhus joined with Pusan: ye have prepared the
							rite with stones adjusted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Borne on their flashing car, the spear-armed Maruts, the nimble Youths
							of Heaven, the Sons of Order,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Holy, and Sarasvati, shall hear us: ye Mighty, give us wealth with
							noble offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Visnu rich in marvels, songs And praises shall go as singers on the
							road of Bhaga,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Chieftain of the Mighty Stride, whose Mothers, the many young
							Dames, never disregard him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, who rules through all his powers heroic, hath with his majesty
							filled earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of brave hosts, Fort-crusher, Vrtra-slayer, gather thou up and
							bring us store of cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							My Sires are the Nasatyas, kind tokinsmen: the Asvins' kinship is a
							glorious title.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							For ye are they who give us store of riches: ye guard your gift
							uncheated by the bounteous.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is, ye Wise, your great and glorious title, that all ye Deities
							abide in Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Friend, Much-invoked! art thou with thy dear Rbhus: fashion ye this our
							hymn for our advantage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aryaman, Aditi deserve our worship: the laws of Varuna remain unbroken.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							The lot of childlessness remove ye from us, and let our course be rich
							in kine and offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Gods' envoy, sent to many a quarter, proclaim us sinless for
							our perfect safety.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Earth and Heaven, the Sun, the waters, hear us, and the wide
							firmament and constellations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear us the mouatains which distil the rain-drops, and, resting firm,
							rejoice in freshening moisture.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Aditi with the Adityas hear us, and Maruts grant us their
							auspicious shelter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soft be our path for ever, well-provisioned: with pleasant meath, O
							Gods, the herbs besprinkle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Safe be my bliss, O Agni, in thy friendship: may I attain the seat of
							foodful. riches,
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Enjoy the offering: beam thou strength upon us; combine thou for our
							good all kinds of glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 54: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Conquer in battle, Agni, all those foemen, and light us every day with
							loving kindness.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 55
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AT the first shining of the earliest Mornings, in the Cow's home was
							born the Great Eternal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now shall the statutes of the Gods be valid. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion -
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let not the Gods here injure us, O Agni, nor Fathers of old time who
							know the region,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nor the sign set between two ancient dwellings. Great is the Gods'
							supreme and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							My wishes fly abroad to many places: I glance back to the ancient
							sacrifices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us declare the truth when fire is kindled. Great is the Gods'
							supreme and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							King Universal, born to sundry quarters, extended through the wood be
							lies on couches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							One Mother rests: another feeds the Infant. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lodged in old plants, he grows again in younger, swiftly within the
							newly-born and tender.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Though they are unimpregned, he makes them fruitful. Great is the Gods'
							supreme and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now lying far away, Child of two Mothers, he wanders unrestrained, the
							single youngling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							These are the laws of Varuna and Mitra. Great is the Gods' supreme and
							sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Child of two Mothers, Priest, sole Lord in synods, he still precedes
							while resting as foundation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They who speak sweetly bring him sweet addresses. Great is the Gods'
							supreme and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							As to a friendly warrior when he battles, each thing that comes anear
							is seen to meet him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The hymn commingles with the cow's oblation. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Deep within these the hoary envoy pierceth; mighty, he goeth to the
							realm of splendour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							And looketh on us, clad in wondrous beauty. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Visnu, the guardian, keeps the loftiest station, upholding dear,
							immortal dwelling-places.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni knows well all these created beings. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, variant Pair, have made yourselves twin beauties: one of the Twain
							is dark, bright shines the other;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							And yet these two, the dark, the red, are Sisters. Great is the Gods'
							supreme and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where the two Cows, the Mother and the Daughter, meet and give suck
							yielding their lordly nectar,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							I praise them at the seat of law eternal. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loud hath she lowed, licking the other's youngling. On what world hath
							the Milch-cow laid her udder?
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							This Ila streameth with the milk of Order. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Earth weareth beauties manifold: uplifted, licking her Calf of eighteen
							months, she standeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well-skilled I seek the seat of law eternal. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Within a wondrous place the Twain are treasured: the one is manifest,
							the other hidden.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							One common pathway leads in two directions. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the milch-kine that have no calves storm downward, yielding rich
							nectar, streaming, unexhausted,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							These who are ever new and fresh and youthful. Great is the Gods'
							supreme and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the Bull bellows in other regions, another herd receives the
							genial moisture;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							For he is Bhaga, King, the earth's Protector. Great is the Gods'
							supreme and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us declare the Hero's wealth in horses, O all ye folk: of this the
							Gods have knowledge.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sixfold they bear him, or by fives are harnessed. Great is the Gods'
							supreme and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tvastar the God, the omniform. Creator, begets and feeds mankind in
							various manner.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							His, verily, arc all these living creatures. Great is the Gods' supreme
							dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							The two great meeting Bowls hath he united: each of the Pair is laden
							with histreasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Hero is renowned for gathering riches. Great is the Gods' supreme
							and sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, and on this our earth the All-Sustainer dwells like a King with
							noble friends about him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							In his protection heroes rest in safety. Great is the Cods' supreme and
							sole dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rich in their gifts for thee are herbs and waters, and earth brings all
							her wealth for thee, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 55: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we as friends of thine share goodly treasures. Great is the Gods'
							supreme and sole dominion.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 56
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							NOT men of magic skill, not men of wisdom impair the Gods' first
							steadfast ordinances.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ne'er may the earth and heaven which know not malice, nor the fixed
							hills, be bowed by sage devices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							One, moving not away, supports six burthens: the Cows proceed to him
							the true, the Highest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Near stand three Mighty Ones who travel swiftly: two are concealed from
							sight, one is apparent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Bull who wears all shapes, the triple-breasted, three-uddered, with
							a brood in many places,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ruleth majestic with his triple aspect, the Bull, the Everlasting Ones'
							impregner.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							When nigh them, as their tracer he observed them: he called aloud the
							dear name of Adityas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Goddesses, the Waters, stayed to meet him: they who were wandering
							separate enclosed him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Streams! the wise Gods have thrice three habitations. Child of three
							Mothers, he is Lord in synods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Three are the holy Ladies of the Waters, thrice here from heaven
							supreme in our assembly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do thou, O Savitar, from heaven thrice hither, three times a day, send
							down thy blessings daily.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Send us, O Bhaga, triple wealth and treasure; cause the two worlds to
							prosper us, Preserver!
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Savitar thrice from heaven pours down abundance, and the fair-handed
							Kings Varuna, Mitra;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And spacious Heaven and Earth, yea, and the Waters, solicit wealth that
							Savitar may send us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three are the bright realms, best, beyond attainment, and three, the
							Asura's Heroes, rule as Sovrans,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 56: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Holy and vigorous, never to be injured. Thrice may the Gods from heaven
							attend our synod.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 57
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MY thought with fine discernment hath discovered the Cow who wanders
							free without a herdsman,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Her who hath straightway poured me food in plenty: Indra and Agni
							therefore are her praisers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Pusan, deft of hand and mighty, well-pleased have drained the
							heaven's exhaustless udder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As in this praise the Gods have all delighted, may I win blessing here
							from you, O Vasus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fain to lend vigour to the Bull, the siste.. with reverence recognize
							the germ within him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Cows come lowing hither to the Youngling, to him endued with great
							and wondrous beauties.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fixing with thought, at sacrifice, the press-stones, I bid the
							well-formed Heaven and Earth come hither;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For these thy flames, which give men boons in plenty, rise up on high,
							the beautiful, the holy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, thy meath-sweet tongue that tastes fair viands, which among Gods
							is called the far-extended,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therewith make all the Holy Odes be seated here for our help, and feed
							them with sweet juices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let thy stream give us drink, O God, O Agni, wonderful and exhaustless
							like the rain-clouds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thus care for us, O Vasu Jatavedas, show us thy loving-kindness,
							reaching all men.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 58
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Ancient's Milch-cow yields the things we long for: the Son of
							Daksina travels between them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							She with the splendid chariot brings refulgence. The praise of Usas
							hath awoke the Asvins.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They bear you hither by well-orderd statute: our sacred offerings rise
							as if to parents.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Destroy in us the counsel of the niggard come hitherward, for we have
							shown you favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With lightly-rolling car and well-yoked horses hear this, the
							press-stone's song, ye Wonder-Workers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have not the sages of old time, ye Asvins, called you most prompt to
							come and stay misfortune?
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Remember us, and come to us, for ever men, as their wont is, invocate
							the Asvins.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Friends as it were have offered you these juices, sweet, blent with
							milk at the first break of morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even through many regions, O ye Asvins high praise is yours among
							mankind, ye Mighty-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come, helpers, on the paths which Gods have travelled: here your
							libations of sweet meath are ready.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ancient your home, auspicious is your friendship: Heroes, your wealth
							is with the house of Jahnu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Forming again with you auspicious friendship, let us rejoice with
							draughts of meath together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Asvins, Very Mighty ones, with Vayu and with his steeds, one-minded,
							ever-youthful,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nasatyas, joying in the third day's Soma, drink it, not hostile, Very
							Bounteous Givers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Asvins, to you are brought abundant viands in rivalry with sacred
							songs, unceasing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sprung from high Law your car, urged on by press-stones, goes round the
							earth and heaven in one brief moment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Asvins, your Soma sheds delicious sweetness: drink ye thereof and come
							unto our dwelling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 58: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your car, assuming many a shape, most often goes to the Soma-presser's
							place of meeting.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 59
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MITRA, when speaking, stirreth men to labour: Mitra sustaineth both the
							earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mitra beholdeth men with eyes that close not. To Mitra bring, with holy
							oil, oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Foremost be he who brings thee food, O Mitra, who strives to keep thy
							sacred Law, Aditya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He whom thou helpest ne'er is slain or conquered, on him, from near or
							far, falls no affliction.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							joying in sacred food and free from sickness, with knees bent lowly on
							the earth's broad surface,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Following closely the Aditya's statute, may we remain in Mitra's
							gracious favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Auspicious and adorable, this Mitra was born with fair dominion, King,
							Disposer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we enjoy the grace of him the Holy, yea, rest in his propitious
							loving-kindness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The great Aditya, to be served with wor. ship, who stirreth men, is
							gracious to the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Mitra, him most highly to be lauded, offer in fire oblation that he
							loveth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The gainful grace of Mitra,. God, supporter of the race of man,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gives splendour of most.glorious fame.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mitra whose glory spreads afar, he who in might surpasses heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Surpasses earth in his renown.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							All the Five Races have repaired to Mitra, ever strong to aid,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							For he sustaineth all the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mitra to Gods, to living men, to him who strews the holy grass,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 59: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gives food fulfilling sacred Law.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 60
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HERE is your ghostly kinship, here, O Men: they came desirous to these
							holy rites with store of wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With wondrous arts, whereby, with schemes to meet each need, Ye gained,
							Sudhanvan's Sons! your share in sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mighty powers wherewith. ye formed the chalices, the thought by
							which ye drew the cow from out the hide,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The intellect wherewith ye wrought the two Bay Steeds,-through these, O
							Rbhus, ye attained divinity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Friendship with Indra have the Rbhus, fully gained: grandsons of Manu,
							they skilfully urged the work.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sudhanvan's Children won them everlasting life, serving with holy
							rites, pious with noble acts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							In company with Indra come ye to the juice, then gloriously shall your
							wishes be fulfilled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not to be paragoned, ye Priests, are your good deeds, nor your heroic
							acts, Rbhus, Sudhanvan's Sons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, with the Rbhus, Mighty Ones, pour down the Soma juice effused,
							well-blent, from both thy hands.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Maghalan, urged by song, in the drink-offerer's house rejoice thee with
							the Heroes, with Sudhanvan's Sons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Rbhu near, and Vaja, Indra, here exult, with Saci, praised of
							many, in the juice we pour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							These homes wherein we dwell have turned themselves to thee, -devotions
							to the Gods, as laws of men ordain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come with the mighty Rbhus, Indra, come to us, strengthening with thy
							help the singer's holy praise;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 60: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							At hundred eager calls come to the living man, with thousand arts
							attend the act of sacrifice.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 61
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Usas, strong with strength, endowed witli knowledge, accept the
							singer's praise, O wealthy Lady.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Goddess, ancient, young, and full of wisdom, movest,
							all-bounteous! as the Law ordaineth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shine forth, O Morning, thou auspicious Goddess, on thy bright car
							awaking pleasant voices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let docile horses of far-reaching splendour convey thee hitherward, the
							goldencoloured.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Morning, turning thee to every creature, standest on high as
							ensign of the Immortal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To one same goal ever and ever wending now, like a wheel, O newly-born,
							roll hi ther.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Letting her reins drop downward, Morning cometh, the wealthy Dame, the
							Lady of the dwelling;
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bringing forth light, the Wonderful, the Blessed hath spread her from
							the bounds of earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither invoke the radiant Goddess Morning, and bring with reverence
							your hymn to praise her.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							She, dropping sweets, hath set in heaven her brightness, and, fair to
							look on, hath beamed forth her splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							From heaven, with hymns, the Holy One was wakened: brightly to both
							worlds came the wealthy Lady.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Morning, Agni, when she comes refulgent, thou goest forth soliciting
							fair riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							On Law's firm base the speeder of the Mornings, the Bull, hath entered
							mighty earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 61: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Great is the power of Varuna and Mitra, which, bright, hath spread in
							every place its splendour.
						-
			-
				Mandala 3: Hymn 62
			-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YOUR well-known prompt activities aforetime needed no impulse from your
							faithful servant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where, Indra-Varuna, is now that glory wherewith ye brought support to
							those who loved you?
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							This man, most diligent, seeking after riches, incessantly invokes you
							for your favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accordant, Indra-Varuna, with Maruts, with Heaven and Earth, hear ye
							mine invocation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra-Varuna, ours be this treasure ours be wealth, Maruts, with full
							store of heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							.May the Varutris with their shelter aid us, and Bharati and Hotri with
							the Mornings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be pleased! with our oblations, thou loved of all Gods, Brhaspati:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give wealth to him who brings thee gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							At sacrifices, with your hymns worship the pure Brhaspati-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							I pray for power which none may bend-
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Bull of men, whom none deceive, the wearer of each shape at will,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati Most Excellent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Divine, resplendent Pusan, this our newest hymn of eulogy,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							By us is chanted forth to thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Accept with favour this my song, be gracious to the earnest thought,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as a bridegroom to his bride.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he who sees all living things, see, them together at a glancc,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May lie, may Pusan be our help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we attain that excellent glory of Savitar the God:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							So May he stimulate our prayers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							With understanding, earnestly, of Savitar the God we crave
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our portion of prosperity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men, singers worship Savitar the God with hymn and holy rites,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Urged by the impulse of their thoughts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma who gives success goes forth, goes to the gathering place of Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							To seat him at the seat of Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							To us and to our cattle may Soma give salutary food,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							To biped and to quadruped.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Soma, strengthening our power of life, and conquering our foes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							In our assembly take his seat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Mitra-Varuna, sapient Pair, bedew our pasturage with oil,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							With meatb the regions of the air.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far-ruling, joyful when adored, ye reign through majesty of might,
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							With pure laws everlastingly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lauded by Jamadagni's song, sit in the place of holy Law:
						-
					-
						Mandala 3: Hymn 62: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink Soma, ye who strengthen Law.
						-
		-
			Mandala 4
		-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 1
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THEE Agni, have the Gods, ever of one accord, sent hither down, a God,
							appointed messenger, yea, with their wisdom sent thee down.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Immortal, O thou Holy One, mid mortal men, the God-devoted God, the
							wise, have they brought forth, brought forth the omnipresent
							God-devoted Sage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As such, O Agni, bring with favour to the Gods thy Brother Varuna who
							loveth sacrifice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							True to the Law, the Aditya who supporteth men, the King, supporter of
							mankind.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do thou, O Friend, turn hither him who is our Friend, swift as a wheel,
							like two car-steeds in rapid course, Wondrous! to us in rapid course.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Agni, find thou grace for us with Varuna, with Maruts who illumine
							all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							Bless us, thou Radiant One, for seed and progeny, yea, bless us, O thou
							Wondrous God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do thou who knowest Varuna, O Agni, put far away from us the God's
							displeasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best Sacrificer, brightest One, refulgent remove thou far from us all
							those who hate us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be thou, O Agni, nearest us with succour, our closest Friend while now
							this Morn is breaking.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Reconcile to us Varuna, be bounteous enjoy the gracious juice; be swift
							to hear us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Excellent is the glance, of brightest splendour, which the auspicious
							God bestows on mortals-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The God's glance, longed-for even as the butter, pure, heated, of the
							cow, the milch-cow's bounty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three are those births, the true, the most exalted, eagerly longed-for,
							of the God, of Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He came invested in the boundless region, pure, radiant, friendly,
							mightily resplendent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							This envoy joyeth in all seats of worship, borne on his golden car,
							sweet-tongued Invoker:
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lovely to look on, with red steeds, effulgent, like a feast rich in
							food, joyous for ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Allied by worship, let him give man knowledge: by an extended cord they
							lead him onward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He stays, effectual in this mortal's dwelling, and the God wins a share
							in his possessions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let Agni -for he knows the way- conduct us to all that he enjoys of
							God-sent riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							What all the Immortals have prepared with wisdom, Dyaus, Sire,
							Begetter, raining down true blessings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							In houses first he sprang into existence, at great heaven's base, and
							in this region's bosom;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Footless and headless, both his ends concealing, in his Bull's lair
							drawing himself together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wondrously first he rose aloft, defiant, in the Bull's lair, the homeof
							holy Order,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Longed-for, young, beautiful, and far-resplendent: and sevendear
							frieuds sprang up unto the Mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here did our human fathers take their places, fain to fulfil the sacred
							Law of worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Forth drave they, with loud call, Dawn's teeming Milch-kine bid in the
							mountainstable, in the cavern.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Splendid were they when they had rent the mountain: others, around,
							shall tell forth this their exploit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							They sang their song, prepared to free the cattle: they found the
							light; with holy hymns they worshipped.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eager, with thought intent upon the booty, the men with their celestial
							speech threw open,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							The solid mountain firm, compact, enclosing, confining Cows, the stable
							full of cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Milch-cow's earliest name they comprehended: they found the
							Mother's thrice-seven noblest titles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							This the bands knew, and sent forth acclamation:with the Bull's sheen
							the Red One was apparent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							The turbid darkness fled, the heaven was sp, endid! up rose the bright
							beam of celestial Morning.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Surya ascended to the wide expanses, beholding deeds of men both good
							and evil.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then, afterwards they looked around, awakened, when first they held
							that Heaven allotted treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now all the Gods abide in all their dwellings. Varuna, Mitra, be the
							prayer effective.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will call hither brightly-beaming Agni, the Herald, all-supporting,
							best at worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath disclosed, like the milch cows' pure udder, the Sorria's juice
							when cleansed and poured from beakers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							The freest God of all who should be worshipped, the guest who is
							received in all men's houses,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 1: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni who hath secured the Gods' high favour,-may he be gracious, to us
							Jatavedas.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 2
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE, Faithful One, Immortal among mortals, a God among the Gods,
							appointed envoy,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Priest, best at worship, must shine forth in glory . Agni shall be
							raised high with man's oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born for us here this day, O Son of Vigour, between both races of born
							beings, Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou farest as an envoy, having harnessed, Sublime One! thy
							strong-muscled radiant stallions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							I laud the ruddy steeds who pour down blessing, dropping oil, flectest
							through the thoualit of Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yoking red horses to and fro thou goest between you Deities and mortal
							races.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aryaman, Mitra, Varuna, and Indra with Visnu, of the Gods, Maruts and
							Asvins-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							These, Agni, with good car and steeds, bring hither, most bountiful, to
							folk with fair oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, be this our sacrifice eternal, with brave friends, rich in kine
							and sheep and horses,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rich, Asura! in sacred food and children, in full assembly, wealth
							broad-based and during.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The man who, sweating, brings for thee the fuel, and makes his head to
							ache, thy faithful servant,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, to him be a self-strong Protector guard him from all who seek to
							do him mischief.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who brings thee food, though thou hast food in plenty, welcomes his
							cheerful guest and speeds him onward,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who kindles thee devoutly in his dwelling,to him be wealth secure and
							freely giving.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso sings praise to thee at eve or morning, and, with oblation, doth
							the thing thou lovest,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							In his own home, even as a goId-girt courser, rescue him from distress,
							the bounteous giver.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso brings gifts to thee Immortal, Agni, and doth thee service with
							uplifted ladle,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him not, sorely toiling, lose his riches; let not the sinner's
							wickedness enclose him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whose well-wrought worship thou acceptest, Agni, thou God a mortal's
							gift, thou liberal Giver,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dear be his sacrifice to thee, Most Youthful! and may we strengthen him
							when he adores thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he who knows distinguish sense and folly of men, like straight and
							crooked backs of horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lead us, O God, to wealth and noble offspring: keep penury afar and
							grant us plenty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Sage the Sages, ne'er deceived, commanded, setting him down in
							dwellings of the living.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hence mayst thou, friendly God, with rapid footsteps behold the Gods,
							wonderful, fair to look on.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Good guidance hast thou for the priest, O Agni, who, Youngest God! with
							outpoured Soma serves thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ruler of men, thou joyous God, bring treasure splendid and plentiful to
							aid the toiler.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now all that we, thy faithful servants, Agni, have done with feet, with
							hands, and with our bodies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							The wise, with toil, the holy rite have guided, as those who frame a
							car with manual cunning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we, seven sages first in rank, engender, from Dawn the Mother, men
							to be ordainers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we, Angirases, be sons of Heaven, and, radiant, burst the
							wealth-containing mountain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							As in the days of old our ancient Fathers, speeding the work of holy
							worship, Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sought pure light and devotion, singing praises; they cleft the ground
							and made red Dawns apparent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods, doing holy acts, devout, resplendent, smelting like ore their
							human generations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enkindling Agni and exalting Indra, they came encompassing the stall of
							cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong One! he marked them-and the Gods before them-like herds of
							cattle in a foodful pasture.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							There they moaned forth their strong desire for mortals, to aid the
							True, the nearest One, the Living.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							We have worked for thee, we have laboured nobly-bright Dawns have shed
							their light upon our worship-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Adding a beauty to the perfect Agni, and the God's beauteous eye that
							shines for ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 2: Verse 20
				-
