						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou a wild elephant with might invested. like a dread lion as thou
							wieldest weapons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wishes for wealth have gone to Indra, longing for him in war for light
							and at libation,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eager for glory, labouring with praisesongs: he is like home, like
							sweet and fair nutrition.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call we for you that Indra, prompt to listen, him who hath done so much
							for men's advantage;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, Lord of envied bounty, to a singer like me brings quickly booty
							worth the capture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							When the sharp-pointed arrow, O thou Hero, flieth mid any conflict of
							the people,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, Faithful One, the dread encounter cometh, then be thou the
							Protector of our body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Further the holy thoughts of Vamadeva be thou a guileless Friend in
							fight for booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							We come to thee whose providence protects us: wide be thy sway for ever
							for thy singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, with these men who love thee truly, free givers, Maghavan, in
							every battle,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we rejoice through many autumns, quelling our foes, as days subdue
							the nights with splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 16: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, as the Bhrgus wrought a car, for Indra the Strong, the Mighty, we
							our prayer have fashioned,
