					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Heaven trembled at the birth of thine effulgence; Earth trembled at the
							fear of thy displeasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The stedfast mountains shook in agitation . the waters flowed, and
							desert spots were flooded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hurling his bolt with might he cleft the mountain, while, putting forth
							his strength, he showed his vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He slaughtered Vrtra with his bolt, exulting, and, their lord slain,
							forth flowed the waters swiftly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy Father Dyaus esteemed himself a hero: most noble was the work of
							Indra's Maker,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							His who begat the strong bolt's Lord who roareth, immovable like earth
							from her foundation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who alone o'erthrows the world of creatures, Indra the peoples'
							King, invoked of many-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Verily all rejoice in him, extolling the boons which Maghavan the God
							hath sent them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							All Soma juices are his own for ever, most gladdening draughts are ever
							his, the Mighty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou ever wast the Treasure-Lord of treasures: Indra, thou lettest all
							folk share thy bounty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Moreover, when thou first wast born, O Indra, thou struckest terror
							into all the people.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Maghavan, rentest with thy bolt the Dragon who lay against the
							waterfloods of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The ever-slaying, bold and furious Indra, the bright bolt's Lord,
							infinite, strong and mighty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who slayeth Vrtra and acquireth booty, giver of blessings, Maghavan the
							bounteous:
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Alone renowned as Maghavan in battles, he frighteneth away assembled
							armies.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He bringeth us the booty that he winneth may we, well-loved, continue
							in his friendship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Renowned is he when conquering and when slaying: 'fis he who winneth
							cattle in the combat.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Indra hardeneth his indignation all that is fixed and all that
							moveth fear him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra hath won all kine, all gold, all horses,-Maghavan, he who
							breaketh forts in pieces;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most manly with these men of his who help him, dealing out wealth and
							gathering the treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							What is the care of Indra for his Mother, what cares he for the Father
							who begat him?
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							His care is that which speeds his might in conflicts, like wind borne
							onward by the clouds that thunder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Maghavan makes the settled man unsettled: he scatters dust that he hath
							swept together,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Breaking in pieces like Heaven armed with lightning: Maghavan shall
							enrich the man who lauds h;m.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							He urged the chariot-wheel of Surya forward: Etasa, speeding on his
							way, he rested.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him the black undulating cloud bedeweth, in this mid-air's depth, at
							the base of darkness,
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 15
				-
					-
						As in the night the sacrificing priest.
					-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eager for booty, craving strength and horses, we-singers stir Indra,
							the strong, for friendship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who gives the wives we seek, whose succour fails not, to hasten, like a
							pitcher to the fountain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be thou our guardian, show thyself our kinsman, watching and blessing
							those who pour the Soma;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							As Friend, as Sire, most fatherly of fathers giving the suppliant vital
							strength and freedom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be helping Friend of those who seek thy friendship . give life, when
							lauded, Indra, to the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							For, Indra, we the priests have paid thee worship, exalting thee with
							these our sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Alone, when Indra Maghavan is lauded, he slayeth many ne'er-resisted
							Vrtras.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him in whose keeping is the well-loved singer never do Gods or mortals
							stay or hinder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							E’en so let Maghavan, the loud-voiced Indra, give us true blessings,
							foeless, men's upholder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							King of all creatures, give us glory amply, exalted glory due to him
							who lauds thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, Indra! lauded, glorified with praises, let power swell high like
							rivers for the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 17: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thee a new hymn, Lord of Bays! is fashioned. May we, car-borne,
							through song be victors ever.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 18
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS is the ancient and accepted pathway by which all Gods have come
							into existence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hereby could one be born though waxen mighty. Let him not, otherwise,
							destroy his Mother.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not this way go I forth: hard is the passage. Forth from the side
							obliquely will I issue.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Much that is yet undone must I accomplish; one must I combat and the
							other question.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He bent his eye upon the dying Mother: My word I now withdraw. That way
							I follow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In Tvastar's dwelling India drank the Soma, a hundredworth of juice
							pressed from the mortar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							What strange act shall he do, he whom his Mother bore for a thousand
							months and many autumns?
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							No peer hath he among those born already, nor among those who shall be
							born hereafter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Deeming him a reproach, his mother hid him, Indra, endowed with all
							heroic valour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then up he sprang himself, assumed his vesture, and filled, as soon as
							born, the earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							With lively motion onward flow these waters, the Holy Ones, shouting,
							as 'twere, together.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ask them to. tell thee what the floods are saying, what girdling rock
							the waters burst asunder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Are they addressing him with words of welcome? Will the floods take on
							them the shame of Indra?
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With his great thunderbolt my Son hath slaughtered Vrtra, and set these
							rivers free to wander.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							I cast thee from me, mine,-thy youthful mother: thee, mine own
							offspring, Kusava hath swallowed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him, mine infant, were the waters gracious. Indra, my Son, rose up
							in conquering vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art mine own, O Maghavan, whom Vyamsa struck to the ground and
							smote thy jaws in pieces.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							But, smitten through, the mastery thou wonnest, and with thy bolt the
							Dasa's head thou crushedst.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Heifer hath brought forth the Strong, the Mighty, the unconquerable
							Bull, the furious Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mother left her unlicked Calf to wander, seeking himself, the path
							that he would follow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then to her mighty Child the Mother turned her, saying, My son, these
							Deities forsake thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then Indra said, about to slaughter Vrtra, O my friend Vrtra, stride
							full boldly forward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who was he then who made thy Mother widow? Who sought to stay thee
							lying still or moving?
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							What God, when by the foot thy Sire thou tookest and slewest, was at
							hand to give thee comfort?
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							In deep distress I cooked a dog's intestines. Among the Gods I found
							not one to comfort.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							My consort I beheld in degradation. The Falcon then brought me the
							pleasant Soma.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 19
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THEE, verily, O Thunder-wielding Indra, all the Gods here, the Helpers
							swift to listen,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							And both the worlds elected, thee the Mighty, High, waxen strong, alone
							to slaughter Vrtra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Gods, as worn witheld, relaxed their efforts: thou, Indra, born of
							truth, wast Sovran Ruler.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou slewest Ahi who besieged the waters, and duggest out their
							all-supporting channels.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The insatiate one, extended, hard to waken, who slumbered in perpetual
							sleep, O Indra,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Dragon stretched against the seven prone rivers, where no joint
							was, thou rentest with thy thunder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra with might shook earth and her foundation as the wind stirs the
							water with its fury.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Striving, with strength he burst the firm asunder, and tore away the
							summits of the mountains.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							They ran to thee as mothers to their offspring: the clouds, like
							chariots, hastened forth together.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou didst refresh the streams and force the billows: thou, Indra,
							settest free obstructed rivers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou for the sake of Vayya and Turviti didst stay the great stream,
							flowing, allsustaining:
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, at their prayer didst check the rushing river and make the floods
							easy to cross, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He let the young Maids skilled in Law, unwedded, like fountains,
							bubbling, flow forth streaming onward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He inundated thirsty plains and deserts, and milked the dry Cows of the
							mighty master.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through many a morn and many a lovely autumn, having slain Vrtra, lie
							set free the rivers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra hath set at liberty to wander on earth the streams encompassed
							pressed together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of Bay Steeds, thou broughtest from the ant-hill the unwedded
							damsel's son whom ants were eating.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The blind saw clearly, as he grasped the serpent, rose, brake the jar:
							hisjoints again united.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							To the wise man, O Sage and Sovran Ruler, the man who knoweth all thine
							ancient exploits.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hath told these deeds of might as thou hast wrought them, great acts,
							spontaneous, and to man's advantage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, Indra! lauded, glorified with praises, let powers swell high, like
							rivers, for the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 19: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thee a new hymn, Lord of Bays! is fashioned. May we, car-borne,
							through song be victors ever.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 20
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FROM near or far away may mighty Indra giver of succour, come for our
							protection
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of men, armed with thunder, with the Strongest, slaying his foes
							in conflict, in the battles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra come to us with Tawny Coursers, inclined to us, to favour and
							enrich us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Maghavan, loud-voiced and wielding thunder, stand by us at this
							sacrifice, in combat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, honouring this our sacrifice, O Indra, shalt give us strength and
							fill us full of courage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To win the booty, Thunder-armed! like hunters may we with thee subdue
							in fight our foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loving us well, benevolent, close beside us, drink, Godlike Indra, of
							the wellpressed Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink of the meath we offer, and delight thee with food that cometh
							from the mountain ridges.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him who is sung aloud by recent sages, like a ripe-fruited tree, a
							scythe-armed victor,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							I, like a bridegroom thinking of his consort, call hither Indra, him
							invoked of many;
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him who in native strength is like a mountain, the lofty Indra born or
							old for conquest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Terrific wielder of the ancient thunder. filled full with splendour as
							a jar with water.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whom from of old there is not one to hinder, none to curtail the riches
							of his bounty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pouring forth freely, O thou Strong and Mighty, vouchsafe us riches,
							God invoked of many!
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of wealth and homes of men thou art the ruler, and opener of the stable
							of the cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Helper of men, winner of spoil in combats, thou leadest to an ample
							heap of riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							By what great might is he renowned as strongest, wherewith the Lofty
							One stirs up wild battles?
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best soother of the worshipper's great sorrow, he gives possessions to
							the man who lauds him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Slay us not; bring, bestow onus the ample gift which thou hast to give
							to him who offers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							At this new gift, with this laud sung before thee, extolling thee, we,
							Indra, will declare it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, Indra! lauded, glorified with praises, let power swell high, like
							rivers, for the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 20: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							A new hymn, Lord of Bays! for thee is fashioned. May we, car-born,
							through song be victors ever.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 21
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY Indra come to us for our protection; here be the Hero, praised, our
							feast-companion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he whose powers are many, waxen mighty, cherish, like Dyaus, his
							own supreme dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here magnify his great heroic exploits, most glorious One, enriching
							men with bounties,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose will is like a Sovran in assembly, who rules the people,
							Conqueror, all-surpassing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither let Indra come from earth or heaven, hither with speech from
							firmament or ocean;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Maruts, from the realm of light to aid us, or from a distance,
							from the seat of Order.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Indra will we laud in our assemblies, him who is Lord of great and
							lasting riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Victor with Vayu where the herds are gathered, who leads with boldness
							on to higher fortune.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Priest, Lord of many blessings, striving,-who fixing reverence
							on reverence, giving
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vent to his voice, inciteth men to worshipwith lauds bring Indra hither
							to our dwellings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When sitting pondering in deep devotion in Ausija's abode they ply the
							press-stone,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he whose wrath is fierce, the mighty bearer, come as the
							house-lord's priest within our chambers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surely the power of Bharvara the mighty for ever helpeth to support the
							singer;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							That which in Ausija's abode lies hidden, to come forth for delight and
							for devotion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When he unbars the spaces of the mountains, and quickens with his
							floods the water-torrents,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He finds in lair the buffalo and wild-ox when the wise lead him on to
							vigorous exploit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Auspicious are thy hands, thine arms wellfashioned which proffer
							bounty, Indra, to thy praiser.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							What sloth is this? Why dost thou not rejoice thee? Why dost thou not
							delight thyself with giving?
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							So Indra is the truthful Lord of treasure. Freedom he gave to man by
							slaying Vrtra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Much-lauded! help us with thy power to riches: may I be sharer of thy
							Godlike favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, Indra! lauded, glorified with praises, let power swell high, like
							rivers, for,the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 21: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thee a new hymn, Lord of Bays! is fashioned. May we, care-borne,
							through song be victqrs ever.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 22
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THAT gift of ours which Indra loves and welcomes, even that he makes
							for us, the Great and Strong One.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who comes wielding in his might the thunder, Maghavan, gives prayer,
							praise, and laud, and Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bull, hurler of the four-edged rain-producer with both his arms,
							strong, mighty, most heroic;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wearing as wool Parusni for adornment, whose joints for sake of
							friendship he hath covered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							God who of all the Gods was born divinest, endowed with ample strength
							and mighty powers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And bearing in his arrns the yearning thunder, with violent rush caused
							heaven and earth to tremble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Before the High God, at his birth, heaven trembled, earth, many floods
							and all the precipices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Strong One bringeth nigh the Bull's two Parents: loud sing the
							winds, like men, in air's mid-region.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							These are thy great deeds, Indra, thine, the Mighty, deeds to be told
							aloud at all libations,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							That thou, O Hero, bold and boldly daring, didst with thy bolt, by
							strength, destroy the Dragon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							True are all these thy deeds, O Most Heroic. The Milch-kine issued from
							the streaming udder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							In fear of thee, O thou of manly spirit, the rivers swiftly set
							themselves in motion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							With joy, O Indra, Lord of Tawny Coursers, the Sisters then, these
							Goddesses, extolled thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou didst give the prisoned ones their freedom to wander at their
							will in long succession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pressed is the gladdening stalk as 'twere a river: so let the rite, the
							toiler's power, attract thee
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							To us-ward, of the Bright One, as the courser strains his. exceedingly
							strong leather bridle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ever by us perform thy most heroic, thine highest, best victorious
							deeds, O Victor.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							For us make Vrtras easy to be conquered: destroy the weapon of our
							mortal foeman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Graciously listen to our prayer, O Indra, and strength of varied sort
							bestow thou on us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Send to us all intelligence arid wisdom O Maghavan, be he who gives us
							cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, Indra! lauded, glorified with praises, let wealth swell hiah like
							rivers to the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 22: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thee a new hymn, Lord of Bays, is fashioned. May we, car-borne,
							through song be victors ever.
