						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 33: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rbhus, as those who wish a friend to prosper, bestow upon us gear and
							growth of riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 33: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							This day have they set gladdening drink before you. Not without toil
							are Gods inclined to friendship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therefore do ye who are so great, O Rbhus, vouchsafe us treasures at
							this third libation.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 34
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To this our sacrifice come Rbhu, Vibhvan, Vaja, and Indra with the gift
							of riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Because this day hath Dhisana the Goddess set drink for you: the
							gladdening draughts have reached you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Knowing your birth and rich in gathered treasure, Rbhus, rejoice
							together with the Rtus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The gladdening draughts and wisdom have approached you: send ye us
							riches with good store of heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For you was made this sacrifice, O Rbhus, which ye, like men, won for
							yourselves aforetime.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To you come all who find in you their pleasure: ye all were-even the
							two elder-Vajas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now for the mortal worshipper, O Heroes, for him who served you, was
							the gift of riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink, Vajas, Rbhus! unto you is offered, to gladden you, the third and
							great libation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to us, Heroes, Vajas and Rbhuksans, glorified for the sake of
							mighty treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These draughts approach you as the day is closing, as cows, whose
							calves are newly-born, their stable.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to this sacrifice of ours, ye Children of Strength, invoked with
							humble adoration.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink of this meath, Wealth-givers, joined with Indra with whom ye are
							in full accord, ye Princes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Close knit with Varuna drink the Soma, Indra; close-knit, ilymn-lover!
							with the Maruts drink it:
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Close-knit with drinkers first, who drink in season; close-knit with
							heavenly Dames who give us treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rejoice in full accord with the Adityas, in concord with the Parvatas,
							O Rbhus;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							In full accord with Savitar, Divine One; in full accord with floods
							that pour forth riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rbhus, who helped their Parents and the Asvins, who formed the
							Milch-cow and the pair of horses,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Made armour, set the heaven and earth asunder,-far- reaching Heroes,
							they have made good offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye who have wealth in cattle and in booty, in heroes, in rich
							sustenance and treasure,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Such, O ye Rbhus, first to drink, rejoicing, give unto us and those who
							laud our present.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye were not far: we have not left you thirsting, blameless in this our
							sacrifice, O Rbhus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 34: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rejoice you with the Maruts and with Indra, with the Kings, Gods! that
							ye may give us riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 35
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come hither, O ye Sons of Strength, ye Rbhus; stay not afar, ye
							Children of Sudhanvan.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							At this libation is your gift of treasure. Let gladdening draughts
							approach you after Indra's.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither is come the Rbhus' gift of riches; here was the drinking of the
							well-pressed Soma,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Since by dexterity and skill as craftsmen ye made the single chalice to
							be fourfold
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye made fourfold the chalice that wag single: ye spake these words and
							said, O Friend, assist us;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then, Vajas! gained the path of life eternal, deft-handed Rbhus, to the
							Gods' assembly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Out of what substance was that chalice fashioned which ye made fourfold
							by your art and wisdom?
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now for the gladdening draught press out the liquor, and drink, O
							Rbhus, of die meath of Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye with your cunning made your Parents youthful; the cup, for Gods to
							drink, ye formed with cunning;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With cunning, Rbhus, rich in treasure, fashioned the two swift Tawny
							Steeds who carry Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso pours out for you, when days are closing, the sharp libation for
							your joy, O Vajas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For him, O mighty Rbhus, ye, rejoicing, have fashioned wealth with
							plenteous store of heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of Bay Steeds, at dawn thejuice thou drankest: thine, only thine,
							is the noonday libation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now drink thou with the wealth-bestowing Rbhus, whom for their skill
							thou madest friends, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, whom your artist skill hath raised to Godhead have set you down
							above in heaven like falcons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							So give us riches, Children of Sudhanvan, O Sons of Strength; ye have
							become immortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The third libation, that bestoweth treasure, which ye have won by
							skill, ye dexterous-handed,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							This drink hath been effused for you, O Rbhus . drink it with high
							delight, with joy like Indra's.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 36
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THia car that was not made for horses or for reins, three-wheeled,
							worthy of lauds, rolls round the firmament.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That is the great announcement of your Deity, that, O ye Rbhus, ye
							sustain the earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Sapient Ones who made the lightly-rolling car out of your mind, by
							thought, the car that never errs,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							You, being such, to drink of this drinkoffering, you, O ye Vajas, and
							ye Rbhus, we invoke.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Vajas, Rbhus, reaching far, among the Gods this was your exaltation
							gloriously declared,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In that your aged Parents, worn with length of days, ye wrought again
							to youth so that they moved at will.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The chalice that wag single ye have made fourfold, and by your wisdom
							brought the Cow forth from the hide.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							So quickly, mid the Gods, ye gained immortal life. Vajas and Rbhus,
							your great work must be extolled.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wealth from the Rbhus is most glorious in renown, that which the
							Heroes, famed for vigour, have produced.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							In synods must be sung the car which Vibhvan wrought: that which ye
							favour, Gods! is famed among mankind.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong is the steed, the man a sage in eloquence, the bowman is a hero
							hard to beat in fight,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Great store of wealth and manly power hath he obtained whom Vaja,
							Vibhvan, Rbhus have looked kindly on.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you hath been assigned the fairest ornament, the hymn of praise:
							Vajas and Rbhus, joy therein;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							For ye have lore and wisdom and poetic skill: as such, with this our
							prayer we call on you to come.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							According to the wishes of our hearts may ye, who have full knowledge
							of all the delights of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fashion for us, O Rbhus, power and splendid wealth, rich in high
							courage, excellent, and vital strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bestowing on us here riches and offspring, here fashion fame for us
							befitting heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 36: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us wealth of splendid sort, O Rbhus, that we may make us more
							renowned than others.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 37
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COME to our sacrifice, Vajas, Rbhuksans, Gods, by the paths which Gods
							are wont to travel,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As ye, gay Gods, accept in splendid weather the sacrifice among these
							folk of Manus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May these rites please you in your heart and spirit; may the drops
							clothed in oil this day approach you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the abundant juices bear you onward to power and strength, and,
							when imbibed, delight you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your threefold going near is God-appointed, so praise is given you,
							Vajas and Rbhuksans.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, Manus-like, mid younger folk I offer, to you who are aloft in
							heaven, the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong, with fair chains of gold and jaws of iron, ye have a splendid
							car and well-fed horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Sons of Strength, ye progeny of Indra, to you the best is offered to
							delight you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rbhuksans! him, for handy wealth, the mightiest comrade in the fight,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him, Indra's equal, we invoke, most bounteous ever, rich in steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mortal man whom, Rbhus, ye and Indra favour with your help,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Must be successful, by his thoughts, at sacrifice and with the steed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Vajas and Rbhuksans, free for us the paths to sacrifice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Princes, lauded, that we may press forward to each point of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Vajas and Rbhuksans, ye Nasatyas, Indra, bless this wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 37: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, before other men's, the steed, that ample riches may be won.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 38
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FROM you two came the gifts in days aforetime which Trasadasyu granted
							to the Purus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye gave the winner of our fields and plough-lands, and the strong
							smiter who subdued the Dasytis.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							And ye gave mighty Dadhikras, the giver of many gifts, who visiteth all
							people,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Impetuous hawk, swift and of varied colour, like a brave King whom each
							true man must honour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whom, as 'twere down a precipice, swift rushing, each Puru praises and
							his heart rejoices,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Springing forth like a hero fain for battle, whirling the car and
							flying like the tempest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who gaineth precious booty in the combats and moveth, winning spoil,
							among the cattle;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shown in bright colour, looking on the assemblies, beyond the churl, to
							worship of the living.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loudly the folk cry after him in battles, as 'twere a thief who steals
							away a garment;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Speeding to glory, or a herd of cattle, even as a hungry falcon
							swooping downward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							And, fain to come forth first amid these armies, this way and that with
							rows of cars he rushes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gay like a bridesman, making him a garland, tossing the dust, champing
							the rein that holds him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							And that strong Steed, victorious and faithful, obedient with his body
							in the combat,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Speeding straight on amid the swiftly ressing, casts o'er his brows the
							dust he tosses upward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							And at his thunder, like the roar of heaven, those who attack tremble
							and are affrighted;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							For when he fights against embattled thousands, dread is he in his
							striving; none may stay him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The people praise the overpowering swiftness of this fleet Steed who
							giveth men abundance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 38: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
