						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 51: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							As from our pleasant place of rest ye rouse us may we be masters of
							heroic vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 51: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well-skilled in lore of sacrifice, ye Daughters of Heaven, refulgent
							Dawns, I thus address you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we be glorious among the people. May Heaven vouchsafe us this, and
							Earth the Goddess,
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 52
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THIS Lady, giver of delight, after her Sister shining forth, Daughter of
						Heaven, hath shown herself.-
					-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unfailing, Mother of the Kine, in colour like a bright red mare,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Dawn became the Asvins' Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, and thou art the Asvins' Friend, the Mother of the Kine art thou:
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Dawn thou rulest over wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thinking of thee, O joyous One, as her who driveth hate away,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							We woke to meet thee with our lauds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Our eyes behold thy blessed rays like troops of cattle loosed to feed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dawn hath filled full the wide expanse.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou hast filled it, Fulgent One! thou layest bare the gloom with
							light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							After thy nature aid us, Dawn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou overspreadest heaven with rays, the dear wide region of mid-air.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 52: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thy bright shining lustre, Dawn.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 53
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							OF Savitar the God, the sapient Asura, we crave this great gift which
							is worthy of our choice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith he freely grants his worshiper defence. This with his rays
							the Great God hath vouchsafed to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sustainer of the heaven, Lord of the whole world's life, the Sage, he
							putteth on his golden-coloured mail.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Clear-sighted, spreading far, filling the spacious realm, Savitar hath
							brought forth bliss that deserveth laud.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He hath filled full the regions of the heaven and earth: the God for
							his own strengthening waketh up the hymn.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savitar hath stretched out his arms to cherish life, producing with his
							rays and lulling all that moves.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lighting all living creatures, neer to be deceived, Savitar, God,
							protects each holy ordinance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath stretched out his arms to all the folk of earth, and, with his
							laws observed, rules his own mighty course.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Savitar thrice surrounding with his mightiness mid-air, three regions,
							and the triple sphere of light,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sets the three heavens in motion and the threefold earth, and willingly
							protects us with his triple law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Most gracious God, who brings to life and lulls to rest, he who
							controls the world, what moves not and what moves,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he vouchsafe us shelter, -Savitar the God,- for tranquil life, with
							triple bar against distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							With the year's seasons hath Savitar, God, come nigh: may he prosper
							our home, give food and noble sons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 53: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he invigorate us through the days and nights, and may he send us
							opulence with progeny.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 54
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now must we praise and honour Savitar the God: at this time of the day
							the men must call to him,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who distributes wealth to Manu's progeny, that he may grant us here
							riches most excellent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For thou at first producest for the holy Gods the noblest of all
							portions, immor-tality:
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thereafter as a gift to men, O Savitar, thou openest existence, life
							succeeding life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							If we, men as we are, have sinned against the Gods through want of
							thought, in weakness, or through insolence,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Absolve us from the guilt and make us free from sin, O Savitar, alike
							among both Gods and men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							None may impede that power of Savitar the God whereby he will maintain
							the universal world.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							What the fair-fingered God brings forth on earth's expanse or in the
							height of heaven, that work of his stands sure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To lofty hills thou sendest those whom Indra leads, and givest fixed
							abodes with houses unto these.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							However they may fly and draw themselves apart, still, Savitar, they
							stand obeying thy behest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the libations poured to thee thrice daily, day after day, O
							Savitar, bring us blessing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 54: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Indra, Heaven, Earth, Sindhu with the Waters, Aditi with Adityas,
							give us shelter.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 55
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHO of you, Vasus, saveth? who protecteth? O Heaven and Earth and
							Aditi, preserve us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Varuna., Mitra, from the stronger mortal. Gods, which of you at
							sacrifice giveth comfort?
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who with laud extol the ancient statutes, when they shine forth
							infallible dividers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have ordered as perpetual Ordainers, and beamed as holy-thoughted
							WonderWorkers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Housewife Goddess, Aditi, and Sindhu, the Goddess Svasti I implore
							for friendship:
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And may the unobstructed Night and Morning both, day and night, provide
							for our protection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aryaman, Varuna have disclosed the pathway, Agni as Lord of Strength
							the road to welfare.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lauded in manly mode may Indra-Visnu grant us their powerful defence
							and shelter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I have besought the favourof the Maruts, of Parvata, of Bhaga God who
							rescues.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							From trouble caused by man the Lord preserve us; from woe sent by his
							friend let Mitra save us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agree, through these our watery oblations, Goddesses, Heaven and Earth,
							with Ahibudhnya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As if to win the sea, the Gharma-heaters have opened, as they come
							anear, the rivers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Goddess Aditi with Gods defend us, save us the saviour God with
							care unceasing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							We dare not stint the sacred food of Mitra and Varuna upon the back of
							Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni is Sovran Lord of wealth, Agni of great prosperity:
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he bestow these gifts on us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither to us, rich pleasant Dawn, bring many things to be desired,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou who hast ample store of wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 55: Verse 10
				-
					-
						So then may Bhaga, Savitar, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman, Indra, with bounty come
						to us.
					-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 56
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY mighty Heaven and Earth, most meet for honour, be present here with
							light and gleaming splendours;
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, fixing them apart, vast, most extensive, the Steer roars loudly
							in far-reaching courses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Goddesses with Gods, holy with holy, the Two stand pouring out
							their rain, exhaustless:
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Faithful and guileless, having Gods for children, leaders of sacrifice
							with shining splendours.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sure in the worlds he was a skilful Craftsman, he who produced these
							Twain the Earth and Heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wise, with his power he brought both realms, together spacious and
							deep, wellfashioned, unsupported.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Heaven and Earth, with one accord promoting, with high protection as
							of Queens, our welfare,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far-reaching, universal, holy, guard us. May we, car-borne, through
							song be victors ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To both of you, O Heaven and Earth, we bring our lofty song of praise,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pure Ones! to glorify you both.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye sanctify each other's form, by your own proper might ye rule,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							And from of old observe the Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Furthering and fulfilling, ye, O Mighty, perfect Mitra's Law.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 56: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye sit around our sacrifice.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 57
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WE through the Master of the Field, even as through a friend, obtain
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							What nourisheth our kine and steeds. In such may he be good to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the cow yieldeth milk, pour for us freely, Lord of the Field, the
							wave that beareth sweetness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Distilling meath, well-purified like butter, and let the. Lords of holy
							Law be gracious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sweet be the plants for us. the heavens, the waters, and full of sweets
							for us be air's mid-region.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the Field's Lord for us be full of sweetness, and may we follow
							after him uninjured.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Happily work our steers and men, may the plough furrow happily.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Happily be the traces bound; happily may he ply the goad.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Suna and Sira, welcome ye this laud, and with the milk which ye have
							made in heaven
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bedew ye both this earth of ours.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Auspicious Sita, come thou near: we venerate and worship thee
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							That thou mayst bless and prosper us and bring us fruits abundantly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra press the furrow down, may Pusan guide its course aright.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May she, as rich in milk, be drained for us through each succeeding
							year.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Happily let the shares turn up the ploughland, happily go the ploughers
							with the oxen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 57: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With meath and milk Parjanya make us happy. Grant us prosperity, Suna
							and Sira.
						-
			-
				Mandala 4: Hymn 58
			-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FORTH from the ocean sprang the wave of sweetness: together with the
							stalk it turned to Amrta,
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That which is holy oil's mysterious title: but the Gods' tongue is
							truly Amrta's centre.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us declare aloud the name of Ghrta, and at this sacrifice hold it
							up with homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So let the Brahman hear the praise we utter. This hath the four-horned
							Buffalo emitted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Four are his horns, three are the feet that bear him; his heads are
							two, his hands are seven in number.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bound with a triple bond the Steer roars loudly: the mighty God hath
							entered in to mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							That oil in triple shape the Gods discovered laid down within the Cow,
							concealed by Panis.
						-
					-
						Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra produced one shape, Surya another: by their own power they formed
							the third from Vena.
						-
				-
					Mandala 4: Hymn 58: Verse 5
				-
					-
