					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni is wakened by the people's fuel to meet the Dawn who cometh like a
							milch-cow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like young trees shooting up on high their branches, his flames are
							rising to the vault of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For worship of the Gods the Priest was wakened: at morning gracious
							Agni hath arisen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Kindled, his radiant might is made apparent, and the great Deity set
							free from darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When he hath stirred the line of his attendants, with the pure milk
							pure Agni is anointed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The strength-bestowing gift is then made ready, which spread in front,
							with tongues, erect, he drinketh.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The spirits of the pious turn together to Agni, as the eyes of all to
							Surya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, when both Dawns of different hues have borne him, springs up at
							daybreak as a strong white charger.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The noble One was born at days' beginning, laid red in colour mid the
							well-laid fuel.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yielding in every house his seven rich treasures, Agni is seated,
							Priest most skilled in worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni hath sat him down, a Priest most skilful, on a sweet-smelling
							place, his Mother's bosom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Young, faithful, sage, preeminent o'er many, kindled among the folk
							whom he sustaineth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Singer excellent at sacrifices, Agni the Priest, they glorify with
							homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who spread out both worlds by Law Eternal they balm with oil,
							strong Steed who never faileth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, worshipful House-Friend, in his home is worshipped, our own
							auspicious guest, lauded by sages.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							That strength the Bull with thousand horns possesses. In might, O Agni,
							thou excellest others.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou quickly passest by all others, Agni, for him to whom thou hast
							appeared most lovely,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wondrously fair, adorable, effulgent, the guest of men, the darling of
							the people.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee, Most Youthful God! to thee, O Agni from near and far the
							people bring their tribute.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mark well the prayer of him who best extols thee. Great, high,
							auspicious, Agni, is thy shelter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ascend to-day thy splendid car, O Agni, in splendour, with the Holy
							Ones around it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Knowing the paths by mid-air's spacious region bring hither Gods to
							feast on our oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him adorable, sage, strong and mighty we have sung forth our song of
							praise and homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gavisthira hath raised with prayer to Agni this laud far-reaching, like
							gold light to heaven.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 2
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE youthful Mother keeps the Boy in secret pressed to her close, nor
							yields him to the Father.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							But, when he lies upon the arm, the people see his unfading countenance
							before them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							What child is this thou carriest as handmaid, O Youthful One? The
							Consort-Queen hath bome him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Babe unborn increased through many autumns. I saw him born what
							time his Mother bare him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							I saw him from afar gold-toothed, bright-coloured, hurling his weapons
							from his habitation,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time I gave him Amrta free from mixture. How can the Indraless,
							the hymnless harm me?
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I saw him moving from the place he dwells in, even as with a herd,
							brilliantly shining.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							These seized him not: he had been born already. They who were grey with
							age again grow youthful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who separate my young bull from the cattle, they whose protector was in
							truth no stranger?
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let those whose hands have seized upon them free them. May he,
							observant, drive the herd to us-ward.
						-
