							makcst wife and lord one-minded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Maruts deck their beauty for thy glory, yea, Rudra! for thy birth
							fair, brightly-coloured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							That which was fixed as Visnu's loftiest station-therewith the secret
							of the Cows thou guardest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods through thy glory, God who art so lovely! granting abundant gifts
							gained life immortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As their own Priest have men established Agni; and serve him fain for
							praise from him who liveth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							There is no priest more skilled than thou in worship; none
							Self-sustainer pass thee in wisdom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ile man within whose house as guest thou dwellest, O God, by sacrifice
							shall conquer mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aided by thee, O Agni may we conquer through our oblation, fain for
							wealth, awakened:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we in battle, in the days' assemblies,O Son of Strength, by riches
							conquer mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He shall bring evil on the evil-plottcr whoever turns against us sin
							and outrage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Destroy this calumny of him, O Agni, whoever injures us with
							double-dealing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							At this dawn's flushing, God! our ancient fathers served thee with
							offerings, making thee their envoy,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, Agni, to the store of wealth thou goest, a God cnkindled with
							good things by mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Save, thou who knowest, draw thy father near thee, who counts as thine
							own son, O Child of Power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							O sapient Agni, when wilt thou regard us? When, skilled in holy Law,
							wilt thou direct us?
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adoring thee he gives thee many a title, when thou, Good Lord!
							acceptest this as Father.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							And doth not Agni, glad in strength of Godhead, gain splendid bliss
							when he hath waxen mighty?
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Most Youthful Agni, verily thou bearest thy praiser safely over all his
							troubles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thieves have been seen by us and open foemen: unknown have been the
							plottings of the wicked.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee these eulogies have been directed: or to the Vasu hath this sin
							been spoken.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 3: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							But this our Agni, flaming high, shall never yield us to calumny, to
							him who wrongs us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 4
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O AGNI, King and Lord of wealth and treasures, in thee is my delight at
							sacrifices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through thee may we obtain the strength we long for, and overcome the
							fierce attacks of mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, Eternal Father, offering- bearer, fair to behold, far-reaching,
							far-refulgent,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							From well-kept household fire beam food to feed us, and measure out to
							us abundant glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sage of men, the Lord of human races, pure, purifying Agni, balmed
							with butter,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him the Omniscient as your Priest ye stablish: he wins among the Gods
							things worth the choosing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, enjoy, of one accord with Ila, striving in rivalry with beams of
							Sarya,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enjoy, O Jatavedas, this our fuel, and bring the Gods to us to taste
							oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As dear House-Friend, guest welcome in the dwelling, to this our
							sacrifice come thou who knowest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, Agni, having scattered all assailants, bring to us the possessions
							of our foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 1
