				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, invoked and kindled, serve the Gods, thou skilled in sacrifice:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thou art bearer of our gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Invoke and worship Agni while the sacrificial rite proceeds:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For offering-bearer choose ye him.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 29
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAN'S worship of the Gods hath three great lustres, and three celestial
							lights have they established
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Maruts gifted with pure strength adore thee, for thou, O Indra, art
							their sapient Rsi.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the Maruts sang their song to Indra, joyous when he had drunk
							of Soma juices,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He grasped his thunderbolt to slay the Dragon, and loosed, that they
							might flow, the youthful Waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							And, O ye Brahmans, Maruts, so may Indra drink draughts of this my
							carefully pressed Sorna;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							For this oblation found for man the cattle, and Indra, having quaffed
							it, slew the Dragon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then heaven and earth he sundered and supported: wrapped even in these
							he struck the Beast with terror.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							So Indra forced the Engulfer to disgorgement, and slew the Danava.
							panting against him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus all the Gods, O Maghavan, delivered to thee of their free will the
							draught of Soma;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou for Etasa didst cause to tarry the flying mares of Surya
							racing forward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Maghavan with the thunderbolt demolished his nine-and-ninety
							castles all together,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Maruts, where they met, glorified Indra: ye with the Trstup hymn
							obstructed heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							As friend to aid a friend, Agni dressed quickly three hundred
							buffaloes, even as he willed it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Indra, from man's gift, for Vrtra's slaughter, drank ofr at once
							three lakes of pressed-out Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou three hundred buffaloes' flesh hadst eaten, and drunk, as
							Maghavan, three lakes of Soma,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							All the Gods raised as 'twere a shout of triumph to Indra praise
							because he slew the Dragon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time ye came with strong steeds swiftly speeding, O Usana and
							Indra, to the dwelling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou camest thither -conquering together with Kutsa and the Gods: thou
							slewest Susna.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							One car-wheel of the Sun thou rolledst forward, and one thou settest
							free to move for Kutsa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou slewest noseless Dasyus with thy weapon, and in their home
							o'erthrewest hostile speakers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The lauds of Gauriviti made thee mighty to Vidathin's son, as prey,
							thou gavest Pipru.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rjisivan drew thee into friendship dressing the sacred food, and thou
							hast drunk his Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Navagvas and Dasgvas with libations of Soma juice sing hymns of praise
							to Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Labouring at their task the men laid open the stall of Kine though
							firmly closed and fastened.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							How shall I serve thee, Maghavan, though knowing full well what hero
							deeds thou hast accomplished?
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							And the fresh deeds which thou wilt do, Most Mighty! these, too, will
							we tell forth in sacred synods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Resistless from of old through hero courage, thou hast done all these
							many acts, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							What thou wilt do in bravery, Thunder-wielder! none is there who may
							hinder this thy prowess.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, accept the prayers which now are offered, accept the new
							prayers, Mightiest! which we utter.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like fair and well-made robes, I, seeking riches, as a deft craftsman
							makes a car, have wrought them.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 30
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHERE is that Hero? Who hath looked on Indra borne on light-rolling car
							by Tawny Coursers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, Thunderer, seeks with wealth the Soma-presser, and to his house
							goes, much-invoked, to aid him?
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I have beheld his strong and secret dwelling, longing have sought the
							Founder's habitation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							I asked of others, and they said in answer, May we, awakened men,
							attain to Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							We will tell, Indra, when we pour libation, what mighty deeds thou hast
							performed to please us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him who knows not learn, who knows them listen: hither rides
							Maghavan with all his army.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, when born, thou madest firm thy spirit: alone thou seekest war
							to fight with many.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With might thou clavest e'en the rock asunder, and foundest out the
							stable of the Milch-kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou wast born supremest at a distance, bearing a name renowned in
							far-off regions,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Since then e'en Gods have been afraid of Indra: he conquered all the
							floods which served the Dasa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							These blissful Maruts sing their psalm to praise thee, and pour to thee
							libation of the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra with wondrous powers subdued the Dragon, the guileful lurker who
							beset the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Maghavan, from the first didst scatter foemen, speeding, while
							joying in the milk, the Giver.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							There, seeking man's prosperity, thou torest away the head of Namuci
							the Dasa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pounding the head of Namuci the Dasa, me, too thou madest thine
							associate, Indra!
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, and the rolling stone that is in heaven both worlds, as on a car,
							brought to the Maruts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Women for weapons hath the Dasa taken, What injury can his feeble
							armies To me?
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well he distinguished his two different voices, and Indra then advanced
							to fight the Dasyu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Divided from their calves the Cows went lowing around, on every side,
							hither and thither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							These Indra re-united with his helpers, what time the well-pressed Soma
							made him joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the Somas mixed by Babhru cheered him, loud the Steer
							bellowed in his habitations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							So Indra drank thereof, the Fort-destroyer, and gave him guerdon, in
							return, of milch-kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							This good deed have the Rusamas done, Agni! that they have granted me
							four thousand cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							We have received Rnancaya's wealth, of heroes the most heroic, which
							was freely offered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Rusamas, O Agni, sent me homeward with fair adornment and with kine
							in thousands.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							The strong libations have made Indra joyful, when night, whose course
							was ending, changed to morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Night, well-nigh ended, at Rnancaya's coming, King of the Rusamas, was
							changed to morning.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a strong courser, fleet of foot, urged onward, Babhru hath gained
							four thousand as his guerdon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							We have received four thousand head of cattle presented by the Rusamas,
							O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							And we, the singers, have received the caldron of metal which was
							heated for Pravargya.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 31
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAGHAVAN Indra turns his chariot downward, the strength-displaying car
							which he hath mounted.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as a herdsman driveth forth his cattle, he goeth, first,
							uninjured, fain for treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Haste to us, Lord of Bays; be not ungracious: visit us, lover of
							gold-hued oblation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							There is naught else better than thou art, Indra: e'en to the wifeless
							hast thou given spouses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When out of strength arose the strength that conquers, Indra displayed
							all powers that he possesses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Forth from the cave he drove the milky mothers, and with the light laid
							bare investing darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Anus have wrought a chariot for thy Courser, and Tvastar, Much-invoked!
							thy bolt that glitters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Brahmans with their songs exalting Indra increased his strength
							that he might slaughter Ahi.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When heroes sang their laud to thee the Hero, Indra! and stones and
							Aditi accordant,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Without or steed or chariot were the fellies which, sped by Indra,
							rolled upon the Dasytis.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will declare thine exploits wrought aforetime, and, Maghavan, thy
							deeds of late achievement,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, Lord of Might, thou sunderedst earth and heaven, winning for man
							the moistly-gleaming waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is thy deed, e'en this, Wonderful! Singer! that, slaying Ahi, here
							thy strength thou showedst,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Didst check and stay e'en gusna's wiles and magic, and, drawing nigh,
							didst chase away the Dasytis.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, on the farther bank forYadu and Turvaga didst stay the
							gushing waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye both assailed the fierce: thou barest Kutsa: when Gods and Usana
							came to you together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the steeds bring you both, Indra and Kutsa, borne on the chariot
							within hearing-distance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye blew him from the waters, from his dwelling, and chased the darkness
							from the noble's spirit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even this sage hath come looking for succour even to Vata's docile
							harnessed horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here are the Maruts, all, thy dear companions: prayers have increased
							thy power and might, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							When night was near its close he carried forward e'en the Sun's chariot
							backward in its running.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Etaga brought his wheel and firmly stays it: setting it eastward he
							shall give us courage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Indra, O ye men, hath come to see you, seeking a friend who hath
							expressed the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							The creaking stone is laid upon the altar, and the Adhvaryus come to
							turn it quickly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let mortals who were happy still be happy; let them not come to sorrow,
							O Immortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Love thou the pious, and to these thy people-with whom may we be
							numbered-give thou vigour.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 32
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							well thou clavest, settest free the fountains, and gavest rest to
							floods that were obstructed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, laying the great mountain open, slaying the Danava, didst
							loose the torrents.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The fountain-depths obstructed in their seasons, thou, Thunderer!
							madest flow, the mountain's udder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strong Indra, thou by slaying e'en the Dragon that lay extended there
							hast shown thy vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra with violence smote down the weapon,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							yea, even of that wild and mighty creature.
						-
					-
