			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WIDE, Indra Satakratu, spreads the bounty of thine ample grace:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, Lord of fair dominion, Friend of all men, give us splendid wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The food which, Mightiest Indra, thou possessest worthy of renown
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is bruited as most widely famed, invincible, O Golden-hued!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Darter of the Stone, the powers which readily obey thy will,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Divinities, both thou and they, ye rule, to guard them, earth and
							heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							And from whatever power of thine, O Vrtra-slayer, it may be,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring thou to us heroic strength: thou hast a man's regard for us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							In thy protection, with these aids of thine, O Lord of Hundred Powers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, may we be guarded well, Hero, may we be guarded well.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 39
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							STONE-DARTING Indra. Wondrous One, what wealth is richly given from
							thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That bounty, Treasure-Finder! bring filling both thy hands, to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring what thou deemest worth the wish, O Indra, that which is in
							heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may we know thee as thou art, boundless in thy munificence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy lofty spirit, far-renowned as fain to give and prompt to win,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With this thou rendest e'en the firm, Stone-Darter! so to gain thee
							strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Singers with many songs have made Indra propitious to their fame,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who is King of human kind, most liberal of your wealthy ones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him, to Indra must be sung the poet's word, the hymn of praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him, accepter of the prayer, the Atris raise their songs on high,
							the Atris beautify their songs.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 40
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COME thou to what the stones have pressed, drink Soma, O thou Soma's
							Lord,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra best Vrtra-slayer Strong One, with the Strong.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong is the stone, the draught is strong, strong is this Soma that is
							pressed,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, best Vrtra-slayer, Strong One with the Strong.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							As strong I call on thee the Strong, O Thunder-armed, with various
							aids,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, best Vrtra-slayer, Strong One with the Strong.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Impetuous, Thunderer, Strong, quelling the mighty, King, potent,
							Vrtra-slayer, Soma-drinker,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he come hither with his yoked Bay Horses; may Indra gladden him at
							the noon libation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Surya, when the Asura's descendant Svarbhanu, pierced thee through
							and through with darkness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							All creatures looked like one who is bewildered, who knoweth not the
							place where he is standing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time thou smotest down Svarbhanu's magic that spread itself
							beneath the sky, O Indra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							By his fourth sacred prayer Atri disoovered Surya concealed in gloom
							that stayed his function.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let not the oppressor with this dread, through anger swallow me up, for
							I am thine, O Atri.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mitra art thou, the sender of true blessings: thou and King Varuna be
							both my helpers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Brahman Atri, as he set the press-stones, serving the Gods with
							praise and adoration,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Established in the heaven the eye of Surya, and caused Svarbhanu's
							magic arts to vanish.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Atris found the Sun again, him whom Svarbhanu of the brood
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of Asuras had pierced with gloom. This none besides had power to do.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 41
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHO, Mitra-Varuna, is your pious servant to give you gifts from earth
							or mighty heaven?
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Preserve us in the seat of holy Order, and give the offerer power that
							winneth cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Mitra, Varuna, Aryaman, and Ayu, Indra Rbhuksan, and the Maruts,
							love us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							And they who of one mind with bounteous Rudra accept the hymn and laud
							with adorations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							You will I call to feed the car-horse, Asvins, with the wind's flight
							swiftest of those who travel:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or also to the Asura of heaven, Worshipful, bring a hymn as 'twere
							libation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The heavenly Victor, he whose priest is Kanva, Trta with Dyaus
							accordant, Vata, Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							All-feeding Pusan, Bhaga sought the oblation, as they whose steeds are
							fleetest seek the contest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring ye your riches forward borne on horses: let thought be framed for
							help and gain of treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blest he the priest of Ausija through courses, the courses which are
							yours the fleet, O Maruts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring hither him who yokes the car, your Vayu, who praises with his
							songs, the God and Singer;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, praying and devout, noble and prudent, may the Gods' Spouses in
							their thoughts retain us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							I speed to you with powers that should be honoured, with songs
							distinguishing Heaven's mighty Daughters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Morning and Night, the Two, as 'twere all-knowing: these bring the
							sacrifice unto the mortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							You I extol, the nourishers of heroes bringing you gifts, Vastospati
							and Tvastar-
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rich Dhisana accords through our obeisance - andTrees and Plants, for
							the swift gain of riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ours be the Parvatas, even they, for offspring, free-moving, who are
							Heroes like the Vasus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May holy Aptya, Friend of man, exalted, strengthen our word for ever
							and be near us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Trta praised him, germ of the earthly hero, with pure songs him the
							Offspring of the Waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agn; with might neighs loudly like a charger: he of the flaming hair
							destroys the forests.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							How shall we speak to the great might of Rudra? How speak to Bhaga who
							takes thought for riches?
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Plants, the Waters, and the Sky preserve us, and Woods and
							Mountains with their trees for tresses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the swift Wanderer, Lord of refreshments listen to our songs, who
							speeds throuih cloudy heaven:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							And may the Waters, bright like castles, hear us, as they flow onward
							from the cloven mountain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							We know your ways, ye Mighty Ones receiving choice meed, ye Wonderful,
							we will proclaim it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even strong birds descend not to the mortal who strives to reach them
							with swift blow and weapons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Celestial and terrestrial generations, and Waters will I summon to the
							feasting.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							May days with bright dawns cause my songs to prosper, and may the
							conquered streams increase their waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Duly to each one hath my laud been offered. Strong be Varutri with her
							powers to succour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the great Mother Rasa here befriend us, straight-handed, with the
							princes, striving forward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							How may we serve the Liberal Ones with worship, the Maruts swift of
							course in invocation, the Maruts far-renowned in invocation?
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not the Dragon of the Deep annoy us, and gladly may he welcome our
							addresses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus thinking, O ye Gods, the mortal wins you to give him increase of
							his herds of cattle: the mortal wins him, O ye Gods, your favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here he wins wholesome food to feed this body: as for mine old age,
							Nirrti consume it
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Gods, may we obtain from you this favour, strengthening food through
							the Cow's praise, ye Vasus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							May she who gives good gifts, the gracious Goddes. s, come speeding
							nigh to us for our well-being.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Ila, Mother of the herds of cattle, and Urvasi with all the streams
							accept us;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Urvasi in lofty heaven accepting, as she partakes the oblation of
							the living,
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Visit us while she shares Urjavya's food.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 42
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now may our sweetest song with deep devotion reach Varuna, Mitra,
							Aditi, and Bhaga.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the Five Priests' Lord, dwelling in oblations, bliss-giving Asura,
							hear, whose paths are open.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Aditi welcome, even as a mother her dear heart-gladdening son, my
							song that lauds her.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The prayer they love, bliss-giving, God-appointed, I offer unto Varuna
							and Mitra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							In spirit him, the Sagest of the Sages; with sacrificial oil and meath
							bedew him
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So then let him, God Savitar, provide us excellent, ready, and
							resplendent treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With willing mind, Indra, vouchsafe us cattle, prosperity, Lord of
							Bays! and pious patrons;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, with the sacred prayer by Gods appointed, give us the holy
							Deities' lovingkindness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							God Bhaga, Savitar who deals forth riches, Indra, and they who conquer
							Vrtra's treasures,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Vaja and Rbhuksan and Purandhi, the Mighty and Immortal Ones,
							protect us!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us declare his deeds, the undecaying unrivalled Victor whom the
							Maruts follow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							None of old times, O Maghavan, nor later, none of these days hath
							reached thy hero prowess.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praise him the Chief who gives the boon of riches, Brhaspati
							distributor of treasures,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, blessing most the man who sings and praises, comes with abundant
							wealth to his invoker.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tended, Brhaspati, with thy protections, the princes are unharmed and
							girt by heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth that brings bliss is found among the givers of horses and of
							cattle and of raiment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Make their wealth flee who, through our hymns enjoying their riches,
							yield us not an ample guerdon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far from the sun keep those who hate devotion, the godless, prospering
							in their vocation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							With wheelless chariots drive down him, O Maruts, who at the feasts of
							Gods regards the demons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, though bathed in sweat, form empty wishes, who blames his
							sacred rite who toils to serve you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praise him whose bow is strong and sure his arrow, him who is Lord of
							every balm that bealeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Worship thou Rudra for his great good favour: adore the Asura, God,
							with salutations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the House-friends, the cunning-handed Artists, may the Steer's
							Wives, the streams carved out by Vibhvan,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							And may the fair Ones honour and befriend us, Sarasvati, Brhaddiva, and
							Raka.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							My newest song, thought that now springs within me, I offer to the
							Great, the Sure Protector,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who made for us this All, in fond love laying each varied form within
							his Daughter's bosom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, even now, may thy fair praise, O Singer, attain Idaspati who roars
							and thunders,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, rich in clouds and waters with his lightning speeds forth bedewing
							both the earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this my laud attain the troop of Maruts, those who are youths in
							act, the Sons of Rudra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							The wish calls me to riches and well-being: praise the unwearied Ones
							whose steeds are dappled.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this my laud reach earth and air's mid-region, and forest trees and
							plants to win me riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							May every Deity be swift to listen, and Mother Earth with no ill
							thought regard me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Gods, may we dwell in free untroubled bliss.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we obtain the Asvins' newest favour, and gain their
							health-bestowing happy guidance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring riches hither unto us, and heroes, and all felicity and joy,
							Immortals!
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 43
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY the Milch-cows who hasten to their object come harmless unto us
							with liquid sweetness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Singer, lauding, calls, for ample riches, the Seven Mighty Ones who
							bring enjoyment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With reverence and fair praise will I bring hither, for sake of
							strength, exhaustless Earth and Heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Father and Mother, sweetof speech, fairhanded, may they, far-famed, in
							every fight protect us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adhvaryus, make the sweet libations ready, and bring the beautiful
							bright juice to Vayu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							God, as our Priest, be thou the first to drink it: we give thee of the
							mead to make thee joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Two arms-the Soma's dexterous immo. lators-and the ten fingers set and
							fix the press-stone.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The stalk hath poured, fair with its spreading branches, the mead's
							bright glittering juice that dwells on mountains.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Soma hath been pressed for thee, its lover, to give thee power and
							might and high enjoyment.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Invoked, turn hither in thy car, O Indra, at need, thy two well-trained
							and dear Bay Horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring by God-traversed paths, accordant, Agni, the great Aramati,
							Celestial Lady,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Exalted, worshipped with our gifts and homage, who knoweth holy Law, to
							drink sweet Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							As on his father's lap the son, the darling, so on the fire is set the
							sacred caldron,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Which holy singers deck, as if extending and heating that which holds
							the fatty membrane.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither, as herald to invite the Asvins, come the great lofty song, most
							sweet and pleasant!
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come in one car, joy-givers! to the banquet, like the bolt binding pole
							and nave, come hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							I have declared this speech of adoration to mightiest Pusan and
							victorious Vayu,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who by their bounty are the hymns' inspirers, and of themselves give
							power as a possession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Invoked by us bring hither, jatavedas the Maruts all under their names
							and figures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come to the sacrifice with aid all Maruts, all to the songs and praises
							of the singer!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							From high heaven may Sarasvati the Holy visit our sacrifice, and from
							the mountain.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eager, propitious, may the balmy Goddess hear our effectual speech, our
							invocation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Set in his seat the God whose back is dusky, Brhaspati the lofty, the
							Disposer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him let us worship, set within the dwelling, the red, the golden-hued,
							the allresplendent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Sustainer, high in heaven, come hither, the Bounteous One,
							invoked, with all his favours,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dweller with Dames divine, with plants, unwearied, the Steer with
							triple horn, the life-bestower.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The tuneful eloquent priests of him who liveth have sought the Mother's
							bright and loftiest station.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							As living men, with offered gifts and homage they deck the most
							auspicious Child to clothe him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, great vital power is thine, the mighty: pairs waxing old in their
							devotion seek thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							May every Deity be swift to listen, and Mother Earth with no ill
							thought regard me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Gods, may we dwell in free untroubled bliss.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we obtain the Asvins' newest favour, and gain their
							health-bestowing happy guidance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring riches hither unto us, and heroes, and all felicity and joy,
							Immortals!
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 44
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As in the first old times, as all were wont, as now, he draweth forth
							the power turned hitherward with song,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Princedom throned on holy grass, who findeth light, swift,
							conquering in the' plants wherein he waxeth strong.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shining to him who leaves heaven's regions undisturbed, which to his
							sheen who is beneath show fair in light,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Good guardian art thou, not to be deceived, Most Wise! Far from deceits
							thy name dwelleth in holy Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Truth waits upon oblation present and to come: naught checks him in his
							way, this vic tory- bringing Priest:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mighty Child who glides along the sacred grass, the undecaying
							Youth set in the midst of plants.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							These come, well-yoked, to you for furtherance in the rite: down come
							the twinborn strengtheners of Law for him,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With reins easily guided and commanding all. In the deep fall the hide
							stealeth away their names.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, moving beauteously in visibly pregnant ones, snatching with trees
							the branching plant that grasps the juice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shinest, true Singer! mid the upholders of the voice. Increase thy
							Consorts thou, lively at sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as he is beheld such is he said to be.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							They with effectual splendour in the floods have made
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							Earth yield us room enough and amply wide extent, great might
							invincible, with store of hero sons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surya the Sage, as if unwedded, with a Spouse, in battle-loving spirit
							moveth o'er the foes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, self-excellent, grant us a sheltering home, a house that wards
							the fierce heat off on every side.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy name, sung forth by Rsis in these hymns of ours, goes to the
							loftier One with this swift mover's light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							By skill he wins the boon whereon his heart is set: he who bestirs
							himself shall bring the thing to pass.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The chief and best of these abideth in the sea, nor doth libation fail
							wherein it is prolonged.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The heart of him who praiseth trembleth not in fear there where the
							hymn is found connected with the pure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							For it is he: with though to of Ksatra, Manasa, of Yajata, and Sadhri,
							and Evavada,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Avatsara's sweet songs will we strive to win the mightiest
							strength which even he who knows should gain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Hawk is their full source, girth-stretching rapturous drink of
							Visvavara, of Mayin, and Yajata.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							They ever seek a fresh draught so that they may come, know when thy
							time to halt and drink thy fill is near.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sadaprna the holy, Tarya, Srutavit, and Bahuvrkta, joined with you,
							have slain the foes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							He gains his wish in both the worlds and brightly shines-when he adores
							the host with well-advancing steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The worshipper's defender is Sutambhara, producer and uplifter of all
							holy thoughts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							The milch-cow brought, sweet-flavoured milk was dealt around. Who
							speaks the bidding text knows this, not he who sleeps.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The sacred hymns love him who wakes and watches: to him who watches
							come the Sama verses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							This Soma saith unto the man who watches, I rest and have my dwelling
							in thy friendship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni is watchful, and the gcas love him; Agni is watchful, Sama verses
							seek him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni is watchful, to him saith this Soma, I rest and have my dwelling
							in thy friendship.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 45
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BARDS of approaching Dawn who know the heavens are come with hymns to
							throw the mountain open.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Sun hath risen and oped the stable portals: the doors of men, too,
							hath the God thrown open.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surya hath spread his light as splendour: hither came the Cows' Mother,
							conscious, from the stable,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							To streams that flow with biting waves to deserts; and heaven is
							stablished like a firm-set pillar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							This laud hath won the burden of the mountain. To aid the ancient birth
							of mighty waters
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The mountain parted, Heaven performed his office. The worshippers were
							worn with constant serving.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With hymns and God-loved words will I invoke you, Indra and Agni, to
							obtain your favour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For verily sages, skilled in sacrificing, worship the Maruts and with
							lauds invite them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							This day approach us: may our thoughts be holy, far from us let us cast
							away misfortune.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us keep those who hate us at a distance, and haste to meet the man
							who sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come, let us carry out, O friends, the purpose wherewith the Mother
							threw the Cow's stall open,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							That wherewith Manu conquered Visisipra, wherewith the wandering
							merchant gained heaven's water.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here, urged by hands, loudly hath rung the press-stone wherewith
							Navagvas through ten months sang praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sarama went aright and found the cattle. Angiras gave effect to all
							their labours.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When at the dawning of this mighty Goddess, Angirases all sang forth
							with the cattle,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Their spring is in the loftiest place of meeting,-Sarama found the kine
							by Order's pathway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Borne by his Coursers Seven may Surya visit the field that spreadeth
							wide for his long journey.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Down on the Soma swooped the rapid Falcon. Bright was the young Sage
							moving mid his cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surya hath mounted to the shining ocean when he hath yoked his
							fair-backed Tawny Horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The wise have drawn him like a ship through water: the floods obedient
							have descended hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							I lay upon the Floods your hymn, lightwinning, wherewith Navagvas their
							ten months completed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through this our hymn may we have Gods to guard us: through this our
							hymn pass safe beyond affliction.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 46
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WELL knowing I have bound me, horselike, to the pole: I carry that
							which bears as on and gives us help.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I seek for no release, no turning back therefrom. May he who knows the
							way, the Leader, guide me straight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, Indra, Varuna, and Mitra, give, O ye Gods, and Marut host, and
							Visnu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May both Nasatyas, Rudra, heavenly Matrons, Pusan, Sarasvati, Bhaga,
							accept us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, Mitra, Varuna, Aditi, the Waters, Mountains, Maruts,
							Sky, and Earth and Heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Visnu I call, Pusan, and Brahmanaspati, and Bhaga, Samsa, Savitar that
							they may help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Visnu also and Vata who injures none, and Soma granter of
							possessions give us joy;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And may the Rbhus and the Asvins, Tvastar and Vibhvan remember us so
							that we may have wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may the band of Maruts dwelling in the sky, the holy, come to us to
							sit on sacred grass;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati and Pusan grant us sure defence, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman guard
							and shelter us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							And may the Mountains famed in noble eulogies, and the fair-gleaming
							Rivers keep us safe from harm.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Bhaga the Dispenser come with power and grace, and far-pervading
							Aditi listen to my call.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Gods' Spouses aid us of their own freewill, aid us to offspring
							and the winning of the spoil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant us protection, O ye gracious Goddesses, ye who are on the earth
							or in the waters' realm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Dames, wives of Gods, enjoy our presents, Rat, Asvini, Agnayi,
							and Indrani.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Rodasi and Varunani hear us, and Goddesses come at the Matrons'
							season.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 47
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							URGING to toil and making proclamation, seeking Heaven's Daughter comes
							the Mighty Mother:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							She comes, the youthful Hymn, unto the Fathers, inviting to her home
							and loudly calling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Swift in their motion, hasting to their duty, reaching the central
							point of life immortal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							On every side about the earth and heaven go forth the spacious paths
							without a limit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Steer, Sea, Red Bird with strong wings, he hath entered the
							dwelling-place of the Primeval Father.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							A gay-hued Stone set in the midst of heaven, he hath gone forth and
							guards mid-air's two limits.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Four bear him up and give him rest and quiet, and ten invigorate the
							Babe for travel.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							His kine most excellent, of threefold nature, pass swiftly round the
							boundaries of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wondrous, O people, is the mystic knowledge that while the waters stand
							the streams are flowing:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							That, separate from his Mother, Two support him, closely-united, twins,
							here made apparent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							For him they lenghten prayers and acts of worship: the Mothers weave
							garments for him their offspring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rejoicing, for the Steer's impregning contact, his Spouses move on
							paths or heaven to meet him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be this our praise, O Varuna and Mitra may this be health and force to
							us, O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we obtain firm ground and room for resting: Glory to Heaven, the
							lofty habitation!
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 48
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHAT may we meditate for the beloved Power, mighty in native strength
							and glorious in itself,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Which as a magic energy seeking waters spreads even to theimmeasurable
							middle region's cloud?
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O'er all the region with their uniform advance these have spread out
							the lore that giveth heroes strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Back, with their course reversed, the others pass away: the pious
							lengthens life with those that are before.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With pressing-stones and with the bright beams of the day he hurls his
							broadest bolt against the Guileful One.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even he whose hundred wander in his own abode, driving the days afar
							and bringing them again.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I, to enjoy the beauty of his form, behold that rapid rush of his as
							'twere an axe's edge,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time he gives the man who calls on him in fight wealth like a
							dwelling-house filled full with store of food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Four-faced and nobly clad, Varuna, urging on the pious to his task,
							stirs himself with the tongue.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Naught by our human nature do we know of him, him from whom Bhaga
							Savitar bestows the boon.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 49
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS day I bring God Savitar to meet you, and Bhaga who allots the
							wealth of mortals.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							You, Asvins, Heroes rich in treasures, daily seeking your friendship
							fain would I turn hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Knowing full well the Asura's time of coming, worship God Savitar with
							hymns and praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him who rightly knoweth speak with homage to him who dealeth out
							man's noblest treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not for reward doth Pusan send his blessings, Bhaga, or Aditi: his garb
							is splendour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Indra, Visniu, Varuna, Mitra, Agni produce auspicious days, the
							Wonder-Workers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sending the shelter which we ask, the foeless Savitar and the Rivers
							shall approach us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When I, the sacrifice's priest, invite them, may we he lords of wealth
							and rich possessions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who devote such worship to the Vasus, singing their hymns to
							Varuna and Mitra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe them ample room, far off be danger. Through grace of Heaven
							and Earth may we be happy.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 50
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET every mortal man elect the friendship of the guiding God.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Each one solicits him for wealth and seeks renown to prosper him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							These, leading God, are thine, and these here ready to speak after us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As such may we attain to wealth and wait with services on thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							So further honour as our guests the Hero Gods and then the Dames.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he remove and keep afar our foes and all who block our path.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where fire is set, and swiftly runs the victim dwelling in the trough,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He wins, with heroes in his home, friendly to man, like constant
							streams.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May these thy riches, Leader God! that rule the car, be blest to us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, blest to us for wealth and weal. This will we ponder praising
							strength, this ponder as we praise the God.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 51
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH all assistants, Agni, come hither to drink the Soma-juice;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Gods unto our sacred gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to the sacrifice, O ye whose ways are right, whose laws are true,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							And drink the draught with Agni's tongue.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Singer, with the singers, O Gracious, with those who move at dawn,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come to the Soma-draught with Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Indra and to Vayu dear, this Soma, by the mortar pressed,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is now poured forth to fill the jar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vayu, come hither to the feast, wellpleased unto our sacred gifts:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink of the Soma juice effused come to the food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, Indra, Vayu, well deserve to drink the juices pressed by us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gladly accept them, spotless Pair come to the food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Indra and for Vayu pressed are Soma juices blent with curd,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							As rivers to the lowland flow: come to the food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Associate with all the Gods, come, with the Asvins and with Dawn,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, as erst with Atri, so enjoy the juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Associate with Varuna, with Mitra, Soma, Visnu, come,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, as erstwith Atri, so enjoy the juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Associate with Vasus, with Adityas, Indra, Viyu, come, Agni as erst with
						Atri, so enjoy the juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Bhaga and the Asvins grant us health and wealth, and Goddess Adid
							and he whom none resist.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Asura Pusan grant us all prosperity, and Heaven and Earth most wise
							vouchsafe us happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us solicit Vayu for prosperity, and Soma who is Lord of all the
							world for weal;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							For weal Brhaspati with all his company. May the Adityas bring us
							health and happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							May all the Gods, may Agni the beneficent, God of all men, this day be
							with us for our weal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Help us the Rbhus, the Divine Ones, for our good. May Rudra bless and
							keep us from calamity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prosper us, Mitra, Varuna. O wealthy Pathya, prosper us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, prosper us; prosper us thou, O Aditi.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like Sun and Moon may we pursue in full prosperity our path,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							And meet with one who gives again, -who knows us well and slays us not.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 52
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING boldly forth, Syavasva, with the Maruts who are loud in song,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, holy, as their wont is, joy in glory that is free from guile.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For in their boldness they are friends of firm and sure heroic
							strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							They in their course, bold-spirited, guard all men of their own accord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
