						Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For this place, Asvins, was of old your dwelling, these were your
							houses, this your habitation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come to us from high heaven and from the mountain. Come from the waters
							bringing food and vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we obtain the Asvins' newest favour, and gain their
							health-bestowing happy guidance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring riches hither unto us, and heroes, and all felicity and joy,
							Immortals!
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 77
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FIRST worship those who come at early morning: let the Twain drink
							before the giftless niggard.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Asvins claim the sacrifice at daybreak: the sages yielding the
							first share extol them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worship at dawn and instigate the Asvins:nor is the worshipper at eve
							rejected.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Besides ourselves another craves and worships: each first in worship is
							most highly favoured.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Covered with gold, meath-tinted, dropping fatness, your chariot with
							its freight of food comes hither,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Swift as thought, Asvins, rapid as the tempest, wherewith ye travel
							over all obstructions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who hath served most often the Nasatyas, and gives the sweetest food
							at distribution,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Furthers with his own holy works his offspring, and ever passes those
							whose flames ascend not.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we obtain the Asvins' newest favour, and gain their
							health-bestowing happy ildance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring riches hither unto us, and heroes, and all felicity and joy,
							Immortals!
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 78
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YE Asvins, hither come to us: Nasatyas, be not disinclined.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fly hither like two swans unto the juice we shed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Asvins, like a pair of deer, like two wild cattle to the mead:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fly hither like two swans unto the juice we shed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Asvins rich in gifts, accept our sacrifice to prosper it:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fly hither like two swans unto the juice we shed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							As Atri when descending to the cavem called on you loudly like a
							wailing woman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye came to him, O Asvins, with the freshest and most auspicious
							fleetness of a falcon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tree, part asunder like the side of her who bringeth forth a child.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Asvins, listen to my call: loose Saptavadhri from his bonds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Saptavadhri, for the seer affrighted when he wept and wafled,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, Asvins, with your magic powers rent up the tree and shattered it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as the wind on every side ruffles a pool of lotuses,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							So stir in thee the babe unborn, so may the ten-month babe descend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as the wind, like as the wood, like as the sea is set astir,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							So also, ten-month babe, descend together with the after-birth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The child who hath for ten months' time been lying in his mother's
							side,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he come forth alive, unharmed, yea, livingfrorn the living dame.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 79
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O HEAVENLY Dawn, awaken us to ample opulence to-day
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as thou hast wakened us with Satyasravas, Vayya's son, high-born!
							delightful with thy steeds!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Daughter of Heaven, thou dawnedst on Sunitha Sucadratha's son,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So dawn thou on one mightier still, on Satyasravas, Vayya's son,
							high-born! delightful with thy steeds!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, bringing treasure, dawn to-day on us thou Daughter of the Sky,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As thou, O mightier yet. didst shine for Satyatravas, Vayya's son,
							high-born! delightful with thy steeds!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here round about thee are the priests who laud thee, Bright One, with
							their hymns,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And men with gifts, O Bounteous Dame, splendid with wealth and offering
							much, high-born! delightful with thy steeds!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whatever these thy bands perform to please thee or to win them wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							E'en fain they gird us round and give rich gifts which ne'er are reft
							away, high-born! delightful with thy steeds!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give to these wealthy patrons fame, O affluent Dawn, with hero sons,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							To these our princes who have brought rich gifts ne'er to be reft away,
							highborn! delightful with thy steeds!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring lofty and resplendent fame, O thou munificent Dawn, to these
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our wealthy patrons who bestow rich gifts on us of steeds and kine,
							high-born! delightful with thy steeds!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring us, O Daughter of the Sky, subsistence in our herds of kine,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Together with the sunbeams, with the shine of pure refulgent flames,
							highborn! delightful with thy steeds!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Daughter of the Sky, shine forth; delay not to perform thy task.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not the Sun with fervent heat consume thee like a robber foe,
							high-born! delightful with the steeds!
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							So much, and more exceedingly, O Dawn, it suits thee to bestow,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou Radiant One who ceasest not to shine for those who sing thy
							praise, highborn! delightful with thy steeds!
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 80
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE singers welcome with their hymns and praises the Goddess Dawn who
							bringeth in the sunlight,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sublime, by Law true to eternal Order, bright on her path, red-tinted,
							far-refulgent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							She comes in front, fair, rousing up the people, making the pathways
							easy to be travelled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							High, on her lofty chariot, all-impelling, Dawn gives her splendour at
							the days' beginning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							She, harnessing her car with purple oxen. injuring none, hath brought
							perpetual riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Opening paths to happiness, the Goddess shines, praised by all, giver
							of every blessing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With changing tints she gleams in double splendour while from the
							eastward she displays her body.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							She travels perfectly the path of Order, nor fails to reach, as one who
							knows, the quarters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As conscious that her limbs are bright with bathing, she stands, as
							'twere, erect that we may see her.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Driving away malignity and darkness, Dawn, Child of Heaven, hath come
							to us with lustre.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Daughter of the Sky, like some chaste woman, bends, opposite to
							men, her forehead downward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Maid, disclosing boons to him who worships, hath brought again the
							daylight as aforetime.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 81
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE priests of him the lofty Priest well-skilled in hymns harness their
							spirit, yea, harness their holy thoughts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He only knowing works assigns their priestly tasks. Yea, lofty is the
							praise of Savitar the God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sapient One arrays himself in every form: for quadruped and biped
							he hath brought forth good.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Excellent Savitar hath looked on heaven's high vault, and shineth after
							the outgoing of the Dawn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even he, the God whose going-forth and majesty the other Deities have
							followed with their might,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who hath measured the terrestrial regions out by his great power, he
							is the Courser Savitar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To the three spheres of light thou goest, Savitar, and with the rays of
							Sidrya thou combinest thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Around, on both sides thou encompassest the night: yea, thou, O God,
							art Mitra through thy righteous laws.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Over all generation thou art Lord alone: Pusan art thou, O God, in all
							thy goings-forth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, thou hast domination over all this world. Syavasva hath brought
							praise to thee, O Savitar,
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 82
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WE crave of Savitar the God this treasure much to be enjoyed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The best, all-yielding, conquering gift of Bhaga we would gladly win.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Savitar's own supremacy, most glorious and beloved of all,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							No one diminisheth in aught.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Savitar who is Bhaga shall send riches to his worshipper.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							That wondrous portion we implore.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send us this day, God Savitar, prosperity with progeny.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drive thou the evil dream away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Savitar, God, send far away all sorrows and calamities,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And send us only what is good.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sinless in sight of Aditi through the God Savitar's influence,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we obtain all lovely things.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							We with our hymns this day elect the general God, Lord of the good,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savitar whose decrees are true.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who for ever vigilant precedes these Twain, the Day and Night,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is Savitar the thoughtful God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who gives glory unto all these living creatures with the song,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							And brings them forth, is Savitar.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 83
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING with these songs thy welcome to the Mighty, with adoration praise
							and call Parjanya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Bull, loud roaring, swift to send his bounty, lays in the plants
							the seed. for germination.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He smites the trees apart, he slays the demons: all life fears him who
							wields the mighty weapon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							From him exceeding strong fices e'en the guiltless, when thundering
							Parjanya smites the wicked.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a car-driver whipping on his horses, he makes the messengers of
							rain spring forward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far off resounds the roaring of the lion, what time Parjanya fills the
							sky with rain-cloud.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forth burst the winds, down come the lightning-flashes: the plants
							shoot up, the realm of light is streaming.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Food springs abundant for all living creatures, what time Parjanya
							quickens earth with moisture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou at whose bidding earth bows low before thee, at whose command
							hoofed cattle fly in terror,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							At whose behest the plants assume all colours, even thou Parjanya,
							yield us great protection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send down for us the rain of heaven, ye Maruts, and let the Stallion's
							flood descend in torrents.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come hither with this thunder while thou pourest the waters down, our
							heavenly Lord and Father.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thunder and roar: the germ of life deposit. Fly round us on thy chariot
							waterladen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thine opened water-skin draw with thee downward, and let the hollows
							and the heights be level.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lift up the mighty vessel, pour down water, and let the liberated
							streams rush forward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Saturate both the earth and heaven with fatness, and for the cows let
							there be drink abundant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou, with thunder and with roar, Parjanya, smitest sinners down,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							This universe exults thereat, yea, all that is upon the earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast poured down the rain-flood now withhold it. Thou hast made
							desert places fit for travel.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast made herbs to grow for our enjoyment: yea, thou hast won thee
							praise from living creatures.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 84
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU, of a truth,O Prthivi, bearest the tool that rends the hills:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou rich in torrents, who with might quickenest earth, O Mighty One.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee, O wanderer at will, ring out the lauds with beams of day,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who drivest, like a neighing steed, the swelling cloud, O bright of
							hue.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who graspest with thy might on earth. e'en the strong sovrans of the
							wood,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When from the lightning of thy cloud the rain-floods of the heaven
							descend.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 85
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING forth a hymn sublime and solemn, grateful to glorious. Varuna,
							imperial Ruler,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who hath struck out, like one who slays the victim, earth as a skin to
							spread in front of Surya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							In the tree-tops the air he hath extended, put milk in kine and
							vigorous speed in horses,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Set intellect in hearts, fire in the waters, Siurya in heaven and Soma
							on the mountain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Varuna lets the big cask, opening downward, flow through the heaven and
							earth and air's mid-region.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therewith the universe's Sovran waters earth as the shower of rain
							bedews the barley.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Varuna is fain for milk he moistens the sky, the land, and earth
							to her foundation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then straight the mountains clothe them in the rain-cloud: the Heroes,
							putting forth their vigour, loose them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will declare this mighty deed of magic, of glorious Varuna the Lord
							Immortal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who standing in the firmament hath meted the earth out with the Sun as
							with a measure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							None, verily, hath ever let or hindered this the most wise God's mighty
							deed of magic,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whereby with all their flood, the lucid rivers fill not one sea wherein
							they pour their waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							If we have sinned against the man who loves us, have ever wronged a
							brother, friend, or comrade,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The neighbour ever with us, or a stranger, O Varuna, remove from us the
							trespass.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							If we, as gamesters cheat at play, have cheated, done wrong unwittingly
							or sinned of purpose,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cast all these sins away like loosened fetters, and, Varuna let us be
							thine own beloved.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 86
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE mortal man whom ye, the Twain, Indra and Agni, help in fight,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Breaks through e'en strongly-guarded wealth as Trta burst his way
							through reeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Twain invincible in war, worthy to be renowned in frays,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lords of the Fivefold. People, these, Indra and Agni, we invoke.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Impetuous is their strength, and keen the lightning of the mighty Pair,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Which from their arms speeds with the car to Vrtra's slayer for the
							kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, we invoke you both, as such, to send your cars:
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lords of quick-coming bounty, ye who know, chief lovers of the song.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							These who give increase day by day, Gods without guile for mortal man,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Worthy themselves, I honour most, Two Gods as partners, for my horse.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The strength-bestowing offering thus to Indra-Agni hath been paid, as
							butter, purified by stones.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Deal to our princes high renown, deal wealth to those who sing your
							praise, deal food to those who sing your praise.
						-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 87
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Visnu, to the Mighty whom the Maruts follow let your hymns born in
							song go forth, Evayamarut;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To the impetuous, strong band, adorned with bracelets, that rushes on
							in joy and ever roars for vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who with might were manifest, and who willingly by their own
							knowledge told it forth, Evayamarut.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Maruts, this strength of yours no wisdom comprehendeth: through their
							gifts' greatness they are moveless as the mountains.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who by the psalm they sing are heard, from lofty heaven, the strong,
							the brightly shining Ones, Evayamarut;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In whose abode there is no mightier one to move them, whose lightnings
							are as fires, who urge the roaring rivers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He of the Mighty Stride forth strode, Evayamarut, out of the spacious
							dwelling-place, their home in common.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When he, himself, hath yoked his emulous strong horses on heights, he
							cometh forth, joy-giving, with the Heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like your tremendous roar, the rainer with light flashing, strong,
							speeding, hath made all tremble, Evayamarut,
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith victorious ye, self-luminous, press onward, with strong
							reins, decked with gold, impetuous and well-weaponed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unbounded is your greatness, ye of mighty power: may your bright vigour
							be our aid, Evayamarut;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For ye are visible helpers in the time of trouble: like fires, aglow
							with light, save us from shame and insult.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may the Rudras, mighty warriors, Evayamarut, with splendid
							brilliancy, like fires, be our protectors;
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They whose terrestrial dwelling-place is wide-extended, whom none
							suspect of sin, whose bands have lofty courage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come in a friendly spirit, come to us, O Maruts, and hear his call who
							praises you, Evayamarut.
						-
					-
						Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like car-borne men, one-minded with the mighty Visnu, keep enmity far
							from us with your deeds of wonder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Come to our sacrifice, ye Hnly Ones, to bless it, and, free from demons,
						hear our call, Evayamarut.
					-
		-
			Mandala 6
		-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 1
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU, first inventor of this prayer, O Agni, Worker of Marvels, hast
							become our Herald.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Bull, hast made us strength which none may conquer, strength that
							shall overcome all other prowess.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As Priest thou sattest at the seat of worship, furthering us, best
							Offerer, meet for honour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So first to thee have pious men resorted, turning thy mind to thoughts
							of ample riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							In thee, still watching, they have followed riches, who goest with much
							wealth as with an army,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The radiant Agni, lofty, fair to look on, worshipped with marrow,
							evermore resplendent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who approached the God's abode with homage, eager for glory, won
							them perfect glory:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, they gained even sacrificial titles, and found delight in thine
							auspicious aspect.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							On earth the people magnify thee greatly, thee their celestial and
							terrestrial riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Helper, must be known as our Preserver, Father and Mother of
							mankind for ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dear priest among mankind, adorable Agni hath seated him, joy-giver,
							skilled in worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us approach thee shining in thy dwelling, kneeling upon our knees,
							with adoration.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Longing for bliss, pure-minded, God-devoted, Agni, we seek thee, such,
							meet to be lauded.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Agni, leddest forth our men to battle, refulgent with the
							heaven's exalted splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sage of mankind, all peoples' Lord and Master, the Bull of men, the
							sender down of blessings,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Still pressing on, promoting, purifying, Agni the Holy One, the Lord of
							riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, the mortal who hath toiled and worshipped, brought thee oblations
							with his kindled fuel,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							And well knows sacrifice with adoration, gains every joy with thee to
							guard and help him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mightily let us worship thee the Mighty, with reverence, Agni! fuel and
							oblations,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							With songs, O Son of Strength, with hymns, with altar: so may we strive
							for thine auspicious favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou who hast covered heaven and earth with splendour and with thy
							glories, glorious and triumphant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Continue thou to shine on us, O Agni, with strength abundant, rich, and
							long enduring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us ever, as man needs, O Vasu, abundant wealth of kine for
							son and offspring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Food noble, plenteous, far from sin and evil, he with us, and fair fame
							to make us happy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							May I obtain much wealth in many places by love of thee and through thy
							grace, King Agni;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							For in thee Bounteous One, in thee the Sovran, Agni, are many boons for
							him who serves thee.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 2
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU, Agni, even as Mitra, hast a princely glory of thine own.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, active Vasu, makest fame increase like full prosperity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For, verily, men pray to thee with sacrifices and with songs.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							To thee the Friendly Courser, seen of all, comes speeding through the
							air.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of one accord men kindle thee Heaven's signal of the sacrifice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, craving bliss, this race of man invites thee to the solemn rite.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the man thrive who travails sore, in prayer, far thee the
							Bountiful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He with the help of lofty Dyaus comes safe through straits of enmity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mortal who with fuel lights thy flame and offers unto thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Supports a house with many a branch, Agni, to live a hundred years.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy bright smoke lifts itself aloft, and far-extended shines in heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For, Purifier! like the Sun thou beamest with thy radiant glow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							For in men's houses thou must be glorified as a well-loved guest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gay like an elder in a fort, claiming protection like a son.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Agni, like an able steed, art urged by wisdom in the wood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art like wind; food, home art thou, like a young horse that runs
							astray.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							E'en things imperishable, thou, O Agni, like a gazing ox,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eatest, when hosts, Eternal One! of thee the Mighty rend the woods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, thou enterest as Priest the home of men who sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of the people, prosper them. Accept the ofrering, Angiras!
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, God with Mitra's might, call hither the favour of the Gods from
							earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring weal from heaven, that men may dwell securely. May we o'ercome
							the foe's malign oppressions, may we o'ercome them, through thy help
							o'ercome them.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 3
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							TRUE, guardian of the Law, thy faithful servant wins ample light and
							dwells in peace, O Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom thou, as Varuna in accord with Mitra, guardest, O God, by
							banishing his trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He hath paid sacrifices, toiled in worship, and offered gifts to
							wealth-increasing Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him the displeasure of the famous moves not, outrage and scorn affect
							not such a mortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bright God, whose look is free from stain like Surya's, thou, swift,
							what time thou earnestly desirest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hast gear to give us. Come with joy at evening, where, Child of Wood,
							thou mayest also tarry.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fierce is his gait and vast his wondrous body: he champeth like a horse
							with bit and bridle,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, darting forth his tongue, as 'twere a hatchet, burning the woods,
							smelteth them like a smelter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Archer-like, fain toshoot, he sets his arrow, and whets his splendour
							like the edge of iron:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The messenger of night with brilliant pathway, like a tree-roosting
							bird of rapid pinion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							In beams of morn he clothes him like the singer, and bright as Mitra
							with his splendour crackles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Red in the night, by day the men's possession: red, he belongs to men
							by day, Immortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like Heaven's when scattering beams his voice was uttered: among the
							plants the radiant Hero shouted,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who with his glow in rapid course came hither to fill both worlds,
							well-wedded Dames, with treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who, with supporting streams and rays that suit him, hath flashed like
							lightning with his native vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like the deft Maker of the band of Maruts, the bright impetuous One
							hath shone refulgent.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 4
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As at man's service of the Gods, Invoker, thou, Son of Strength, dost
							sacrifice and worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							So bring for us to-day all Gods together, bring willingly the willing
							Gods, O Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Agni, radiant Herald of the morning, meet to be known, accept our
							praise with favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dear to all life, mid mortal men Immortal, our guest, awake at dawn, is
							Jatavedas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whose might the very heavens regard with wonder: bright as the Sun he
							clothes himself with lustre.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who sends forth,, Eternal Purifier, hath shattered e'en the ancient
							works of Asna.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art a Singer, Son! our feast-companion: Agni at birth prepared his
							food and pathway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therefore vouchsafe us strength, O Strength-bestower. Win like a King:
							foes trouble not thy dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even he who cats his firm hard food with swiftness,and overtakes the
							nights as Vayu kingdoms.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we o'ercome those who resist thine orders, like a steed casting
							down the flying foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like Surya with his fulgent rays, O Agni, thou overspreadest both the
							worlds with splendour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Decked with bright colour he dispels the darkness, like Ausija, with
							clear flame swifily flying.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							We have elected thee as most delightful for thy beams' glow: hear our
							great laud, O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The best men praise thee as the peer of Indra in strength, mid Gods,
							like Viyu in thy bounty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, Agni, on the tranquil paths of riches come to us for our weal:
							save us from sorrow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant chiefs and bard this boon. May we live happy, with hero children,
							through a hundred winters.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 5
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I INVOCATE your Son of Strength, the Youthful, with hymns, the Youngest
							God, whose speech is guileless;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sage who sends wealth comprising every treasure, bringer of many boons,
							devoid of malice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							At eve and morn thy pious servants bring thee their precious gifts, O
							Priest of many aspects,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							On whom, the Purifier, all things living as on firm. ground their
							happiness have stablished.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou from of old hast dwelt among these people, by mental power the
							charioteer of blessings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hence sendest thou, O sapient Jatavedas, to him who serves thee
							treasures in succession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, whoever secretly attacks us, the neighbour, thou with Mitra's
							might! who harms us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Burn him with thine own Steers for ever youthful, burning with burning
							heat, thou fiercest burner.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who serves thee with sacrifice and fuel, with hymn, O Son of
							Strength, and chanted praises,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shines out, Immortal! in the midst of mortals, a sage, with wealth,
							with splendour and with glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do this, O Agni, when we urge thee, quickly, triumphant in thy might
							subdue our foemen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou art praised with words and decked with brightness, accept
							this chanted hymn, the singer's worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Help us, that we may gain this wish, O Agni, gain riches, Wealthy One!
							with store of heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Desiring strength from thee may we be strengthened, and win, Eternal!
							thine eternal glory.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 6
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HE who seeks furtherance and grace to help him goes to the Son of
							Strength with newest worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Calling the heavenly Priest to share the banquet, who rends the wood,
							bright, with his blackened pathway.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							White-hued and thundering he dwells in splendour, Most Youthful, with
							the loudvoiced and eternal-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, most variform, the Purifier, who follows crunching many ample
							forests.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Incited by the wind thy flames, O Agni, move onward, Pure One! pure, in
							all directions.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy most destructive heavenly Navagvas break the woods down and
							devastate them boldly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy pure white horses from their bonds are loosened: O Radiant One,
							they shear the ground beneath them,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And far and wide shines out thy flame, and flickers rapidly moving over
							earth's high ridges.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forth darts the Bull's tongue like the sharp stone weapon discharged by
							him who fights to win the cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni's fierce flame is like a hero's onset: dread and resistless he
							destroys the forests.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou with the sunlight of the great Impeller hast boldly over-spread
							the earth's expanses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							So drive away with conquering might all perils. fighting out foemen
							burn up those who harm us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wondrous! of wondrous power! give to the singer wealth wondrous,
							marked, most wonderful, life-giving.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth bright, O Bright One, vast, with many heroes, give with thy
							bright flames to the man who lauds thee.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 7
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, messenger of earth and head of heaven, Agni Vaisvanara, born in
							holy Order,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Sage, the King, the guest of men, a vessel fit for their mouths,
							the Gods have generated.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him have they praised, mid-point of sacrifices, great cistern of
							libations, seat of riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara, conveyer of oblations, ensign of worship, have the Gods
							engendered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							From thee, O Agni, springs the mighty singer, from thee come heroes who
							subdue the foeman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							O King, Vaisvanara, bestow thou on us excellent treasures worthy to
							belonged fo r.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee, Immortal! when to life thou springest, all the Gods sing for
							joy as to their infant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They by thy mental powers were made immortal, Vaisvanara, when thou
							shonest from thy Parents.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni Vaisvanara, no one hath ever resisted these thy mighty ordinances,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou, arising from thy Parents' bosom, foundest the light for
							days' appointed courses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The summits of the heaven are traversed through and through by the
							Immortal's light, Vaisvanara's brilliancy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							All creatures in existence rest upon his head. The Seven swift-flowing
							Streams have grown like branches forth,
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara, who measured out the realms of air, Sage very wise who made
							the lucid spheres of heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Undeceivable who spread out all the worlds, keeper is he and guard
							of immortality.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 8
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AT Jatavedas' holy gathering I will tell aloud the conquering might of
							the swift red-hued Steer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							A pure and fresher hymn flows to Vaisvanara, even as for Agni lovely
							Soma is made pure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Agni, when in loftiest heaven he sprang to life, Guardian of Holy
							Laws, kept and observed them well.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Exceeding wise, he measured out the firmament. Vaisvanara attained to
							heaven by mightiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wonderful Mitra propped the heaven and earth apart, and covered and
							concealed
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							the darkness with his light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 3: Line 3
					-
						-
							He made the two bowls part asunder like two skins. Vaisvanara put forth
							all his creative power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Migbty seized him in the bosom of the floods: the people waited on
							the King who should be praised.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As envoy of Vivasvan MatariSvan brought Agni Vaisvanara hither from far
							away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							In every age bestow upon the singers wealth, worthy of holy synods,
							glorious, ever new.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							King, undecaying, as it were with sharpened bolt, smite down the sinner
							like a tree with lightning-flash.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do thou bestow, O Agni, on our wealthy chiefs, rule, with good heroes,
							undecaying, bending not.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may we win for us strength. O Vaisvanara, hundredfold, thousandfold,
							O Agni, by thy help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O thou who dwellest in three places, Helper, keep with effective guards
							our princely patrons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Keep our band, Agni, who have brought thee presents. Lengthen their
							lives, Vaisvanara, when lauded.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 9
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ONE half of day is dark, and bright the other: both atmospheres move on
							by sage devices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni Vaisvanara, when born as Sovran, hath with his lustre overcome the
							darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I know not either warp or woof, I know not the web they weave when
							moving to the contest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose son shall here speak words that must be spoken without assistance
							from the Father near him?
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For both the warp and woof he understandeth, and in due time shall
							speak what should be spoken,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who knoweth as the immortal world's Protector, descending, seeing with
							no aid from other.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He is the Priest, the first of all: behold him. Mid mortal men he is
							the light immortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here was he born, firm-seated in his station Immortal, ever waxing in
							his body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							A firm light hath been set for men to look on: among all things that
							fly the mind is swiftest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							All Gods of one accord, with one intention, move unobstructed to a
							single purpose.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mine ears unclose to hear, mine eye to see him; the light that harbours
							in my spirit broadens.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far roams my mind whose thoughts are in the distance. What shall I
							speak, what shall I now imagine?
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							All the Gods bowed them down in fear before thee, Agni, when thou wast
							dwelling in the darkness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara be gracious to assist us, may the Immortal favour us and
							help us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 10
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							INSTALL at sacrifice, while the rite advances, your pleasant, heavenly
							Agni, meet for praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With hymns-for he illumines us-install him. He, Jatavedas, makes our
							rites successful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear this laud, Radiant Priest of many aspects, O Agni with the fires
							of man enkindled,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Laud which bards send forth pure as sacred butter, strength to this
							man, as 'twere for self-advantage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mid mortal men that singer thrives in glory who offers gifts with hymns
							of praise to Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And the God, wondrous bright, with wondrous succours helps him to win a
							stable filled with cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, at his birth, whose path is black behind him, filled heaven and
							earth with far-apparent splendour:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And he himself hath been. through night's thick darkness, made manifest
							by light, the Purifier.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With thy most mighty aid, confer, O Agni, wonderful wealth on us and on
							our princes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who stand preeminent, surpassing others in liberal gifts, in fame, and
							hero virtues.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, accept this sacrifice with gladness, which, seated here, the
							worshipper presenteth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fair hymns hadst thou among the Bharadvajas, and holpest them to gain
							abundant vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Scatter our foes, increase our store. May we he glad a hundred winters with
						brave sons.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 11
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							EAGERLY Sacrifice thou, most skilful, Agni! Priest, pressing on as if
							the Maruts sent thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To our oblation bring the two Nasatyas, Mitra and Varuna and Earth and
							Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art our guileless, most delightful Herald, the God, among mankind,
							of holy synods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							A Priest with purifying tongue, O Agni, sacrifice with thy mouth to
							thine own body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For even the blessed longing that is in thee would bring the Gods down
							to the singer's worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the Angirases' sagest Sage, the Poet, sings the sweet measure at
							the solemn service.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bright hath he beamed, the wise, the far-refulgent. Worship the two
							widespreading Worlds, O Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom as the Living One rich in oblations the Five Tribes, bringing
							gifts, adorn with homage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When I with reverence clip the grass for Agni, when the trimmed ladle,
							fullof oil, is lifted,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Firm on the seat of earth is based the altar: eye-like, the sacrifice
							is directed Sun-ward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Enrich us, O thou Priest of many aspects, with the Gods, Agni, with thy
							fires, enkindled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Son of Strength, clad in the robe of riches, may we escape from woe
							as from
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							a prison.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 12
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							KING of trimmed grass, Herald within the dwelling, may Agni worship the
							Impeller's World-halves.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, Son of Strength, the Holy, from a distance hath spread himself
							abroad with light like Surya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							In thee, most wise, shall Dyaus, for full perfection, King! Holy One!
							pronounce the call to worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Found in three places, like the Speeder's footstep, come to present
							men's riches as oblations!
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whose blaze most splendid, sovran in the forest, shines waxing on his
							way like the - Impeller.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He knows himself, like as a guileless smelter, not to be stayed among
							the plants, Immortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Our friends extol him like a steed for vigour even Agni in the
							dwelling, jatave~as.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Trce-fed, he fights with power as doth a champion, like Dawn's Sire to
							be praised with sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men wonder at his shining glows when, paring the woods with case, o'er
							the broad earth he goeth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, like a rushing flood, loosed quickly, burneth, swift as a guilty
							thief, o'er desert places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							So mighty thou protectest us from slander, O Champion, Agni! with all
							fires enkindled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring opulence and drive away affliction. May brave sons gladden us
							through a hundred winters.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 13
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FROM thee, as branches from a tree, O Agni, from thee, Auspicious God!
							spring all our blessings-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth swiftly, strength in battle with our foemen, the rain besought
							of heaven, the flow of waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art our Bhaga to send wealth thou dwellest, like circumambient
							air, with wondrous splendour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Friend art thou of the lofty Law, like Mitra, Controller, Agni! God! of
							many a blessing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni! the hero slays with might his foeman; the singer bears away the
							Pani's booty-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even he whom thou, Sage, born in Law, incitest by wealth, accordant
							with the Child of Waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The man who, Son of Strength 1 with sacrifices, hymns, lauds, attracts
							thy fervour to the altar,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enjoys each precious thing, O God, O Agni, gains wealth of corn and is
							the lord of treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grant, Son of Strength, to men for their subsistence such things as
							bring high fame and hero children.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thou with might givest much food in cattle even to the wicked wolf
							when he is hungry.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eloquent, Son of Strength, Most Mighty, Agni, vouchsafe us seed and
							offspring, full of vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May I by all my songs obtain abundance. May brave sons gladden us
							through a hundred winters.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 14
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHOSO to Agni hath endeared his thought and service by his hymns,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That mortal cats before the rest, and finds sufficiency of food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, in truth, is passing wise, most skilled in ordering, a Seer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							At sacrifices Manus' sons glorify Agni as their Priest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The foeman's wealth in many a place, Agni, is emulous to help.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men fight the fiend, and seek by rites to overcome the riteless foe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni bestows the hero chief, winner of waters, firm in fray.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Soon as they look upon his might his enemies tremble in alarm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							For with his wisdom Agni, God, protects the mortal from reproach,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose conquering wealth is never checked, is never checked in deeds of
							might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, God with Mitra's might call hither the favour of the Gods from
							earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring weal from heaven that men may dwell securely. May we o'ercome the
							foe's malign oppressions, may we o'ercome them, through thy help
							o'ercome them.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 15
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH this my song I strive to reach this guest of yours, who wakes at
							early morn, the Lord of all the tribes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Each time he comes from heaven, the Pure One from of old: from ancient
							days the Child cats everlasting food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whom, well-dis sed, the Blirgus stablished as a rriend, whom men must
							glorify, high-flaming in the wood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As such, most friendly, thou art every day extolled in lauds by
							Vitahavya, O thou wondrous God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be thou the foeless helper of the skilful man, subduer of the enemy
							near or far away.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bestow a wealthy home on men, O Son of Strength. Give Vitahavya riches
							spreading far and wide, give Bharadvaja wide-spread wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, your refulgent guest, Agni who comes from heaven, the Herald of
							mankind, well-skilled in sacred rites,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, like a holy singer, utters heavenly words, oblation-bearer, envoy,
							God, I seek with hymns.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who with his purifying, eye-attracting form hath shone upon the earth
							as with the light of Dawn;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who speeding on, as in the fight of Etaia, cometh, untouched by age, as
							one athirst in heat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worship ye Agni, Agni, with your log of wood; praise your beloved, your
							beloved guest with songs.
