						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 43
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 43: Line 1
					-
						-
							Harness, O Agni, O thou God, thy steeds which are most excellent:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 43: Line 2
					-
						-
							They bear thee as thy spirit wills.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 44
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 44: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come hither, bring the Gods to us to taste the sacrificial feast,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 44: Line 2
					-
						-
							To drink the draught of Soma juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 45
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 45: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni of the Bharatas, blaze high with everlasting might,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 45: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shine forth and gleam, Eternal One.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 46
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 46: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mortal man who serves the God with banquet, and, bringing gifts at
							sacrifice, lauds Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 46: Line 2
					-
						-
							May well attract, with prayer and hands uplifted, the Priest of Heaven
							and Earth, true Sacrificer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 47
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 47: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, we bring thee, with our hymn, oblation fashioned in the heart.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 47: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let these be oxen unto thee, let these be bulls and kine to thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 48
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 48: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Gods enkindle Agni, best slayer of Vrtra, first in rank,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 16: Verse 48: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mighty, One who brings us wealth and crushes down the Raksasas.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 17
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							DRINK Soma, Mighty One, for which, when lauded, thou breakest through
							the cattle-stall, O Indra;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou who, O Bold One, armed with thunder smotest Vrtra with might, and
							every hostile being.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drink it thou God who art impetuous victor, Lord of our hymns, with
							beauteousjaws, the Hero,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Render of kine-stalls, car-borne, thunder-wielding, so pierce thy way
							to wondrous strength, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drink as of old, and let the draught delight thee. hear thou our prayer
							and let our songs exalt thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make the Sun visible, make food abundant, slaughter the foes, pierce
							through and free the cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							These gladdening drops, O Indra, Self-sustainer, quaffed shall augment
							thee in thy mighty splendour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, let the cheering drops delight thee greatly, great, perfect,
							strong, powerful, all-subduing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gladdened whereby, bursting the firm enclosures, thou gavest splendour
							to the Sun and Morning.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The mighty rock that compassed in the cattle, ne'er moved, thou
							shookest from its seat, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou with thy wisdom, power, and works of wonder, hast stored the ripe
							milk in the raw cows' udders
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unbarred the firm doors for the kine of Morning, and, with the
							Angirases, set free the cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast spread out wide earth, a mighty marvel, and, high thyself,
							propped lofty heaven, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Both worlds, whose Sons are Gods, thou hast supported, young, Mothers
							from old time ofholy Order.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, Indra, all the Deities installed thee their one strong Champion in
							the van for battle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time the godless was the Gods' assailant, Indra they chose to win
							the light of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, e'en that heaven itself of old bent backward before thy bolt, in
							terror of its anger,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Indra, life of every living creature, smote down within his lair
							the assailing Dragon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, Strong One! Tvastar turned for thee, the Mighty, the bolt with
							thousand spikes and hundred edges,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eager and prompt at will, wherewith thou crushedst the boasting Dragon,
							O impetuous Hero.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							He dressed a hundred buffaloes, O Indra, for thee whom all accordant
							Maruts strengthen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, Pusan Visnu, poured forth three great vessels to him, the juice
							that cheers, that slaughters Vrtra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou settest free the rushing wave of waters, the floods' great swell
							encompassed and obstructed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Along steep slopes their course thou tumedst, Indra, directed downward,
							speeding to the ocean.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may our new prayer bring thee to protect us, thee well-armed Hero
							with thy bolt of thunder,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, who made these worlds, the Strong, the ty, who never groweth
							old, the victory-giver.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, Indra, form us brilliant holy singers for strength, for glory, and
							for food and riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give Bharadvaja hero patrons, Indra Indra, be ours upon the day of
							trial.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 17: Verse 15
				-
					-
						With this may we obtain strength God-appointed, and brave sons gladden us
						through a hundred winters.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 18
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GLORIFY him whose might is all-surpassing, Indra the much-invoked who
							fights uninjured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Magnify with these songs the never-vanquished, the Strong, the Bull of
							men, the Mighty Victor.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, Champion, Hero, Warrior, Lord of battles, impetuous, loudly
							roaring, great destroyer,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who whirls the dust on high, alone, oerthrower, hath made all races of
							mankind his subjects.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, thou alone, hast tamed the Dasyus; singly thou hast subdued the
							people for the Arya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In this, or is it not, thine hero exploit, Indra? Declare it at the
							proper season.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For true, I deem, thy strength is, thine the Mighty, thine, O Most
							Potent, thine the Conquering Victor;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strong, of the strong, Most Mighty, of the mighty, thine, driver of the
							churl to acts of bounty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be this our ancient bond of friendship with you and with Angirases here
							who speak of Vala.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Wondrous, Shaker of things firm, didst smite him in his fresh
							strength, and force his doors and castles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							With holy thoughts must he be called, the Mighty, showing his power in
							the great fight with Vrtra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He must be called to give us seed and offspring, the Thunderer must he
							moved and sped to battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He in his might, with name that lives for ever, hath far surpassed all
							human generations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, most heroic, hath his home with splendour, with glory and with
							riches and with valour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stranger to guile, who ne'er was false or faithless, bearing a name
							that may be well remembered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra crushed Cumuri, Dhuni, Sambara, Pipru, and Susna, that their
							castles fell in ruin.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							With saving might that must be praised and lauded, Indra, ascend thy
							car to smite down Vrtra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							In thy right hand hold fast thy bolt of thunder, and weaken, Bounteous
							Lord, his art and magic.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							As Agni, as the dart burns the dry forest, like the dread shaft burn
							down the fiends, O Indra;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou who with high deep-reaching spear hast broken, hast covered over
							mischief and destroyed it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							With wealth, by thousand paths come hither, Agni, paths that bring
							ample strength, O thou Most Splendid.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come, Son of Strength, o'er whom, Invoked of many! the godless hath no
							power to keep thee distant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							From heaven, from earth is bruited forth the greatness of him the firm,
							the fiery, the resplendent.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							No foe hath he, no counterpart, no refuge is there from him the
							Conqueror full of wisdom
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							This day the deed that thou hast done is famous, when thou, for him,
							with many thousand others
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Laidest low Kutsa, Ayu, Atithigva, and boldly didst deliver Turvayana.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							In thee, O God, the wisest of the Sages, all Gods were joyful when thou
							slewest Ahi.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							When lauded for thyself, thou gavest freedom to sore-afflicted Heaven
							and to the people.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							This power of thine both heaven and earth acknowledge, the deathless
							Gods acknowledge it, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 18: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Do what thou ne'er hast done, O Mighty Worker: beget a new hymn at thy
							sacrifices.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 19
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GREAT, hero-like controlling men is Indra, unwasting in his powers,
							doubled in vastness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, turned to us, hath grown to hero vigour: broad, wide, he hath been
							decked by those who serve him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The bowl made Indra swift to gather booty, the High, the Lofty,
							Youthful, Undecaying,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who hath waxed by strength which none may conquer, and even at once
							grown to complete perfection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stretch out those hands of thine, extend to us-ward thy wide capacious
							arms, and grant us glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like as the household herdsman guards the cattle, so move thou round
							about us in the combat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, fain for strength, let us invite your Indra hither, who lieth
							hidden with his Heroes,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Free from all blame, without reproach, uninjured, e'en as were those
							who sang, of old, his praises.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With steadfast laws, wealth-giver, strong through Soma, he hath much
							fair and precious food to feed us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							In him unite all paths that lead to riches, like rivers that commingle
							with the ocean.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring unto us the mightiest might, O Hero, strong and most potent
							force, thou great Subduer!
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							All splendid vigorous powers of men vouchsafe us, Lord of Bay Steeds,
							that they may make us joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring us, grown mighty in its strength, O Indra, thy friendly rapturous
							joy that wins the battle,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith by thee assisted and triumphant, we may laud thee in gaining
							seed and offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, bestow on us the power heroic skilled and exceeding strong, that
							wins the booty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith, by thine assistance, we may conquer our foes in battle, be
							they kin or stranger.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let thine heroic strength come from behind us, before us, from above us
							or below us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							From every side may it approach us, Indra. Give us the glory of the
							realm of splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							With most heroic aid from thee, like heroes Indra, may we win wealth by
							deeds glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, King, art Lord of earthly, heavenly treasure: vouchsafe us riches
							vast, sublime, and lasting.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Bull, whose strength hath waxed, whom Maruts follow, free-giving
							Indra, the Celestial Ruler,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mighty, all-conquering, the victory-giver, him let us call to grant us
							new protection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give up the people who are high and haughty to these men and to me, O
							Thunder-wielder!
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therefore upon the earth do we invoke thee, where heroes win, for sons
							and kine and waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through these thy friendships, God invoked of many! may we be victors
							over every foeman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 19: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slaying both kinds of foe, may we, O Hero, be happy, helped by thee,
							with ample riches.
						-
