							o'ercomes our foes in battle
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth that brings thousands and that wins the corn-lands, wealth, Son
							of Strength! that vanquishes the foeman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as the power of Dyaus, to thee, O Indra, all Asura sway was by the
							Gods entrusted,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou, Impetuous! leagued with Visnu, slewest Vrtra the Dragon who
							enclosed the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, Strong, Victor, Mightier than the mighty, addressed with prayer
							and perfect in his splendour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of the bolt that breaketh forts in pieces, became the King of the
							sweet juice of Soma..
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							There, Indra, while the light was won, the Panis f1ed, 'neath a hundred
							blows, for wise Dasoni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And greedy Susna's magical devices nor left he any of their food
							remaining.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the thunder fell and Susna perished, all life's support from
							the great Druh was taken.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra made room for his car-drivcr Kutsa who sate beside him, when he
							gained the sunlight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the Hawk rent for him the stalk that gladdens, he wrenched the head
							from Namuci the Dasa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He guarded Nam, Sayya's son, in slumber, and sated him with food,
							success, and riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, thunder-armed, with thy great might hast shattered Pipru's strong
							forts who knew the wiles of serpents.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou gavest to thy worshipper Rjisvan imperishable Wealth, O Bounteous
							Giver.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The crafty Vetasu, the swift Dasni, and Tugra speedily with all his
							servants,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hath Indra, gladdening with strong assistance, forced near as 'twere to
							glorify the Mother.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Resistless, with the hosts he battles, bearing in both his arms the
							Vrtra-slaying thunder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He mounts his Bays, as the car-seat an archer: yoked at a word they
							bear the lofty Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we, O Indra, gain by thy new favour: so Parus laud thee, with their
							sacrifices,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							That thou hast wrecked seven autumn forts, their shelter, slain Dasa
							tribes and aided Purukutsa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Favouring Usana the son of Kavi, thou wast his ancient strengthener, O
							Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou gavest Navavastva. as a present, to the great father gavest back
							his grandson.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, roaring Indra, drovest on the waters that made a roaring sound
							like rushing rivers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time, O Hero, o'er the sea thou broughtest, in safety broughtest
							Turvasa and Yadu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Indra, was thy work in war: thou sentest Dhuni and Cumuri to sleep
							and slumber.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 20: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dabhiti lit the flame for thee, and worshipped with fuel, hymns, poured
							Soma, dressed oblations.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 21
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE the most constant singer's invocations call thee who art to be
							invoked, O Hero;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hymns call anew the chariot-borne, Eternal: by eloquence men gain
							abundant riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I praise that Indra, known to all men, honoured with songs, extolled
							with hymns at sacrifices,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose majesty, rich in wondrous arts, surpasseth the magnitude of
							earth, and heaven in greatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He hath made pathways, with the Sun to aid him, throughout the darkness
							that extended pathless.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mortals who yearn to worship ne'er dishonour, O Mighty God, thy Law who
							art Immortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							And he who did these things, where is that Indra? among what tribes?
							what people doth he visit?
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							What sacrifice contents thy mind , and wishes? What priest among them
							all? what hymn, O Indra?
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, here were they who, born of old, have served thee, thy friends of
							ancient time, thou active Worker.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bethink thee now of these, Invoked of many! the midmost and the recent,
							and the youngest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Inquiring after him, thy later servants, Indra, have gained thy former
							old traditions.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hero, to whom the prayer is brought, we praise thee as great for that
							wherein we know thee mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The demon's strength is gathered fast against thee: great as that
							strength hath grown, go forth to meet it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thine own ancient friend and companion, the thunderbolt, brave
							Champion! drive it backward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear, too, the prayer of this thy present beadsman, O Indra, Hero,
							cherishing the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thou wast aye our fathers' Friend aforetime, still swift to listen
							to their supplication.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring to our help this day, for our protection, Varuna, Mitra , Indra,
							and the Maruts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pusan and Visnu, Agni and Purandhi, Savitar also, and the Plants and
							Mountains.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							The singers here exalt with hymns and praises thee who art very Mighty
							and Most Holy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hear, when invoked, the invoker's invocation. Beside thee there is
							nonelike thee, Immortal!
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now to my words come quickly thou who knowest, O Son of Strength, with
							all who claim our worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who visit sacred rites, whose tongue is Agni, Gods who made Manu
							stronger than the Dasyu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							On good and evil ways be thou our Leader, thou who art known to all as
							Path-preparer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 21: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring power to us, O Indra, with thy Horses, Steeds that are best to
							draw, broad-backed, unwearied.
						-
