					Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tell thou us this, if at thy hand aforetime the earlier singers have
							obtained good fortune,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							What is thy share and portion, Strong Subduer, Asura-slayer, rich,
							invoked of many?
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who for car-borne Indra, armed with thunder, hath a hymn, craving,
							deeply-piercing, fluent,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who sends a song effectual, firmly-grasping, and strength-bestowing, he
							comes near the mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong of thyself, thou by this art hast shattered, with thought-swift
							Parvata, him who waxed against thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, Mightiest! roaring! boldly rent in pieces things that were firmly
							fixed and never shaken.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him will we fit for you with new devotion, the strongest Ancient One,
							in ancient manner.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may that Indra, boundless, faithful Leader, conduct us o'er all
							places hard to traverse.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou for the people who oppress hast kindled the earthly firmament and
							that of heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With heat, O Bull, on every side consume them: heat earth and flood for
							him who hates devotion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of all the Heavenly Folk, of earthly creatures thou art the King, O God
							of splendid aspect.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							In thy right hand, O Indra, grasp die thunder: Eternal! thou destroyest
							all enchantments.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us confirmed prosperity, O Indra, vast and exhaustless for the
							foe's subduing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strengthen therewith the Arya's hate and Dasa's, and let the arms of
							Nahusas be mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come with thy team which brings all blessings hither, Disposer,
							much-invoked, exceeding holy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 22: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou whom no fiend, no God can stay or hinder, come swittly with these
							Steeds in my direction.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 23
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU art attached to pressed-out Soma, Indra, at laud, at prayer, and
							when the hymn is chanted;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or when with yoked Bays, Maghavan, thou comest, O Indra, bearing in
							thine arms the thunder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Or when on that decisive day thou holpest the presser of the juice at
							Vrtra's slaughter;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or when thou, while the strong one feared, undaunted, gavest to death,
							Indra, the daring Dasyus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let Indra drink the pressed-out Soma, Helper and mighty Guide of him
							who sings his praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He gives the hero room who pours oblations, and treasure even to the
							lowly singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							E'en humble rites with his Bay steeds he visits: he wields the bolt,
							drinks Soma, gives us cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He makes the valiant rich in store of heroes, accepts our praise and
							hears the singer's calling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							What he hath longed for we have brought to Indra, who from the days of
							old hath done us service.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							While Soma flows we will sing hymn, and laud him, so that our prayer
							may streng. then Indra's vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast made prayer the means of thine exalting, therefore we wait on
							thee with hymns, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we, by the pressed Soma, Somadrinker! bring thee, with sacrifice,
							blissful sweet refreshment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mark well our sacrificial cake, delighted Indra, drink Soma and the
							milk commingled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here on the sacrificer's grass be seated: give ample room to thy
							devoted servant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Mighty One, be joyful as thou willest. Let these our sacrifices reach
							and find thee;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							And may this hymn and these our invocations turn thee, whom many men
							invoke, to help us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Friends, when thejuices flow, replenish duly your own, your bounteous
							Indra with the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Will it not aid him to support us? Indra. spares him who sheds the
							juice to win his favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							While Soma flowed, thus Indra hath been lauded, Ruler of nobles, mid
							the Bharadvajas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 23: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							That Indra may become the singer's patron and give him wealth in every
							kind of treasure.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 24
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							STRONG rapturous joy, praise, glory are with Indra: impetuous God, he
							quaffs the juice of Soma:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That Maghavan whom men must laud with singing, Heaven-dweller, King of
							songs, whose help is lasting.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, Friend of man, most wise, victorious Hero, hears, with far-reaching
							aid, the singer call him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Excellent, Praise of Men, the bard's Supporter, Strong, he gives
							strength, extolled in holy synod.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The lofty axle of thy wheels, O Hero, is not surpassed by heaven and
							earth in greatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like branches of a tree, Invoked of many manifold aids spring forth
							from thee, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong Lord, thine energies, endowed with vigour, are like the paths of
							kine converging homeward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like bonds of cord, Indra, that bind the younglings, no bonds are they,
							O thou of boundless bounty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							One act to-day, another act tomorrow oft Indra makes what is not yet
							existeni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here have we Mitra, Varuna, and Pusan to overcome the foeman's
							domination.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							By song and sacrifice men brought the waters from thee, as from a
							mountain's ridge, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Urging thy might, with these fair lauds they seek thee, O theme of
							song, as horses rush tobattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Indra whom nor months nor autumn seasons wither with age, nor
							fleeting days enfeeble,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Still may his body Wax, e'en now so mighty, glorified by the lauds and
							hymns that praise him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Extolled, he bends not to the strong, the steadfast, nor to the bold
							incited by the Dasyu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							High mountains are as level plains to Indra: even in the deep he finds
							firm ground to rest on.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Impetuous Speeder through all depth and distance, give strengthening
							food, thou drinker of the juices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Stand up erect to help us, unreluctant, what time the gloom of night
							brightens to morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hasting to help, come hither and protect him, keep him from harm when
							he is here, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 24: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							At home, abroad, from injury preserve him. May brave sons gladden us
							through a hundred winters.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 25
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH thine assistance, O thou Mighty Indra, be it the least, the
							midmost, or the highest,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Great with those aids and by these powers support us, Strong God! in
							battle that subdues our foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With these discomfit hosts that fight against us, and check the
							opponent's wrath, thyself uninjured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With these chase all our foes to every quarter: subdue the tribes of
							Dasas to the Arya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those who array themselves as foes to smite us, O Indra, be they kin or
							be they strangers,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strike thou their manly strength that it be feeble, and drive in
							headlong flight our foemen backward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With strength of limb the hero slays the hero, when bright in arms they
							range them for the combat.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When two opposing hosts contend in battle for seed and offspring,
							waters, kine, or corn-lands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yet no strong man hath conquered thee, no hero, no brave, no warrior
							trusting in his valour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not one of these is match for thee, O Indra. Thou far surpassest all
							these living creatures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							He is the Lord of both these armies' valour when the commanders call
							them to the conflict:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When with their ranks expanded they are fighting with a great foe or
							for a home with heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							And when the people stir themselves for battle, be thou their saviour,
							Indra, and protector,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And theirs, thy manliest of our friends, the pious, the chiefs who have
							installed us priests, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee for high dominion hath been for evermore, for slaughtering the
							Vrtras,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							All lordly power and might, O Holy Indra, given by Gods for victory in
							battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							So urge our hosts together in the combats: yield up the godless bands
							that fight against us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 25: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Singing, at morn may we find thee with favour, yea, Indra, and e'en
							now, we Bharadvajas.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 26
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O INDRA, hear us. Raining down the Soma, we call on thee to win us
							mighty valour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us strong succour on the day of trial, when the tribes gather on
							the field of battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The warrior, son of warrior sire, invokes thee, to gain great strength
							that may be won as booty:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							To thee, the brave man's Lord, the fiends' subduer, he looks when
							fighting hand to hand for cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou didst impel the sage to win the daylight, didst ruin Susna for the
							pious Kutsa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The invulnerable demon's head thou clavest when thou wouldst win the
							praise of Atithigva.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The lofty battle-car thou broughtest forward; thou holpest Dasadyu the
							strong when fighting.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Along with Vetasu thou slewest Tugra, and madest Tuji strong, who
							praised thee, Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou madest good the laud, what time thou rentest a hundred thousand
							fighting foes, O Hero,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slewest the Dasa Sambara of the mountain, and with strange aids didst
							succour Divodasa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Made glad with Soma-draughts and faith, thou sentest Cumuri to his
							sleep, to please Dabhiti.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, kindly giving Raji to Pithinas, slewest with might, at once, the
							sixty thousand.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May I too, with the liberal chiefs, O Indra, acquire thy blin supreme
							and domination,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, Mightiest! Hero-girt! Nahusa heroes boast them in thee, the
							triply-strong Defender.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may we he thy friends, thy best beloved, O Indra, at this holy
							invocation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 26: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best be Pratardani, illustrious ruler, in slaying foemen and in gaining
							riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 27
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHAT deed hath Indra done in the wild transport, in quaffing or in
							friendship with, the Soma?
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							What joys have men of ancient times or recent obtained within the
							chamber of libation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							In its wild joy Indra hath proved him faithful, faithful in quaffing,
							faithful in its friendship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							His truth is the delight that in this chamber the men of old and recent
							times have tasted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							All thy vast power, O Maghavan, we know not, know not the riches of thy
							full abundance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							No one hath seen that might of thine, productive of bounty every day
							renewed, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This one great power of thine our eyes have witnessed, wherewith thou
							slewest Varasikha's children,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When by the force of thy descending thunder, at the mere solund, their
							boldest was demolished.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							In aid of Abhyavartin Cayamana, Indra destroyed the seed of Varasikha.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							At Hariyupiya he smote the vanguard of the Vrcivans, and the rear fled
							frighted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three thousand, mailed, in quest of fame, together, on the Yavyavati, O
							much-sought Indra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vrcivan's sons, falling before the arrow, like bursting vessels went to
							their destruction.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, whose two red Steers, seeking goodly pasture, plying their tongues
							move on 'twixt earth and heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gave Turvasa to Srnjaya, and, to aid him, gave the Vrcivans up to
							Daivavata.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Two wagon-teams, with damsels, twenty oxen, O Agni, Abhydvartin
							Cayamdna,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 27: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The liberal Sovran, giveth me. This guerdon of Prthu's seed is hard to
							win from others.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 28
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Kine have come and brought good fortune: let them rest in the
							cow-pen and be happy near us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here let them stay prolific, many-coloured, and yield through many
							morns their milk for Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra aids him who offers sacrifice and gifts: he takes not what is
							his, and gives him more thereto.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Increasing ever more and ever more his wealth, he makes the pious dwell
							within unbroken bounds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							These are ne'er lost, no robber ever injures them: no evil-minded foe
							attempts to harass them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The master of the Kine lives many a year with these, the Cows whereby
							he pours his gifts and serves the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The charger with his dusty brow o'ertakes them not, and never to the
							shambles do they take their way.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							These Cows, the cattle of the pious worshipper, roam over widespread
							pasture where no danger is.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To me the Cows seem Bhaga, they seem Indra, they seem a portion of the
							first-poured Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These present Cows, they, O ye Indra. I long for Indra with my heart
							and spirit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Cows, ye fatten e'en the worn and wasted, and make the unlovely
							beautiful tolook on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Prosper my house, ye with auspicious voices. Your power is glorified in
							our assemblies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Crop goodly pasturage and be prolific drink pure sweet water at good
							drinking places.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Never be thief or sinful man your matter, and may the dart of Rudra
							still avoid you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now let this close admixture be close intermigled with these Cows,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 28: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mixt with the Steer's prolific flow, and, Indra, with thy hero might.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 29
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YOUR men have followed Indra for his friendship, and for his
							loving-kindness glorified him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For he bestows great wealth, the Thunder-wielder: worship him, Great
							and Kind, to win his favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him to whose hand, men closely cling, and drivers stand on his golden
							chariot firmly stationed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With his firm arms he holds the reins; his Horses, the Stallions, are
							yoked ready for the journey.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy devotees embrace thy feet for glory. Bold, thunder-armed, rich,
							through thy strength, in guerdon,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Robed in a garment fair as heaven to look on, thou hast displayed thee
							like an active dancer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Soma when effused hath best consistence, for which the food is
							dressed and grain is mingled;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							By which the men who pray, extolling Indra chief favourites of Gods,
							recite their praises.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							No limit of thy might hath been appointed, which by its greatness
							sundered earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These the Prince filleth full with strong endeavour, driving, as
							'twere, with help his flocks to waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							So be the lofty Indra prompt to listen, Helper unaided, golden-visored
							Hero.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 29: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, so may he, shown forth in might unequalled, smite down the many
							Vrtras and the Dasyus.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 30
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							INDRA hath waxed yet more for hero prowess, alone, Eternal, he
							bestoweth treasures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra transcendeth both the worlds in greatness: one half of him
							equalleth earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, mighty I esteem his Godlike nature: none hindereth what he hath
							once determined.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Near and afar he spread and set the regions, and every day the Sun
							became apparent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							E'en now endures thine exploit of the Rivers, when, Indra, for their
							floods thou clavest passage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like men who sit at meat the mountains settled: by thee, Most Wise! the
							regions were made steadfast.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the truth, none else is like thee, Indra, no God superior to
							thee, no mortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou slewest Ahi who besieged the waters, and lettest loose the streams
							to hurry seaward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, thou breakest up the floods and portals on all sides, and the
							firmness of the mountain.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art the King of men, of all that liveth, engendering at once Sun,
							Heaven, and Morning.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 31
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SOLE Lord of wealth art thou, O Lord of riches: thou in thine hands
							hast held the people, Indra!
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men have invoked thee with contending voices for seed and waters,
							progeny and sunlight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through fear of thee, O Indra, all the regions of earth, though naught
							may move them, shake and tremble.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							All that is firm is frightened at thy coming, -the earth, the heaven,
							the mountain, and the forest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Kutsa, Indra! thou didst conquer Susna, voracious, bane of crops,
							in fight for cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In the close fray thou rentest him: thou stolest the Sun's wheel and
							didst drive away misfortunes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou smotest to the ground the hundred castles, impregnable, of Sambara
							the Dasyu,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, Strong, with might thou holpest Divodasa who poured libations
							out, O Soma-buyer, and madest Bharadvaja rich who praised thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As such, true Hero, for great joy of battle mount thy terrific car, O
							Brave and Manly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 31: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come with thine help to me, thou distant Roamer, and, glorious God,
							spread among men my glory.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 32
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I WITH my lips have fashioned for this Hero words never matched, most
							plentiful and auspicious,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For him the Ancient, Great, Strong, Energetic, the very mighty Wielder
							of the Thunder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Amid the sages, with the Sun he brightened the Parents: glorified, he
							burst the mountain;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, roaring with the holy-thoughted singers, he loosed the bond that
							held the beams of Morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Famed for great deeds, with priests who kneel and laud him, he still
							hath conquered in the frays for cattle,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And broken down the forts, the Fort-destroyer, a Friend with friends, a
							Sage among the sages.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come with thy girthed mares, with abundant vigour and plenteous
							strength to him who sings thy praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come hither, borne by mares with many heroes, Lover of song! Steer! for
							the people's welfare.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra with rush and might, sped by his Coursers, hath swiftly won the
							waters from the southward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 32: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thus set at liberty the rivers daily flow to their goal, incessant and
							exhaustless.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 33
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GIVE us the rapture that is mightiest, Indra, prompt to bestow and
							swift to aid, O Hero,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That wins with brave steeds where brave steeds encounter, and quells
							the Vrtras and the foes in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For with loud voice the tribes invoke thee, Indra, to aid them in the
							battlefield of heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, with the singers, hast pierced through the Panis: the charger
							whom thou aidest wins the booty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Both races, Indra, of opposing foemen, O Hero, both the Arya and the
							Dasa,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hast thou struck down like woods with well-shot lightnings: thou
							rentest them in fight, most manly Chieftain!
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, befriend us with no scanty succour, prosper and aid us, Loved of
							all that liveth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, fighting for the sunlight, we invoke thee, O Hero, in the fray,
							in war's division.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be ours, O Indra, now and for the future, be graciously inclined and
							near to help us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thus may we, singing, sheltered by the Mighty, win many cattle on the
							day of trial.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 34
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FULL Many songs have met in thee, O Indra, and many a noble thought
							from thee proceedeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now and of old the eulogies of sages, their holy hymns and lauds, have
							yearned for Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, praised of many, bold, invoked of many, alone is glorified at
							sacrifices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a car harnessed for some great achievement, Indra must be the
							cause of our rejoicing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							They make their way to Indra and exalt him, bim whom no prayers and no
							laudations trouble;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							For when a hundred or a thousand singers. laud him who loves the song
							their praise delights him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							As brightness mingles with the Moon in heaven, the offered Soma yearns
							to mix with Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like water brought to men in desert places, our gifts at sacrifice have
							still refreshed him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him this mighty eulogy, to Indra hath this our laud been uttered by
							the poets,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 34: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							That in the great encounter with the foemen, Loved of all life, Indra
							may guard and help us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 35
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHEN shall our prayers rest in thy car beside thee? When dost thou give
							the singer food for thousands?
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When wilt thou clothe this poet's laud with plenty, and when wilt thou
							enrich our hymns with booty?
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When wilt thou gatber men with men, O Indra, heroes with heroes, and
							prevail in combat?
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou shalt win triply kine in frays for cattle, so, Indra, give thou us
							celestial glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, when wilt thou, O Indra, thou Most Mighty, make the prayer
							all-sustaining for the singer?
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When wilt thou yoke, as we yoke songs, thy Horses, and come to
							offerings that bring wealth in cattle?
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grant to the Singer food with store of cattle, splendid with horses and
							the fame of riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Send food to swell the milch-cow good at milking: bright be its shine
							among the Bharadvajas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lead otherwise this present foeman, Sakra! Hence art thou praised as
							Hero, foe destroyer
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who gives pure gifts may I praise unceasing. Sage, quicken the
							Angirases by devotion.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 36
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THY raptures ever were for all men's profit: so evermore have been
							thine earthly riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou still hast been the dealer-forth of vigour, since among Gods thou
							hast had power and Godhead.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men have obtained his strength by sacrificing, and ever urged him, on
							to hero valour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							For the rein-seizing, the impetuous Charger they furnished power even
							for Vrtra's slaughter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Associate with him, as teams of horses, help, manly might, and vigour
							follow Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As rivers reach the sea, so, strong with praises, our holy songs reach
							him the Comprehensive.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lauded by us, let flow the spring, O Indra, of excellent and
							brightly-shining riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thou art Lord of men, without an equal: of all the world thou art
							the only Sovran.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear what thou mayst hear, thou who, fain for worship, as heaven girds
							earth, guardest thy servant's treasure;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Tlat thou mayst be our own, joying in power, famed through thy might in
							every generation.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 37
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET thy Bay Horses, yoked, O mighty Indra, bring thy car hither fraught
							with every blessing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thee, the Heavenly, e'en the poor invoketh: may we this day, thy
							feast-companions, prosper.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forth to the vat the brown drops flow for service, and purified proceed
							directly forward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Indra drink of this, our guest aforetime, Celestial King of the
							strong draught of Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bringing us hitherward all-potent Indra on well-wheeled chariot, may
							the Steeds who bear him
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Convey him on the road direct to glory, and ne'er may Vayu's Amrta
							cease and fail him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Supreme, he stirs this man to give the guerdon,-Indra, most efficacious
							of the princes,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith, O Thunderer, thou removest sorrow, and, Bold One! partest
							wealth among the nobles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra is hewho gives enduring vigour: may our songs magnify the God
							Most Mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 37: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best Vrtra-slayer be the Hero Indra these things he gives as Prince,
							with strong endeavour.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 38
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HE hath drunk hence, Most Marvellous, and carried away our great and
							splendid call on Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Bounteous, when we serve the Gods, accepteth song yet more famous
							and the gifts we bring him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The speaker filleth with a cry to Indra his ears who cometh nigh e'en
							from a distance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May this my call bring Indra to my presence, this call to Gods composed
							in sacred verses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him have I sung with my best song and praises, Indra of ancient birth
							and Everlasting.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							For prayer and songs in him are concentrated: let laud wax mighty when
							addressed to Indra:
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, whom sacrifice shall strengthen, Soma, and song and hymn, and
							praises and devotion,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom Dawns shall strengthen when the night departeth, Indra whom days
							shall strengthen, months, and autumns.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, born for conquering might in full perfection, and waxen strongfor
							bounty and for glory,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
