						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lead us to ample room, O thou who knowest, to happiness, security, and
							sunlight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							High, Indra, are the arms of thee the Mighty: may we betake. us to
							their lofty shelter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Set us on widest chariot-seat, O Indra, with two steeds best to draw, O
							Lord of Hundreds!
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring us the best among all sorts of viands: let not the foe's wealth,
							Maghavan, subdue us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be gracious, Indra, let my days be lengthened: sharpen my thought as
							'twere a blade of iron
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Approve whatever words I speak, dependent on thee, and grant me thy
							divine protection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra the Rescuer, Indra the Helper, Hero who listens at each
							invocation,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sakra I call, Indra invoked of many. May Indra Maghavan prosper and
							bless us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							May helpful Indra as our good Protector, Lord of all treasures, favour
							us with succour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Baffle our foes, and give us rest and safety, and may we be the lords
							of hero vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we enjoy the grace of him the Holy, yea, may we dwell in his
							auspicious favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							May helpful Indra as our good Preserver drive from us, even from afar,
							our foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like rivers rushing down a slope, O Indra, to thee haste songs and
							prayers and linked verses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou gatherest, Thunderer! like widespread bounty, kine, water, drops,
							and manifold libations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who lauds him, satisfies him, pays him worship? E'en the rich noble
							still hath found him mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							With power, as when one moves his feet alternate, he makes the last
							precede, the foremost follow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Famed is the Hero as each strong man's tamer, ever advancing one and
							then another.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							King of both worlds, hating the high and haughty, Indra protects the
							men who are his people.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							He loves no more the men he loved aforetime: he turns and moves away
							allied with others.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rejecting those who disregard his worship, Indra victorious lives
							through many autumns.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							In every figure he hath been the mode: this is his only form for us to
							look on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra moves multiform by his illusions; for his Bay Steeds are yoked,
							ten times a hundred.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here Tvastar, yoking to the car the Bay Steeds, hath extended sway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who will for ever stand upon the foeman's side, even when our princes
							sit at ease?
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods, we have reached a country void of pasture the land, though
							spacious, was too small to hold us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, provide in war for cattle; find a path, Indra, for this
							faithful singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Day after day far from their seat he drove them, alike, from place to
							place, those darksome creatures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Hero slew the meanly-huckstering Dasas, Varcin and Sambara, where
							the waters gather.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Out of thy bounty, Indra, hath Prastoka bestowed ten coffers and ten
							mettled horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							We have received in turn from Divodasa Sambara's wealth, the gift of
							Atithigva.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ten horses and ten treasure-chests, ten garments as an added gift,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							These and ten lumps of gold have I received from Divodasa's hand.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ten cars with extra steed to each, for the Atharvans hundred cows,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hath Asvatha to Payu given.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Thus Srnjaya's son honoured the Bharadvajas, recipients of all noble gifts
						and bounty.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 26
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 26: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of the wood, be firm and strong in body: be, bearing us, a brave
							victorious hero
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 26: Line 2
					-
						-
							Show forth thy strength, compact with straps of leather, and let thy
							rider win all spoils of battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 27: Line 1
					-
						-
							Its mighty strength was borrowed from the heaven and earth: its
							conquering force was brought from sovrans of the wood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 27: Line 2
					-
						-
							Honour with holy gifts the Car like Indra's bolt, the Car bound round
							with straps, the vigour of the floods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 28
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 28: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou Bolt of Indra, Vanguard of the Maruts, close knit to Varuna and
							Child of Mitra,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 28: Line 2
					-
						-
							As such, accepting gifts which here we offer, receive, O Godlike
							Chariot, these oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 29
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 29: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send forth thy voice aloud through earth and heaven, and let the world
							in all its breadth regard thee;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 29: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Drum, accordant with the Gods and Indra, drive thou afar, yea, very
							far, our foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 30
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 30: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thunder out strength and fill us full of vigour: yea, thunder forth and
							drive away all dangers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 30: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drive hence, O War-drum, drive away misfortune: thou art the Fist of
							Indra: show thy firmness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 31
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 31: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drive hither those, and these again bring hither: the War-drum speaks
							aloud as battle's signal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 47: Verse 31: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our heroes, winged with horses, come together. Let our car-warriors,
							Indra, be triumphant.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 48
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING to your Agni with each song, at every sacrifice, for strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come, let us praise the Wise and Everlasting God, even as a
							well-beloved Friend,
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Son of Strength; for is he not our gracious Lord? Let us serve him
							who bears our gifts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							In battle may he be our help and strengthener, yea, be the saviour of
							our lives.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, thou beamest forth with light, great Hero, never changed by time.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shining, pure Agni! with a light that never fades, beam with thy fair
							beams brilliantly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou worshippest great Gods: bring them without delay by wisdom and thy
							wondrous power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Agni, make them turn hither to succour us. Give strength, and win it
							for thyself.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He whom floods, stones, and trees support, the offspring of eternal
							Law;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who when rubbed with force is brought to life by men upon the lofty
							height of earth;
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who hath filled both worlds fult with his brilliant shine, who
							hastens with his smoke to heaven;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He made himself apparent through the gloom by night, the Red Bull in
							the darksome nights, the Red Bull in the darksome nights.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, with thy lofty beams, with thy pure brilliancy, O God,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Kindled, Most Youthful One! by Bharadvaja's hand, shine on us, O pure
							God, with wealth, shine, Purifier! splendidly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art the Lord of house and home of all the tribes, O Agni, of all
							tribes of men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard with a hundred forts thy kindler from distress, through hundred
							winters, Youngest God! and those who make thy singers rich.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wonderful, with thy favouring help, send us thy bounties, gracious
							Lord.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art the Charioteer, Agni, of earthly wealth: find rest and safety
							for our seed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							With guards unfailing never negligent speed thou our children and our
							progeny.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Keep far from us, O Agni, all celestial wrath and wickedness of godless
							men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither, O friends, with newest song drive her who freely pours her
							milk;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Loose her who never turns away;
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who, for the host of Maruts bright with native sheen, hath shed
							immortal fame like milk;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom the impetuous Maruts look upon with love, who moves in splendour
							on their ways.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Bharadvaja she poured down in days of old
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							The milch-cow yielding milk for all, and food that gives all
							nourishment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your friend like Indra passing wise, with magic power like Varuna.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like Aryaman joy-giving, bringing plenteous food like ViSnxu for my
							wish, I praise,
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bright as the host of Maruts mighty in their roar. May they bring Pusan
							free from foes;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they bring hither hundreds, thousands for our men: may they bring
							hidden stores to light, and make wealth easy to be found.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Haste to me, Pusan, in thine car, bright Deity: I fain would speak:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most sinful is our foeman's hate.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tear not up by the roots the Kakambira tree: destroy thou all
							malignity.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let them not snare by day the neck of that Celestial Bird the Sun.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Uninjured let thy friendship be, like the smooth surface of a skin,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							A flawless skin, containing curds, full to the mouth, containing curds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							For thou art high above mankind, in glory equal to the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therefore, O Pusan, look upon us in the fight: now help us as in days
							of old.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the kind excellence of him the Kind, loud Roarers! be our guide,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be it the God's, O Maruts, or a mortal man's who worships, ye impetuous
							Ones!
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							They whose high glory in a moment like the God, the Sun, goes round the
							space of heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Maruts have obtained bright strength, a sacred name, strength that
							destroys the Vrtras, strength Vrtra-destroying excellent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Once, only once, the heaven was made, once only once, the earth was
							formed-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 48: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Once, only Prsni's milk was shed: no second, after this, is born.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 49
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I LAUD with newest songs the Righteous People, Mitra and Varuna who
							make us happy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let them approach, here let them listen,Agni, Varuna, Mitra, Lords of
							fair dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, to be praised at each tribe's sacrifices, the Two young Matrons'
							sober-minded Herald,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Son of Strength, the Child of Heaven, the signal of sacrifice, red
							Agni will I worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unlike in form are the Red God's two Daughters: one is the Sun's, and
							stars bedeck the other.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Apart, the Sanctifiers, in succession, come to the famed hymn, praised
							in holy verses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I with a lofty song call hither Vayu, all-bounteous, filler of his car,
							most wealthy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Sage, with bright path, Lord of harnessed horses, impetuous,
							promptly honourest the prudent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							That chariot of the Asvins, fair to look on, pleaseth me well, yoked
							with a thought, refulgent,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith, Nasatyas, Chiefs, ye seek our dwelling, to give new strength
							to us and to our children.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bulls of the Earth, O Vata and Parjanya, stir up for us the regions of
							the water.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hearers of truth, ye, Sages, World-Supporters, increase his living
							wealth whose songs delight you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may Sarasvati, the Hero's Consort, brisk with rare life, the
							lightning's Child, inspire us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, with the Dames accordant, give the singer a refuge unassailable
							and flawless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							I praise with eloquence him who guards all pathways. He, when his love
							impelled him, went to Arka.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he vouchsafe us gear with gold to grace it: may Pusan make each
							prayer of ours efective.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Herald Agni, fulgent, bring for worship Tvastar adored, in homes
							and swift to listen,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Glorious, first to share, the life-bestower, the ever active God,
							fair-armed, fair-handed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rudra by day, Rudra at night we honour with these our songs, the
							Universe's Father.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him great and lofty, blissful, undecaying let us call specially as the
							Sage impels us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye who are youthful, wise, and meet for worship, come, Martits, to the
							longing of the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Coming, as erst to Angiras, O Heroes, ye animate and quicken e'en the
							desert.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as the herdsman driveth home his cattle, I urge my songs to him
							the strong swift Hero
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, the glorious, lay upon his body the singer's hymns, as stars
							bedeck the heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who for man's behoof in his afiliction thrice measured out the
							earthly regions, Visnu-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							When one so great as thou affordeth shelter, may we with wealth and
							with ourselves be happy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sweet be this song of mine to Ahibudhnya, Parvata, Savitar, with Floods
							and Lightnings;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sweet, with the Plants, to Gods who seek oblations. May liberal Bhaga
							speed us on to riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give riches borne on cars, with many heroes, contenting men, the guard
							of mighty Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 49: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us a lasting home that we may battle with godless bands of men who
							fight against us, and meet with tribes to whom the Gods are gracious.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 50
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I CALL with prayers on Aditi your Goddess, on Agni, Mitra, Varuna for
							favour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							On Aryaman who gives unasked, the gracious, on Gods who save, on
							Savitar and Bhaga.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Visit, to prove us free from sin, O Surya Lord of great might, the
							bright Gods sprung from Daksa,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Twice-born and true, observing sacred duties, Holy and full of light,
							whose tongue is Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							And, O ye Heaven and Earth, a wide dominion, O ye most blissful Worlds,
							our lofty shelter,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give ample room and freedom for our dwelling, a home, ye Hemispheres,
							which none may rival.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This day invited may the Sons of Rudra, resistless, excellent, stoop
							down to meet us;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For, when beset with slight or sore affliction, we ever call upon the
							Gods, the Maruts;
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To whom the Goddess Rodasi clings closely, whom Pusan follows bringing
							ample bounty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time ye hear our call and come, O Maruts, upon your separate path
							all creatures tremble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							With a new hymn extol, O thou who singest, the Lover of the Song, the
							Hero Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, exalted, hear our invocation, and grant us mighty wealth and
							strength when lauded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give full protection, Friends of man, ye Waters, in peace and trouble,
							to our sons and grandsons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							For ye are our most motherly physicians, parents of all that standeth,
							all that moveth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Savitar come hither and approach us, the God who rescues, Holy,
							goldenhanded,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The God who, bounteous as the face of Morning, discloses precious gifts
							for him who worships.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							And thou, O Son of Strength, do thou turn hither the Gods to-day to
							this our holy service.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May I for evermore enjoy thy bounty and, Agni, by thy grace be rich in
							heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come also to my call, O ye Nasatyas, yea, verily, through my prayers,
							ye Holy Sages.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							As from great darkness ye delivered Atri, protect us, Chiefs, from
							danger in the conflict.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Gods, bestow upon us riches, splendid with strength and heroes,
							bringing food in plenty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be gracious, helpful Gods of earth, of heaven, born of the Cow, and
							dwellers in the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Rudra and Sarasvati, accordant, Visnu and Vayu, pour down gifts and
							bless us;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rbhuksan, Vaja, and divine Vidhatar, Parjanya, Vata make our food
							abundant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this God Savitar, the Lord, the Offspring of Waters, pouring down
							his dew be gracious,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, with the Gods and Dames accordant, Tvastar; Dyaus with the Gods
							and Prthivi with oceans.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Aja-Ekapad and Ahibudhnya, and Earth and Ocean hear our invocation;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							All Gods who strengthen Law, invoked and lauded, and holy texts uttered
							by sages, help us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							So with my thoughts and hymns of praise the children of Bharadvaja sing
							aloud to please you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 50: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Dames invoked, and the resistless Vasus, and all ye Holy Ones have
							been exalted.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 51
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THAT mighty eye of Varuna and Mitra, infallible and dear, is moving
							upward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The pure and lovely face of holy Order hath shone like gold of heaven
							in its arising.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sage who knows these Gods' three ranks and orders, and all their
							generations near and distant,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beholding good and evil acts of mortals, Sura marks well the doing of
							the pious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							I praise you Guards of mighty Law eternal, Aditi, Mitra, Varuna, the
							noble,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aryaman, Bhaga, all whose thoughts are faithful: hither I call the
							Bright who share in common.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lords of the brave, infallible, foe-destroyers, great Kings, bestowers
							of fair homes to dwell in,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Young, Heroes, ruling heaven with strong dominion, Adityas, Aditi I
							seek with worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Heaven our Father, Earth our guileless Mother, O Brother Agni, and ye
							Vasus, bless us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant us, O Aditi and ye Adityas, all of one mind, your manifold
							protection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us not up to any evil creature, as spoil to wolf or she-wolf, O ye
							Holy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For ye are they who guide aright our bodies, ye are the rulers of our
							speech and vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us not suffer for the sin of others, nor do the deed which ye, O
							Vasus, punish.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, Universal Gods! are all-controllers: may he do harm unto himself
							who hates Me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mighty is homage: I adopt and use it. Homage hath held in place the
							earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Homage to Gods! Homage commands and rules them. I banish even committed
							sin by homage
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							You Furtherers of Law, pure in your spirit, infallible, dwellers in the
							home of Order,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							To you all Heroes mighty and far-seeing I bow me down, O Holy Ones,
							with homage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							For these are they who shine with noblest splendour; through all our
							troubles these conduct us safely-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Varuna, Mitra, Agni, mighty Rulers, trueminded, faithful to the hymn's
							controllers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May they, Earth, Aditi, Indra, Bhaga, Pusan increase our laud, increase
							the Fivefold people.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giving good help, good refuge, goodly guidance, be they our good
							deliverers, good protectors.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come now, O Gods, to your celestial station: the Bharadvajas' priest
							entreats your favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, sacrificing, fain for wealth, hath honoured the Gods vath those who
							sit and share oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, drive thou the wicked foe, the evil-hearted thief away,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far, far, Lord of the brave I and give us easy paths.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma, these pressing-stones have called aloud to win thee for our
							Friend.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Destroy the greedy Pani, for a wolf is he.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, O most bountiful, are they who, led by Indra, seek the sky.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us good paths for travel: guard us ivell at home.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now have we entered on the road that leads to bliss, without a foe,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 51: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							The road whereon a man escapes all enemies and gathers wealth.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 52
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS I allow not in the earth or heaven, at sacrifice or in these holy
							duties.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the huge mountains crush him down: degraded be Atiyaja's
							sacrificing patron.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Or he who holds us in contempt, O Maruts, or seeks to blame the prayer
							that we are making,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May agonies of burning be his portion. May the sky scorch the man who
							hates devotion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Why then, O Soma, do they call thee keeper of prayer? Why then our
							guardian from reproaches?
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Why then beholdest thou how men revile us? Cast thy hot dart at him who
							hates devotion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Mornings as they spring to life, protect me, and may the Rivers as
							they swell preserve me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							My guardians be the firmly-seated mountains: the Fathers, when I call
							on Gods, defend me!
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through all our days may we be healthy. minded, and look upon the Sun
							when he arises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant this the Treasure-Lord of treasures, coming, observant, oftenest
							of Gods, with succour!
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Most near, most oft comes Indra with protection, and she Sarasvati, who
							swells with rivers -
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Parjanya, bringing health with herbs, and Agni, well lauded swift to
							listen, like a father.
						-
				-
