						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Compass this house to keep it from the foeman, that none may force it,
							either near or distant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Juice in wide room hath been prepared to feast you: for you the grass
							is strewn, most soft to tread on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With lifted hands your servant hath adored you. Yearningfor you the
							press-stones shed the liquid.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni uplifts him at your sacrifices: forth goes the oblation dropping
							oil and glowing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Up stands the grateful-minded priest, elected, appointed to invoke the
							two Nasatyas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lords of great wealth! for glory, Surya's Daughter mounted your car
							that brings a hundred succours.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Famed for your magic arts were ye, magicians! amid the race of Gods, ye
							dancing Heroes!
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Twain, with these your glories fair to look on, brought, to win
							victory, rich gifts for Surya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							After you flew your birds, marvels of beauty: dear to our hearts! the
							song, well lauded, reached you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May your winged coursers, best to draw. Nasatyas! convey you to the
							object of your wishes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Swift as the thought, your car hath been sent onward to food of many a
							sort and dainty viands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lords of great wealth, manifold is your bounty: ye filled our cow with
							food that never faileth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lovers of sweetness! yours are praise and singers, and poured libations
							which have sought your favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mine were two mares of Puraya, brown, swift-footed; a hundred with
							Sumidha, food with Peruk
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sanda gave ten gold-decked and well-trained horses, tame and obedient
							and of lofty stature.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Nasatyas! Purupanthas offered hundreds, thousands of steeds to him who
							sang your praises,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gave, Heroes! to the singer Bharadvaja. Ye-Wonder-Workers, let the
							fiends be slaughtered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 63: Verse 11
				-
					-
						May I with princes share your bliss in freedom.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 64
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE radiant Dawns have risen up for glory, in their white splendour
							like the waves of waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							She maketh paths all easy, fair to travel, and, rich, hath shown
							herself benign and friendly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							We see that thou art good: far shines thy lustre; thy beams, thy
							splendours have flown up to heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Decking thyself, thou makest bare thy bosom, shining in majesty, thou
							Goddess Morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Red are the kine and luminous that bear her the Blessed One who
							spreadeth through the distance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The foes she chaseth like a valiant archer, like a swift warrior she
							repelleth darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy ways are easy on the hills: thou passest Invincible! Se1f-luminous!
							through waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							So lofty Goddess with thine ample pathway, Daughter of Heaven, bring
							wealth to give us comfort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dawn, bring me wealth: untroubled, with thine oxen thou bearest riches
							at thy will and pleasure;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou who, a Goddess, Child of Heaven, hast shown thee lovely through
							bounty when we called thee early.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the birds fly forth from their restingplaces, so men with store of
							food rise at thy dawning.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 64: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, to the liberal mortal who rernaineth at home, O Goddess Dawn, much
							good thou bringest.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 65
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SHEDDING her light on human habitations this Child of Heaven hath
							called us from our slumber;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							She who at night-time with her argent lustre hath shown herself e'en
							through the shades of darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							All this with red-rayed steeds have they divided: the Dawns on bright
							cars shine in wondrous fashion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							They, bringing near the stately rite's commencement, drive far away the
							night's surrounding shadows.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dawns, bringing hither, to the man who worships, glory and power and
							might and food and vigour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Opulent, with imperial sway like heroes, favour your servant and this
							day enrich him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now is there treasure for the man who serves you, now for the hero,
							Dawns! who brings oblation;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now for the singer when he sings the praise-song. Even to one like me
							ye brought aforetime.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Dawn who standest on the mountain ridges, Angirases now praise thy
							stalls of cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With prayer and holy hymn they burst them open: the heroes' calling on
							the Gods was fruitful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shine on us as of old, thou Child of Heaven,on him, rich Maid! who
							serves like Bharadvaja.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 65: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give to the singer wealth with noble heroes, and upon us bestow
							wide-spreading glory.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 66
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							E'EN to the wise let that be still a wonder to which the general name
							of Cow is given.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The one hath swelled among mankind for milking: Prsni hath drained but
							once her fair bright udder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who like kindled flames of fire are glowing,. the Maruts, twice
							and thrice have waxen mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Golden and dustless were their cars, invested with their great strength
							and their heroic vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who are Sons of the rain-pouring Rudra, whom the long-lasting One
							had power to foster:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mighty Ones whose germ great Mother Prsni is known to have received
							for man's advantage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They shrink not from the birth; in this same manner still resting there
							they purge away reproaches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When they have streamed forth, brilliant, at their pleasure, with their
							own splendour they bedew their bodies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even those who bear the brave bold name of Maruts, whom not the active
							quickly wins for milking.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even the liberal wards not off those fierce ones, those who are light
							and agile in their greatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, strong in strength and armed with potent weapons, they had united
							wellformed earth and heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rodasl stood among these furious Heroes like splendour shining with her
							native brightness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							No team of goats shall draw your car, O Maruts, no horse no charioteer
							be he who drives it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Halting not, reinless, through the air it travels, speeding alone its
							paths through earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							None may obstruct, none overtake, O Maruts, him whom ye succour in the
							strife of battle
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							For sons and progeny, for kine and waters: he bursts the cow-stall on
							the day of trial.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring a bright hymn to praise the band of Maruts, the Singers, rapid,
							strong in native vigour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who conquer mighty strength with strength more mighty: earth shakes in
							terror at their wars, O Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bright like the flashing flames of sacrifices, like tongues of fire
							impetuous in their onset,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Chanting their psalm, singing aloud, like heroes, splendid from birth,
							invincible, the Maruts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							That swelling band I call with invocation, the brood of Rudra, armed
							with glittering lances.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 66: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pure hymns are meet for that celestial army: like floods and mountains
							have the Strong Ones battled.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 67
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							NOW Mitra-Varuna shall be exalted high by your songs, noblest of all
							existing;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							They who, as 'twere with reins are best Controllers, unequalled with
							their arms to check the people.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you Two Gods is this my thought extended, turned to the sacred grass
							with loving homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us, O Mitra-Varuna, a dwelling safe from attack, which ye shall
							guard, Boon-Givers!
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come hither, Mitra-Varuna, invited with eulogies and loving adoration,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye who with your might, as Work-Controllers, urge even men who quickly
							hear to labour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whom, of pure origin, like two strong horses, Aditi bore as babes in
							proper season,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom, Mighty at your birth, the Mighty Goddess brought forth as terrors
							to the mortal foeman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As all the Gods in their great joy and gladness gave you with one
							accord your high dominion,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							As ye surround both worlds, though wide and spacious your spies are
							ever true and never bewildered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, through the days maintaining princely power. ye prop the height as
							'twere from loftiest heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Star of all the Gods, established, filleth the heaven and earth
							with food of man who liveth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Take the strong drink, to quaff till ye are sated, when he and his
							attendants fill the chamber.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The young Maids brook not that none seeks to win them, when, Quickeners
							of all! they scatter moisture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							So with your tongue come ever, when your envoy, faithful and very wise,
							attends our worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nourished by holy oil! he this yGur glory: annihilate the sacrificer's
							trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, Mitra-Varuna, they strive against you and break the friendly laws
							ye have established,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							They, neither Gods nor men in estimation, like Api's sons have godless
							sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							When singers in their song uplift their voices, some chant the Nivid
							texts with steady purpose.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then may we sing you lauds that shall be fruitful: dp ye not rival all
							the Gods in greatness?
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Mitra-Varuna, may your large bounty come to us hither, near to this
							our dwelling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 67: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the kine haste to us, and when they harness the fleet-foot mettled
							stallion for the battle.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 68
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HIS honouring rite whose grass is trimmed is offered swiftly to you, in
							Manu's wise, accordant,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The rite which Indra-Varuna shall carry this day to high success and
							glorious issue.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For at Gods' worship they are best through vigour; they have become the
							strongest of the Heroes;
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With mighty strength, most liberal of the Princes, Chiefs of the host,
							by Law made Vrtra's slayers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praise those Twain Gods for powers that merit worship, Indra and
							Varuna, for bliss, the joyous.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							One with his might and thunderbolt slays Vrtra; the other as a Sage
							stands near in troubles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Though dames and men have waxen strong and mighty, and all the Gods
							selfpraised among the Heroes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, Indra-Varuna, have in might surpassed them, and thus were ye spread
							wide, O Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Righteous is he, and liberal and helpful who, Indra-Varuna, brings you
							gifts with gladness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							That bounteous man through food shall conquer faemen, and win him
							opulence and wealthy people.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May wealth which ye bestow in food and treasure on him who brings you
							gifts and sacrifices,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth, Gods! which breaks the curse of those who vex us, be,
							Indra-Varuna, e'en our own possession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							So also, Indra-Varuna, may our princes have riches swift to save, with
							Gods to guard them-
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They whose great might gives victory in battles, and their triumphant
							glory spreads with swiftness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra. and Varuna, Gods whom we are lauding, mingle ye wealth with our
							heroic glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we, who praise the strength of what is mighty, pass dangers, as
							with boats we cross the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now will I sing a dear and far-extending hymn to Varuna the God,
							sublime, imperial Lord,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, mighty Governor, Eternal, as with flame, illumines both wide
							worlds with majesty and power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							True to Law, Indra-Varuna, drinkers of the juice, drink this pressed
							Soma which shall give you rapturous joy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your chariot cometh to the banquet of the Gods, to sacrifice, as it
							were home, that ye may drink.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Varuna, drink your fill, ye Heroes, of this invigorating
							sweetest Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 68: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							This juice is shed by us that ye may quaff it: on this trimmed grass be
							seated, and rejoice you
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 69
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							INDRA and Visnu, at my task's completion I urge you on with food and
							sacred service.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accept the sacrifice and grant us riches, leading us on by unobstructed
							pathways.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye who inspire all hymns, Indra and Visnu, ye vessels who contain the
							Soma juices,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May hymns of praise that now are sung address you, the lauds that are
							recited by the singers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lords of joy-giving draughts, Indra and Visnu, come, giving gifts of
							treasure, to the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With brilliant rays of hymns let chanted praises, repeated with the
							lauds, adorn and deck you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May your foe-conquering horses bring you hither, Indra and Visnu,
							sharers of the banquet.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of all our hymns accept the invocations list to my prayers and hear the
							songs I sing you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							This your deed, Indra-Visnu, must be lauded: widely ye strode in the
							wild joy of Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye made the firmament of larger compass, and made the regions broad for
							our existence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strengthened with sacred offerings, IndraVisnu, first eaters, served
							with worship ana oblation,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fed with the holy oil, vouchsafe us riches ye are the lake, the vat
							that holds the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drink of this meath, O Indra, thou, and Visnu; drink ye your fill of
							Soma, Wonder-Workers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The sweet exhilarating juice hath reached you. Hear ye my prayers, give
							ear unto my calling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Twain have conquered, ne'er have yc been conquered: never hath
							either of the Twain been vanquished.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 69: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, Indra-Visnu, when ye fought the battle, produced this infinite with
							three divisions.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 70
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FILLED full of fatness, compassing all things that be, wide, spacious,
							dropping meath, beautiful in their form,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Heaven and the Earth by Varuna's decree, unwasting, rich in germs,
							stand parted each from each.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Everlasting Pair, with full streams, rich in milk, in their pure
							rule pour fatness for the pious man.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye who are Regents of this world, O Earth and Heaven, pour into us the
							genial flow that prospers meit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso, for righteous life, pours offerings to you, O Heaven and Earth,
							ye Hemispheres, that man succeeds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He in his seed is born again and spreads by Law: from you flow things
							diverse in form, but ruled alike.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Enclosed in fatness, Heaven and Earth are bright therewith: they mingle
							with the fatness which they still increase.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wide, broad, set foremost at election of the priest, to them the
							singers pray for bliss to further them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Heaven and Earth pour down the balmy rain for us, balm-dropping,
							yielding balm, with balm upon your path,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bestowing by your Godhead sacrifice and wealth, great fame and strength
							for us and good heroic might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Heaven and Earth make food swell plenteously for us, all-knowing
							Father, jother, wondrous in their works.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 70: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pouring out bounties, may, in union, both the Worlds, all beneficial,
							send us gain, and power, and wealth.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 71
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FULL of effectual wisdom Savitar the God hath stretched out golden arms
							that he may bring forth life.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Young and most skilful, while he holds the region up, the Warrior
							sprinkles fatness over both his hands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we enjoy the noblest vivifying force of Savitar the God, that he
							may give us wealth:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thou art mighty to produce and lull to rest the world of life that
							moves on two feet and on four.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Protect our habitation, Savitar, this day, with guardian aids around,
							auspicious, firm and true.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							God of the golden tongue, keep us for newest bliss: let not the
							evil-wisher have us in his power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Savitar the God, the golden-handed, Friend of the home, hath risen
							to meet the twilight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With cheeks of brass, with pleasant tongue, the Holy, he sends the
							worshipper rich gifts in plenty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a Director, Savitar hath extended his golden arms, exceeding fair
							to look on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath gone up the heights of earth and heaven, and made each monster
							fall and cease from troubling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fair wealth, O Savitar, to-day, to-morrow, fair wealth produce for us
							each day that passes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 71: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we through this our song be happy gainers, God, of a fair and
							spacious habitation.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 72
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GREAT is this might of yours, Indra and Soma: the first high exploits
							were your own achievements.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye found the Sun ye found the light of heaven: ye killed all darkness
							and the Gods' blasphemers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, Indra-Soma, gave her light to Morning, and led the Sun on high with
							all his splendour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye stayed the heaven with a supporting pillar, and spread abroad apart,
							the Earth, the Mother.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye slew the flood -obstructing serpent Vrtra, Indra and Soma: Heaven
							approved your exploit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye urged to speed the currents of the rivers, and many seas have ye
							filled full with waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye in the unripe udders of the milch-kine have set the ripe milk,
							Indra, thou, and Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye have held fast the unimpeded whiteness within these many-coloured
							moving creatures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Verily ye bestow, Indra and Soma, wealth, famed, victorious, passing to
							our children.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 72: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye have invested men, ye Mighty Beings, with manly strength that
							conquers in the battle.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 73
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 73: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 73: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SERVED with oblations, first-born, mountain-render, Angiras' son,
							Brhaspati, the Holy,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 73: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With twice-firm path, dwelling in light, our Father, roars loudly, as a
							bull, to Earth and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 73: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 73: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, who made for such a people wide room and verge when Gods
							were invocated,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 73: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slaying his enemies, breaks down their castles, quelling his foes and
							conquering those who hate him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 73: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 73: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaspati in war hath won rich treasures, hath won, this God, the great
							stalls filled with cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 73: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Striving to win waters and light, resistless, Brhaspati with lightning
							smites the foeman.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 74
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HOLD fast your Godlike sway, O Soma-Rudra: let these our sacrifices
							quickly reach you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Placing in every house your seven great treasures, bring blessing to
							our quadrupeds and bipeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma and Rudra, chase to every quarter the sickness that hath visited
							our dwelling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drive Nirrti away into the distance, and give us excellent and happy
							glories.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Provide, O Soma-Rudra, for our bodies all needful medicines to heal and
							cure us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Set free and draw away the sin committed which we have still inherent
							in our persons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Armed with keen shafts and weapons, kind and loving, be gracious unto
							us, Soma and Rudra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 74: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Release us from the noose of Varuna; keep us from sorrow, in your
							tender loving-kindness.
						-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 75
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE warrior's look is like a thunderous rain-cloud's, when, armed with
							mail, he seeks the lap of battle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be thou victorious with unwounded body: so let the thickness of thy
							mail protect thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Bow let us win kine, with Bow the battle, with Bow be victors in
							our hot encounters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Bow brings grief and sorrow to the foeman: armed with the Bow may
							we subdue all regions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Close to his car, as fain to speak, She presses, holding her well-loved
							Friend in her embraces.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strained on the Bow, She whispers like a woman-this Bowstring that
							preserves us in the combat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							These, meeting like a woman and her lover, bear, mother-like, their
							child upon their bosom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the two Bow-ends, starting swift asunder, scatter, in unison, the
							foes who hate us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With many a son, father of many daughters, He clangs and clashes as he
							goes to battle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slung on the back, pouring his brood, the Quiver vanquishes all
							opposing bands and armies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Upstanding in the Car the skilful Charioteer guides his strong Horses
							on whithersoe'er he will.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							See and admire the strength of those controlling Reins which from
							behind declare the will of him who drives.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Horses whose hoofs rain dust are neighing loudly, yoked to the
							Chariots, showing forth their vigour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With their forefeet descending on the foemen, they, never flinching,
							trample and destroy them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Car-bearer is the name of his oblation, whercon are laid his Weapons
							and his Armour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							So let us here, each day that passes, honour the helpful Car with
							hearts exceeding joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							In sweet association lived the fathers who gave us life, profound and
							strong in trouble,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unwearied, armed with shafts and wondrous weapons, free, real heroes,
							conquerors of armies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Brahmans, and the Fathers meet for Soma-draughts, and, graciously
							inclined, unequalled Heaven and Earth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard us trom evil, Pusan, guard us strengtheners of Law: let not the
							evil-wisher master us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Her tooth a deer, dressed in an eagle's feathers, bound with cow-hide,
							launched forth, She flieth onward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							There where the heroes speed hither and thither, there may the Arrows
							shelter and protect us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Avoid us thou whose flight is straight, and let our bodies be as stone.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Soma kindly speak to us, and Aditi protect us well.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							He lays his blows upon their backs, he deals his blows upon their
							thighs.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Whip, who urgest horses, drive sagacious horses in the fray.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							It compasses the arm with serpent windings, fending away the friction
							of the bowstring:
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may the Brace, well-skilled in all its duties, guard manfully the
							man from every quarter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now to the Shaft with venom smeared, tipped with deer-horn, with iron
							mouth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Celestial, of Parjanya's seed, be this great adoration paid.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loosed from the Bowstring fly away, thou Arrow, sharpened by our
							prayer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Go to the foemen, strike them home, and let not one be left alive.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							There where the flights of Arrows fall like boys whose locks are yet
							unshorn.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even there may Brahmanaspati, and Aditi protect us well, protect us
							well through all our days.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy vital parts I cover with thine Armour: with immortality King Soma
							clothe thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Varuna give tliee what is more than ample, and in thy triumph may the
							Gods be joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 75: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Whoso would kill us, whether he be a strange foe or one of us,
					-
		-
			Mandala 7
		-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 1
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE men from fire-sticks, with their hands' swift movement, have, in
							deep thought, engendered glorious Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far-seen, with pointed flame, Lord of the homestead.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Vasus set that Agni in the dwelling, fair to behold, for help from
							every quarter:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, in the home for ever, must be honoured.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shine thou before us, Agni, well-enkindled, with flame, Most Youthful
							God, that never fadeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To thee come all our sacrificial viands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Among all fires these fires have shone most brightly, splendid with
							light, begirt by noble heroes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where men of lofty birth sit down together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Victorious Agni, grant us wealth with wisdom, wealth with brave sons,
							famous and independent,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Which not a foe who deals in magic conquers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To whom, the Strong, at morn and eve comes, maid-like, the ladle
							dropping oil, with its oblation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth-seeking comes to him his own devotion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Burn up all malice with those flames, O Agni, wherewith of old thou
							burntest up Jarutha,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And drive away in silence pain and sickness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							With him who lighteth up thy splendour, Agni, excellent, pure,
							refulgent, Purifier,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be present, and with us through these our praises.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, the patriarchal men, the mortals who have in many places spread
							thy lustre,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be gracious to us here for their sake also.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let these men, heroes in the fight with foemen, prevail against all
							godless arts of 4magic,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							These who ipprove the noble song I sing thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us not sit in want of men, O Agni, without descendants, heroleu,
							about thee:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							But, O House-Friend, in houses full of children.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							By sacrifice which the Steeds' Lord ever visits, there make our
							dwelling rich in seed and offspring,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Increasing still with lineal successors.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guard us, O Agni, from the hated demon, guard us from malice of the
							churlish sinner:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Allied with thee may I subdue assailants.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this same fire of mine surpass all others, this fire where
							offspring, vigorous and firm-handed,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wins, on a thousand paths, what ne'er shall perish.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is that Agni, saviour from the foeman, who guards the kindler of
							the flame from sorrow:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Heroes of noble lineage serve and tend him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is that Agni, served in many places, whom the rich lord who brings
							oblation kindles,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							And round him goes the priest at sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, may we with riches in possession bring thee continual ofierings
							in abundance,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Using both means to draw thee to our worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, bear thou, Eternal, these most welcome oblations to the Deities'
							assembly:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let them enjoy our very fragrant presents.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us not up, Agni, to want of heroes, to wretched clothes, to need,
							to destitution.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yield us not, Holy One, to fiend or hunger; injure us not at home or in
							the forest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give strength and power to these my prayers, O Agni; O God, pour
							blessings on our chiefs and nobles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant that both we and they may share thy bounty. Ye Gods, protect us
							evermore with blessings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou Agni, swift to hear, art fair of aspect: beam forth, O Son of
							Strength, in full effulgence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let me not want, with thee, a son for ever: let not a manly hero ever
							fail us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Condemn us not to indigence, O Agni, beside these flaming fires which
							Gods have kindled;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nor, even after fault, let thy displeasure, thine as a God, O Son of
							Strength, o'ertake us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, fair of face, the wealthy mortal who to the Immortal offers his
							oblation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hath him who wins him treasure by his Godhead, to whom the prince, in
							need, goes supplicating.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							Knowing our chief felicity, O Agni, bring hither ample riches to our
							nobles,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith we may enjoy ourselves, O Victor, with undiminished life and
							hero children.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 25: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give strength and power to these my prayers, O Agni; O God, pour
							blessings on bur chiefs and nobles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 1: Verse 25: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant that both we and they may share thy bounty. Ye Gods, protect us
							evermore with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 2
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GLADLY accept, this day, our fuel, Agni: send up thy sacred smoke and
							shine sublimely.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Touch the celestial summits with thy columns, and overspread thee with
							the rays of Surya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With sacrifice to these we men will honour the majesty of holy
							Narasamsa-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							To these the pure, most wise, the thought. inspirers, Gods who enjoy
							both sorts of our oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							We will extol at sacrifice for ever, as men may do, Agni whom Manu
							kindled,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your very skilful Asura, meet for worship, envoy between both worlds,
							the truthful speaker.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bearing the sacred grass, the men who serve him strew it with
							reverence, on their knees, by Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Calling him to the spotted grass, oil-sprinkled, adorn him, ye
							Adhvaryus, with oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With holy thoughts the pious have thrown open Doors fain for chariots
							in the Gods' assembly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like two full mother cows who lick their youngling, like maidens for
							the gathering, they adorn them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							And let the two exalted Heavenly Ladies, Morning and Night, like a cow
							good at milking,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come, much-invoked, and on our grass be seated ' wealthy, deserving
							worship, for our welfare.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							You, Bards and Singers at men's sacrifices, both filled with wisdom, I
							incline to worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Send up our offerings when we call upon you, and so among the Gods
							obtain us treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Bharati with all her Sisters, Ila accordant with the Gods, with
							mortals Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sarasvati with all her kindred Rivers, come to this grass, Three
							Goddesses, and seat them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well pleased with us do thou, O God, O Tvastar, give ready issue to our
							procreant vigour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whence springs the hero, powerful, skilled in action, lover of Gods,
							adjuster of the press-stones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send to the Gods the oblation, Lord of Forests, and let the Immolator,
							Agni, dress it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He as the truer Priest shall offer worship, for the God'sgenerations
							well he knoweth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come thou to us, O Agni, duly kindled, together with the potent Gods
							and Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 2: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							On this our grass sit Aditi, happy Mother, and let our Hail! delight
							the Gods Immortal.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 3
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ASSOCIATE with fires, make your God Agni envoy at sacrifice, best
							skilled in worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Established firm among mankind, the Holy, flame-crowned and fed with
							oil, the Purifier.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a steed neighing eager for the pasture, when he hath stepped forth
							from the great enclosure:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then the wind following blows upon his splendour, and, straight, the
							path is black which thou hast travelled.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							From thee a Bull but newly born, O Agni, the kindled everlasting flames
							rise upward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aloft to heaven thy ruddy smoke ascendeth: Agni, thou speedest to the
							Gods as envoy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou whose fresh lustre o'er the earth advanceth when greedily with thy
							jaws thy food thou eatest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a host hurried onward comes thy lasso: fierce, with thy tongue
							thou piercest, as 'twere barley.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The men have decked him both at eve and morning, Most Youthful Agni, as
							they tend a courser.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							They kindle him, a guest within his dwelling: bright shines the
							splendour of the worshipped Hero.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							O fair of face, beautiful is thine aspect when, very near at hand, like
							gold thou gleamest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like Heaven's thundering roar thy might approaches, and like the
							wondrous Sun thy light thou showest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							That we may worship, with your Hail to Agni! with sacrificial cakes and
							fat oblations,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard us, O Agni, with those boundless glories as with a hundred
							fortresses of iron.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine are resistless songs for him who offers, and hero-giving hymns
							wherewith thou savest;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With these, O Son of Strength, O Jatavedas, guard us, preserve these
							princes and the singers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							When forth he cometh, like an axe new-sharpened, pure in his form,
							resplendent in his body,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sprung, sought with eager longing, from his Parents, for the Gods'
							worship, Sage and Purifier:
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shine this felicity on us, O Agni: may we attain to perfect
							understanding.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 3: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							All happiness be theirs who sing and praise thee. Ye Gods, preserve us
							evermore with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 4
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BRING forth your gifts to his refulgent splendour, your hymn as purest
							offering to Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him who goes as messenger with knowledge between all songs of men
							and Gods in heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wise must this Agni be, though young and tender, since he was born,
							Most Youthful, of his Mother;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who with bright teeth seizeth fast the forests, and eats his food,
							though plenteous, in a moment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Before his presence must we all assemble, this God's whom men have
							seized in his white splendour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							This Agni who hath brooked that men should seize him hath shone for man
							with glow insufferable.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far-seeing hath this Agni been established, deathless mid mortals, wise
							among the foolish.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here, O victorious God, forbear to harm us: may weforever share thy
							gracious favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who hath occupied his God-made dwelling, Agni, in wisdom hath
							surpassed Immortals.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							A Babe unborn, the plants and trees support him, and the earth beareth
							him the All-sustainer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni is Lord of Amrta. in abundance, Lord of the gift of wealth and
							hero valour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Victorious God, let us not sit about thee like men devoid of strength,
							beauty, and worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The foeman's treasure may be won with labour: may we be masters of our
							own possessions.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, no son is he who springs from others: lengthen not out the
							pathways of the foolish.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unwelcome for adoption is the stranger, one to be thought of as
							another's offipring,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Though grown familiar by continual presence. May our strong hero come,
							freshly triumphant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guard us from him who would assail us, Agni; preserve us O thou Victor,
							from dishonour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here let the place of darkening come upon thee: may wealth be ours,
							desirable, in thousands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shine this felicity on us, O Agni: may we attain to perfect
							understanding.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 4: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							All happiness be theirs who sing and praise thee. Ye Gods, preserve us
							evermore with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 5
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BRING forth your song of praise to mighty Agni, the speedy messenger of
							earth and heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara, who, with those who wake, hath waxen great in the lap of
							all the Gods Immortal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sought in the heavens, on earth is Agni stablished, leader of rivers,
							Bull of standing waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara when he hath grown in glory, shines on the tribes of men
							with light and treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For fear of thee forth fled the dark-hued races, scattered abroad,
							deserting their possessions,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, glowing, O Vaisvanara, for Puru, thou Agni didst light up and
							rend their castles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni Vaisvanara, both Earth and Heaven submit them to thy threefold
							jurisdiction.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Refulgent in thine undecaying lustre thou hast invested both the worlds
							with splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, the tawny horses, loudly neighing our resonant hymns that drop
							with oil, attend thee;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of the tribes, our Charioteer of riches, Ensign of days,
							Vaisvanara of mornings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							In thee, O bright as Mitra, Vasus seated the might of Aduras, for they
							loved thy spirit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou dravest Dasyus from their home, O Agni, and broughtest forth broad
							light to light the Arya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born in the loftiest heaven thou in a moment reachest, like wind, the
							place where Gods inhabit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, favouring thine offspring, roaredst loudly when giving life to
							creatures, Jatavedas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send us that strength, Vaisvanara, send it, Agni, that strength, O
							Jatavedas, full of splendour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith, all-bounteous God, thou pourest riches, as fame
							wide-spreading, on the man who offers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, bestow upon our chiefs and nobles that famous power, that wealth
							which feedeth many.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 5: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accordant with the Vasus and the Rudras, Agni, Vaisvanara, give us sure
							protection.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 6
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							PRAISE of the Asura, high imperial Ruler, the Manly One in whom the
							folk shall triumph-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I laud his deeds who is as strong as Indra, and lauding celebrate the
							Fort-destroyer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sage, Sing, Food, Light,-they bring him from the mountain, the blessed
							Sovran of the earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							I decorate with songs the mighty actions which Agni, Fort-destroyer,
							did aforetime.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The foolish, faithless, rudely-speaking niggards, without belief or
							sacrifice or worship,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far far sway hath Agni chased those Dasytis, and, in the cast, hath
							turned the godless westward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him who brought eastward, manliest with his prowess, the Maids
							rejoicing in the western darkness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That Agni I extol, the Lord of riches, unyielding tamer of assailing
							foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him who brake down the walls with deadly weapons, and gave the Mornings
							to anoble Husband,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Young Agni, who with conquering strength subduing the tribes of Nahus
							made them bring their tribute.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							In whose protection all men rest by nature, desiring to enjoy his
							gracious favour-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni Vaisvanara in his Parents, bosom hath found the choicest seat in
							earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vaisvanara the God, at the sun's setting, hath taken to himself
							deep-hidden treasures:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 6: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni hath taken them from earth and heaven, from the sea under and the
							sea above us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 7
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I SEND forth even your God, victorious Agni, like a strong courser,
							with mine adoration.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Herald of sacrifice be he who knoweth he hath reached Gods, himself,
							with measured motion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							By paths that are thine own come hither, Agni, joyous, delighting in
							the Gods' alliance,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Making the heights of earth roar with thy fury, burning with eager
							teeth the woods and forests.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The grass is strewn; the sacrifice advances adored as Priest, Agni is
							made propitious,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Invoking both All-boon-bestowing Mothers of whom, Most Youthful! thou
							wast born to help us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forthwith the men, the best of these for wisdom, have made him leader
							in the solemn worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As Lord in homes of men is Agni stablished, the Holy One, the joyous,
							sweetly speaking.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He hath come, chosen bearer, and is seated in man's home, Brahman,
							Agni, the Supporter,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He whom both Heaven anct Earth exalt and strengthenwhom, Giver of all
							boons, the Hotar worships.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							These have passed all in glory, who, the manly, have wrought with skill
							the hymn of adoration;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, listening, have advanced the people's welfare, and set their
							thoughts on this my holy statute.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							We, the Vasisthas, now implore thee, Agni, O Son of Strength, the Lord
							of wealth and treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 7: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast brought food to singers and to nobles. Ye Gods, preserve us
							evermore with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 8
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE King whose face is decked with oil is kindled with homage offered
							by his faithful servant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The men, the priests adore him with oblations. Agni hath shone forth
							when the dawn is breaking.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, he hath been acknowledged as most mighty, the joyous Priest of
							men, the youthful Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, spreading o'er the earth, made light around him, and grew among the
							plants with blackened fellies..
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							How dost thou decorate our hymn, O Agni? What power dost thou exert
							when thou art lauded?
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, Bounteous God, may we be lords of riches, winners of precious
							wealth which none may conquer?
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far famed is this the Bharata's own Agni he shineth like the Sun with
							lofty splendour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who hath vanquished Puru in the battle, the heavenly guest hath
							glowed in full refulgence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Full many oblations are in thee collected: with all thine aspects thou
							hast waxen gracious.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art already famed as praised and lauded, yet still, O nobly born,
							increase thy body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be this my song, that winneth countless treasure, engendered with
							redoubled force for Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							That, splendid, chasing sickness, slaying demons, it may delight our
							friend and bless the singers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							We, the Vasisthas, now implore thee, Agni, O Son of Strength, the Lord
							of wealth and riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 8: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast brought food to singers and to nobles. Ye Gods, preserve us
							evermore with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 9
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 9: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 9: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ROUSED from their bosom is the Dawns' beloved, the joyous Priest, most
							sapient, Purifier.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 9: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He gives a signal both to Gods and mortals, to Gods oblations, riches
							to the pious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 9: Verse 2
				-
					-
