				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 16: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him have the Gods appointed Priest of sacrifice, oblation-bearer,
							passing wise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 16: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni gives wealth and valour to the worshipper, to folk who offer up
							their gifts.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 17
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 17: Verse 1
				-
					-
						AGNI, be kindled well with proper fuel, and let the grass be scattered wide
						about thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 17: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Let the impatient Portals be thrown open bring thou the Gods impatient to
						come hither.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 17: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Taste, Agni: serve the Gods with our oblation. Offer good sacrifices,
						Jatavedas!
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 17: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Let Jatavedas pay fair sacrifices, worship andgratify the Gods Immortal.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 17: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Wise God, win for us things that are all-goodly, and let the prayers, we
						pray today be fruitful.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 17: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Thee, even thee, the Son of Strength, O Agni, those Gods have made the
						bearer of oblations.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 17: Verse 7
				-
					-
						To thee the God may we perform our worship: do thou, besought, grant us
						abundant riches.
					-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 18
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ALL is with thee, O Indra, all the treasures which erst our fathers won
							who sang thy praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thee are milch-kine good to milk, and horses: best winner thou of
							riches for the pious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For like a King among his wives thou dwellest: with glories, as a Sage,
							surround and help us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make us, thy servants, strong for wealth, and honour our songs wirth
							kine and steeds and decoration.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here these our holy hymns with joy and gladness in pious emulation have
							approached thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hitherward come thy path that leads to riches: may we find shelter in
							thy favour, Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vasistha hath poured forth his prayers, desiring to milk thee like a
							cow in goodly pasture.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							All these my people call thee Lord of cattle: may Indra. come unto the
							prayer we offer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							What though the floods spread widely, Indra made them shallow and easy
							for Sudas to traverse.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, worthy of our praises, caused the Simyu, foe of our hymn, to curse
							the rivers' fury.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eager for spoil was Turvasa Purodas, fain to win wealth, like fishes
							urged by hunger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Bhrgus and the Druhyus quickly listened: friend rescued friend mid
							the two distant peoples.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Together came the Pakthas, the Bhalanas, the Alinas, the Sivas, the
							Visanins.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yet to the Trtsus came the Arya's Comrade, through love of spoil and
							heroes' war, to lead them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fools, in their folly fain to waste her waters, they parted
							inexhaustible Parusni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of the Earth, he with his might repressed them: still lay the herd
							and the affrighted herdsman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							As to their goal they sped to their destruetion: they sought Parusni;
							e'en the swift returned not.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra abandoned, to Sudas the manly, the swiftly flying foes, unmanly
							babblers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							They went like kine unherded from the pasture, each clinging to a
							friend as chance directed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							They who drive spotted steeds, sent down by Prsni, gave ear, the
							Warriors and the harnessed horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The King who scattered one-and-twenty people of both Vaikarna tribes
							through lust of glory-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							As the skilled priest clips grass within the chamber, so hath the Hero
							Indra, wrought their downfall.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, thunder-armed, o'erwhelmedst in the waters famed ancient Kavasa
							and then the Druhyu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Others here claiming friendship to their friendship, devoted unto thee,
							in thee were joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra at once with conquering might demolished all their strong places
							and their seven castles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							The goods of Anu's son he gave to Trtsu. May we in sacrifice conquer
							scorned Puru.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Anavas and Druhyus, seeking booty, have slept, the sixty hundred,
							yea, six thousand,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							And six-and-sixty heroes. For the pious were all these mighty exploits
							done by Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Trtsus under Indra's careful guidance came speeding like loosed
							waters rushing downward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							The foemen, measuring exceeding closely, abandoned to Sudas all their
							provisions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							The hero's side who drank the dressed oblation, Indra's denier, far
							o'er earth he scattered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra brought down the fierce destroyer's fury. He gave them various
							roads, the path's Controller.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							E'en with the weak he wrought this matchless exploit: e'en with a goat
							he did to death a lion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							He pared the pillar's angles with a needle. Thus to Sudas Indra gave
							all provisions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee have all thine enemies submitted: e'en the fierce Bheda hast
							thou made thy subject.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cast down thy sharpened thunderbolt, O Indra, on him who harms the men
							who sing thy praises.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yamuna and the Trtsus aided Indra. There he stripped Bheda bare of all
							his treasures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Ajas and the Sigrus and the Yaksus brought in to him as tribute
							heads of horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not to be scorned, but like Dawns past and recent, O Indra, are thy
							favours and thy riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Devaka, Manyamana's son, thou slewest, and smotest Sambara from the
							lofty mountain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who, from home, have gladdened thee, thy servants Parasara,
							Vasistha, Satayatu,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Will not forget thy friendship, liberal Giver. So shall the days dawn
							prosperous for the princes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Priest-like, with praise, I move around the altar, earning Paijavana's
							reward, O Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Two hundred cows from Devavan's descendant, two chariots from Sudas
							with mares to draw them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gift of Paijavana, four horses bear me in foremost place, trained
							steeds with pearl to deck them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sudas's brown steeds, firmly-stepping, carry me and my son for progeny
							and glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him whose fame spreads between wide earth and heaven, who, as
							dispenser, gives each chief his portion,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seven flowing Rivers glorify like Indra. He slew Yudhyamadhi in close
							encounter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 25: Line 1
					-
						-
							Attend on him O ye heroic Maruts as on Sudas's father Divodasa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 18: Verse 25: Line 2
					-
						-
							Further Paijavana's desire with favour. Guard faithfully his lasting
							firm dominion.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 19
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HE like a bull with sharpened horns, terrific, singly excites and
							agitates all the people:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou givest him who largely pours libations his goods who pours not,
							for his own possession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, verily, Indra, gavest help to Kutsa, willingly giving car to him
							in battle,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, aiding Arjuneya, thou subduedst to him both Kuyava and the Dasa
							Susna.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Bold One, thou with all thine aids hast boldly holpen Sudas whose
							offerings were accepted,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Puru in winning land and slaying foemen, and Trasadasyu son of
							Purukutsa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							At the Gods' banquet, hero-souled! with Heroes, Lord of Bay Steeds,
							thou slewest many foemen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou sentest in swift death to sleep the Dasyu, both Cumuri and Dhuni,
							for Dabhiti.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							These were thy mighty powers that, Thunder-wielder, thou swiftly
							crushedst nine-and-ninety castles:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou capturedst the hundredth in thine onslaught; thou slewest Namuci,
							thou slewest Vrtra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Old are the blessings, Indra, which thou gavest Sudas the worshipper
							who brought oblations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thee, the Strong, I yoke thy strong Bay Horses: may our prayers
							reach thee and win strength, Most Mighty!
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us not up, Lord of Bay Horses, Victor, in this thine own assembly,
							to the wicked.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Deliver us with true and faithful succours: dear may we be to thee
							among the princes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we men, Maghavan, the friends thou lovest, near thee be joyful
							under thy protection.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fain to fulfil the wish of Atithigva humble. the pride of Turvasa and
							Yadva.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Swiftly, in truth, O Maghavan, about thee men skilled in hymning sing
							their songs and praises. '
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Elect us also into their assembly who by their calls on thee despoiled
							the niggards.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine are these lauds, O manliest of heroes, lauds which revert to us
							and give us riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Favour these, Indra, when they fight with faemen, as Friend and Hero
							and the heroes' Helper.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, lauded for thine aid, Heroic Indra, sped by our prayer, wax mighty
							in thy body.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 19: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Apportion to us strength and habitations. Ye Gods, protect us evermore
							with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 20
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							STRONG, Godly-natured, born for hero exploit, man's Friend, hedoth
							whatever deed he willeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Saving us e'en from great transgression, Indra, the Youthful, visiteth
							man's home with favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Waxing greatness Indra slayeth Vrtra: the Hero with his aid hath helped
							the singer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He gave Sudas wide room and space, and often hath granted wealth to him
							who brought oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soldier unchecked, war-rousing, battling Hero, unconquered from of old,
							victorious ever,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra the very strong hath scattered armies; yea, he hath slain each
							foe who fought against him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou with thy greatness hast filled full, O Indra, even both the worlds
							with might, O thou Most Mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of Bays, Indra, brandishing his thunder, is gratified with Soma at
							the banquet.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							A Bull begat the Bull for joy of battle, and a strong Mother brought
							forth him the manly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who is Chief of men, their armies' Leader, is strong Hero, bold, and
							fain for booty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The people falter not, nor suffer sorrow, who win themselves this God's
							terrific spirit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who with sacrifices worships Indra is lord of wealth, law-born and
							law's protector.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whene'er the elder fain would help the younger the greater cometh to
							the lesser's present.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shall the Immortal sit aloof' inactive? O Wondrous Indra, bring us
							wondrous riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy dear folk, Indra, who present oblations, are, in chief place, thy
							friends, O Thunder-wielder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we be best content in this thy favour, sheltered by One who slays
