						Mandala 7: Hymn 27: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose perfect guerdon, never failing, bringeth wealth to the men, to
							friends the thing they covet.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 27: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 27: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Quick, Indra, give us room and way to riches, and let us bring thy mind
							to grant us treasures,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 27: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							That we may win us cars and Steeds and cattle. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 28
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COME to our prayers, O Indra, thou who knowest: let thy Bay Steeds be
							yoked and guided hither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Though mortal men on every side invoke thee, still give thine ear to
							us, O All-impeller.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy greatness reacheth to our invocation, the sages' prayer which,
							Potent God, thou guardest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time thy hand, O Mighty, holds the thunder, awful in strength thou
							hast become resistless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time thou drewest both world-halves together, like heroes led by
							thee who call each other-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thou wast born for strength and high dominion-then e'en the active
							overthrew the sluggish.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Honour us in these present days, O Indra, for hostile men are making
							expiation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our sin that sinless Varuna discovered, the Wondrous-Wise hath long ago
							forgiven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							We will address this liberal Lord, this Indra, that he may grant us
							gifts of ample riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best favourer of the singer's prayer and praises. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 29
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS Soma hath been pressed for thee, O Indra: come hither, Lord of
							Bays, for this thou lovest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink of this fair, this well-effused libation: Maghavan, give us
							wealth when we implore thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to us quickly with thy Bay Steeds, Hero, come to our prayer,
							accepting our devotion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enjoy thyself aright at this libation, and listen thou unto the prayers
							we offer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What satisfaction do our hymns afford thee? When, Maghavan? Now let us
							do thee service.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hymns, only hymns, with love for thee, I weave thee: then hear, O
							Indra, these mine invocations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They, verily, were also human beings whom thou wast wont to hear, those
							earlier sages.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hence I, O Indra Maghavan, invoke thee: thou art our Providence, even
							as a Father.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							We will address this liberal Lord, this Indra, that he may grant us
							gifts of ample riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best favourer of the singer's prayer and praises. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 30
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH power and strength, O Mighty God, approach us: be the augmenter,
							Indra, of these riches;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strong Thunderer, Lord of men, for potent valour, for manly exploit and
							for high dominion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee, worth invoking, in the din of battle, heroes invoke in fray for
							life and sunlight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Among all people thou art foremost fighter: give up our enemies to easy
							slaughter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When fair bright days shall dawn on us, O Indra, and thou shalt bring
							thy banner near in battle,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni the Asura shall sit as Herald, calling Gods hither for our great
							good fortune.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine are we, Indra, thine, both these who praise thee, and those who
							give rich gifts, O God and Hero.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant to our princes excellent protection, may they wax old and still
							be strong and happy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							We will address this liberal Lord, this Indra that he may grant us
							gifts of ample riches:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best favourer of the singer's prayer and praises. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 31
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING ye a song, to make him glad, to Indra, Lord of Tawny Steeds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Soma-drinker, O my friends.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 2
				-
					-
						To him the Bounteous say the laud, and let us glorify, as men May do, the
						Giver of true gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, Lord of boundless might, for us thou winnest strength and
							kine,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou winnest gold for us, Good Lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Faithful to thee we loudly sing, heroic Indra, songs to thee: Mark, O Good
						Lord, this act of ours.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Give us not up to man's reproach, to foeman's hateful calumny: In thee
						alone is all my strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art mine ample coat of mail, my Champion, Vrtra-Slayer, thou:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thee for Friend I brave the foe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, great art thou whose conquering might two independent Powers
							confess.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Heaven, O India, and the Earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							So let the voice surround thee, which attends the Maruts on their way,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Reaching thee with the rays of light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the ascending drops attain to thee, the Wondrous God, in heaven:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let all the folk bow down to thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring to the Wise, the Great, who waxeth mighty, your offerings, and
							make ready your devotion;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							To many clans he goeth, man's controller.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Indra, the sublime, the far-pervading, have singers generated
							prayer and praises:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The sages never violate his statutes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							The choirs have stablished Indra King for ever, for victory, him whose
							anger is resistless:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 31: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, for the Bays' Lord, strengthened those he loveth.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 32
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET none, no, not thy worshippers, delay thee far away from us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even from far away come thou unto our feast, or listen if already here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For here, like flies on honey, these who pray to thee sit by the juice
							that they have poured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth-craving singers have on Indra set their hope, as men set foot
							upon a car.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Longing for wealth I call on him, the Thunderer with the strong right
							hand,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As a son calleth on his sire.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Soma juices, mixed with curd, have been expressed for Indra here.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come with thy Bay Steeds, Thunder-wielder, to our home, to drink them
							till they make thee glad.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he whose ear is open hear us. He is asked for wealth: will he
							despise our prayer?
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who bestows at once a hundred thousand gifts none shall restrain
							when he would give.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The hero never checked by men hath gained his strength through Indra,
							he
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who presses out and pours his deep libations forth, O Vrtra-slayer,
							unto thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou dost drive the fighting men together be, thou Mighty One, the
							mighty's shield.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we divide the wealth of him whom thou hast slain: bring us,
							Unreachable, his goods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Indra, Soma-drinker, armed with thunder, press the Soma juice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make ready your dressed meats: cause him to favour us. The Giver
							blesses him who gives.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grudge not, ye Soma pourers; stir you, pay the rites, for wealth, to
							the great Conqueror.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Only the active conquers dwells in peace, and thrives: not for the
							niggard are the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							No one hath overturned or stayed the car of him who freely gives.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The man whom Indra and the Marut host defend comes to a stable full of
							kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, that man when fighting shall obtain the spoil, whose strong
							defender thou wilt be.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be thou the gracious helper, Hero I of our cars, be thou the helper of
							our men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							His portion is exceeding great like a victorious soldier's spoil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who is Indra, Lord of Bays, no foes subdue. He gives the
							Soma-pourer strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Make for the Holy Gods a hymn that is not mean, but well-arranged and
							fair of form.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even many snares and bonds subdue not him who dwells with Indra through
							his sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, what mortal will attack the man who hath his wealth in thee?
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							The strong will win the spoil on the decisive day through faith in
							thee, O Maghavan.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							In battles with the foe urge on our mighty ones who give the treasures
							dear to thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							And may we with our princes, Lord of Tawny Steeds! pass through all
							peril, led by thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine, Indra, is the lowest wealth, thou cherishest the mid-most
							wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou ever rulest all the highest: in the fray for cattle none resisteth
							thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art renowned as giving wealth to every one in all the battles that
							are fought.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Craving protection, all these people of the earth, O Much-invoked,
							implore thy name.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							If I, O Indra, were the Lord of riches ample as thine own,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							I should support the singer, God. who givest wealth! and not abandon
							him to woe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Each day would I enrich the man who sang my praise, in whatsoever place
							he were.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							No kinship is there better, Maghavan, than thine: a father even is no
							more.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Plenty for his true ally the active man will gain the spoil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your Indra, Much-invoked, I bend with song, as bends a wright his wheel
							of solid wood.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							A moral wins no riches by unworthy praise: wealth comes not to the
							niggard churl.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Light is the task to give, O Maghavan, to one like me on the decisive
							day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like kine unmilked we call aloud, Hero, to thee, and sing thy praise,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Looker on heavenly light, Lord of this moving world, Lord, Indra, of
							what moveth not.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							None other like to thee, of earth or of the heavens, hath been or ever
							will be born.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							Desiring horses, Indra Maghavan! and kine, as men of might we call on
							thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring, Indra, the Victorious Ones; bring, elder thou, the younger host.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							For, Maghavan, thou art rich in treasures from of old, and must be
							called in every fight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 25: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drive thou away our enemies, O Maghavan: make riches easy to be won.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 25: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be thou our good Protector in the strife for spoil: Cherisher of our
							friends be thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 26
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 26: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, give us wisdom as a sire gives wisdom to his sons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 26: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guide us, O Much-invoked, in this our way may we still live and look
							upon the light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 27: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grant that no mighty foes, unknown, malevolent, unhallowed, tread us to
							the ground.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 32: Verse 27: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thine assistance, Hero, may we ass through all the waters that are
							rul`ng down.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 33
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE who wear hair-knots on the right, the movers of holy thought,
							white-robed, have won me over.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I warned the men, when from the grass I raised me, Not from afar can my
							Vasisthas help you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With soma they brought Indra from a distance, Over Vaisanta, from the
							strong libation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra preferred Vasisthas to the Soma pressed by the son of Vayata,
							Pasadyumna.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, verily, with these he crossed the river, in company with these he
							slaughtered Bheda.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So in the fight with the Ten Kings, Vasisthas! did Indra help Sudas
							through your devotions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I gladly, men I with prayer prayed by our fathers have fixed your axle:
							ye shall not be injured:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Since, when ye sang aloud the Sakvari verses, Vasisthas! ye invigorated
							Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like thirsty men they looked to heaven, in battle with the Ten Kings,
							surrounded and imploring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then Indra heard Vasistha as he praised him, and gave the Trtsus ample
							room and freedom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like sticks and staves wherewith they drive the cattle, Stripped bare,
							the Bharatas were found defenceless:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vasistha then became their chief and leader: then widely. were the
							Trtsus' clans extended.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three fertilize the worlds with genial moisture: three noble Creatures
							cast a light before them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Three that give warmth to all attend the morning. All these have they
							discovered, these Vasisthas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like the Sun's growing glory is their splendour, and like the sea's is
							their unflathomed greatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Their course is like the wind's. Your laud, Vasisthas, can never be
							attained by any other.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							They with perceptions of the heart in secret resort to that which
							spreads a thousand branches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Apsaras brought hither the Vasisthas wearing the vesture spun for
							them by Yama.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							A form of lustre springing from the lightning wast thou, when Varuna
							and Mitra saw thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Tliy one and only birth was then, Vasistha, when from thy stock Agastya
							brought thee hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born of their love for Urvasi, Vasistha thou, priest, art son of Varuna
							and Mitra;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							And as a fallen drop, in heavenly fervour, all the Gods laid thee on a
							lotus-blossorn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							He thinker, knower both of earth and heaven, endowed with many a gift,
							bestowing thousands,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Destined to wear the vesture spun by Yama, sprang from the Apsaras to
							life, Vasistha.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born at the sacrifice, urged by adorations, both with a common flow
							bedewed the pitcher.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then from the midst thereof there rose up Mana, and thence they say was
							born the sage Vasistha.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							He brings the bearer of the laud and Saman: first shall he speak
							bringing the stone for pressing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 33: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							With grateful hearts in reverence approach him: to you, O Pratrdas,
							Vasistha cometh.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 34
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 1
				-
					-
						MAY our divine and brilliant hymn go forth, like a swift chariot wrought
						and fashioned well.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 2
				-
					-
						The waters listen as they flow along: they know the origin of heaven and
						earth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Yea, the broad waters swell their flood ior him: of him strong heroes think
						amid their foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Set ye for him the coursers to the pole: like Indra Thunderer is the
						Golden-armed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Arouse you, like the days, to sacrifice speed gladly like a traveller on
						the way.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Go swift to battles, to the sacrifice: set up a flag, a hero for the folk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Up from his strength hath risen as 'twere a light: it bears the load as
						earth bears living things.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Agni, no demon I invoke the Gods: by law completing it, I form a hymn.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Closely albout you lay your heavenly song, and send your voice to where the
						Gods abide.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Varuna, Mighty, with a thousand eyes, beholds the paths wherein these
						rivers run.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 11
				-
					-
						He, King of kings, the glory of the floods, o'er all that liveth hath
						resistless sway.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 12
				-
					-
						May he assist us among all the tribes, and make the envier's praise devoid
						of light.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 13
				-
					-
						May the foes' threatening arrow pass us by: may he put far from us our
						bodies' sin.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Agni, oblation-cater, through our prayers aid us: to him our dearest laud
						is brought.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Accordant with the Gods choose for our Friend the Waters' Child: may he be
						good to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 16
				-
					-
						With lauds I sing the Dragon born of floods: he sits beneath the streams in
						middle air.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Ne'er may the Dragon of the Deep harm us: ne'er fail this faithful
						servant's sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 18
				-
					-
						To these our heroes may they grant renown: may pious men march boldly on to
						wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Leading great hosts, with fierce attacks of these, they burn their foes as
						the Sun burns the earth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 20
				-
					-
						What time our wives draw near to us, may he, left-handed Tvastar, give us
						hero sons.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 21
				-
					-
						May Tvastar find our hymn acceptable, and may Aramati, seeking wealth, be
						ours.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							May they who lavish gifts bestow those treasures: may Rodasi and
							Varunani listen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, with the Varutris, be our refuge, may bountiful Tvastar give us
							store of riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may rich Mountains and the liberal Waters, so may all Herbs that
							grow on ground, and Heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Earth accordant with the Forest-Sovrans, and both the World-halves
							round about protect us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							To this may both the wide Worlds lend approval, and Varuna in heaven,
							whose Friend is Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							May all the Maruts give consent, the Victors, that we may hold great
							wealth in firm possession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 25: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra, Varuna, Mitra, and Agni, Waters, Herbs, Trees accept the
							praise we offer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 34: Verse 25: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we find refuge in the Marut's bosom. Protect us evermore, ye Gods,
							with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 35
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BEFRIEND us with their aids Indra and Agni, Indra and Varuna who
							receive oblations!
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra and Soma give health, strength and comfort, Indra and Pusan be
							our help in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Auspicious Friends to us be Bhaga, Sathsa, auspicious be Purandhi aid
							all Riches;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The blessing of the true and well-conducted, and Aryaman in many forms
							apparent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Kind unto us he Maker and Sustainer, and the far-reaching Pair with
							God-like natures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Auspicious unto us be Earth and Heaven, the Mountain, and the Gods'
							fair invocations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Favour us Agni with his face of splendour, and Varuva and Mitra and the
							Asvins.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Favour us noble actions of the pious, impetuous vita blow on us with
							favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Early invoked, may Heaven and Earth be friendly, and Air's mid-region
							good for us to look on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To us may Herbs and Forest-Trees be gracious, gracious the Lord
							Victorious of the region.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be the God Indra with the Vasus friendly, and, with Adityas, Varuna who
							blesseth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Kind, with the Rudras, be the Healer Rudra, and, with the Dames, may
							Tvastar kindly listen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Blest unto us be Soma, and devotions, blest be the Sacrifice, the
							Stones for pressing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blest be the fixing of the sacred Pillars, blest be the tender Grass
							and blest the Altar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the far-seeing Sun rise up to bless us: be the four Quarters of the
							sky auspicious.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Auspicious be the firmly-seated Mountains, auspicious be the Rivers and
							the Waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Adid through holy works be gracioas, and may the Maruts, loud in
							song, be friendly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Visnu give felicity, and Pusan, the Air that cherisheth our life,
							and Vayu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prosper us Savitar, the God who rescues, and let the radiant Mornings
							be propitious.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Auspicious to all creatures be Parjanya, auspicious be the field's
							benign Protector.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May all the fellowship of Gods befriend us, Sarasvati, with Holy
							Thoughts, be gracious.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Friendly be they, the Liberal Ones who seek us, yea, those who dwell in
							heaven, on earth, in waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the great Lords of Truth protect and aid us: blest to us be our
							horses and our cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Kind be the pious skilful-handed Rbhus, kind be the Fathers at our
							invocations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Aja-Ekapad, the God, be gracious, gracious the Dragon of the Deep,
							and Ocean.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gracious be he the swelling Child of Waters, gracious be Prsni who hath
							Gods to guard her.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may the Rudras, Vasus, and Adityas accept the new hymn which we now
							are making.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							May all the Holy Ones of earth and heaven, and the Cow's offipring hear
							our invocation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who of Holy Gods are very holy, Immortal, knowing Law, whom man
							must worship,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 35: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these to-day give us broad paths to travel. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 36
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET the prayer issue from the seat of Order, for Surya with his beams
							hath loosed the cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With lofty ridges earth is far extended, and Agni's flame hath lit the
							spacious surface.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Asuras, O Varuna and Mitra, this hymn to you, like food, anew I
							offer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							One of you is a strong unerring Leader, and Mitra, speaking, stirreth
							men to labour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The movements of the gliding wind come hither: like cows, the springs
							are filled to overflowing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Born in the station e'en of lofty heaven the Bull hath loudly bellowed
							in this region.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May I bring hither with my song, O Indra, wise Aryaman who yokes thy
							dear Bay Horses,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Voracious, with thy noble car, O Hero, him who defeats the wrath of the
							malicious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							In their own place of sacrifice adorers worship to gain long life and
							win his friendship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath poured food on men when they have praised him; be this, the
							dearest reverence, paid to Rudra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Coming together, glorious, loudly roaring - Sarasvati, Mother of
							Floods, the seventh-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							With copious milk, with fair streams, strongly flowing, full swelling
							with the volume of their water;
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							And may the mighty Maruts, too, rejoicing, aid our devotion and protect
							our offspring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not swift-moving Aksara neglect us: they have increased our own
							appropriate riches,
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring ye the great Aramati before you, and Pusan as the Hero of the
							synod,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bhaga who looks upon this hymn with favour, and, as our strength, the
							bountiful Purandbi.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this our song of praise reach you, O Maruts, and Visnu guardian of
							the future infant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 36: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they vouchsafe the singer strength for offspring. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 37
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET your best-bearing car that must be lauded, ne'er injured, bring you
							Vajas and Rbhuksans.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fill you, fair-helmeted! with mighty Soma, thrice-mixed, at our
							libations to delight you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye who behold the light of heaven, Rbhuksans, give our rich patrons
							unmolested riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink, heavenly-natured. at our sacrifices, and give us bounties for
							the hymns we sing you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For thou, O Bounteous One, art used to giving, at parting treasure
							whether small or ample.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Filled full are both thine arms with great possessions: thy goodness
							keeps thee not from granting riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, high-famed, as Vaja and Rbhuksans, thou goest working, singing
							to the dwelling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of Bay Steeds, this day may we Vasisthas offer our prayers to thee
							and bring oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou winnest swift advancement for thy servant, through hymns, Lord of
							Bay Steeds, which thou hast favoured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							For thee with friendly succour have we battled, and when, O Indra, wilt
							thou grant us riches?
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To us thy priests a home, as 'twere, thou givest: when, Indra wilt thou
							recognize our praises?
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May thy strong Steed, through our ancestral worship, bring food and
							wealth with heroes to our dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Though Nirrti the Goddess reigneth round him, Autumns with food in
							plenty come to Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With three close Friends to length of days he cometh, he whom men let
							not rest at home in quiet.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Promise us gifts, O Savitar: may riches come unto us in Parvata's full
							bounty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 37: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the Celestial Guardian still attend us. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 38
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ON high hath Savitar, this God, extended the golden lustre which he
							spreads around him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now, now must Bhaga be invoked by mortals, Lord of great riches who
							distributes treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rise up, O Savitar whose hands are golden, and hear this man while
							sacrifice is offered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Spreading afar thy broad and wide effulgence, and bringing mortal men
							the food that feeds them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let Savitar the God he hymned with praises, to whom the Vasus, even,
							all sing glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sweet be our lauds to him whose due is worship: may he with all
							protection guard our princes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even he whom Aditi the Goddess praises, rejoicing in God Savitar's
							incitement:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even he who praise the high imperial Rulers, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman,
							sing in concert.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who come emulous to our oblation, dispensing bounty, from the
							earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they and Ahibudhnya hear our calling: guard us Varutri with the
							Ekadhenus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							This may the Lord of Life, entreated, grant us,-the wealth which
							Savitar the God possesses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The mighty calls on Bhaga for protection, on Bhaga calls the weak to
							give him riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bless us the Vajins when we call, while slowly they move, strong
							Singers, to the Gods' assembly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Crushing the wolf, the serpent, and the demons, may they completely
							banish all affliction.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Deep-skilled in Law eternal, deathless, Singers, O Vajins, help us in
							each fray for booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 38: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink of this meath, he satisfied, be joyful: then go on paths which
							Gods are wont to travel.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 39
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI, erect, hath shown enriching favour: the flame goes forward to the
							Gods' assembly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like car-borne men the stones their path have chosen: let the priest,
							quickened, celebrate our worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soft to the tread, their sacred grass is scattered: these go like Kings
							amid the band around them,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							At the folks early call on Night and Morning,-Vayu, and Pusan with his
							team, to bless us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here on their path the noble Gods proceeded: in the wide firmament the
							Beauteous decked them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bend your way hither, ye who travel widely: hear this our envoy who
							hath gone to meet you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For they are holy aids at sacrifices: all Gods approach the place of
							congregation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring these, desirous, to our worship, Agni, swift the Nisatyas, Bhaga,
							and Purandhi.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, to these men's hymns, from earth, from heaven, bring Mitra,
							Varuna, Indra, and Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Aryaman, and Aditi, and Visnu. Sarasvati be joyful, and the Maruts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as the holy wish, the gift is offered: may he, unsated, come when
							men desire him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give never-failing ever-conquering riches: with Gods for our allies may
							we be victors.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now have both worlds been praised by the Vasisthas; and holy Mitra,
							Varuna, and Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 39: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they, bright Deities, make our song supremest. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 40
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BE gathered all the audience of the synod: let us begin their praise
							whose course is rapid.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whate'er God Savitar this day produces, may we be where the Wealthy One
							distributes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							This, dealt from heaven ' may both the Worlds vouchsafe us, and Varuna,
							Indra, Aryaman, and Mitra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Goddess Aditi assign us riches, Vayu and Bhaga make them ours for
							ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong be the man and full of power, O Maruts, whom ye, borne on by
							spotted coursers, favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him, too, Sarasvati and Agni further, and there is none to rob him of
							his riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Varuna is guide of Law, he, Mitra, and Aryaman, the Kings, our
							work have finished.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Divine and foeless Aditi quickly listens. May these deliver us unharmed
							from trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With offerings I propitiate the branches of this swift-moving God, the
							bounteous Visnu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hence Rudra gained his Rudra-strength: O Asvins, ye sought the house
							that hath celestial viands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be not thou angry here, O glowing Pusan, for what Varutri and the
							Bounteous gave us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the swift-moving Gods protect and bless us, and Vata send us rain,
							wha wanders round us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now have both worlds been praised by the Vasisthas, and holy Mitra,
							Varuna, and Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 40: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they, bright Deities, make our song supremest. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 41
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI at dawn, and Indra we invoke at dawn, and Varuna and Mitra, and
							the Asvins twain.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bhaga at dawn, Pusan, and Brahmanaspati, Soma at dawn, Rudra we will
							invoke at dawn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							We will invoke strong, early-conquering Bhaga, the Son of Aditi, the
							great supporter:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thinking of whom, the poor, yea, even the mighty, even the King himself
							says, Give me Bhaga.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bhaga our guide, Bhaga whose gifts are faithful, favour this song, and
							give us wealth, O Bhaga.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bhaga, augment our store of kine and horses, Bhaga, may we be rich in
							men and heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may felicity be ours at present, and when the day approaches, and at
							noontide;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And may we still, O Bounteous One, at sunset be happy in the Deities'
							loving-kindness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Bhaga verily be bliss-bestower, and through him, Gods! may
							happiness attend us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							As such, O Bhaga, all with might invoke thee: as such be thou our
							Champion here, O Bhaga.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To this our worship may all Dawns incline them, and come to the pure
							place like Dadhikravan.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As strong steeds draw a chariot may they bring us hitherward Bhaga who
							discovers treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May blessed Mornings dawn on us for ever, with wealth of kine, of
							horses, and of heroes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 41: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Streaming with all abundance, pouring fatness. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 42
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET Brahmans and Angirases come forward, and let the roar of cloudy
							heaven surround us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Loud low the Milch-kine swimming in the waters: set be the stones that
							grace our holy service.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fair, Agni, is thy long-known path to travel: yoke for the juice tfiy
							bay, thy ruddy horses,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or red steeds, Hero-bearing, for the chamber. Seated, I call the
							Deities' generations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							They glorify your sacrifice with worship, yet the glad Priest near them
							is left unequalled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring the Gods hither, thou of many aspects: turn hitherward Aramati
							the Holy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the Guest hath made himself apparent, at ease reclining in
							the rich man's dwelling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, well-pleased, well-placed within the chamber gives to a house
							like this wealth worth the choosing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Accept this sacrifice of ours, O Agni; glorify it with Indra and the
							Maruts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here on our grass let Night and Dawn be seated: bring longing Varuna
							and Mitra hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus hath Vasistha praised victorious Agni, yearning for wealth that
							giveth all subsistence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 42: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he bestow on us food, strength, and riches. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 43
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING out the pious at your sacrifices to move with adorations Earth and
							Heaven-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Holy Singers, whose unmatched devotions, like a tree's branches,
							part in all directions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let sacrifice proceed like some fleet courser: with one accord lift ye
							on high the ladles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strew sacred grass meet for the solenm service: bright flames that love
							the Gods have mounted upward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like babes in arms reposing on their mother, let the Gods sit upon the
							grass's summit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let general fire make bright the flame of worship: scorn us not, Agni,
							in the Gods' assembly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gladly the Gods have let themselves be honoured, milking the copious
							streams of holy Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The highest might to-day is yours, the Vasits': come ye, as many as ye
							are, one-minded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, Agni, send us wealth among the people: may we be closely knit to
							thee, O Victor,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 43: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unharmed, and rich, and taking joy together. Preserve us evermore, ye
							ods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 44
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I CALL on Dadhikras, the first, to give  you aid, the Asvins, Bhaga,
							Dawn, and Agni kindled well,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, and Visnu, Pusan, Brahmanaspati, Adityas, Heaven and Earth, the
							Waters, and the Light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, rising, to the sacrifice we hasten, awaking Dadhikras with
							adorations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seating on sacred grass the Goddess Ila. let us invoke the sage
							swift-hearing Asvins.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							While I am thus arousing Dadhikravan I speak to Agni, Earth, and Dawn,
							and Surya,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The red, the brown of Varuna ever mindful: may they ward off from us
							all grief and trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Foremost is Dadhikravan, vigorous courser; in forefront of the cars,
							his way he knoweth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Closely allied with Surya and with Morning, Adityas, and Angirases, and
							Vasus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Dadhikras prepare the way we travel that we may pass along the path
							of Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 44: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni bear us, and the Heavenly Army: hear us all Mighty Ones whom
							none deceiveth.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 45
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY the God Savitar, rich in goodly treasures, filling the region,
							borne by steeds, come hither,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							In his hand holding much that makes men happy, lulling to slumber and
							arousing creatures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Golden, sublime, and easy in their motion, his arms extend unto the
							bounds of heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now shall that mightiness of his he lauded: even Surya yields to him in
							active vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this God Savitar, the Strong and Mighty, the Lord of precious
							wealth, vouchsafe us treasures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, advancing his far-spreading lustre, bestow on us the food that
							feedeth mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							These songs praise Savitar whose tongue is pleasant, praise him whose
							arms are full, whose hands are lovely.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 45: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							High vital strength, and manifold, may he grant us. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 46
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Rudra bring these songs, whose bow is firm and strong, the
							self-dependent God with swiftly-flying shafts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Wise, the Conqueror whom none may overcome, armed with
							sharp-pointed weapons: may he hear our call.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He through his lordship thinks on beings of the earth, on heavenly
							beings through his high imperial sway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come willingly to our doors that gladly welcome thee, and heal all
							sickness, Rudra., in our families.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May thy bright arrow which, shot down by thee from heaven, flieth upon
							the earth, pass us uninjured by.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, very gracious God, bast thousand medicines: inflict no evil on
							our sons or progeny.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Slay us not, nor abandon us, O Rudra let not thy noose, when thou art
							angry, seize us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 46: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us trimmed grass and fame among the living. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 47
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY we obtain this day from you, O Waters, that wave of pure
							refreshment, which the pious
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Made erst the special beverage of Indra, bright, stainless, rich in
							sweets and dropping fatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Floods' Offspring, he whose course is rapid, protect that wave
							most rich in sweets, O Waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That shall make Indra and the Vasus joyful. This may we gain from you
							to-day, we pious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							All-purifying, joying in their nature, to paths of Gods the Goddesses
							move onward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							They never violate the laws of Indra. Present the oil-rich offering to
							the Rivers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whom Surya with his bright beams hath attracted, and Indra dug the path
							for them to travel,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 47: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these Streams give us ample room and freedom. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 48
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YE liberal Heroes, Vajas and Rbhuksans, come and delight you with our
							flowing Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May your strength, Vibhus, as ye come to meet us, turn hitherward your
							car that brings men profit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we as Rbhu with your Rbhus conquer strength with our strength, as
							Vibhus with the Vibhus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Vaja aid us in the fight for booty, and helped by Indra may we
							quell the foeman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For they rule many tribes with high dominion, and conquer all their
							foes in close encounter.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Indra, Vibhvan, Vaja, and Rbhuksan destroy by turns the wicked
							foeman's valour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, Deities, give us ample room and freedom: be all of you,
							one-minded, our protection.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 48: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							So let the Vasus grant us strength and vigour. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 49
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FORTH from the middle of the flood the Waters-their chief the Sea-flow
							cleansing, never sleeping.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, the Bull, the Thunderer, dug their channels: here let those
							Waters, Goddesses, protect me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Waters which come from heaven, or those that wander dug from the earth,
							or flowing free by nature,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bright, purifying, speeding to the Ocean, here let those Waters.
							Goddesses, protect me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those amid whom goes Varuna the Sovran, he who discriminates men's
							truth and falsehood-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Distilling meath, the bright, the purifying, here let those Waters,
							Goddesses, protect me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They from whom Varuna the King, and Soma, and all the Deities drink
							strength and vigour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 49: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They into whom Vaisvanara Agni entered, here let those Waters,
							Goddesses, protect Me.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 50
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O MITRA-VARUNA, guard and protect me here: let not that come to me
							which nests within and swells.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I drive afar the scorpion hateful to the sight: let not the winding
							worm touch me and wound my foot.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eruption that appears upon the twofold joints, and that which
							overspreads the ankles and the knees,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the refulgent Agni banish far away let not the winding worm touch
							me and wound my foot.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The poison that is formed upon the Salmali, that which is found in
							streams, that which the plants produce,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							All this may all the Gods banish and drive away: let not the winding
							worm touch me and wound my foot.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The steep declivities, the valleys, and the heights, the channels full
							of water, and the waterless-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May those who swell with water, gracious Goddesses, never afflict us
							with the Sipada disease, may all the rivers keep us free from Simida.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 51
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 51: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THROUGH the Adityas' most auspicious shelter, through their most recent
							succour may we conquer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they, the Mighty, giving ear, establish this sacrifice, to make us
							free and sinless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 51: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let Aditi rejoice and the Adityas, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman, most
							righteous.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they, the Guardians of the world, protect us, and, to show favour,
							drink this day our Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 51: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							All Universal Deities, the Maruts, all the Adityas, yea, and all the
							Rbhus,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, and Agni, and the Asvins, lauded. Preserve us evermore, ye Gods,
							with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 52
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 52: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY we be free from every bond, Adityas! a castle among Gods and men,
							ye Vasus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Winning, may we win Varuna and Mitra, and, being, may we be, O Earth
							and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 52: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Varuna and Mitra grant this blessing, our Guardians, shelter to our
							seed and offspring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us not suffer for another's trespass. nor do the thing that ye, O
							Vasus, punish.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 52: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The ever-prompt Angirases, imploring riches from Savitar the God,
							obtained them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may our Father who is great and holy, and all the Gods, accordant,
							grant this favour.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 53
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 53: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AS priest with solemn rites and adorations I worship Heaven and Earth,
							the High and Holy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To them, great Parents of the Gods, have sages of ancient time,
							singing, assigned precedence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 53: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With newest hymns set in the seat of Order, those the Two Parents, born
							before all others,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come, Heaven and Earth, with the Celestial People, hither to us, for
							strong is your protection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 53: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, Heaven and Earth, ye hold in your possession full many a treasure
							for the liberal giver.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant us that wealth which comes in free abundance. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 54
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 54: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ACKNOWLEDGE us, O Guardian of the Homestead: bring no disease, and give
							us happy entrance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whate'er we ask of thee, be pleased to grant it, and prosper thou
							quadrupeds and bipeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 54: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Protector of the Home, be our promoter: increase our wealth in kine and
							steeds, O Indu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we be ever-youthful in thy friendship: be pleased in us as in his
							sons a father.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 54: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through thy dear fellowship that bringeth welfare, may we be victors,
							Guardian of the Dwelling!
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Protect our happiness in rest and labour. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 55
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							VASTOSPATI, who killest all disease and wearest every form,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be an auspicious Friend to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, O bright Son of Sarama, thou showest, tawny-hued! thy teeth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							They gleam like lances' points within thy mouth when thou wouldst bite;
							go thou to steep.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sarama's Son, retrace thy way: bark at the robber and the thief.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							At Indra's singers barkest thou? Why dust thou seek to terrify us? Go
							to sleep.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be on thy guard against the boar, and let the boar beware of thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							At Indra's singers barkest thou? Why dost thou seek to terrify us? Go
							to sleep.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sleep mother, let the father sleep, sleep dog and master of the house.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let all the kinsmen sleep, sleep all the people who are round about.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The man who sits, the man who walks, and whosoever looks on us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of these we closely shut the eyes, even as we closely shut this house.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Bull who hath a thousand horns, who rises up from out the sea,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							By him the Strong and Mighty One we lull and make the people sleep.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The women sleeping in the court, lying without, or stretched on beds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The matrons with their odorous sweetsthese, one and all, we lull to
							sleep.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 56
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Wno are these radiant men in serried rank, Rudra's young heroes borne by
						noble steeds?
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Verily no one knoweth whence they sprang: they, and they only, know each
						other's birth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 3
				-
					-
						They strew each other with their blasts, these Hawks: they strove together,
						roaring like the wind.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 4
				-
					-
						A sage was he who knew these mysteries, what in her udder mighty Prsni
						bore.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Ever victorious, through the Maruts, be this band of Heroes, nursing manly
						strength,
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Most bright in splendour, flectest on their way, close-knit to glory,
						strong with varied power.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Yea, mighty is your power and firm your strength: so, potent, with the
						Maruts, be the band.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Bright is your spirit, wrathful are your minds: your bold troop's minstrel
						is like one inspired.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Ever avert your blazing shaft from us, and let not your displeasure reach
						us here
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Your dear names, conquering Maruts, we invoke, calling aloud till we are
						satisfied.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Well-armed, impetuous in their haste, they deck themselves, their forms,
						with oblations: to you, the pure, ornaments made of gold.
					-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pure, Maruts, pure yourselves, are your oblations: to you, the pure,
							pure sacrifice I offer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							By Law they came to truth, the Law's observers, bright by their birth,
							and pure, and sanctifying.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your rings, O Maruts, rest upon your shoulders, and chains of gold are
							twined upon your bosoms.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gleaming with drops of rain, like lightning-flashes, after your wont ye
							whirl about your weapons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wide in the depth of air spread forth your glories, far, most adorable,
							ye bear your titles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Maruts, accept this thousandfold allotment of household sacrifice and
							household treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							If, Maruts, ye regard the praise recited here at this mighty singer
							invocation,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us quickly wealth with noble heroes, wealth which no man uho
							hateth us may injure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Maruts, fleet as coursers, while they deck them like youths
							spectators of a festal meeting,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Linger, like beauteous colts, about the dwelling, like frisking calves,
							these who pour down the water.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may the Maruts help us and be gracious, bringing free room to lovely
							Earth and Heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far be your bolt that slayeth men and cattle. Ye Vasus, turn yourselves
							to us with blessings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							The priest, when seated, loudly calls you, Maruts, praising in song
							your universal bounty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, Bulls! who hath so much in his possession, free from duplicity,
							with hymns invokes you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Maruts bring the swift man to a stand-still, and strength with
							mightier strength they break and humble
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							These guard the singer from the man who hates him and lay their sore
							displeasure on the wicked.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Maruts rouse even the poor and needy: the Vasus love him as an
							active champion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drive to a distance, O ye Bulls, the darkness: give us full store of
							children and descendants.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Never, O Maruts, may we lose your bounty, nor, car-borne Lords! be
							hitidmost when ye deal it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us a share in that delightful treasure, the genuine wealth that,
							Bulls! is your possession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the men in fury rush together for running streams, for
							pastures, and for houses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then, O ye Maruts, ye who spring from Rudra, be our protectors in the
							strife with foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							Full many a deed ye did for our forefathers worthy of lauds which, even
							of old, they sang you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							lle strong man, with the Maruts, wins in battle, the charger, with the
							Maruts, gains the booty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ours, O ye Maruts, be the vigorous Hero, the Lord Divine of men, the
							strong Sustainer,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 56: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							With whom to fair lands we may cross the waters, and dwell in our own
							home with you beside us.
						-
