					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							They cause even spacious heaven and earth to tremble, they make the
							spring flow when they come, the Mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Maruts watch the man who sings their praises, promoters of the
							thought of him who worships.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seat you on sacred grass in our assembly, this day, with friendly
							minds, to share the banquet.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							No others gleam so brightly as these Maruts with their own forms, their
							golden gauds, their weapons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With all adornments, decking earth and heaven, they heighten, for
							bright show, their common splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far from us be your blazing dart, O Maruts, when we, through human
							frailty, sin against you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us not he exposed to that, ye Holy! May your most loving favour
							still attend us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May even what we have done delight the Maruts, the blameless Ones, the
							bright, the purifying.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Further us, O ye Holy, with your kindness: advance us mightily that we
							may prosper.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							And may the Maruts, praised by all their titles, Heroes, enjoy the
							taste of our oblations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us of Amrta for the sake of offspring: awake the excellent fair
							stores of riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither, ye Maruts, praised, with all your succours, with all felicity
							come to our princes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 57: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, of themselves, a hundredfold increase us. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 58
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING to the troop that pours down rain in common, the Mighty Company of
							celestial nature.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							They make the world-halves tremble with their greatness: from depths of
							earth and sky they reach to heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, your birth, Maruts, was with wild commotion, ye who move swiftly,
							fierce in wrath, terrific.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye all-surpassing in your might and vigour, each looker on the light
							fears at your coming.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give ample vital power unto our princes let our fair praises gratify
							the Maruts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As the way travelled helpeth people onward, so further us with your
							delightful succours.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your favoured singer counts his wealth by hundreds: the strong steed
							whom ye favour wins a thousand.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Sovran whom ye aid destroys the foeman. May this your gift, ye
							Shakers, be distinguished.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I call, as such, the Sons of bounteous Rudra: will not the Maruts turn
							again to us-ward?
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							What secret sin or open stirs their anger, that we implore the Swift
							Ones to forgive us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							This eulogy of the Bounteous hath been spoken: accept, ye Maruts, this
							our hymn of praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 58: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Bulls, keep those who hate us at a distance. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 59
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHOMSO ye rescue here and there, whomso ye guide, O Deities,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him give shelter, Agni, Mitra, Varuna, ye Maruts, and thou Aryaman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through your kind favour, Gods, on some auspicious day, the worshipper
							subdues his foes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That man increases home and strengthening ample food who brings you
							offerings as ye list.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vasistha will not overlook the lowliest one among you all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Maruts, of our Soma juice effused to-day drink all of you with eager
							haste.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your succour in the battle injures not the man to whom ye, Heroes,
							grant your gifts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May your most recent favour turn to us again. Come quickly, ye who fain
							would drink.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come hitherward to drink the juice, O ye whose bounties give you joy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These offerings are for you, these, Maruts, I present. Go not to any
							place but this.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sit on our sacred grass, be graciously inclined to give the wealth for
							which we long,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							To take delight, ye Maruts, Friends of all, with Svaha, in sweet Soma
							juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Decking the beauty of their forms in secret the Swans with purple backs
							have flown down hither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Around me all the Company hath settled, like joyous Heroes glad in our
							libation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Maruts, the man whose wrath is hard to master, he who would slay us ere
							we think, O Vasus,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he be tangled in the toils of mischief; smite ye him down with your
							most flaming weapon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Maruts, ye consuming Gods, enjoy this offering brought for you,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							To help us, ye who slay the foe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sharers of household sacrifice, come, Maruts, stay not far away,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							That ye may help us, Bounteous Ones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here, Self-strong Maruts, yea, even here. ye Sages with your sunbright
							skins
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							I dedicate your sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tryambaka we worship, sweet augmenter of prosperity.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 59: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							As from its stem the cucumber, so may I be released from death, not
							reft of immortality.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 60
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHEN thou, O Sun, this day, arising sinless, shalt speak the truth to
							Varuna and Mitra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Aditi, may all the Deities love us, and thou, O Aryaman, while we are
							singing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Looking on man, O Varuna and Mitra, this Sun ascendeth up by both the
							pathways,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guardian of all things fixt, of all that moveth, beholding good and
							evil acts of mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He from their home hath yoked the Seven gold Coursers who, dropping oil
							and fatness, carry Surya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yours, Varuna and Mitra, he surveyeth the worlds and living creatures
							like a herdsman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your coursers rich in store of sweets have mounted: to the bright ocean
							Surya hath ascended,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For whom the Adityas make his pathway ready, Aryaman, Mitra, Varuna,
							accordant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							For these, even Aryaman, Varuna and Mitra, are the chastisers of all
							guile and falsehood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These, Aditi's Sons, infallible and mighty, have waxen in the home of
							law Eternal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							These, Mitra, Varuna whom none deceiveth, with great power quicken even
							the fool to wisdom,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, wakening, moreover, thoughtful insight, lead it by easy paths o'er
							grief and trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							They ever vigilant, with eyes that close not, caring for heaven and
							earth, lead on the thoughtless.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even in the river's bed there is a shallow. across this broad expanse
							may they conduct us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Aditi and Varuna and Mitra, like guardians, give Sudas their
							friendly shelter,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Granting him sons and lineal succession, let us not, bold ones! move
							the Gods to anger.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he with ofierings purify the altar from any stains of Varuna's
							reviler.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aryaman save us us all those who hate us: give room and freedom to
							Sudas, ye Mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hid from our eyes is their resplendent meeting: by their mysterious
							might they hold dominion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Heroes! we cry trembling in fear before you, even in the greatness of
							your power have mercy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who wins favour for his prayer by worship, that he may gain him
							strength and highest riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							That good man's mind the Mighty Ones will follow: they have brought
							comfort to his spacious dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							This priestly task, Gods! Varuna and Mitra! hath been performed for you
							at sacrifices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 60: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Convey us safely over every peril. Preserve us evermore, ye Gods, with
							blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 61
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O VARUNA and Mitra, Surya spreading the beauteous light of you Twain
							Gods ariseth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who beholdetb all existing creatures observetb well the zeal that is
							in mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The holy sage, renowned afar, directeth his hymns to you, O Varuna and
							Mitra,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He whose devotions, sapient Gods, ye favour so that ye fill, as 'twere,
							with power his autumns.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							From the wide earth, O Varuna and Mitra from the great lofty heaven,
							ye, Bounteous Givers, -
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have in the fields and houses set your warder-, who visit every spot
							and watch unceasing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I praise the strength of Varuna and Mitra that strength, by mightiness,
							keeps both worlds asunder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Heroless pass the months of the ungodly he who loves sacrifice makes
							his home enduring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Steers, all infallible are these your people in whom no wondrous thing
							is seen, no worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guile follows close the men who are untruthful: no secrets may be
							hidden from your knowledge.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will exalt your sacrifice with homage: as priest, I, Mitra-Varuna,
							invoke you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these new hymns and prayers that I have fashioned delight you to
							the profit of the singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							This priestly task, Gods! Varuna and Mitra! hath been performed for you
							at sacrifices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 61: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Convey us safely over every peril. Preserve us evermore, ye Gods, with
							blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 62
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SURYA hath sent aloft his beams of splendour o'er all the tribes of men
							in countless places.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Together with the heaven he shines apparent, formed by his Makers well
							with power and wisdom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							So hast thou mounted up before us, Surya, through these our praises,
							with fleet dappled horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Declare us free from all offence to Mitra, and Varuna, and Aryaman, and
							Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May holy Agni, Varuna, and Mitra send down their riches upon us in
							thousands.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they, the Bright Ones, make our praise-song perfect, and, when we
							laud them, grant us all our wishes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O undivided Heaven and Earth, preserve us, us, Lofty Ones! your
							nobIy-born descendants.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us not anger Varuna, nor Vayu, nor him, the dearest Friend of
							mortals, Mitra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stretch forth your arms and let our lives be lengthened: with fatness
							dew the pastures of our cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Youthful, make us famed among the people: hear, Mitra-Varuna, these
							mine invocations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now Mitra, Varuna, Aryaman vouchsafe us freedom and room, for us and
							for our children.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 62: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we find paths all fair and good to travel. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 63
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COMMON to all mankind, auspicious Surya, he who beholdeth all, is
							mounting upward;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The God, the eye of Varuna and Mitra, who rolled up darkness like a
							piece of leather.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surya's great ensign, restless as the billow, that urgeth men to
							action, is advancing:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Onward he still would roll the wheel well-rounded, which Etasa,
							harnessed to the car-pole, moveth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Refulgent from the bosom of the Mornings, he in Whom singers take
							delight ascendeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							This Savitar, God, is my chief joy and pleasure, who breaketh not the
							universal statute.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Golden, far-seeing, from the heaven he riseth: far is his goal, he
							hasteth on resplendent.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men, verily, inspirited by Surya speed to their aims and do the work
							assigned them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where the irrunortals have prepared his pathway he flieth through the
							region like a falcon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With homage and oblations will we serve you, O Mitra-Varuna, when the
							Sun hath risen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now Mitra, Varuna, Aryaman vouchsafe us freedom and room, for us and
							for our children.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 63: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we find paths all fair and good to travel. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 64
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YE Twain who rule, in heaven and earth, the region, clothed be your
							clouds in robes of oil and fatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the imperial Varuna, and Mitra, and high-born Aryaman accept our
							presents.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Kings, guards of rrtighty everlasting Order, come hitherward, ye
							Princes, Lords of Rivers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Send us from heaven, O Varuna and Mitra, rain and sweet food, ye who
							pour down your bounties.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the dear God, and Varuna and Mitra conduct us by the most effective
							pathways,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							That foes may say unto Sudas our chieftain, May, we, too, joy in food
							with Gods to guard us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him who hath wrought for you this car in spirit, who makes the song
							rise upward and sustains it,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bedew with fatness, Varuna nd Mitra ye Kings, make glad the pleasant
							dwelling-places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you this laud, O Varuna and Mitra is offered like bright Soma juice
							to Vayu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 64: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Favour our songs of praise, wake thought and spirit. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 65
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH hymns I call you, when the Sun hath risen, Mitra, and Varuna whose
							thoughts are holy,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose Power Divine, supreme and everlasting, comes with good heed at
							each man's supplication.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For they are Asuras of Gods, the friendly make, both of you, our lands
							exceeding fruitful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we obtain you, Varuna and Mitra, wherever Heaven and Earth and days
							may bless us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bonds of the sinner, they bear many nooses: the wicked mortal hardly
							may escape them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Varuna-Mitra, may your path of Order bear us o'er trouble as a boat
							o'er waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come, taste our offering, Varuna and Mitra: bedew our pasture wil sweet
							food and fatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pour down in plenty here upon the people the choicest of your fair
							celestial water.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you this laud, O Varuna and Mitra, is offered, like bright Soma
							juice to Vayu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 65: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Favour our songs of praise, wake thought and spirit. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 66
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 66: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 66: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET our strong hymn of praise go forth, the laud of Mitra-Varuna,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 66: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With homage to that high-born Pair;
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 66: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 66: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Two exceeding wise, the Sons of Daksa, whom the gods ordained
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 66: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
