							are chanted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 70: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 70: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the thought, this is the song, O Asvins: accept this hymn of
							ours, ye Steers, with favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 70: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these our prayers addressed to you come nigh you. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 71
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Night retireth from the Dawn her Sister; the Dark one yieldeth to
							the Red her pathway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us invoke you rich in steeds and cattle - by day and night keep far
							from us the arrow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bearing rich treasure in your car, O Asvins, come to the mortal who
							presents oblation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Keep at a distance penury and sickness; Lovers of Sweetness, day and
							night preserve us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May your strong horses, seeking bliss, bring hither your chariot at the
							earliest flush of morning.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With coursers yoked by Law drive hither, Asvins, your car whose reins
							are light, laden with treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The chariot, Princes, that conveys you, moving at daylight,
							triple-seated, fraught with riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even with this come unto us, Nasatyas, that laden with all food it may
							approach us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye freed Cyavana from old age and weakness: ye brought the courser
							fleet of food to Pedu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye rescued Atri from distress and darkness, and loosed for Jahusa the
							bonds that bound him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the thought, this is the song, O Asvins: accept this hymn of
							ours, ye Steers, With favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 71: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these our prayers addressed to you come nigh you. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 72
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COME, O Nasatyas, on your car resplendent, rich in abundant wealth of
							kine and horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As harnessed steeds, all our laudations follow you whose forms shine
							with most delightful beauty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come with the Gods associate, come ye hither to us, Nasatyas, with your
							car accordant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							'Twixt you and us there is ancestral friendship and common kin:
							remember and regard it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Awakened are the songs that praise the Asvins, the kindred prayers and
							the Celestial Mornings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Inviting those we long for, Earth and Heaven, the singer calleth these
							Nasatyas hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the Dawns break forth in light, O Asvins, to you the poets
							offer their devotions.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							God Savitar hath sent aloft his splendour, and fires sing praises with
							the kindled fuel.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come from the west, come from the cast, Nasatyas, come, Asvins, from
							below and from above us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 72: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring wealth from all sides for the Fivefold People. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 73
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WE have o'erpassed the limit of this darkness while, worshipping the
							Gods, we sang their praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The song invoketh both Immortal Asvins far-reaching, born of old, great
							WonderWorkers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							And, O Nasatyas, man's dear Priest is seated, who brings to sacrifice
							and offers worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be near and taste the pleasant juice, O Asvins: with food, I call you
							to the sacrifices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							We choosing you, have let our worship follow its course: ye Steers,
							accept this hymn with favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Obeying you as your appointed servant, Vasistha singing hath with lauds
							aroused you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							And these Two Priests come nigh unto our people, united, demon-slayers,
							mighty-handed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The juices that exhilarate are mingled. Injure us not, but come with
							happy fortune.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come from the west, come from the cast, Nasatyas, come, Asvins, from
							below and from above us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 73: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring wealth from all sides for the Fivefold People. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 74
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE morning sacrifices call you, Asvins, at the break of day.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For help have I invoked you rich in power and might: for, house by
							house ye visit all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Heroes, ye bestow wonderful nourishment. send it to him whose songs
							are sweet
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accordant, both of you, drive your car down to us, and drink the
							savoury Soma juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Approach ye and be near to us. drink, O ye Asvins, of the meath.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Draw forth the milk, ye Mighty, rich in genuine wealth: injure us not,
							and come to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The horses that convey you in their rapid flight down to the
							worshipper's abode,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With these your speedy coursers, Heroes, Asvins, come, ye Gods, come
							well-inclined to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, verily, our princes seek the Asvins in pursuit of food.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These shall give lasting glory to our liberal lords, and, both
							Nasatyas, shelter us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those who have led the way, like cars, offending none, those who are
							guardians of the men-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 74: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Also through their own might the heroes have grown strong, and dwell in
							safe and happy homes.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 75
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BORN in the heavens the Dawn hath flushed, and showing her majesty is
							come as Law ordaineth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							She hath uncovered fiends and hateful darkness; best of Angirases, hath
							waked the pathways.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rouse us this day to high and happy fortune: to great felicity, O Dawn,
							promote us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us manifold and splendid riches, famed among mortals,
							man-befriending Goddess!
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							See, lovely Morning's everlasting splendours, bright with their varied
							colours, have approached us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Filling the region of mid-air, producing the rites of holy worship,
							they have mounted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							She yokes her chariot far away, and swiftly visits the lands where the
							Five Tribes are settled,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Looking upon the works and ways of mortals, Daughter of Heaven, the
							world's Imperial Lady.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							She who is rich in spoil, the Spouse of Surya, wondrously opulent,
							rules all wealth and treasures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Consumer of our youth, the seers extol her: lauded by priests rich Dawn
							shines out refulgent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Apparent are the steeds of varied colour, the red steeds carrying
							resplendent Morning.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							On her all-lovely car she comes, the Fair One, and brings rich treasure
							for her faithful servant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							True with the True and Mighty with the Mighty, with Gods a Goddess,
							Holy with the Holy,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							She brake strong fences down and gave the cattle: the kine were lowing
							as they greeted Morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Dawn, now give us wealth in kine and heroes, and horses, fraught with
							manifold enjoyment.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 75: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Protect our sacred grass from man's reproaches. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 76
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SAVITAR God of all men hath sent upward his light, designed for all
							mankind, immortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through the Gods' power that Eye was first created. Dawn hath made all
							the universe apparent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I see the paths which Gods are wont to travel, innocuous paths made
							ready by the Vasus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eastward the flag of Dawn hath been uplifted; she hath come hither o'er
							the tops of houses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Great is, in truth, the number of the Mornings which were aforetime at
							the Sun's uprising.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Since thou, O Dawn, hast been beheld repairing as to thy love, as one
							no more to leave him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They were the Gods' companions at the banquet, the ancient sages true
							to Law Eternal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Fathers found the light that lay in darkness, and with effectual
							words begat the Morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Meeting together in the same enclosure, they strive not, ofone mind,
							one with another.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							They never break the Gods' eternal statutes, and injure none, in
							rivalry with Vasus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Extolling thee, Blest Goddess, the Vasisthas, awake at early mom, with
							lauds implore thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Leader of kine and Queen of all that strengthens, shine, come as first
							to us, O high-born Morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							She bringeth bounty and sweet charm of voices. The flushing Dawn is
							sung by the Vasisthas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 76: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giving us riches famed to distant places. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 77
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SHE hath shone brightly like a youthful woman, stirring to motion every
							living creature.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni hath come to feed on mortal? fuel. She hath made light and chased
							away the darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Turned to this All, far-spreading, she hath risen and shone in
							brightness with white robes about her.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							She hath beamed forth lovely with golden colours, Mother of kine, Guide
							of the days she bringeth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bearing the Gods' own Eye, auspicious Lady, leading her Courser white
							and fair to look on,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Distinguished by her bean-is Dawn shines apparent, come forth to all
							the world with wondrous treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Draw nigh with wealth and dawn away the foeman: prepare for us wide
							pasture free from danger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drive away those who hate us, bring us riches: pour bounty, opulent
							Lady, on the singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send thy most excellent beams to shine and light us, giving us
							lengthened days, O Dawn, O Goddess,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Granting us food, thou who hast all things precious, and bounty rich in
							chariots, kine, and horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Usas, nobly-born, Daughter of Heaven, whom the Vasisthas with their
							hymns make mighty,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 77: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bestow thou on us vast and glorious riches. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 78
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WE have beheld her earliest lights approaching: her many glories part,
							on high, asunder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							On car sublime, refulgent, wending hither, O Usas, bring the Wealth
							that makes us happy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The fire well-kindIed sings aloud to greet her, and with their hymns
							the priests are chaming welcome.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Usas approaches in her splendour, driving all evil darkness far away,
							the Goddess.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Apparent eastward are those lights of Morning, sending out lustre, as
							they rise, around them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							She hath brought forth Sun, sacrifice, and Agni, and far away hath fled
							detested darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rich Daughter of the Sky, we all behold her, yea, all men look on Dawn
							as she is breaking.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							fler car that moves self-harnessed hath she mounted, the car drawn
							onward by her well-yoked horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Inspired with loving thoughts this day to greet thee, we and our
							wealthy nobles have awakened.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Show yourselves fruitful, Dawns, as ye are rising. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 79
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ROUSING the lands where men's Five Tribes are settled, Dawn hath
							disclosed the pathways of the people.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							She hath sent out her sheen with beauteous oxen. The Sun with light
							hath opened earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They paint their bright rays on the sky's far limits. the Dawns come on
							like tribes arrayed for battle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy cattle, closely shutting up the darkness, as Savitar spreads his
							arms, give forth their lustre.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wealthy, most like to Indra, Dawn hath risen, and brought forth lauds
							that shall promote our welfare.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Daughter of Heaven, a Goddess, she distributes, best of Angirases,
							treasures to the pious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bestow on us, O Dawn, that ample bounty which thou didst send to those
							who sang thy praises;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou whom with bellowings of a bull they quickened: thou didst unbar
							the firm-set mountain's portals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Impelling every God to grant his bounty sending to us the charm of
							pleasant voices,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us thoughts, for profit, as thou breakest. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 80
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 80: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 80: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE priests, Vasisthas, are the first awakened to welcome Usas with
							their songs and praises,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 80: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who makes surrounding regions part asunder,and shows apparent all
							existing creatures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 80: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 80: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Giving fresh life when she hath hid the darkness, this Dawn hath
							wakened there with new-born lustre.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 80: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Youthful and unrestrained she cometh forward: she hath turned thoughts
							to Sun and fire and worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 80: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 80: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May blessed Mornings shine on us for ever, with wealth of kine, of
							horses, and of heroes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 80: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Streaming with all abundance, pouring fatness. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 81
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ADVANCING, sending forth her rays, the Daughter of the Sky is seen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Uncovering, that we may see, the mighty gloom, the friendly Lady makes
							the light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sun ascending, the refulgent Star, pours down his beams together
							with the Dawn.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Dawn, at thine arising, and the Sun's, may we attain the share
							allotted us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Promptly we woke to welcome thee, O Usas, Daughter of the Sky,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee, Bounteous One, who bringest all we long to have, and to the
							offerer health and wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, dawning, workest fain to light the great world, yea, heaven,
							Goddess! that it may be seen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							We yearn to be thine own, Dealer of Wealth: may we be to this Mother
							like her sons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring us that wondrous bounty, Dawn, that shall be famed most far away.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							What, Child of Heaven, thou hast of nourishment for man, bestow thou on
							us to enjoy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give to our princes opulence and immortal fame, and strength in herds
							of kine to us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 81: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May she who prompts the wealthy, Lady of sweet strains, may Usas dawn
							our foes away.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 82
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GRANT us your strong protection, IndraVaruna, our people, and our
							family, for sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we subdue in fight our evil-hearted foes, him who attacks the man
							steadfast in lengthened rites.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra-Varuna, mighty and very rich One of you is called Monarch and
							One Autocrat.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							All Gods in the most lofty region of the air have, O ye Steers,
							combined all power and might in you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye with your strength have pierced the fountains of the floods: the Sun
							have ye brought forward as the Lord in heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cheered by this magic draught ye, Indra-Varuna, made the dry places
							stream, made songs of praise flow forth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							In battels and in frays we ministering priests, kneeling upon our knees
							for furtherance of our weal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Invoke you, only you, the Lords of twofold wealth, you prompt to hear,
							we bards, O Indra-Varuna.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra-Varuna, as ye created all these creatures of the world by your
							surpassing might,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							In peace and quiet Mitra waits on Varuna, the Other, awful, with the
							Maruis seeks renown.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Varuna's high worth may shine preeminent, these Twain have
							measured each his proper power and might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The One subdueth the destructive enemy; the Other with a few furthereth
							many a man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							No trouble, no misfortune, Indra-Varuna, no woe from any side assails
							the mortal man
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose sacrifice, O Gods, ye visit and enjoy: ne'er doth the crafty
							guile of mortal injure him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							With your divine protection, Heroes, come to us: mine invncation hear,
							if ye be pleased therewith.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bestow ye upon us, O Indra-Varuna, your friendship and your kinship and
							your favouring grace.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							In battle after battle, Indra-Varuna, be ye our Champions, ye who are
							the peoples' strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When both opposing bands invoke you for the fight, and men that they
							may gain offspring and progeny.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra, Varuna, Mitra, and Aryaman vouchsafe us glory and great
							shelter spreading far.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 82: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							We think of the beneficent light of Aditi, and Savitar's song of
							praise, the God who strengthens Law.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 83
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LOOKING to you and your alliance, O ye Men, armed with broad axes they
							went forward, fain for spoil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye smote and slew his Dasa and his Aryan enemies, and helped Sudas with
							favour, Indra-Varuna.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where heroes come together with their banners raised, in the encounter
							where is naught for us to love,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where all things that behold the light are terrified, there did ye
							comfort us, O Indra-Varuna.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The boundaries of earth were seen all dark with dust: O Indra-Varuna,
							the shout went up to heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The enmities of the people compassed me about. Ye heard my calling and
							ye came to me with help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With your resistless weapons, Indra-Varuna, ye conquered Bheda and ye
							gave Sudas your aid.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye heard the prayers of these amid the cries of war: effectual was the
							service of the Trtsus' priest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra-Varuna, the wickedness of foes and mine assailants' hatred
							sorely trouble me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Twain are Lords of riches both of earth and heaven: so grant to us
							your aid on the decisive day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The men of both the hosts invoked you in the fight, Indra and Varuna,
							that they might win the wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time ye helped Sudas, with all the Trtsu folk, when the Ten Kings
							had pressed him down in their attack.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ten Kings who worshipped not, O Indra-Varuna, confederate, in war
							prevailed not o'er Sudas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							True was the boast of heroes sitting at the feast: so at their
							invocations Gods were on their side.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra-Varuna, ye gave Sudas your aid when the Ten Kings in battle
							compassed him about,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							There where the white-robed Trtsus with their braided hair, skilled in
							song worshipped you with homage and with hymn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							One of you Twain destroys the Vrtras in the fight, the Other evermore
							maintains his holy Laws.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							We call on you, ye Mighty, with our hymns of praise. Vouchsafe us your
							protection, Indra-Varuna.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra, Varuna, Mitra, and Aryaman vouchsafe us glory and great
							shelter spreading far.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 83: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							We think of the beneficent light of Aditi, and Savitar's song of
							praise, the God who strengthens Law.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 84
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							KINGS, Indra-Varuna, I would turn you hither to this our sacrifice with
							gifts and homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Held in both arms the ladle, dropping fatness, goes of itself to you
							whose forms are varied.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dyaus quickens and promotes your high dominion who bind with bonds not
							wrought of rope or cordage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far from us still be Varuna's displeasure may Indra give us spacious
							room to dwell in.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Make ye our sacrifice fair amid the assemblies: make ye our prayers
							approved among our princes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May God-sent riches come for our possession: further ye us with your
							delightful succours.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra-Varuna, vouchsafe us riches with store of treasure, food, and
							every blessing;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For the Aditya, banisher of falsehood, the Hero, dealeth wealth in
							boundless plenty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this my song reach Varuna and Indra, and, strongly urging, win me
							sons and offspring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 84: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To the Gods' banquet may we go with riches. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 85
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FOR you I deck a harmless hymn, presenting the Soma juice to Varuna and
							Indra-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							A hymn that shines like heavenly Dawn with fatness. May they be near us
							on the march and guard us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here where the arrows fall amid the banners both hosts invoke the Gods
							in emulation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra-Varuna, smite back those-our foemen,yea, smite them withyour
							shaft to every quarter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Self-lucid in their seats, e'en heavenly Waters endowed with Godhead
							Varuna and Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							One of these holds the folk distinct and sundered, the Other smites and
							slays resistless foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wise be the priest and skilled in Law Eternal, who with his sacred
							gifts and oration.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brings you to aid us with your might, Adityas: let him have viands to
							promote his welfare.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this my song reach Varuna and Indra, and, strongly urging, win me
							sons and offspring.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 85: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To the Gods' banquet may we go with riches. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 86
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WISE, verily, are creatures through his greatness who stayed ever,
							spacious heaven and earth asunder;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who urged the high and mighty sky to motion, the Star of old, and
							spread the earth before him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With mine own heart I commune on the question how Varuna and I may be
							united.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							What gift of mine will he accept unangered? When may I calmly look and
							find him gracious?
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fain to know this in I question others: I seek the wise, O Varuna, and
							ask them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							This one same answer even the sages gave me, "Surely this Varuna is
							angry with thee."
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							What, Varuna, hath been my chief transgression, that thou wouldst slay
							the friend who sings thy praises?
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Tell me, Unconquerable Lord, and quickly sinless will I approach thee
							with mine homage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Free us from sins committed by our fathers, from those wherein we have
							ourselves offended.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							O King, loose, like a thief who feeds the cattle, as from the cord a
							calf, set free Vasistha.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not our own will betrayed us, but seduction, thoughtlessness, Varuna
							wine, dice, or anger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The old is near to lead astray the younger: even sleep removeth not all
							evil-doing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Slavelike may I do service to the Bounteous, serve, free from sin, the
							God inclined to anger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							This gentle Lord gives wisdom to the simple: the wiser God leads on the
							wise to riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Lord, O Varuna, may this laudation come close to thed and lie within
							thy spirit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 86: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May it be well with us in rest and labour. Preserve us ever-more, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 87
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							VARUNA cut a pathway out for Surya, and led the watery floods of rivers
							onward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mares, as in a race, speed on in order. He made great channels for
							the days to follow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The wind, thy breath, hath sounded through the region like a wild beast
							that seeks his food in pastures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Within these two, exalted Earth and Heaven, O Varuna, are all the forms
							thou lovest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Varuna's spies, sent forth upon their errand, survey the two
							world-halves well formed and fashioned.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wise are they, holy, skilled in sacrifices, the furtherers of the
							praise-songs of the prudent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To me who understand hath Varuna spoken, the names borne by the Cow are
							three times seven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The sapient God, knowing the place's secret, shall speak as 'twere to
							teach the race that cometh.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							On him three heavens rest and are supported, and the three earths are
							there in sixfold order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The wise King Varuna hath made in heaven that Golden Swing to cover it
							with glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like Varuna from heaven he sinks in Sindhu, like a white-shining spark,
							a strong wild creature.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ruling in depths and meting out the region, great saving power hath he,
							this world's Controller.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Before this Varuna may we be sinless him who shows mercy even to the
							sinner-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 87: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							While we are keeping Aditi's ordinances. Preserve us evermore, ye Gods,
							with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 88
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							PRESENT to Varuna thine hymn, Vasistha, bright, most delightful to the
							Bounteous Giver,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who bringeth on to us the Bull, the lofty, the Holy, laden with a
							thousand treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							And now, as I am come before his presence, I take the face of Varuna
							for Agni's.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So might he bring-Lord also of the darkness-the light in heaven that I
							may see its beauty!
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Varuna and I embark together and urge our boat into the midst of
							ocean,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							We, when we ride o'er ridges of the waters, will swing within that
							swing and there be happy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Varuna placed Vasistha in the vessel, and deftly with his niight made
							him a Rsi.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When days shone bright the Sage made him a singer, while the heavens
							broadened and the Dawns were lengthened.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							What hath become of those our ancient friendships, when without enmity
							we walked together?
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							I, Varuna, thou glorious Lord, have entered thy lofty home, thine house
							with thousand portals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							If he, thy true ally, hath sinned against thee, still, Varuna, he is
							the friend thou lovedst.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us not, Living One, as sinners I know thee: give shelter, as a
							Sage, to him who lauds thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							While we abide in these fixed habitations, and from the lap of Aditi
							win favour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 88: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Varuna untie the bond that binds us. Preserve us evermore, ye Gods,
							with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 89
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET me not yet, King Varuna, enter into the house of clay:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have mercy, spare me, Mighty Lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, Thunderer! I move along tremulous like a wind-blown skin,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have mercy, spare me, Mighty Lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Bright and Powerful God, through want of strength I erred and went
							astray
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have mercy, spare me, Mighty Lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thirst found thy worshipper though he stood in the midst of
							water-fijods:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have mercy, spare me, Mighty Lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Varuna, whatever the offence may be which we as men commit against
							the heavenly host,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 89: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When through our want of thought we violate thy laws, punish us not, O
							God, for that iniquity.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 90
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you pure juice, rich in meath, are offered by priest: through
							longing for the Pair of Heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drive, Vayu, bring thine harnessed horses hither: drink the pressed
							Soma till it make thee joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso to thee, the Mighty, brings oblation, pure Soma unto thee,
							pure-drinking Vayu,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That man thou makest famous among mortals: to him strong sons are born
							in quick succession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The God whom both these worlds brought forth for riches, whom heavenly
							Dhisana for our wealth appointeth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							His team of harnessed horses waits on Vayu, and, foremost, on the
							radiant Treasure-bearer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The spotless Dawns with fair bright days have broken; they found the
							spacious light when they were shining.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eagerly they disclosed the stall of cattle: floods streamed for them as
							in the days aforetime.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							These with their truthful spirit, shining brightly, move on provided
							with their natural insight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Viands attend the car that beareth Heroes, your car, ye Sovran Pair,
							Indra and Vayu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May these who give us heavenly light, these rulers, with gifts of kine
							and horses, gold and treasures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							These princes, through full life, Indra and Vayu! o'ercome in battle
							with their steeds and heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like coursers seeking fame will we Vasisthas, O Indra-Vayu, with our
							fair laudations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 90: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Exerting all our power call you to aid us. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 91
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WERE not in sooth, the Gods aforetime blameless, whose pleasure was
							increased by adoration?
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For Vayu and for man in his affliction they caused the Morning to arise
							with Surya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guardians infallible, eager as envoys' preserve us safe through many
							months and autumns.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Addressed to you, our fair praise, Indra-Vayu, implores your favour and
							renewed well-being.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wise, bright, arranger of his teams, he. seeketh men with rich food
							whose treasures are abundant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							They have arranged them of one mind with Vayu: the men have wrought all
							noble operations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							So far as native power and strength permit you, so far as men behold
							whose eyes have vision,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							O ye pure-drinkers, drink with us pure Soma: sit on this sacred grass,
							Indra and Vayu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Driving down teams that bear the lovely Heroes, hitherward, Indra-Vayu,
							come together.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To you this prime of savoury juice is offered: here loose your horses
							and be friendly-minded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your hundred and your thousand teams, O Indra and Vayu, all-munificent,
							which attend you,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							With these most gracious-minded come ye hither, and drink, O Heroes of
							the meath we offer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like coursers seeking fame will we Vasisthas, O Indra-Vayu, with our
							fair laudations,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 91: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Exerting all our powe-,, call you to aid us. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 92
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O VAYU, drinker of the pure, be near us: a thousand teams are thine,
							Allbounteous Giver.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To thee the rapture-bringing juice is offered, whose first draught,
							God, thou takest as thy portion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prompt at the holy rites forth came the presser with Soma-draughts for
							Indra and for Vayu,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When ministering priests with strong devotion bring to you Twain the
							first taste of the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The teams wherewith thou seekest him who offers, within his home, O
							Viyu, to direct him,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therewith send wealth: to us with full enjoyment, a hero son and gifts
							of kine and horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Near to the Gods and making Indra joyful, devout and ofFering precious
							gifts to Vayu,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Allied with princes, smiting down the hostile, may we with heroes
							conquer foes in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With thy yoked teams in hundreds and in thousands come to our sacrifice
							and solemn worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come, Vayu, make thee glad at this libation. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 93
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SLAYERS of enemies, Indra and Agni, accept this day our new-born pure
							laudation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Again, again I call you prompt to listen, best to give quickly strength
							to him who craves it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For ye were strong to gain, exceeding mighty, growing together, waxing
							in your vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lords of the pasture filled with ample riches, bestow upon us strength
							both fresh and lasting.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea when the strong have entered our assembly, and singers seeking with
							their hymns your favour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							They are like steeds who come into the race-course, those men who call
							aloud on Indra-Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The singer, seeking with his hymns your favour, begs splendid riches of
							their first possessor.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Further us with new bounties, Indra-Agni, armed with strong thunder,
							slayers of the foeman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When two great hosts, arrayed against each other, meet clothed with
							brightness, in the fierce encounter
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Stand ye beside the godly, smite the godless; and still assist the men
							who press the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To this our Soma-pressing, Indra-Agni, come ye prepared to show your
							loving-kindness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For not at any time have ye despised us. So may I draw you with all
							strengthenings hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							So Agni, kindled mid this adoration, invite thou Mitra, Varuna, and
							Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Forgive whatever sin we have committed may Aryaman and Aditi remove it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							While we accelerate these our sacrifices, may we win strength from both
							of you, O Agni:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 93: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ne'er may the Maruts, Indra, Visnu slight us. Preserve us evermore, ye
							Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 94
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As rain from out the cloud, for you, Indra and Agni, from my soul
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							This noblest praise hath been produced.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do ye, O Indra-Agni, hear the singer's call: accept his songs.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Rulers, grant his heart's desire.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us not up to poverty, ye Heroes, Indra-Agni, nor
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To slander and reproach of men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Indra and to Agni we bring reverence, high and holy hymn,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, craving help, softwords with prayer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							For all these holy singers here implore these Twain to succour them,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And priests that they may win them strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eager to laudyou, we with songs invoke you, bearing sacred food,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fain for success in sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, come to us with favour, ye who conquer men:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not the wicked master us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							At no time let the injurious blow of hostile mortal fall on us:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra-Agni, shelter us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whatever wealth we crave of you, in gold, in cattle, or in steeds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							That, Indra-Agni, let us gain;
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							When heroes prompt in worship call Indra and Agni, Lords of steeds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beside the Soma juice effused.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call hither with the song and lauds those who best slay the foemen,
							those
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who take delight in hymns of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Slay ye the wicked man whose thought is evil of the demon kind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 94: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slay him who stays the waters, slay the Serpent with your deadly dart.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 95
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS stream Sarasvati with fostering current comes forth, our sure
							defence, our fort of iron.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As on a car, the flood flows on, surpassing in majesty and might all
							other waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pure in her course from mountains to the ocean, alone of streams
							Sarasvati hath listened.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thinking of wealth and the great world of creatures, she poured for
							Nahusa her milk and fatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Friendly to man he grew among the women, a strong young Steer amid the
							Holy Ladies.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He gives the fleet steed to our wealthy princes, and decks their bodies
							for success in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this Sarasvati be pleased and listen at this our sacrifice,
							auspicious Lady,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When we with reverence, on our knees, implore her close-knit to wealth,
							most kind to those she loveth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							These offerings have ye made with adoration: say this, Sarasvati, and
							accept our praises;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, placing us under thy dear protection, may we approach thee, as a
							tree, for shelter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							For thee, O Blest Sarasvati, Vasistha hath here unbarred the doors d
							sacred Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 95: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wax, Bright One, and give strength to him who lauds thee. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 96
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I SING a lofty song, for she is mightiest,  most divine of Streams.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sarasvati will I exalt with hymns and lauds, and, O Vasistha, Heaven
							and Earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When in the fulness of their strength the Purus dwell, Beauteous One,
							on thy two grassy banks,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Favour us thou who hast the Maruts for thy friends: stir up the bounty
							of our chiefs.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may Sarasvati auspicious send good luck; she, rich in spoil, is
							never niggardly in thought,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When praised in jamadagni's way and lauded as Vasistha lauds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							We call upon Sarasvan, as unmarried men who long for wives,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As liberal men who yearn for sons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be thou our kind protector, O Sarasvan, with those waves of thine
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Laden with sweets and dropping oil.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we enjoy Sarasvan's breast, all-beautiful, that swells with
							streams,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 96: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we gain food and progeny.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 97
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHERE Heaven and Earth combine in men's assembly, and ttose who love
							the Gods delight in worship,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where the libations are effused for Indra, may he come first to drink
							and make him stronger.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							We crave the heavenly grace of Gods to guard us-so may Brhaspati, O
							friends, exalt us-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That he, the Bounteous God, may find us sintess, who giveth from a
							distance like a father.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							That Brahmanaspati, most High and Gracious, I glorify with offerings
							and with homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the great song of praise divine, reach Indra who is the King of
							prayer the Gods' creation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May that Brhaspati who brings all blessings, most dearly loved, be
							seated by our altar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Heroes and wealth we crave; may he bestow them, and bear us safe beyond
							the men who vex us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To us these Deathless Ones, erst born, have granted this laud of ours
							which gives the Immortal pleasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us invoke Brhaspati, the foeless, the clear-voiced God, the Holy
							One of households
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, this Brhaspati, his red-hued horses, drawing together, full of
							strength, bring hither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Robed in red colour like the cloud, they carry the Lord of Might whose
							friendship gives a dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							For he is pure, with hundred wings, refulgent, with sword of gold,
							impetuous, winning sunlight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sublime Brhaspati, easy of access granteth his friends most bountiful
							refreshment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Both Heaven and Earth, divine, the Deity's Parents, have made Brhaspati
							increase in grandeur.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Glorify him, O friends, who merits glory: may he give prayer fair way
							and easy passage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							This, Brahmanaspati, is your laudation prayer hath been made to
							thunderwielding Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Favour our songs, wake up our thought and spirit: destroy the godless
							and our foemen's malice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Twain are Lords of wealth in earth and heaven, thou, O Brhaspati,
							and thou, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 97: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mean though he be, give wealth to him who lauds you. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 98
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							PRIESTS, offer to the Lord of all the people the milked-out stalk of
							Soma, radiant-coloured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							No wild-bull knows his drinking-place like Indra who ever seeks him who
							hath pressed the Soma,
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou dost desire to drink, each day that passes, the pleasant food
							which thou hast had aforetime,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra, gratified in heart and spirit, drink eagerly the Soma set
							before thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, newly-born, for strength didst drink the Soma; the Mother told
							thee of thy future greatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra, thou hast filled mid-air's wide region, and given the Gods by
							battle room and freedom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou hast urged the arrocrant to combat, proud in their strength
							of arm, we will subdue them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or, Indra, when thou fightest girt by heroes, we in the glorious fray
							with thee will conquer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will declare the earliest deeds of Indra, and recent acts which
							Maghavan hath accomplished.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When he had conquered godless wiles and magic, Soma became his own
							entire possession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine is this world of flocks and herds around thee, which with the eye
							of Surya thou beholdest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, art alone the Lord of cattle; may we enjoy the treasure
							which thou givest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Twain are Lords of wealth in earth and heaven, thou, O Brhaspati,
							and thou, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 98: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mean though he be, give wealth to him who lauds you. Preserve us
							evermore, ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 99
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MEN come not nigh thy majesty who growest beyond all bound and measure
							with thy body.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Both thy two regions of the earth, O Visnu, we know: thou God, knowest
							the highest also.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							None who is born or being born, God Visnu, hath reached the utmost
							limit of thy grandeur.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The vast high vault of heaven hast thou supported, and fixed earth's
							eastern pinnacle securely.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rich in sweet food be ye, and rich in milch-kine, with fertile
							pastures, fain to do men service.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Both these worlds, Visnu, hast thou stayed asunder, and firmly fixed
							the earth with pegs around it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye have made spacious room for sacrificing by generating Surya, Dawn,
							and Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Heroes, ye have conquered in your battles even the bull-jawed Dasa's
							wiles and magic.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye have destroyed, thou, Indra, and thou Visnu, Sambara's
							nine-and-ninety fenced castles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Twain smote down a hundred times a thousand resistless heroes of the
							royal Varcin.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the lofty hymn of praise, exalting the Lords of Mighty Stride,
							the strong and lofty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							I laud you in the solemn synods, Visnu: pour ye food on us in our
							camps, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Visnu, unto thee my lips cry Vasat! Let this mine offering,
							Sipivista, please thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 99: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these my songs of eulogy exalt thee. Preserve us evermore, ye Gods,
							with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 100
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							NE'ER doth the man repent, who, seeking profit, bringeth his gift to
							the far-striding Visnu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who adoreth him with all his spirit winneth himself so great a
							benefactor.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Visnu, constant in thy courses, gavest good-will to all men, and
							a hymn that lasteth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That thou mightst move us to abundant comfort of very splendid wealth
							with store of horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three times strode forth this God in all his grandeur over this earth
							bright with a hundred splendours.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Foremost be Visnu, stronger than the strongest: for glorious is his
							name who lives for ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Over this earth with mighty step strode Visnu, ready to give it for a
							home to Manu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							In him the humble people trust for safety: he, nobly born, hath made
							them spacious dwellings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To-day I laud this name, O gipivista, I, skilled in rules, the name of
							thee the Noble.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, I the poor and weak praise thee the Mighty who dwellest in the
							realm beyond this region.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							What was there to be blamed in thee, O Visnu, when thou declaredst, I
							am Sipivista?
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hide not this form from us, nor keep it secret, since thou didst wear
							another shape in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Visnu, unto thee my lips cry Vasat! Let this mine offering,
							Sipivista, please thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 100: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these my songs of eulogy exalt thee. Preserve us evermore, ye Gods,
							with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 101
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SPEAK forth three words, the words which light precedeth, which milk
							this udder that produceth nectar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Quickly made manifest, the Bull hath bellowed, engendering the germ of
							plants, the Infant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Giver of growth to plants, the God who ruleth over the waters and all
							moving creatures,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us triple shelter for our refuge, and threefold light to
							succour and befriend us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now he is sterile, now begetteth offspring, even as he willeth doth he
							change his figure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Father's genial flow bedews the Mother; therewith the Sire,
							therewith the son is nourished.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							In him all living creatures have their being, and the three heavens
							with triplyflowing waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Three reservoirs that sprinkle down their treasure shed their sweet
							streams around him with a murmur.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this my song to Sovran Lord Parjanya come near unto his heart and
							give him pleasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we obtain the showers that bring enjoyment, and God-protected
							plants with goodly fruitage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							He is the Bull of all, and their impregner lie holds the life of all
							things fixed and moving.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 101: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May this rite save me till my hundredth autumn. Preserve us evermore,
							ye Gods, with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 102
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 102: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 102: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING forth and laud Parjanya, son of Heaven, who sends the gift of rain
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 102: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he provide our pasturage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 102: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 102: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Parjanya is the God who forms in kine, in mares, in plants of earth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 102: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							And womankind, the germ of life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 102: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 102: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Offer and pour into his mouth oblation rich in savoury juice:
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 102: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he for ever give us food.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 103
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THEY who lay quiet for a year, the Brahmans who fulfil their vows,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Frogs have lifted up their voice, the voice Parjanya hath inspired.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time on these, as on a dry skin lying in the pool's bed, the
							floods of heaven descended,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The music of the Frogs comes forth in concert like the cows lowing with
							their calves beside them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When at the coming of the Rains the water has poured upon them as they
							yearned and thirsted,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							One seeks another as he talks and greets him with cries of pleasure as
							a son his father.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Each of these twain receives the other kindly, while they are revelling
							in the flow of waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the Frog moistened by the rain springs forward, and Green and
							Spotty both combine their voices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When one of these repeats the other's language, as he who learns the
							lesson of the teacher,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your every limb seems to be growing larger as ye converse with
							eloquence on the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Onc is Cow-bellow and Goat-bleat the other, one Frog is Green and one
							of them is Spotty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							They bear one common name, and yet they vary, and, talking, modulate
							the voice diversely.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							As Brahmans, sitting round the brimful vessel, talk at the Soma-rite of
							Atiratra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, Frogs, ye gather round the pool to honour this day of all the year,
							the first of Rain-time.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Brahmans with the Soma juice, performing their year-long rite,
							have lifted up their voices;
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							And these Adhvaryus, sweating with their kettles, come forth and show
							themselves, and none are hidden.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							They keep the twelve month's God-appointed order, and never do the men
							neglect the season.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Soon as the Rain-time in the year returneth, these who were heated
							kettles gain their freedom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Cow-bellow and Goat-bleat have granted riches, and Green and Spotty
							have vouchsafed us treasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 103: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Frogs who give us cows in hundreds lengthen our lives in this most
							fertilizing season.
						-
			-
				Mandala 7: Hymn 104
			-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							INDRA and Soma, burn, destroy the demon foe, send downward, O ye Bulls,
							those who add gloom to gloom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Annihilate the fools, slay them and burn them up: chase them away from
							us, pierce the voracious ones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Soma, let sin round the wicked boil like as a caldron set
							amid the flames of fire.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Against the foe of prayer, devourer of raw flesh, the vile fiend fierce
							of eye, keep ye perpetual hate.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Soma, plunge the wicked in the depth, yea, cast them into
							darkness that hath no support,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So that not one of them may ever thence return: so may your wrathful
							might prevail and conquer them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Soma, hurl your deadly crushing bolt down on the wicked fiend
							from heaven and from the earth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, forge out of the mountains your celestial dart wherewith ye burn
							to death the waxing demon race.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Soma, cast ye downward out of heaven your deadly darts of
							stone burning with fiery flame,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eternal, scorching darts; plunge the voracious ones within the depth,
							and let them sink without a sound.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Soma, let this hymn control you both, even as the girth
							encompasses two vigorous steeds-
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The song of praise which I with wisdom offer you: do ye, as Lords of
							men, animate these my prayers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							In your impetuous manner think ye both thereon: destroy these evil
							beings, slay the treacherous fiends.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra and Soma, let the wicked have no bliss who evermore assails us
							with malignity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso accuses me with words of falsehood when I pursue my way with
							guileless spirit,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, the speaker of untruth, be, Indra, like water which the
							hollowed hand compresses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those who destroy, as is their wont, the simple, and with their evil
							natures barm the righteous,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Soma give them over to the serpent, or to the lap of Nirrti consign
							them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							The fiend, O Agni, who designs to injure the essence of our food, kine,
							steeds, or bodies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, the adversary, thief, and robber, sink to destruction, both
							himself and offspring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he be swept away, himself and children: may all the three earths
							press him down beneath them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							May his fair glory, O ye Gods, be blighted, who in the day or night
							would fain destroy us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							The prudent finds it easy to distinguish the true and false: their
							words oppose each other.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of these two that which is the true and honest, Soma protects, and
							brings the false to nothing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Never doth Soma aid and guide the wicked or him who falsely claims the
							Warrior's title.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							He slays the fiend and him who speaks untruly: both lie entangled in
							the noose of Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							As if I worshipped deities of falsehood, or thought vain thoughts about
							the Gods, O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Why art thou angry with us, Jatavedas? Destruction fall on those who
							lie against thee!
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may I die this day if I have harassed any man's life or if I be a
							demon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, may he lose all his ten sons together who with false tongue hath
							called me Yatudhana.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra slay him with a mi weapon, and let the vilest ofghty
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							all creatures perish,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 16: Line 3
					-
						-
							The fiend who says that he is pure, who calls me a demon though devoid
							of demon nature.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							She too who wanders like an owl at night-time, hiding her body in her
							guile and malice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							May she fall downward into endless caverns. May press-stones with loud
							ring destroy the demons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Spread out, ye Maruts, search among the people: seize ye and grind the
							Raksasas to pieces,
						-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who fly abroad, transformed to birds, at night-time, or sully and
							pollute our holy worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 7: Hymn 104: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
