					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aditi guard our herd by day, Aditi, free from guile, by night,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aditi, ever strengthening, save us from grief!
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							And in the day our hymn is this: May Aditi come nigh to help,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With loving-kindness bring us weal and chase our foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							And may the Asvins, the divine Pair of Physicians, send us health:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they remove iniquity and chase our foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Agni bless us with his fires, and Surya warm us pleasantly:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the pure Wind breathe sweet on us, and chase our foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drive ye disease and strife away, drive ye away malignity:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Adityas, keep us ever far from sore distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Remove from us the arrow, keep famine, Adityas! far away:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Keep enmities afar from us, Lords of all wealth!
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, O Adityas, grant to us the shelter that lets man go free,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, even the sinner from his sin, ye Bounteous Gods 1
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whatever mortal with the powe r of demons fain would injure us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, impetuous, suffer harm by his own deeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							May sin o'ertake our human foe, the man who speaketh evil thing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who would cause our misery, whose heart is false.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods, ye are with the simple ones, ye know each mortal in your hearts;
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, Vasus, well discriminate the false and true.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fain would we have the sheltering aid of mountains and of water-floods:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Keep far from us iniquity, O Heaven and Earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							So with auspicious sheltering aid do ye, O Vasus, carry us
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beyond all trouble and distress, borne in your ship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adityas, ye Most Mighty Ones, grant to our children and their seed
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Extended term of life that they may live long days.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sacrifice, O Adityas, is your inward monitor: be kind,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							For in the bond of kindred we are bound to you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Maruts' high protecting aid, the Asvins, and the God who saves,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mitra and Varuna for weal we supplicate.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grant us a home with triple guard, Aryaman, Mitra, Varuna!
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unthreatened, Maruts! meet for praise, and filled with men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							And as we human beings, O Adityas, are akin to death,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Graciously lengthen ye our lives that we may live.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 19
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING praise to hiin, the Lord of Light. The Gods have made the God to
							be their messenger,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							And sent oblation to Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, the Bounteous Giver, bright with varied flames, laud thou, O
							singer Sobhari-
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who controls this sacred food with Soma blent, who hath first claim
							to sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thee have we chosen skilftillest in sacrifice, Immortal Priest among
							the Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wise finisher of this holy rite:
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Son of Strength, the blessed, brightly shining One, Agni whose
							light is excellent.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May be by sacrifice win us in heaven the grace of Mitra, Varuna, and
							the Floods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mortal who hath ministered to Agni with oblation, fuel, ritual
							lore,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And reverence, skilled in sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Verily swift to run are his fleet-footed steeds, and most resplendent
							fame is his.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							No trouble caused by Gods or wrought by mortal man from any side
							o'ertaketh him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we by thine own fires be well supplied with fire, O Son of
							Strength, O Lord of Might:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou as our Friend hast worthy men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, who praises like a guest of friendly mind, is as a car that
							brings us gear.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Also in thee is found perfect security thou art the Sovran Lord of
							wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							That man, moreover, merits praise who brings, auspicious Agni,
							sacrificial gifts
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he win riches by his thoughts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							He for whose sacrifice thou standest up erect is prosperous and rules
							o'er men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He wins with coursers and with singers killed in song: with heroes he
							obtains the prize.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							He in whose dwelling Agni is chief ornament, and, all-desired, loves
							his laud well,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							And zealously tends his offerings-
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							His, or the lauding sage's word, his, Son of Strength! who Is most
							prompt with sacred gifts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Set thou beneath the Gods, Vasu, above mankind, the speech of the
							intelligent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who with sacrificial gifts or homage bringeth very skilful Agni
							nigh,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or him who flashes fast with song,
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mortal who with blazing fuel, as his laws command, adores the
							Perfect God,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blest with his thoughts in splendour shall exceed all men, as though he
							overpassed the floods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us the splendour, Agni, which may overcome each greedy fiend in
							our abode,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							The wrath of evil-hearted folk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							That, wherewith Mitra, Varuna, and Aryaman, the Asvins, Bhaga give us
							light,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							That may we, by thy power finding best furtherance, worship, O Indra,
							helped by thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, most devout are they, the sages who have set thee Sage
							exceeding wise,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							O God, for men to look upon:
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who have arranged thine altar Blessed God, at morn brought thine
							oblation, pressed the juice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							They by their deeds of strength have won diem, mighty wealth, who have
							set all their hope in thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							-May Agni worshipped bring us bliss, may the gift, Blessed One, and
							sacrifice bring bliss;
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, may our praises bring us bliss.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Show forth the mind that brings success in war with fiends, wherewith
							thou conquerest in fight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring down the many firm hopes of our enemies, and let us vanquish with
							thine aid.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							I praise with song the Friend of man, whom Gods sent down to be herald
							and messenger,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best worshipper, bearer of our gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou unto sharp-toothed Agni, Young and Radiant God, proclaimest with
							thy song the feast-
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, who for our sweet strains moulds heroic strength when sacred oil
							is offered him,
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							While, served with sacrificial oil, now upward and now downward Agni
							moves his sword,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							As doth the Asura his robe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							The God, the Friend of man, who bears our gifts to heaven, the God with
							his sweet-smelling mouth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							Distributes, skilled in sacrifice, his precious things, Invoking
							Priest, Immortal God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 25: Line 1
					-
						-
							Son of Strength, Agni, if thou wert the mortal, bright as Mitra, I
							worshipped with our gifts!
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 25: Line 2
					-
						-
							And I were the Immortal God
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 26
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 26: Line 1
					-
						-
							I would not give thee up, Vasu, to calumny, or misery, O Bounteous One.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 26: Line 2
					-
						-
							My worshipper should feel no hunger or distress, nor, Agni, should he
							live in sin.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Like a son cherished in his father's house, let our oblation rise unto the
						Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 28
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 28: Line 1
					-
						-
							With thine immediate aid may I, excellent Agni, ever gain my wish
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 28: Line 2
					-
						-
							A mortal with a God to help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 29
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 29: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, by thy wisdom, by thy bounties, by thy leading may I gather
							wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 29: Line 2
					-
						-
							Excellent Agni, thou art called my Providence: delight thou to be
							liberal.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 30
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 30: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, he conquers by thine aid that brings him store of noble heroes
							and great strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 30: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose bond of friendship is thy choice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 31
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 31: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spark is black and crackling, kindled in due time, O Bounteous, it
							is taken up.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 31: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art the dear Friend of the mighty Mornings: thou shinest in
							glimmerings of the night.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 32
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 32: Line 1
					-
						-
							We Sobharis have come to him, for succour, who is good to help with
							thousand powers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 32: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Sovran, Trasadasyu's Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 33
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 33: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, thou on whom all other fires depend, as branches on the parent
							stem,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 33: Line 2
					-
						-
							I make the treasures of the folk, like songs, mine own, while I exalt
							thy sovran might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 34
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 34: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mortal whom, Adityas, ye, Guilelew, lead to the farther bank
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 34: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of all the princes, Bounteous Ones
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 35
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 35: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoe'er he be, Man-ruling Kings! the Regent of the race of men-
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 35: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we, O Mitra, Varuna, and Aryaman, like him be furtherers of your
							law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 36
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 36: Line 1
					-
						-
							A gift of fifty female slaves hath Trasadasyu given me, Purukutsa's
							son,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 36: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most liberal, kind, lord of the brave.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 37
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 37: Line 1
					-
						-
							And Syava too for me led forth a strong steed at Suvastu's ford:
						-
					-
