						Thou helpest one to power, and one thou hast not helped, O Indra, Lord of
						Strength, with all thy saving aid.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear thou Syavasva while he sings to thee, as erst thou heardest Atri
							when he wrought his holy rites.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, thou only gavest Trasadasyu aid in the fierce fight with heroes,
							strengthening his powers.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 38
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YE Twain are Priests of sacrifice, wmners in war and holy works:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, mark this well.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye bounteous riders on the car, ye Vrtra-slayers unsubdued:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, mark this well.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The men with pressing-stones have pressed this meath of yours which
							gives delight:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, and Agni, mark this well.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Accept our sacrifice for weal, sharers of praise! the Soma shed:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, Heroes, come.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be pleased with these libations which attract you to our sacred gifts
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, Heroes, come.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Accept this eulogy of mine whose model is the Gayatri:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, Heroes, Come.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come with the early-faring Gods, ye who are Lords of genuine wealth:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra-Agni, to the Soma-draught
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear ye the call of Atris, hear Syavasva as he sheds the juice:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra-Agni to the Soma-draught
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus have I called you to our aid as sages called on you of old:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra-Agni to the Soma draught!
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra's and Agni's grace I claim, Sarasvati's associates
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							To whom this psalm of praise is sung.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 39
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE glorious Agni have I praised, and worshipped with. the sacred food.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni deck the Gods for us. Between both gathering-places he goes on
							his embassy, the Sage. May all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, burn down the word within their bodies through our newest speech,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							All hatreds of the godless, all the wicked man's malignities. Away let
							the destroyers go. May all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, I offer hymns to thee, like holy oil within thy moutlh.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Acknowledge them. among the Gods, for thou art the rmost excellent, the
							worshipper's blissful messenger. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni bestows all vital power even as each man supplicates.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He brings the Vasus strengthening gifts, and grants deliglht, in rest
							and stir, for every calling on the Gods. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni hath made himself renowned by wonderful victorious act.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He is the Priest of all the tribes, chosen with sacrificial meeds. He
							urges Deities to receive. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni knows all that springs from Gods, he knows the mystery of men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giver of wealth is Agni, he uncloses both the doors to us when
							worshipped with our newest gift. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni inhabiteth with Gods and men who offer sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He cherisheth with great delight much wisdom, as all things that be,
							God among Gods adorable. May all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni who liveth in all streams, Lord of the Sevenfold Race of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him dweller in three homes we seek, best slayer of the Dasytis for
							Mandhatar, first in sacrifice. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni the Wise inhabiteth three gathering-places, triply formed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Decked as our envoy let the Sage bring hither and conciliate the Thrice
							Eleven Deities. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Our Agni, thou art first among the Gods, and first mid living men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou only rulest over wealth. Round about thee, as natural dams,
							circumfluous the waters run. Let all the others die away.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 40
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							INDRA and Agni, surely ye as Conquerors will give us wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whereby in fight we may o'ercome that which is strong and firmly fixed,
							as Agni burns the woods with wind. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							We set no snares to tangle you; Indra we worship and adore, Hero of
							heroes mightiest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Once may he come unto us with his Steed, come unto us to win us
							strength, and to complete the sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For, famous Indra-Agni, ye are dwellers in the midst of frays.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sages in wisdom, ye are knit to him who seeketh you as friends. Heroes,
							bestow on him his wish.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Nabhaka-like, with sacred song Indra's and Agni's praise I sing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Theirs to whom all this world belongs, this heaven and this mighty
							earth which bear rich treasure in their lap.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Indra and to Agni send your prayers, as was Nabhaka's wont,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who oped with sideway opening the sea with its foundations seven-Indra
							all powerful in his might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tear thou asunder, as of old, like tangles of a creeping plant,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Demolish thou the Dasa's might. May we with Indra's help divide the
							treasure he hath gathered up.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time with this same song these men call Indra-Agni sundry ways,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we with our own heroes quell those who provoke us to the fight, and
							conquer those who strive with us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Two refulgent with their beams rise and come downward from the sky.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							By Indra's and by Agni's hest, flowing away, the rivers, run which they
							released from their restraint.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, many are thine aids, many thy ways of guiding us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of the Bay Steeds, Hinva's Son. To a Good Hero come our prayers,
							which soon shall have accomplishment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Inspire him with your holy hymns, the Hero bright and glorious,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who with might demolisbeth even the brood of Susna, and winneth for
							us the heavenly streams.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Inspire him worshipped with fair rites, the glorious Hero truly brave.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							He brake in pieces Susna's brood who still expected not the stroke, and
							won for us the heavenly streams. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus have we sung anew to Indra-Agni, as sang our sires, Angirases, and
							Mandhatar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard us with triple shelter and preserve us: may we be masters of a
							store of riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 41
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To make this Varuna come forth sing thou a song unto the band of Maruts
							wiser than thyself,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							This Varuna who guardeth well the thoughts of men like herds of kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him altogether praise I with the song and hymns our fathers sang, and
							with Nabhaka's eulogies,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him dwelling at the rivers' source, surrounded by his Sisters Seven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The nights he hath encompassed, and stablished the morns with magic art
							visible over all is he.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							His dear Ones, following his Law, have prospered the Three Dawns for
							him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, visible o'er all the earth, stablished the quarters of the sky:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He measured out the eastern place, that is the fold of Varuna: like a
							strong herdsman is the God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who supports the worlds of life, he who well knows the hidden names
							mysterious of the morning beams,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He cherishes much wisdom, Sage, as heaven brings forth each varied
							form.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							In whom all wisdom centres, as the nave is set within the wheel.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Haste ye to honour Trita, as kine haste to gather in the fold, even as
							they muster steeds to yoke.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He wraps these regions as a robe; he contemplates the tribes of Gods
							and all the works of mortal men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Before the home of Varuna all the Gods follow his decree.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							He is an Ocean far-removed, yet through the heaven to him ascends the
							worship which these realms possess.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With his bright foot he overthrew their magic, and went up to heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ruler, whose bright far-seeing rays, pervading all three earths, have
							filled the three superior realms of heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Firm is the seat of Varuna: over the Seven he rules as King.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who, after his decree, o'erspread the Dark Ones with a robe of light;
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who measured out the ancient seat, who pillared both the worlds apart
							as the Unborn supported heaven. Let all the others die away.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 42
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LORD of all wealth, the Asura propped the heavens, and measured out the
							broad earth's wide expanses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, King supreme, approached all living creatures. All these are
							Varuna's holy operations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							So humbly worship Varuna the Mighty revere the wise Guard of World
							Immortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he vouchsafe us triply-barred protection. O Earth and Heaven,
							within your lap preserve us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sharpen this song of him who strives his utmost, sharpen, God Varuna,
							his strength and insight;
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we ascend the ship that bears us safely, whereby we may pass over
							all misfortune.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Asvins, with songs the singer stones have made you hasten hitherward,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nasatyas, to the Soma-draught. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the sage Atri with his hymns, O Asvins, called you eagerly,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nasatyas, to the Soma-draught. Let all the others die away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							So have I called you to our aid, even as the wise have called of old,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nasatyas, to the Soma-draught. Let all the others die away.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 43
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE songs of mine go forth as lauds of Agni, the disposing Sage,
						-
					-
