					-
						-
							I count thee as the Banner of the heroes, I count thee as the Chief of
							all men living.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time, O Indra, in thine arms thou tookest thy wildly rushing bolt
							to Slay the Dragon,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The mountains roared, the cattle loudly bellowed, the Brahmans with
							their hymns drew nigh to Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us praise him who made these worlds and creatures, all things that
							after him sprang into being.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we win Mitra with our songs, and Indra, and. wait upon our Lord
							with adoration.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Flying in terror from the snort of Vrtra, all Deities who were thy
							friends forsook thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, Indra, be thy friendship with the Maruts: in all these battles thou
							shalt be the victor.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrice-sixty Maruts, waxing strong, were with thee, like piles of
							beaming light, worthy of worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							We come to thee: grant us a happy portion. Let us adore thy might with
							this oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							A sharpened weapon is the host of Maruts. Who, Indra, dares withstand
							thy bolt of thunder?
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Weaponless are the Asuras, the godless: scatter them with thy wheel,
							Impetuous Hero.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the Strong and Mighty, most auspicious, send up the beAuteous
							hymn for sake of cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lay oa his body many songs for Indra invoked with song, for will not he
							regard. them?
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him, the Mighty, who accepts laudation, send forth thy thought as by
							a boat o'er rivers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Stir with thy hymn the body of the Famous and Dearest One, for will not
							he regard it?
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Serve him with gifts of thine which Indra welcomes: praise with fair
							praise, invite him with thine homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 85: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Draw near, O singer, and refrain from outcry. Make thy voice heard, for
							will not he regard it?
						-
