						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 92
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THAT noblest Furtherer hath appeared, to whom men bring their holy
							works.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our songs of praise have risen aloft to Agni who was barn to give the
							Arya strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni of Divodasa turned, as 'twere in majesty, to the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Onward he sped along the mother earth, and took his station in the
							height of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him before whom the people shrink when he performs his glorious deeds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who wins thousands at the worship of the Gods, himself, that Agni,
							serve with son s.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The mortal man whom thou wouldst lead to opulence, O Vasu, he who
							brings thee gifts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, Agni, wins himself a hero singing lauds, yea, one who feeds a
							thousand men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He with the steed wins spoil even in the fenced fort, and gains
							imperishable fame.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							In thee, O Lord of wealth, continually we lay all precious offerings to
							the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him who dealeth out all wealth, who is the cheerful Priest of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him, like the first vessels filled with savoury juice, to Agni go
							the songs of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Votaries, richly-gifted, deck him with their songs, even as the steed
							who draws the car.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							On both, Strong Lord of men! on child and grandson pour the bounties
							which our nobles give.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sing forth to him, the Holy, most munificent, sublime with his
							refulgent glow,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Agni, ye Upastutas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worshipped with gifts, enkindled, splendid, Maghavan shall win himself
							heroic fame.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							And will not his most newly shown benevolence come to us with abundant
							strength?
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Priest, presser of the juice! praise now the dearest Guest of all our
							friends,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, the driver of the cars.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who, finder-out of treasures open and concealed, bringeth them hither,
							Holy One;
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose waves, as in a cataract, are hard to pass, when he, through song,
							would win him strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let not the noble Guest, Agni, be wroth with us: by many a man his
							praise is sung,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Good Herald, skilled in sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Vasu, Agni, let not them be harmed who come in any way with lauds to
							thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even the lowly, skilled in rites, with offered gifts, seeketh thee for
							the envoy's task.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Friend of the Maruts, Agni, come with Rudras to the Soma-draught,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Sobhar's fair song of praise, and be thou joyful in the light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 92: Verse 14: Line 3
					-
						-
							VALAKHILYA
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 93
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							TO you will I sing Indra's praise who gives good gifts as well we know;
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The praise of Maghavan who, rich in treasure, aids his singers with
							wealth thousandfold.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As with a hundred hosts, he rushes boldly on, and for the offerer slays
							his foes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As from a mountain flow the water-brooks, thus flow his gifts who
							feedeth many a one.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The drops effused, the gladdening draughts, O Indra, Lover of the Son
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As waters seek the lake where they are wont to rest, fill thee, for
							bounty, Thunderer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The matchless draught that strengthens and gives eloquence, the
							sweetest of the meath drink thou,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That in thy joy thou maysi scatter thy gifts o'er us, plenteously, even
							as the dust.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come quickly to our laud, urged on by Soma-pressers like a horse-
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Laud, Godlike Indra, which milch-kine make sweet for thee: with Kanva's
							sons are gifts for thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							With homage have we sought thee as a Hero, strong, preeminent, with
							unfailing wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Thunderer, as a plenteous spring pours forth its stream, so, Indra,
							flow our songs to thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							If now thou art at sacrifice, or if thou art upon the earth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come thence, high-thoughted! to our sacrifice with the Swift, come,
							Mighty with the Mighty Ones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The active, fleet-foot, tawny Coursers that are thine are swift to
							victory, like the Wind,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith thou goest round to visit Manus' seed, wherewith all heaven
							is visible.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, from thee so great we crave prosperity in wealth of kine,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							As, Maghavan, thou favouredst Medhyatithi, and, in the fight,
							Nipatithi.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							As, Maghavan, to Kanva, Trasadasyu, and to Paktha and Dasavraja;
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 93: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							As, Indra, to Gosarya and Rjisvan, thou vouchsafedst wealth in kine and
							gold.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 94
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SAKRA I praise, to win his aid, far-famed, exceeding bountiful,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who gives, as 'twere in thousands, precious wealth to him who sheds the
							juice and worships him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Arrows with hundred points, unconquerable, are this Indra's n-dghty
							arms in war.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He streams on liberal worshippers like a hill with springs, when juices
							poured have gladdened him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the flowing Soma-drops have gladdened with their taste the
							Friend,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like water, gracious Lord! were my libations made, like milch-kine to
							the worshipper.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the peerless, who is calling you to give you aid, forth flow the
							drops of pleasant meath.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Soloa-drops which call on thee, O gracious Lord, have brought thee
							to our hymn of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He rushes hurrying like a steed to Soma that adorns our rite,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Which hymns make sweet to thee, lover of pleasant food. The call to
							Paura thou dost love.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praise the strong, grasping Hero, winner of the spoil, ruling supreme
							oer mighty wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a full spring, O Thunderer, from thy store hast thou poured on the
							worshipper evermore.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now whether thou be far away, or in the heavens, or on the earth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra, mighty- thoughted, harnessing thy Bays, come Lofty with the
							Lofty Ones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Bays who draw thy chariot, Steeds who injure none, surpass the
							wind's impetuous strength-
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With whom thou silencest the enemy of man, with whon; thou goest round
							the sky.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							O gracious Hero, may we learn anew to know thee as thou art:
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							As in decisive fight thou holpest Etasa, or Vasa 'gainst Dasavraja,
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							As, Maghavan, to Kanva at the sacred feast, to Dirghanitha thine
							home-friend,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							As to Gosarya thou, Stone-darter, gavest wealth, give me a gold-bright
							stall of kine.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 95
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As with Manu Samvarani, Indra, thou drankest Soma juice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, Maghavan, with Nipatithi, Medbyatithi, with Pustigu and Srustigu,-
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							T'he son of Prsadvana was Praskaniva's host, who lay decrepit and
							forlorn.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Aided by thee the Rsi Dasyave-vrka strove to obtain thousands of kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call hither with thy newest song Indra who lacks not hymns of praise,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who observes and knows, inspirer of the sage, him who seems eager
							to enjoy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He unto whom they sang the seven-headed hymn, three-parted, in the
							loftiest place,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He sent his thunder down on all these living things, and so displayed
							heroic might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							We invocate that Indra who bestoweth precious things on us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now do we know his newest favour; may we gain a stable that is full of
							kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							He whom thou aidest, gracious Lord, to give again, obtains great wealth
							to nourish him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							We with our Soma ready, Lover of the Song! call, Indra Maghavan, on
							thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ne'er art thou fruitless, Indra ne'er dost thou desert the worshipper
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							But now, O Maghavan, thy bounty as a God is poured forth ever more and
							more.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who hath. overtaken Krvi with his might, and silenced Susna with
							deathbolts,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							When he supported yonder heaven and spread it out, then first the son
							of earth was born.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Good Lord of wealth is he to whom all Aryas, Dasas here belong.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Directly unto thee, the pious Rusama Paviru, is that wealth brought
							nigh.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							In zealous haste the singers have sung forth a song distilling oil and
							rich in sweets.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Riches have spread among us and heroic strength, with us are flowing
							Soma-drops.
						-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 96
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As, Sakra, thou with Manu called Vivasvan drankest Soma juice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As, Indra, thou didst love the hymn by Trita's side, so dost thou joy
							with Ayu now.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As thou with Matarisvan, Medhya, Prsadhra, hast cheered thee Indra,
							with pressed juice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drunk Soma with Rjunas, Syumarasmi, by Dasonya's Dasasipra's side.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							'Tis he who made the lauds his own and boldly drank the Soma juice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He to whom Visnu came striding his three wide steps, as Mitra's
							statutes ordered it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							In whose laud thou didst joy, Indra, at the great deed, O Satakratu,
							Mighty One!
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seeking renown we call thee as the milkers call the cow who yields
							abundant milk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He is our Sire who gives to us, Great, Mighty, ruling as he wills.
						-
					-
						Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unsought, may he the Strong, Rich, Lord of ample wealth, give us of
