							He flows about the sheep-skin, longing for a bride: he looses Aditi's
							Daughters for the worshipper.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The sacred drink hath come, gold-tinted, well-restrained: like a strong
							Bull he shines, whetting his manly might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Bull is bellowing; the Cows are coming nigh: the Goddesses approach
							the God's own resting-place.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Onward hath Soma passed through the sheep's fair bright fleece, and
							hath, as 'twere, endued a garment newly washed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The golden-hued, Immortal, newly bathed, puts on a brightly shining
							vesture that is never harmed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He made the ridge of heaven to be his radiant robe, by sprinkling of
							the bowls from moisture of the sky.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as the beams of Surya, urging men to speed, that cheer and send to
							sleep, together rush they forth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							These swift outpourings in long course of holy rites: no form save only
							Indra shows itself so pure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							As down the steep slope of a river to the vale, drawn from the Steer
							the swift strong draughts have found a way.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well be it with the men and cattle in our home. May powers, O Soma, may
							the people stay with us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pour out upon us wealth in goods, in gold, in steeds, in cattle and in
							corn, and great heroic strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, Soma, are my Fathers, lifted up on high as heads of heaven and
							makers of the strength of life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Pavamanas here, these drops of Soma, to Indra have sped forth
							like cars to booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Effused, they pass the cleansing fleece, while, gold-hued, they cast
							their covering off to pour the rain down.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indu, flow thou on for lofty Indra, flow blameless, very gracious,
							foe-destroyer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 69: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring splendid treasures to the man who lauds thee. O Heaven and Earth,
							with all the Gods protect. us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 70
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE three times seven Milch-kine in the eastern heaven have for this
							Soma poured the genuine milky draught.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Four other beauteous Creatures hath he made for his adornment, when he
							waxed in strength through holy rites.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Longing for lovely Amrta, by his wisdom he divided, each apart from
							other, earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He gladly wrapped himself in the most lucid floods, when through their
							glory they found the God's resting-place.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May those his brilliant rays he ever free from death, inviolate, for
							both classes of created things,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rays wherewith powers of men and Gods are purified. Yea, even for this
							have sageswelcomed him as King.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, while he is adorned by the ten skilful ones, that he too in the
							Midmost Mothers may create,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							While he is watching o'er the lovely Amrta's ways, looks on both races
							as Beholder of mankind.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, while he is adorned to stream forth mighty strength, rejoices in
							his place between the earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Steer dispels the evil-hearted with his might, aiming at offerings
							as an archer at the game.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Beholding, as it were, Two Mother Cows, the Steer goes roaring on his
							way even as the Maruts roar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Knowing Eternal Law, the earliest light of heaven, he, passing wise,
							was chosen out to tell it forth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The fearful Bull is bellowing with violent might, far-sighted,
							sharpening his yellowcoloured horns.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Soma assumes his seat in the well-fashioned place: the cowhide and the
							sheepskin are his ornament.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bright, making pure his body free from spot and stain, on the sheep's
							back the Golden-coloured hath flowed down.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Acceptable to Mitra, Vayu, Varuna, he is prepared as threefold meal by
							skilful men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Flow on for the God's banquet, Soma, as a Steer, and enter Indra's
							heart, the Soma's reservoir.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bear us beyond misfortune ere we be oppres. sed. the man who knows the
							land directs the man who asks.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Urged like a car-steed flow to strength, O Soma: Indu, flow onward to
							the throat of Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 70: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Skilled, bear us past, as in a boat o'er water: as battling Hero save
							us from the foeman.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 71
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE guerdon is bestowed: the Mighty takes his Seat, and, ever-Watchful,
							guards from fiend and evil sprite.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gold-hued, he makes the cloud his diadem, the milk his carpet in both
							worlds, and prayer his robe of state.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong, bellowing, he goes, like one who slays the folk; he lets this
							hue of Asuras flow off from him,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Throws off his covering, seeks his father's meeting-place, and thus
							makes for himself the bright robe he assumes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Onward he flows, from both the hands, pressed out with stones: excited
							by the prayer, the water makes him wild.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He frolics and draws near, completes his work with song, and bathes in
							streams to satisfy the worshipper.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They pour out meath around the Master of the house, Celestial
							Strengthener of the mountain that gives might;
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							In whom, through his great powers, oblation-eating cows in their
							uplifted udder mix their choicest milk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							They, the ten sisters, on the lap of Aditi, have sent him forward like
							a car from both the arms.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He wanders and comes near the Cow's mysterious place, even the place
							which his inventions have produced.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as a falcon to his home, so speeds the God to his own golden
							wisely-tashioned place to rest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							With song they urge the darling to the sacred grass: the Holy One goes
							like a courser to the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							From far away, from heaven, the redhued noted Sage, Steer of the triple
							height, hath sung unto the kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thousand guidings he, leading this way and that, shines, as a
							singer, splendidly through many a morn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							His covering assumes a radiant hue; where'er he comes into the fight he
							drives the foe afar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Winner of the Floods, with food he seeks the host of heaven, he
							comes to praises glorified with milk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a bull roaming round the herds he bellows: he hath assumed the
							brilliancy of Surya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 71: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Down to the earth hath looked the heavenly Falcon: Soma with wisdom
							views all living creatures.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 72
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THEY cleanse the Gold-hued: like a red Steed is he yoked, and Soma in
							the jar is mingled with the milk.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He sendeth out his voice, and many loving friends of him the highly
							lauded hasten with their songs.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The many sages utter words in unison, while into Indra's throat they
							pour the Soma juice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, with the ten that dwell together closely joined, the men whose
							hands are skilful cleanse the lovely meath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He goes upon his way, unresting, to the cows, over the roaring sound
							which Sarya's Daughter loves.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Falcon brought it to him for his own delight: now with the twofold
							kindred sisters is his home.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Washed by the men, stone-pressed, dear on the holy grass, faithful to
							seasons, Lord of cattle from of old,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most liberal, completing sacrifice for men, O Indra, pure bright Soma,
							Indu, flows for thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, urged by arms of men and poured in streams, Soma flows on for
							thee after.his Godlike kind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Plans thou fulfillest, gatherest thoughts for sacrifice: in the bowls
							sits the Gold-hued like a roosting bird.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sages well-skilled in work, intelligent, drain out the stalk that
							roars, the Sage, the Everlasting One.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The milk, the hymns unite them with him in the place of sacrifice, his
							seat who is produced anew.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Earth's central point, sustainer of the mighty heavens, distilled into
							the streams, into the waters' wave,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							As Indra's thunderbolt, Steer with farspreading wealth, Soma is flowing
							on to make the heart rejoice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Over the earthly region flow thou on thy way, helping the praiser and
							the pourer, thou Most Wise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us not lack rich treasure reaching to our home, and may we clothe
							ourselves in manifold bright wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither, O Indu, unto us a hundred gifts of steeds, a thousand gifts of
							cattle and of gold,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 72: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Measure thou forth, yea, splendid ample strengthening food do thou, O
							Pavamana, heed this laud of ours.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 73
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THEY from the spouting drop have sounded at the rim: naves speed
							together to the place of sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That Asura hath formed, to seize, three lofty heights. The ships of
							truth have borne the pious man across.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The strong Steers, gathering, have duly stirred themselves,and over the
							stream's wave the friends sent forth the song.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Engendering the hymn, with flowing streams of meath, Indra's dear body
							have they caused to wax in strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With sanctifying gear they sit around the song: their ancient Father
							guards their holy work from harm.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Varuna hath o'erspread the mighty sea of air. Sages had power to hold
							him in sustaining floods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sweet-tongued, exhaustless, they have sent their voices down togetlier,
							in heaven's vault that pours a thousand streams.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							His wildly-restless warders never close an eye: in every place are
							found the bonds that bind man last.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O'er Sire and Mother they have roared in unison bright with the verse
							of praise, burning up riteless men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blowing away with supernatural might from earth and from the heavens
							the swarthy skin which Indra hates.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those which, as guides of song and counsellors of speed, were
							manifested from their ancient dwelling place,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							From these the eyeless and the deaf have turned aside: the wicked
							travel not the pathway of the Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the filter with a thousand streams is stretched, the
							thoughtful sages purify their song therein.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bright-coloured are their spies, vigorous, void of guile, excellent,
							fair to see, beholders of mankind.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guardian of Law, most wise, he may not be deceived: three Purifiers
							hath he set within his heart.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With wisdom he beholds all creatures that exist: he drives into the pit
							the hated riteliess ones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The thread of sacrifice spun in the cleansing sieve, on Varuna's
							tongue-tip, by supernatural might,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 73: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							This, by their striving, have the prudent ones attained: he who hath
							not this power shall sink into the pit.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 74
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BORN like a youngling he hath clamoured in the wood, when he, the Red,
							the Strong, would win the light of heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He comes with heavenly seed that makes the water swell: him for
							wide-spreading shelter we implore with prayer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							A far-extended pillar that supports the sky the Soma-stalk, filled
							full, moves itself every way.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He shall bring both these great worlds while the rite proceeds: the
							Sage holds these who move! together and all food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wide space hath he who follows Aditi's right path, and mighty,
							well-made food, meath blent with Soma juice;
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who from hence commands the rain, Steer of the kine, Leader of
							floods, who helps us hence, who claims our laud.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Butter and milk are drawn from animated cloud; thence Amrta is
							produced, centre of sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hini the Most Bounteous Ones, ever united, love; him as ouir Friend the
							Men who make all swell rain down.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Soma-stalk hath roared, following with the wave: he swells with sap
							for man the skin which Gods enjoy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Upon the lap of Aditi he lays the germ, by means whereof we gain
							children and progeny.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							In the third region which distils a thousand streams, may the
							Exhaustless Ones descend with procreant power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The kindred Four have been sent downward from the heavens: dropping
							with oil they bring Amrta and sacred gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma assumes white colour when he strives to gain: the bounteous Asura
							knows full many a precious boon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Down the steep slope, through song, he comes to sacrifice, and he will
							burst the water-holding cask of heaven,
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, to the shining milk-anointed beaker, as to his goal, hath stepped
							the conquering Courser.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pious-souled men have sent their giffi of cattle unto Kaksivan of the
							hundred winters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma, thy juice when thou art blended with the streams, flows,
							Pavamana, through the long wool of the sheep.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 74: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, cleansed by sages. O best giver of delight, grow sweet for Indra,
							Pavamana! for his drink.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 75
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GRACIOUSLY-MINDED he is flowing on his way to win dear names o'er which
							the Youthful One grows great.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mighty and Far-seeing One hath mounted now the mighty Surya's car
							which moves to every side.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Speaker, unassailable Master of this hymn, the Tongue of sacrifice
							pours forth the pleasant meath.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Within the lustrous region of the heavens the Son makes the third
							secret name of Mother and of Sire.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sending forth flashes he hath bellowed to the jars, led by the men into
							the golden reservoir.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The milky streams of sacrifice have sung to him: he of the triple
							height shines brightly through the morns.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pressed by the stones, with hymns, and graciously inclined,
							illuminating both the Parents, Heaven and Earth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He flows in ordered season onward through the flee, a current of sweet
							juice still swelling day by day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Flow onward, Soma, flow to bring prosperity: cleansed by the men,
							invest thee with the milky draught.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 75: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							What gladdening drinks thou hast, foaming, exceeding strong, even with
							these incite Indra to give us wealth.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 76
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ON flows the potent juice, sustainer of the heavens, the strength of
							Gods, whom men must hail with shouts of joy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Gold-hued, started like a courser by brave men, impetuously winneth
							splendour in the streams.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He takes his weapons, like a hero, in his hands, fain to win light,
							car-borne, in forays for the kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indu, while stimulating India's might, is urged forward and balmed by
							sages skilful in their task.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma, as thou art purified with flowing wave, exhibiting thy strength
							enter thou Indra's throat.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make both worlds stream for us, as lightning doth the clouds: mete out
							exhaustless powers for us, as 'twere through song.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Onward he flows, the King of all that sees the light: the Rsis' Lord
							hath raised the song of sacrifice;
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even he who is adorned with Surya's arrowy beam, Father of hymns, whose
							wisdom is beyond our reach.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as a bull to herds, thou flowest to the pail, bellowing as a steer
							upon the water's lap.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 76: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, best of Cheerers, thou for Indra flowest on that we, with thy
							protection, may o'ercome in fight.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 77
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MORE beauteous than the beautiful, as Indra's bolt, this Soma, rich in
							sweets, hath clamoured in the vat.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dropping with oil, abundant, streams of sacrifice flow unto him like
							milch-kine, lowing, with their milk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							On flows that Ancient One whom, hitherward, from heaven, sped through
							the region of the air, the Falcon snatched.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, quivering with alarm and terrified in heart before bow-armed
							Krsanu, holdeth fast the sweet.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May those first freshest drops of Soma juice effused flow on, their way
							to bring us mighty strength in kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beauteous as serpents, worthy to be looked upon, they whom each sacred
							gift and all our prayers have pleased.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May that much-lauded Indu, with a heart inclined to us, well-knowing,
							fight against our enemies.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who hath brought the germ beside the Strong One's seat moves onward
							to the widely-opcned stall of kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The active potent juice of heaven is flowing on, great Varuna whom the
							forward man can ne'er deceive.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mitra, the Holy, hath been pressed for troubled times, neighing like an
							impatient horse amid the herd,
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 78
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							RAISING his voice the King hath flowed upon his way: invested with the
							waters he would win the kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The fleece retains his solid parts as though impure, and bright and
							cleansed he seeks the special place of Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Soma, art effused for Indra by the men, balmed in the wood as
							wave, Sage, Viewer of mankind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Full many are the paths whereon thou mayest go: a thousand bay steeds
							hast thou resting in the bowls.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Apsarases who dwell in waters of the sea, sitting within, have flowed
							to Soma wise of heart.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							They urge the Master of the house upon his way, and to the Eternal
							Pavamana pray for bliss.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma flows on for u's as winner of the kine, winner of thousands, cars,
							water, and light, and gold;
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He whom the Gods have made a gladdening draught to drink, the drop most
							sweet to taste, weal-bringing, red of hue.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma, as Pavamana thou, our faithful Friend, making for us these real
							treasures, flowest on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slay thou the enemy both near and,far away: grant us security and ample
							pasturage.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 79
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SPONTANEOUS let our drops of Soma juice flow on, pressed, golden-hued,
							among the Gods of lofty heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Perish among us they who give no gifts of food! perish the godless! May
							our prayers obtain success.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forward to us the drops, distilling meath, shall flow, like riches for
							whose sake we urge the horses on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beyond the crafty hindering of all mortal men may we continually bear
							precious wealth away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, yerily, foe of hate shown to himself is he, yea, verity, destroyer
							too of other hate.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As thirst subdueth in the desert, conquer thou, O Soma Pavarnana, men
							of evil thoughts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Near kin to thee is he, raised loftiest in the heavens: upon the
							earth's high ridge thy scions have grown forth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The press-stones chew and crunch thee on the ox's hide: sages have
							milked thee with their hands into the streams.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							So do they hurry on thy strong and beauteous juice, O Indu, as the
							first ingredient of the draught.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring low, thou Pavamana, every single foe, and be thy might shown
							forth as sweet and gladdening drink.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 80
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ON flows the stream of Soma who beholds mankind: by everlasting Law he
							calls the Gods from heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He lightens with the roaring of Br aspati: h the lakes have not
							contained the pourings of juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, powerful Soma, thou to whom the cows have -lowed, ascendest
							bright with sheen, thine iron-fashioned home.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, lengthening our princes' life and high renown, flowest for Indra
							as his might to gladdening drink.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Best giver of delight, he flows to Indra's throat, robing himself in
							might, Auspicious One, for fame.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He spreads himself abroad to meet all things that be: the vigorous
							Tawny Steed flows sporting on his way.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The men, the ten swift fingers, milk thee out for Gods, even thee most
							rich in meath, with thousand flowing streams.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Soma who winnest thousands, driven by the men, expressed with stones,
							bring, as thou flowest, all the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Deft-handed men with stones, the ten swift fingers, drain thee into
							waters, thee, the Steer enriched with sweets.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 80: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Soma, gladdening Indra, and the Heavenly Host, flowest as
							Pavamana like a river's wave.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 81
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ONWARD to Indra's throat move, beauteously adorned, the waves of Soma
							as he purifies himself,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When they, brought forward with the lovely curd of kine, effused, have
							cheered the Hero to bestow his gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither hath Soma flowed unto the beakers, like a chariot-horse, a
							stallion swift upon his way.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thus, knowing both the generations, he obtains the rights and dues of
							Gods from yonder and from hence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							While thou art cleansed, O Soma, scatter wealth on us; Indu, bestow
							great bounty as a liberal Prince.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giver of life, with wisdom help to opulence; strew not our home
							possessions far away from us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither let Pusan Pavamana come to us, Varuna, Mitra, bountiful, of one
							accord,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Maruts, Asvins, Vayu, and Brhaspati, Savitar, Tvastar, tractable
							Sarasvati.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Both Heaven and Earth, the all-invigorating Pair, Vidhatar, Aditi, and
							Aryaman the God,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 81: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bhaga who blesses men, the spacious Firmament,-let all the Gods in
							Pavamana take delight.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 82
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 82: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 82: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							EVEN as a King hath Soma, red and tawny Bull, been pressed: the
							Wondrous One hath bellowed to the kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 82: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							While purified he passes through the filtering fleece to seat him
							hawk-like on the place that drops with oil.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 82: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 82: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To glory goest thou, Sage with disposing skill, like a groomed steed
							thou rusbest forward to the prize.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 82: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Soma, be thou gracious, driving off distress: thou goest, clothed in
							butter, to a robe of state.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 82: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 82: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Parjanya is the Father of the Mighty Bird: on mountains, in earth's
							centre hath he made his home.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 82: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The waters too have flowed, the Sisters, to the kine: he meets the
							pressing-stones at the beloved rite.
