						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Going to Indra, sharpening his weapons, and in his hand containing
							every treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him the tones of sacred song have sounded, Steer of the triple
							height, the Life-bestower.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dwelling in wood as Varuna in rivers, lavishing treasure he distributes
							blessings
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Great Conqueror, warnor-girt, Lord of all heroes, flow on thy way as he
							who winneth riches;
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With sharpened. arms, with swift bow, never vanquished in battle,
							vanquishing in fight the foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Giving security, Lord of wide dominion, send us both earth and heaven
							with all their fulness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Striving to win the Dawns, the light, the waters, and cattle, call to
							us abundant vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Soma, gladden Varuna and Mitra; cheer, Indu Pavamana! Indra, Visnu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cheer thou the Gods, the Company of Maruts: Indu, cheer mighty Indra to
							rejoicing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus like a wise and potent King flow onward, destroying with thy
							vigour all misfortunes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 90: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							For our well-spoken hymn give life, O Indu. Do ye preserve us evermore
							with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 91
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As for a chariot-race, the skilful Speaker, Chief, Sage, Inventor,
							hath, with song, been started.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The sisters ten upon the fleecy summit drive on the Car-horse to the
							resting places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The drop of Soma, pressed by wise Nahusyas, becomes the banquet of the
							Heavenly People-
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indu, by hands of mortal men made beauteous, immortal, with the sheep
							and cows and waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Steer roaring unto Steer, this Pavamana, this juice runs to the white
							milk of the milch-cow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through thousand fine hairs goes the tuneful Singer, like Sura by his
							fair and open pathways.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Break down the, strong seats even of the demons: cleansing thee, Indu,
							robd thyself in vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rend with thy swift bolt, coming from above them, those who are near
							and those who yet are distant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prepare the forward paths in ancient manner for the new bymn, thou
							Giver of all bounties.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Those which are high and hard for foes to conquer may we gain from
							thee, Active! Food-bestower!
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							So purifying thee vouchsafe us waters, heaven's light, and cows,
							offipring and many children.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 91: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us health, ample land, and lights, O Soma, and grant us long to
							look upon the sunshine.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 92
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE gold-hued juice, poured out upon the filter, is started like a car
							sent forth to conquer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath gained song and vigour while they cleansed him, and hath
							rejoiced the Gods with entertainments.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who beholdeth man hath reached the filter: bearing his name, the
							Sage hath sought his dwelling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Rsis came to him, seven holy singers, when in the bowls he settled
							as Invoker.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shared by all Gods, mobt wise, propitious, Soma goes, while they
							cleanse him, to his constant station.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him rejoice in all his lofty wisdom to the Five Tribes the Sage
							attains with labour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							In thy mysterious place, O Pavamana Soma, are all the Gods, the
							Thrice-Eleven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ten on the fleecy height, themselves, self-prompted, and seven fresh
							rivers, brighten and adorn thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now let this be the truth of Pavamana, there where all singers gather
							them together,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							That he hath given us room and made the daylight, hath holpen Manu and
							repelled the Dasyu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the priest seeks the station rich in cattle, like a true King who
							goes to great assemblies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 92: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Soma hath sought the beakers while they cleansed him, and like a wild
							bull, in the wood hath settled.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 93
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							TEN sisters, pouring out the rain together, swift-moving thinkers of
							the sage, adorn him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hither hath run the gold-hued Child of Surya and reached the vat like a
							fleet vigorous courser.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as a youngling crying to his mothers, the bounteous Steer hath
							flowed along to waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As youth to damsel, so with milk he hastens on to the. chose
							meeting-place, the beaker.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, swollen is the udder of the milch-cow: thither in streams goes
							very sapient Indu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The kine make ready, as with new-washed treasures, the Head and Chief
							with milk within the vessels.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With all the Gods, O Indu Pavamana, while thou art roaring send us
							wealth in horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hither upon her car come willing Plenty, inclined to us, to give us of
							her treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 93: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now unto us mete riches, while they cleansethee, all-glorious, swelling
							wealth, with store of heroes.
