					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 94: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They, clothed in glory, have become immortal. He, measured in his
							course, makes frays successful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 94: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stream to us food and vigour, kine and horses: give us broad lights and
							fill thGods with rapture.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							All ther are easy things for thee to master thou, Pavamana Soma,
							quellest foemen.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 95
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loud neighs the Tawny Steed when started, settling deep in the wooden
							vessel while they cleanse him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Led by the men he takes the milk for raiment: then shall he, through
							his powers, engender praise-songs.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As one who rows drives on his boat, he, Gold-hued, sends forth his
							voice, loosed on the path of Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As God, the secret names of Gods he utters, to be declared on sacred
							grass more widely.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hastening onward like the waves of waters, our holy hymns are pressing
							nigh to Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him they come with lowly adoration, and, longing, enter him who
							longs to meet them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They drain the stalk, the Steer who dwells on mountains, even as a Bull
							who decks him on the upland.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hymns follow and attend him as he bellows: Trita bears Varuna aloft in
							ocean.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sending thy voice out as Director, loosen the Invoker's thought, O
							Indu, as they cleanse thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							While thou and Indra rule for our advantage, may we be masters of
							heroic vigour.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 96
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							IN forefront of the cars forth goes the Hero, the Leader, winning
							spoil: his host rejoices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Soma endues his robes of lasting colours, and blesses, for his friends,
							their calls on Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men decked with gold adorn his golden tendril, incessantly with
							steed-impelling homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Friend of Indra mounts his car well-knowing, he comes thereon to
							meet the prayer we offer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O God, for service of the Gods flow onward, for food sublime, as
							Indra's drink, O Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Making the floods, bedewing earth and heaven, come from the vast,
							comfort us while we cleanse thee
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Flow for prosperity and constant Vigour, flow on for happiness and high
							perfection.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							This is the wish of these friends assembled: this is my wish, O Soma
							Pavamana.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Father of holy hymns, Soma flows onward the Father of the earth, Father
							of heaven:
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Father of Agni, Surya's generator, the Father who begat Indra and
							Visnu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brahman of Gods, the Leader of the poets, Rsi of sages, Bull of savage
							creatures,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Falcon amid the vultures, Axe of forests, over the cleansing sieve goes
							Soma singing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, Soma Pavamana, like a river, hath stirred the wave of voice, our
							songs and praises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beholding these inferior powers in cattle, he rests among them as a
							Steer well-knowing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							As Gladdener, Warrior never harmed in battle, with thousand genial
							streams, pour strength and vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							As thoughtful Pavamana, urge O Indu, speeding the kine, the plant's
							wave on to Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dear, grateful to the Gods, on to the beaker moves Soma, sweet to
							Indra, to delight him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							With hundred powers, with thousand currents, Indu, like a strong
							car-horse, goes to the assembly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born in old time as finder-out of treasures, drained with the stone,
							decking himself in waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Warding off curses, King of all existence, he shall find way for prayer
							the while they cleanse him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							For our sage fathers, Soma Pavamana, of old performed, by thee, their
							sacred duties.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fighting unvanquished, open the enclosures: enrich us with large gifts
							of steeds and heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							As thou didst flow for Manu Life-bestowing, Foe-queller, Comforter,
							rich in oblations,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even thus flow onward now conferring riches: combine with Indra, and
							bring forth thy weapons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Flow onward, Soma, rich in sweets and holy,. enrobed in waters on the
							fleecy summit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Settle in vessels that are full of fatness, as cheering and most
							gladdening drink for Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pour, hundred-streamed, winner of thousands, mighty at the Gods'
							banquet, Pour the rain of heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							While thou with rivers roarest in the beaker, and blent with milk
							prolongest our existence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Purified with our holy hymns, this Soma o'ertakes malignities like some
							strong charger,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like fresh milk poured by Aditi, like passage in ample room, or like a
							docile car-horse.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Cleansed by the pressers, armed with noble weapons, stream to us the
							fair secret name thou bearest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pour booty, like a horse, for love of glory God, Soma, send us kine,
							and send us Vayu.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							They deck him at his birth, the lovely Infant, the Maruts with their
							troop adorn the Car-horse.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							By songs a Poet and a Sage by wisdom, Soma joes singing through the
							cleansing filter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Light-winner, Rsi-mindcd, Rsi-maker, hymned in a thousand hymns, Leader
							of sages,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							A Steer who strives to gain his third form, Soma is, like Viraj,
							resplendent as a Singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hawk seated in the bowls, Bird wide-extended, the Banner seeking kine
							and wielding weapons,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Following close the sea, the wave of waters, the great Bull tells his
							fourth form and declares it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a fair youth who decorates his body, a courser rushing to the gain
							of riches,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							A steer to herds, so, flowing to the pitcher, he with a roar hath
							passed into the beakers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Flow on with might as Pavamana, Indu flow loudly roaring through the
							fleecy filter.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enter the beakers sporting, as they cleanse thee, and let thy
							gladdening juice make Indra joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							His streams have been effused in all their fulness, and he hath
							entered, balmed with milk, the goblets.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Singing his psalm, well-skilled in song, a Chanter, be comes as 'twere
							to his friend's sister roaring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							Chasing our foes thou comest, Pavamana Indu, besting, as lover to his
							darling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							As a bird flies and settles in the forest, thus Soma settles, purified,
							in goblets.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							With full stream and abundant milk, O Soma, thy beams come, like a
							woman, as they cleanse thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 96: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, gold-hued, rich in boons, brought to the waters, hath roared within
							the goblet of the pious.
						-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 97
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MADE pure by this man's urgent zeal and impulse the God hath to the
							Gods his juice imparted.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He goes, effused and singing, to the filter, like priest to measured
							seats supplied with cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Robed in fair raiment meet to wear in battle, a mighty Sage pronouncing
							invocations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Roll onward to the beakers as they cleanse thee, far-seeing at the
							feast of Gods, and watchful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dear, he is brightened on the fleecy summit, a Prince among us, nobler
							than the noble.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Roar out as thou art purified, run forward. Do ye preserve us evermore
							with blessings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let us sing praises to the Gods: sing loudly, send ye the Soma forth
							for mighty riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him flow, sweetly-flavoured, through the filter, and let our pious
							one rest in the pitcher.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Winning the friendship of the Deities, Indu flows in a thousand streams
							to make them joyful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Praised by the men after the ancient statute, he hath come nigh, for
							our great bliss, to Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Flow, Gold-hued, cleansing thee, to enrich the singer: let thy juice go
							to Indra to support him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come nigh, together with the Gods, for bounty. Do ye preserve us
							evermore with blessings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The God declares the Deities' generations, like Usana, proclaiming
							lofty wisdom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With brilliant kin, far-ruling, sanctifying, the Boar advances,
							singing, to the places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Swans, the Vrsaganas from anear us have brought their restless
							spirit to our dwelling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Friends come to Pavamana meet for praises, and sound in concert their
							resistless music.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							He follows the Wide-strider's rapid movement: cows low, as 'twere, to
							him who sports at pleasure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He with the sharpened horns brings forth abundance: the Silvery shines
							by night, by day the Golden.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong Indu, bathed in milk, flows on for Indra, Soma exciting
							strength, to make him joyful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He quells malignities and slays the demons, the King of mighty power
							who brings us comfort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then in a stream he flows, milked out with press-stones, mingled with
							sweetness, through the fleecy filter-
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indu rejoicing in the love of Indra, the God who gladdens, for the
							God's enjoyment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							As he is purified he pours out treasures, a God bedewing Gods with his
							own juices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indu hath, wearing qualities by seasons, on the raised fleece engaged,
							the ten swift fingers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Red Bull bellowing to the kine advances, causing the heavens and
							earth to roar and tbunder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well is he beard like Indra's shout in battle: letting this voice be
							known he hastens hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Swelling with milk, abounding in sweet flavours, urging the meath-rich
							plant thou goest onward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Raising a shout thou flowest as they cleanse thee, when thou, O Soma,
							art effused for Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							So flow thou on inspiriting, for rapture, aiming deatb-shafts at him
							who stays the waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Flow to us wearing thy resplendent colour, effused and eager for the
							kine, O Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pleased with us, Indu, send us as thou flowest good easy paths in ample
							space and comforts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dispelling, as 'twere with a club, misfortunes, run o'er the height,
							run o'er the fleecy summit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pour on us rain celestial, quickly streaming, refreshing, fraught with
							health and ready bounty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Flow, Indu, send these Winds thy lower kinsmen, setting them free like
							locks of hair unbraided.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Part, like a knotted tangle, while they cleanse thee, O Soma, righteous
							and unrighteous conduct.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Neigh like a tawny courser who is loosened, come like a youth, O God, a
							house-possessor.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							For the God's service, for delight, O Indu, run o'er the height, run
							o'ver the fleecy summit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thousand streams, inviolate, sweet-scented, flow on for gain of
							strength that conquers heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Without a car, without a rein to guide them, unyoked, like coursers
							started in the contest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							These brilliant drops of Soma juice run forward. Do ye, O Deities, come
							nigh to drink them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							So for our banquet of the Gods, O Indu, pour down the rain of heaven
							into the vessels.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Soma grant us riches sought with longing, mighty, exceeding strong,
							with store of heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the loving spirit's word had formed him Chief of all food, by
							statute of the Highest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then loudly lowing came the cows to Indu, the chosen, well-loved Master
							in the beaker.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sage, Celestial, liberal, raining bounties, pours as he flows the
							Genuine for the Truthful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							The King shall be effectual strength's upholder: he by the ten bright
							reins is mostly guided.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who beholds mankind, made pure with filters, the King supreme of
							Deities and mortals,
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							From days of old is Treasure-Lord of riches: he, Indu, cherishes fair
							well-kept Order.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 25: Line 1
					-
						-
							Haste, like a steed, to vittory for glory, to Indra's and to Vayu's
							entertainment.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 25: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us food ample, thousandfold: be, Soma, the finder-out of riches
							when they cleanse thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 26
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 26: Line 1
					-
						-
							Effused by us let God-delighting Somas bring as they flow a home with
							noble heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 26: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rich in all boons like priests acquiring favour, the worshippers of
							heaven, the best of Cheerers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 27: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, God, for service of the Gods flow onward, flow, drink of Gods, for
							ample food, O Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 27: Line 2
					-
						-
							For we go forth to war against the mighty make heaven and earth well
							stablished by thy cleansing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 28
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 28: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, yoked by strong men, neighest like a courser, swifter than
							thought is, like an awful lion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 28: Line 2
					-
						-
							By paths directed hitherward, the straightest, send thou us happiness,
							Indu, while they cleanse thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 29
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 29: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sprung from the Gods, a hundred streams, a thousand, have been effused:
							sages prepare and purge them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 29: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring us from heaven the means of winnning, Indu; thou art-forerunnner
							of abundant riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 30
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 30: Line 1
					-
						-
							The streams of days, were poured as 'twere from heaven: the wise King
							doth not treat his friend unkindly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 30: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a son following his father's wishes, grant to this family success
							and safety.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 31
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 31: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now are thy streams poured forth with all their sweetness, when,
							purified. thou goest through the filter.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 31: Line 2
					-
						-
							The race of kine is thy gift, Pavarridna: when born thou madest Surya
							rich with brightness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 32
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 32: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bright, bellowing aiong the path of Order, thou shinest as the form of
							life eternal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 32: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou flowest on as gladdening drink for Indra, sending thy voice out
							with the hymns of sages.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 33
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 33: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pouring out streams at the Gods' feast with service, thou, Soma,
							lookest down, a heavenly Eagle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 33: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enter the Soma-holding beaker, Indu, and with a roar approach the ray
							of Sarya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 34
				-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 34: Line 1
					-
						-
							Three are the voices that the Courser utters: he speaks the thought of
							prayer, the law of Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 9: Hymn 97: Verse 34: Line 2
					-
