					-
						-
							When we most ignorant neglect the statutes of you, O Deities with whom
							is knowledge,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wise Agni shall correct our faults and failings, skilled to assign each
							God his fitting season.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, weak in mind, of feeble understanding, mortals bethink them not
							of sacrificing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then shall the prudent and discerning Agni worship the Gods, best
							worshipper, in season.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Because the Father hath produced thee, Leader of all our solemn rites,
							their brilliant Banner:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							So win by worship pleasant homes abounding in heroes, and rich food to
							nourish all men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou whom the Heaven and Earth, thou whom the Waters, and Tvastar,
							maker of fair things, created,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 2: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well knowing, all along the Fathers' pathway, shine with resplendent
							light, enkindled, Agni.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 3
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O KING, the potent and terrific envoy, kindled for strength, is
							manifest in beauty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He shines, all-knowing, with his lotty splendour: chasing black Night
							he comes with white-rayed Morning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Having o'ercome the glimmering Black with beauty, and bringing forth
							the dame the Great Sire's Daughter,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Holding aloft the radiant light of Surya, as messenger of heaven he
							shines with treasures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Attendant on the Blessed Dame the Blessed hath come: the Lover
							followeth his Sister.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, far-spreading with conspicuous lustre, hath compassed Night with
							whitelyshining garments.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							His goings-forth kindle as 'twere high voices the goings of the
							auspicious Friend of Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The rays, the bright beams of the strong-jawed, mighty, adorable Steer
							are visible as he cometh.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whose radiant splendours flow, like sounds, about us, his who is lofty,
							brilliant, and effulgent,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who reaches heaven with best and brightest lustres, sportive and
							piercing even to the summit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							His powers, whose chariot fellies gleam and glitter have loudly roared
							while, as with teams, he hasted.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, the most Godlike, far-extending envoy, shines with flames ancient,
							resonant, whitely-shining.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							So bring us ample wealth: seat thee as envoy of the two youthful
							Matrons, Earth and Heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 3: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let Agni rapid with his rapid, horses, impetuous with impetuous Steeds,
							come hither.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 4
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee will send praise and bring oblation, as thou hast merited lauds
							when we invoked thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							A fountain in the desert art thou, Agni, O Ancient King, to man who
							fain would worship,
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou unto whom resort the gathered people, as the kine seek the warm
							stall, O Most Youthful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art the messenger of Gods and mortals, and goest glorious with thy
							light between them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Making thee grow as 'twere some noble infant, thy Mother nurtures thee
							with sweet affection.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Over the desert slopes thou passest longing, and seekest, like some
							beast set free, thy fodder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Foolish are we, O Wise and free from error: verily, Agni, thou dost
							know thy grandeur.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							There lies the form: he moves and licks, and swallows, and, as
							House-Lord, kisses the Youthful Maiden.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He rises ever fresh in ancient fuel: smoke-bannered, gray, he makes the
							wood his dwelling.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							No swimmer, Steer, he presses through the waters, and to his place
							accordant mortals bear him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like thieves who risk their lives and haunt the forest, the twain with
							their ten girdles have secured him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							This is a new hymn meant for thee, O Agni: yoke as it were thy car with
							parts that glitter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Homage and prayer are thine, O Jatavedas, and this my song shall
							evermore exalt thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 4: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, protect our children and descendants, and guard with
							ever-watcliful care our bodies.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 5
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HE only is the Sea, holder of treasures: born many a time he views the
							hearts within us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hides him in the secret couple's bosom. The Bird dwells in the
							middle of the fountain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Inhabiting one dwelling-place in common, strong Stallions and the Mares
							have come together.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The sages guard the seat of Holy Order, and keep the highest names
							concealed within them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Holy Pair, of wondrous power, have coupled: they formed the Infant,
							they who bred produced him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The central point of all that moves and moves not, the while they wove
							the Sage's thread with insight
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For tracks of Order and refreshing viands attend from ancient times the
							goodly Infant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wearing him as a mantle, Earth and Heaven grow strong by food of
							pleasant drink and fatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, calling loudly to the Seven red Sisters, hath, skilled in sweet
							drink, brought them to be looked on.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, born of old, in middle air hath halted, and sought and found the
							covering robe of Pusan.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Seven are the pathways which the wise have fashioned; to one of these
							may come the troubled mortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He standeth in the dwelling of the Highest, a Pillar, on sure ground
							where paths are parted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not Being, Being in the highest heaven, in Aditi's bosom and in Daksa's
							birthplace,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 5: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is Agni, our first-born of Holy Order, the Milch-cow and the Bull in
							life's beginning.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 6
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS is that Agni, he by whose protection, favour, and help. the singer
							is successful;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who with the noblest flames of glowing fuel comes forth encompassed
							with far-spreading lustre.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, the Holy One, the everlasting, who shines far beaming with
							celestial splendours;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who hath come unto his friends with friendship, like a fleet steed
							who never trips or stumbles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who is Lord of all divine oblation, shared by all living men at
							break of morning,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni to whom our offerings are devoted, in whom rests he whose car,
							through might, is scatheless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Increasing by his strength. while lauds content him, with easy flight
							unto the Gods he travels.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni the cheerful Priest, best Sacrificer, balms with his tongue the
							Gods with whom he mingles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With songs and adorations bring ye hither Agni who stirs himself at
							dawn like Indra,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom sages laud with hymns as Jatavedas of those who wield the
							sacrificial ladle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							In whom all goodly treasures meet together, even as steeds and riders
							for the booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Inclining hither bring us help, O Agni, even assistance most desired by
							Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, at thy birth, when thou hadst sat in glory, thou, Agni, wast the
							aim of invocations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 6: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Gods came near, obedient to thy sunimons, and thus attained their
							rank as chief Protectors.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 7
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O AGNI, shared by all men living bring us good luck for sacrifice from
							earth and heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With us be thine intelligence, WonderWorker! Protect us, God, with thy
							far-reaching blessings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							These hymns brought forth for thee, O Agni, laud thee for bounteous
							gifts, with cattle and with horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Good Lord, when man from thee hath gained enjoyment, by hymns, O
							noblyborn, hath he obtained it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni I deem my Kinsman and my Father, count him my Brother and my
							Friend for ever.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							I honour as the face of lofty Agni in heaven the bright and holy light
							of Surya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Effectual, Agni, are our prayers for profit. He whom, at home thou,
							Priest for ever, guardest
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is rich in food, drawn by red steeds, and holy: by day and night to him
							shall all be pleasant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men with their arms have generated Agni, helpful as some kind friend,
							adorned with splendours,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And stablished as Invoker mid the people the ancient Priest the
							sacrifice's lover.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worship, thyself, O God, the Gods in heaven: what, void of knowledge,
							shall the fool avail thee?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As thou, O God, hast worshipped Gods by seasons, so, nobly-born! to
							thine own self pay worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, be thou our Guardian and Protector bestow upon us life and vital
							vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 7: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Accept, O Mighty One, the gifts we offer, and with unceasing care
							protect our bodies.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 8
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI advances with his lofty banner: the Bull is bellowing to the earth
							and heavens.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath attained the sky's supremest limits. the Steer hath waxen in
							the lap of waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Bull, the youngling with the hump, hath frolicked, the strong and
							never-ceasing Calf hath bellowed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bringing our offerings to the God's assembly, he moves as Chief in his
							own dwelling-places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him who hath grasped his Parents' head, they stablished at sacrifice a
							wave of heavenly lustre.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In his swift flight the red Dawns borne by horses refresh their bodies
							in the home of Order.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For, Vasu thou precedest every Morning, and still hast been the Twins'
							illuminator.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							For sacrifice, seven places thou retainest while for thine own self
							thou engenderest Mitra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art the Eye and Guard of mighty Order, and Varuna when to
							sacrifice thou comest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art the Waters' Child O Jatavedas, envoy of him whose offering
							thou acceptest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art the Leader of the rite and region, to which with thine
							auspicious teams thou teadest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy light-bestowing head to heaven thou liftest, making thy tongue the
							oblationbearer, Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through his wise insight Trita in the cavern, seeking as ever the Chief
							Sire's intention,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Carefully tended in his Parents' bosom, calling the weapons kin, goes
							forth to combat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well-skilled to use the weapons of his Father, Aptya, urged on by
							Indra, fought the battle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then Trita slew the foe seven-rayed, three-headed, and freed the cattle
							of the Son of Tvastar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of the brave, Indra cleft him in pieces who sought to gain much
							strength and deemed him mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 8: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He smote his three heads from his body, seizing the cattle of the
							oniniform Son of Tvastar.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 9
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YE, Waters, are beneficent: so help ye us to energy
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That we may look on great delight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us a portion of the sap, the most auspicious that ye have,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like mothers in their longing love.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you we gladly come for him to whose abode ye send us on;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And, Waters, give us procreant strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Waters. be to us for drink, Goddesses for our aid and bliss:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let them stream to us health and strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							1 beg the Floods to give us balm, these Queens who rule o'er precious
							things,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And have supreme control of men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Within the Waters-Soma thus hath told me-dwell all balms that heal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Agni, he who blesseth all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Waters, teem with medicine to keep my body safe from harm,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							So that I long may see the Sun.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whatever sin is found in me, whatever evil I have wrought,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							If I have lied or falsely sworn, Waters, remove it far from me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Waters I this day have sought, and to their moisture have we come:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 9: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Agni, rich in milk, come thou, and with thy splendour cover me.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 10
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FAIN would I win my friend to kindly friendship. So may the Sage, come
							through the air's wide ocean,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Remembering the earth and days to follow, obtain a son, the issue of
							his father.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy friend loves not the friendship which considers her who is near in
							kindred as stranger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sons of the mighty Asura, the Heroes, supporters of the heavens, see
							far around them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, this the Immortals seek of thee with longing, progeny of the sole
							existing mortal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then let thy soul and mine be knit together, and as a loving husband
							take thy consort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shall we do now what we ne'er did aforetime? we who spake righteously
							now talk impurely?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gandharva in the floods, the Dame of Waters-such is our bond, such our
							most lofty kinship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even in the womb God Tvastar, Vivifier, shaping all forms, Creator,
							made us consorts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							None violates his holy ordinances: that we are his the heavens and
							earth acknowledge.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who knows that earliest day whereof thou speakest? Who hatb beheld it?
							Who can here declare it?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Great is the Law of Varuna and Mitra. What, wanton! wilt thou say to
							men to tempt them?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							I, Yami, am possessed by love of Yama, that I may rest on the same
							couch beside him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							I as a wife would yield me to my husband. Like car-wheels let us speed
							to meet each other.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							They stand not still, they never close their eyelids, those sentinels
							of Gods who wander round us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not me-go quickly, wanton, with another, and hasten like a chariot
							wheel to meet him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Surya's eye with days and nights endow him, and ever may his light
							spread out before him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							In heaven and earth the kindred Pair commingle. On Yam! be the
							unbrotherly act of Yama.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sure there will come succeeding times when brothers and sisters will do
							acts unmeet for kinsfolk.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not me, O fair one,-seek another husband, and make thine arm a pillow
							for thy consort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Is he a brother when no lord is left her? Is she a sister when
							Destruction cometh?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Forced by my love these many words I utter. Come near, and hold me in
							thy close embraces.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will not fold mine arms about thy body: they call it sin when one
							comes near his sister.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not me,-prepare thy pleasures with another: thy brother seeks not this
							from thee, O fair one.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Alas! thou art indeed a weakling, Yama we find in thee no trace of
							heart or spirit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							As round the tree the woodbine clings, another will cling albout thee
							girt as with a girdle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Embrace another, Yami; let another, even as the woodbine rings the
							tree, enfold thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 10: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Win thou his heart and let him win thy fancy, and he shall form with
							thee a blest alliance.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 11
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Bull hath yielded for the Bull the milk of heaven: the Son of Aditi
							can never be deceived.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							According to his wisdom Varuna knoweth all: may he, the Holy, hallow
							times for sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gandharvi spake: may she, the Lady of the flood, amid the river's
							roaring leave my heart untouched.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Aditi accomplish all that we desire, and may our eldest Brother
							tell us this as Chief.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, even this blessed Morning, rich in store of food, splendid, with
							heavenly lustre, hath shone out for man,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Since they, as was the wish of yearning Gods, brought forth that
							yearning Agni for the assembly as the Priest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							And the fleet Falcon brought for sacrifice from afar this flowing Drop
							most excellent and keen of sight,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then when the Aryan tribes chose as Invoking Priest Agni the
							Wonder-Worker, and the hymn rose up.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Still art thou kind to him who feeds thee as with grass, and, skilled
							in sacrifice, offers thee holy gifts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou, having received the sage's strengthening food with lauds,
							after long toil, cornest with many more.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Urge thou thy Parents, as a lover ' to delight: the Lovely One desires
							and craves it from his heart.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The priest calls out, the sacrificer shows his skill, the Asura tries
							his strength, and with the hymn is stirred.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far-famed is he, the mortal man, O Agni, thou Son of Strength, who hath
							obtained thy favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, gathering power, borne onward by his horses, makes his days lovely
							in his might and splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, Holy Agni, the divine assembly, the sacred synod mid the Gods, is
							gathered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							And when thou, Godlike One, dealest forth treasures, vouchsafe us, too,
							our portion of the riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear us, O Agni, in your common dwelling: harness thy rapid car of
							Amrta.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 11: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring Heaven and Earth, the Deities' Parents, hither: stay with us
							here, nor from the Gods be distant.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 12
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HEAVEN and Earth, first by everlasting Order, speakers of truth, are
							near enough to hear us,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the God, urging men to worship. sitteth as Priest, assuming all
							his vital vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As God comprising Gods by Law Eternal, bear, as the Chief who knoweth,
							our oblation,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Smoke-bannered with the fuel, radiant, joyous, better to praise and
							worship, Priest for ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							When the cow's nectar wins the God completely, men here below are
							heaven's sustainers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							All the Gods came to this thy heavenly Yajus which from the motley Pair
							milked oil and water.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							1 praise your work that ye may make me prosper: hear, Heaven and Earth,
							Twain Worlds that drop with fatness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							While days and nights go to the world of spirits, here let the Parents
							with sweet meath refresh us
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hath the King siezed us? How have we offended against his holy
							ordinance? Who knoweth?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							For even Mitra mid the Gods is angry there are both song and strength
							for those who come not.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							'Tis hard to understand the Immortal's nature, where she who is akin
							becomes astranger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard ceaselessly, great Agni, him who ponders Yama's name, easy to be
							comprehended.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							They in the synod where the Gods rejoice them, where they are seated in
							Vivasvan's dwelling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have given the Moon his beams, the Sun his splendour-the Two
							unweariedly maintain their brightness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The counsel which the Gods meet to consider, their secret plan,-of that
							we have no knowledge.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							There let God Savitar, Aditi, and Mitra proclaim to Varuna that we are
							sinless.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear us, O Agni, in your comninn dwell ing: harness thy rapid car, the
							car of Amrta.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 12: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring Heaven and Earth, the Deities' Parents, hither: stay with us
							here, nor from the Gods be distant.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 13
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I YOKE with prayer your ancient inspiration: may the laud rise as on
							the prince's pathway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							All Sons of Immortality shall hear it, all the possessors of celestial
							natures.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When speeding ye came nigh us like twin sisters, religious-hearted
							votaries brought you forward.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Take your place, ye who know your proper station: be near, be very near
							unto our Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Five paces have I risen from Earth. I follow her who hath four feet
							with devout observance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							This by the Sacred Syllable have I measured: I purify in the central
							place of Order,
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, for God's sake, chose death to be his portion. He chose not, for
							men's good, a life eternal
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They sacrificed Brhaspati the Rsi. Yama delivered up his own dear body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Seven flow to the Youth on whom the Maruts wait: the Sons unto the
							Father brought the sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 13: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Both these are his, as his they are the Lords of both: both toil;
							belonging unto both they prosper well.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 14
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HONOUR the King with thine oblations, Yama, Vivasvan's Son, who gathers
							men together,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who travelled to the lofty heights above us, who searcbes out and shows
							the path to many.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yama first found for us a place to dwell in: this pasture never can be
							taken from
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 2: Line 3
					-
						-
							Men born on earth tread their own paths that lead them whither our
							ancient Fathers have departed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mitali prospers there with Kavyas, Yama with Angiras' sons, Brhaspati
							with Rkvans:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Exalters of the Gods, by Gods exalted, some joy in praise and some in
							our oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come, seat thee on this bed of grass, O Yama, in company with Angirases
							and Fathers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let texts recited by the sages bring thee O King, let this oblation
							make thee joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come, Yama, with the Angirases the Holy, rejoice thee here with
							children of Virupa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To sit on sacred grass at this our worship, I call Vivasvan, too, thy
							Father hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Our Fathers are Angirases, Navagvas, Atharvans, Bhrgus who deserve the
							Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these, the Holy, look on us with favour, may we enjoy their
							gracious loving-kindness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Go forth, go forth upon the ancient pathways whereon our sires of old
							have gone before us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							'Mere shalt thou look on both the Kings enjoying their sacred food, God
							Varuna and Yama.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Meet Yama, meet the Fathers, meet the merit of free or ordered acts, in
							highest heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Leave sin and evil, seek anew thy dwelling, and bright with glory wear
							another body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Go hence, depart ye, fly in all directions: this place for him the
							Fathers have provided.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yama bestows on him a place to rest in adorned with days and beams of
							light and waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Run and outspeed the two dogs, Sarama's offspring, brindled, four-eyed,
							upon thy happy pathway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Draw nigh then to the gracious-minded Fathers where they rejoice in
							company with Yama.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							And those two dogs of thine, Yama, the watchers, four-eyed, who look on
							men and guard the pathway,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Entrust this man, O King, to their protection, and with prosperity and
							health endow him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dark-hued, insatiate, with distended nostrils, Yama's two envoys roam
							among the People;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they restore to us a fair existence here and to-day, that we may
							see the sunlight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Yama pour the Soma, bring to Yama consecrated gifts:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Yama sacrifice prepared and heralded by Agni goes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Offer to Yama holy gifts enriched with butter, and draw near:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may he grant that we may live long days of life among the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Offer to Yama, to the King, oblation very rich in meath:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bow down before the Rsis of the ancient times, who made this path in
							days of old.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Into the six Expanses flies the Great One in Trkadrukas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 14: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Gayatri, the Trstup, all metres in Yama are contained.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 15
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY they ascend, the lowest, highest, midmost, the Fathers who deserve
							a share of Soma-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they who have attained the life of spirits, gentle and righteous,
							aid us when we call them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now let us pay this homage to the Fathers, to those who passed of old
							and those who followed,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Those who have rested in the earthly region, and those who dwell among
							the Mighty Races.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							1 have attained the gracious-minded Fathers, I have gained son and
							progeny from Visnu.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							They who enjoy pressed juices with oblation seated on sacred grass,
							come oftenest hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fathers who sit on sacred grass, come, help us: these offerings have we
							made for you; accept them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							So come to us with most auspicious favour, and give us health and
							strength without a trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May they, the Fathers, worthy of the Soma, invited to their favourite
							oblations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Laid on the sacred grass, come nigh and listen: may they be gracious
							unto us and bless us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bowing your bended knees and seated southward, accept this sacrifice of
							ours with favour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Punish us not for any sin, O Fathers, which we through human frailty
							have committed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lapped in the bosom of the purple Mornings, give riches to the man who
							brings oblations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant to your sons a portion of that treasure, and, present, give them
							energy, ye Fathers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Our ancient Fathers who deserve the Soma, who came, most noble, to our
							Soma banquet,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With these let Yama, yearning with the yearning, rejoicing eat our
							offerings at his pleasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come to us, Agni, with the gracioug Fathers who dwell in glowing light,
							the very Kavyas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who thirsted mid the Gods, who hasten hither, oblation winners, theme
							of singers' praises.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come, Agni, come with countless ancient Fathers, dwellers in light,
							primeval, God-adorers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eaters and drinkers of oblations, truthful, who travel with the Deities
							and Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fathers whom Agni's flames have tasted, come ye nigh: ye kindly
							leaders, take ye each your proper place.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eat sacrificial food presented on the grass: grant riches with a
							multitude of hero sons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Agni Jatavedas, when entreated, didst bear the offerings which
							thou madest fragrant,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							And give them to the Fathers who did cat them with Svadha. Eat, thou
							God, the gifts we bring thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Jatavedas, knowest well the number of Fathers who are here and
							who are absent,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of Fathers whom we know and whom we know not: accept the sacrifice
							wellprepared with portions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who, consumed by fire or not cremated, joy in their offering in
							the midst of heaven,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 15: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant them, O Sovran Lord, the world of spirits and their own body, as
							thy pleasure wills it.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 16
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Burn him not up, nor quite consume him, Agni: let not his body or his
							skin be scattered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Jatavedas, when thou hast matured him, then send him on his way unto
							the Fathers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou hast made him ready, Jatavedas, then do thou give him over to
							the Fathers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When he attains unto the life that waits him, he shall become the
							Deities' controller.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sun receive thine eye, tne Wind thy spirit; go, as thy merit is, to
							earth or heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Go, if it be thy lot, unto the waters; go, make thine home in plants
							with all thy members.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy portion is the goat: with heat consume him: let thy fierce flame,
							thy glowing splendour, burn him
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thine auspicious forms, o Jatavedas, bear this man to the region
							of the pious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Again, O Agni, to the Fathers send him who, offered in thee, goes with
							our oblations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wearing new life let him increase his offspring: let him rejoin a body,
							Jatavedas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							What wound soe'er the dark bird hath inflicted, the emmet, or the
							serpent, or the jackal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni who devoureth all things heal it and Soma who hath passed into
							the Brahmans.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shield thee with flesh against the flames of Agni, encompass thee about
							with fat and marrow,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							So will the Bold One, eager to attack thee with fierce glow fail to
							girdle and consume thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forbear, O Agni, to upset this ladle: the Gods and they who merit Soma
							love it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							This ladle, this which serves the Gods to drink from, in this the
							Immortal Deities rejoice them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							1 send afar flesh eating Agni, bearing off stains may he depart to
							Yama's subjects.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							But let this other Jatavedas carry oblation to the Gods, for he is
							skilful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							I choose as God for Father-worship Agni, flesh-eater, who hath past
							within your dwelling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							While looking on this other Jatavedas. Let him light flames in the
							supreme assembly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							With offerings meet let Agni bring the Fathers who support the Law.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him announce oblations paid to Fathers and to Deities.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Right gladly would we set thee down, right gladly make thee burn and
							glow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gladly bring yearning Fathers nigh to cat the food of sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Cool, Agni, and again refresh the spot which thou hast scorched and
							burnt.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here let the water-lily grow, and tender grass and leafy herb.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							O full of coolness, thou cool Plant, full of fresh moisture, freshening
							Herb,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 16: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come hither with the female frog: fill with delight this Agni here.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 17
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							TVASTAR prepares the bridal of his Daughter: all the world hears the
							tidings and assembles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							But Yama's Mother, Spouse of great Vivasvan, vanished as she was
							carried to her dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							From mortal men they hid the Immortal Lady, made one like her and gave
							her to Vivasvan.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Saranyu brought to him the Asvin brothers, and then deserted both
							twinned pairs of children.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guard of the world, whose cattle ne'er are injured, may Pusan bear thee
							hence, for he hath knowledge.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he consign thee to these Fathers' keeping, and to the gracious Gods
							let Agni give thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Ayu, giver of all life, protect thee, and bear thee forward on the
							distant pathway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thither let Savitar the God transport thee, where dwell the pious who
							have passed-before thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pusan knows all these realms: may he conduct us by ways that are most
							free from fear and danger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giver of blessings, glowing, all-heroic, may he, thewise and watchful,
							go before us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pusan was born to move on distant pathways, on the road far from earth
							and far from heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							To both most wonted places of assembly he travels and returns with
							perfect knowledge.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The pious call Sarasvati, they worship Sarasvati while sacrifice
							proceedeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The pious called Sarasvati aforetime. Sarasvati send bliss to him who
							giveth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sarasvati, who camest with the Fathers, with them rejoicing thee in our
							oblations,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seated upon this sacred grass be joyful, and give us strengthening food
							that brings no sickness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, called on as Sarasvati by Fathers who come right forward to our
							solemn service,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give food and wealth to present sacrificers, a portion, worth a
							thousand, of refreshment.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Mother Floods shall make us bright and shining, cleansers of holy
							oil, with oil shall cleanse us:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							For, Goddesses, they bear off all defilement: I, rise up from them
							purified and brightened.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through days of earliest date the Drop descended on this place and on
							that which was before it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							I offer up, throughout the seven oblations, the Drop which still to one
							same place is moving.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Drop that falls, thy stalk which arms have shaken, which from the
							bosom of the press hath fallen,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or from the Adhvaryu's purifying filter, I offer thee with heart and
							cry of Vasat!
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							That fallen Drop of thine, the stalk which from the ladle fell away,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							This present God Brhaspati shall pour it forth to make us rich.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The plants of earth are rich in milk, and rich in milk is this my
							speech;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 17: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							And rich in milk the essence of the Waters: make me pure therewith.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 18
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Go hence, O Death, pursue thy special pathway apart from that which
							Gods are wont to travel.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To thee I say it who hast eyes and hearest: Touch not our offspring,
							injure not our heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As ye have come effacing Mrtyu's footstep, to further times prolonging
							your existence,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May ye be rich in children and possessions. cleansed, purified, and
							meet for sacrificing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Divided from the dead are these, the living: now be our calling on the
							Gods successful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							We have gone forth for dancing and for laughter, tofurther times
							prolonging our existence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here I erect this rampart for the living; let none of these, none
							other, reach this limit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they survive a hundred lengthened autumns, and may they bury Death
							beneath this mountain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the days follow days in close succession, as with the seasons duly
							come the seasons,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							As each successor fails not his foregoer, so form the lives of these, O
							great Ordainer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Live your full lives ap! find old age delightful, all of you striving
							one behind the other.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Tvastar, maker of fair things, be gracious and lengthen out the
							days of your existence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let these unwidowed dames with noble husbands adorn themselves with
							fragrant balm and unguent.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Decked with fair jewels, tearless, free from sorrow, first let the
							dames go up to where he lieth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rise, come unto the world of life, O woman: come, he is lifeless by
							whose side thou liest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wifehood with this thy husband was thy portion, who took thy hand and
							wooed thee as a lover.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							From his dead hand I take the bow be carried, that it may be our power
							and might and glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							There art thou, there; and here with noble heroes may we o'ercome all
							hosts that fight against us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Betake thee to the Iap of Earth the Mother, of Earth far-spreading,
							very kind and gracious.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Young Dame, wool-soft unto the guerdongiver, may she preserve tbee from
							Destruction's bosom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Heave thyself, Earth, nor press thee downward heavily: afford him easy
							access, gently tending him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cover him, as a mother wraps her skirt about her child, O Earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now let the heaving earth be free from motion: yea,- let a thousand
							clods remain above him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be they to him a home distilling fatness, here let them ever be his
							place of refuge.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							I stay the earth from thee, while over thee I place this piece of
							earth. May I be free from injury.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here let the Fathers keep this pillar firm for thee, and there let Yama
							make thee an abiding-place.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as an arrow's feathers, they have set me on a fitting day.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 18: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							The fit word have I caught and held as 'twere a courser with the rein.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 19
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							TURN, go not farther on your way: visit us, O ye Wealthy Ones.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni and Soma, ye who bring riches again, secure us wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Make these return to us again, bring them beside us once again.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May. Indra give them back to us, and Agni drive them hither-ward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let them return to us again: under this herdsman let them feed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Do thou, O Agni, keep them here, and let the wealth we have remain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							1 call upon their herdsman, him who knoweth well their coming nigh,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Their parting and their home-return, and watcheth their approach and
							rest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, let the herdsman, too, return, who marketh well their
							driving-forth;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Marketh their wandering away, their turning back and coming home.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Home-leader, lead them home to us; Indra, restore to us our kine:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							We will rejoice in them alive.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							1 offer you on every side butter and milk and strengthening food.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May all the Holy Deities pour down on us a flood of wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O thou Home-leader, lead them home, restore them thou who bringest
							home.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 19: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Four are the quarters of the earth; from these bring back to us our
							kine,
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 20
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 1
				-
					-
						SEND unto us a good and happy mind.
					-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							1 worship Agni, Youthfullest of Gods, resistless, Friend of laws;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Under whose guard and heavenly light the Spotted seek the Mother's
							breast:
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whom with their mouth they magnify, bannered with flame and homed in
							light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He glitters with his row of teeth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Kind, Furtherer of men, he comes, when he hath reached the ends of
							heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sage, giving splendour to the clouds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To taste man's offerings, he, the Strong, hath risen erect at
							sacrifice:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fixing his dwelling he proceeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here are oblation, worship, rest: rapidly comes his furtherance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							To sword-armed Agni come the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							With service for chief bliss I seek the Lord of Sacrifice, Agni, whom
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They call the Living, Son of Cloud.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Blest evermore be all the men who come from us, who magnify
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni with sacrificial gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The path he treads is black and white and red, and striped, and brown,
							crimson, and glorious.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							His sire begat him bright with hues of gold.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus with his thoughts, O Son of Strength, O Agni, hath Vimada,
							accordant with the Immortals,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 20: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Offered thee hymns, soliciting thy favour. Thou hast brought all food,
							strength, a prosperous dwelling.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 21
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH offerings of our own we choose thee, Agni, as Invoking Priest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							For sacrifice with trimmed grass,-at your glad carouse-piercing and
							brightly shining. Thou art waxing great.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The wealthy ones adorn thee, they who bring us horses as their gift:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The sprinkling ladle, Agni,-at your glad carouse -and glowing offering
							taste thee. Thou art waxing great.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The holy statutes rest by thee, as 'twere with ladles that o'erflow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Black and white-gleaming colours,-at your glad carouse-all glories thou
							assurnest. Thou art waxing great.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, what thou deemest wealth, Victorious and Immortal One!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring thou to give us vigour,-at your glad carouse -splendid at
							sacrifices. Thou art waxing great.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Skilled in all lore is Agni, he whom erst Atharvan brought to life.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He was Vivasvan's envoy, at your glad carouse-the weIl-loved friend of
							Yama, Thou art waxing great.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							At sacrifices they adore thee, Agni, when the rite proceeds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							All fair and lovely treasures-at your glad carouse-thou givest him who
							offers. Thou art waxing great.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men, Agni, have established thee as welcome Priest at holy rites,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee whose face shines with butter,-at your glad carouse-bright, with
							eyes most observant. Thou art waxing great.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wide and aloft thou spreadest thee, O Agni, with tby brilliant flame.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 21: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							A Bull art thou when bellowing,-at your glad carouse-thou dost impregn
							the Sisters. Thou art waxing great.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 22
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHERE is famed Indra heard of? With what folk is he renowned to-day as
							Mitra is,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who in the home of Rsis and in secret is extolled with song?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even here is Indra famed, and among us this day the glorious Thunderer
							is praised,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who like Mitra mid the folk hath won complete and full renown.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who is Sovran Lord of great and perfect strength, exerter of heroic
							might,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who bears the fearless thunder as a father bears his darling son.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Harnessing to thy car, as God, two blustering Steeds Of the Wind-God, O
							Thunderer,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That speed along the shining path, thou making ways art glorified.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 22: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
