				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou wast, thou grewest to full vital vigour: an earlier saw, a later
							one shall see thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Two canopies, as 'twere, are round about him who reacheth to the limit
							of this region.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The freed kine eat the barley of the pious. 1 saw them as they wandered
							with the herdsman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The calling of the pious rang around them. What portion will these kine
							afford their owner?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							When we who cat the grass of men are gathered I am with barley-eaters
							in the corn-land.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							There shall the captor yoke the yokeless bullock, and he who hath been
							yoked seek one to loose him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							There wilt thou hold as true my spoken purpose, to bring together
							quadrupeds. and bipeds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							I will divide, without a fight, his riches who warreth here, against
							the Bull, with women.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							When a man's daughter hath been ever eyeless, who, knowing, will be
							wroth with her for blindness?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Which of the two will loose on him his anger-the man who leads her home
							or he who woos her?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							How many a maid is pleasing to the suitor who fain would marry for her
							splendid riches?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							If the girl be both good and fair of feature, she finds, herself, a
							friend among the people.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							His feet have grasped: he eats the man who meets him. Around his head
							he sets the head for shelter.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sitting anear and right above he smites us, and follows earth that lies
							spread out beneath him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							High, leafless, shadowless, and swift is Heaven: the Mother stands, the
							Youngling, loosed, is feeding.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Loud hath she lowed, licking Another's offspring. In what world hath
							the Cow laid down her udder?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Seven heroes from the nether part ascended, and from the upper part
							came eight together.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nine from behind came armed with winnowing-baskets: ten from the front
							pressed o'er the rock's high ridges.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							One of the ten, the tawny, shared in common, they send to execute their
							final purpose.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mother carries on her breast the Infant of noble form and soothes
							it while it knows not.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Heroes dressed with fire the fatted wether: the dice were thrown by
							way of sport and gaming.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Two reach the plain amid the heavenly waters, hallowing and with means
							of purifying.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Crying aloud they ran in all directions: One half of them will cook,
							and not the other.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							To me hath Savitar, this God, declared it: He will perform, whose food
							is wood and butter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							I saw a troop advancing from the distance moved, not by wheels but
							their own God-like nature.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Friendly One seeks human generations, destroying, still new bands
							of evil beings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							These my two Bulls, even Pramara's, are harnessed: drive them not far;
							here let them often linger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							The waters even shall aid him to his object, and the all-cleansing Sun
							who is above us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the thunderbolt which often whirleth down from the lofty misty
							realm of Surya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beyond this realm there is another glory so through old age they pass
							and feel no sorrow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bound fast to,every tree the cow is lowing, and thence the
							man-consuming birds are flying,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then all this world, though pressing juice for Indra and strengthening
							the Rsi, is affrighted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							In the Gods' mansion stood the first-created, and from their separation
							came the later.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							Three warm the Earth while holding stores of water, and Two of these
							convey the murmuring moisture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is thy life: and do thou mark and know it. As such, hide not
							thyself in time of battle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 27: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							He manifests the light and hides the vapour: his foot is never free
							from robes that veil it.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 28
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now all my other friends are here assembled: my Sire-in-law alone hath
							not come hither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							So might he eat the grain and drink the Soma, and, satisfied, return
							unto; his dwelling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loud belloweth the Bull whose horns are sharpened: upon the height
							above earth's breadth he standeth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That man I guard and save in all his troubles who fills my flanks when
							he hath shed the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men with the stone press out for thee, O Indra, strong, gladdening
							Soma, and thereof thou drinkest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bulls they dress for thee, and of these thou eatest when, Maghavan,
							with food thou art invited.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Resolve for me, O singer, this my riddle: The rivers send their
							swelling water backward:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The fox steals up to the approaching lion: the jackal drives the
							wild-boar from the brushwood.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							How shall I solve this riddle, I, the simple, declare the thought of
							thee the Wise and Mighty?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Tell us, well knowing, as befits the season: Whitherward is thy
							prosperous car advancing?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus do they magnify me, me the mighty higher than even high heaven is
							my car-pole.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							I all at once demolish many thousands: my Sire begot me with no foe to
							match me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, and the Gods have known me also, Indra, as mighty, fierce and
							strong in every exploit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Exulting with the bolt I slaughtered Vrtra, and for the offerer oped
							with might the cow-stall.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Deities approached, they carried axes; splitting the wood they came
							with their attendants.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							They laid good timber in the fire-receivers, and burnt the grass up
							where they found it growing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The hare hath swallowed up the opposing razor: I sundered with a clod
							the distant mountain.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The great will I make subject to the little: the calf shall wax in
							strength and cat the bullock.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							There hath the strong-winged eagle left his talon, as a snared lion
							leaves the trap that caught him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even the wild steer in his thirst is captured: the leather strap still
							holds his foot entangled.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may the leather strap their foot entangle who fatten on the viands
							of the Brahman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							They all devour the bulls set free to wander, while they themselves
							destroy their bodies' vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							They were well occupied with holy duties who sped in person with their
							lauds to Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 28: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Speaking like man, mete to us wealth and booty: in heaven thou hast the
							name and fame of Hero.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 29
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As sits the young bird on the tree rejoicing, ye, swift Pair, have been
							roused by clear laudation,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose Herald-Priest through many days is Indra, earth's Guardian,
							Friend of men, the best of Heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we, when this Dawn and the next dance hither, be thy best servants,
							most heroic Hero!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let the victorious car with triple splendour bring hitherward the
							hundred chiefs with Kutsa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What was the gladdening draught that pleased thee, Indra? Speed through
							our doors to songs, for thou art mighty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Why comest thou to me, what gift attracts thee? Fain would I bring thee
							food most meet to offer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, what fame hath one like thee mid heroes? With what plan wilt
							thou act? Why hast thou sought us?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As a true Friend, Wide-Strider! to sustain us, since food absorbs the
							thought of each among us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Speed happily those, as Surya ends his journey, who meet his wish as
							bridegrooms meet their spouses;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men who present, O Indra strong by nature, with food the many songs
							that tell thy praises.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine are two measures, Indra, wide-wellmeted, heaven for thy majesty,
							earth for thy wisdom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Here for thy choice are Somas mixed with butter: may the sweet meath be
							pleasant for thy drinking.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							They have poured out a bowl to him, to Indra, full of sweet juice, for
							faithful is his bounty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							O'er earth's expanse hath he grown great by wisdom, the Friend of man,
							and by heroic exploits.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra hath conquered in his wars, the Mighty: men strive in multitudes
							to win his friendship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 29: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ascend thy chariot as it were in battle, which thou shalt drive to us
							with gracious favour.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 30
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As 'twere with swift exertion of the spirit, let the priest speed to
							the celestial Waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The glorious food of Varuna and Mitra. To him who spreadeth far this
							laud I offer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adhvaryus, he ye ready with oblations,, and come with longing to the
							longing Waters,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Down on which looks the. purple-tinted Eagle. Pour ye that flowing wave
							this day, deft-handed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Go to the reservoir, O ye Adhvaryus worship the Waters' Child with your
							oblations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							A consecrated wave he now will give you, so press for him the Soma rich
							in sweetness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who shines bright in floods, unfed with fuel, whom sages worship at
							their sacrifices:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give waters rich in sweets, Child of the Waters, even those which gave
							heroic might to Indra:
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those in which Soma joys and is delighted, as a young man with fair and
							pleasant damsels.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Go thou unto those Waters, O Adhvaryu, and purify with herbs what thou
							infusest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							So maidens bow before the youthful gallant who comes with love to them
							who yearn to meet him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							In heart accordant and in wish one-minded are the Adhvaryus and the
							heavenly Waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who made room for you when fast imprisoned, who freed you from the
							mighty imprecation,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even to that Indra send the meath-rich current, the wave that gratifies
							the Gods, O Waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send forth to him the meath-rich wave, O Rivers, which is your
							offspring and a well of sweetness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Oil-balmed, to be implored at sacrifices. Ye wealthy Waters, hear mine
							invocation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send forth the rapture-giving wave, O Rivers, which Indra drinks, which
							sets the Twain in motion;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The well that springeth from the clouds, desirous, that wandereth
							triple-formed, distilling transport.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							These winding Streams which with their double current, like
							cattle-raiders, seek the lower pastures,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Waters which dwell together, thrive together, Queens, Mothers of the
							world, these, Rsi, honour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 30: Verse 11
				-
