					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE fires associate with Indra are awake, bringing their light when
							first the Dawn begins to shine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Heaven and Earth, great Pair, observe our holy work. We claim for
							us this day the favour of the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, for ourselves we claim the grace of Heaven and Earth, of
							Saryanavan, of the Hills and Mother Streams.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							For innocence we pray to Surya and to Dawn. So may the flowing Soma
							bring us bliss to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the great Twain, the Mothers, Heaven and Earth, this day preserve
							us free from sin for peace and happiness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Morning sending forth her light drive sin afar. We pray to kindled
							Agni for felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this first Dawn bring us the host of gracious Gods: rich, may it
							richly shine for us who strive for wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The wrath of the malignant may we keep afar. We pray to kindled Agni
							for feilicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dawns, who come forward with the bright beams of the Sun, and at your
							earliest flushing bring to us the light,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shine ye on us to-day auspicious, for renown. We pray to kindled Agni
							for felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Free from all sickness may the Mornings come to us, and let our fires
							mount upward with a lofty blaze.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Asvin Pair have harnessed their swift-moving car. We pray to
							kindled Agni for felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Send us to-day a portion choice and excellent, O Savitar, for thou art
							he who dealeth wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							I cry to Dhisana, Mother of opulence. We pray to kindled Agni for
							felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Further me this declaring of Eternal Law, the Law of Gods, as we
							mortals acknowledge it!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Sun goes up beholding all the rays of morn. We pray to kindled Agni
							for felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							This day we pray with innocence in strewing grass, adjusting
							pressing-stones, and perfecting the hymn.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou in the Adityas' keeping movest restlessly. We pray to kindled Agni
							for felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							To our great holy grass I bid the Gods at morn to banquet, and will
							seat them as the seven priests,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Varuna, Indra, Mitra, Bhaga for our gain. We pray to kindled Agni for
							felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come hither, O Adityas, for our perfect weal: accordant help our
							sacrifice that we may thrive.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pusan, Brhaspati, Bhaga, both Asvins, and enkindled Agni we implore for
							happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adityas, Gods, vouchsafe that this our home may be praise-worthy,
							prosperous, our heroes' sure defence,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							For cattle, for our sons, for progeny, for life. We pray to kindled
							Agni for felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							This day may all the Maruts, all he near us with aid: may all our fires
							be well enkindled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							May all Gods come to us with gracious favour. May spoil and wealth he
							ours, and all possessions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							He whom ye aid, O Deities, in battle, whom ye protect and rescue from
							affliction,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 35: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who fears no danger at your milk-libation, -such may we be to feast the
							Gods, ye Mighty.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 36
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THERE are the Dawn and Night, the grand and beauteous Pair, Earth,
							Heaven, and Varuna, Mitra, and Aryaman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra I call, the Maruts, Mountains, and the Floods, Adityas, Heaven
							and Earth, the Waters, and the Sky.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Dyaus and Prthivi, wise, true to Holy Law, keep us in safety from
							distress and injury.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not malignant Nirrti rule over us. We crave to-day this gracious
							favour of the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mother of Mitra and of opulent Varuna, may Aditi preserve us safe from
							all distress.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we obtain the light of heaven without a foe. We crave this gracious
							favour of the Gods to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May ringing press-stones keep the Raksasas afar, ill dream, and Nirrti,
							and each voracious fiend.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the Adityas and the Maruts shelter us. We crave this gracious
							favour of the Gods to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Full flow libations; on our grass let Indra sit; Brhaspati the singer
							laud with Sama hymns!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wise be our hearts' imaginings that we may live. We crave this gracious
							favour of the Gods to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Asvins, make our sacrifice ascend to heaven, and animate the rite
							that it may send us bliss,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Offered with holy oil, with forward-speeding rein. We crave the
							gracious favour of the Gods to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither I call the band of Maruts, swift to hear, great, purifying,
							bringing bliss, to he our Friends.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we increase our wealth to glorify our name. We crave this
							graciousfavour of the Gods to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							We bring the Stay of Life, who makes the waters swell, swift-hearing,
							Friend of Gods, who waits on sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we control that Power, Soma whose rays are bright. We crave this
							gracious favour of the Gods to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Alive ourselves, with living sons, devoid of guilt, may we win this
							with winners by fair means to win.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let the prayer-haters bear our sin to every side. We crave this
							gracious favour of the Gods to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hear us, O ye who claim the worship of mankind, and give us, O ye Gods,
							the gift for which we pray,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Victorious wisdom, fame with heroes and with wealth. We crave to-day
							this gracious favour of the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							We crave the gracious favour of the Gods to-day, great favour of great
							Gods, sublime and free from foes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							That we may gain rich treasure sprung from hero sons. We crave this
							gracious favour of the Gods to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							In great enkindled Agni's keeping, and, for bliss, free from all sin
							before Mitra and Varuna.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we share Savitar's best animating help. We crave this gracious
							favour of the Gods to-day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							All ye, the Gods whom Savitar the Father of truth, and Varuna and Mitra
							govern,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us prosperity with hero children, and opulence in kine and various
							treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Savitar, Savitar from cast and westward, Savitar, Savitar from north
							and southward,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 36: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savitar send us perfect health and comfort, Savitar let our days of
							life be lengthened!
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 37
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do homage unto Varuna's and Mitra's Eye: offer this solemn worship to
							the Mighty God,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who seeth far away, the Ensign, born of Gods. Sing praises unto Surya,
							to the Son of Dyaus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this my truthful speech guard me on every side wherever heaven and
							earth and days are spread abroad.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							All else that is in motion finds a place of rest: the waters ever flow
							and ever mounts the Sun.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							No godless man from time remotest draws thee down when thou art driving
							forth with winged dappled Steeds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							One lustre waits upon thee moving to the cast, and, Surya, thou arisest
							with a different light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Surya, with the light whereby thou scatterest gloom, and with thy ray
							impellest every moving thing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Keep far from us all feeble, worthless sacrifice, and drive away
							disease and every evil dream.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sent forth thou guardest well the Universe's law, and in thy wonted way
							arisest free from wrath.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When Surya, we address our prayers to thee to-day, may the Gods favour
							this our purpose and desire.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							This invocation, these our words may Heaven and Earth, and Indra and
							the Waters and the Maruts hear.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ne'er may we suffer want in presence of the Sun, and, living happy
							lives, may we attain old age.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Cheerful in spirit, evermore, and keen of sight, with store of
							children, free from sickness and from sin,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Long-living, may we look, O Surya, upon thee uprising day by day, thou
							great as Mitra is!
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surya, may we live long and look upon thee still, thee, O Far-seeing
							One, bringing the glorious light,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The radiant God, the spring of joy to every eye, as thou art mounting
							up o'er the high shining flood.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou by whose lustre all the world of life comes forth, and by thy
							beams again returns unto its rest,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Surya with the golden hair, ascend for us day after day, still
							bringing purer innocence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bless us with shine, bless us with perfect daylight, bless us with
							cold, with fervent heat and lustre.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bestow on us, O Surya, varied riches, to bless us in our home and when
							we travel.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods, to our living creatures of both kinds vouchsafe protection, both
							to bipeds and to quadrupeds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							That they may drink and eat invigorating food. So grant us health and
							strength and perfect innocence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							If by some grievous sin we have provoked the Gods, O Deities, with the
							tongue or thoughtlessness of heart,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 37: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							That guilt, O Vasus, lay upon the Evil One, on him who ever leads us
							into deep distress.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 38
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							O INDRA, in this battle great and glorious, in this loud din of war
							help us to victory,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where in the strife for kine among bold ring-decked men arrows fly all
							around and heroes are subdued.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							At home disclose to us opulence rich in food, streaming with milk, O
							Indra, meet to be renowned.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sakra, may we be thine, the friendly Conqueror's: even as we desire, O
							Vasu, so do thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The godless man, much-lauded Indra, whether he be Dasa or be Arya, who
							would war with us,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Easy to conquer he for thee, with us, these foes: with thee may we
							subdue them in the clash of fight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him who must be invoked by many and by few, who standeth nigh with
							comfort in the war of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, famed Hero, winner in the deadly strife, let us bring hitherward
							to-day to favour us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							For, Indra, I have heard thee called Self. capturer, One, Steer! who
							never yields, who urges even the churl.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 38: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Release thyself from Kutsa and come hither. How shall one like thee sit
							still bound that he may not move?
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 39
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As 'twere the name of father, easy to invoke, we all assembled here
							invoke this Car of yours,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Asvins, your swiftly-rolling circumambient Car which he who worships
							must invoke at eve and dawn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Awake all pleasant strains and let the hymns flow forth: raise up
							abundant fulness: this is our desire.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Asvins, bestow on us a glorious heritage, and give our princes treasure
							fair as Soma is.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye are the bliss of her who groweth old at home, and helpers of the
							slow although he linger last.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men call you too, Nasatyas, healers of the blind, the thin and feeble,
							and the man with broken bones.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye made Cyavana, weak and worn with length of days, young again, like a
							car, that he had power to move.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye lifted up the son of Tugra from the floods. At our libations must
							all these your acts be praised.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							We will declare among the folk your ancient deeds heroic; yea, ye were
							Physicians bringing health.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							You, you who must be lauded, will we bring for aid, so that this foe of
							ours, O Asvins, may believe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Listen to me, O Asvins; I have cried to you. Give me-your aid as sire
							and mother aid their son.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Poor, without kin or friend or ties of blood am I. Save me before it be
							too late, from this my curse.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, mounted on your chariot brought to Vimada the comely maid of
							Purumitra as a bride.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, came unto the calling of the weakling's dame, and granted noble
							offspring to the happy wife.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye gave a ain the vigour of his youthful life to tge sage Kali when old
							age was coming nigh.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye rescued Vandana and raised him from the pit, and in a moment gave
							Vispala power to move.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Asvins Twain, endowed with manly strength, brought forth Reblia when
							hidden in the cave and well-nigh dead,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Freed Saptavadliri, and for Atri caused the pit heated with fire to be
							a pleasant resting-place.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							On Pedu ye bestowed, Asvins, a courser white, mighty with
							nine-and-ninety varied gifts of strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							A horse to be renowned, who bore his friend at speed, joy-giving,
							Bhaga-like to be invoked of men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							From no side, ye Two Kings whom none may check or stay, doth grief,
							distress, or danger come u on the man
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom, Asvins swift to hear, borne on your glowing path, ye with your
							Consort make the foremost in the race.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come on that Chariot which the Rbhus wrought for you, the Chariot,
							Asvins, that is speedier than thought,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							At harnessing whereof Heaven's Daughter springs to birth, and from
							Vivasvan come auspicious Night and Day.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come, Conquerors of the sundered mountain, to our home, Asvins who made
							the cow stream milk for Sayu's sake,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye who delivered even from the wolf's deep throat and set again at
							liberty the swallowed quail.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							We have prepared this laud for you, O Asvins, and, like the Bhrgus, as
							a car have framed it,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 39: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have decked it as a maid to meet the bridegroom, and brought it as a
							son, our stay for ever.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 40
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YOUR radiant Chariot-whither goes it on its way?-who decks it for you,
							Heroes, for its happy course,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Starting at daybreak, visiting each morning every house, borne
							hitherward through prayer unto the sacrifice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where are ye, Asvins, in the evening, where at morn? Where is your
							haltingplace, where rest ye for the night?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who brings you homeward, as the widow bedward draws her husband's
							brother, as the bride attracts the groom?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Early ye sing forth praise as with a herald's voice, and, meet for
							worship, go each morning to the house.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom do ye ever bring to ruin? Unto whose libations come ye, Heroes,
							like two Sons of Kings?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as hunters follow two wild elephants, we with oblations call you
							down at morn and eve.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							To folk who pay you offierings at appointed times, Chiefs, Lords of
							splendour, ye bring food to strengthen them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you, O Asvins, came the daughter of a King, Ghosa, and said, O
							Heroes, this I beg of you:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be near me in the day, he near me in the night: help me to gain a
							car-borne chieftain rich in steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Asvins, ye are wise: as Kutsa comes to men, bring your car nigh the
							folk of him who sings your praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The bee, O Asvins, bears your honey in her mouth, as the maid carries
							it purified in her hand.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Bhujyu and to Vasa ye come near with help, O Asvins, to Sinjara and
							to Usana.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Your worshipper secures your friendship for himself. Through your
							protection I desire felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Krsa and Sayu ye protect, ye Asvins Twain: ye Two assist the widow and
							the worshipper;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							And ye throw open, Asvins, unto those who win the cattle-stall that
							thunders with its serenfold mouth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Woman hath brought forth, the Infant hath appeared, the plants of
							wondrous beauty straightway have sprung up.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him the rivers run as down a deep descent, and he this day becomes
							their master and their lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							They mourn the living, cry aloud, at sacrifice: the men have set their
							thoughts upon a distant cast.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							A lovely thing for fathers who have gathered here,-a joy to
							husbands,-are the wives their arms shall clasp
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of this we have no knowledge. Tall it forth to us, now the youth rests
							within the chambers of the bride.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fain would we reach the dwelling of the vigorous Steer who loves the
							kine, O Asvins: this is our desire.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your favouring grace hath come, ye Lords of ample wealth: Asvins, our
							longings are stored up within your hearts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye, Lords of splendour, have become our twofold guard: may we as
							welcome friends reach Aryaman's abode.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even so, rejoicing in the dwelling-place of man, give hero sons and
							riches to the eloquent.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make a ford, Lords of splendour, where men well may drink: remove the
							spiteful tree-stump standing in the path.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Asvins, Wonder-Workers, Lords of lustre, where and with what folk do
							ye delight yourselves to-day?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 40: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who hath detained them with him? Whither are they gone? Unto what
							sage's or what worshipper's abode?
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 41
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 41: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 41: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THAT general Car of yours, invoked by many a man, that comes to our
							libations, three-wheeled, meet for lauds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 41: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That circumambient Car, worthy of sacrifice, we call with our pure
							hymns at earliest flush of dawn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 41: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 41: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, O Nasatyas, mount that early-harnessed Car, that travels early,
							laden with its freight of balm,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 41: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith ye, Heroes, visit clans who sacrifice, even the poor man's
							worship where the priest attends.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 41: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 41: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							If to the deft Adhvaryu with the meath in hand, or to the Kindler firm
							in strength, the household friend,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 41: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or to the sage's poured libations ye approach, come thence, O Asvins,
							now to drink the offered meath.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 42
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							EVEN as an archer shoots afar his arrow, offer the laud to him with
							meet adornment.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Quell with your voice the wicked's voice, O sages. Singer, make Indra
							rest beside the Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Draw thy Friend to thee like a cow at milking: O Singer, wake up Indra
							as a lover.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make thou the Hero haste to give us riches even as a vessel filled
							brimful with treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Why, Maghavan, do they call thee Bounteous; Giver? Quicken me: thou, I
							hear, art he who quickens.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sakra, let my intelligence be active, and bring us luck that finds
							great wealth, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Standing, in battle for their rights, together, the people, Indra, in
							the fray invoke thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who brings gifts the Hero makes his comrade: with him who pours no
							juice he seeks not friendship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso with plenteous food for him expresses strong Somas as much
							quickly-coming treasure,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							For him he overthrows in early morning his swift well-weaponed foes,
							and slays the tyrant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							He unto whom we offer praises, Indra, Maghavan, who hath joined to ours
							his wishes,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Before him even afar the foe must tremble: low before him must bow all
							human glories.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							With thy fierce bolt, O God invoked of many, drive to a distance from
							afar the foeman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra, give us wealth in corn and cattle, and make thy singer's
							prayer gain strength and riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, the swallower of strong libations rich in the boons they bring,
							the potent Somas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, Maghavan, will not restrict his bounty he brings much wealth unto
							the Soma-presser.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, by superior play he wins advantage, when he, a gambler, piles his
							gains in season.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Celestial-natured, he o'erwhelms with riches the devotee who keeps not
							back his treasure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Much-invoked, may we subdue all famine and evil want with store of
							grain and cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we allied, as first in rank, with princes obtain possessions by our
							own exertion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaspati protect us from the rearward, and from above, and from below,
							from sinners!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 42: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Indra from the front, and from the centre, as Friend to friends,
							vouchsafe us room and freedom.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 43
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							IN perfect unison all yearning hymns of mine that find the light of
							heaven have sung forth Indra's praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As wives embrace their lord, the comely bridegroom, so they compass
							Maghavan about that he may help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Directed unto thee my spirit never strays, for I have set my hopes on
							thee, O Much-invoked!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sit, Wonderful! as King upon the sacred grass, and let thy
							drinking-place be by the Soma juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							From indigence and hunger Indra turns away: Maghavan hath dominion over
							precious wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							These the Seven Rivers flowing on their downward path increase the
							vital vigour of the potent Steer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							As on the fair-leafed tree rest birds, to Indra flow the gladdening
							Soma juices that the bowls contain.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Their face that glows with splendour through their mighty power hath
							found the shine of heaven for man, the Aryas' light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As in the game a gambler piles his winnings, so Maghavan, sweeping all
							together, gained the Sun
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							This mighty deed of thine none other could achieve, none, Maghavan,
							before thee, none in recent time.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Maghavan came by turns to all the tribes of men: the Steer took notice
							of the people's songs of praise.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The man in whose libations Sakra hath delight by means of potent Somas
							vanquisheth his foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 43: Verse 7
				-
					-
