					-
						-
							I, Indra, am Atharvan's stay and firm support: I brought forth kine to
							Trita from the Dragon's grasp.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							I stripped the Dasyus of their manly might, and gave the cattle-stalls
							to Matarigvan and Dadhyac.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							For me hath Tvastar forged the iron thunderbolt: in me the Gods have
							centred intellectual power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							My sheen is like the Sun's insufferably bright: men honour me as Lord
							for past and future deeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I won myself these herdi of cattle, steeds and kine, and gold in ample
							store, with my destructive bolt.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							I give full many a thousand to the worshipper, what time the Somas and
							the lauds have made me glad.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra am I none ever wins my wealth from me never at any time am I a
							thrall to death.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pressing the Soma, ask riches from me alone: ye, Purus, in my
							friendship shall not suffer harm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							These, breathing loud in fury, two and two, who caused Indra to bring
							his bolt of thunder to the fray,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The challengers, I struck with deadly weapon down: firm stand what
							words the God speaks to his worshippers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							This One by stronger might I conquered singly; yea, also two: shall
							three prevail against me?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 6: Line 4
					-
						-
							Like many sheaves upon the floor I thrash them. How can my foes, the
							Indraless, revile me?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Against the Gungus I made Atithigva strong, and kept him mid the folk
							like Vrtra-conquering strength,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							When I won glory in the great foe-slaying fight, in battle where
							Karanja fell, and Parnaya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							With food for mine enjoyment Sapya Nami came: he joined me as a friend
							of old in search of kine.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							As I bestowed on him an arrow for the fight I made him worthy of the
							song apd hymn of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							One of the two hath Soma, seen within it; the Herdsman with the bone
							shows forth the other.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, fain to fight the Bull whose horns were sharpened, stood fettered
							in the demon's ample region.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							I, as a God, ne'er violate the statutes of Gods, of Vasus, Rudriyas,
							Adityas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 48: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							These Gods have formed me for auspicious vigour, unconquered and
							invincible for ever.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 49
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I HAVE enriched the singer with surpassing wealth; I have allowed the
							holy hymn to strengthen me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I, furtherer of him who offers sacrifice, have conquered in each fight
							the men who worship not.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The People of the heavens, the waters, and the earth have stablished me
							among the Gods with Indra's name.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							I took unto myself the two swift vigorous Bays that speed on divers
							paths, and the fierce bolt for strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With deadly blows I smote Atka for Kavi's sake; I guarded Kutsa well
							with these saving helps.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As Susna's slayer I brandished the dart of death: I gave not up the
							Aryan name to Dasyu foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Smadibha, Tugra, and the Vetasus I gave as prey to Kutsa, father-like,
							to succour him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							I was a worthy King to rule the worshipper, when I gave Tuji dear
							inviolable gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I gave up Mrgaya to Srutarvan as his prey because he ever followed me
							and kept my laws.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							For Ayu's sake I caused Veta to bend and bow, and into Savya's hand
							delivered Padgrbhi.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							1, I crushed Navavastva of the lofty car, the Dasa, as the Vrtra-slayer
							kills the fiends;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When straightway on the region's farthest edge I brought the God who
							makes the lights to broaden and increase.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							I travel round about borne onward in my might by the fleet-footed
							dappled Horses of the Sun.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							When man's libation calls me to the robe of state I soon repel the
							powerful Dasyu with my blows.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stronger am I than Nabus, I who slew the seven: I glorified with might
							Yadu and Turvaga.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							I brought another low, with strength I bent his strength: I let the
							mighty nine-and-ninety wax in power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bull over all the streams that flow along the earth, I took the Seven
							Rivers as mine own domain.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							I, gifted with great wisdom, spread the floods abroad: by war I found
							for man the way to high success.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							I set within these cows the white milk which no God, not even Tvastar's
							self, had there deposited,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Much-longed-for, in the breasts, the udders of the kine, the savoury
							sweets of meath, the milk and Soma juice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even thus hath Indra Maghavan, truly bounteous, sped Gods and men with
							mighty operation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 49: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The pious glorify all these thine exploits, Lord of Bay Coursers,
							Strong, and Selfresplendent.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 50
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I LAUD your Mighty One who joyeth in the juice, him who is shared by
							all men, who created all;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, whose conquering strength is powerful in war, whose fame and
							manly vigour Heaven and Earth revere.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He with his friend is active, lauded, good to man, Indra who must be
							glorified by one like me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hero, Lord of the brave, all cars are thy delight, warring with Vrtra,
							or for waters, or for spoil.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who are the men whom thou wilt further, Indra, who strive to win thy
							bliss allied with riches?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who urged thee forward to exert thy power divine, to valour, in the war
							for waters on their fields?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, through the holy prayer art mighty, worthy of sacrifice at
							all libations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							In every fight thou castest heroes on the ground: thou art the noblest
							song, O Lord of all the folk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Help now, as Highest, those who toil at sacrifice: well do the people
							know thy great protecting might.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou shalt be Everlasing, Giver of success yea, on all these libations
							thou bestowest strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							All these libations thou makest effectual, of which thou art thyself
							supporter, Son of Power.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therefore thy vessel is to be esteemed the best, sacrifice, holy text,
							prayer, and exalted speech.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who with flowing Soma pray to thee, O Sage, to pour on them thy
							gifts of opulence and wealth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 50: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they come forward, through their spirit, on the path of bliss, in
							the wild joy of Soma juice effused.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 51
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LARGE was that covering, and firm of texture, folded wherein thou
							enteredst the waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							One Deity alone, O Jatavedas Agni, saw all thy forms in sundry places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							What God hath seen me? Who of all their number clearly beheld my forms
							in many places?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where lie, then, all the sacred logs of Agni that lead him God-ward,
							Varuna and Mitra?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							In many places, Agni Jatavedas, we sought thee hidden in the plants and
							waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then Yama marked thee, God of wondrous splendour! effulgent from thy
							tenfold secret dwelling,
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I fled in fear from sacrificial worship, Varuna, lest the Gods should
							thus engage me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thus were my forms laid down in many places. This, as my goal, I Agni
							saw before me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come; man is pious and would fain do worship, he waits prepared: in
							gloom thou, Agni, dwellest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make pathways leading God-ward clear and easy, and bear oblations with
							a kindly spirit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							This goal mine elder brothers erst selected, as he who drives a car the
							way to travel.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							So,Varuna, I fled afar through terror, as flies the wild-bull from an
							archer's bowstring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							We give thee life unwasting, Jatavedas, so that, employed, thou never
							shalt be injured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							So, nobly born! shalt thou with kindly spirit bear to the Gods their
							share of men's oblations.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grant me the first oblations and the latter, entire, my forceful shares
							of holy presents,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The soul of plants, the fatness of the waters, and let there be long
							life, ye Gods, to Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine be the first oblations and the latter, entire, thy forceful
							shares of holy presents.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 51: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let all this sacrifice be thine, O Agni, and let the world's four
							regions how before thee.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 52
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							INSTRUCT me, all ye Gods, how I, elected your Priest, must seat me
							here, and how address you.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Instruct me how to deal to each his portion, and by what ' path to
							bring you man's oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I sit as Priest most skilled in sacrificing: the Maruts and all Deities
							impel me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Asvins, each day yours is the Adhvaryu's duty: Brahman and wood are
							here: 'tis yours to offer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who is the Priest? Is he the Priest of Yama? On whom is thrust this
							God-appointed honour?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He springs to life each month, each day that passes; so Gods have made
							him their oblation-bearer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Gods have made me bearer of oblations, who slipped away and passed
							through many troubles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wise Agni shall ordain for us the worship, whether five-wayed,
							threefold, or seven-threaded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							So will I win you strength and life for ever. O Gods, that I may give
							you room and freedom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Indra's arms would I consign the thunder; in all these battles shall
							he then be victor.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Deities three hundred and thirty-nine, have served and honoured
							Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 52: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strewn sacred grass, anointed him with butter, and seated him as
							Priest, the Gods' Invoker.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 53
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HE hath arrived, he whom we sought with longing, who skilled in
							sacrifice well knows its courses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him discharge his sacrificial duties: let him sit down as Friend
							who was before
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 1: Line 3
					-
						-
							Us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Best Priest, he hath been won by being seated, for he hath looked on
							the well-ordered viands.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come, let usworship Gods who must be worshipped, and pouring oil, laud
							those who should be lauded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now hath he made the feast of Gods effective: now have we found the
							secret tongue of worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now hath he come, sweet, robed in vital vigour, and made our calling on
							the Gods effective.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This prelude of my speech I now will utter, whereby we Gods may quell
							our Asura foemen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eaters of strengthening food who merit worship, O ye Five Tribes, be
							pleased with mine oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Five Tribes be pleased with mine oblation, and the Cow's Sons
							and all who merit worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							From earthly trouble may the earth protect us, and air's mid realm from
							woe that comes from heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Spinning the thread, follow the region's splendid light: guard thou the
							path ways well which wisdom hath prepared.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Weave ye the knotless labour of the bards who sing: be Manu thou, and
							bring the Heavenly People forth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lovers of Soma, bind the chariot traces fast: set ye the reins in order
							and embellish them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring hitherward the car with seats where eight may sit, whereon the
							Gods have brought the treasure that we love.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here flows Asmanvati: hold fast each other, keep yourselves up, and
							pass, my friends, the river.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							There let us leave the Powers that brought no profit, and cross the
							flood to Powers that are auspicious.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tvastar, most deft of workmen, knew each magic art, bringing most
							blessed bowls that hold the drink of Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							His axe, wrought of good metal, he is sharpening now, wherewith the
							radiant Brahmanaspati will cut.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now, O ye Sapient Ones, make ye the axes sharp wherewith ye fashion
							bowls to hold the Amrta.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Knowing the secret places make ye ready that whereby the Gods have
							gotten immortality.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye with a secret tongue and dark intention laid the maiden deep within,
							the calf within the mouth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 53: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							They evermore are near us with their gracious help: successful is the
							song that strives for victory.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 54
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I SING thy fame that, Maghavan, through thy Greatness the heavens and
							earth invoked thee in their terror,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, aiding Gods, didst quell the power of Dasas, what time thou
							holpest many a race, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							When thou wast roaming, waxen strong in body, telling thy might, Indra,
							among the people,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							All that men called thy battles was illusion: no foe hast thou to-day,
							nor erst hast found one.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who are the Rsis, then, who comprehended before our time the bounds of
							all thy greatness?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							For from thy body thou hast generated at the same time the Mother and
							the Father.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Mighty Steer, hast four supremest natures, Asura natures that may
							ne'er be injured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							All these, O Maghavan, thou surely knowest, wherewith thou hast
							performed thy great achievements.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou hast all treasures in thy sole possession, treasures made manifest
							and treasures hidden.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Defer not thou, O Maghavan, my longing: thou, art Director, Indra, thou
							art Giver.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him who set the light in things of splendour, and with all sweetness
							blent essential sweetness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 54: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Indra hath this welcome hymn that strengthens been uttered by the
							votary Brhaduktha.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 55
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FAR is that secret name by which, in terror, the worlds invoked thee
							and thou gavest vigour
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The earth and heaven thou settest near each other, and Maghavan, madest
							bright thy Brother's Children.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Great is that secret name and far-extending, whereby thou madest all
							that is and shall be.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Five Tribes whom he loveth well have entered the light he loveth
							that was made aforetime.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He filled the heaven and earth and all between them, Gods five times
							sevenfold in their proper seasons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With four-and-thirty lights he looks around him, lights of one colour
							though their ways are divers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							As first among the lights, O Dawn, thou shonest, whereby thou
							broughtest forth the Stay of Increase,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Great art thou, matchless is thine Asura nature, who, high above, art
							kin to those beneath thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The old hath waked the young Moon from his slumber who runs his
							circling course with many round him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Behold the Gods' high wisdom in its greatness: he who died yesterday
							to-day is living.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong is the Red Bird in his strength, great Hero, who from of old
							hath had no nest to dwell in.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							That which he knows is truth and never idle: he wins and gives the
							wealth desired of many.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through these the Thunderer gained strong manly vigour, through whom he
							waxed in power to smite down Vrtra,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who through the might of Indra's operation came forth as Gods in course
							of Law and Order.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							All-strong, performing works with his companion, All-marking, rapid
							Victor, Curse-averter,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 55: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Hero, waxing, after draughts of Soma, blew far from heaven the
							Dasyus with his weapon.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 56
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HERE is one light for thee, another yonder: enter the third and he
							therewith united.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Uniting with a body be thou welcome, dear to the Gods in their
							sublimest birthplace.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bearing thy body, Vajin, may thy body afford us blessing and thyself
							protection.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unswerving, stablish as it were in heaven thine own light as the mighty
							God's supporter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong Steed art thou: go to the yearning Maidens with vigour, happily
							go to heaven and praises:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fly happily to the Gods with easy passage, according to the first and
							faithful statutes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Part of their grandeur have the Fathers also gained: the Gods have
							seated mental power in them as Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They have embraced within themselves all energies, which, issuing
							forth, again into their bodies pass.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							They strode through all the region with victorious might, establishing
							the old immeasurable laws.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							They compassed in their bodies all existing things, and streamed forth
							offipring in many successive forms.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							In two ways have the sons established in his place the Asura who finds
							the light, by the third act,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As fathers, they have set their heritage on earth, their offspring, as
							a thread continuously spun out.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							As in a ship through billows, so through regions of air, with
							blessings, through toils and troubles
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 56: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hath Brhaduktha brought his seed with glory, and placed it here and in
							the realms beyond us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 57
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET us not, Indra, leave the path, the Soma-presser's sacrifice:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let no malignity dwell with us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we obtain, completely wrought, the thread spun out to reach the
							Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That perfecteth the sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							We call the spirit hither with the Soma of our parted sires,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, with the Fathers' holy hymns.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit come to thee again for wisdom, energy, and lire,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That thou mayst long behold the sun!
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Fathers, may the Heavenly Folk give us our spirit once again,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							That we may be with those who live.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Soma with the spirit still within us, blest with progeny,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 57: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we be busied in the law.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 58
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THY spirit, that went far away to Yama to Vivasvan's Son,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away, that passed away to earth and heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away, away to the four-cornered earth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away to the four quarters of the world,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away, away unto the billowy sea,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away to beams of light that flash and flow,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to tbee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away, went to the waters and the plants,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away, that visited the Sun and Dawn.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away, away to lofty mountain heights,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away into this All, that lives and moves,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away to distant realms beyond our ken,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn here.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy spirit, that went far away to all that is and is to be,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 58: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							We cause to come to thee again that thou mayst live and sojourn heie.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 59
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							His life hath been renewed and carried forward as two men, car-borne,
							by the skilful driver.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							One falls, then seeks the goal with quickened vigour. Let Nirrti depart
							to distant places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here is the psalm for wealth, and food, in plenty: let us do many deeds
							to bring us glory.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							All these our doings shall delight the singer. Let Nirrti depart to
							distant places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we o'ercome our foes with acts of valour, as heaven is over earth,
							hills over lowlands.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							All these our deeds the singer hath considered. Let Nirrti depart to
							distant places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us not up as prey to death, O Sorna still let us look upon the Sun
							arising.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let our old age with passing days be kindly. Let Nirrti depart to
							distant places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Asuniti, keep the soul within us, and make the days we have to live
							yet longer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant that we still may look upon the sunlight: strengthen thy body
							with the oil we bring thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give us our sight again, O Asuniti, give us again our breath and our
							enjoyment.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Long may we look upon the Sun uprising; O Anumati, favour thou and
							bless us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Earth restore to us our vital spirit, may Heaven the Goddess and
							mid-air restore it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Soma give us once again our body, and Pusan show the Path of peace
							and comfort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May both Worlds bless Subandhu, young Mothers of everlasting Law.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Heaven and Earth uproot and sweep iniquity and shame away: nor sin
							nor sorrow trouble thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Health-giving medicines descend sent down from heaven in twos and
							threes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or wandering singly on the earth. May Heaven and Earth uproot and sweep
							iniquity and shame away: nor sin nor sorrow trouble thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drive forward thou the wagon-ox, O Indra, which brought Usinarani's
							wagon hither.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 59: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Heaven and Earth uproot and sweep iniquity and shame away: nor sin
							nor sorrow trouble thee.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 60
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BRINGING our homage we have come to one magnificent in look.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Glorified of the mighty Gods
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Asamati, spring of gifts, lord of the brave, a radiant car,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The conqueror of Bhajeratha
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who, when the spear hath armed his hand, or even weaponless o'erthrows
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men strong as buffaloes in fight;
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him in whose service flourishes Iksvaku, rich and dazzling-bright.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As the Five Tribes that are in heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, support the princely power of Rathaprosthas matched by none,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as the Sun for all to see.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou for Agastya's sister's sons yokest thy pair of ruddy steeds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou troddest niggards under foot, all those, O King, who brought no
							gifts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the mother, this the sire, this one hath come to be thy life.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							What brings thee forth is even this. Now come, Subandhu, get thee
							forth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							As with the leather thong they bind the chariot yoke to hold it fast,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							So have I held thy spirit fast, held it for life and not for death,
							held it for thy security.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as this earth, the mighty earth, holds fast the monarchs of the
							wood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							So have I held thy spirit fast, held it for life and not for death,
							held it for thy security.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Subandlin's spirit I have brought from Yarna, from Vivasvan's Son,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brought it for life and not for death, yea, brought it for security.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The wind blows downward from on high, downward the Sun-God sends his
							heat,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Downward the milch-cow pours her milk: so downward go thy pain and
							grief.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Felicitous is this mine hand, yet more felicitous is this.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 60: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							This hand contains all healing balms, and this makes whole with gentle
							touch.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 61
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE welcome speaker in the storm of battle uttered with might this
							prayer to win the Asvins,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the most liberal God, for Paktha, rescued his parents, and
							assailed the seven Hotras.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Cyavana, purposing deceptive presents, with all ingredients, made the
							altar ready.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most sweet-voiced Turvayana poured oblations like floods of widely
							fertilizing water.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							To his oblations, swift as thought, ye hurried, and welcomed eagerly
							the prayers he offered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With arrows in his hand the Very Mighty forced from him all obedience
							of a servant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I call on you the Sons of Dyaus, the Asvins, that a dark cow to my red
							kine be added.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enjoy my sacrifice, come to my viands contented, not deceiving
							expectation. '
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Uttering praise to suit the rite Navagvas came speedily to win the
							damsel's friendship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							They who approached the twice-strong stable's keeper, meedless would
							milk the rocks that naught had shaken.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Swift was new friendship with the maid they quickly accepted it as
							genuine seed and bounty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Milk which the cow Sabardugha had yielded was the bright heritage which
							to thee they offered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							When afterwards they woke- and missed the cattle, the speaker thus in
							joyful mood addressed them:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Matchless are singers throulgh the Vasu's nature; he bringeth them all
							food and all possessions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							His followers then who dwelt in sundry places came and desired too slay
							the son of Nrsad.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Resistless foe, be found the hidden treasure of Susna multiplied in
							numerous offipring.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, called Effulgence, in whose threefold dwelling, as in the light
							of heaven, the Gods are sitting,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou who art called Agni or Jatavedas, Priest, hear us, guileless
							Priest of holy worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							And, Indra, bring, that I may laud and serve them, those Two
							resplendent glorious Nasatyas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blithe, bounteous, man-like, to the sacrificer, honoured among our men
							with offered viands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							This King is praised and honoured as Ordainer: himself the bridge, the
							Sage speeds o'er the waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath stirred up Kaksivan, stirred up Agni, as the steed's swift
							wheel drives the felly onward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vaitarana, doubly kinsman, sacrificer, shall milk the cow who ne'er
							hath calved, Sabardhu,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							When I encompass Varuna and Mitra with lauds, and Aryaman in safest
							shelter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Their kin, the Prince in heaven, thy nearest kinsman, turning his
							thought to thee thus speaks in kindness:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							This is our highest bond: I am his offspring. How many others came ere
							I succeeded?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here is my kinship, here the place I dwell in: these are my Gods; I in
							full strength am present.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Twice-born am I, the first-born Son of Order: the Cow milked this when
							first she had her being.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							So mid these tribes he rests, the friendly envoy, borne on two paths,
							refulgent Lord of fuel.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, like a line, the Babe springs up erectly, his Mother straight
							hath borne him strong to bless us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then went the milch-kine forth to please the damsel, and for the good
							of every man that liveth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hear us, O wealthy Lord; begin our worship. Thou hast grown mighty
							through Asvaghna's virtues.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							And take thou notice of us also, Indra, for ample riches, King whose
							arm wields thunder!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Protect our wealthy nobles, guard our princes unmenaced near thee, Lord
							of Tawny Coursers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							When he goes forth, ye Pair of Kings, for booty, speeding to war and
							praise to please the singer,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							I was the dearest sage of those about him,-let him lead these away and
							bring them safely.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now for this noble man's support and comfort, singing with easy voice
							we thus implore thee:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Impetuous be his son and fleet his courser: and may I be his priest to
							win him glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							If, for our strength, the priest with adoration to win your friendship
							made the laud accepted,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							That laud shall be a branching road to virtue for every one to whom the
							songs are suited.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Glorified thus, with holy hymns and homage:-Of noble race, with Waters,
							God-attended
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he enrich us for our prayers and praises: now can the cow be
							milked; the path is open.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be to us, then, ye Gods who merit worship, be ye of one accord our
							strong protection,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 61: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who went on various ways and brought us vigour, ye who are undeceivable
							explorers.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 62
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YE, who, adorned with guerdon through the sacrifice, have won you
							Indra's friendship and eternal life,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even to you be happiness, Angirases. Welcome the son of Manu, ye who
							are most wise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Fathers, who drave forth the wealth in cattle, have in the year's
							courses cleft Vala by Eternal Law:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							A lengthened life be yours, O ye Angirases. Welcome the son of Manu, ye
							who are most wise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye raised the Sun to heaven by everlasting Law, and spread broad earth,
							the Mother, out on every side.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fair wealth of progeny be yours, Angirases. Welcome the son of Manu, ye
							who are most wise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This kinsman in your dwellingplace speaks pleasant words: give car to
							this, ye Rsis, children of the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							High Brahman dignity be yours, Angirases. Welcome the son of Manu, ye
							who are most wise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Distinguished by their varied form, these Rsis have been deeply moved.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These are the sons of Angirases: from Agni have they sprung to life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Distinguished by their varied form, they sprang from Agni, from the
							sky.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Navagva and Dasagva, noblest Angiras, he giveth bounty with the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Indra for associate the priests have cleared the stable full of
							steeds and kine,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giving to me a thousand with their eightmarked cars, they gained renown
							among the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May this man's sons be multiplied; like springing corn may Manu grow,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who gives at once in bounteous gift a thousand kine, a hundred steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							No one attains to him, as though a man would grasp the heights of
							heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savarnya's sacrificial meed hath broadened like an ample flood.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yadu and Turva, too, have given two Dasas, well-disposed, to serve,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Together with great store of kine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Blest be the hamlet's chief, most liberal Manu, and may his bounty
							rival that of Surya.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the God let Ssvarni's life be leng
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 62: Verse 11: Line 3
					-
						-
							thened, with whom, unwearied, we have lived and prospered.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 63
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY they who would assume kinship from far away, Vivasvan's
							generations, dearly loved of men,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even the Gods who sit upon the sacred grass of Nahusa's son Yayati,
							bless and comfort us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For worthy of obeisance, Gods, are all your names, worthy of adoration
							and of sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye who were born from waters, and from Aditi, and from the earth, do ye
							here listen to my call.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will rejoice in these Adityas for my weal, for whom the Mother pours
							forth water rich in balm,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Dyaus the Infinite, firm as a rock, sweet milk,-Gods active, strong
							through lauds, whose might the Bull upholds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Looking on men, ne'er slumbering, they by their deserts attained as
							Gods to lofty immortality.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Borne on refulgent cars, sinless, with serpents' powers, they robe
							them, for our welfare, in the height of heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Great Kings who bless us, who have come to sacrifice, who, ne'er
							assailed, have set their mansion in the sky,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							These I invite with adoration and with hymns, mighty Adityas, Aditi,
							for happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who offereth to you the laud that ye accept, O ye All-Gods of Manu,
							many as ye are?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, Mighty Ones, will prepare for you the sacrifice to bear us over
							trouble to felicity?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye to whom Manu, by seven priests, with kindled fire, offered the first
							oblation with his heart and soul,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us, ye Adityas, sheitcr free from fear, and make us good and
							easy paths to happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wise Deities, who have dominion o'er the world, ye thinkers over all
							that moves not and that moves,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Save us from uncommitted and committed sin, preserve us from all sin
							to-day for happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							In battles we invoke Indra still swift to hear, and all the holy Host
							of Heaven who banish grief,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, Mitra, and Varuna that we may gain, Dyays, Bhaga, Maruts, Prthivi
							for happiness:
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mightily-saving Earth, incomparable Heaven the good guide Aditi who
							gives secure defence
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The well-oared heavenly Ship that lets no waters in, free from defect,
							will we ascend for happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bless us, all Holy Ones, that we may have your help, guard and protect
							us from malignant injury.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							With fruitful invocation may we call on you, Gods, who give ear to us
							for grace, for happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Keep all disease afar and sordid sacrifice, keep off the wicked man's
							malicious enmity.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Keep far away from us all hatred, O ye Gods, and give us ample shelter
							for our happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Untouched by any evil, every mortal thrives, and, following the Law,
							spreads in his progeny.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom ye with your good guidance, O Adityas, lead safely through all his
							pain and grief to happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							That which ye guard and grace in battle, O ye Gods, ye Maruts, where
							the prize is wealth, where heroes win,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							That conquering Car, O Indra, that sets forth at dawn, that never
							breaks, may we ascend for happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us blessing in our paths and desert tracts, blessing in
							waters and in battle, for the light;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blessing upon the wombs that bring male children forth, and blessing, O
							ye Maruts, for the gain of wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							The noblest Svasti with abundant riches, who comes to what is good by
							distant pathway,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							May she at home and far away preserve us, and dwell with us under the
							Gods' protection
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus hatb the thoughtful sage, the son of Plati, praised you, O Aditi
							and all Adityas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 63: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men are made rich by those who are Immortal: the Heavenly Folk have
							been extolled by Gaya.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 64
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHAT God, of those who hear, is he whose well-praised name we may
							record in this our sacrifice; and how?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who will be gracious? Who of many give us bliss? Who out of all the
							Host will come to lend us aid?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The will and thoughts within my breast exert their power: they yearn
							with love, and fly to all the regions round.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							None other comforter is found save only these: my longings and my hopes
							are fixt upon the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Narasamsa and to Pusan I sing forth, unconcealable Agni kindied by
							the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Sun and Moon, two Moons, to Yama in the heaven, to Trita, Vata,
							Dawn, Night, and the Atvins Twain.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							How is the Sage extolled whom the loud singers praise? What voice, what
							hymn is used to laud Brhaspati?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Aja-Ekapad with Rkvans swift to hear, and Ahi of the Deep listen
							unto our call.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aditi, to the birth of Daksa and the vow thou summonest the Kings Mitra
							and Varuna.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With course unchecked, with many chariots Aryaman comes with the seven
							priests to tribes of varied sort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							May all those vigorous Coursers listen to our cry, hearers of
							invocation, speeding on their way;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Winners of thousands where the priestly meed is won, who gather of
							themselves great wealth in every race.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring ye Purandbi, bring Vayu who yokes his steeds, for friendship
							bring ye Pusan with your songs of praise:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They with one mind, one thought attend the sacrifice, urged by the
							favouring aid of Savitar the God.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The thrice-seven wandering Rivers, yea, the mighty floods, the forest
							trees, the mountains, Agni to our aid,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Krsanu, Tisya, archers to our gathering-place, and Rudra strong amid
							the Rudras we invoke.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the great Streams come hither with their mighty help, Sindhu,
							Sarasvati, and Sarayu with waves.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Goddess Floods, ye Mothers, animating all, promise us water rich in
							fatness and in balm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							And let Brhaddiva, the Mother, hear our call, and Tvastar, Father, with
							the Goddesses and Dames.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rbhuksan, Vaja, Bhaga, and Rathaspati, and the sweet speech of him who
							labours guard us well!
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pleasant to look on as a dwelling rich in food is the blest favour of
							the Maruts, Rudra's Sons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we be famed among the folk for wealth in kine. and ever come to
							you, ye Gods, with sacred food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							The thought which ye, O Maruts, Indra and ye Gods have given to me, and
							ye, Mitra and Varuna,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Cause this to grow and swell like a milchcow with milk. Will ye not
							bear away my songs upon your car?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Maruts, do ye never, never recollect and call again to mind this our
							relationship?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							When next we meet together at the central point, even there shall Aditi
							confirm our brotherhood.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Mothers, Heaven and Earth, those mighty Goddesses, worthy of
							sacrifice, ecune with the race of Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							These Two with their support uphold both Gods and men, and with the
							Fathers pour the copious genial stream.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							This invocation wins all good that we desire Brhaspati, highly-praised
							Aramati, are here,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even where the stone that presses meath rings loudly out, and where the
							sages make their voices heard with hymns.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus hath the sage, skilled in loud singers' duties, desiring riches,
							yearning after treasure,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gaya, the priestly singer, with his praises and hymns contented the
							Celestial people.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus hath the thoughtful sage the son of Plati, praised you, O Aaiti
							and all Adityas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 64: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men are made rich by those who are Immortal: the Heavenly Folk have
							been extolled by Gaya.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 65
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY Agni, Indra, Mitra, Varuna consent, Aryaman, Vayu, Pusan, and
							Sarasvati,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Adityas, Maruts, Visnu, Soma, lofty Sky, Rudra and Aditi, and
							Brahmanaspati.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni, Hero-lords when Vrtra fell, dwelling together, speeding
							emulously on,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Soma blent with oil, putting his greatness forth, have with their
							power filled full the mighty firmament.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Skilled in the Law I lift the hymn of praise to these,
							Law-strengtheners, unassailed, and great in majesty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							These in their wondrous bounty send the watery sea: may they as kindly
							Friends send gifts to make us great.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They with their might have stayed Heaven, Earth, and Prthivi, the Lord
							of Light, the firmament, -the lustrous spheres.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as fleet-foot steeds who make their masters glad, the princely
							Gods are praised, most bountiful to man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring gifts to Mitra and to Varuna who, Lords of all, in spirit never
							fail the worshipper,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose statute shines on high through everlasting Law, whose places of
							sure refuge are the heavens and earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The cow who yielding milk goes her appointed way hither to us as leader
							of holy rites,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Speaking aloud to Varuna and the worshipper, shall with oblation serve
							Vivasvan and the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Gods whose tongue is Agni dwell in heaven, and sit, aiders of Law,
							reflecting, in the seat of Law.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They propped up heaven and then brought waters with their might, got
							sacrifice and in a body made it fair.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born in the oldest time, the Parents dwelling round are sharers of one
							mansion in the home of Law.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bound by their common vow Dyaus, Prthivi stream forth the moisture rich
							in oil to Varuna the Steer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Parjanya, Vata, mighty, senders of the rain, Indra and Vayu, Varuna,
							Mitra, Aryaman:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							We call on Aditi, Adityas, and the Gods, those who are on the earth, in
							waters, and in heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tvastar and Vayu, those who count as Rbhus, both celestial
							Hotar-priests, and Dawn for happiness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Winners of wealth, we call, and wise Brhaspati, destroyer of our foes,
							and Soma Indra's Friend.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							They generated prayer, the cow, the horse, the plants, the forest
							trees, the earth, the waters, and the hills.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							These very bounteous Gods made the Sun mount to heaven, and spread the
							righteous laws of Aryas o'er the land.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Asvins, ye delivered Bhujyu from distress, ye animated Syava,
							Vadhrmati's son.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Vimada ye brought his consort Kamadyu, and gave his lost Visnapu
							back to Visvaka.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thunder, the lightning's daughter, Aja-Ekapad, heaven's bearer, Sindhu,
							and the waters of the sea:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hear all the Gods my words, Sarasvati give ear together with Purandhi
							and with Holy Thoughts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Holy Thoughts and with Purandhi may all Gods, knowing the Law
							immortal, Manu's Holy Ones,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Boon-givers, favourers, finders of light, and Heaven, with gracious
							love accept my songs, my prayer, my hymn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Immortal Gods have I, Vasistha, lauded, Gods set on high above all
							other beings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 65: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they this day grant us wide space and freedom: ye Gods, preserve us
							evermore with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 66
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I CALL the Gods of lofty glory for our weal, the makers of the light,
							well-skilled in sacrifice;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Those who have waxen mightily, Masters of all wealth, Immortal,
							strengthening Law, the Gods whom Indra leads.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							For the strong band of Maruts will we frame a hymn: the chiefs shall
							bring forth sacrifice for Indra's troop,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who, sent by Indra and advised by Varuna, have gotten for themselves a
							share of Surya's light
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra with the Vasus keep our dwelling safe, and Aditi with Adityas
							lend us sure defence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the God Rudra with the Rudras favour us, and Tvastar with the Dames
							further us to success.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aditi, Heaven and Earth, the great eternal Law, Indra, Visnu, the
							Maruts, and the lofty Sky.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							We call upon Adityas, on the Gods, for help, on Vasus, Rudras, Savitar
							of wondrous deeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Holy Thoughts Sarasvan, firm-lawed Varuna, great Vayu, Pusan,
							Visnu, and the Asvins Twain,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lords of all wealth, Immortal, furtherers of prayer, grant us a
							triply-guarding refuge from distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong be the sacrifice, strong be the Holy Ones, strong the preparers
							of oblation, strong the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mighty be Heaven and Earth, true to eternal Law, strong be Parjanya,
							strong be they who laud the Strong.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							To win us strength I glorify the Mighty Twain, Agni and Soma, Mighty
							Ones whom many laud.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these vouchsafe us shelter with a triple guard, these whom the
							strong have served in worship of the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Potent, with firm-fixt laws, arranging sacrifice, visiting solemn rites
							in splendour of the day,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Obeying Order, these whose priest is Agni, free from falsehood, poured
							the waters out when Vrtra died.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Holy Ones engendered, for their several laws, the heavens and
							earth, the waters, and the plants and trees.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							They filled the firmament with heavenly light for help: the Gods
							embodied Wish and made it beautiful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							May they who bear up heaven, the Rbhus deft of hand, and Vata and
							Parjanya of the thundering Bull,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The waters and the plants, promote the songs we sing: come Bhaga, Rati,
							and the Vaijns to my call.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sindhu, the sea, the region, and the firmament, the thunder, and the
							ocean, Aja-Ekapad,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Dragon of the Deep, shall listen to my words, and all the Deities
							and Princes shall give ear.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we, be yours, we men, to entertain the Gods: further our sacrifice
							and give it full success.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Adityas, Rudras, Vasus, givers of good gifts, quicken the holy hymns
							which we are singing now
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							I follow with success upon the path of Law the two celestial Hotars,
							Priests of oldest time.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							We pray to him who dwelleth near, Guard of the Field, to all Immortal
							Gods who never are remiss.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vasistha's sons have raised their voices, like their sire. Rsi-like
							praying to the Gods for happiness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like friendly-minded kinsmen, come at our desire, O Gods, and shake
							down treasures on us from above.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Immortal Gods have I, Vasistha, lauded, Gods set on high above all
							other beings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 66: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							May they this day grant us wide space and freedom: ye Gods, preserve us
							evermore with blessings.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 67
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS holy hymn, sublime and sevenheaded, sprung from eternal Law, our
							sire discovered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ayasya, friend of all men, hath engendered the fourth hymn as he sang
							his laud to Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thinking aright, praising eternal Order, the sons of Dyaus the Asura,
							those heroes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Angirases, holding the rank of sages, first honoured sacrifice's holy
							statute.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Girt by his friends who cried with swanlike voices, bursting the stony
							barriers of the prison,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati spake in thunder to the cattle, and uttered praise and song
							when he had found them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Apart from one, away from two above him, he drave the kine that stood
							in bonds of falsehood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, seeking light amid the darkness, drave forth the bright
							cows: three he made apparent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							When he had cleft the lairs and western castle, he cut off three from
							him who held the waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati discovered, while he thundered like Dyaus, the dawn, the Sun,
							the cow, the lightning.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							As with a hand, so with his roaring Indra cleft Vala through, the
							guardian of the cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seeking the milk-draught with sweatshining comrades he stole the Pani's
							kine and left him weeping.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He with bright faithful Friends, winners of booty, hath rent the milker
							of the cows asunder.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati with wild boars strong and mighty, sweating with heat, hath
							gained a rich possession.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							They, longing for the kine, with faithful spirit incited with their
							hymns the Lord of cattle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati freed the radiant cows with comrades self-yoked, averting
							shame from one another.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							In our assembly with auspicious praises exalting him who roareth like a
							lion,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Maywe, in every fight where heroes conquer, rejoice in strong Brhaspati
							the Victor.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							When he had won him every sort of booty and gone to heaven and its most
							lofty mansions,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men praised Brhaspati the Mighty, bringing the light within their
							mouths from sundry places.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fulfil the prayer that begs for vital vigour: aid in your wonted manner
							even the humble.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let all our foes be turned and driven backward. Hear this, O Heaven and
							Earth, ye All-producers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra with mighty strength cleft asunder the head of Arbuda the watery
							monster,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 67: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Slain Ahi, and set free the Seven Rivers. O Heaven and Earth, with all
							the Gods protect us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 68
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LIKE birds who keep their watch, plashing in water, like the loud
							voices of the thundering rain-cloud,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like merry streamlets bursting from the mountain, thus to Brhaspati our
							hymns have sounded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Son of Angirases, meeting the cattle, as Bhaga, brought in Aryaman
							among us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As Friend of men he decks the wife and husband: as for the race,
							Brhaspati, nerve our coursers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, having won them from the mountains, strewed down, like
							barley out of winnowing- baskets,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The vigorous, wandering cows who aid the pious, desired of all, of
							blameless form, well-coloured.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							As the Sun dews with meath the seat of Order, and casts a flaming
							meteor down from heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							So from the rock Brhaspati forced the cattle, and cleft the earth's
							skin as it were with water.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forth from mid air with light he dravc the darkness, as the gale blows
							a lily from the fiver.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like the wind grasping at the cloud of Vala, Brhaspati gathered to
							himself the cattle,
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, when he with fiery lightnings cleft through the weapon of
							reviling Vala,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Consumed.him as tongues cat what teeth have compassed: he threw the
							prisons of the red cows open.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							That secret name borne by the lowing cattle within the cave Brhaspati
							discovered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And drave, himself, the bright kine from the mountain, like a bird's
							young after the egg's disclosure.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							He looked around on rock-imprisoned sweetness as one who eyes a fish in
							scanty water.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, cleaving through with varied clamour, brought it forth like
							a bowl from out the timber.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							He found the light of heaven, and fire, and Morning: with lucid rays he
							forced apart the darkness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							As from a joint, Brhaspati took the marrow of Vala as he gloried in his
							cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							As trees for foliage robbed by winter, Vala mourned for the cows
							Brhaspati had taken.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He did a deed ne'er done, ne'er to be equalled, whereby the Sun and
							Moon ascend alternate.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a dark steed adorned with pearl, the Fathers have decorated heaven
							With constellations.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							They set the light in day, in night the darkness. Brhaspati cleft the
							rock and found the cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							This homage have we.offered to the Cloud God who thunders out to many
							in succession.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 68: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							May this Brhaspati vouchsafe us fulness of life with kine and horses,
							men, and heroes.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 69
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Auspicious is the aspect of Vadhryasva's fire good is its guidance,
							pleasant are its visitings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When first the people Of Sumitra kindle it, with butter poured thercon
							it crackles and shines bright.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Butter is that which makes Vadhryaiva's fire growstrong: the butter is
							its food, the butter makes it fat.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							It spreads abroad when butter hath been offered it, and balmed with
							streams of butter shines forth like the Sun.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Still newest is this face of thine, O Agni, which Manu and Sumitra have
							enkindled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So richly shine, accept our songs with favour, so give us strengthening
							food, so send us glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Accept this offering, Agni, whom aforetime Vadhryasva, hath entreated
							and enkindled.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard well our homes and ople, guard our bodies, protect thy girt to us
							which thou hast granted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be splendid, guard us Kinsman of Vadhryasva: let not the enmity of men
							o'ercome thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like the bold hero Cyavana, I Sumitra tell forth the title of
							Vadhryaiva's Kinsman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							All treasures hast thou won, of plains and mountains, and quelled the
							Dasas' and Aryas' hatred.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like the bold hero Cyavana, O Agni, mayst thou subdue the men who long
							for battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Deft Agni hath a lengthened thread, tall oxen, a thousand heifers,
							numberless devices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Decked by the men, splendid among the splendid, shine brightly forth
							amid devout Sumitras.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine is the teeming cow, O Jatavedas, who pours at once her ceaseless
							flow, Sabardhuk,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou. art lit up by men enriched with guerdon, O Agni, by the
							pious-souled Sumitras.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even Immortal Gods, O Jatavedas, Vadhryasva's Kinsman, have declared
							thy grandeur.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When human tribes drew near with supplication thou conqueredst with men
							whom thou hadst strengthened.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as a father bears his son, O Agni, Vadhryasva bare thee in his lap
							and served thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Youngest God, having enjoyed his fuel, didst vanquish those of
							old though they were mighty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vadhryasva's Agni evermore hath vanquished his foes with heroes who had
							pressed the Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of bright rays, thou burntest up the battle, subduing, as our
							help, e'en mighty foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Agni of Vadhryasva, Vrtra-slayer, lit from of old, must be invoked
							with homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 69: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							As such assail our enemies, Vadhryasva, whether the foes be strangers
							or be kinsmen.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 70
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ENJOY, O Agni, this my Fuel, welcome the oil-filled ladle where we pour
							libation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rise up for worship of the Gods, wise Agni, on the earth's height,
							while days are bright with beauty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May he who goes before the Gods come hither with steeds whose shapes
							are varied, Narasarhsa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he, most Godlike, speed our offered viands with homage God-ward on
							the path of Order.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men with oblations laud most constant Agni, and pray him to perform an
							envoy's duty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With lightly-rolling car and best draught-horses, bring the Gods hither
							and sit down as Hotar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the delight of Gods spread out transversely: may it be with us long
							in length and fragrant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Holy Grass divine, with friendly spirit bring thou the willing Gods
							whose Chief is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Touch ye the far-extending height of heaven or spring apart to suit the
							wide earth's measure.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yearning, ye Doors, with those sublime in greatness, seize eagerly the
							heavenly Car that cometh.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here in this shrine may Dawn and Night, the Daughters of Heaven, the
							skilful Goddesses, be seated.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							In your wide lap, auspicious, willing Ladies may the Gods seat them
							with a willing spirit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Up stands the stone, high burns the fire enkindled: Aditi's lap
							contains the Friendly Natures
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Two Chief Priests who serve at this our worship, may ye, more
							skilled, win for us rich possessions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							On our wide grass, Three Goddesses be seated: for you have we prepared
							and made it pleasant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Ila, she whose foot drops oil, the Goddess, taste, man-like,
							sacrifice and well-set presents.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Since thou, God Tvastar, hast made beauty perfect, since hou hast been
							the Angirases' Companion,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Willing, most wealthy, Giver of possessions, grant us the Gods'
							assembly, thou who knowest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well-knowing, binding with thy cord, bring hither, Lord of the Wood,
							the Deities' assembly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The God prepare and season our oblations may Heaven and Earth be
							gracious to my calling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, bring hither Varuna to help us, Indra from heaven, from air's
							mid-realm the Maruts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 70: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							On sacred grass all Holy ones be seated and let the Immortal Gods
							rejoice in Svaha.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 71
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHEN-men, Brhaspati, giving names to objects, sent out Vak's first and
							earliest utterances,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							All that was excellent and spotless, treasured within them, was
							disclosed through their affection.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where, like men cleansing corn-flour in a cribble, the wise in spirit
							have created language,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Friends see and recognize the marks of friendship: their speech retains
							the blessed sign imprinted.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							With sacrifice the trace of Vak they foIlowed, and found her harbouring
							within the Rsis.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							They brought her, dealt her forth in many places: seven singers make
							her tones resound in concert.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							One man hath ne'er seen Vak, and yet he seeth: one man hath hearing but
							hath never heard her.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							But to another hath she shown her beauty as a fond well-dressed woman
							to her husband.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							One man they call a laggard, dull in friendship: they never urge him on
							to deeds of valour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He wanders on in profitless illusion: the Voice he heard yields neither
							fruit,nor blossom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							No part in Vak hath he who hath abandoned his own dear friend who knows
							the truth of friendship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even if he hears her still in vain he listens: naught knows he of the
							path of righteous action.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unequal in the quickness of their spirit are friends endowed alike with
							eyes and hearing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Some look like tanks that reach the mouth or shoulder, others like
							pools of water fit to bathe in.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When friendly Brahmans sacrifice together with mental impulse which the
							heart hath fashioned,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							They leave one far behind through their attainments, and some who count
							as Brahmans wander elsewhere.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those men who step not back and move not forward, nor Brahmans nor
							preparers of libations,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Having attained to Vak in sinful fashion spin out their thread in
							ignorance like spinsters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							All friends are joyful in the friend who cometh in triumph, having
							conquered in assembly.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He is their blame-averter, food-provider prepared is he and fit for
							deed of vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							One plies his constant task reciting verses. one sings the holy psalm
							in Sakvari measures.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 71: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							One more, the Brahman, tells the lore of being, and one lays down the
							rules of sacrificing.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 72
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET US with tuneful skill proclaim these generations of the Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That one may see them when these hymns are chanted in a future age.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Brahmanaspati produced with blast and smelting, like a Smith,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Existence, in an earlier age of Gods, from Non-existence sprang.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Existence, in the earliest age of Gods, from Non-existence sprang.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thereafter were the regions born. This sprang from the Productive
							Power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Earth sprang from the Productive Power the regions from the earth were
							born.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Daksa was born of Aditi, and Aditi was Daksa's Child.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							For Aditi, O Daksa, she who is thy Daughter, was brought forth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							After her were the blessed Gods born sharers of immortal life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When ye, O Gods, in yonder deep closeclasping one another stood,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thence, as of dancers, from your feet a thickening cloud of dust arose.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, O ye Gods, like Yatis, ye caused all existing things to grow,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then ye brought Surya forward who was lying hidden in the sea.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eight are the Sons of Adid who from her body sprang to life.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With seven she went to meet the Gods she cast Martanda far away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							So with her Seven Sons Aditi went forth to meet the earlier age.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 72: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							She brought Martanda thitherward to spring to life and die again.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 73
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU wast born mighty for victorious valour, exulting, strongest, full
							of pride and courage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							There, even there, the Maruts strengthened Indra when. his most rapid
							Mother stirred the Hero.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							There with fiend's ways e'en Prsni was seated: with much laudation they
							exalted Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As if encompassed by the Mighty-footed, from darkness, near at hand,
							forth came the Children.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							High are thy feet when on thy way thou goest: the strength thou
							foundest here hath lent thee vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thousand hyenas in thy mouth thou holdest. O Indra, mayst thou turn the
							Asvins hither.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Speeding at once to sacrifice thou comest for friendship thou art
							bringing both Nasatyas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hadst a thousand treasures in possession. The Asvins, O thou Hero,
							gave thee riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Glad, for the race that rests on holy Order, with friends who hasten to
							their goal, hath Indra
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With these his magic powers assailed the Dasyu: he cast away the gloomy
							mists, the darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Two of like name for him didst thou demolish, as Indra striking down
							the car of Usas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							With thy beloved lofty Friends thou camest, and with the assurance of
							thine heart thou slewest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							War-loving Namuci thou smotest, robbing the Dasa of his magic for the
							Rsi.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							For man thou madest ready pleasant pathways, paths leading as it were
							directly God-ward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							These names of thine thou hast fulfilled completely: as Lord, thou
							boldest in thine arm, O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							In thee, through thy great might, the Gods are joyful: the roots of
							trees hast thou directed upward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the sweet Soma juices make him happy to cast his quoit that lies in
							depth of waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou from the udder which o'er earth is fastened hast poured the milk
							into the kine and herbage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							When others call him offspring of the Courser, my meaning is that
							Mighty Power produced him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							He came from Manyu and remained in houses: whence he hath sprung is
							known to Indra only.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like birds of beauteous wing the Priyamedhas, Rsis, imploring, have
							come nigh to Indra:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 73: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dispel the darkness and fill full our vision deliver us as men whom
							snares entangle.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 74
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I AM prepared to laud with song or worship the Noble Ones who are in
							earth and heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or Coursers who have triumphed in, the contest, or those who famed,
							have won the prize with glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Their call, the call of Gods, went up to heaven: they kissed the ground
							with glory-seeking spirit,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							There where the Gods look on for happy fortune, and like the kindly
							heavens bestow their bounties.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the song of those Immortal Beings who long for treasures in
							their full perfection.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May these, completing prayers and sacrifices, bestow upon us wealth
							where naught is wanting.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those living men extolled thy deed, O Indra, those who would fain burst
							through the stall of cattle,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fain to milk her who bare but once, great, lofty, whose Sons are many
							and her streams past number.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sacivan, win to your assistance Indra who never bends, who overcomes
							his foemen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rbhuksan, Maghavan, the hymn's upholder, who, rich in food, bears man's
							kind friend, the thunder.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Since he who won of old anew hath triumphed, Indra hath earned his name
							of Vrtra-slaycr.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 74: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath appeared, the mighty Lord of Conquest. What we would have him
							do let him accomplish.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 75
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE singer, O ye Waters in Vivasvan's place, shall tell your grandeur
							forth that is beyond compare.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Rivers have come forward triply, seven and seven. Sindhu in might
							surpasses all the streams that flow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Varuna cut the channels for thy forward course, O Sindhu, when thou
							rannest on to win the race.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou speedest o'er precipitous ridges of the earth, when thou art Lord
							and Leader of these moving floods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							His roar is lifted up to heaven above the earth: he puts forth endless
							vigour with a flash of light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like floods of rain that fall- in thunder from the cloud, so Sindhu
							rushes on bellowing like a bull.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like mothers to their calves, like milch kine with their milk, so,
							Sindhu, unto thee the roaring rivers run.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou leadest as a warrior king thine army's wings what time thou comest
							in the van of these swift streams.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Favour ye this my laud, O Ganga, Yamuna, O Sutudri, Parusni and
							Sarasvati:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Asikni, Vitasta, O Marudvrdha, O Arjikiya with Susoma hear my
							call.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							First with Trstama thou art eager to flow forth, with Rasa, and
							Susartu, and with Svetya here,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Kubha; and with these, Sindhu and Mehatnu, thou seekest in thy
							course Krumu and Gomati.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Flashing and whitely-gleaming in her mightiness, she moves along her
							ample volumes through the realms,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Most active of the active, Sindhu unrestrained, like to a dappled mare,
							beautiful, fair to see.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rich in good steeds is Sindhu, rich in cars and robes, rich in gold,
							nobly-fashioned, rich in ample wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blest Silamavati and young Urnavati invest themselves with raiment rich
							in store of sweets.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sindhu hath yoked her car, light-rolling, drawn by steeds, and with
							that car shall she win booty in this fight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 75: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							So have I praised its power, mighty and unrestrained, of independent
							glory, roaring as it runs.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 76
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I GRASP at you when power and strength begin to dawn: bedew ye, Indra
							and the Maruts, Heaven and Earth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That Day and Night, in every hall of sacrifice, may wait on us and
							bless us when they first spring forth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Press the libation out, most excellent of all: the Pressing-stone is
							grasped like a hand-guided steed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So let it win the valour that subdues the foe, and the fleet courser's
							might that speeds to ample wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Juice that this Stone pours out removes defect of ours, as in old time
							it brought prosperity to man.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							At sacrifices they established holy rites on Tvastar's milk-blent juice
							bright with the hue of steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drive ye the treacherous demons far away from us: keep Nirrti afar and
							banish Penury.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pour riches forth for us with troops of hero sons, and bear ye up, O
							Stones, the song that visits Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To you who are more mighty than the heavens themselves, who, finishing
							your task with more than Vibhvan's speed,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							More rapidly than Vayu seize the Soma juice, better than Agni give us
							food, to you I sing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stirred be the glorious Stones: let it press out the juice, the Stone
							with heavenly song that reaches up to heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							There where the men draw forth the meath for which they long, sending
							their voice around in rivalry of speed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Stones press out the Soma, swift as car-borne men, and, eager for
							the spoil, drain forth the sap thereof
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							To fill the beaker, they exhaust the udder's store, as the men purify
							oblations with their lips.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, present men, have been most skilful in your work, even ye, O Stones
							who pressed Soma for Indra's drink.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 76: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							May all ye have of fair go to the Heavenly Race, and all your treasure
							to the earthly worshipper.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 77
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As with their voice from cloud they sprinkle treasure so are the wise
							man's liberal sacrifices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I praise their Company that merits worship as the good Martits' priest
							to pay them honour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The youths have wrought their ornaments for glory through many
							nights,-this noble band of Maruts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like stags the Sons of Dyatis have striven onward, the Sons of Aditi
							grown strong like pillars.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who extend beyond the earth and heaven, by their own mass, as from
							the cloud spreads Surya;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like mighty Heroes covetous of glory, like heavenly gallants who
							destroy the wicked.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							When ye come nigh, as in the depth of waters, the earth is loosened, as
							it were, and shaken.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							This your all-feedin sacrifice approaches: come all united, fraught, as
							'twere with viands.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye are like horses fastened to the chariot poles, luminous with your
							beams, with splendour as at dawn;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like self-bright falcons, punishers of wicked men, like hovering birds
							urged forward, scattering rain around.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When ye come forth, O Maruts, from the distance, from the great
							treasury of rich possessions,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Knowing, O Vasus, boons that should be granted, even from afar drive
							back the men who hate us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who, engaged in the rite's final duty brings, as a man, oblation to
							the Maruts,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wins him life's wealthy fulness, blest with heroes: he shall be
							present, too, where Gods drink Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							For these are helps adored at sacrifices, bringing good fortune by
							their name Adityas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 77: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Speeding on cars let them protect our praises, delighting in our
							sacrifice and worship.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 78
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye by your hymns are like high-thoughted singers, skilful, inviting
							Gods with sacrifices;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fair to behold, like Kings, with bright adornment, like spotless
							gallants, leaders of the people:
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like fire with flashing flame, breast-bound with chains of gold, like
							tempest-blasts, self-moving, swift to lend your aid;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As best of all foreknowers, excellent to guide, like Somas, good to
							guard the man who follows Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shakers of all, like gales of wind they travel, like tongues of burning
							fires in their effulgence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mighty are they as warriors clad in armour, and, like the Fathers'
							prayers, Most Bounteous Givers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like spokes of car-wheels in one nave united, ever victorious like
							heavenly Heroes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shedding their precious balm like youthful suitors, they raise their
							voice and chant their psalm as singers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who are fleet to travel like the noblest steeds, long to obtain
							the prize like bounteous charioteers,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like waters speeding on with their precipitous floods, like omniform
							Angirases with Sama-hymns.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Born from the stream, like press-stones are the Princes, for ever like
							the stones that crush in pieces;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sons of a beauteous Dame, like playful children, like a great host upon
							the march with splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like rays of Dawn, the visitors of sacrifice, they shine with ornaments
							as eager to be bright.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like rivers hasting on, glittering with their spears, from far away
							they measure out the distances.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods, send us happiness and make us wealthy, letting us singers
							prosper, O ye Maruts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 78: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bethink you of our praise and of our friendship: ye from of old have
							riches to vouchsafe us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 79
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I HAVE beheld the might of this Great Being. Immortal in the midst of
							tribes of mortals.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							His jaws now open and now shut together: much they devour, insatiately
							chewing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							His eyes are turned away, his head is hidden: unsated with his tongue
							he eats the fuel.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With hands upraised, with reverence in the houses, for him they quickly
							bring his food together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Seeking, as 'twere, his Mother's secret bosom, he, like a child, creeps
							on through wide-spread bushes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							One he finds glowing like hot food made ready, and kissing deep within
							the earth's recmes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This holy Law I tell you, Earth and Heaven: the Infant at his birth
							dovours his Parents.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							No knowledge of the God have I, a mortal. Yea, Agni knoweth best, for
							he hath wisdom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							This man who quickly gives him food, who offers his gifts of oil and
							butter and supports him, -
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him with his thousand eyes he closely looks on: thou showest him thy
							face from all sides, Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, hast thou committed sin or treason among the Gods? In ignorance I
							ask thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Playing, not playing, he gold-hued and toothless, hath cut his food up
							as the knife a victim.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 79: Verse 7
