					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							In Magha days are oxen slain, in Arjuris they wed the bride.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							When on your three-wheeled chariot, O Asvins, ye came as wooers unto
							Surya's bridal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then all the Gods agreed to your proposal Pusan as Son elected you as
							Fathers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							O ye Two Lords of lustre, then when ye to Surya's wooing came,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where was one chariot wheel of yours? Where stood ye for die Sire's
							command?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Brahmans, by their seasons, know, O Surya, those two wheels of
							thine:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							One kept concealed, those only who are skilled in highest truths have
							learned.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							To Surya and the Deities, to Mitra and to Varuna.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who know aright the thing that is, this adoration have I paid.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							By their own power these Twain in close succession move;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							They go as playing children round the sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 18: Line 3
					-
						-
							One of the Pair beholdeth all existing things; the other ordereth
							seasons and is born again.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, born afresh, is new and new for ever ensign of days he goes before
							the Mornings
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Coming, he orders f6r the Gods their portion. The Moon prolongs the
							days of our existence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mount this, all-shaped, gold-hued, with strong wheels, fashioned of
							Kimsuka and Salmali, light-rolling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bound for the world of life immortal, Surya: make for thy lord a happy
							bridal journey.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rise up from hence: this maiden hath a husband. I laud Visvavasu with
							hymns and homage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seek in her father's home another fair one, and find the portion from
							of old assigned thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rise up from hence, Visvavasu: with reverence we worship thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seek thou another willing maid, and with her husband leave the bride.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							Straight in direction be the path:s, and thornless, whereon our fellows
							travel to the wooing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let Aryaman and Bhaga lead us: perfect, O Gods, the union of the wife
							and husband.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now from the noose of Varuna I free thee, wherewith Most Blessed
							Savitar hath bound thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							In Law's seat, to the world of virtuous action, I give thee up
							uninjured with thy consort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 25: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hence, and not thence, I send these free. I make thee softly fettered
							there.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 25: Line 2
					-
						-
							That, Bounteous Indra, she may live blest in her fortune and her sons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 26
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 26: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let Pusan take thy hand and hence conduct thee; may the two Asvins on
							their car transport thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 26: Line 2
					-
						-
							Go to the house to be the household's mistress and speak as lady ito
							thy gathered people.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 27: Line 1
					-
						-
							Happy be thou and prosper witlh thy children here: be vigilant to rule
							thy household in this home.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 27: Line 2
					-
						-
							Closely unite thy body with this; man, thy lord. So shall ye, full of
							years, address your company.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 28
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 28: Line 1
					-
						-
							Her hue is blue and red: the fienod who clingeth close is driven off.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 28: Line 2
					-
						-
							Well thrive the kinsmen of this bride the husband is bourid fast in
							bonds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 29
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 29: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give thou the woollen robe away: deal treasure to the Brahman priests.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 29: Line 2
					-
						-
							This female fiend hath got her feet, and as a wife attends her lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 30
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 30: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unlovely is his body when it glistens with this wicked fiend,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 30: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time the husband wraps about his limbs the garment of his wife.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 31
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 31: Line 1
					-
						-
							Consumptions, from her people, which follow the bride's resplendent
							train,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 31: Line 2
					-
						-
							These let the Holy Gods again bear to the place from which they came.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 32
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 32: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let not the highway thieves who lie in ambush find the wedded pair.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 32: Line 2
					-
						-
							By pleasant ways let them escape the danger, and let foes depart.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 33
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 33: Line 1
					-
						-
							Signs of good fortune mark the bride come all of you and look at her.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 33: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wish her prosperity, and then return unto your homes again.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 34
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 34: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pungent is this, and bitter this, filled, as it were, with arrow-barbs,
							Empoisoned and.not fit for use.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 34: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Brahman who knows Surya well deserves the garment of the bride.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 35
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 35: Line 1
					-
						-
							The fringe, the cloth that decks her head, and then the triply parted
							robe,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 35: Line 2
					-
						-
							Behold the hues which Surya wears these doth the Brahman purify.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 36
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 36: Line 1
					-
						-
							I take thy hand in mine for happy fortune that thou mayst reach old age
							with me thy husband.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 36: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gods, Aryaman, Bhaga, Savitar, Purandhi, have given thee to be my
							household's mistress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 37
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 37: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Pusan, send her on as most auspicious, her who shall be the sharer of
							my pleasures;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 37: Line 2
					-
						-
							Her who shall twine her loving arms about me, and welcome all my love
							and mine embraces.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 38
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 38: Line 1
					-
						-
							For thee, with bridal train, they, first, escorted Surya to her home.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 38: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give to the husband in return, Agni, the wife with progeny.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 39
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 39: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni hath given the bride again with splendour and with ample life.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 39: Line 2
					-
						-
							Long lived be he who is her lord; a hundred autumns let him live.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 40
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 40: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma obtained her first of all; next the Gandharva was her lord.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 40: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agai was thy third husband: now one bornof woman is thy fourth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 41
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 41: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma to the Gandharva, and to Agni the Gandharva gave:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 41: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Agni hath bestowed on me riches and sons and this my spouse.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 42
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 42: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be ye not parted; dwell ye here reach the full time of human life.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 42: Line 2
					-
						-
							With sons and grandsons sport and play, rejoicing in your own abode.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 43
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 43: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may Prajapati bring children forth to us; may Aryaman adorn us till
							old age come nigh.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 43: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not inauspicious enter thou thy husband's house: bring blessing to our
							bipeds and our quadrupeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 44
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 44: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not evil-eyed, no slayer of thy husband, bring weal to cattle, radiant,
							gentlehearted;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 44: Line 2
					-
						-
							Loving the Gods, delightful, bearing heroes, bring blessing to our
							quadrupeds and bipeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 45
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 45: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Bounteous Indra, make this bride blest in her sons and fortunate.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 45: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe to her ten sons, and make her husband the eleventh man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 46
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 46: Line 1
					-
						-
							Over thy husband's father and thy husband's mother bear full sway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 46: Line 2
					-
						-
							Over the sister of tby lord, over his brothers rule supreme.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 47
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 47: Line 1
					-
						-
							So may the Universal Gods, so may the Waters join our hearts.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 85: Verse 47: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Matarisvan, Dhatar, and Destri together bind us close.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 86
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MEN have abstained from pouring juice they count not Indra as a God.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where at the votary's store my friend Vrsakapi hath drunk his fill.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, heedless passest by the ill Vrsakapi hath wrought;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yet nowhere else thou findest place wherein to drink the Soma juice.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What hath he done to injure thee, this tawny beast Vrsakapi,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							With whom thou art so angry now? What is the votary's foodful store?
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soon may the hound who hunts the boar seize him and bite him in the
							car,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Indra, that Vrsakapi whom thou protectest as a friend, Supreme is
							Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Kapi hath marred the beauteous things, all deftly wrought, that were my
							joy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							In pieces will I rend his head; the sinner's portion sball be woo.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							No Dame hath ampler charms than 1, or greater wealth of love's
							delights.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							None with more ardour offers all her beauty to her lord's embrace.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Mother whose love is quickly wibn, I say what verily will be.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							My,breast, O Mother, and my head and both my hips seem quivering.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dame with the lovely hands and arms, with broad hair-plaits add ample
							hips,
