					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							This noxious creature looks on me as one bereft of hero's love,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yet Heroes for my sons have I, the Maruts' Friend and Indra's Queen.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							From olden time the matron goes to feast and general sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mother of Heroes, Indra's Queen, the rite's ordainer is extolled.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							So have I heard Indrani called most fortunate among these Dames,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							For never shall her Consort die in future time through length of days.
							Supreme is Indra overall.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Never, Indralni, have I joyed without my friend Vrsakapi,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose welcome offering here, made pure with water, goeth to the Gods.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wealthy Vrsakapayi, blest with sons and consorts of thy sons,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra will eat thy bulls, thy dear oblation that effecteth much.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fifteen in number, then, for me a score of bullocks they prepare,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							And I devour the fat thereof: they fill my belly full with food.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like as a bull with pointed horn, loud bellowing amid the herds,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sweet to thine heart, O Indra, is the brew which she who tends thee
							pours. Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra this Vrsakapi hath found a slain wild animal,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dresser, and new-made pan, and knife, and wagon with a load of wood.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Distinguishing the Dasa and the Arya, viewing all, I go.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							I look upon the wise, and drink the simple votary's Soma juice. Supreme
							is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							The desert plains and steep descents, how many leagues in length they
							spread!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Go to the nearest houses, go unto thine home, Vrsakapi. Supreme is
							Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Turn thee again Vrsakapi: we twain will bring thee happiness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou goest homeward on thy way along this path which leads to sleep.
							Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, Indra and Vrsakapi, ye travelled upward to your home,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where was that noisome beast, to whom went it, the beast that troubles
							man? Supreme is Indra over all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							Daughter of Manu, Parsu bare a score of children at a birth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 86: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Her portion verily was bliss although her burthen caused her grief.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 87
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I BALM with oil the mighty Raksas-slayer; to the most famous Friend I
							come for shelter
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enkindled, sharpened by our rites, may Agni protect us in the day and
							night from evil.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Jatavedas with the teeth of iron, enkindled with thy flame attack the
							demons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seize with thy longue the foolish gods' adorers: rend, put within thy
							mouth the raw-flesh caters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Apply thy teeth, the upper and the lower, thou who hast both, enkindled
							and destroying.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Roam also in the air, O King, around us, and with thy jaws assail the
							wicked spirits.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bending thy shafts through sacrifices, Agni, whetting their points with
							song as if with whetstones,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pierce to the heart therewith the Yatudhanas, and break their arms
							uplifed to attack thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pierce through the Yatudhana's skin, O Agni; let the destroying dart
							with fire consume him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rend his joints, Jatavedas, let the cater of flesh, flesh-seeking,
							track his mangled body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where now thou seest Agni Jatavedas, one of these demons standing still
							or roaming,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or flying on those paths in air's midregion, sharpen the shaft and as
							an archer pierce him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tear from the evil spirit, Jatavedas, what he hath seized and with his
							spears hath captured.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blazing before him strike him down, O Agni; let spotted carrion-eating
							kites devour him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here tell this forth, O Agni: whosoever is, he himself, or acteth as, a
							demon,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him grasp, O thou Most Youthful, with thy fuel. to the Mati-seer's eye
							give him as booty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							With keen glance guard the sacrifice, O Agni: thou Sage, conduct it
							onward to the Vasus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let not the fiends, O Man-beholder, harm thee burning against the
							Raksasas to slay them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Look on the fiend mid men, as Man-beholder: rend thou his three
							extremities in pieces.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Demolish with thy flame his ribs, O Agni, the Yatudhana's root destroy
							thou triply.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrice, Agni, let thy noose surround the demon who with his falsehood
							injures Holy Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Loud roaring with thy flame, O Jatavedas, crush him and cast him down
							before the singer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lead thou the worshipper that eye, O Agni, wherewith thou lookest on
							the hoof-armed demon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							With light celestial in Atharvan's manner burn up the foot who ruins
							truth with falsehood.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, what curse the pair this day have uttered, what heated word the
							worshippers have spoken,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Each arrowy taunt sped from the angry spirit,-pierce to the heart
							therewith the Yatudhanas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							With fervent heat exterminate the demons; destroy the fiends with
							burning flame, O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Destroy with fire the foolish gods' adorers; blaze and destrepy the
							insatiable monsters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Gods destroy this day the evil-doer may each hot curse of his
							return and blast him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let arrows pierce the liar in his vitals, and Visva's net enclose the
							Yatudhana.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							The fiend who smears himself with flesh of cattle, with flesh of horses
							and of human bodies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who steals the milch-cow's milk away, O Agni,-tear off the heads of
							such with fiery fury.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							The cow gives milk each year, O Man-regarder: let not the Yatudhana
							ever taste it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							If one would glut him with the biesting, Agni, pierce with thy flame
							his vitals as he meets thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the fiends drink the poison of the cattle; may Aditi cast off the
							evildoers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the God Savitar give them up to ruin, and be their share of plants
							and herbs denied them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, from days of old thou slayest demons: never shall Raksasas in
							fight o'ercome thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Burn up the foolish ones, the flesh-devourers: let none of them escape
							thine heavenly arrow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guard us, O Agni, from above and under, protect us fl-om behind us and
							before us;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							And may thy flames, most fierce and never wasting, glowing with fervent
							heat, consume the sinner.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							From rear, from front, from under, from above us, O King, protect us as
							a Sage with wisdom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard to old age thy friend, O Friend, Eternal: O Agni, as Immortal,
							guard us mortals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							We set thee round us as a fort, victorious Agni, thee a Sage,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of hero lineage, day by day, destroyer of our treacherous foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							Burn with thy poison turned against the treacherous brood of Raksasas,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Agni, with thy sharpened glow, with lances armed with points of
							flame.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 24: Line 1
					-
						-
							Burn thou the paired Kimidins, brun, Agni, the Yatudhana pairs.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 24: Line 2
					-
						-
							I sharpen thee, Infallible, with hymns. O Sage, be vigilant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 25: Line 1
					-
						-
							Shoot forth, O Agni, with thy flame demolish them on every side.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 87: Verse 25: Line 2
					-
						-
							Break thou the Yatudhana's strength, the vigour of the Raksasa.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 88
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							DEAR, ageless sacrificial drink is offered in light-discovering,
							heaven-pervading Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Gods spread forth through his Celestial Nature, that he might bear
							the world up and sustain it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The world was swallowed and concealed in darkness: Agni was born, and
							light became apparent.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Deities, the broad earth, and the heavens, and plants, and waters
							gloried in his friendship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Inspired by Gods who claim our adoration, I now will laud Eternal Lofty
							Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who hath spread abroad the earth with lustre, this heaven, and both
							the worlds, and air's mid-region.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Earliest Priest whom all the Gods accepted, and chose him, and anointed
							him with butter,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							He swiftly made all things that fly, stand, travel, all that hath
							motion, Agni Jatavedas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Because thou, Agni, Jatavedas, stoodest at the world's head with thy
							refulgent splendour,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							We sent thee forth with hymns and songs and praises: thou filledst
							heaven and earth, God meet for worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Head of the world is Agni in the night-time; then, as the Sun, at morn
							springs up and rises.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then to his task goes the prompt Priest foreknowing the wondrous power
							of Gods who must be honoured.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lovely is he who, kindled in his greatness, hath shone forth, seated in
							the heavens, refulgent.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With resonant hymns all Gods who guard our bodies have offered up
							oblation in this Agni.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							First the Gods brought the hymnal into being; then they engendered
							Agni, then oblation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He was their satrifice that guards our bodies: him the heavens know,
							the earth, the waters know him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, Agni, whom the Gods have generated, in whom they offered up all
							worlds and creatures,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He with his bright glow heated earth and heaven, urging himself right
							onward in his grandeur.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then by the laud the Gods engendered Agni in heaven, who fills both
							worlds through strength and vigour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							They made him to appear in threefold essence: he ripens plants of every
							form and nature.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the Gods, whose due is worship, set him as Surya, Son of
							Aditi, in heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the Pair, ever wandering, sprang to being, all creatures that
							existed looked upon them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							For all the world of life the Gods made Agni Vaisvanara to be the days'
							bright Banner,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who hath spread abroad the radiant Mornings, and, coming with his
							light, unveils the darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The wise and holy Deities engendered Agni Vaisvanara whom age ne'er
							touches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Ancient Star that wanders on for ever, lofty and. strong, Lord of
							the Living Being.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							We call upon the Sage with holy verses, Agni Vaisvanara the
							ever-beaming,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who hath surpassed both heaven and earth in greatness: lie is a God
							below, a God above us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							I have heard mention of two several pathways, ways of the Fathers and
							of Gods and mortals.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							On these two paths each moving creature travels, each thing between the
							Father and the Mother.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							These two united paths bear him who journeys born from the head and
							pondered with the spirit
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							He stands directed to all things existing, hasting, unresting in his
							fiery splendour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							Which of us twain knows where they speak together, upper and lower of
							the two rite-leaders?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our friends have helped to gather our assembly. They came to sacrifice;
							who will announce it?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							How many are the Fires and Suns in number? What is the number of the
							Dawns and Waters?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not jestingly I speak to you, O Fathers. Sages, I ask you this for
							information.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							As great as is the fair-winged Morning's presence to him who dwells
							beside us, matarisvan!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 88: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is what the Brahman does when he approaches to sacrifice and sits below
							the Hotar.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 89
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I WILL extol the most heroic Indra who with his might forced earth and
							sky asunder;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who hath filled all with width as man's Upholder, surpassing floods and
							rivers in his greatness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Surya is he: throughout the wide expanses shall Indra turn him, swift
							as car-wheels, hither,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a stream resting not but ever active he hath destroyed, with
							light, the blackhued darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him I sing a holy prayer, incessant new, matchless, common to the
							earth and heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who marks, as they were backs, all living creatures: ne'er doth he fail
							a friend, the noble Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will send forth my songs in flow unceasing, like water from the
							ocean's depth, to Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who to his car on both its sides securely hath fixed the earth and
							heaven as with an axle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rousing with draughts, the Shaker, rushing onward, impetuous, very
							strong, armed as with arrows
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Is Soma; forest trees and all the bushes deceive not Indra with their
							offered likeness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Soma hath flowed to him whom naught can equal, the earth, the heavens,
							the firmament, the mountains,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When heightened in his ire his indignation shatters the firm and breaks
							the strong in pieces.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							As an axe fells the tree so be slew Vrtra, brake down the strongholds
							and dug out the rivers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He cleft the mountain like a new-made pitcher. Indra brought forth the
							kine with his Companions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wise art thou, Punisher of guilt, O Indra. The sword lops limbs, thou
							smitest down the sinner,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The men who injure, as it were a comrade, the lofty Law of Varuna and
							Mitra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men who lead evil lives, who break agreements, and injure Varuna,
							Aryaman and Mitra,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Against these foes, O Mighty Indra, sharpen, as furious death, thy Bull
							of fiery colour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra is Sovran Lord of Earth and Heaven, Indra is Lord of waters and
							of mountains.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra is Lord of prosperers and sages Indra must be invoked in rest and
							effort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vaster than days and nights, Giver of increase, vaster than firmament
							and flood of ocean,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vaster than bounds of earth and wind's extension, vaster than rivers
							and our lands is Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forward, as herald of refulgent Morning, let thine insatiate arrow fly,
							O Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							And pierce, as 'twere a stone launched forth from heaven, with hottest
							blaze the men who love deception.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, verily, the moons, the mountains followed, the tall trees followed
							and the plants and herbage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yearning with love both Worlds approached, the Waters waited on Indra
							when he first had being.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Where was the vengeful dart when thou, O Indra, clavest the demon ever
							beat on outrage?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							When fiends lay there upon the ground extended like cattle in the place
							of immolation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Those who are set in enmity against us, the Oganas, O Indra, waxen
							mighty,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let blinding darkness follow those our fbemen, while these shall have
							bright shining nights to light them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							May plentiful libations of the people, and singing Rsis' holy prayers
							rejoice thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hearing with love this common invocation, come unto us, pass by all
							those who praise thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, thus may we be made partakers of thy new favours that shall
							bring us profit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Singing with love, may we the Visvamitras win daylight even now through
							thee, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Call we on Maghavan, auspicious Indra, best hero in the fight where
							spoil is gathered,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 89: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Strong who listens, who gives aid in battles, who slays the Vrtras,
							wins and gathers riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 90
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							A THOUSAND heads hath Purusa, a thousand eyes, a thousand feet.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							On every side pervading earth he fills a space ten fingers wide.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Purusa is all that yet hath been and all that is to be;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Lord of Immortality which waxes greater still by food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							So mighty is his greatness; yea, greater than this is Purusa.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							All creatures are one-fourth of him, three-fourths eternal life in
							heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							With three-fourths Purusa went up: onefourth of him again was here.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thence he strode out to every side over what cats not and what cats.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							From him Viraj was born; again Purusa from Viraj was born.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							As soon as he was born he spread eastward and westward o'er the earth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							When Gods prepared the sacrifice with Purusa as their offering,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Its oil was spring, the holy gift was autumn; summer was the wood.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							They balmed as victim on the grass Purusa born in earliest time.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							With him the Deities and all Sadhyas and Rsis sacrificed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							From that great general sacrifice the dripping fat was gathered up.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He formed the creatures of-the air, and animals both wild and tame.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							From that great general sacrifice Rcas and Sama-hymns were born:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therefrom were spells and charms produced; the Yajus had its birth from
							it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							From it were horses born, from it all cattle with two rows of teeth:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							From it were generated kine, from it the goats and sheep were born.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							When they divided Purusa how many portions did they make?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							What do they call his mouth, his arms? What do they call his thighs and
							feet?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Brahman was his mouth, of both his arms was the Rajanya made.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							His thighs became the Vaisya, from his feet the Sudra was produced.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Moon was gendered from his mind, and from his eye the Sun had
							birth;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra and Agni from his mouth were born, and Vayu from his breath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Forth from his navel came mid-air the sky was fashioned from his head
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Earth from his feet, and from his car the regions. Thus they formed the
							worlds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Seven fencing-sticks had he, thrice seven layers of fuel were prepared,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the Gods, offering sacrifice, bound, as their victim, Purusa.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gods, sacrificing, sacrificed the victim these were the carliest holy
							ordinances.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 90: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mighty Ones attained the height of heaven, there where the Sidhyas,
							Gods of old, are dwelling.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 91
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							BRISK, at the place of Ila, hymned by men who wake, our own familiar
							Friend is kindled in the house;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hotar of all oblation, worthy of our choice, Lord, beaming, trusty
							friend to one who loveth him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, excellent in glory, guest in every house, finds like a swift-winged
							bird a home in every tree.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Benevolent to men, he scorns no living man: Friend to the tribes of men
							he dwells with every tribe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Most sage with insight, passing skilful with thy powers art thou, O
							Agni, wise with wisdom, knowing all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As Vasu, thou alone art Lord of all good things, of all the treasures
							that the heavens and earth produce.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Foreknowing well, O Agni, thou in Ila's place hast occupied thy regular
							station balmed with oil.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Marked are thy comings like the comings of the Dawns, the rays of him
							who shineth spotless as the Sun.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy glories are, as lightnings from the rainy cloud, marked, many-hued,
							like heralds of the Dawns' approach,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, loosed to wander over plants and forest trees, thou crammest by
							thyself thy food into thy mouth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, duly coming as their germ, have plants received: this Agni have
							maternal Waters brought to life.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							So in like manner do the forest trees and plants bear him within them
							and produce him evermore.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, sped and urged by wind, thou spreadest thee abroad, swift
							piercing through thy food according to thy will,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy never-ceasing blazes, longing to consume, like men on chariots,
							Agni, strive on every side.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, the Hotar-priest who fills the assembly full, Waker of knowledge,
							chief Controller of the thought,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him, yea, none other than thyself, doth man elect at sacrificial
							offerings great and small alike.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here, Api, the arrangers, those attached to thee, elect thee as their
							Priest in sacred gatherings,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When men with strewn clipt grass and sacrificial gifts offer thee
							entertainment, piously inclined.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thine is the Herald's task and Cleanser's duly timed; Leader art thou,
							and Kindler for the pious man.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art Director, thou the ministering Priest: thou art the Brahman,
							Lord and Master in our home.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							When mortal man presents to thee Immortal God, Agni, his fuel or his
							sacrificial gift,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then thou art his Adhvaryu, Hotar, messenger, callest the Gods and
							orderest the sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							From us these hymns in concert have gone forth to him, these. holy
							words, these Rcas, songs and eulogies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eager for wealth, to Jatavedas fain for wealth: when they have waxen
							strong they please their Strengthener.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							This newest eulogy will I speak forth to him, the Ancient One who loves
							it. May he hear our voice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							May it come near his heart and make it stir with love, as a fond
							well-dressed matron clings about her lord.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							He in whom horses, bulls, oxen, and barren cows, and rams, when duly
							set apart, are offered up,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							To Agni, Soma-sprinkled, drinker of sweet juice, Disposer, with my
							heart I bring a fair hymn forth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Into thy mouth is poured the offering, Agni, as Soma into cup, oil into
							ladle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 91: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vouchsafe us wealth. strength-winning, blest with heroes, wealth lofty,
							praised by men, and full of splendour.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 92
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I PRAISE your Charioteer of sacrifice, the Lord of men, Priest of the
							tribes, refulgent, Guest of night.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blazing amid dry plants, snatching amid the green, the Strong, the Holy
							Herald hath attained to heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Him, Agni, Gods and men have made their chief support, who drinks the
							fatness and completes the sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With kisses they caress the Grandson of the Red, like the swift ray of
							light, the Household Priest of Dawn.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, we discriminate his and the niggard's ways: his branches evermore
							are sent forth to consume.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							When his terrific flames have reached the Immortal's world, then men
							remember and extol the Heavenly Folk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For then the net of Law, Dyaus, and the wide expanse, Earth, Worship,
							and Devotion meet for highest praise,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Varuna, Indra, Mitra were of one accord, and Savitar and Bhaga, Lords
							of holy might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Onward, with ever-roaming Rudra, speed the floods: over Aramati the
							Mighty have they run.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							With them Parijman, moving round his vast domain, loud bellowing,
							bedews all things that are within.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Straightway the Rudras, Maruts visiting all men, Falcons of Dyaus,
							home-dwellers with the Asura,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman look on with these, and the swift-moving Indra
							with swift-moving Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Indra have they found enjoyment, they who toil, in the light's
							beauty, in the very Strong One's strength;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							The singers who in men's assemblies forged for him, according to his
							due, his friend the thunderbolt.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even the Sun's Bay Coursers hath lie held in check: each one fears
							Indra as the mightiest of all.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unhindered, from the air's vault thunders day by day the loud
							triumphant breathing of the fearful Bull.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							With humble adoration show this day your song of praise to mighty
							Rudra, Ruler of the brave:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							With whom, the Eager Ones, going their ordered course, he comes from
							heaven Self-bright, auspicious, strong to guard.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							For these have spread abroad the fame of human kind, the Bull Brhaspati
							and Soma's brotherhood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Atharvan first by sacrifices made men sure: through skill the Bhrgus
							were esteemed of all as Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							For these, the Earth and Heaven with their abundant seed, four-bodied
							Narasmsa, Yama, Aditi,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							God Tvastar Wealth-bestower, the Rbhuksanas, Rodasi, Maruts, Visnu,
							claim and merit praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							And may he too give car, the Sage, from far away, the Dragon of the
							Deep, to this our yearning call.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye Sun and Moon who dwell in heaven and move in turn, and with your
							thought, O Earth and Sky, observe this well.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dear to all Gods, may Pasan guard the ways we go, the Waters' child and
							Vayu help us to success.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sing lauds for your great bliss to Wind, the breath of all: ye Asvins
							prompt to hear, hear this upon your way.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							With hymns of praise we sing him who is throned as Lord over these
							fearless tribes, the Self-resplendent One.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							We praise Night's youthful Lord benevolent to men, the foeless One, the
							free, with all celestial Dames.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							By reason of his birth here Angiras first sang: the pressing-stones
							upraised bebeld the sacrifice-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 92: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							The stones through which the Sage became exceeding vast, and the sharp
							axe obtains in fight the beauteous place.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 93
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MIGHTY are ye, and far-extended, Heaven and Earth: both Worlds are
							evermore to us like two young Dames.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guard us thereby from stronger foe; guard us hereby to give us
							strength.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							In each succeeding sacrifice that mortal honoureth the Gods,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who, most widely known and famed for happiness, invitetb them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye who are Rulers over all, great is your sovran power as Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye all possess all majesty: all must be served in sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							These are the joyous Kings of Immortality, Parijman, Mitra, Aryaman,
							and Varuna.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							What else is Rudra, praised of men? the Maruts, Bhaga, Pusana?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come also to our dwelling, Lords of ample wealth, common partakers of
							our waters, Sun and Moon,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the great Dragon of the Deep hath settled down upon their floors.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							And let the Asvins, Lords of splendour, set us free,- both Gods, and,
							with their Laws, Mitra and Varuna.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through woes, as over desert lands, he speeds to ample opulence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, let the Asvins Twain he gracious unto us, even Rudras, and all
							Gods, Bhaga, Rathaspati;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Parijman, Rbhu, Vaja, O Lords of all wealth Rbhuksanas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prompt is Rbhuksan, prompt the worshipper's strong drink: may thy fleet
							Bay Steeds, thine who sperdest on, approach.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not mans but God's is sacrifice whose psalm is unassailable.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							O God Savitar, harmed by none, lauded, give us a place among wealthy
							princes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							With his Car-steeds at once 'hath our Indra guided the reins and the
							car of these men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							To these men present here, O Heaven and Earth, to us grant lofty fame
							extending over all mankind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give us a steed to win us strength, a steed with wealth for victory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							This speaker, Indra-for thou art our Friend-wherever he may be, guard
							thou, Victor! for help, ever for help
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy wisdom, Vasu! prosper him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							So have they strengthened this mine hymn which seems to take its bright
							path to the Sun, and reconciles the men:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thus forms a carpenter the yoke of horses, not to be displaced.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whose chariot-seat hath come again laden with wealth and bright with
							gold,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lightly, with piercing ends, as 'twere two ranks of heroes ranged for
							fight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							This to Duhsima Prthavana have I sung, to Vena, Rama, to the nobles,
							and the King.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							They yoked five hundred, and their love of us was famed upon their way.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Besides, they showed us seven -and-seventy horses here.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 93: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Tanva at once displayed his gift, Parthya at once displayed his gift;
							and straightway Mayava showed his.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 94
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET these speak loudly forth; let us speak out aloud: to the loud
							speaking Pressing-stones address the speech;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, rich with Soma juice, Stones of the mountain, ye, united, swift
							to Indra bring the sound of praise.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							They speak out like a hundred, like a thousand men: they cry aloud to
							us with their green-tinted mouths,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							While, pious Stones, they ply their task with piety, and, even before
							the Hotar, taste the offered food.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Loudly they speak, for they have found the savoury meath: they make a
							humming sound over the meat prepared.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							As they devour the branch of the Red-coloured Tree, these, the
							well-pastured Bulls, have uttered bellowings.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							They cry aloud, with strong exhilarating drink, calling on Indra now,
							for they have found the meath.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bold, with the sisters they have danced, embraced by them, making the
							earth reecho with their ringing sound.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Eagles have sent forth their cry aloft in heaven; in the sky's
							vault the dark impetuous ones have danced.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then downward to the nether stone's fixt place they sink, and, splendid
							as the Sun, effuse their copious stream.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like strong ones drawing, they have put forth all their strength: the
							Bulls, harnessed together, bear the chariot-poles.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When they have bellowed, panting, swallowing their food, the sound of
							their loud snorting is like that of steeds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							To these who have ten workers and a tenfold girth, to these who have
							ten yoke-straps and ten binding thongs,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							To these who bear ten reins, the eternal, sing ye praise, to these who
							bear ten car-poles, ten when they are yoked.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Stones with ten conductors, rapid in their course, with lovely
							revolution travel round and round.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							They have been first to drink the flowing Soma juice, first to enjoy
							the milky fluid of the stalk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Soma-eaters kiss Indra's Bay-coloured Steeds: draining. the stalk
							they sit upon the ox's hide.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra, when he hath drunk Soma-nicath drawn by them, waxes in strength,
							is famed, is mighty as a Bull.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Strong is your stalk; ye, verily, never shall be harmed; ye have
							refreshment, ye are ever satisfied.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fair are ye, as it were, through splendour of his wealth, his in whose
							sacrifice, O Stones, ye find delight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bored deep, but not pierced through with holes, are ye, O Stones, not
							loosened, never weary, and exempt from death,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eternal, undiseased, moving in sundry ways, unthirsting, full of
							fatness, void of all desire.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your fathers, verily, stand firm from age to age: they, loving rest,
							are not dissevered from their seat.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Untouched by time, ne'er lacking green plants and green trees, they
							with their voice have caused the heavens and earth to hear.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							This, this the Stones proclaim, what time they are disjoined, and when
							with ringing sounds they move and drink the balm.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like tillers of the ground when they are sowing seed, they mix the
							Soma, nor, devouring, minish it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							They have raised high their voice for juice, for sacrifice, striking
							the Mother earth as though they danced thereon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 94: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							So loose thou too his thought who hath effused the sap, and let the
							Stones which we are honouring be disjoined.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 95
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ho there, my consort! Stay, thou fierce-souled lady, and let us reason
							for a while together.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Such thoughts as these of ours, while yet unspoken in days gone by have
							never brought us comfort.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							What am I now to do with this thy saying? I have gone from thee like
							the first of Mornings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pururavas, return thou to thy dwelling: I, like the wind, am difficult
							to capture.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like a shaft sent for glory from the quiver, or swift-steed winning
							cattle winning hundreds.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The lightning seemed to flash, as cowards planned it. The minstrels
							bleated like a lamb in trouble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Giving her husband's father life and riches, from the near dwelling,
							when her lover craved her,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							She sought the home wherein she found her pleasure, accepting day and
							night her lord's embraces.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thrice in the day didst thou embrace thy consort, though coldly she
							received thy fond caresses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							To thy desires, Pururavas, I yielded: so wast thou king, O hero, of my
							body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The maids Sujirni, Sreni, Sumne-api, Charanyu, Granthini, and
							Hradecaksus,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							These like red kine have hastened forth, the bright ones, and like
							milch-cows have lowed in emulation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							While he was born the Dames sate down together, the Rivers with free
							kindness gave him nurture;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							And then, Pururavas, the Gods increased thee for mighty battle, to
							destroy the Dasyus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When I, a mortal, wooed to mine embraces these heavenly nymphs who laid
							aside their raiment,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like a scared snake they fled from me in terror, like chariot horses
							when the car has touched them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, loving these Immortal Ones, the mortal hath converse with the
							nymphs as they allow him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like swans they show the beauty of their bodies, like horses in their
							play they bite and nibble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							She who flashed brilliant as the falling lightning brought me delicious
							presents from the waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Now from the flood be born a strong young hero May Uruvasi prolong her
							life for ever
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy birth hath made me drink from earthly milch-kine: this power,
							Pururavas, hast thou vouchsafed me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							I knew, and, warned thee, on that day. Thou wouldst not hear me. What
							sayest thou, when naught avails thee?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							When will the son be born and seek his father? Mourner-like, will he
							weep when first he knows him?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who shall divide the accordant wife and husband, while fire is shining
							with thy consort's parents?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							I will console him when his tears are falling: he shall not weep and
							cry for care that blesses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							That which is thine, between us, will I send thee. Go home again, thou
							fool;.thou hast not won me.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy lover shall flee forth this day for ever, to seek, without return,
							the farthest distance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then let his bed be in Destruction's bosom, and there let fierce
							rapacious wolves devour him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Nay, do not die, Pururavas, nor vanish: let not the evil-omened wolves
							devour thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							With women there can be no lasting friendship: hearts of hyenas are the
							hearts of women.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							When amid men in altered shape I sojourned, and through four autumns
							spent the nights among them,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							I tasted once a day a drop of butter; and even now with that am I am
							contented.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							I, her best love, call Urvasi to meet me, her who fills air and
							measures out the region.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let the gift brought by piety approach thee. Turn thou to me again: my
							heart is troubled.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus speak these Gods to thee, O son of Ila: As death hath verily got
							thee for his subject,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 95: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy sons shall serve the Gods with their oblation, and thou, moreover,
							shalt rejoice in Svarga.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 96
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							In the great synod will I laud thy two Bay Steeds: I prize the sweet
							strong drink of thee the Warrior-God,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							His who pours lovely oil as 'twere with yellow drops. Let my songs
							enter thee whose form hath golden tints.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye who in concert sing unto the goldhued place, like Bay Steeds driving
							onward to the heavenly seat,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							For Indra laud ye strength allied with Tawny Steeds, laud him whom cows
							content as 'twere with yellow drops.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							His is that thunderbolt, of iron, goldenhued, gold-coloured, very dear,
							and yellow in his arms;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bright with strong teeth, destroying with its tawny rage. In Indra are
							set fast all forms of golden hue.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							As if a lovely ray were laid upon the sky, the golden thunderbolt
							spread out as in a race.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That iron bolt with yellow jaw smote Ahi down. A thousand flames had he
							who bore the tawny-hued.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, thou, when praised by men who sacrificed of old. hadst pleasure
							in their lauds, O Indra golden-haired.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							All that befits thy song of praise thou welcornest, the perfect
							pleasant gift, O Golden-hued from birth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							These two dear Bays bring hither Indra on his car, Thunder-armed,
							joyous, meet for laud, to drink his fill.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Many libations flow for him who loveth them: to Indra have the
							gold-hued Soma juices run.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tle gold-hued drops have flowed to gratify his wish: the yellow dro s
							have urged the swift Bays to the Strong.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who speeds on with Bay Steeds even as he lists hath satisfied his
							longing for the golden drops.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							At the swift draught the Soma-drinker waxed in might, the Iron One with
							yellow beard and yellow hair.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He, Lord of Tawny Coursers, Lord of fleet-foot Mares, will bear his Bay
							Steeds safely over all distress.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							His yellow-coloured jaws, like ladles move apart, what time, for
							strength, he makes the yellow-tinted stir,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, while the bowl stands there, he grooms his Tawny Steeds, when he
							hath drunk strong drink, the sweet juice that he loves.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, to the Dear One's seat in homes of heaven and earth the Bay
							Steeds' Lord hath whinnied like a horse for food.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then the great wish hath seized upon him mightily, and the Beloved One
							hath gained high power of life,
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, comprehending with thy might the earth and heaven, acceptest the
							dear hymn for ever new and new.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Asura, disclose thou and make visible the Cow's beloved home to the
							bright golden Sun.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, let the eager wishes of the folk bring thee, delightful,
							golden-visored, on thy car,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							That, pleased with sacrifice wherein ten fingers toil, thou mayest, at
							the feast, drink of our offered meath.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Juices aforetime, Lord of Bays, thou drankest; and thine especially is
							this libation.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 96: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gladden thee, Indra, with the meath-rich Soma: pour it down ever,
							Mighty One! within thee.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 97
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							HERBS that sprang up in time of old, three ages earlier than the Gods,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Of these, whose hue is brown, will I declare the hundred powers and
							seven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, Mothers, have a hundred homes, yea, and a thousand are your
							growths.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Do ye who have a thousand powers free this my patient from disease.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be glad and joyful in the Plants, both blossoming and bearing fruit,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Plants that will lead us to success like mares who conquer in the race.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Plants, by this name I speak to you, Mothers, to you the Goddesses:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Steed, cow, and garment may I win, win back thy very self, O man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Holy Fig tree is your home, your mansion is the Parna tree:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Winners of cattle shali ye be if ye regain for me this man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who hath store of Herbs at hand like Kings amid a crowd of men,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Physician is that sage's name, fiend-slayer, chaser of disease.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Herbs rich in Soma, rich in steeds, in nourishments, in strengthening
							power,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							All these have I provided here, that this man may be whole again.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The healing virtues of the Plants stream forth like cattle from the
							stall,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Plants that shall win me store of wealth, and save thy vital breath, O
							man.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Reliever is your mother's name, and hence Restorers are ye called.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rivers are ye with wings that fly: keep far whatever brings disease.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Over all fences have they passed, as steals a thief into the fold.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Plants have driven from the frame whatever malady was there.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, bringing back the vanished strength, I hold these herbs within my
							hand,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							The spirit of disease departs ere he can seize upon the life.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							He through whose frame, O Plants, ye creep member by member, joint by
							joint,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							From him ye drive away disease like some strong arbiter of strife.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fly, Spirit of Disease, begone, with the blue jay and kingfisher.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Fly with the wind's impetuousspeed, vanish together with the storm.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 14: Line 1
					-
						-
							Help every one the other, lend assistance each of you to each,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 14: Line 2
					-
						-
							All of you be accordant, give furtherance to this speech of mine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 15: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let fruitful Plants, and fruitless, those that blossom, and the
							blossomless,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 15: Line 2
					-
						-
							Urged onward by Brhaspati, release us from our pain and grief;
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 16: Line 1
					-
						-
							Release me from the curse's plague and woe that comes from Varuna;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 16: Line 2
					-
						-
							Free me from Yama's fetter, from sin and offence against the Gods.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 17: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time, descending from the sky, the Plants flew earthward, thus
							they spake:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 17: Line 2
					-
						-
							No evil shall befall the man whom while he liveth we pervade,
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 18: Line 1
					-
						-
							Of all the many Plants whose King is, Soma, Plants of hundred forms,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 18: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art the Plant most excellent, prompt to the wish, sweet to the
							heart.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 19: Line 1
					-
						-
							O all ye various Herbs whose King is Soma, that o'erspread the earth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 19: Line 2
					-
						-
							Urged onward by Brhaspati, combine your virtue in this Plant.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 20: Line 1
					-
						-
							Unharmed be he who digs you up, unharmed the man for whom I dig:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 20: Line 2
					-
						-
							And let no malady attack biped or quadruped of ours.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 21: Line 1
					-
						-
							All Plants that hear this speech, and those that have departed far
							away,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 21: Line 2
					-
						-
							Come all assembled and confer your healing power upon this Herb.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 22: Line 1
					-
						-
							With Soma as their Sovran Lord the Plants hold colloquy and say:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 22: Line 2
					-
						-
							O King, we save from death the man whose cure a Brahman undertakes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 23: Line 1
					-
						-
							Most excellent of all art thou, O Plant thy vassals are the trees.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 97: Verse 23: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him be subject to our power, the man who seeks to injure us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 98
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COME, be thou Mitra, Varuna, or Pusan, come, O Brhaspati, to mine
							oblation:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With Maruts, Vasus, or Adityas, make thou Parjanya pour for Santanu his
							rain-drops.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The God, intelligent, the speedy envoy whom thou hast sent hath come to
							me, Devapi:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Address thyself to me and turn thee hither within thy lips will I put
							brilliant language.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Within my mouth, Brhaspati, deposit speech lucid, vigorous, and free
							from weakness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thereby to win for Santanu the rain-fall. The meath-rich drop from
							heaven hath passed within it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the sweet drops descend on us, O Indra: give us enough to lade a
							thousand wagons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sit to thy Hotar task; pay worship duly, and serve the Gods, Devapi,
							with oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Knowing the God's good-will, Devapi, Rsi, the son of Rstisena, sate as
							Hotar.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							He hath brought down from heaven's most lofty summit the ocean of the
							rain, celestial waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Gathered together in that highest ocean, the waters stood by deities
							obstructed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							They burried down set free by Arstisena, in gaping clefts, urged onward
							by Devapi.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							When as chief priest for Santanu, Devapi, chosen for Hotar's duty,
							prayed beseeching,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Graciously pleased Brhaspati vouchsafed him a voice that reached the
							Gods and won the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni whom Devapi Arstisena, the mortal man, hath kindled in his
							glory,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Joying in him with all the Gods together, urge on the sender of the
							rain, Parjanya.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							All ancient Rsis with their songs approached thee, even thee, O
							Much-invoked, at sacrifices.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							We have provided wagon-loads in thousands: come to the solemn rite,
							Lord of Red Horses.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							The wagon-loads, the nine-and-ninety thousand, these have been offered
							up to thee, O Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hero, with these increase thy many bodies, and, stimulated, send us
							rain from heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give thou these ninety thousand loads, O Agni, to Indra, to the Bull,
							to be his portion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Knowing the paths which Deities duly travel, set mid the Gods in heaven
							Aulana also.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, drive afar our foes, our troubles chase malady away and wicked
							demons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 98: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							From this air-ocean, from the lofty heavens, send down on us a mighty
							flood of waters.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 99
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHAT Splendid One, Loud-voiced, Farstriding, dost thou, well knowing,
							urge us to exalt with praises?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							What give we him? When his might dawned, he fashioned the Vrtra-slaying
							bolt, and sent us waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							He goes to end his work with lightning flashes: wide is the seat his
							Asura glory gives him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							With his Companions, not without his Brother, he quells Saptatha's
							magic devices.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							On most auspicious path he goes to battle he toiled to win heaven's
							light, full fain to gain it;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He seized the hundred-gated castle's treasure by craft, unchecked, and
							slew the lustful demons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fighting for kine, the prize of war, and I roaming among the berd be
							brings the young streams hither,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Where, footless, joined, without a car to bear them, with jars for
							steeds, they pour their flood like butter.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bold, unsolicited for wealth, with Rudras he came, the Blameless,
							having left his dwelling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Came, seized the food of Vamra and his consort, and left the couple
							weeping and unsheltered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of the dwelling, he subdued the demon who roared aloud, six-eyed
							and triple-headed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Trta, made stronger by the might he lent him, struck down the boar with
							shaft whose point was iron.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He raised himself on high and shot his arrow against the guileful and
							oppressive foeman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strong, glorious, manliest, for us he shattered the forts of Nabus when
							he slew the Dasyus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, like a cloud that rains upon the pasture, hath found for us the way
							to dwell in safety.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the Hawk comes in body to the Soma, armed with his iron claws he
							slays the Dasyus.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							He with his potent Friends gave up the mighty, gave gusnia up to Kutsa
							for affliction.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He led the lauded Kavi, he delivered Atka as prey to him and to his
							heroes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, with his Gods who love mankind, the Wondrous, giving like Varuna
							who works with magic,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Was known, yet young as guardian of the seasons; and he quelled Araru,
							four-footed dernon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through lauds of him hath Ausija Rjisvan burst, with the Mighty's aid,
							the stall of Pipru.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							When the saint pressed the juice and shone as singer, he seized the
							forts and with his craft subdued them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, swiftly Asura, for exaltation, hath the great Vamraka come nigh to
							Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 99: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							He will, when supplicated, bring him blessing: he hath brought all,
							food, strength, a happy dwelling.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 100
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							Be, like thyself, O Indra, strong for our delight: here lauded, aid us,
							Maghavan, drinker of the juice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savitar with the Gods protect us: hear ye Twain. We ask for freedom and
							complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bring swift, for offering, the snare that suits the time, to the
							pure-drinker Vayu, roaring as he goes,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							To him who hath approached the draught of shining milk. We ask for
							freedom and complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Savitar the God send us full life, to each who sacrifices, lives
							aright and pours the juice
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							That we with simple hearts may wait upon the Gods. We ask for freedom
							and complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra evermore be gracious unto us, and may King Soma meditate our
							happiness,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even as men secure the comfort of a friend. We ask for freedom and
							complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra hath given the body with its song and strength: Brhaspati, thou
							art the lengthener of life.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The sacrifice is Manu, Providence, our Sire. We ask for freedom and
							complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra possesseth might celestial nobly formed: the singer in the hotise
							is Agni, prudent Sage.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							lie is the sacrifice in synod, fair, most near. We ask for freedom and
							complete felicity,
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not often have we sinned against you secretly, nor, Vasus, have we
							openly provoked the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Not one of its, ye Gods, hath worn an alien shape. We ask for freedom
							and complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Savitar remove from us our malady, and may the Mountains keep it
							far away from where
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The press-stone as it sheds the meath rings loudly forth. We ask for
							freedom and complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Vasus, let the stone, the presser stand erect: avert all enmities
							and keep them far remote.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our guard to be adored is Savitar this God. We ask for freedom and
							complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eat strength and fatness in the pasture, kine, who are balmed at the
							reservoir and at the seat of Law.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							So let your body be our body's medicine. We ask for freedom and
							complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							The singer fills the spirit: all mens, love hath he. Indra takes kindly
							care of those who pour the juice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							For his libation is the heavenly udder full. We ask for freedom and
							complete felicity.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Wondrous thy spirit-filling light, triumpliant; thy hosts save from
							decay and are resistless.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 100: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							The pious votary by straightest pathway speeds to possess the best of
							all the cattle.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 101
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WAKE with one mind, my friends, and kindle Agni, ye who are many and
							who dwell together.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni and Dadhikras and Dawn the Goddess, you, Gods with Indra, I call
							down to help us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Make pleasant hymns, spin out your songs and praises: build ye a ship
							equipped with oars for transport.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Prepare the implements, make all things ready, and let the sacrifice,
							my friends, go forward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lay on the yokes, and fasten well the traces: formed is the furrow, sow
							the seed within it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through song may we find bearing fraught with plenty: near to the
							ripened grain approach the sickle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Wise, through desire of bliss from Gods, the skilful bind the traces fast,
						And lay the yokes on either side.
					-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Arrange the buckets in their place securely fasten on the straps.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							We will pour forth the well that hath a copious stream, fair-flowing
							well that never fails.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							I pour the water from the well with pails prepared and goodly straps,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Unfailing, full, with plenteous stream.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Refresh the horses, win the prize before you: equip a chariot fraught
							with happy fortune.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Pour forth the well with stone wheel, wooden buckets, the drink of
							heroes, with the trough for armour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prepare the cow-stall, for there drink your heroes: stitch ye the coats
							of armour, wide and many.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Make iron forts, secure from all assailants let not your pitcher leak:
							stay it securely.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hither, for help, I turn the holy heavenly mind of you the Holy Gods,
							that longs for sacrifice.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							May it pour milk for us, even as a stately cow who, having sought the
							pasture, yields a thousand streams.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pour golden juice within the wooden vessel: with stone-made axes
							fashion ye and form it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Embrace and compass it with tenfold girdle, and to both chariot-poles
							attach the car-horse.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Between both poles the car-horse goes pressed closely, as in his
							dwelling moves the doubly-wedded.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lay in the wood the Soviran of the Forest, and sink the well although
							ye do not dig it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra is he, O men, who gives us happiness: sport, urge the giver of
							delight to win us strength
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 101: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring quickly down, O priests, hither to give us aid, to drink the
							Soma, Indra Son of Nistigri.
						-
