				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							In hope of victory that bull was harnessed: Kesi the driver urged him
							on with shouting.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As he ran swiftly with the car behind him his lifted heels pressed
							close on Mudgalani.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Deftly for him he stretched the car-pole forward, guided the bull
							thereto and firmly yoked him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra vouchsafed the lord of cows his favour: with mighty steps the
							buffalo ran onward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Touched by the goad the shaggy beast went nobly, bound to the pole by
							the yoke's thong of leather.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Performing deeds of might for many people, he, looking on the cows,
							gained strength and vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here look upon this mace, this bull's companion, now lying midway on
							the field of battle.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Therewith hath Mudgala in ordered contest won for cattle for himself, a
							hundred thousand.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Far is the evil: who hath here beheld it? Hither they bring the bull
							whom they are yoking..
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							To this they give not either food or water. Reaching beyond the pole it
							gives directions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like one forsaken, she hath found a husband, and teemed as if her
							breast were full and flowing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							With swiftly-racing chariot may we conquer, and rich and blessed be our
							gains in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, art the mark whereon the eyes of all life rest, when thou,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 102: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							A Bull who drivest with thy bull, wilt win the race together with thy
							weakling friend.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 103
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SWIFT, rapidly striking, like a bull who sharpens his horns, terrific,
							stirring up the people,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With eyes that close not, bellowing, Sole Hero, Indra. subdued at once
							a hundred armies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With him loud-roaring, ever watchful, Victor, bold, hard to overthrow,
							Rouser of battle,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Indra. the Strong, whose hand bears arrows, conquer, ye warriors, now,
							now vanquish in the combat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							He rules with those who carry shafts and quivers, Indra who with his
							band rings hosts together,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Foe-conquering, strong of arm, the Soma-drinker, with mighty bow,
							shooting with well-laid arrows.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaspati, fly with thy chariot hither, slayer of demons, driving off
							our foemen.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be thou protector of our cars, destroyer, victor in battle, breaker-up
							of armies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Conspicuous by thy strength, firm, foremost fighter, mighty and fierce,
							victorious, all-subduing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Son of Conquest, passing men and heroes, kine-winner, mount thy
							conquering car, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Cleaver of stalls, kine-winner, armed with thunder, who quells an army
							and with might destroys it.-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Follow him, brothers! quit yourselves like heroes, and like this Indra
							show your zeal and courage.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Piercing the cow-stalls with surpassing vigour, Indra, the pitiless
							Hero, wild with anger,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Victor in fight, unshaken and resistless,may he protect our armies in
							our battles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra guide these: Brhaspati precede them, the guerdon, and the
							sacrifice, and Soma;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							And let the banded Maruts march in forefront of heavenly hosts that
							conquer and demolish.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ours be the potent host of mighty Indra, King Varuna, and Maruts, and
							Adityas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Uplifted is the shout of Gods who conquer high-minded Gods who cause
							the worlds to tremble.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bristle thou up, O Maghavan, our weapons: excite the spirits of my
							warring heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Urge on the strong steeds' might, O Vrtra-slayer, and let the din of
							conquering cars go upward.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Indra aid us when our flags are gathered: victorious be the arrows
							of our army.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 103: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							May our brave men of war prevail in battle. Ye Gods, protect us in the
							shout of onset.
						-
