				Mandala 10: Hymn 106
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS very thing ye Twain hold as your object: ye weave your songs as
							skilful men weave garments.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							That ye may come united have I waked you: ye spread out food like days
							of lovely weather.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like two plough-bulls ye move along in traces, and seek like eager
							guests your bidder's banquet.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye are like glorious envoys mid the people: like bulls, approach the
							place where ye are watered.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like the two pinions of a bird, connected, like two choice animals, ye
							have sought our worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bright as the fire the votary hath kindled, ye sacrifice in many a spot
							as roamers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye are our kinsmen, like two sons, two fathers, strong in your
							splendour and like kings for conquest;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like rays for our enjoyment, Lords to feed us, ye, like quick bearers,
							have obeyed our calling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							You are like two pleasantly moving well-fed (hills) like Mitra and
							Varuna,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							the two bestowers of felicity, veracious, possessors of infinite
							wealth, happy,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 5: Line 3
					-
						-
							like two horses plump with fodder, abiding in the firmament,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 5: Line 4
					-
						-
							like two rams (are you) to be nourished with sacrificial food, to be
							cherished (with oblations).
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							You are like two mad elephants bending their forequarters and smiting
							the foe,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							like the two sons of Nitosa destroying (foes),
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 6: Line 3
					-
						-
							and cherishing (friends); you are bright as two water-born (jewels),
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 6: Line 4
					-
						-
							do you, who are victorious, (render) my decaying mortal body free from
							decay.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Fierce (Asvins), like two powerful (heroes), you enable this moving,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							perishable mortal (frame) to cross over to the objects (of its
							destination) as over water;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 7: Line 3
					-
						-
							extremely strong, like the Rbhus, your chariot, attained its
							destination swift as the wind,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 7: Line 4
					-
						-
							it pervaded (everywhere), it dispensed riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							With your bellies full of the Soma, like two saucepans, preservers of
							wealth, destroyers of enemies.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							(you are) armed with hatchets, moving like two flying (birds)
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 8: Line 3
					-
						-
							with forms like the moon, attaining success through the mind, like two
							laudable beings,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 8: Line 4
					-
						-
							(you are) approaching (the sacrifice).
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like giants, ye will find firm ground to stand on in depths, like feet
							for one who fords a shallow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like cars ye will attend to him who orders: ye Two enjoy our wondrous
							work as sharers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Like toiling bees ye bring to us your honey, as bees into the hide that
						opens downward.
					-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we increase the laud and gain us vigour: come to our song, ye whom
							one chariot carries.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 106: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Filled be our kine with ripened meath like glory: Bhutamsa hath
							fulfilled the Asvins' longing.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 107
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE men's great bounty hath been manifested, and the whole world of
							life set free from darkness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Great light hath come, vouchsafed us by the Fathers: apparent is the
							spacious path of Guerdon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							High up in heaven abide the Guerdon-givers: they who give steeds dwell
							with the Sun for ever.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							They who give gold are blest with life eternal. they who give robes
							prolong their lives, O Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not from the niggards-for they give not fireely-comes Meed at
							sacrifice, Gods' satisfaction:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Yea, many men with hands stretched out with Guerdon present their gifts
							because they dread dishonour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							These who observe mankind regard oblation as streamy Vayu and
							light-finding Arka.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They satisfy and give their gifts in synod, and pour in streams the
							seven-mothered Guerdon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							He who brings Guerdon comes as first invited: chief of the hamlet comes
							the Guerdon-bearer.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him I account the ruler of the people who was the first to introduce
							the Guerdon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							They call him Rsi, Brahman, Sama-chanter, reciter of the laud, leader
							of worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The brightly-shining God's three forms he knoweth who first bestowed
							the sacrificial Guerdon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guerdon bestows the horse, bestows the bullock, Guerdon bestows,
							moreover, gold that Rsisters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Guerdon gives food which is our life and spirit. He who is wise takes
							Guerdon for his armour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							The liberal die not, never are they ruined: the liberal suffer neither
							harm nor trouble.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							The light of heaven, the universe about us,-all this doth sacrificial
							Guerdon give them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							First have the liberal gained a fragrant dwelling, and got themselves a
							bride in fair apparel.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The liberal have obtained their draught of liquor, and conquered those
							who, unprovoked, assailed them.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							They deck the fleet steed for the bounteous giver: the maid adorns
							herself and waits to meet him.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							His home is like a lake with lotus blossoms, like the Gods' palaces
							adorned and splendid.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Steeds good at draught convey the liberal giver, and lightly rolling
							moves the car of Guerdon.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 107: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Assist, ye Gods, the liberal man in battles: the liberal giver conquers
							foes in combat.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 108
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHAT wish of Sarama hath brought her hither? The path leads far away to
							distant places.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							What charge hast thou for us? Where turns thy journey? How hast thou
							made thy way o'er Rasa's waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I come appointed messenger of Indra, seeking your ample stores of
							wealth, O Panis.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							This hath preserved me from the fear of crossing: thus have I made my
							way o'er Rasa's waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What is that Indra like, what is his aspect whose envoy, Sarama, from
							afar thou comest?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him approach, and we will show him friendship: he shall be made the
							herdsman of our cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I know him safe from harm: but he can punish who sent me hither from
							afar as envoy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him rivers flowing with deep waters bide not. Low will ye be, O Panis,
							slain by Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							These are the kine which, Sarama, thou seekest, flying, O Blest One, to
							the ends of heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who will loose these for thee without a battle? Yea, and sharp-pointed
							are our warlike weapons.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even if your wicked bodies, O ye Panis, were arrow-proof, your words
							are weak for wounding;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							And were the path to you as yet unmastered, Brhaspati in neither case
							will spare you.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Paved with the rock is this our treasure-chamber; filled full of
							precious things, of kine, and horses.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							These Panis who are watchful keepers guard it. In vain hast thou
							approached this lonely station.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Rsis will come inspirited with Soma, Angirases unwearied, and Navagvas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							This stall of cattle will they part among them: then will the Panis
							wish these words unspoken.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even thus, O Sarama, hast thou come hither, forced by celestial might
							to make the journey.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Turn thee not back, for thou shalt be our sister: O Blest One, we will
							give thee of the cattle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brotherhood, sisterhood, I know not either: the dread Angirases and
							Indra know them.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							They seemed to long for kine when I departed. Hence, into distance, be
							ye gone, O Panis.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							Hence, far away, ye Panis! Let the cattle lowing come forth as holy Law
							commandeth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 108: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Kine which Brhaspati, and Soma, Rsis, sages, and pressing-stones have
							found when hidden.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 109
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THESE first, the boundless Sea, and Matarisvan, fierce-glowing Fire,
							the Strong, the Bliss-bestower.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							And heavenly Floods, first-born by holy Order, exclaimed against the
							outrage on a Brahman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							King Soma first of all, without reluctance, made restitution of the
							Brahman's consort.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mitra and Varuna were the inviters: Agni as Hota; took her hand and led
							her.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The man, her pledge, must by her hand be taken when they have cried,
							She is a Brahman's consort.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							She stayed not for a herald to conduct her: thus is the kingdom of a
							ruler guarded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus spake of her those Gods of old, Seven Rsis who sate them down to
							their austere devotion:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Dire is a Brahman's wife led home by others: in the supremest heaven
							she plants confusion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Brahmacari goes engaged in duty: he is a member of the Gods' own
							body.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through him Brhaspati obtained his consort, as the Gods gained the
							ladle brought by Soma.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							So then the Gods restored her, so men gave the woman back again.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Kings who kept their promises restored the Brahman's wedded wife,
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Having restored the Brahman's wife, and freed them, with Gods' aid,
							from sin,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 109: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							They shared the fulness of the earth, and won themselves extended sway.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 110
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU in the house of man this day enkindled worshippest Gods as God, O
							Jatavedas.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Observant, bright as Mitra, bring them hither: thou art a sapient and
							foreknowing envoy.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Tanunapat, fair-tongued, with sweet meath balming the paths and waysof
							Order, make them pleasant.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Convey our sacrifice to heaven, exalting with holy thoughts ourhymns of
							praise and worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Invoked, deserving prayer and adoration, O Agni, come accordant with
							the Vasus.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou art, O Youthful Lord, the Gods' Invoker, so, best of Sacrificers,
							bring them quickly.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							By rule the Sacred Grass is scattered eastward, a robe to clothe this
							earth when dawns are breaking.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Widely it spreads around and far-extended, fair for the Gods and
							bringing peace and freedom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the expansive Doors be widely opened, like wives who deck their
							beauty for their husbands.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lofty, celestial, all-impelling Portals, admit the Gods and give them
							easy entrance.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Pouring sweet dews let holy Night and Morning, each close to each, he
							seated at their station,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lofty, celestial Dames with gold to deck them. assuming all their fair
							and radiant beauty.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 110: Verse 7
				-
					-
