							of juice and pouring forth his flood,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Speaking aloud with flame as with his lips a priest, and broadening his
							paths like one of high command.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou Everlasting, whom, far-striding fain to burn, the winds,
							uninterrupted, never overcome,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They have approached, as warriors eager for the fight, heroic Trita,
							guiding him to gain his wish.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							This Agni is the best of Kanvas, Kanvas' Friend, Conqueror of the foe
							whether afar or near.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni guard the singers, guard the princes well: may Agni grant to
							us our princes' gracious help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do thou, Supitrya, swiftly following, make thyself the lord of
							Jatavedas, mightiest of all,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who surely gives a boon even in thirsty land most powerful, prepared to
							aid us in the wilds.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus noble Agni with princes and mortal men is lauded, excellent for
							conquering strength with chiefs,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Men who are well-disposed as friends and true to Law, even as the
							heavens in majesty surpass mankind.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Son of Strength, Victorious, with this title Upastuta's most potent
							voice reveres thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blest with brave sons by thee we will extol thee, and lengthen out the
							days of our existence.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus, Agni, have the sons of Vrstihavya, the Rsis, the Upastutas
							invoked thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 115: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Protect them, guard the singers and the princes. With Vasat! have they
							come, with hands uplifted, with their uplifted hands and cries of
							Glory!
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 116
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							DRINK Soma juice for mighty power and vigour, drink, Strongest One,
							that thou mayst smite down Vrtra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Drink thou, invoked, for strength, and riches: drink thou thy fill of
							meath and pour it down, O Indra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drink of the foodful juice stirred into motion, drink what thou
							choosest of the flowing Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giver of weal, be joyful in thy spirit, and turn thee hitherward to
							bless and prosper.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let heavenly Soma gladden thee, O Indra, let that effused among mankind
							delight thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Rejoice in that whereby thou gavest freedom, and that whereby thou
							conquerest thy foemen.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let Indra come, impetuous, doubly mighty, to the poured juice, the
							Bull, with two Bay Coursers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With juices pressed in milk, with meath presented, glut evermore thy
							bolt, O Foe-destroyer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Dash down, outffaming their sharp flaming weapons, the strong-holds of
							the men urged on by demons.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							I give thee, Mighty One, great strength and conquest: go, meet thy foes
							and rend them in the battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Extend afar the votary's fame and glory, as the firm archer's strength
							drives off the foeman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ranged on our side, grown strong in might that conquers, never
							defeated, still increase thy body.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							To thee have we presented this oblation: accept it, Sovran Ruler, free
							from anger.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Juice, Maghavan, for thee is pressed and ripened: eat, Indra, drink of
							that which stirs to meet thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Eat, Indra, these oblations which approach thee: be pleased with food
							made ready and with Soma.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							With entertainment we receive thee friendly: effectual be the
							sacrificer's wishes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							I send sweet speech to Indra and to Agni: with hymns I speed it like a
							boat through waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 116: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even thus, the Gods seem moving round about me, the fountains and
							bestowers of our riches.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 117
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE Gods have not ordained hunger to be our death: even to the well-fed
							man comes death in varied shape.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							The riches of the liberal never waste away, while he who will not give
							finds none to comfort him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The man with food in store who, when the needy comes in miserable case
							begging for bread to eat,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hardens his heart against him-even when of old he did him service-finds
							not one to comfort him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bounteous is he who gives unto the beggar who comes to him in want of
							food and feeble.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Success attends him in the shout of battle. He makes a friend of him in
							future troubles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							No friend is he who to his friend and comrade who comes imploring food,
							will offer nothing.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let him depart-no home is that to rest in-, and rather seek a stranger
							to support him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let the rich satisfy the poor implorer, and bend his eye upon a longer
							pathway.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Riches come now to one, now to another, and like the wheels of cars are
							ever rolling.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The foolish man wins food with fruitless labour: that food -I speak the
							truth- shall be his ruin.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He feeds no trusty friend, no man to love him. All guilt is he who eats
							with no partaker.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The ploughshare ploughing makes the food that feeds us, and with its
							feet cuts through the path it follows.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Better the speaking than the silent Brahman: the liberal friend
							outyalues him who gives not.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							He with one foot hath far outrun the biped, and the two-footed catches
							the three-footed.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Four-footed creatures come when bipeds call them, and stand and look
							where five are met together.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							The hands are both alike: their labour differs. The yield of sister
							milch-kine is unequal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 117: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Twins even diffier in their strength and vigour: two, even kinsmen,
							differ in their bounty.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 118
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI, refulgent among men thou slayest the devouring fiend,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bright Ruler in thine own abode.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou springest up when worshipped well the drops of butter are thy joy
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							When ladies are brought near to thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Honoured with gifts he shines afar, Agni adorable with song:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							The dripping ladle balms his face.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni with honey in his mouth, honoured with gifts, is balmed with oil,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Refulgent in his wealth of light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Praised by our hymns thou kindlest thee, Oblation-bearer, for the Gods
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							As such do mortals call on thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To that Immortal Agni pay worship with oil, ye mortal men,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of the house, whom none deceives.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, burn the Raksasas with thine unconquerable flame
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shine guardian of Eternal Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							So, Agni, with thy glowing face burn fierce against the female fiends,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Shining among Uruksayas.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Uruksayas have kindled thee, Oblation-bearer, thee, with hymns.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 118: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best Worshipper among mankind.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 119
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS, even this was my resolve, to win a cow, to win a steed:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like violent gusts of wind the draughts that I have drunk have lifted
							me
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The draughts I drank have borne me up, as fleet-foot horses draw a car:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The hymn hath reached me, like a cow who lows to meet her darling calf:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As a wright bends a chariot-seat so round my heart I bend the hymn:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Not as a mote within the eye count the Five Tribes of men with me:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The heavens and earth themselves have not grown equal to one half of me
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							I in my grandeur have surpassed the heavens and all this spacious earth
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Aha! this spacious earth will I deposit either here or there
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							In one short moment will I smite the earth in fury here or there:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 11: Line 1
					-
						-
							One of my flanks is in the sky; I let the other trail below:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 11: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 12: Line 1
					-
						-
							1, greatest of the Mighty Ones, am lifted to the firmament:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 12: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 13: Line 1
					-
						-
							I seek the worshipper's abode; oblation-bearer to the Gods:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 119: Verse 13: Line 2
					-
						-
							Have I not drunk of Soma juice?
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 120
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							IN all the worlds That was the Best and Highest whence sprang the
							Mighty Gods, of splendid valour.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							As soon as born he overcomes his foemen, be in whom all who lend him
							aid are joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Grown mighty in his strength, with ample vigour, he as a foe strikes
							fear into the Dasa,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Eager to win the breathing and the breathless. All sang thy praise at
							banquet and oblation.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							All concentrate on thee their mental vigour, what time these, twice or
							thrice, are thine assistants.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blend what is sweeter than the sweet with sweetness: win. quickly with
							our meath that meath in battle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Therefore in thee too, thou who winnest riches, at every banquet are
							the sages joyful.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							With mightier power, Bold God, extend thy firmness: let not malignant
							Yatudhanas harm thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Proudly we put our trust in thee in battles, when we behold great
							wealth the prize of combat.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							I with my words impel thy weapons onward, and sharpen with my prayer
							thy vital vigour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Worthy of praises, many-shaped, most skilful, most energetic, Aptya of
							the Aptyas:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							He with his might destroys the seven Danus, subduing many who were
							deemed his equals.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou in that house which thy protection guardeth bestowest wealth, the
							higher and the lower.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou stablishest the two much-wandering Mothers, and bringest many
							deeds to their completion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Brhaddiva, the foremost of light-winners, repeats these holy prayers,
							this strength of Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He rules the great self-luminous fold of cattle, and all the doors of
							light hath he thrown open.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus hath Brhaddiva, the great Atharvan, spoken to Indra as himself in
							person.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 120: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The spotless Sisters, they who are his Mothers, with power exalt him
							and impel him onward.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 121
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							IN the beginning rose Hiranyagarbha, born Only Lord of all created
							beings.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							He fixed and holdeth up this earth and heaven. What God shall we adore
							with our oblation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Giver of vital breath, of power and vigour, he whose commandments all
							the Gods acknowledge -.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Lord of death, whose shade is life immortal. What God shall we
							adore with our oblation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who by his grandeur hath become Sole Ruler of all the moving world that
							breathes and slumbers;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who is Lord of men and Lord of cattle. What God shall we adore with
							our oblation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							His, through his might, are these snow-covered mountains, and men call
							sea and Rasa his possession:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							His arms are these, his are these heavenly regions. What God shall we
							adore with our oblation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							By him the heavens are strong and earth is stedfast, by him light's
							realm and sky-vault are supported:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							By him the regions in mid-air were measured. What God shall we adore
							with our oblation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him, supported by his help, two armies embattled look while
							trembling in their spirit,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							When over them the risen Sun is shining. What God shall we adore with
							our oblation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the mighty waters came, containing the universal germ,
							producing Agni,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thence sprang the Gods' one spirit into being. What God shall we adore
							with our oblation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							He in his might surveyed the floods containing productive force and
							generating Worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							He is the God of gods, and none beside him. What God shall we adore
							with our oblation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Neer may he harm us who is earth's Begetter, nor he whose laws are
							sure, the heavens' Creator,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							He who brought forth the great and lucid waters. What God shall we
							adore with our oblation?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 10: Line 1
					-
						-
							Prajapati! thou only comprehendest all these created things, and none
							beside thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 121: Verse 10: Line 2
					-
						-
							Grant us our hearts' desire when we invoke thee: may we have store of
							riches in possession.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 122
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I PRAISE the God of wondrous might like Indra, the lovely pleasant
							Guest whom all must welcome.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Agni, Priest and Master of the household, give hero strength and
							all-sustaining riches.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, graciously accept this song of mine, thou passing-wise who
							knowest every ordinance.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enwrapped in holy oil further the course of prayer: the Gods bestow
							according to thy holy law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Immortal, wandering round the seven stations, give, a liberal Giver, to
							the pious worshipper,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wealth, Agni, with brave sons and ready for his use: welcome the man
							who comes with fuel unto thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The seven who bring oblations worship thee, the Strong, the first, the
							Great Chief Priest, Ensign of sacrifice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The oil-anointed Bull, Agni who hears, who sends as God full hero
							strength to him who freely gives.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							First messenger art thou, meet for election: drink thou thy fill
							invited to the Anirta,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Maruts in the votary's house adorned thee; with lauds the Bhrgus
							gave thee light and glory.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Milking the teeming Cow for all-sustaining food. O Wise One, for the
							worship-loving worshipper,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Agni, dropping oil, thrice lighting works of Law, showest thy
							wisdom circling home and sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who at flushing of this dawn appointed thee their messenger, these
							men have paid thee reverence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gods strengthened thee for work that must be glorified, Agni, while
							they made butter pure for sacrifice.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Arrangers in our synods, Agni, while they sang Vasisistha s sons have
							called thee down, the Potent One.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 122: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Maintain the growth of wealth with men who sacrifice. Ye Gods, preserve
							us with your blessings evermore.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 123
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SEE, Vena, born in light, hath driven hither, on chariot of the air,
							the Calves of Prsni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Singers with hymns caress him as an infant there where the waters and
							the sunlight mingle.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Vena draws up his wave from out the ocean. mist-born, the fair one's
							back is made apparent,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brightly he shone aloft on Order's summit: the hosts sang glory to
							their common birthplace.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Full many, lowing to their joint-possession, dwelling together stood
							the Darling's Mothers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ascending to the lofty height of Order, the bands of singers 'sip the
							sweets of Amrta.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Knowing his form, the sages yearned to meet him: they have come nigh to
							hear the wild Bull's bellow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Performing sacrifice they reached the river: for the Gandharva found
							the immortal waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Apsaras, the Lady, sweetly smiling, supports her Lover in sublimest
							heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							In his Friend's dwelling as a Friend he wanders: he, Vena, rests him on
							his golden pinion.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							They gaze on thee with longing in their spirit, as on a strong-winged
							bird that mounteth sky-ward;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							On thee with wings of gold, Varuna's envoy, the Bird that hasteneth to
							the home of Yama.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Erect, to heaven hath the Gandharva mounted, pointing at us his
							many-coloured weapons;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Clad in sweet raiment beautiful to look on, for he, as light, produceth
							forms that please us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							When as a spark he cometh near the ocean, still looking with a
							vulture's eye to heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 123: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							His lustre, joying in its own bright splendour, maketh dear glories in
							the lowest region.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 124
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							COME to this sacrifice of ours, O Agni, threefold, with seven threads
							and five divisions.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be our oblation-bearer and preceder: thou hast lain long enough in
							during darkness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I come a God foreseeing from the godless to immortality by secret
							pathways,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							While I, ungracious one, desert the gracious, leave mine own friends
							and seek the kin of strangers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							1, looking to the guest of other lineage, have founded many a rule of
							Law and Order.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							I bid farewell to the Great God, the Father, and, for neglect, obtain
							my share of worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							I tarried many a year within this altar: I leave the Father, for my
							choice is Indra.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Away pass Agni, Varuna and Soma. Rule ever changes: this I come to
							favour.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							These Asuras have lost their powers of magic. But thou, O Varuna, if
							thou dost love me,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							O King, discerning truth and right from falsehood, come and be Lord and
							Ruler of my kingdom.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here is the light of heaven, here allis lovely; here there is radiance,
							here is air's wide region.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us two slaughter Vrtra. Forth, O Soma! Thou art oblation: we
							therewith will serve thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Sage hath fixed his form by wisdom in the heavens: Varuna with no
							violence let the waters flow.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like women-folk, the floods that bring prosperity have eau lit his hue
							and colour as they gleamed and shone.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							These wait upon his loftiest power and vigour: he dwells in these who
							triumph in their Godhead;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							And they, like people who elect their ruler, have in abhorrence turned
							away from Vrtra.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							They call him Swan, the abhorrent floods' Companion, moving in
							friendship with celestial Waters.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 124: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							The poets in their thought have looked on Indra swiftly approaching
							when Anustup calls him.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 125
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I TRAVEL with the Rudras and the Vasus, with the Adityas and All-Gods I
							wander.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							I hold aloft both Varuna and Mitra, Indra and Agni, and the Pair of
							Asvins.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							I cherish and sustain high-swelling Soma, and Tvastar I support, Pusan,
							and Bhaga.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							I load with wealth the zealous sacrificer who pours the juice and
							offers his oblation
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							I am the Queen, the gatherer-up of treasures, most thoughtful, first of
							those who merit worship.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thus Gods have stablished me in many places with many homes to enter
							and abide in.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Through me alone all eat the food that feeds them,-each man who sees,
							breathes, hears the word outspoken
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							They know it not, but yet they dwell beside me. Hear, one and all, the
							truth as I declare it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I, verily, myself announce and utter the word that Gods and men alike
							shall welcome.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							I make the man I love exceeding mighty, make him a sage, a Rsi, and a
							Brahman.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							I bend the bow for Rudra that his arrow may strike and slay the hater
							of devotion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							I rouse and order battle for the people, and I have penetrated Earth
							and Heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							On the world's summit I bring forth the Father: my home is in the
							waters, in the ocean.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thence I extend o'er all existing creatures, and touch even yonder
							heaven with my forehead.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							I breathe a strong breath like the wind and tempest, the while I hold
							together all existence.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 125: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Beyond this wide earth and beyond the heavens I have become so mighty
							in my grandeur.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 126
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							No peril, no severe distress, ye Gods, affects the mortal man,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whom Aryaman and Mitra lead, and Varima, of one accord, beyond his
							foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							This very thing do we desire, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whereby ye guhrd the mortal man from sore distress, and lead him safe
							beyond his foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							These are, each one, our present helps, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Best leaders, best deliverers to lead us on and bear as safe beyond our
							foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye compass round and guard each man, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							In your dear keeping may we be, ye who are excellent as guides beyond
							our foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Adityas are beyond all foes,-Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Strong Rudra with the Marut host, Indra, Agni let us call for weal
							beyond our foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							These lead us safely over all, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							These who are Kings of living men, over all troubles far away beyond
							our foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May they give bliss to aid us well, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the Adityas, when we pray, grant us wide shelter and defence beyond
							our foes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							As in this place, O Holy Ones, ye Vasus freed even the Gaud when her
							feet were fettered.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 126: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							So free us now from trouble and affliction: and let our life be
							lengthened still, O Api.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 127
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH all her eyes the Goddess Night looks forth approaching many a
							spot:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							She hath put all her glories on.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Immortal. she hath filled the waste, the Goddess hath filled height and
							depth:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							She conquers darkness with her light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Goddess as she comes hath set the Dawn her Sister in her place:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And then the darkness vanishes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							So favour us this night, O thou whose pathways we have visited
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As birds their nest upon the tree.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The villagers have sought their homes, and all that walks and all that
							flies,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Even the falcons fain for prey.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Keep off the she-wolf and the wolf, O Urmya, keep the thief away;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Easy be thou for us to pass.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Clearly hath she come nigh to me who decks the dark with richest hues:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Morning, cancel it like debts.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							These have I brought to thee like kine. O Night, thou Child of Heaven,
							accept
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 127: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							This laud as for a conqueror.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 128
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET me win glory, Agni, in our battles: enkindling thee, may we support
							our bodies.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the four regions bend and bow before me: with thee for guardian may
							we win in combat.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							May all the Gods be on my side in battle, the Maruts led by Indra,
							Visnu, Agni.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Mine be the middle air's extended region, ani may the wind blow
							favouring these my wishes.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May the Gods grant me riches; may the blessing and invocation of the
							Gods assist me.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Foremost in fight be the divine Invokers: may we, unwounded, have brave
							heroes round us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							For me let them present all mine oblations, and let my mind's intention
							be accomplished.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May I he guiltless of the least transgression: and, all ye Go-is, do ye
							combine to bless us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye six divine Expanses, grant us freedom: here, all ye Gods, acquit
							yourselves like heroes.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let us not lose our children or our bodies: let us not benefit the foe,
							King Soma!
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Baffling the wrath of our opponents, Agni, guard us as our infallible
							Protector.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let these thy foes turn back and seek their houses, and let their
							thought who watch at home be ruined.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of the world, Creator of creators the saviour God who overcomes
							the foeman.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May Gods, Brhaspati, both Asvins shelter from ill thii sacrifice and
							sacrificer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							Foodful, and much-invoked, at this our calling may the great Bull
							vouchsafe us wide protection.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lord of Bay Coursers, Indra, blew our children: harm us not, give us
							riot as prey to others.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 9: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let those who are our foemen stay. afar from us: with Indra and with
							Agni we will drive them off.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 128: Verse 9: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vasus, Adityas, Rudras have exalted me, made me far-reaching, inighty,
							thinker, sovran lord.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 129
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THEN was not non-existent nor existent: there was no realm of air, no
							sky beyond it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							What covered in, and where? and what gave shelter? Was water there,
							unfathomed depth of water?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Death was not then, nor was there aught immortal: no sign was there,
							the day's and night's divider.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That One Thing, breathless, breathed by its own nature: apart from it
							was nothing whatsoever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Darkness there was: at first concealed in darkness this All was
							indiscriminate chaos.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							All that existed then was void and formless: by the great power of
							Warmth was born that Unit.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thereafter rose Desire in the beginning, Desire, the primal seed and
							germ of Spirit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sages who searched with their heart's thought discovered the existent's
							kinship in the non-existent.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Transversely was their severing line extended: what was above it then,
							and what below it?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							There were begetters, there were mighty forces, free action here and
							energy up yonder
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Who verily knows and who can here declare it, whence it was born and
							whence comes this creation?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Gods are later than this world's production. Who knows then whence
							it first came into being?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							He, the first origin of this creation, whether he formed it all or did
							not form it,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 129: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose eye controls this world in highest heaven, he verily knows it, or
							perhaps he knows not.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 130
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THE sacrifice drawn out with threads on every side, stretched by a
							hundred sacred ministers and one,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							This do these Fathers weave who hitherward are come: they sit beside
							the warp and cry, Weave forth, weave back.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Man extends it and the Man unbinds it: even to this vault of heaven
							hath he outspun, it.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							These pegs are fastened to the seat of worship: they made the
							Sama-hymns their weaving shuttles.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							What were the rule, the order and the model? What were the wooden
							fender and the butter?
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							What were the hymn, the chant, the recitation, when to the God all
							Deities paid worship?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Closely was Gayatri conjoined with Agni, and closely Savitar combined
							with Usnih.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Brilliant with Ukthas, Soma joined Anustup: Brhaspati's voice by Brhati
							was aided.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Viraj adhered to Varuna and Mitra: here Tristup day by day was Indra's
							portion.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Jagati entered all the Gods together: so by this knowledge men were
							raised to Rsis.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							So by this knowledge men were raised to Rsis, when ancient sacrifice
							sprang up, our Fathers.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							With the mind's eye I think that I behold them who first performed this
							sacrificial worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							They who were versed in ritual and metre, in hymns and rules, were the
							Seven Godlike Rsis.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 130: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Viewing the path of those of old, the sages have taken up the reins
							like chariot-drivers.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 131
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							DRIVE all our enemies away, O Indra, the western, mighty Conqueror, and
							the eastern.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Hero, drive off our northern foes and southern, that we in thy wide
							shelter may be joyful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							What then? As men whose fields are full of barley reap the ripe corn
							removing it in order,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So bring the food of those men, bring it hither, who went not to
							prepare the grass for worship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Men come not with one horse at sacred seasons; thus they obtain no
							honour in assemblies.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sages desiring herds of kine and horses strengthen the mighty Indra for
							his friendship.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye, Asvins, Lords of Splendour, drank full draughts of grateful Soma
							juice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							And aided Indra in his work with Namuci of Asura birth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							As parents aid a son, both Asvins, Indra, aided thee with their
							wondrous Powers and wisdom.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When thou, with might. hadst drunk the draught that gladdens,
							Sarasvati, O Maghavan, refreshed thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra is strong to save, rich in assistance may he, possessing all, be
							kind and gracious.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							May he disperse our foes and give us safety, and may we be the lords of
							hero vigou r.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							May we enjoy his favour, his the Holy may we enjoy his blessed loving
							kindness.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 131: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							May this rich Indra, as our good Protector, drive off and keep afar all
							those who hate us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 132
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY Dyaus the Lord of lauded wealth, and Earth stand by the man who
							offers sacrifice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							And may the Asvins, both the Gods, strengthen the worshipper with
							bliss.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							As such we honour you, Mitra and Varuna, with hasty zeal, most blest,
							you who sustain the folk.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							So may we, through your friendship for the worshipper, subdue the
							fiends.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							And when we seek to win your love and friendship, we.who have precious
							wealth in our possession,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or when the worshipper augments his riches let not his treasures be
							shut up
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							That other, Asura! too was born of Heaven. thou art, O Varuna, the King
							of all men.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The chariot's Lord was well content, forbearing to anger Death by sin
							so great.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 4: Line 3
					-
						-
							This sin hath Sakaputa here committed. Heroes who fled to their dear
							friend he slayeth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 4: Line 4
					-
						-
							When the Steed bringeth down your grace and favour in bodies dear and
							worshipful.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Your Mother Aditi, ye wise, was purified with water even as earth is
							purified from heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Show love and kindness here below: wash her in rays of heavenly light.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Twain have seated you as Lords of Wealth, as one who mounts a car to
							him who sits upon the pole, upon the wood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 132: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							These our disheartened tribes Nrmedhas saved from woe, Sumedhas saved
							from Woe.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 133
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SING strength to Indra that shall set his chariot in the foremost
							place.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Giver of room in closest fight, slayer of foes in shock of war, be thou
							our great encourager. Let the weak bowstrings break upon the bows of
							feeble enemies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou didst destroy the Dragon: thou sentest the rivers down to earth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Foeless, O Indra, wast thou born. Thou tendest well each choicest
							thing. Therefore we draw us close to thee. Let the weak bowstrings
							break upon the bows of feeble enemies.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Destroyed be all malignities and all our enemy's designs.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thy bolt thou castest, at the foe, O Indra, who would srnite us dead:
							thy liberal bounty gives us wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							The robber people round about, Indra, who watch and aim at us,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Trample them down beneath thy foot; a conquering scatterer art thou.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Whoso assails us, Indra, be the man a stranger or akin,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring down, thyself, his strength although it be as vast as are the
							heavens.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Close to thy friendship do we cling, O Indra, and depend, or, thee.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Lead us beyond all pain and grief along the path of holy Law.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do thou bestow upon us her, O Indra, who yields according to the
							singer's longing,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 133: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							That the great Cow may, with exhaustless udder, pouring a thousand
							streams, give milk to feed us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 134
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 134: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 134: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							As, like the Morning, thou hast filled, O Indra, both the earth and
							heaven.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 134: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
