					-
						-
							In the floods' track he found the bootyseeker: the rocky cow-pen's
							doors he threw wide open.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 139: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							These, the Gandharva told him, Rowed with Amrta. Indra knew well the
							puissancc of the dragons.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 140
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							AGNI, life-power and fame are thine: thy fires blaze mightily, thou
							rich in wealth of beams!
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Sage, passing bright, thou givest to the worshipper, with strength, the
							food that merits laud.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							With brilliant, purifying sheen, with perfect sheen thou liftest up
							thyself in light.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, visiting both thy Mothers, aidest them as Son: thou joinest close
							the earth and heaven.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Jatavedas, Son of Strength, rejoice ihyself, gracious, in our fair
							hymns and songs.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In thee are treasured various forms of strengthening food, born nobly
							and of wondrous help.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni, spread forth, as Ruler, over living things: give wealth to us,
							Immortal God.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou shinest out from beauty fair to look upon: thou leadest us to
							conquering power.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							To him, the wise, who orders sacrifice, who hath great riches un der
							his control,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou givest blest award of good, and plenteous food, givest him wealth
							that conquers all.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							The men have set before them them for their welfare Agni, strong,
							visible to all, the Holy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 140: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thee, Godlike One, with ears to hear, most famous, men's generations
							magnify with praise-songs.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 141
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							TURN hither, Agni, speak to us: come to us with a gracious mind.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Enrich us, Master of the house: thou art the Giver of our wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Let Aryarnan vouchsafe us wealth, and Bhaga, and Brhaspati.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let the Gods give their gifts, and let Sunrta, Goddess, grant us
							wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							We call King Soma to our aid, and Agni with our songs and hymns,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Adityas, Visnu, Surya, and the Brahman Priest Brhaspati.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Indra, Vayu, Brhaspati, Gods swift to listen, we invoke,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That in the synod all the folk may be benevolent to us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Urge Aryaman to send us gifts, and Indra, and Brhaspati,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Vata, Visnu, Sarasvati and the Strong Courser Savitar.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Do thou, O Agni, with thy fires strengthen our prayer and sacrifice:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 141: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Urge givers to bestow their wealth to aid our service of the Gods.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 142
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WITH thee, O Agni, was this singer of the laud: he hath no other
							kinship, O thou Son of Strength.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou givest blessed shelter with a triple guard. Keep the destructive
							lightning far away from us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thy birth who seekest food is in the falling flood, Agni: as Comrade
							thou winnest all living things.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Our coursers and our songs shall be victorious: they of themselves
							advance like one who guards the herd.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							And thou, O Agni, thou of Godlike nature, sparest the stones, while
							caring up the brushwood.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Then are thy tracks like deserts in the corn-lands. Let us not stir to
							wrath thy mighty arrow.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O'er hills through vales devouring as thou goest, thou partest like an
							army fain for booty
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As when a barber shaves a beard, thou shavest earth when the wind blows
							on thy flame and fans it.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Apparent are his lines as he approaches the course is single, but the
							cars are many,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							When, Agni, thou, making thine arms resplendent, advancest o'er the
							land spread out beneath thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now let thy strength, thy burning flames fly upward, thine energies, O
							Agni, as thou toilest.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Gape widely, bend thee, waxing in thy vigour: let all the Vasus sit
							this day beside thee.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 7: Line 1
					-
						-
							This is the waters' reservoir, the great abode of gathered streams.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 7: Line 2
					-
						-
							Take thou another path than this, and as thou listest walk thereon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 8: Line 1
					-
						-
							On thy way hitherward and hence let flowery Durva grass spring up
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 142: Verse 8: Line 2
					-
						-
							Let there be lakes with lotus blooms. These are the mansions of the
							flood.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 143
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							YE made that Atri, worn with eld, free as a horse to win the goal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							When ye restored to youth and strength Kaksivan like a car renewed,
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye freed that Atri like a horse, and brought him newly-born to earth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Ye loosed him like a firm-tied knot which Gods unsoiled by dust had
							bound.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Heroes who showed most wondrous power to Atri, strive to win fair
							songs;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							For then, O Heroes of the sky, your hymn of praise shall cease no more.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							This claims your notice, Bounteous Gods! - oblation, Asvins! and our
							love,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							That ye, O Heroes, in the fight may bring us safe to ample room.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Ye Twain to Bhujyu tossed about in ocean at the region's end,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Nasatyas, with your winged sterds came nigh, and gave him strength to
							win.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come with your joys, most liberal Gods, Lords of all treasures,
							bringing weal.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 143: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Like fresh full waters to a well, so, Heroes come and be with us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 144
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THIS deathless Indu, like a steed, strong and of full vitality,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Belongs to thee, the Orderer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here, by us, for the worshipper, is the wise bolt that works with
							skill.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							It brings the bubbling beverage as a dexterous man brings the effectual
							strong drink.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Impetuous Ahisuva, a bull among cows of his,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							looked down upon the restless Hawk.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							That the strong-pinioned Bird hath brought, Child of the Falcon, from
							afar,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							What moves upon a hundred wheels along the female Dragon's path.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Which, fair, unrobbed, the Falcon brought thee in his foot, the
							red-hued dwelling of the juice;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Through this came vital power which lengthens out our days, and kinship
							through its help awoke.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							So Indra is by lndu's power; e'en among Gods will it repel great
							treachery.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 144: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wisdom, Most Sapient One, brings force that lengthens life. May wisdom
							bring the juice to us.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 145
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FROM out the earth I dig this plant, a herb of most effectual power,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Wherewith one quells the rival wife and gains the husband for oneself.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Auspicious, with expanded leaves, sent by the Gods, victorious plant,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Blow thou the rival wife away, and make my husband only mine.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Stronger am 1, O Stronger One, yea, mightier than the mightier;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							And she who is my rival wife is lower than the lowest dames.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Her very name I utter not: she takes no pleasure in this man.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Far into distance most remote drive we the rival wife away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							I am the conqueror, and thou, thou also act victorious:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							As victory attends us both we will subdue my fellow-wife.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							I have gained thee for vanquisher, have grasped thee with a stronger
							spell.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 145: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							As a cow hastens to her calf, so let thy spirit speed te me, hasten
							like water on its way.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 146
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							GODDESS of wild and forest who seemest to vanish from the sight.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							How is it that thou seekest not the village? Art thou not afraid?
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							What time the grasshopper replies and swells the shrill cicala's voice,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seeming to sound with tinkling bells, the Lady of the Wood exults.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							And, yonder, cattle seem to graze, what seems a dwelling-place appears:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or else at eve the Lady of the Forest seems to free the wains.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Here one is calling to his cow, another there hath felled a tree:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							At eve the dweller in the wood fancies that somebody hath screamed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							The Goddess never slays, unless some murderous enemy approach.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Man eats of savoury fruit and then takes, even as he wills, his rest.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 6: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now have I praised the Forest Queen, sweet-scented, redolent of balm,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 146: Verse 6: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Mother of all sylvan things, who tills not but hath stores of food.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 147
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							I TRUST in thy first wrathful deed, O Indra, when thou slewest Vrtra
							and didst work to profit man;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							What time the two world-halves fell short of thee in might, and the
							earth trembled at thy force, O Thunder-anned.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou with thy magic powers didst rend the conjurer Vrtra, O Blameless
							One, with heart that longed for fame.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Heroes elect thee when they battle for the prey, thee in all sacrifices
							worthy of renown.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							God Much-invoked, take pleasure in these princes here, who, thine
							exalters, Maghavan, have come to wealth.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							In synods, when the rite succeeds, they hymn the Strong for sons and
							progeny and riches undisturbed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							That man shall find delight in well-protected wealth whose care
							provides for him the quick-sought joyous draught.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bringing oblations, strengthened Maghavan, by thee, he swiftly wins the
							spoil with heroes in the fight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Now for our band, O Maghavan, when lauded, make ample room with might,
							and grant us riches.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 147: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Magician thou, our Varuna and Mitra, deal food to us, O Wondrous, as
							Dispenser.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 148
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							WHEN we have pressed the juice we laud thee, Indra, and when, Most
							Valorous we have won the booty.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bring us prosperity, as each desires it under thine own protection may
							we conquer.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Sublime from birth, mayst thou O Indra, Hero, with Surya overcome the
							Dasa races.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							As by a fountain's side, we bring the Soma that lay concealed,
							close-hidden in the waters.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Answer the votary's hymns, for these thou knowest, craving the Rsis'
							prayer, thyself a Singer
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we be they who take delight in Somas: these with sweet food for
							thee, O Chariot-rider.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							These holy prayers, O Indra, have I sung thee: grant to the men the
							strength of men, thou Hero.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Be of one mind with those in whom thou joyest: keep thou the singers
							safe and their companions.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Listen to Prthi's call, heroic Indra, and be thou lauded by the hymns
							of Venya,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 148: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Him who hath sung thee to thine oil-rich dwelling, whose rolling songs
							have sped thee like a torrent.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 149
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SAVITAR fixed the earth with bands to bind it, and made heaven stedfast
							where no prop supported.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Savitar milked, as 'twere a restless courser, air, sea bound fast to
							what no foot had trodden.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Well knoweth Savitar, O Child of Waters, where ocean, firmly fixt,
							o'erflowed its limit.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thence sprang the world, from that uprose the region: thence heaven
							spread out and the wide earth expanded.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Then, with a full crowd of Immortal Beings, this other realm came
							later, high and holy.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							First, verily, Savitar's strong-pinioned Eagle was born: and he obeys
							his law for ever.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							As warriors to their steeds, kine to their village, as fond milk giving
							cows approach their youngling,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							As man to wife, let Savitar come downward to us, heaven's bearer, Lord
							of every blessing.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Like the Angirasa Hiranvastupa, I call thee, Savitar, to this
							achievement:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 149: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							So worshipping and lauding thee for favour I watch for thee as for the
							stalk of Soma.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 150
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							THOU, bearer of oblations, though kindled, art kindled for the Gods.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							With the Adityas, Rudras, Vasus, come to us: to show us favour come to
							us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Come hither and accept with joy this sacrifice and hymn of ours.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							O kindled God, we mortals are invoking thee, calling on thee to show us
							grace.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							I laud thee Jatavedas, thee Lord of all blessings, with my song.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni, bring hitherward the Gods whose Laws we love, whose laws we love,
							to show us grace.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni the God was made the great High-Priest of Gods, Rsis have kindled
							Agni, men of mortal mould.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Agni I invocate for winning ample wealth. kindly disposed for winning
							wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Atri and Bharadvaja and Gavisthira, Kanva and Trasadasyu, in our fight
							he helped.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 150: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							On Agni calls Vasistha, even the household priest, the household priest
							to win his grace.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 151
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							By Faith is Agni kindled, through Faith is oblation offered up.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							We celebrate with praises Faith upon the height of happiness.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Bless thou the man who gives, O Faith; Faith, bless the man who fain
							would give.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bless thou the liberal worshippers: bless thou the word that I have
							said.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Even as the Deities maintained Faith in the mighty Asuras,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							So make this uttered wish of mine true for the liberal worshippers.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Guarded by Vayu, Gods and men who sacrifice draw near to Faith.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Man winneth Faith by yearnings of the heart, and opulence by Faith.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Faith in the early morning, Faith at noonday will we invocate,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 151: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Faith at the setting of the Sun. O Faith, endow us with belief.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 152
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							A MIGHTY Governor art thou, Wondrous, Destroyer of the foe,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whose friend is never done to death, and never, never overcome.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Lord of the clan, who brings us bliss, Strong, Warrior, Slayer of the
							fiend,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							May India, Soma-drinker, go before us, Bull who gives us peace.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Drive Raksasas and foes away, break thou in pieces Vrtra'sjaws:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							O Vrtra-slaying Indra, quell the foeman's wrath who threatens us.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Indra, beat our foes away, humble the men who challenge us:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Send down to nether darkness him who seeks to do us injury.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Baffle the foeman's plan, ward off his weapon who would conquer us.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 152: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Give shelter from his furious wrath, and keep his murdering dart afar.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 153
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							SWAYING about, the Active Ones came nigh to Indra at his birth,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							And shared his great heroic might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Based upon strength and victory and power, O Indra is thy birth:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou, Mighty One, art strong indeed.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou art the Vrtra-slayer, thou, Indra, hast spread the firmament:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast with might upheld the heavens.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, bearest in thine arms the lightning that accords with
							thee,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Whetting thy thunderbolt with might.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Indra, art preeminent over all creatures in thy might:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 153: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Thou hast pervaded every place.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 154
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							FOR some is Soma purified, some sit by sacrificial oil:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							To those for whom the meath flows forth, even to those let him depart.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Invincible through Fervour, those whom Fervour hath advanced to heaven,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Who showed great Fervour in their lives, -even to those let him depart.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							The heroes who contend in war and boldly cast their lives away,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Or who give guerdon thousandfold, -even to those let him depart.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yea, the first followers of Law, Law's pure and holy strengtheners,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Fathers, Yama! Fervour-moved,even to those let him depart.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Skilled in a thousand ways and means, the sages who protect the Sun,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 154: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							The Rsis, Yama! Fervour-moved,-even to those let him depart.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 155
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							ARAYI, one-eyed limping hag, fly, ever-screeching, to the hill.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							We frighten thee away with these, the heroes of Sirimbitha.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Scared from this place and that is she, destroyer of each germ unborn.
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							Go, sharp-horned Brahmanaspti and drive Arayi far away.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							Yon log that floats without a man to guide it on the river's edge,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Seize it, thou thing with hideous jaws, and go thou far away thereon.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							When, foul with secret stain and spot, ye hastened onward to the
							breast,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							All Indra's enemies were slain and passed away like froth and foam.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							These men have led about the cow, have duly carried Agni round,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 155: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							And raised their glory tg the Gods. Who will attack them with success?
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 156
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							LET songs of ours speed Agni forth like a fleet courser in the race,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							And we will win each prize through him.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Agni the dart whereby we gain kine for ourselves with help from thee,-
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							That send us for the gain of wealth.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, bring us wealth secure, vast wealth in horses and in kine:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							Oil thou the socket, turn the wheel.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							O Agni, thou hast made the Sun, Eternal Star, to mount the sky,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							Bestowing light on living men.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou, Agni, art the people's light, best, dearest, seated in thy
							shrine:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 156: Verse 5: Line 2
					-
						-
							Watch for the singer, give him life.
						-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 157
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 157: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WE will, with Indra and all Gods to aid us, bring these existing worlds
						into subjection.
					-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 157: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Our sacrifice, our bodies, and our offspr. let Indra form together with
						Adityas.
					-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 157: Verse 3
				-
					-
						With the Adityas, with the band of Maruts, may Indra be Protector of our
						bodies.
					-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 157: Verse 4
				-
					-
						As when the Gods came, after they had slaughtered the Asuras, keeping safe
						their Godlike nature,
					-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 157: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Brought the Sun hitherward with mighty powers, and looked about them on
						their vigorous Godhead.
					-
			-
				Mandala 10: Hymn 158
			-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 1: Line 1
					-
						-
							MAY Surya guard us out of heaven, and Vata from the firmament,
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 1: Line 2
					-
						-
							And Agni from terrestrial spots.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 2: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thou Savitar whose flame deserves hundred libations, be thou pleased:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 2: Line 2
					-
						-
							From failing lightning keep us safe.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 3: Line 1
					-
						-
							May Savitar the God, and may Parvata also give us sight;
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 3: Line 2
					-
						-
							May the Creator give us sight.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 4: Line 1
					-
						-
							Give sight unto our eye, give thou our bodies sight that they may see:
						-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 4: Line 2
					-
						-
							May we survey, discern this world.
						-
				-
					Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mandala 10: Hymn 158: Verse 5: Line 1
					-
						-
							Thus, Surya, may we look on thee, on thee most lovely to behold,
						-
					-
